<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CUP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP GOVERNED BY CUSTOMS
</HEADLINE>
 JOURNAL-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ For three days, it stood on its pedestal behind
velvet ropes at Buffalo's Walden Galleria.
</P>
<P>
   But as Game 4 began Tuesday night, it was time to pack up the
Stanley Cup for its next adventure.
</P>
<P>
   At the worldly age of 106, the Cup has traveled to both the
Kremlin and the White House. Sylvain Lefebvre of Colorado baptized
his daughter in it during the summer of 1996. The Red Wings' Joey
Kocur used it to hold a serving of his grandfather's special-recipe
popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   For those who pursue hockey as a living, there is no more
memorable journey than that one lap of the ice that a winning
player takes while holding the just-won Stanley Cup high over his
head. It is hockey's version of cutting down the net, of donning
the green jacket or of dousing Tim McCarver with pennant champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Only, in hockey, there is so much more to it than that.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey is awash with superstitions and bows to protocol. And
Tuesday night, one of the most dramatic of those hockey bows was
poised to take place.
</P>
<P>
   A Game 4 victory by the Stars would have meant that the Cup
would have been packed and primped for a flight today to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Two chaperones, Craig Campbell and Phil Pritchard from the
Hockey Hall of Fame, had been assigned to take custody of the Cup
upon its arrival in Dallas. Protocol dictates that it would have
remained packed in its protective case and then hidden from sight,
somewhere deep in the bowels of Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   If the Stars had won Game 4 and were leading in Game 5 as the
contest reached its 55th minute, Campbell and Pritchard were to
unpack Lord Stanley's famous prize and carry it onto the ice for
the joyous presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it wasn't meant to be. Packed and ready, with the series
now knotted 2-2, the Cup instead will be returned today to the
Hockey Hall of Fame in downtown Toronto, where it will sit and wait
for its new itinerary. WHO YA GONNA CALL?
</P>
<P>
   Because, we can only assume, downtown Buffalo is such a wild and
wacky party town, the Stars cloistered themselves for Games 3 and 4
at something called the Grand Island Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Island is exactly that _ an island, surrounded by a river,
visited occasionally by seagulls and by Presidents' Trophy-winning
hockey clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line was, the Stars spent their five days closer to
Canada than they did to downtown Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   They were not the five-star accommodations that professional
hockey teams are accustomed to. No big deal, the players said. But
after a couple of days, the Stars began hearing ... stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the place is haunted,'' broadcaster Daryl Reaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, related Tuesday by a bellman who used to work
at the hotel, the town supervisor once lived on the property and
his home was destroyed by a great fire. His daughter died in the
blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The Holiday Inn was erected on the same site, but the daughter's
spirit has refused to leave. She haunts the grounds, reportedly
rattling doors and making occasional odd noises. Managers have
quit, convinced that the legend is true, the former bellman said.
</P>
<P>
   On a somewhat related note, no Stars players disappeared through
the TV set during the five-day stay. THE ROAD WARRIORS
</P>
<P>
   To the Stars, the road is anything but a foreboding place.
</P>
<P>
   They fear neither the long flight, nor the enemy crowd, nor the
$12 room-service hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Tuesday night's game, the Stars had won six times
in opposing teams' arenas during the playoffs. They clinched their
opening-round series in Edmonton in triple overtime. They won their
conference semifinal series in overtime in St. Louis. They forced a
deciding seventh game against Colorado by storming past the
Avalanche in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   So, how do you explain that?
</P>
<P>
   ``We drink a lot more on the road,'' defenseman Craig Ludwig
deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig was kidding. Anyone who follows the game knows that the
days of the hard-drinking, hard-skating, hell-raising hockey player
are past.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't afford to do that anymore,'' said Dave Reid, a
16-year NHL veteran. ``With the travel we have and the competition
now, you'd only be jeopardizing your career.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars survive the road because, they are convinced, their
game travels well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our style of play is very consistent,'' Reid explained.
``We're very controlled in what we do, whether we're at home or on
the road. And with the experience we have, guys know how to play in
different arenas and in front of different crowds, and they don't
let it distract them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig said he agrees with that and, in truth, some of the
Stars' most out-of-character performances this season have come at
home. Game 5 of the Colorado series, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get home, we hear the crowd, and, I don't know, we try to
put on a good show or something,'' the 17-year veteran said.
</P>
<P>
   Having a core of mature, experienced veterans helps, though,
when a team finds itself standing on strange ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have guys on this team that have been to all the hostile
places on the road,'' Ludwig said. ``You think some buildings are
bad now. You should have seen them 15 years ago. People throwing
towels on the ice and stuff. We just kind of turn the cheers off.''
</P>
<P>
   Having so many thirtysomething players, 35-year-old winger Pat
Verbeek said, can be ``a calming influence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It also helps when we're playing like (something smelly),''
Verbeek went on. ``We kick our own butts.''
</P>
<P>
   As a vital Game 4 of the Stanley finals neared, the Stars'
locker room at Marine Midland Arena seemed serene and confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the benefit of having so many older players,'' Ludwig
said. ``They've all been through that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like this game here. Even though we're probably going to have
to weather the first five or six minutes, we'll settle down, and
for us it'll be just another night.''
</P>
<P>
   Just another night. Sure. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
