<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES CALL UP CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The reason that minor-league call-up Randy
Cunneyworth was in the lineup Tuesday night for Buffalo was around
his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   His face is littered with bruises and scratches, souvenirs from
the playoff run he just finished with Rochester, the Sabres'
American Hockey League affiliate, and proof that he's one of those
players willing to do anything to win.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the type of player Sabres coach Lindy Ruff says
he needed for Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he did play with us before, he played very well,'' Ruff
said. ``He supplied some spunk and some character.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunneyworth, 38, also plays left wing, a spot where Buffalo has
been short-handed since back spasms sidelined Michal Grosek.
</P>
<P>
   Cunneyworth said he received word that he had been called up at
2 a.m. while on the Rochester team bus returning from a
season-ending loss in the playoffs. To him, fatigue isn't a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really energized,'' Cunneyworth said. ``Obviously, I know
what is at stake. It's a chance of a lifetime. It's been something
I thought about all year. You hope for a chance like this, and here
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunneyworth replaced Rob Ray in the Sabres' lineup. LOSING THE
FACEOFFS
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have been dominating the Sabres in the faceoff circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're not trying,'' Buffalo center Wayne Primeau
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres are trying. The Stars are trying harder. They won 57
percent of the faceoffs in Game 3. Tuesday night, they won 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a lot of different faceoffs in different places on the
ice,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said. ``We have got to try to get
close to 50 percent against these guys. We know that is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Primeau said it's tough because the Stars have veteran centers
like Guy Carbonneau and Brian Skrudland who have almost perfected
the art of winning faceoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make sure we have our stick down first,'' Primeau said.
``They've also got a winger in close so when they win the faceoff,
he's there to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Primeau said the Sabres had been stressing faceoffs on the two
off-days before Game 4. SHUFFLING LINES
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to jump-start his offense, Sabres coach Lindy Ruff
moved forward Joe Juneau to Buffalo's second line with Curtis Brown
and Miroslav Satan in place of Geoff Sanderson.
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson moved to a line with Stu Barnes and Brian Holzinger.
</P>
<P>
   The move not only helped the offense _ the Sabres had four more
shots through two periods in Game 4 (16) than they had all of Game
3 (12) _ it jump-started Sanderson. He had the Sabres' first goal
on a breakaway in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been such a good feeling lately,'' Sanderson said.
``I have been shut down on so many break plays in the playoffs. I
was starting to get a little frustrated with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
