<HEADER>
A6905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-HNS &LR;      06-16 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFINALS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ Eventually, even on the careful and complimentary
Spurs, someone had to say it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There had been hints that San Antonio could not help but look at
the No. 8-seeded Knicks, who come limping into town for tonight's
NBA Finals opener, and see a potential mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Sean Elliott was asked if New York's inexplicable
success made it seem like a team destined for greatness. His
response in a nutshell: No.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be battling destiny as well,'' Elliott said. ``This
is a team and a franchise that struggled for a lot of years to get
here. We have the players to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurs coach Gregg Popovich reacted similarly to the notion that
the Knicks' ability to overcome injuries and distractions had
proved they had championship mettle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always say that when you win,'' Popovich said. ``When
you start winning, people say you know how to win. Until you do
that, people say you don't know what the hell is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, finally, guard Mario Elie got to the heart of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not disrespecting the Knicks,'' Elie said, ``but this is
probably the weakest team we're going to play in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, for obvious reasons, have heard it all before. But
winning despite all the doubts has given them reason to welcome
such slights.
</P>
<P>
   They defeated Miami, the Eastern Conference's top seed, and
Indiana, the East's season-long favorite, with center and captain
Patrick Ewing playing hurt and then not at all and with coach Jeff
Van Gundy fighting to keep his job. General manager Ernie Grunfeld
had already failed to keep his, receiving his pink slip shortly
before the regular season ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been the underdog a lot of the regular season and the
whole playoffs,'' Knicks guard Allan Houston said. ``But we never
considered ourselves as underdogs. It's the same thing (now). We'll
leave it to everybody else to not believe in us. We'll keep
believing in ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But with forward Larry Johnson unlikely to play because of a
sprained right knee, the Knicks have a fresh reason to be doubted.
Johnson on Tuesday still could not predict whether he would play
tonight, and though his knee had improved markedly since Monday, he
said he would be slowed by the injury whenever he returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' he said. ``Even when I do come back bulky brace,
five, six days off, a little bit out of shape. It's tough. But
who's complaining? No excuses. You lower your head and go out and
do what you have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing low post the way I do, I get by with strength and
quickness. If I've got a bigger guy on me, I try to be quicker.
This has taken away from that. Getting out there and not doing what
I want to do is really going to hamper me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is the Finals. There's no would have, could have,
should have. It's just going at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson admitted that even if he were not hurt, the matchup
would be difficult for him and the Knicks. For all of New York's
well-earned confidence and its three consecutive Game 1 victories _
all on the road _ the Spurs' strengths do seem to play neatly off
the Knicks' weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm guarding one of the big guys (7-footers Tim Duncan and
David Robinson), I'm pretty sure they're going to have to come
after me,'' Johnson said. ``It's not just my knee. It's the height
disadvantage between me (at 6-6) and one of the twin towers. It's
been that way my whole career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a difficult situation against those guys if
I was 100 percent. If I have to scratch, kick, claw, to do whatever
I can get away with without a foul, that's what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Johnson, the Knicks typically do not send much
defensive help inside, preferring to let their big men fend for
themselves while Latrell Sprewell, Chris Childs and Charlie Ward
pressure the ball and challenge passing lanes.
</P>
<P>
   If Sprewell were forced to help inside or rotate over to open
shooters, it would seem to cost the Knicks one of their greatest
weapons. But with Ewing and possibly Johnson out, Duncan and
Robinson will test Chris Dudley, Kurt Thomas and Marcus Camby in
ways Eastern Conference big men could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pride themselves on defense,'' Duncan said. ``They play
hard. They're going to come out and take it as one of those
underdog challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking at it like that. We're not saying we're
better than they are or we have an advantage over them. But we're
going to go out there and get it done. That's the attitude we've
taken with everybody. There's going to be the effort to go at them,
whether for foul trouble or just to wear them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had a couple of injuries, so they're a little thinner
than we are. We have to just be able to attack them and take it to
the rim.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks are to make up for the injuries to Ewing and
Johnson, their talented combination of Houston and Sprewell must
deliver. Sprewell moved into the starting lineup soon after Ewing
went out, while Houston took over the Game 6 clincher against
Indiana after Johnson went down Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be more efficient,'' Houston said. ``The ball is
going to be in our hands. We have to make sure we make the right
plays. We can't turn the ball over. We have to get assists. We're
going to be aggressive. But we can't score every point. We learned
in the playoffs you can't do it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs will have their best perimeter defender, Elie, defend
Houston. And Elliott will finally have a size advantage going
against Sprewell instead of facing the post-up players he has
looked up to throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allan, I think, is really, really the key to their team,''
Elie said. ``I feel I'm the best out-front defender at the guard
position, but Allan is really a tough cover. Allan is great inside
and outside.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Elie left little doubt about the Spurs' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a confident team,'' he said. ``We feel good about
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, having heard it all before, feel the same way. So
much so that they took no offense at the other teams' doubts about
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been underdogs in every series and come out on top,''
Childs said. ``Let them keep it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
