<HEADER>
A6918 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAIR-SALARIES-KAN &LR;      06-16 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIR-SALARIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINKING CEO SALARIES TO EMPLOYEES' DRAWS LIMITED SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ An effort to tie CEO pay more closely to
average worker salaries met with limited support at eight corporate
annual meetings this spring.
</P>
<P>
   {United for a Fair Economy}, a Boston-based organization that is
trying to reduce the pay gap between top executives and their
employees, reported Friday that more than 500 million shareholder
votes were cast in favor of gap-shrinking resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, all of the resolutions failed by wide margins.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest support for pay equalization came from shareholders
of {R.R. Donnelley}, which met in March. A resolution on gender-
and race-based pay equity received 16.6 percent of the vote at the
printing company.
</P>
<P>
   The Fair Economy organization selected the eight corporations as
those where corporate leaders received large pay increases while
rank-and-file jobs were being cut.
</P>
<P>
   At seven of the corporations, Fair Economy-backed resolutions
called for CEO pay to be tied to a multiple of the lowest-paid
worker's pay at the company. The seven companies and the vote
percentages:
</P>
<P>
   {AlliedSignal}, 12 percent for and 88 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {AT&AMP;T}, 7.6 percent for and 92.4 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {BankAmerica}, 6.7 percent for and 93.3 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {BankBoston}, 4.8 percent for and 95.2 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {Citigroup}, 10.8 percent for and 89.2 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {General Electric}, 5 percent for and 95 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   {Huffy}, 8.3 percent for and 91.7 percent against.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholder resolutions were sponsored by Responsible
Wealth, a project of United for a Fair Economy that is a network of
more than 400 affluent Americans who are concerned about economic
inequality.
</P>
<P>
   Responsible Wealth spokesmen said they were not dispirited by
the votes. They said annual meeting voting procedures typically
favored management in proxy voting.
</P>
<P>
   Responsible Wealth spokesmen also said they were glad to have
started a dialogue on the pay issue. Management at AT&AMP;T,
BankAmerica and BankBoston issued statements acknowledging that
growing pay gaps were a social and business problem.
</P>
<P>
   The group intends to continue its efforts in August by
introducing a shareholder resolution at Computer Associates' annual
meeting. Next year, it intends to resubmit resolutions at several
of the corporations and submit more resolutions elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Members also are pledging to push mutual fund managers to
disclose their proxy voting records, something that typically is
kept secret by most mutual funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6919 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-16 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN ANTONIO _ This story has become typical New York. Bigger,
louder and supposedly better than anyplace else.
</P>
<P>
   It might as well have been written, produced and directed by
Spike Lee and Woody Allen, who would have us all believe that
anything from outside the five boroughs is wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   New York gave us style, sophistication and the $6 cup of coffee,
while the rest of the world merely offers right turn on red.
</P>
<P>
   Now New York gives us the Knicks, who we are supposed to believe
have invented teamwork, enthusiasm and a whole new way to the play
basketball, probably along with a cure for the common cold.
</P>
<P>
   To hear the tabloids scream it, the Knicks, in this magical
spring of the No. 8 seed in the playoffs, have discovered a way to
make the ball rounder, the baskets bigger and each game another
step along the path to enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   We are being told that Marcus Camby, a player who could not
break into the starting lineup all season long, is now ready to
take his place alongside the World Trade Center towers and the
Empire State Building as one of Manhattan's skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   We are being told that Latrell Sprewell _ he of the choke hold _
and Allan Houston _ he of the disappearing acts _ are now capable
of performing more feats of magic than Siegfried &AMP; Roy.
</P>
<P>
   We are being told that Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy, a rumpled
little fellow, is now the basketball equivalent of Werner von Braun
at the dawning of the U.S. space program.
</P>
<P>
   This is all so quaint, so familiar, so New York, the biggest
little city in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the traveling party who made the trip with the Knicks
probably thought they needed a passport to get inside our Texas
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive them if they think that any time they are outside the
sniffing distance of the New Jersey plants and the Turnpike, they
believe they're in a foreign country. And you'll have to forgive
them, of course, for barely knowing the names of the starting
lineup for the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   It's only natural that the Knicks and their bandwagon rolled
into town with the notion they are a team of destiny. After all,
when a New Yorker burps, he usually believes it is some kind of
inner sign from God, not merely a breath of sour air that still
smells better than the inside of any taxi on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Knicks are destiny's children. If, that is, you believe
somebody out there in the cruel world is always fated to get the
wrong end of the stick.
</P>
<P>
   We are being told over and over by the New York hype that the
Knicks are special, and indeed, they are. No team in recent playoff
memory has had a more fortuitous path covered with rose petals to
the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks won their first-round matchup with Miami in the final
seconds of Game 5 when a running heave by Houston practically wore
out the iron on the rim before rolling in.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks practically had a bye in the second round when
overrated Atlanta didn't even bother to compete.
</P>
<P>
   That put the Knicks into the Eastern Conference finals against
the Indiana Pacers, who practically disintegrated before their
eyes. Rik Smits broke his toe and went to hide in a corner. Reggie
Miller shriveled up. The Davis boys, Antonio and Dale, took turns
vanishing. And still it took a positively horrible call by referee
Jess Kersey on Larry Johnson's four-point play for the Knicks to
win Game 2 and a 3-for-18 shooting effort by Miller to give them
Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   There are delirious comparisons being made between Camby and
Bill Russell, between the Sprewell-Houston backcourt and the Hall
of Fame combo of Walt Frazier and Earl Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way it is in New York, where they believe that if
you yell it loud enough and long enough, it is true. It always
happens when a New York team is involved. It is always the
toughest, the strongest, the best.
</P>
<P>
   At least as far as New Yorkers can see. Which is usually only as
far as the west bank of the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   What the Knicks' bandwagon can't or won't see is that any one of
three other Western Conference teams _ Portland, Utah and the
Lakers _ would be prohibitive favorites in this series. What they
can't or won't see is that the Spurs' first three playoff opponents
_ Minnesota, LA and Portland _ were all more formidable than the
Knicks. And the Spurs swept those last two series over the Lakers
and Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   What they can't or won't see is how David Robinson and Tim
Duncan will swallow them up and end this quaint Manhattan fairy
tale in quick fashion.
</P>
<P>
   It is a typical New York story, made up of so much noise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
