<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL CHANGES COULD BE ON THE HORIZON FOR NHL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ NHL general managers met in Buffalo on Tuesday
and talked over several issues. The GMs are allowed to make
suggestions to the Board of Governors, who then vote on possible
changes.
</P>
<P>
   The GMs voted to recommend reducing the size of a goalie's
``catcher'' from 50 inches in circumference to 48 inches. They also
discussed moving the schedule ahead to start on Oct. 1. They
discussed the possibility of changing the ``in the crease'' rule
from ``no skate in the crease'' to ``no harm, no foul.'' And they
discussed the possibility of recommending trying to look into a
softer form of the seamless glass that is being used in new arenas
and has resulted in more shoulder and head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pushed some things in the direction they need to be pushed
to effect further change,'' Stars GM Bob Gainey said. ``We didn't
do anything today, but we tried to move things along on their
proper track.''
</P>
<P>
   The league GMs will gather again at the draft in late June. HULL
SITS
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Brett Hull sat out Tuesday night's game with a
strained groin and could miss Game 5, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea if he is going to be a player for Game 5,''
Hitchcock said. ``He has made significant progress and I think our
next step is to get him on the ice and see where it goes. But he is
not ready to go on the ice right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock moved Tony Hrkac to the first line with Mike Modano
and Jere Lehtinen and added rookie Jon Sim on the fourth line.
Darryl Sydor stayed on defense and did not move to forward. HOGUE
REMAINS SIDELINED
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Benoit Hogue skated Tuesday for the second day on
his injured left knee and said he felt much better. However, he
still doesn't know if he will be able to play in Game 5 Thursday at
Reunion Arena in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is day-to-day,'' he said. ``I know after skating
(Tuesday) I can't play, but I don't know how it will respond
(Wednesday),'' Hogue said. All I know is I need to be able to help
the team and not hurt the team, and I won't say I'm ready to come
in unless I know I'm ready to come in and help.'' TUREK'S TRADE
STATUS
</P>
<P>
   Stars goalie Roman Turek will likely be traded by the team
before the expansion draft on June 25, so the Stars will not lose
their backup goalie without getting an asset in return. The Atlanta
Thrashers, who can pick up to five goalies, have said they would
probably select Turek if he is left available. The Stars are
allowed to protect only one goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Turek said he knows all of the situations, but that he would
rather not hear about whether he's going to be traded or not. He
told his agent, Rich Winter, to keep tuned into potential trade
talks, but not to tell him anything until the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to enjoy Stanley Cup Finals, I don't want to hear
any of that stuff,'' Turek, from the Czech Republic, said. He was
16-3-3 during the regular season and has drawn the most interest
from the Tampa Bay Lightning. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
