<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6924 &Cx1f; tth-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-ORDER-SPI &LR;      06-16 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-ORDER-SPI </SLUG>
  
 BOEING LANDS HUGE ORDER FOR 737s AT PARIS AIR SHOW  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ International Lease Finance Corp. has ordered 50 of
Boeing's next generation 737s with options for 50 more, making it
the biggest order ever for the next generation family of airplanes
built in Renton, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   With the options, the value of the order is about $4.5 billion
based on the average list price of the various mix of planes.
</P>
<P>
   But International Lease reportedly received steep discounts from
Boeing, so much so that some analysts said Boeing may still be
going for market share over archrival Airbus Industrie rather than
trying to improve its minuscule commercial profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not true,'' Alan Mulally, president of the
Commercial Airplanes group, said in an interview following the
order announcement Tuesday at the Paris Air Show.
</P>
<P>
   He said the deal was good business, for Boeing and International
Lease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of this deal,'' Mulally said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has said its goal is to increase profit margins on its
commercial airplanes to 10 percent, and Mulally said the
transaction with International Lease was ``supportive of Boeing's
approach toward making a reasonable financial return ... this is
absolutely supportive of moving in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   At an earlier news conference for the order announcement, Steven
Udvar-Hazy, president and chief executive of International Lease,
was asked about the discount his leasing company received for the
737-700s, 737-800s and 737-900s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only say we did not pay retail price,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said negotiations took six months, and he described them as
``hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A transaction of this size is very complex,'' he said, adding
that he believes the final result was a ``win-win'' situation for
Boeing and International Lease.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is under a lot of pressure to improve its commercial
financial performance, and top executives have vowed they will
sacrifice market share for profitability, even if it means losing
an order on price to Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   But Byron Callan, aerospace analyst for Merrill Lynch who is in
Paris for the air show, said if the discounts are as steep as he
has heard, then he would begin to question Boeing's commitment to
better jetliner margins.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing delivered a record 563 commercial jetliners last year,
but made no profit on those planes. Mulally, in the interview, said
Boeing has not changed its previous projection that commercial
margins this year and next will be 2 percent to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Nisbet, an industry analyst with JSA Research, did a recent
analysis that concluded Boeing last year sold its planes below the
cost of producing them, with average prices paid by customers 14
percent to 27 percent below list prices.
</P>
<P>
   Nisbet did his analysis to quantify Boeing's practice of
discounting its jetliners to customers in its price war with
Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Tuesday, Nisbet said he does not know
how much discount Boeing gave International Lease on the 50 firm
orders.
</P>
<P>
   But the discount was likely steep, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a foregone conclusion that these huge orders from
leasing companies are full of deep discounts because they mean so
much to Boeing and Airbus in terms of market share,'' Nisbet said.
</P>
<P>
   One factor to consider in trying to understand if the deal is
good for Boeing is the delivery date of the planes ordered, he
said. If the deliveries mean Boeing can keep production rates high,
then the cost of each plane is less. ``In that case, Boeing could
offer some discounts without hurting its earnings,'' Nisbet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Boeing probably went beyond `some' with an order of that
size,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus also announced a billion-dollar order Tuesday by
Singapore Aircraft Leasing Enterprise for 20 A320s and three A321s.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus announcement,though, was overshadowed by the
International Lease order for Boeing planes.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Udvar-Hazy said the first delivery in the
new orders will come in early 2001, and if the additional 50
airplanes are confirmed, deliveries would continue until 2007.
</P>
<P>
   He called the next generation 737 a ``cornerstone of our
portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest order brings to 360 the number of 737s that
International Leasing owns, including planes that have not yet been
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Separately Tuesday, Boeing received orders from Korean Air Lines
Co. for two 747-400 freighters. The airline said it would replace
two Airbus A300 freighters when it accepts delivery of the new
plans, currently set or May and June of next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
