<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUDWIG PICKS WRONG TIME TO COMMIT COSTLY BLUNDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Craig Ludwig was late getting back to his locker
Tuesday night after the Sabres' 2-1 victory against the Stars in
Game 4 squared the Stanley Cup Finals at two games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   There's a joke in there somewhere, but it seems too cruel to
trot out the obvious punch line.
</P>
<P>
   By now you've probably caught ``The Play'' on ESPN, CNN-SI, or
the Cartoon Network, whatever you happened to be watching late
Tuesday night or this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say that's never happened to me before,'' Ludwig
said, ``but I'd be lying. It's just that now it's the playoffs and
everything is magnified.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, you might say that.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup Finals are heading to Dallas for Game 5 Thursday
night and this teeter-totter of a playoff series is balanced once
again. The Sabres' victory also assured a return to Buffalo's
Marine Midland Arena for Game 6 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig might be sentenced to drive the bus.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' veteran defenseman has had nightmares like this. He's
even had games like this one. They just didn't happen in the
Stanley Cup Finals, with the entire hockey world watching.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig's turnover in the slot allowed Buffalo's Dixon Ward to
drill the tiebreaking goal past Eddie Belfour early in the second
period and the Sabres' defense, led by Dominik Hasek's superb play
in net, made it stand up for the third one-goal victory in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams have been separated by only one goal or tied for
all but 26 seconds in four games.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars dominated the first and third periods, outshot the
Sabres 31-18, including 13-2 in the final 20 minutes, but made two
critical mistakes and both wound up in the net behind Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give up a couple of goals,'' Ludwig said, ``and that guy
(Hasek) gives them a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   This should have been a 1-0 Dallas victory and if it had been,
we'd all be singing Belfour's praises and talking about another
suffocating job by the Stars' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Messrs. Chambers and Ludwig, front and center, please.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Ludwig wasn't the only Stars' defenseman who was
blushing Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   First came Shawn Chambers, who also had that horrendous
performance in Game 5 against Colorado, when he was a minus-4 ``for
the game'' in a 7-5 Stars' loss.
</P>
<P>
   His one big boo-boo in this game came with about 12 minutes
remaining in the first period, when he allowed Pat Verbeek's pass
to skip over his stick at the Sabres' blue line. Geoff Sanderson
raced past him, skated in on Belfour unchallenged and slipped it
past him after faking the Dallas goalie to the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chambers was unfortunate because we really had great cycle
rotation going and his stick hooked in the boards, I guess,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   We're all guessing, Hitch, since Chambers didn't make a postgame
appearance to face the media. Ludwig may have been slow, but at
least when he arrived at his locker, he stayed until everyone had
their shot at him.
</P>
<P>
   None hurt as much as the one Ward stung him with in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd just dumped it out of their zone and I went out to get
it,'' Ludwig said, trying to reconstruct the play. ``I was going to
get it over to Shawn. That's what we've been doing the whole
series, just trying to get the pucks out of the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just hit the top of my stick and went right on (Ward's)
tape. He put it in. I may have even screened Eddie or (the shot)
might have even hit me, I don't know. I looked back and saw it in
the net and wanted to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates tried desperately to get him off the hook and
failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels real bad,'' teammate Darryl Sydor said. ``As a team,
we're all together in this. We hurt for him right now, but he's a
character player and he'll bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he will. But he'll replay this one for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rolling and bouncing, but no more than a hundred others
I've handled,'' Ludwig said. ``I could have done 10 different
things with it. I could have fallen on it or I could have picked it
up and thrown it in the stands. Obviously I didn't do the right
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things happen in games all the time. It's happened to me
before. Just not in a game that was this important. They take
advantage of mistakes. They see a crack, they're through it and
(Hasek) slams the door. We didn't give Eddie a chance on either of
those goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Dallas, the debate has raged over the parade route once
the Stars win the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Note to parade director: Better include a return trip to Buffalo
in those plans. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
