<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-VOLUNTEERS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Students give time, attention to more deprived youngsters  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WINSTON ROSS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Daniel Clark understands that life in the
inner city is not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty, he knows, presents the most talented and capable youth
with daunting challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel has faced those challenges, too. Even now, his room at
home is too small for a bed. But he managed to win a scholarship to
Rockhurst High School, and this week 10 of his classmates get to
see some of what he has experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel and the 10 others are sleeping on church floors and
spending time with youngsters from the most deprived areas of
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The students are working at St. Louis Church on Swope Parkway as
part of a new program called the Total Ignatian Experience.
</P>
<P>
   School administrators at Rockhurst chose the students on the
basis of scholarship and overall achievement. They deliver food to
the church, study, play with and be mentors to children enrolled in
the church's youth program, Upper Room. They also serve dinner at
soup kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel sees the week as a chance to give something back to the
community. He wants to show his younger peers that success is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these kids are very intelligent,'' he said. ``I've
seen both sides, and I realize these kids can do it. They don't
realize that sometimes it's not their fault.''
</P>
<P>
   What is challenging for the other Rockhurst students is to be
plunged into an environment that, for most of them, is completely
foreign. .MDNM/They don't know what it's like to worry about their
next meals or how long they will have a roof over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Rockhurst's Aaron Clevinger said listening to inner-city
residents' stories of hardship made him think twice about his own
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're comfortable, you start taking things for
granted,'' he said. ``I thought, coming in, you could do anything
you wanted as long as you're motivated to do it. Here, there's so
much against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The week is part academia, part hard labor, and all fun, said
the students. And the children enjoy working with their older
mentors.
</P>
<P>
   Rockhurst teacher Peg Mulvihill is coordinating the volunteer
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're being `men for others' '' she said. ``This gives them
the chance to have a different outlook.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
