<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK SUPPLIES CZECH-LIST, BRUISING SABRES RESPOND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Desperate times call for desperate Czech
messages.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Dominik Hasek's Czech-O-Gram to his teammates was
that he was the goalie. They were the goal scorers. And it was time
to get up off the Stanley Cup floor and take care of business.
</P>
<P>
   Message deliveritch, Sabres. Seizing two unexpected gift
opportunities handed them by the Stars, the Sabres rode Hasek's
steel-trap goaltending to a 2-1 victory Tuesday night, knotting the
Stanley Cup finals at two games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The (trumpets, please) world's greatest goaltender had laid out
his wishes on the eve of Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be more aggressive,'' Hasek implored. ``More forechecking. Go
after them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do it as a unit. It can't be one guy being aggressive and four
guys waiting at the blue line.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the puck dropped Tuesday night, and the desperate Sabres
commenced an all-night massage. If you believe in statistics, the
NHL bruise-counters had Buffalo with 34 hits delivered to the
Stars' 16. That's more than a two-to-one edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he said it all, really,'' Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said.
``He said to bring it on, and I kind of echoed those sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you play it safe and try to win the game, 1-0, it's not
going to happen. Emotionally, he was the leader of the game for us
and he set the tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek stopped 30 of 31 shots, and his performance ranged from
everyday brilliant to the Hasek we know from the Vezina trophies
and the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it's not as if the Stars rained a hailstorm of golden
scoring chances at him.
</P>
<P>
   With a chance to seize a commanding 3-1 edge in the series, the
Stars lost far too many physical battles and failed to convert the
handful of rebound opportunities that Hasek presented them.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview room later, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock was
lobbed a verbal softball by a writer trying to elicit some praise
for Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I don't think,'' Hitch said, his voice sounding a tad
drained by what had happened. ``I mean, he was good. Eddie
(Belfour) was good, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think, though, that Hasek was the factor in the game.
I thought Hasek was good and he made some great saves, but you know
what? So did Eddie.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, I suspect, wasn't being discourteous as much as he
was still seething over the uncharacteristic way in which his
veteran team literally handed Buffalo the game.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Chambers' turnover at the blue line, instantly transformed
into Geoff Sanderson's goal, was in some ways not shocking.
Chambers, in general, has had some dreadful moments in these
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But fellow defenseman Craig Ludwig's blunder, which spoon-fed
Dixon Ward with the eventual game-winning goal, was not the sort of
thing you'd expect from a 17-year NHL veteran. Behind the Stars
bench, the camera caught Hitchcock muttering a one-syllable
profanity after the Ludwig mistake.
</P>
<P>
   So much for those Capt. Kangaroo comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Hitch calmly observed later: ``Everybody makes individual
mistakes like that. Those guys have played a lot of minutes and
played well for us in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   He called Ludwig's pass ``flippy'' and suggested that Chambers'
error was ``unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe ``he'' needs to listen to Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate times, after all, call for desperate Czech messages.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it wasn't anything that the Sabres' offense did that
scuttled the Stars here Tuesday night. They managed only 18 shots
on goal. Only two shots came in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres' offensive game plan still looks like the road map
for those TV crash-test dummies. Let's see _ dump to the corner ...
go to the body ... hope somebody kicks the puck free for a
centering pass.
</P>
<P>
   Don't anyone with Buffalo wings on their breath ever again dare
to call the Stars' offensive style boring. Don't dare.
</P>
<P>
   But because their goalie spoke, the Sabres did listen. Handed
the lead for keeps just eight minutes into the second period,
Buffalo finally attacked with some sense of abandon. It might have
been their best period since the overtime of Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominik said that if this team is going to get physical, then
I am going to get involved, too,'' Ruff noted.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek did. And on this night, the Stars had no answer, either in
Czech or any other language.
</P>
<P>
   If there an Eddie-gram in the offing?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
