<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES TURN ON JETS, TIE STANLEY CUP SERIES 2-2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The puck fluttered on Craig Ludwig's stick for
one moment. And a few seconds later, butterflies fluttered in the
stomach of the Stars' defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   In the time it took to make a routine pass _ or mess up a
routine pass, in Ludwig's case _ the Stanley Cup Finals took a
sharp turn. Ludwig's second-period turnover led to Dixon Ward's
game-winning goal in a 2-1 Buffalo Sabres victory against the Stars
in Game 4 last night at Marine Midland Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The best-of-seven series is tied at 2-2 heading into Game 5
tomorrow night at Reunion Arena. And while the Stars have home-ice
advantage in what amounts to a best-of-three series, Ludwig said he
and his teammates learned a hard lesson in just how tight the
margin of error is in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of these goaltenders are playing so great that a little
break here or there is all teams are looking for,'' Ludwig said.
</P>
<P>
   Goalies Dominik Hasek of the Sabres and Ed Belfour of the Stars
each came up with spectacular performances. And that put even more
emphasis on two giveaways; Stars defenseman Shawn Chambers also had
a gaffe that led to a unassisted goal for the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig's giveaway, in particular, changed the game. With the
score tied at 1-1 and the Stars controlling play in the first seven
minutes of the second period, Ludwig failed to control a bouncing
puck before he attempted a cross-ice pass to Chambers. The puck sat
out in the high slot, and Ward was able to scoop it up and head in
on Belfour. Ludwig then compounded the problem by trying to block
the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I screened Eddie on it, and he didn't have a chance,''
Ludwig said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the game turned into a street brawl as each side
fought for territory, fought for chances to rile the goaltenders
and fought to get a puck in the net. At one point, Hasek went after
Stars captain Derian Hatcher and ended up being cross-checked by
Pat Verbeek in a scrum. Near the end, the teams exchanged verbal
and physical assaults and there were 10 minutes of combined
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams are so good at feeding off mistakes, they feed off
that and wait for it,'' said center Mike Modano, who was held
without a goal for the ninth consecutive playoff game. ``It's
getting a little heated; frustration is building on both sides.
It's time to dig in and get dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars thought they had dug in pretty well, churning out 31
shots on goal to go with 12 missed shots. In the meantime, they
held the Sabres to 18 shots and seven missed shots. The Stars often
controlled the puck deep in the Sabres' end of the ice for long
stretches and basically carried over the near flawless game plan
they executed in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Sabres were a much improved team over Game 3. They
were more intense, they were more physical, they were more
committed on defense. In short, the regained their confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a must-win for us,'' defenseman Jason Woolley said.
``There's a reason why we got here. We're a very good team with a
great goaltender.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres scored first for the third time in the series and
this time made the first goal matter. Sabres winger Geoff Sanderson
was able to pick up a loose puck off the stick of Chambers and race
up to drop in a backhand on Belfour in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, however, countered with Jere Lehtinen's power-play
goal 2:05 later. The score stayed that way until Ward watched the
biggest gift of the playoffs land in his lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it just got our energy going,'' he said. ``We started
throwing everything at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig reflected on what is surely going to be called the worst
mistake of his career. But, he said, he couldn't dwell on the
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have done 10 different things,'' Ludwig said. ``I
could have fell on it, or I could have picked it up and thrown it
in the stands. Obviously, I didn't do the right thing, but that's
part of hockey.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
