<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
 
OATES VENTS ANGER AFTER RANGERS LOSE TO YANKEES (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Texas Rangers manager Johnny Oates exploded in anger.
</P>
<P>
   Oates' outburst perhaps exceeded that displayed by the weekend
hacker who chunks a 150-yard approach shot into water with an
8-iron, but the manager's message _ the family version _ would be
similar.
</P>
<P>
   No mulligans.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Ryan Glynn needed one in New York's six-run second
inning of Tuesday night's 6-2 loss at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Glynn (0-1) retired 14 of the 17 batters the Yankees
sent to the plate during his six-inning appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter!'' Oates screamed before clearing his office
of postgame company after the Rangers' season-high, four-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Oates' display could be described as highly uncharacteristic for
an otherwise patient, even-tempered manager.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn's response matched that of Oates, but it lacked the
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could do that,'' Glynn said of disregarding that
second inning. ``If I get out of that inning with three runs, maybe
it's a different game. I feel like I let my team down.''
</P>
<P>
   It unfolded without warning.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn's 1-2-3 first inning included strikeouts of shortstop
Derek Jeter and right fielder Paul O'Neill, but a second-inning,
leadoff walk issued to center fielder Bernie Williams set the
wheels of disaster in motion.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Tino Martinez and designated hitter Chili Davis
collected consecutive singles, and Davis' hit scored Williams with
the Yankees' first run and tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn retired left fielder Shane Spencer before allowing a
run-scoring double to third baseman Luis Sojo, but the 24-year-old
rookie appeared to gain control of the situation by retiring
catcher Joe Girardi on a routine fly ball to right field for the
inning's second out.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, though, drew a two-out walk on a
wild pitch that allowed Davis to cross the plate with the Yankees'
third run, and Jeter sealed the Rangers' fate with his three-run,
opposite-field home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have never put myself in that situation,'' Glynn
said. ``I should have never walked Knoblauch.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn threw Jeter a first-pitch fastball away and attempted to
go away with a slider on his second pitch. That pitch was supposed
to set up a third-pitch fastball in on Jeter's fists.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn, though, never got to throw that third pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit a slider out, a very bad slider,'' Glynn said. ``It was
a bad pitch. I think a low (Class) A-ball hitter could have hit
that one out of the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter certainly did. It measured 382 feet and gave the Yankees a
6-1 lead with right-hander David Cone on top of his game. Cone
(7-2) surrendered only two runs on four hits and two walks and
recorded six strikeouts in his seven-inning appearance. It also
gave Cone his 10th victory in 13 career decisions against the
Rangers and improved his earned-run average to 2.17 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn allowed only a fourth-inning walk to Sojo and sixth-inning
singles to Davis and Spencer after Jeter's home run, but it didn't
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately in this game, you can't throw out the bad
innings or the bad at-bats,'' Oates said. ``That's all part of it.
Sometimes one bad pitch can cost you a ballgame.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
