<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES FOLLOW GUIDELINE TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ After their humbling 2-1 loss in Game 3 Saturday
night, the Buffalo Sabres went into last night's critical Game 4
with a long checklist of do's and don'ts.
</P>
<P>
   Do take more wrist shots, and do fake some of those shots to
avoid blocks by Dallas defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Do forecheck hard in the Dallas zone to create turnovers and
scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Do pinch in the defensemen when controlling the puck deep in
Stars' territory to create more chances.
</P>
<P>
   Do get ineffective scorer Miroslav Satan involved in the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Don't take stupid penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The Game 4 scorecard: Check, check, check, check and check.
</P>
<P>
   The result: A 2-1 victory that turned the Stanley Cup Finals
into a best-of-three series heading back to Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround from Game 3 had the Sabres feeling good going
back on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always going to say we can improve our overall game, but
we want to build off this game today,'' defenseman Jay McKee said.
``We're pretty happy with the way we played. We were more
aggressive with the puck, and breaking down their defensive zone.
Everybody's a little more up now. We're excited to get back to
Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres showed early in the first period that they'd learned
the lessons coach Lindy Ruff had been teaching them the past two
off days when Geoff Sanderson scored on a fake and a wrist shot
against Ed Belfour, not a blast from long distance.
</P>
<P>
   The game-winner came off a foray deep into Dallas territory by
winger Dixon Ward after he intercepted an errant Craig Ludwig pass.
Ward, too, used a wrist shot to beat Belfour _ after avoiding
Ludwig's attempted shot block.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was going to go down on one knee,'' said Ward, who
added that he was so intent on avoiding a block that he didn't even
look at the net as he shot.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the game, Sabres' attackers used fakes to avert shot
blocks, then fired quick wristers rather than long-windup slap
shots. Meanwhile, defenders joined the rush in the Dallas zone.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Buffalo players acknowledged the improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't like the way we worked in Game 3,'' said defenseman
Jason Woolley. ``We did a lot of stupid things. We're a lot smarter
team than that and we started to make smart plays tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the smartest things Buffalo did was listen to goalie
Dominik Hasek, who urged his blueliners to jump into the rush and
help boost the Sabres' anemic attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the reasons we were able to get more pressure
in their zone,'' said McKee. ``Throughout the playoffs, our
defensemen have been able to pinch and we got back to that today.
We kept some pucks in the zone and that helped us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Sabres' pinching defensemen helped the Buffalo
offense, aggressive forechecking aided the Buffalo defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight,'' Woolley said, ``when they turned around, we were in
their face.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres accomplished two other objectives. They continued to
play rough _ dishing out 34 hits to 16 for Dallas _ but limited the
Stars to just three power-play opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   And, while he didn't score, regular season leading goal-scorer
Satan had a strong game, skating well and creating chances.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 0105EDT &QL; 
