<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-HNS &LR;      06-16 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BUFFALO, N.Y. _ In the end, the mood was one of chagrin more than
anger.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two goals that made the difference were giveaways, a point
even the winners would concede. At the other end, plenty of
opportunities had been missed. When it was done, the Dallas Stars
seemed to realize they had dominated Game 4 of the Stanley Cup
Finals everywhere but on the big board hanging at the center of
Marine Midland Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Stars, that was the scoreboard, which read
``Buffalo 2, Dallas 1'' at the end of a different sort of Tuesday
night of hockey, one that left an increasingly strange
best-of-seven series tied at two games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   What to make of all this?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought most of this game was passion and emotion,'' Sabres
coach Lindy Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars saw it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take a look at the two plays, and there were some very
lucky bounces on their part,'' center Mike Modano said with a
shrug. ``That's hockey in June.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Stars and Sabres will play hockey a little longer _ at
least two more games _ after an offbeat evening in which Dallas
outshot Buffalo 31-18 (including a 13-2 edge in the final period)
and controlled the flow, yet contributed to its demise with two
highly uncharacteristic defensive gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple of mistakes that gave them their two goals,''
Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Game 5 is Thursday night at Reunion Arena, leaving the Stars
little time to dwell on the opportunity lost. If there was
something naggingly familiar about the whole experience, though,
there is good reason for that. In the Western Conference finals
against Colorado, Dallas won Game 3 on the road. With a chance to
go up 3-1 in the series, the Stars got off to a slow start in Game
4, rallied, then lost 3-2 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, this was worse, because the Stars needed only to
look in the mirror to find the chief culprits.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was a Shawn Chambers giveaway in the offensive end
that quickly turned into a Geoff Sanderson breakaway goal midway
through the first period, energizing a crowd that was beginning to
lose some enthusiasm in the face of another slow Buffalo start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether it was the ice or mishandling the puck,''
Sanderson said, ``but it was nice to capitalize on the few mistakes
they made.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Stars drew even, there would be another inexplicable
blunder. This time, Dixon Ward took a gift in the form of a fumbled
pass by Craig Ludwig and wristing a shot past Ed Belfour (18 shots,
16 saves) for what proved to be the winning goal 7 minutes, 37
seconds into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really playing well at that time,'' Hitchcock said.
``It was really coming. Then we gave it easily, and it kind of took
the wind out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuses? Sure, this was a virtual must-win situation for
Buffalo. And yes, Dallas went without wing Brett Hull, who sat out
the game with a groin injury suffered in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all of that, the Stars left town with a split that
produced more letdown than satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   With goalie Dominik Hasek (who stopped 30 of 31 shots) exhorting
his team to pick up the pace on the offensive end, the Sabres were
more aggressive than in Game 3, when they got off just 12 shots.
Still, Dallas seemed to be weathering the storm before Chambers
failed to control a pass from Pat Verbeek in the offensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson was off on a breakaway down the left side. He pulled
up as if winding up for a slap shot, then cruised by Belfour and
eased the puck beyond the sprawled goalie's grasp 8:09 into the
opening period.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was up. Hasek pumped his arms in celebration. A little
more than two minutes later, though, the party was back on hold.
</P>
<P>
   On a power play, Modano got the puck behind the net and found
Jere Lehtinen in the slot. Lehtinen beat Hasek to the goalie's
right, tying the score at 1 at 10:14.
</P>
<P>
   The second period began with the Stars finishing up a power
play, but it was the Sabres who were taking the offensive. Again,
Buffalo got a little help when Ludwig virtually handed the puck to
Ward, who quickly cashed in by beating the partially screened
Belfour just inside the left post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were two rare mistakes for them to make defensively,''
Ward said. ``We were fortunate enough to take advantage of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas pressed the issue in the third but to no avail. So the
series heads back to Texas, with each team already having won a
game on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas is probably a little better team than us,'' Ruff said.
``But we still think we can beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Sabres have a better chance now; the Stars will
hope another bit of recent history doesn't repeat itself: After
losing Game 4 in Denver, Dallas dropped Game 5 at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to play error-free to win now,'' Modano said. ``At
this time of year, that's what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars fell a little short in that department Tuesday night.
Come Thursday, they might begin to find out if more than just
margin for error was lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
