<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-EARTHQUAKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARTHQUAKE KILLS 14 IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A strong earthquake rattled central Mexico today,
killing at least 14 people and injuring dozens as buildings
collapsed in and around the capital of Puebla state, east of Mexico
City, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Puebla put the death toll at 12 there. Landslides
blocked several rural highways in Puebla and Oaxaca, reports said.
Two people were killed in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The quake was felt strongly in Mexico City. Thousands of
residents fled into the streets as buildings swayed. Telephone
service was interrupted in much of the city for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   The National Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo.,
measured the quake at 6.5 on the Richter scale. The National
Seismological Center of Mexico recorded it at 6.7.
</P>
<P>
   The quake struck at 3:42 p.m. and both services located its
epicenter in a rural area 125 miles southeast of here, along a
volcanic border that divides Oaxaca and Puebla. Authorities in
Oaxaca said they had been unable to establish communication with
Huajuapan, the rural area at the epicenter.
</P>
<P>
   The worst damage in preliminary reports was in the center of the
city of Puebla, 55 miles east of here. The defense secretary, Gen.
Enrique Cervantes, said at least five people were killed around
Puebla. Parts of the Puebla City Hall collapsed, killing one woman
and temporarily trapping 12 municipal workers, who were rescued.
Dozens of other structures suffered heavy damage. The dome of the
San Augustine church collapsed, and the tower of another church, La
Concepcion, also suffered heavy damage.
</P>
<P>
   Radio announcements reported the deaths of at least five
additional people and the collapse of hundreds of houses in towns
and villages across the state of Puebla.
</P>
<P>
   The Puebla Red Cross reported that it had treated 200 people for
injuries like broken bones and shock. A spokesman said the injured
streamed into clinics hours after the quake.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo, who was in the Caribbean resort city
of Cancun, spoke in an interview with a radio station here 90
minutes after the quake. He said he had ordered his secretaries of
interior, defense and transport, as well as the head of the Federal
Electricity Utility, to travel immediately to Puebla to oversee
relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The Volkswagen plant in Puebla, supplier of the Volkswagen
Beetle and the New Beetle, suspended production and ordered
buildings inspected for damage.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, a handful of buildings appeared to have suffered
severe damage, although they did not collapse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
