<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TICKETMASTER-COMPLAINTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL CREDIT CARD PRACTICES ANGER CUSTOMERS, STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE HADLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Peter Laurie of Poulsbo, Wash., called Ticketmaster
Northwest recently to order tickets to a Tom Jones concert.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks later, the Lauries received a copy of
Entertainment Weekly in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   An envelope that came with it said that unless the Lauries
called to cancel, their credit card would be billed $19.95 for 20
weeks of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Laurie, wondering how Entertainment Weekly could bill
their credit card automatically, called the 800 number listed on
the envelope.
</P>
<P>
   She was told the company would just bill the credit card number
Peter Laurie had used to order the concert tickets through
Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Laurie was outraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot believe they have the right to give my credit card
number to anybody,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Ticketmaster Northwest official denied that the company gives
credit card information to other companies. Ticketmaster has a
contract with Entertainment Weekly to market the magazine to people
who buy tickets through Ticketmaster, said Curt Logan, general
manager of Ticketmaster Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   When someone calls Ticketmaster to buy concert tickets, the
operator will at that time offer them a free trial subscription to
Entertainment Weekly, Logan said.
</P>
<P>
   The customer has to agree to the offer and will be billed only
if they don't cancel at the end of eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Lauries say they weren't offered and didn't agree to a trial
subscription. Logan said if that's true, the operator should be
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups call Ticketmaster's practice ``unacceptable''
and cite it as one example of a growing trend of banks and other
companies using consumers' credit card information to bill them
without their explicit approval.
</P>
<P>
   The Lauries' case is in the early stages _ the state Attorney
General's Office plans to send them a complaint form.
</P>
<P>
   But across the nation attorneys general and other authorities
have begun taking aim at controversial credit card practices,
particularly in the banking industry.
</P>
<P>
   Developments in the past week include:
</P>
<P>
   _U.S. Comptroller John Hawke said the practice of banks selling
customer information to telemarketing firms was growing and is
``seamy.'' He warned the industry it could be risking a crackdown
by legislators or regulators.
</P>
<P>
   _Minnesota Attorney General Mike Hatch announced a lawsuit
against US Bank for allegedly sharing customers' private banking
information with Member Works Inc. in exchange for fees of $4
million, plus commissions of 22 percent on net sale revenues.
Member Works is a Connecticut telemarketer that sells myriad club
memberships based on buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   _Democrats in the U.S. House of Representatives introduced a
bill that would bar banks from sharing credit and bank account
numbers or giving access to accounts for telemarketing purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public, when they find out that the bank can take their
most sacred personal financial information and put it on the
Internet or sell it to a telemarketer _ people go through the roof.
And they're fully justified in that,'' said Rep. Jay Inslee,
D-Wash., a co-sponsor of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Inslee introduced a broader bill last month that would require
banks to tell consumers their intent to sell information and allow
consumers to refuse.
</P>
<P>
   _Bank of America, which owns Seafirst Bank, announced it would
change its privacy policies and no longer share any customer
information with third-party marketers who offer their products and
services to Bank of America customers.
</P>
<P>
   At least one customer was not pleased with Seafirst's earlier
policy. In April, Woodinville resident Linda Crosby said she had
recently been billed $59.95 on her credit card by CUC Shopper's
Advantage, a club she'd never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lady at Seafirst told me that my credit card does not belong
to me. It belongs to them and therefore they can have these other
companies do what they want with it,'' Crosby said. ``I can't
believe this is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America spokesman John Cleghorn said Friday, ``We're not
going to do business of that kind any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Intelligencer in April reported on complaints by
Washington state residents against Member Works and against
BrandDirect Marketing, another Connecticut-based telemarketing
company that sells club memberships.
</P>
<P>
   The complaining consumers said they were billed without their
approval for memberships in Outdoor Explorer's Club, SmartSource
and other clubs they did not recognize or want.
</P>
<P>
   The credit card issuers, which include Chase Manhattan Bank,
Travelers Bank, General Electric Consumer Appliance Finance and
Exxon, said most of the consumers had agreed to the billings in
telemarketing calls, but the consumers were not aware that they had
and never gave out their credit card numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The telemarketing companies, however, already had either the
numbers or enough information to bill their cards.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota attorney general alleged that scripts read by
Member Works' telemarketers were deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Attorney General's Office says it is currently
investigating BrandDirect Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster's practices are no better than those of the banks
selling account information, said Ed Mierzwinski, a Washington,
D.C., lobbyist for US PIRG, which represents WashPIRG, a local
consumer and environmental advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   The Lauries, the Poulsbo couple, called Ticketmaster to buy a
ticket, not to buy a magazine, Mierzwinski said. If they want to
buy the magazine, they can call again and give their credit card
number for that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are taking advantage of you,'' said Mierzwinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't just keep your credit card number and trick you
into buying things.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan of Ticketmaster Northwest said it's not always
Ticketmaster pushing the magazine on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers want the magazine because of its eight- to
16-page insert that tells what Northwest events are coming up, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Logan said sometimes an operator trying to make ``an extra
buck'' will sign people up without their permission, but they're
fired if anyone finds out.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie is skeptical. She said she was called by a company
wanting to sell her a satellite dish. The company told her it got
her name through Ticketmaster and could bill it to her credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Logan said Ticketmaster has no connection with a satellite dish
company. ``We absolutely do not give anybody's credit card
information to anybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another consumer had the same complaint as the Lauries about
Ticketmaster and filed a complaint in December with the Attorney
General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was purchasing tickets for `Disney on Ice' entertainment,
not a subscription to a magazine,'' Kenmore resident Kristian Leite
wrote in his complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Ticketmaster has found a new way for them to
generate additional revenue at my expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I, as a simple consumer, protect myself if every time
I use my credit card, the business will take the information and
give it to anybody willing to buy it?''
</P>
<P>
   A Ticketmaster official responded that Leite's experience was
``a miscommunication on the part of the operator who processed your
ticket order.''
</P>
<P>
   He said ``appropriate measures'' were being taken ``to avoid
future complaints of this nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Paula Selis said Washington state has
a law called the Unsolicited Goods Act that prohibits sending
something to someone without their positive assent and then billing
them later for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
