<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BENEFIT FROM EWING'S MISFORTUNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He won an NCAA basketball title and was named one of the 50
greatest NBA players of all time. He has led his team in scoring
average 11 seasons and had them within a game of the 1994 NBA
title.
</P>
<P>
   He is, having spent 14 seasons wearing the blue and orange, Mr.
New York Knick.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, the New York Knicks are better off now without Patrick
Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is terrible if you are a Ewing fan, for he has led
them to the playoffs for 11 consecutive seasons. Throughout all of
the coaching changes and front-office changes, Ewing has been as
consistent as a New York traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, when the Knicks center was lost for the rest of the
playoffs with a partially torn Achilles' tendon in Game 2 of the
Eastern Conference finals, the Knicks became a better team.
</P>
<P>
   Swingmen Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell fuel a Knicks team
that runs more and creates more offense in the open court. Post
Marcus Camby has fresher legs.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Knicks are heavy underdogs against the San
Antonio Spurs in the NBA Finals, which begin Wednesday night. But
New York has a better chance of scoring points against Tim Duncan
and Co. without the plodding, 36-year-old Ewing slowing down the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing awfully well without him,'' said Spurs guard
Steve Kerr, a member of the past three championship teams with the
Chicago Bulls. ``They're doing an amazing job.''
</P>
<P>
   So what should this say about the Ewing legacy?
</P>
<P>
   Even though injuries have marred his past two seasons _ he
missed 56 games in 1997-98 with a dislocated wrist _ you can't
argue about Ewing's career production. He has been an All-Star 11
times, and he has put together seven seasons averaging 20 or more
points and 10 or more rebounds per game.
</P>
<P>
   No, if you are a Ewing fan, you look at the old Knick and wonder
how things could have been if he had one more weapon for all those
wars with Larry Bird and Michael Jordan; a point guard to get him
the ball perhaps, or a small forward to take some of the scoring
load off of him.
</P>
<P>
   He rarely had that kind of help. In six career playoff series
against Jordan's Bulls or Bird's Celtics, Ewing's Knicks were 1-5,
including 0-4 against Jordan. The Knicks did break through against
Chicago in the 1994 Eastern Conference semifinals. But that victory
came with Jordan in temporary retirement. The series outcome may
have been different if not for a questionable foul call on Scottie
Pippen in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   But that's another column.
</P>
<P>
   This columnist feels for Ewing, and Charles Barkley, and Karl
Malone, and any other perennial superstar drafted in the mid-1980s
who has been part of the league's highlights only to play second to
Jordan every year.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's retirement was supposed to give one of these guys a
chance to win it all. Barkley's Rockets and Malone's Jazz did not
even make it to the conference finals. Ewing, of course, is hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel bad for (Ewing),'' said Spurs center David Robinson,
who is making his first NBA Finals appearance. ``As you know, those
opportunities don't come very often.''
</P>
<P>
   They might never come again for Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard sitting here watching, but that's my fate,'' Ewing
said. ``I've just got to do whatever I can do by talking to the
guys and cheering them.''
</P>
<P>
   So his place in history, for the most part, must be measured
against the other big men of his day. In his prime he was as
consistent a scorer as Shaquille O'Neal, and as solid a defender as
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   But he was outclassed in his one and only chance in the Finals.
In a one-on-one matchup against Hakeem Olajuwon's Houston Rockets
in the 1994 NBA Finals, the Knicks fell in seven games and Ewing
could not prevent Olajuwon from being selected the series' most
valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing won't have a hand in these Finals. But perhaps an upset
series victory by the Knicks could help change his legacy a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither one of us has won one yet,'' Ewing said of himself and
Robinson. ``At the end of this series one of us is going to walk
away knowing that they're the champions.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
