<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-HASEK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES' HASEK SURVIVES STARS' PUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jennifer Floyd 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Buffalo Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek gulped,
taking a deep breath as time expired in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   He had just spent 20 minutes flailing, sprawling and diving at
chance after chance being tossed his way by Stars players, and he
had survived.
</P>
<P>
   His survival led to a Sabres revival, a 2-1 victory last night
at Marine Midland Arena sending the best-of-seven Stanley Cup
Finals series back to Dallas for Game 5 tied 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember two, maybe three, good scoring chances for
Dallas,'' Sabres defenseman Jason Woolley said of that final-period
push. ``That's where Dom came up and made some big saves.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek had challenged his teammates to play more aggressive going
into Game 4. He said he'd handle any mistakes if his teammates were
too aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he said it all really,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said.
``He said what he said and what he said was `Bring it on.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Stars players brought ``it'' and a little more in the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres went into the third period with a 2-1 lead. The Stars
went into the third period with both sticks blazing. They outshot
the Sabres 13-2, including 5-0 in the first five minutes. The
Sabres didn't get their first shot on goal in the period until 6:27
remained.
</P>
<P>
   Sabres forward Randy Cunneyworth fired a shot on net that Erik
Rasmussen tipped right into the waiting hands of Stars goalie Ed
Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   The shots were 10-1 at that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't give them a lot of quality shots,'' Ruff said. ``We
gave them outside shots, and they came on hard. You have to give
them credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Stars chances were once again created by Joe
Nieuwendyk's line. He, along with Jamie Langenbrunner and Dave
Reid, were constantly providing Hasek with chances to bolster his
image as unbeatable when leading after two periods in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo goaltender has a 19-0 mark in playoff games when he
has a lead after two periods.
</P>
<P>
   Reid had an outstanding chance at 12:15, creeping from behind
Hasek and stepping into the slot. He tried to lift the puck high,
but Hasek got it with his leg pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the ones we have to have,'' Reid said. ``I
didn't get a good shot off.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's best save, though, came from a Sabres player other
than Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   The goaltender had come too far out of the net to challenge a
Langenbrunner rush, leaving the goal wide open. Langenbrunner
whipped a pass from behind the net that defenseman Craig Ludwig
corralled at the blue line. Ludwig turned and launched a shot but
Cunneyworth used his body as a buffer.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek was still scrambling to get back in net.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times we have sat back on leads in the third period,''
Sabres defenseman Jay McKee said. ``We talked about that on the
bench, and we came out and responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, too.
</P>
<P>
   He told his teammates that he'd have their backs, and he more
than delivered in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dominik's telling the team to be more aggressive,
\Rsaying\S `Don't worry I'll bail you out if you give up the
odd-man rush' ... you know he did that tonight,'' Geoff Sanderson
said. ``He made some great saves for us and he held us in the game
in the third period.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
