<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
 FINALS-TEX 
CAN THE BELEAGUERED KNICKS BIG MEN STOP SPURS' TOWERING DUO? (For
use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Even Don King would have trouble drumming up
enthusiasm for this NBA Finals mismatch:
</P>
<P>
   In the Spurs' corner, two of the most agile, productive
7-footers in the NBA. They combine to average 36 points, 20
rebounds and five blocks per game. Ladies and gentlemen, a former
MVP and a future MVP, David Robinson and Tim Duncan!
</P>
<P>
   And in the Knicks' corner, um, one of the worst shooters in NBA
history and another guy who a year ago was an assistant coach for
the Mavericks. Ladies and gentlemen, Chris Dudley and Kurt Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may seem like we should have our way, but the Knicks
wouldn't be here without those two guys,'' Robinson said. ``They're
physical, they've got a little mean streak and they don't give an
inch. We're not expecting it to be easy at all.''
</P>
<P>
   As if sneaking around as the Eastern Conference's eighth seed
and not having the homecourt advantage against a team that is 42-6
since March weren't enough, the New York Knicks will likely be
without their top two low-post players in Game 1 of the NBA Finals
against the Spurs Wednesday night at the Alamodome. Center Patrick
Ewing (Achilles' tendon) is definitely out for the series, and
forward Larry Johnson, fresh off his heroics in Games 3 and 5 of
the Eastern Conference finals, is questionable with a sprained
knee.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson can't play, Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy will attempt
to stop San Antonio's Twin Towers with Thomas on Duncan, Dudley on
Robinson and _ no kidding _ 38-year-old ex-Mavericks player Herb
Williams as a key reserve.
</P>
<P>
   With the Spurs' having lost only twice in the past two months,
most experts are predicting a speed bump of a series against a team
of Knick-knacks who, looking like an aging Ferrari with a busted
fan belt, seem one tweak away from suiting up Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a huge discrepancy in points in the paint, rebounds
or free throws, we're in big trouble,'' Van Gundy said. ``It's what
they thrive on, and so do we. Their size usually turns teams into
jump shooters. We can't win a series from the perimeter.''
</P>
<P>
   With the 29 points and 15 rebounds of Ewing-Johnson on the
bench, it's hard to imagine the Knicks denting San Antonio's Twin
Peaks. Of course, after a 27-23 regular season, it was difficult to
see the Knicks advancing past the first round, much less this far.
Not lost on the Spurs is the fact that during their run from
eight-to-great, the Knicks have disposed of star centers in Miami's
Alonzo Mourning, Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo and Indiana's Rik Smits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so active, they kept Smits in foul trouble the whole
series,'' Robinson said. ``And they kept Dikembe and Mourning under
wraps. We're talking about great players. Patrick won't be here,
but the rest of those guys are all about defense, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley, owner of possibly the ugliest free-throw motion in the
history of basketball, will likely bang with Robinson down low
while the more athletic Thomas will chase Duncan on the perimeter.
Williams has played only 13 minutes in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Expect New York to try to disrupt San Antonio's offense by
trapping the ball out of point guard Avery Johnson's hands, then
fronting Duncan or Robinson to make the Spurs throw lob passes over
the defense. Offensively, the Knicks must have spark plugs Latrell
Sprewell and Marcus Camby create points in the transition game and
not get caught up into a half-court game with the methodically
powerful Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio, meanwhile, will attempt to continue its strategy of
funneling the opponent toward shot-blockers Robinson and Duncan at
one end while feeding the 7-footers for easy shots or pass-out
3-pointers at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a scary team,'' Spurs point guard Avery Johnson said
of the Knicks. ``They believe in their destiny, and they're really
talking up that underdog stuff. We've got to stick with our plan
and plug up our ears or they can beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, who will have the support of 40,000 fans, also
realize the key to the Knicks' playoff upsets were victories in
Game 1 at Miami, Atlanta and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, two months ago they said we were a soft team going
nowhere,'' Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said. ``Now, those same
people are saying how we're like the old Celtics about to steamroll
to the title. Well, I don't buy that one either, and I hope our
players don't.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
