<HEADLINE>
IRVIN'S STATUS WITH COWBOYS STILL UNCERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ After being a no-show at the morning workout,
disgruntled receiver Michael Irvin was on the practice field for
the afternoon workout Tuesday as the Dallas Cowboys opened a
three-day minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   And he was looking and talking like the team's all-time leading
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   His situation, however, is far from resolved, even after a
nearly two-hour conversation with Cowboys owner Jerry Jones that
prevented Irvin from attending the opening workout at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into the status of where we are at this
time,'' Jones said. ``We had a good visit, and he will contribute
in camp this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The same, however, can't be said about linebacker Randall
Godfrey, who didn't practice Tuesday because he refused to accept
and sign the Cowboys' contract offer. The Cowboys don't know if
Godfrey, a restricted free agent, will sign before the end of
minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   As for Irvin, Jones said he would like to have the 12-year
veteran on the team in 1999 and possibly for the rest of his career
``under the right circumstances.'' However, he said Irvin's
presence at then minicamp should not be seen as an indication that
anything has been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, whose contract expires after this season, is miffed that
the Cowboys haven't offered him an extension. He has also given the
Cowboys permission to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, citing changes in the offense that don't rely on
one primary receiver and Irvin's age (33), want to wait until the
end of the season to talk about a contract beyond 1999. They have
also discussed Irvin in trade talks with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   And, a source said the Cowboys are even considering cutting him
if they feel his attitude will be counter-productive to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, declined to comment after the morning meeting, saying
``there was nothing to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   He jumped into his car and left. He returned a few hours later,
shielding himself from news media by entrance to the practice
field,]sandwiching himself between offensive linemen Everett McIver
and Erik Williams.
</P>
<P>
   During practice, Irvin caught a few passes and unleashed his
usual amount of trash talk.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey was pleased to see Irvin on the field
after he missed all of the team's voluntary workouts the past
couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like he was in good shape,'' Gailey said. ``He's got
a lot of catching up to do. But it's good to have him on the field
working out and playing hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said there was never any doubt Irvin would work hard.
Jones said there is just a question of how Irvin would mentally
handle his evolving role in the offense and the impact on his
contract situation because of the changed role.
</P>
<P>
   To Jones, the 1999 season is not an issue, as Irvin has a base
salary of $2.99 million. But Jones is not ready to discuss a
contract beyond 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing things differently than we did in 1992 and even
two years ago,'' Jones said. ``It's harder and harder to find a
team where one receiver gets all the balls. And he is working in
his mind on how this is going to work in the last year of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mike deserves and has earned the right to sort through
and feel comfortable with everything. He just needs to sort through
and get it together inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said of Godfrey, who believes the Cowboys' offer
of $429,000 for 1999 is unfair. Jones, however, said the team
doesn't plan to offer more. Godfrey's agent, Ben Dogra,
acknowledged that his client is still struggling with the offer,
but he believes Godfrey will likely sign at some point. He just
doesn't know when.
</P>
<P>
   While Gailey would like Godfrey on the field working to learn
the middle linebacker position _ after playing strongside
linebacker the past three seasons _ Jones said it would worry him
more if Godfrey was missing time at training camp. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
