<HEADLINE>
KINGS PURSUING PALFFY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kings' seemingly eternal quest to acquire a marquee player
has been anything but fruitful. Pavel Bure eluded their grasp, as
did Theo Fleury and Zigmund Palffy, leaving the Kings without the
showpiece player they covet for the opening of the Staples Center
in four months.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, however, has re-entered the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' Dave Taylor, in Buffalo for general managers'
meetings, confirmed Tuesday that he has had discussions with the
New York Islanders about a trade for Palffy, the New York
Islanders' high-scoring right wing.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN reported that the Islanders want right wing Pavel Rosa or
center Olli Jokinen, two of the Kings' best young players, for the
27-year-old Palffy.
</P>
<P>
   However, a source in New York said Rosa and Jokinen are not
involved in the discussions, but that the Kings are considering a
deal that would include several prospects, among them 1998
first-round draft choice Mathieu Biron, a defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also have the rights to 21-year-old defenseman Aki
Berg, who played this season in his native Finland. In dealing for
Palffy, the Kings also might receive 31-year-old defenseman Rich
Pilon, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as though the cash-strapped Islanders were a &UR; zQ
</P>
