<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-GRIEVANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS UNION FILES GRIEVANCE FOR MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The National Basketball Players Association filed a
grievance yesterday on behalf of the Mavericks, who were fined
$25,000 by the NBA last week for picking up the tab on a trip to
Hawaii for free-agent power forward Gary Trent and several members
of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Association spokesman Dan Wasserman said the league was out of
bounds for fining the Mavericks. Arbitrator Kenneth Dam, a law
professor from the University of Chicago, is to hear the case
within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Granik, NBA deputy commissioner and chief operating
officer, said Mavericks general manager Don Nelson violated the
salary cap and provisions of the collective-bargaining agreement by
paying for the trip to Maui, Hawaii, three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Wasserman said the fine violates procedures laid out in the
collective-bargaining agreement. Wasserman said charges pertaining
to salary-cap violations must be determined by an arbitrator _ not
by the league without a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a precedent, which we can't tolerate,'' Wasserman
said. ``Teams interested in free agents have frequently provided
transportation and lodging for a player and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruiting a player, speaking with a player and trying to
convince the player that signing with a team is in his best
interest, and trying to convince the player and his family that
living in a particular city is in his best interest, has never been
and is not a salary-cap violation.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
