<SLUG> BC-BKN-WHITT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS SAYS DEAL NEVER MADE WITH MAVS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Kurt Thomas spent Tuesday defending himself.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, he'll defend Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Texas for the first time since bolting the
Mavericks and signing a free-agent contract with the Knicks, the
former TCU star called Dallas coach and general manager Don Nelson
a liar while downplaying the Spurs' front line of Duncan and David
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   With Patrick Ewing out and Larry Johnson questionable for Game 1
Wednesday, Thomas likely will be New York's only low-post threat.
Defensively, look for him to start out guarding Duncan but switch
to Robinson at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played some pretty good centers in the playoffs and
found ways to not let them dominate us,'' Thomas said. ``I don't
see why that's going to change now.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who attended Dallas' Hillcrest High School before
leading the nation in scoring and rebounding at TCU, played in only
five games over two seasons for the Mavericks while recovering from
ankle fractures. Before training camp in January, Nelson said
Thomas verbally agreed to a one-year contract before flying to New
York less than 24 hours later and accepting a two-year, $4 million
deal with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's bull,'' said Thomas, who expects 30 family members and
friends at Wednesday's game. ``There were things still to be worked
out, and Nellie knows that. The Knicks made me a better offer, and
the Mavericks decided to shell out their money on Hot Rod Williams.
What can I say? This is a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who said he flirted with the idea of retiring after
suffering a third ankle injury while jogging at SMU in 1997, said
his daily routine now includes a good pinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed every day where I am,'' Thomas said. ``A lot of
people gave up on me, and it's a miracle that I'm back playing at
all. But not only that, here I am in the Finals.'' JOHNSON MIGHT
PLAY
</P>
<P>
   Knicks forward and Dallas native Larry Johnson remains a
game-time decision for Wednesday because of a sprained right knee.
Johnson, injured Friday in a game against Indiana, hobbled through
Tuesday's workout wearing a brace but said he won't really test the
knee as far as full-speed cutting and running until hours before
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worse than not playing would be to go out there and be able to
do only 70 percent of what I normally do,'' Johnson said. BEST AND
WORST
</P>
<P>
   Best omen for Spurs: All but one of the past 20 NBA champions
finished the regular season with one of the league's top three
records. Only the 1994-95 Rockets (10th) bucked the trend. The
Spurs had the league's best record, but the 27-23 Knicks could
become the team with the second-worst regular-season record to win
the NBA Finals, behind the 1977-78 Washington Bullets at 44-38.
</P>
<P>
   Worst predictions:] It was Portland's Damon Stoudamire who said
Spurs point guard Avery Johnson would never lead a team to the
Finals, and ditto for the Nets' Stephon Marbury about New York's
Charlie Ward and Chris Childs. ``That's why this world is so
crazy,'' Childs said. ``People flap their mouths without having a
clue about what they're talking about.'' NUMBERS GAME
</P>
<P>
   37-15: NBA Finals record of teams with the home-court advantage.
24 SECONDS
</P>
<P>
   While most of the country predicts a Spurs victory, Michael
Jordan picked the
</P>
<P>
   Knicks in six. ``After all those years of beating them, he's
probably just throwing them a bone,'' said Spurs guard and former
Jordan teammate Steve Kerr. ... Coaches Gregg Popovich and Jeff Van
Gundy never played in the NBA, marking the first Finals since
Boston's Bill Fitch and Houston's Del Harris in 1981 when neither
coach had playing experience. Popovich and Van Gundy were
assistants under Don Nelson at Golden State and New York. nn
</P>
