<SLUG> BC-GLF-CLOSE-CALLS-OPEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTGOMERIE, LEHMAN TIRING OF CLOSE CALLS IN OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jimmy Burch 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Colin Montgomerie folded his umbrella,
positioned himself on the interview dais and smiled broadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hear that?'' Montgomerie said, as the intensity of raindrops
falling on the clubhouse roof increased tenfold during a short
stretch yesterday. ``That's the sound of greens softening. It's a
beautiful noise.''
</P>
<P>
   For the hard-luck Scot, who is convinced that putting problems
have been his biggest stumbling block in winning an elusive U.S.
Open title, the pounding rains at Pinehurst No. 2 provided sweet
music. Montgomerie, 35, has finished as the Open runner-up twice in
the past five years, including a playoff loss to Ernie Els in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, his heartbreak pales in comparison to Tom Lehman, one of
only two men to play in the final group of the final round at four
consecutive Opens. Lehman has done so each year since 1995, with no
titles to show for his efforts. Bobby Jones also played in the
final group at four consecutive Opens but won two of those, in 1929
and 1930.
</P>
<P>
   Like Montgomerie, Lehman heads into tomorrow's opening round at
Pinehurst Resort and Country Club comfortable in the knowledge he
can handle a demanding course, but haunted by the near-victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you think about it,'' said Lehman, 40. ``You ask
yourself, `Is something missing in me? Is something missing in my
game?' I've been so close before, and this is the tournament I'd
like to win more than any other.
</P>
<P>
   ``After awhile, you realize, `I've played under a lot of heat.
I'm OK.' But sometimes you make the key putt. Sometimes, you
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players hope the rain-softened Pinehurst greens will help
them in this year's Open quest. Montgomerie, a two-time winner on
the European Tour this season, said a balky putter has dogged him
in more majors than the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   The worst case, he said, was the 1995 PGA Championship, when he
lost in a playoff to Steve Elkington. During the 72 holes of
regulation, Montgomerie took 17 more putts than Elkington. As a
result, Montgomerie _ star of Europe's 1997 Ryder Cup victory _ has
yet to win a tournament on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before my career finishes, I would like to win a tournament in
the U.S. Because I've come so close in this particular event, I'd
like to take that one step farther and make this the one,''
Montgomerie said. ``I've never blamed my long game, my driving or
my iron play for not winning in this country. It's always been that
I haven't holed out as well as the winner has.''
</P>
<P>
   In Montgomerie's estimation, Pinehurst's small greens _ now
slowed by rain, and with more showers in today's forecast _ could
be just the tonic for what has ailed his short game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to talk myself into believing that, so we'll see
what happens,'' said Montgomerie, who has finished first and fifth
in his past two starts in Europe. ``I don't think you come to this
tournament and find your game. You've got to bring your game with
you, and I'm certainly confident that I've brought a good game of
golf here.''
</P>
<P>
   So has Lehman, who finished second in Monday's rain-delayed
conclusion to the FedEx St. Jude Classic in Memphis, Tenn. After
celebrating his 40th birthday on March 7, however, Lehman said he
wonders how many more chances he will have to exorcise his Open
demons.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I'm hitting my stride, I'm turning 40,'' Lehman
said. ``I wish I could have some of those years in my early 30s
over, knowing what I know now. I feel like I have three or four
good years left. I just wish it was eight or nine.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Lehman hopes he will answer questions Sunday
about an Open achievement rather than another near-victory.
Montgomerie, rest assured, shares the same desire.
NEAR VICTORIES Between them, Colin Montgomerie and Tom Lehman have
eight finishes of sixth or better at the U.S. Open since 1992
without a victory. The breakdown: Finish Player Year (winner) 2nd
Montgomerie 1997 (Ernie Els) 2nd Lehman 1996 (Steve Jones) 2nd
Montgomerie 1994 (Ernie Els) 3rd Lehman 1997 (Ernie Els) 3rd Lehman
1995 (Corey Pavin) 3rd Montgomerie 1992 (Tom Kite) 5th Lehman 1998
(Lee Janzen) 6th Lehman 1992 (Tom Kite)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
