<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWNS ARE NERVOUSLY BECOMING AWARE OF PRESENCE OF PIPELINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When oil began flowing more than 30 years ago from the
Canadian border to the Columbia River, it passed under mostly rural
land.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Olympic Pipe Line Co. has neighbors _ a lot of them in
the Seattle area. In the communities that make up Seattle's booming
suburbs, houses and schools that have that paint-barely-dry look
flank the pipeline as it carries jet fuel, gasoline and diesel fuel
south.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, local leaders can only cringe over the
potentially dangerous coexistences.
</P>
<P>
   But not in North Bend, where town leaders are trying to keep a
pipeline out before it is even built.
</P>
<P>
   Town leaders say they have no intention of welcoming Olympic to
North Bend, a community in the foothills of the Cascade mountain
range, about 30 miles southeast of Seattle. They want the company's
pipeline kept out of town or at least confined to a corridor
running along Interstate 90.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Olympic, even as it tries to repair the damage done to its
image after the deadly explosion of its pipeline in Bellingham last
week, won't stand for being told to get out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the company have filed a petition with a regional
growth-management board, asking it to rule that North Bend's
passing of an ordinance forbidding fuel pipelines in the town runs
afoul of state law. The pipeline, Olympic lawyers have argued, is
an essential public facility that North Bend may not like but can't
keep out. Under the ordinance, passed by the North Bend City
Council on April 6, if pipelines are deemed ``essential public
facilities,'' then they would have to run along I-90 inside the
city limits but away from residential development.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic objects to North Bend's ordinance because transportation
officials don't like pipelines along interstates, said Joann
Hamick, a spokeswoman for Olympic. Such an arrangement would keep
the interstate from being expanded, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other problem is that this sets a bad precedent for the
entire pipeline industry,'' she said. ``We go into cities. We make
deliveries in cities. It's where the automobiles are and where the
terminals are.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of a pipeline and residential developments has
worried safety watchdogs for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pipelines transport about 57 percent of the crude petroleum
and petroleum products moved within the United States,'' the
National Transportation Safety Board noted in a 1996 report on
pipeline safety. ``The potential threat to public safety from such
releases has become more severe in recent years, as residential and
commercial development adjacent to all types of pipelines has
accelerated.''
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB has urged regulators to make tougher rules for
pipelines in populated areas. It has recommended, for example, that
sturdier pipe be used in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   But the branch of the U.S. Transportation Department that
regulates pipelines doesn't regulate what sort of building or
development can take place near them.
</P>
<P>
   And while the state won't allow a structure to be built on a
pipeline, it doesn't try to control how close to the line a
structure can be located. Those decisions are left up to local
jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   Many communities do little more than keep buildings out of the
rights of way.
</P>
<P>
   The sometimes tragic results can be seen in neighborhoods like
those along Whatcom Creek in Bellingham, where a leak of gasoline
from the Olympic pipeline ignited Thursday and killed a teenager
and two boys.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the houses nearby were built after the 34-year-old
pipeline had been installed.
</P>
<P>
   East of Lake Washington in King County, houses routinely rise up
along the Olympic pipeline and its right of way.
</P>
<P>
   In Renton, where fuel has been flowing since 1965, Mayor Jesse
Tanner said he would never let another pipeline in, if he could
prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   But, Tanner said, ``Frankly, there's nothing I can do about it
now. It goes through residential neighborhoods and will continue to
go through residential neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   The rupture and fire in Bellingham shows the worst that can
happen. But fires following pipeline leaks are rare, though experts
say the chances for an explosion are greater in an urban area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're out in the desert somewhere, and there's no human
for literally miles, they will find the leak before an ignition,''
said John Wagner, a professor at Texas A&AMP;M University who teaches
safety engineering and industrial hygiene. But the odds are greater
that something will occur to ignite the leaking petroleum in an
urban area before the rupture is discovered or stopped, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive power of gasoline vapor is such that a seemingly
benign electric spark created by turning on a flashlight or
cellular telephone could ignite it, Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, all you need (for an explosion) is sufficient fuel
mixed with air. For gasoline, because it has a very low flash
point, that occurs at all temperatures down to minus 40 degrees
Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner has also been a consultant to groups opposed to a
pipeline that Olympic wants to build across the Cascades to Pasco.
</P>
<P>
   The cities and towns along the pipeline also worry about
something less severe than fire.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 in Renton, a small leak in the Olympic pipeline under
the Maplewood neighborhood went undetected for nine months. By the
time it was discovered, more than 80,000 gallons had leaked.
</P>
<P>
   Residue from the leak remains and probably will for years to
come, Tanner said.
</P>
<P>
   Renton has tried to make the pipeline safer, negotiating to get
enhancements when Olympic's franchise is about to expire. Recently,
for example, the city got the Renton-based company to agree to
remote-control valves that will block the flow in the event of a
leak, Tanner said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Bellingham fire, he said, Renton officials are
investigating how they can make the pipeline safer.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cascade foothills, town leaders have a different problem.
Olympic wants its proposed 231-mile pipeline from Woodinville to
Pasco to run through or near the towns.
</P>
<P>
   Their response is simple. ``We flat don't want it in our town,''
said Phil Messina, North Bend's city administrator.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline would pass just outside Carnation, through the
outskirts of Snoqualmie and by two of its schools, then through
downtown North Bend.
</P>
<P>
   In Carnation, officials worry about leaks in the Tolt River. In
Snoqualmie, it's the Snoqualmie River that causes worries, said
Mayor Fuzzy Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline would pass within 200 feet or less of North Bend
Elementary School and Two Rivers Alternative High School, Messina
said. It would pass through downtown North Bend under an abandoned
railroad bed that has since become the Snoqualmie Valley hiking
trail.
</P>
<P>
   Hamick, the company spokeswoman, said state law requires that
pipeline companies try to run their lines in conjunction with other
utilities. In North Bend, it has proposed running its pipeline
where power lines run.
</P>
<P>
   The three towns recently sent a letter to Gov. Gary Locke, who
has the final say on the proposed pipeline, and asked him to reject
it.
</P>
<P>
   By passing its ordinance, North Bend went one step further.
</P>
<P>
   State growth-management laws say cities can't keep out such
essential facilities like airports, colleges prisons or
drug-treatment hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic has told the Central Puget Sound Growth Management
Hearings Board that its proposed pipeline fits in with those
essential facilities and that the North Bend ordinance essentially
forbids the pipeline by confining it to one location.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in North Bend have different thoughts on the matter.
``This is a private, profit-making pipeline,'' Messina said. ``It's
not a public facility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
