<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY BENCHED IN SHAKEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Not one to sit and watch his team flounder in
frustration, manager Davey Johnson shook up the Dodgers on Tuesday
by benching catcher Todd Hundley and banishing Darren Dreifort to
the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's spot in the rotation will be taken by rookie
right-hander Jamie Arnold, who will start Saturday against
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Angel Pena takes over the daily catching duties. Hundley
will serve as a pinch-hitter and spell Pena while working his sore
throwing elbow into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the right thing to do,'' Hundley said. ``The best
thing is to step back and get back to basics, good mechanics, get
my arm back in shape. It's muscle memory. It's doing it over and
over and over again. I think, subconsciously, my brain is trying to
protect my elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mechanically, it's been brutal. You have to deal with reality.
I haven't been myself defensively. I have to get my arm in catching
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the team considered placing Hundley on the disabled
list. Hundley, recovering from reconstructive elbow surgery in
September of 1997, said he wanted to remain with the club. He said
he's treating the situation like a mini-spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still some soreness in the elbow we've been
fighting,'' Hundley said. ``It's not tendon or ligament soreness.
It's muscle soreness, which is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley has lived up to his reputation for being an hard worker,
but it hasn't translated into better defense. He missed most of
spring training working, and hasn't caught up.
</P>
<P>
   The catching situation hit bottom Sunday against Oakland when
Hundley threw wildly to first base after a wild pitch on a third
strike. Hundley's ninth error allowed two runs to score. Also,
runners have stolen 53 bases in 60 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Hundley developed the longer throwing motion when
he tried to play outfield for the Mets last season. To remedy it,
Hundley will work with bullpen catcher Rick Dempsey. The two spent
nearly an hour before Tuesday's game working on mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do Camp Dempsey,'' Johnson said. ``He's in
rehab for me. I'll keep him here and I can still use his bat.
Hopefully, it'll give him time to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, who's making $5.3 million this season, was acquired in
a deal that sent Gold Glove catcher Charles Johnson to the Mets
(who traded him to Baltimore). He was supposed to supply power from
the left side, but he's hitting a combined .248 with seven homers
and 18 RBI as a lefty. Pena, 24, is hitting .237 with three RBI in
12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Johnson elected to send the control-plagued Dreifort
to the bullpen instead of lefty Carlos Perez because he thinks
Dreifort can help more there.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort, who declined to talk speak with reporters, and Perez
both have been terrible of late. Perez is 2-8 with a 7.18 ERA and
lasted just 21/3 innings in his last start. Dreifort, a former
reliever, is 5-5 with a 6.42 ERA but is averaging slightly more
than five innings a start.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson talked about using Dreifort out of the bullpen in the
spring, but was advised against it. Dreifort had reconstructive
elbow surgery in 1995, and team physicians feared his arm wouldn't
respond to pitching in relief. Johnson said he talked to the
Dodgers medical staff, which gave the move the OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``He screams out to me, `Late-innings guy,' and I can't get to
him there as a starter,'' Johnson said. ``I know this will help my
bullpen. I don't abuse my pitchers. It's easier for him with work
out of the pen than it is to start, and if not, I'll reverse it.
He's got a valuable arm and I want to use it. I don't see where
Perez can do that much for me in the pen. Dreifort can. Carlos has
to do it starting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
