<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS RELEASE SUALUA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Clarence E. Hill Jr. and Jeff Caplan 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys released fullback Nicky Sualua
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Sualua has received a lot of negative attention since the death
of former tackle Mark Tuinei last month. Sualua, a two-year
veteran, was with Tuinei the night when the tackle died after using
heroin and designer drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones said, however, that the little-used fullback
was released because of ``football considerations'' only. The
Cowboys say they'll save $231,000 against the salary cap by
releasing Sualua.
Minicamp opens
</P>
<P>
   The first day of minicamp finished far less dramatic than it
began when Michael Irvin failed to show for the morning session of
two-a-days. With Irvin back in the fold in the afternoon, it was a
typically hot day of workouts that kicked off the drive to the July
26 opening of training camp in Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day, six-practice minicamp continues today and
tomorrow at the Cowboys' Valley Ranch practice facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went a lot better than the one last year, that's for sure,
but it wasn't where I hoped to be,'' coach Chan Gailey said. ``This
is just a glimpse of what it's going to be like in training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sessions concentrated on conditioning as well as offensive,
defensive and special-teams drills. Gailey said he was most
impressed with the ``way the defense moved around'' and a ``solid
day of work from the kicking game.''
Sanders ready for new deal
</P>
<P>
   Injured cornerback Deion Sanders said he was pleased to hear
that Jones has decided to work on signing him to a contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, expected to be sidelined four to six months after toe
surgery April 27, said he's confident that a deal can be worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, 31, is scheduled to earn $6.5 million next season. The
Cowboys want to restructure his contract to free up money to sign
their rookie draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   Any extension would probably be a multiyear deal that gives
Sanders a larger signing bonus and lower base salary, which would
clear salary-cap room for the Cowboys and give Sanders the security
of finishing his career with the team.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
