<HEADLINE>
POSTPONEMENT AT CWS GIVES RICE MANAGER OPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Heavy rains moved in Tuesday and shoved the
College World Series schedule back 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's schedule, Rice (59-14) against Alabama (52-15) at 2:30
p.m. and Cal State Fullerton (50-13) against Florida State (54-13)
at 6:30, has been rescheduled for Wednesday, weather permitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only thing I don't like about baseball, being
subject to the effects of weather,'' Owls coach Wayne Graham said.
``But maybe that's part of its charm.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, this is the first time in 74 games this year that
the Owls have had weather problems.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rice could now pitch Mario Ramos (13-2) with four days'
rest against Alabama, Graham said he is ``leaning toward'' Jeff
Nichols (15-4), who has worked three innings in two relief
appearances. A third possibility would be Marc Gwyn (7-1), who
pitched two-thirds of an inning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The single games scheduled for Wednesday and Thursday will now
be compacted into a doubleheader tomorrow, with the Rice-Alabama
winner facing Miami at 2:30 p.m. and the Fullerton-Florida State
winner meeting Stanford at 7:30 p.m. RICE RECAP
</P>
<P>
   Watching the steady drizzle fall out of a cold, gloomy sky
Tuesday, Rice athletic director Bobby May reflected on the state of
the Owls at this juncture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great year,'' he said. ``We have more wins (59)
than we've ever had, and we won another regional, which was great.
Then we got to host the Super Regional in the Astrodome, which was
a first, and a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're back here for the second time, and we finally got
our first win up here, beating Oklahoma State. We need more wins
like that. It was a big hump, and we're over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if we can just play well ... every day ... there's a
chance. That would really be something, if we made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never won a national championship _ in anything.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Owls, who lost their opening game, can come back and win
it all, they will join a select group. It's only happened twice,
but the most recent occasion was last year, when Southern Cal lost
its opener and then reeled off five consecutive wins.
</P>
<P>
   The only other teams to accomplish the feat were Arizona in 1980
and Cal State Fullerton in '79.
</P>
<P>
   May, however, is willing to make any sacrifice to make it
happen. Asked why, on a chilly day, he was attired in slacks,
moccasins and no socks, he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I wore last night,'' he said, ``when we won.''
SHUTOUTS SHUT OUT
</P>
<P>
   Although no one is expecting a repeat of last year's 21-14 title
game, neither is there any great expectation of a goose egg war.
</P>
<P>
   The last shutout game in CWS play was in 1995, when Cal State
Fullerton beat Tennessee, 11-0.
</P>
<P>
   The last complete-game shutout was pitched by Georgia Tech's
Brad Rigby, who blanked Fullerton, 2-0, in 1994. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
