<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Djakovica, Yugoslavia) _ The Serbs' most brutal
force in their campaign to drive out Kosovo's ethnic Albanian
majority fell on this city and a swath of villages around it in the
shadow of the Accursed Mountains. On Tuesday, in a landscape of
gravesites, burned homes, toppled mosque minarets and smashed shops
it became clear just how ferocious that campaign had been. By John
Kifner and Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ End of war leaves Russians fed up with
an overbearing West. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GA-RAPE-DNA (Atlanta) _ Calvin Johnson, a black man convicted of
rape 17 years ago in Clayton County, Ga., will be freed after new
DNA testing shows he could not have been the attacker. His case was
taken up by the Innocence Project, run by Barry Scheck, Peter
Neufeld, etc., who say Johnson has been in prison longer than any
of the 40 prisoners they've exonerated. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS _ What may be one of the last great health care
struggles of the Clinton administration _ providing a major new
drug benefit for older Americans _ has begun on Capitol Hill. And
the politics around it are so ferocious, so inextricably linked to
the battle over control of the House and the White House, and so
reminiscent of health care battles past, that no one is quite sure
whether the end result will be a policy or a campaign issue. By
Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS _ The proposed anti-violence legislation and the
politics of gun control in the House. Representatives from cities
are mostly for gun control while those from the south mostly
against, and the suburban districts are the pivots. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-VALLEY (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ In Silicon Valley, these
are the days of miracles and wonder. In the midst of the longest
sustained boom in the nation's high-technology heartland, there is
an air of unreality that has come to color the outlook of the
computer engineers, venture capitalists and software hackers,
leading to a growing sense of unease ``The valley is now divided
into two camps,'' said John Shoch, a partner at Alloy Ventures,
``there are those people who are firmly inside a reality-distortion
field, and there are the rest of us who realize that this is going
to end but who can't help going along for the ride.'' By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-HEALTHCARE (Undated) _ Millions of people across Latin
America are, for better or worse, getting a taste of North
American-style health insurance. Pushed by the rising expectations
of a growing middle class, countries in the region are opening
their government-dominated health systems to private companies,
both domestic and foreign. Some of the biggest North American
insurers are actively testing the waters from Mexico to Argentina,
Brazil and Chile. By Milt Freudenheim and Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-REPUBS (Washington) _ Al Gore may not have invented the
Internet, but he and President Clinton clearly perfected the skill
of extracting political contributions from Silicon Valley. Now, in
a three-day ``high-tech summit'' on Capitol Hill, Republicans are
trying to show that they have the capacity to be even better
friends of Bill Gates and his competitors. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-STANLEY (New York) _ A self-styled whistle-blower whose
dealings with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter put them both under
criminal investigation has had a previous tussle with corporate
America. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
