<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6965 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-AZR &LR;      06-16 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET BOOTING UP AS POLITICAL TOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet has arrived on the national political scene. Every
serious presidential candidate has a Web site. Volunteers are being
organized by e-mail. Money is being raised in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Vice President Al Gore will announce his candidacy
for president with a so-called cybercast _ a broadcast carried on
the Internet and viewed on personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the Internet will play a bigger role in 2000 than
ever before, as candidates learn how to make the electronic
universe work for them. But it isn't going to transform American
politics overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the Internet going to have the impact that television did
in 1960?'' asked David Haase, an expert on politics on the
Internet. ``Almost certainly not.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, a televised debate between Richard Nixon and John F.
Kennedy changed American politics forever. Under the harsh TV
lights, Nixon's 5 o'clock shadow turned off voters, while Kennedy
looked young and vibrant.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet won't hold that kind of sway until it becomes as
pervasive as television or the telephone, experts say. Right now,
40 percent of the population doesn't have Internet access, and many
others are using old technology that makes Web surfing slow and
clunky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not there yet,'' said Rob Kubasko, an ASU Web site
designer who helped build Bob Dole's campaign site in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now is definitely the time to innovate, and now is the
time to pioneer. . . . Just like when Kennedy and Nixon got on TV
for the first time, it took candidates a while to understand (the
medium.)''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is becoming an effective fund-raising tool, because
it allows contributors to give by using credit cards. The practice
got a boost last week when the Federal Election Commission made
such donations eligible for federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also allows candidates to communicate directly with
voters with an unfiltered message.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be able to get informed where they want it and
when they want it,'' said Bill Lewis, vice provost for information
technology at ASU, ``instead of having to wait until it comes on
TV, or they go to a forum or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said good Web sites will help a candidate, and bad ones
can damage them.
</P>
<P>
   As a success story, some point to Republican Pat Buchanan's Web
site (www.gopatgo2000.org), which isn't fancy but stays on message
and works to rally the troops.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the spectrum is Republican John Kasich's
site, a collection of snapshots that includes a complete bio of the
family pet, a springer spaniel named Penny Bird. Making matters
worse, Kasich selected a domain name similar to a looming computer
worry (www. k2k.org).
</P>
<P>
   Other sites run the gamut. Democrat Bill Bradley
(www.billbradley. com) includes a long biography with pictures of
his basketball days with the U.S. Olympic team and the New York
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush has sparred with the creator of a
parody site (www.gwbush.com), which bears a striking resemblance to
the Republican's real site (www. georgewbush.com).
</P>
<P>
   The parody site plans to sell T-shirts emblazoned with Bush's
now-celebrated quote about the site: ``There ought to be limits to
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle's site (www.quayle.org) focuses
on political philosophy, saying Quayle wants to ``resurrect Ronald
Reagan's vision of government that will `stand by our side, not
ride on our back.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole's site (www. edole2000.org) trumpets Dole's
appearance on Rosie O'Donnell's show and her ``virtual college
commencement speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his claim of inventing the Internet, Vice President Al
Gore's site (www.algore2000.com) is relatively plain. One feature
is the text of Gore's Graceland College commencement speech last
month. There is also a Gore parody site (www.allgore.com).
</P>
<P>
   Republican John McCain's site (www.mccain2000.com) includes
video footage of McCain as a child and as a Navy pilot captured by
the North Vietnamese. But people with slow modems and old software
won't be able to view it, Haase said.
</P>
<P>
   Web designer Kubasko said some campaigns are mistakenly filling
their sites with staggering amounts of useless information instead
of supplying simple, strong messages about candidates and their
views.
</P>
<P>
   Kubasko noted that Steve Forbes has spent nearly $1.5 million on
his site (www.forbes2000.com), which is very busy and full of
gimmicks like his ``e-Precinct,'' a club to basically to help
Forbes gather e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   While Web pages are neat _ every serious candidate has one _
e-mail and discussion groups are much more critical to candidates,
said Haase, who until recently wrote a syndicated column called
``Plugged-In Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   With e-mail, candidates can contact supporters and potential
volunteers virtually for free, instead of spending critical
campaign funds on postage. By using discussion groups, candidates
can tap into issues and hear from voters.
</P>
<P>
   One Internet success story is Jesse Ventura, the former
professional wrestler elected governor of Minnesota, who used
e-mail masterfully in the final days of his campaign while he
zigzagged across the state last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were literally organizing events and trying to round up
turnout two towns away. . . . They were (sending e-mail), saying,
`Hey we're 15 miles away,' '' Haase said.
</P>
<P>
   For the political junkie, there are plenty of sites that dig as
deep into politics as anyone would want to go.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the better clearinghouse sites, where people can find
links to almost every political site, include Politics1
(www.politics1.com/p2000. htm), Political Junkie (www.
politicaljunkie.com) and White House 2000 (www.niu.edu/
newsplace/whitehouse.html).
</P>
<P>
   For hard-core political analysis, including campaign finance and
candidate profiles, people can try Project Vote Smart
(www.vote-smart.org/ce), FECInfo (www.tray. com/fecinfo) or the
Center for Responsive Politics (www.
opensecrets.org/home/index.asp).
</P>
<P>
   And for dirty laundry on the candidates, as well as some links
to humor sites, try the Skeleton Closet (www.realchange.org).
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Internet's impact, people ultimately will be better
informed, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be able to allow a larger percentage of
the electorate to be an educated electorate,'' Lewis said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Muller can be reached at (602) 444-8178 or at
bill.muller(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
