<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD DAY FOR DODGERS, BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Remember Sunday in Oakland, when it couldn't get
worse for the Dodgers?
</P>
<P>
   It got worse. Much worse. The man who's been the steadying force
through the mayhem did the Dodgers starters' strut, not lasting
very long.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown had one of the worst outings of his career, allowing
eight runs in three innings as the Pittsburgh Pirates blasted the
Dodgers 11-1 Tuesday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (29-33) have lost four straight, 10 of 13 and all
four they've played against the financially challenged Pirates this
season. Pittsburgh hit five homers, three of which came off Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 9-3 fiasco came after a team meeting. Tuesday's
browbeating came on the heels of the Dodgers' making a minor trade
to acquire Craig Counsell and manager Davey Johnson announcing Todd
Hundley was being benched and Darren Dreifort sent to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   And Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone, returning from Vero
Beach, Fla., walked into the ballpark just in time to see first
baseman Eric Karros throw wildly to home in a failed attempt to
nail Al Martin at the plate in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for the fans,'' Malone said. ``It's discouraging,
it's upsetting, it's frustrating. When you look at the talent we
have and don't see a performance that equates to the talent, it's
puzzling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to figure out how to get out of this rut. Players have
to figure out what they can do to get this thing going. We're here
to support them. If we have the talent, and it's comparable to that
of other baseball clubs, why aren't we performing? This is
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hurts. This hurts us a lot. (From) the president (Bob
Graziano) to myself to Bill Geivett (assistant to the general
manager) to the manager and the coaches, this is painful.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Brown (7-4) was supposed to provide a reprieve. He
was 5-1 after Dodgers' losses and stopped three-game losing streaks
in his last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   But two pitches into the game you could tell this wasn't his
night. Brown's first pitch was hit by Martin for a double. His
second one was hit out of the ballpark by Ed Sprague as the Pirates
took a 2-0 lead. Kevin Young hit a solo homer two batters later to
make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   It got worse in the second when Brown walked Martin with one out
and Sprague singled. Brian Giles then grounded to Karros, who threw
the ball to the left and out of catcher Angel Pena's reach to allow
Martin to score and put runners on second and third.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Brown committed the gaffe. Jason Kendall hit a
comebacker, but instead of checking the runner at third Brown
apparently lost track of the number of outs and flipped the ball to
first for the second out. Sprague scored and Brown, realizing his
mistake, hunched over behind the mound. Warren Morris added an
RBI-single to give the Pirates a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Martin then hit a two-out homer in the third inning, the third
homer Brown allowed. After yielding eight homers with the San Diego
Padres last season, Brown has given up 12 this season. In three
innings he allowed eight runs (four earned) on eight hits.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd grew so restless with the Dodgers that it mockingly
gave a standing ovation when Pirates starter Todd Ritchie (6-4)
wild pitched Devon White home in the seventh for the Dodgers' only
run.
</P>
<P>
   Brant Brown and Kendall also homered for the Pirates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
