<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON MAY BE SORRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Hollywood had been smart, it would have beaten
Jerry Buss to the bank vault and offered Phil Jackson the moon, his
own star on the Walk of Fame and whatever else it took so he'd do
its bidding in the hallowed halls of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's lobbying for the Lakers' head coaching job was
cunning. It was so politically artful it was easy to turn a blind
eye to the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   The machinations that have married Jackson to the Lakers _ the
formal ceremony is today, at the Beverly Hilton _ weren't set into
motion last week when the courting began in earnest or even last
month when the Lakers were swept out of the postseason for the
second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have been in Jackson's crosshairs for more than a
year. Buss' luxury liner was sailing along pretty smoothly under
Del Harris' command in the spring of 1998 when Jackson _ who was
well on his way to a sixth NBA championship title as coach of the
Chicago Bulls _ gently rocked the boat.
</P>
<P>
   He told a magazine reporter he had watched Lakers center
Shaquille O'Neal commit a foul wholly out of anger in a home loss
to Phoenix and then snap at Harris on the bench when the coach
tried to explain to the petulant O'Neal the error of his ways.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it doesn't take a Zen master to recognize that no official
can unnerve O'Neal unless he allows it. Alas, after seven seasons
in the NBA, O'Neal seems to be the last to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   As he watched O'Neal unravel that night, Jackson was quoted as
saying, ``It didn't frighten me, but it was a warning signal: Is
this kid smart enough yet to know what he can and can't do in this
game to become a winner? I see that as a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes time, running off two coaches, but all these months
later the challenge finally is his. Be careful what you wish for,
is all we have to say.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson thought the Bulls front office was a load, just wait
until he sees Tex Winter's triple-post offense become the Bermuda
Triangle in O'Neal's needy hands. Remember, in the Spurs' four-game
sweep of the Lakers in the Western Division semifinals, O'Neal had
two assists.
</P>
<P>
   In O'Neal, we're talking about a player who thinks a varied
offense means he dunks one time down the court, flips in a hook on
the next possession and makes a baby jumper after that.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what he says, his game doesn't lie. To watch O'Neal
hold onto defensive rebounds under the basket so the fast break
can't go on without him, or force a shot rather than kick the ball
out to the perimeter, is to understand that in his mind, his
teammates exist to make him better.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven help Jackson in getting it through O'Neal's stubborn
skull that it has to be the other way around if the Lakers are
going to be anything but also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has yet to prove himself smart enough to do the little
things it takes to become a winner _ such as sink free throws with
any consistency and play defense with any compulsion. Too bad the
7-foot-1 center exerts his will more forcefully off the court than
on it.
</P>
<P>
   It was O'Neal who hastened Harris' departure by tuning him out,
and he turned on Harris' replacement, Kurt Rambis, so fast Rambis'
head must have been spinning like a basketball (it does seem O'Neal
is collecting coaches' heads these days).
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal championed the pursuit of Jackson as he did the promotion
of Rambis. It could be a short honeymoon, unless O'Neal looks long
and hard enough in the mirror to recognize that his game has warts.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who's barking orders from the sideline, it'll be the
same old Lakers that haven't advanced to the finals since 1991 as
long as O'Neal blames the head coach and/or his teammates for the
team's failings.
</P>
<P>
   Until he can sink seven free throws out of 10 without blinking;
until he becomes a student of defense; until he has the good sense
not to pose with a rap star for the cover of a sports magazine; as
long as his name graces more albums than NBA title rosters, O'Neal
shouldn't even think about passing the buck.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jackson will be able to hold O'Neal's attention for more
than two minutes. O'Neal and Jackson aren't so different, when it
comes right down to it. They are different sides of the same
hubris.
</P>
<P>
   For all his talk about winning NBA titles, O'Neal showed this
season that as long as he gets his 30 points and 10 rebounds, he
can live with himself (Harris, Rambis, Eddie Jones and Elden
Campbell, on the other hand, had to go).
</P>
<P>
   And for all his metaphysical musings and spiritual wanderings,
Jackson has demonstrated recently that he is very much a child of
the corporal world. Nobody but a true egocentric would have been
caught dead dining with Knicks president Dave Checketts as long as
Jeff Van Gundy was ensconced at the end of the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson apparently forgot how miffed he was when he found out
the Bulls had interviewed Tim Floyd for Jackson's job even as he
was doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Oh well. It'll help having a short memory when coaching the
Lakers. Better to forget the way things were in L.A. in the '80s,
or in Chicago in the '90s, than to have them as a constant reminder
of the way things aren't. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
