r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR &LR;      06-16 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDANT TO TAKE STAND IN SLEEPWALKING TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Scott Falater, the electronics engineer who says he
was sleepwalking when he stabbed his wife 44 times, will take the
witness stand Wednesday in a high-risk effort to persuade a
Maricopa County Superior Court jury that he is innocent of
premeditated murder.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Michael Kimerer confirmed Tuesday that he would
call Falater to bolster a defense that has effectively assumed the
burden of disproving the prosecution's charge.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer declined to elaborate, but before the trial he spoke
about the importance of testimony from a defendant who offers such
an unusual defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case like this, the jury wants to hear from the
defendant, to evaluate what he says and to judge him as a man,''
Kimerer said. Falater's testimony, first with his own attorneys and
then with combative prosecutor Juan Martinez, will likely climax a
trial that has already heard from relatives, friends and colleagues
at Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   They testified that Falater's bloody violence in 1997 seemed to
come from nowhere, contradicting everything they knew about a
devout Mormon who was known for kindness and decency. Several
described Falater as a harmless ``nerd.''
</P>
<P>
   Other key defense witnesses were two renowned sleep disorders
experts, including one who said Tuesday that she believed so
strongly in Falater's case that she was helping the defense for
free.
</P>
<P>
   To support their opinions that Falater was sleepwalking, the
experts cited his history of childhood sleepwalking, sophisticated
hospital sleep studies, and what they called the bizarre, illogical
nature of his behavior that night.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's expert was Rosalind Cartwright, director of a Chicago
sleep disorder center, who said she has studied hundreds of cases
of sleepwalking violence.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Falater's case compared to the others, she responded,
``I believe he's the purest case I've seen with an act of violence
of this kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the jury will have its chance to take the measure of
Falater, 43, who is hoping to establish reasonable doubt about the
prosecution's claim that he knowingly and deliberately attacked his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Falater claims to have no memory of the attack, which his
attorneys say occurred during a sleepwalking episode that lasted 45
to 50 minutes. He is expected to talk at length about his 20-year
marriage to Yarmila, who was his high school sweetheart and the
mother of his two children.
</P>
<P>
   Both children, 17-year-old Megan and 15-year-old Michael,
testified that their parents had a loving, harmonious marriage that
had never before been marred by violence.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, however, has suggested that the Falater marriage was
under severe strain. Under his questioning, several defense
witnesses acknowledged that Yarmila sometimes complained about the
demands of the Mormon Church, where Scott was an enthusiastic
member.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez will present most of his case with rebuttal witnesses,
who will take the stand after Falater. The assistant county
attorney has lined up his own sleep experts, as well as some
witnesses who are expected to testify about signs of trouble in the
Falater marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez on Tuesday sparred with Cartwright, especially about
her testimony that she needed ``eyeball to eyeball contact'' to
determine if a subject had been sleepwalking at the time of a
violent act.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to be confident that this is someone who is not
pulling the wool over your eyes, is not a liar or con man or making
up a story,'' Cartwright told Kimerer. She said she had concluded
that Falater ``was not malingering.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez launched his cross-examination by showing the jury a
report Cartwright submitted before she met Falater. ``I think he
suffered from a sleep disorder, and I would be willing to render
this opinion under oath,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   With that evidence, Martinez dramatized a persistent theme in
his questioning of defense witnesses: that they jumped too quickly
to a conclusion and had been conned by a manipulative murderer.
</P>
<P>
   In his earlier questioning of Cartwright, Kimerer sought to
present her as a conscientious citizen-scientist who had come
forward to assist a man she believed had been wrongly accused.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright, a psychologist, said if she decides that a
sleepwalking defense is valid she has a ``duty as a citizen to help
that person any way I can.'' She said she has two principal
motivations: to help the sleepwalker and to educate the public
about sleepwalking violence.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright acknowledged a third motivation, which was both
professional and personal. ``Each case teaches us something,'' she
said. ``It's a privilege to work with these people and learn from
them.'' &QL; 
Jerry Kammer can be reached at (602) 444-8185 or at
jerry.kammer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
