<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS TRADE FOR COUNSELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The acquisition of second baseman Craig Counsell
from the Florida Marlins may be a small move in trying to cure
what's wrong with the Dodgers, but it is symbolic in why it was
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a baseball player,'' said Dodgers general manager Kevin
Malone, pointing out that's different than a guy who plays
baseball. ``We need baseball players, guys that are hard-nosed,
execute the fundamentals, play the game. He's a good fit for us. A
left-handed hitter, knows how to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers traded for Counsell, who scored the winning run in
Game 7 of the 1997 World Series, for a player to be named later on
Tuesday. Counsell was used as a pinch-hitter against Pittsburgh at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said they did it for depth in the infield and to give the
Dodgers the option of using another left-handed bat against tough
right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the limited level of talent we have at the minor-league
level, we do what we can do to get better,'' Malone said. ``Craig
Counsell makes us a little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   Counsell was eager to get to Los Angeles. He asked the Marlins
to be traded after he lost his starting second base job to Luis
Castillo. Counsell was particularly upset after he was the victim
of a defensive replacement when the Marlins were leading a game
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he could use Counsell as a
defensive replacement late in games, and to rest the Young at
second.
</P>
<P>
   Young has been hampered injuries for much of the last month.
Counsell, 28, was hitting .152 in 37 games for the Marlins before
being designated for assignment Friday. He's a lifetime .253 hitter
with a .990 fielding percentage. Counsell makes $245,000 this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to have (Young) out there when he has a broken
ankle or he was out of gas,'' Johnson said. ``He was a perfect
fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said the move wasn't a precursor to trading any of the
middle infielders _ Young, Jose Vizcaino or injured Mark
Grudzielanek. However, he did say Counsell had the capability to
play every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the right spot, on the right club, he's an everyday
player,'' Malone said. ``At this point in time, he's a quality
extra infielder.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a reunion for Counsell, who was greeted by former
Marlins teammate Kevin Brown in the clubhouse. Gary Sheffield and
Devon White also played with Counsell in Florida and Eric Young and
outfielder Trenidad Hubbard know him from their Colorado Rockies
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I wasn't getting an opportunity (in Florida) and I
asked to be traded,'' Counsell said. ``It wasn't a good situation
for both of us. But this is a team (the Dodgers) that has a chance
to win, or should win. I've won a World Series and there's nothing
like it.''
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Counsell, the Dodgers designated outfielder
Brent Cookson, a former Ventura College and Long Beach State star,
for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Pitching coach Claude Osteen left the
team for a few days to attend the funeral of his mother in
Nashville, Tenn. Dodgers minor-league pitching coordinator Jim
Benedict is filling in.... Right-handed reliever Antonio Osuna
tossed a baseball Friday and remains on target for a late July
return.... Grudzielanek had the cast removed from his broken right
wrist Monday and is wearing a splint. He's still at least a week
away from beginning any type of rehab work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
