<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6971 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     06-16 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG, BLUE MESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a news flash for the fine people at Fox regarding their
baseball team, the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   It really sucks.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so that isn't exactly news.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also boring.
</P>
<P>
   Now that should get the attention of the men running Dodger
blue. They are, after all, in the entertainment business. The
purchase of the Dodgers had as much to do with TV sports
programming as it did baseball. If the Dodgers were a TV show, they
would have been cancelled last season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the feeble 25-man congregation for 1999 is slow-walking
through the requirements of a 162 game season, playing comatose
baseball with nary a single reason for fan interest or affection.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Raul Mondesi has his faithful fans, there's a smattering of
appreciation for The Last Dodger, Eric Karros, and we all may grow
to like that smirk on Kevin Brown's face.
</P>
<P>
   But everywhere else, the Dodgers are apathy personified, as
demonstrative as a shrug. There may be some nice fellows here and
there, but as Shania Twain puts it, that doesn't keep us warm in
the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew the chemistry-failing, post-season wailing Dodgers of
the mid-'90s would be the good old days? As derelict as some of
those teams were, there was some success (two division titles and a
record 44 games over .500 between 1995-97) and always a reason for
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   I can trace this problem to its source. It all began last year
when Fox put a buzz saw to the family tree and started throwing
money at problems like it was fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   When Fox officially purchased the team in spring training of
1998, new execs Chase Carey and Peter Chernin pointed at the World
Series champs, the New York Yankees, as a model for baseball
success. The Yanks were willing to take risks and spend money to
solve problems.
</P>
<P>
   That's all fine and good -- if you make the right decisions on
where to throw the money. The Yankees have won two World Series in
the last three years, but they also went from 1982 to 1992 without
a single division title or postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   During that span, the Yankees threw money at every free agent or
well-shopped veteran there was, hoping to find the right
combination. But for every intriguing pick up like Rickey Henderson
or Don Baylor, there were three or four bobbles -- like Steve Kemp,
Toby Harrah, Omar Moreno, Phil Niekro, Joe Niekro, Rick Rhoden, Ron
Kittle, Claudell Washington, Don Slaught, Jack Clark, John
Candelaria, Steve Sax, Jesse Barfield, Roberto Kelly, Dave
Lapointe, Steve Balboni and Mike Witt.
</P>
<P>
   This turnstile approach to solving problems has an effect beyond
adding thirty-somethings to the major league roster. On a list of
club priorities, it moves major league scouting ahead of minor
league scouting development. It can wither a farm system as
prospects either get traded or die on the vine.
</P>
<P>
   By the late '80s, the Yankees had few if any pitching prospects
in their system. One simple arc of Yankee ``aces'' says it all: The
Yanks' No. 1 starters from 1988 to 1992 were John Candelaria
(1988), someone named Andy Hawkins (1989), someone else named Lee
Guetterman (1990), Scott Sanderson (1991) and Melido Perez (1992).
</P>
<P>
   Plus, when you look at the Yankees of today, you take more
notice of home-growns Derek Jeter, Bernie Williams and Mariano
Rivera, and the way Joe Torre massages his lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Malone isn't much of masseuse. After working with crumbs
for years in Montreal, he is acting now like he won the lottery.
But all of his moves are on par with those the Foxes made early
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield? Fine player, but he shirks the limelight. If you
were going to pay any recalcitrant player $10 million a year, it
should have been someone the fans liked, like Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla? Thankfully, he is now someone else's problem. But
the Dodgers had to take him as Sheffield's chaperon, which cost the
club Todd Zeile. And to get the Mets to take him in the
Charles-Johnson-Todd Hundley deal, the Dodgers had to take Mel
Rojas, who has since been sent to Detroit with Dave Mlicki for
fodder -- meaning, the Dodgers lost Zeile and got bupkis in return.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley? The Dodgers turned one gaffe into two by trading
Charles Johnson, a good defensive catcher with some power and
staunch clubhouse status, for a catcher who was never very good
defensively, was coming off elbow surgery, and had just one pop-up
season as a hitter in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek? Bad defense, impatient hitter and so smart
that he broke his hand slugging a wall. Plus, did the Dodgers need
another major league shortstop with Jose Vizcaino on the roster?
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Perez? He was 29-31 before coming to L.A., and his
reputation as a flake was confirmed before his arrival, and before
he was given a new contract, and before he blew apart this season.
</P>
<P>
   Here's your bottom line: If fans were given the chance to pick
the players they want from the repository of the last eight years,
they might keep only three everyday players -- Karros, Mondesi and
Eric Young.
</P>
<P>
   They might ask for Piazza back, or at least Johnson. They might
want veteran Zeile at third ahead of youngster Adrian Beltre. They
may question why the Dodgers gave up on Henry Rodriguez and Roger
Cedeno. They might even admit they were too hard on Jose Offerman.
And don't even get them started on the legacy of the Fred Claire
era, Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Malone's next deal will be a good one. But change for
change's sake isn't the safest or surest way to win the loyalty of
fans who were already a bit restless. The Dodgers may not have been
a great team before Fox and Malone rolled into town, but at least
they were familiar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
