<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6987 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESIDENT-2000-AZR &LR;      06-16 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENT-2000-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HAMPSHIRE SWAMPED WITH BIG NAMES MONTHS BEFORE PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (resending to correct headline, slug) 
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES, CHARLES KELLY  
 and JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Presidential Campaign 2000 kicked off in
earnest this week, looking like a rush to judgment. Even veterans
of New Hampshire's always-hectic first-in-the-nation primary seemed
put off by the early stampede of candidates through this city of
70,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early, if you ask me,'' said David Woodcock, 48, a
retired U.S. Navy petty officer, as he sat with friends in front of
Lala's Hungarian Pastry in downtown Manchester. ``This all could
have waited until next year.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the candidates, next year will be too late. Here in New
Hampshire, Republicans flocked feverishly to back Texas Gov. George
W. Bush. Elsewhere in the nation, states scrambled for early spots
in the primary process, worried that the race could be over by late
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the two front-runners took their initial steps: Bush,
the top Republican contestant, waded into Iowa and New Hampshire
for the first time and Vice President Al Gore, the leading
Democrat, prepared to announce his candidacy in Tennessee
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, Bush will make his first foray into
California, where he will hit cities with heavy Hispanic
populations to trumpet his credentials as a coalition-building
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   He already has made his mark as a fund raiser, having officially
attracted $7.6 million, more than three times the amount pulled in
by his nearest rival in the money sweepstakes, former Vice
President Dan Quayle, who took in $2.1 million in the first quarter
of the campaign cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Other GOP candidates, who have been courting voters in the early
primary states for months now, have struggled to raise cash and to
make their voices heard amid the din surrounding Bush.
</P>
<P>
   University of Virginia political science Professor Larry Sabato
said the frenzy has been pumped up by huge sums gushing into
certain campaigns and the front-loading of the primary and caucus
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no room for second thoughts, for buyer's remorse,''
Sabato said. ``If you were in a loony bin and were designing a
process for presidential selection, this is the process you would
put together.''
</P>
<P>
   And most of the candidates show no signs of reining in their
efforts. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., spent much of the week in
Senate business but still found time for a couple of campaign
speeches in Chicago and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In major campaign action:
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Gore will officially kick off his campaign for
president in his hometown, Carthage, Tenn., marking the start of
his faceoff with challenger Bill Bradley, a former senator from New
Jersey. Bradley is campaigning in California in an attempt to spark
support for his upstart bid.
</P>
<P>
   Publishing magnate Steve Forbes will add to his already bulging
campaign till Wednesday with a Wall Street fund-raiser expected to
bring in $1.1 million. The dinner will be broadcast live over the
Internet on Forbes' Web site and will be preceded by an ``Internet
reception'' during which the candidate will take questions.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere was the action as intense as in New Hampshire. Mary
Sysyn, an alderman from Manchester, said the pace of campaigning
has been picking up in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's par for the course, but it didn't used to heat up
this early,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Forbes will travel to New Hampshire to christen his
local campaign headquarters. Quayle will make a campaign stop in
New Hampshire Wednesday to attempt to bolster his position in this
state, which he views as critical to his presidential fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   In only his second day of campaigning in New Hampshire, Bush was
clearly causing a stir with voters, who turned out in respectable
numbers to meet the candidate during his tour through Derry on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush made stops in New Castle, Bow, Goffstown and
Manchester, finally showing his hand on several issues, answering
at least some of the recent criticism that he was seeking to become
the party's standard bearer without exposing his views to the
sometimes searing scrutiny of his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told New Hampshire residents that he would not subject
Supreme Court nominees to an abortion litmus test, and made it
clear during campaign stops that he would ``make my stand'' on
moderate Republican ground.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside the Merrimack Restaurant in downtown
Manchester, pharmacist John Karas speculated that the Bush push was
designed to end-run the regular campaign process and anoint Bush
without a real fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a united front by the Republicans to get one
candidate out early,'' Karas said. ``Maybe it's a little too
early.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken a week ago by the ``Boston Herald'' demonstrated
how much territory Bush's rivals for the GOP nomination must cover.
</P>
<P>
   Likely New Hampshire Republican voters favored Bush. He led the
pack, with 45 percent, followed by former Red Cross President
Elizabeth Dole (20 percent), McCain (11 percent), conservative
pundit Pat Buchanan (6 percent), Forbes (4 percent), Quayle (4
percent) and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander (2 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Among all likely New Hampshire voters, Bush out-polled Gore 54
percent to 32 percent head to head. Gore, matched up against his
primary challenger Bradley, led 46 percent to 34 percent. The
survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   As they jockey for position in the crowded field, the candidates
must contend with a primary/caucus calendar that continues to shift
beneath them. Last week, South Carolina moved its GOP primary to
Feb. 19, putting it ahead of Arizona's Feb. 22 GOP primary.
Louisiana Republicans also voted this week to move their caucus to
one week before the Iowa caucuses, or tentatively, Jan. 29. That
would make party members in their state the first in the nation to
cast votes, ahead of those in Iowa, traditionally the first.
</P>
<P>
   As the timing of these crucial votes remains in doubt, the
intensity of the early scrimmaging has been a challenge for
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaigns definitely have to be more creative and more
flexible in how they approach it,'' said Jonathan Baron,
communications director for Quayle. He adds that if there is a
silver lining to the front-loaded campaign season, it is that
conservative activists in states such as Iowa and New Hampshire
will take on even greater import. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
