<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD NIGHT FOR DODGERS, BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers' gloomy season was supposed to have
plummeted to the bottom in Sunday's six-run loss to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   It got worse. Much, much worse. The man who has been the
steadying force through the mayhem did the Dodgers' starters strut.
</P>
<P>
   And Kevin Brown was battered for eight runs in three innings as
the Pittsburgh Pirates blasted the Dodgers 11-1 Tuesday night at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Brown give up three homers, he also was beaten to
the base on a grounder to first and then gaffed when he forget
there was only one out on a grounder hit back to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crappy pitching, crappy breaks, crappy all the way around,''
Brown said of his 69-pitch performance. ``It's the only subtle word
I can use for it. I can't explain it. I pitched like crap. A bad
situation all the way around. I never let a guy beat me to first
base. Just brain dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there were two outs on the one play. I was so caught
up in trying to get out of the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Four of the runs Brown (7-4) allowed were earned. He gave up
eight hits and walked two in his shortest outing since being
ejected April 21, 1998, with the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   The browbeating came on the heels of another shakeup. The
Dodgers acquired Craig Counsell in a trade, and manager Davey
Johnson announced catcher Todd Hundley was being benched and Darren
Dreifort sent to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   And after the debacle, Johnson held the clubhouse closed for 20
minutes to meet. The Dodgers held a closed-door meeting before a
9-3 loss to Oakland on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (29-33) have lost four straight, seven of eight, 10
of 13 and all four they've played against the financially
challenged Pirates this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown on the mound was supposed to be a guarantee. He ended
three-game losing streaks in each of his last two starts, was 5-1
after Dodgers losses and 5-0 at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in worse situations and come out of it pretty
good,'' Johnson said. ``I just told them to forget about this one,
have a good night, and let's get on track. When things are going
bad the dam bursts, and that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Brown's first two pitches _ a double by Al Martin and
a homer by Ed Sprague _ the Dodgers trailed 2-0. Kevin Young added
a first-inning homer.
</P>
<P>
   And in the second, the water gushed through the dam. Brian Giles
grounded to Eric Karros, who threw the ball out of catcher Angel
Pena's reach to allow Martin to score. Later, Young reached first
when Brown was late covering on a grounder to Karros. And when
Jason Kendall hit a comebacker to Brown, he forgot there was only
one out and flipped the ball to first. Sprague scored and Brown,
realizing his mistake, hunched over behind the mound. Warren Morris
added an RBI single to give the Pirates a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Just as this inning was unraveling, Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone returned from Vero Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for the fans,'' Malone said. ``It's discouraging,
it's upsetting, it's frustrating. When you look at the talent we
have and don't see a performance that equates to the talent, it's
puzzling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to figure out how to get out of this rut. Players have
to figure out what they can do to get this thing going. We're here
to support them. If we have the talent, and it's comparable to that
of other baseball clubs, why aren't we performing? This is
difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 0215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7003 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS     06-16 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Sometimes you do all the right things and get all the wrong
results. Chris Holt saw that at work again for most of his seven
innings on the mound Tuesday night, and Scott Elarton got a taste
of it in the ninth as the Atlanta Braves rallied past the Astros
4-3 at the Astrodome.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a tough loss to swallow for the Astros, particularly
Holt, who is still looking for his first win in almost two years.
He is winless in six decisions this season, and the Astros have
lost nine of his 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting old,'' Holt said. ``I'm tired of talking about
it. Hopefully I'll get this thing turned around so that we don't
lose every time I pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was Elarton who was charged with the loss in
Tuesday's game, although the stuff he was dealing toward the plate
was hardly the stuff of losers. He struck out three batters in two
innings and had good action on his breaking pitches, not to mention
a lively fastball.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Braves first baseman Brian Hunter was jammed on the
pitch he punched into center field for the game-winning hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I made good pitches,'' Elarton said. ``I jammed
Hunter; it's just one of those things you can't control. It just
didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   After allowing only four earned runs in his first 26 innings
this year, Elarton (4-2) has seen his fortunes turn to the tune of
a 10.13 ERA this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt fine,'' he said. ``My mechanics were better, and I went
out there with a lot of confidence. I made good pitches. I'd rather
get beat on good pitches. That's easier to deal with than when you
get beat and make bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves starter Tom Glavine didn't make many bad pitches. Then
again, he seldom does when he visits the Astrodome. This season has
been full of struggles for Glavine, but they all seemed to go away
when he laid eyes on his home away from home.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine (4-7) continued his Astrodome mastery, holding the
Astros to three runs on five hits in eight innings. He's 8-0 with a
1.35 ERA in his last 10 starts in the building and can't be too
pleased that the Astros are leaving it for Enron Field next year.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, meanwhile, has to be wondering what he has to do to win a
game anywhere. The Astros' hard-luck pitcher matched Glavine's
performance for seven innings, yielding just five hits and three
runs. But he lost a three-run lead after four innings, and the
Astros could never get back on top.
</P>
<P>
   Braves closer John Rocker pitched a scoreless ninth inning to
earn his 14th save. The Astros got the tying run in scoring
position in the ninth before pinch hitter Russ Johnson hit a sharp
grounder to second to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros haven't had a pinch-hit RBI since Bill Spiers'
two-run double off the bench May 18 in Los Angeles. The team has a
.160 pinch-hit average during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the ball hard,'' Johnson said. ``I just hit it right at
him (Braves second baseman Keith Lockhart).''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, who entered the game with an uncharacteristically high
4.91 ERA, retired 10 of the first 11 batters he faced. He showed
flashes of his two-time Cy Young Award-winning form until the
Astros touched him up for three runs in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell opened the scoring with his second home run in two
nights and his 22nd of the season. Richard Hidalgo drove in a run
with a double, and Carl Everett's team-leading fourth sacrifice fly
gave the Astros a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Now you see it; now you don't.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the Braves rallied to tie the score against
Holt, whose biggest mistake of the game was allowing a two-run
homer to Andruw Jones in the fifth inning. Randall Simon, whom
Hunter replaced in the seventh, followed with a double and scored
from second thanks to an error by Astros second baseman Craig
Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris pitched well,'' Astros interim manager Matt Galante
said. ``He made a bad pitch with the hanging slider to Jones. But
other than that, he was fine. We had the lead, and we let it get
away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the way he has pitched in his last four starts, Holt
deserved a better fate. He has a 2.16 ERA during that stretch, and
the Astros have averaged just three runs in those games.
</P>
<P>
   They had chances to beef up the run support in the sixth inning
_ when Holt was still the pitcher of record _ and again in the
eighth. Both times, they had runners on first and second with one
out, and both times they came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the key,'' Astros third baseman Tim Bogar said.
``When you get an opportunity against a guy like Glavine, you have
to cash in. You have to give him credit for getting out of those
situations. He definitely got the best of us tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   That seldom happens to the Astros when it comes to facing
lefthanders. They have the best winning percentage (.789) in the
majors against lefthanded starters, and they also lead the majors
with a .317 overall batting average against lefties.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Glavine _ struggling or not _ is not your average
lefty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice to win a game against an upper-echelon club,
particularly when things aren't going that great for you,'' Glavine
said. ``If you go out there and beat a lower-echelon club, yeah,
you're happy you won, but you're still wondering, `If I pitch that
same game against one of the top two or three teams in the league,
do I win that game?' Obviously, tonight I can say that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 0236EDT &QL; 
