r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT     06-16 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' RUN ENDS HERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are gathered here to interpret the scheduled collision of two
great cities.
</P>
<P>
   In this corner weighing in with its first appearance at the NBA
Finals is ABA orphan San Antonio, whose tastefully old-school motto
is ``Sweep L.A. and remember the Alamo!''
</P>
<P>
   Barging into its eighth Finals from the other corner is New York
City, where the only civic battle cry fit to print in a family
newspaper is ``Freeze!''
</P>
<P>
   On your ``intangibles'' scoreboard, it might be helpful to note
that San Antonio is where honest Davy Crockett tasted the agony of
defeat in Game 7 vs. Santa Ana. New York answers by being known as
the scene of a possible last stand by Knicks executive liar Davy
Checketts.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, San Antonio's Spurs and New York's Knicks square off
tonight in Game 1 of a series that will determine the 52nd champion
of the NBA. This best-of-7 event begins at the Alamodome, a vast
stadium that seems as appropriate for basketball as a battleship is
for bass fishing.
</P>
<P>
   But since you're watching on TV, you don't care about
atmosphere. You care about knowing which team is going to win.
Gambling, of course, is a collateral issue, because you're aware
that it's illegal to bet if you're not in Las Vegas, on the
Internet, or on a pay phone.
</P>
<P>
   You also know through the historical chanting of coaches and
barstool prophets that ``Defense wins championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Say it loud.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's enough. It might not be a bad idea to get comfy with
another historical imperative. It goes like this: ``Great players
win championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, of course they do. As any Phil Jackson knows, you need
outstanding players to win. But we're not talking about just very
good players. No. What we're selling is the concept of Hall of Fame
players.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't have anything to do with your spare time, you
might be aware that every NBA championship team with a single
exception had at least one player with a Hall of Fame pedigree.
(The 1979 Seattle crew recently threatened to join the party when
former Dominguez High, Pepperdine, SuperSonics and Boston Celtics
star Dennis Johnson was nominated.)
</P>
<P>
   So why do Hall of Famers win championships? Favorable
officiating? Perhaps, but we'll have to check that theory with
Oliver Stone. Then again, great players may not be considered Hall
material until they win a championship. Roll over, Charles Barkley;
we're just kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave the Spurs? It leaves them in a dandy
predicament. David Robinson is a mortal lock for eternal props at
Springfield. Tim Duncan, by lock standards, appears to be flirting
with immortality.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks? Well, Patrick Ewing will be enshrined, but unless he
pulls a Willis Reed won't be on the court. That leaves New York
with the go-to names of Allan Houston, who isn't Fame caliber, and
Latrell Sprewell, whose future credentials would be enhanced by
shooting 1,000 off-season jumpers per day and bribing about 1,000
memory-influenced citizens who vote for such things.
</P>
<P>
   Third-year power forward Marcus Camby hasn't even started for
the Knicks, but if the rest of his career is being advertised by
his playoff run, he'd be a cinch. The Spurs admit they are worried
about Camby, because he's so darned active. Active? The guy appears
to be more lit up than a five-year-old who crashed the line at
Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   But even though he outplayed Duncan in college, Camby could be
doomed in this series.
</P>
<P>
   With such star power against them, just how do the Knicks
compensate? Speed. Sure, the Spurs can haul, too, but most of the
Knicks are quick enough to navigate the New York City subway system
with their wallets in their back pockets.
</P>
<P>
   They should use this quickness to extend their defense, make it
more difficult to dump the ball into Robinson and Duncan, box out,
then run like hell after grabbing the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   And unless you've been in a coma for a month, you're aware that
the Knicks are murder in transition. That's what throttled the
Pacers, though it should be noted that in Indiana, ``transition''
means switching from Miller to Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks fail to muster a bunch of easy baskets, they're
goners. The Spurs, a collection of law-abiding, renaissance guys
who tape ``Jeopardy'' on game nights, happen to be ogres on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   And we all know what happens when great, law-abiding players
play great defense, right?
</P>
<P>
   Right, they soak each other's skulls with Snapple after Game 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
