<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCHOA HOPES TO TURN OPEN FANTASY TO REALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ To the best of his recollection, former TCU
golfer Alberto Ochoa wrapped up the 1999 U.S. Open championship
eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The title netted him $1 each from other PGA Tour wannabes in the
field at Ebony Hills Golf Course in Edinburg. As a teen-ager,
winning mythical majors at the nine-hole facility in the Rio Grande
Valley became a way to stretch a shoestring budget for Ochoa.
</P>
<P>
   Contestants would agree on a future championship that all
expected to be old enough to enter _ 1999 Open, 2000 Masters _ and
cheat Father Time by playing it that day. Entry fee was $1 per
player, winner take all. Ochoa, 22, proved to be the Valley's
version of Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, I was always taking their money,'' Ochoa said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if life imitates fantasy, Ochoa would collect a lot more
than lunch money by winning the real-world version of the 1999
Open, which begins tomorrow at Pinehurst Resort and Country Club.
But he'd settle for a strong finish and confidence boost that would
help validate his decision to leave school in December, midway
through his senior season, to pursue his pro career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it wasn't the right thing to do. Who knows?'' Ochoa said
of his decision to accept a $100,000, multiyear commitment from a
group of Valley-based businessmen to help launch his quest for a
PGA Tour card. ``If I'd stayed, maybe I would've won the NCAA
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wanted to be as prepared as possible for qualifying
school this fall. That's where my future is. I figured the more pro
experience I had before Q-school, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Open berth, which Ochoa earned June 7 during a rain-soaked
qualifying tournament in West Palm Beach, Fla., should provide the
litmus test the two-time All-American seeks to gauge his progress
as a pro. Ochoa struggled with his driver early in the season,
failing in four attempts to land berths in Nike Tour events. He has
yet to finish better than 35th in a tournament on the Golden Bear
Tour, a minitour in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But after months of struggling, Ochoa began splitting fairways
during the 36-hole qualifier. He opened with a 68, lowest round of
the tournament, then coasted home in 74 as the skies opened and
scores soared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooting the 68 changed my whole attitude,'' said Ochoa, who
will be making his debut in one of golf's major championships.
``I'd been playing in the trees for the last six months. Now, my
confidence is back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's not possible for me to win the Open. But I'm always
going to think, `Why not?' Those guys on the PGA Tour are no
different from me. I've shot 64s and 65s before. Why not this
week?''
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, TCU coach Bill Montigel said Ochoa has
nothing to prove to him _ this week or in the future. Although the
player's December departure was instrumental in TCU's fall from
12th in the NCAA (1998) to fifth in the Western Athletic Conference
(1999) in a one-year period, Ochoa left in good academic standing
and in good graces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could get another guy that good for 3 1/2 years,''
Montigel said. ``He did all he could in college golf. He's still
No. 1 in my book, and I'm rooting for him. I know this is a huge
week for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Much bigger than when Ochoa won the mythical version of the '99
Open, back during his teen-age years in Edinburg.
SPOTLIGHT ON
Janzen in comfort zone in bid for third Open title
</P>
<P>
   Even when he let his imagination work overtime, Lee Janzen never
expected to be in this situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid, I dreamed of winning a U.S. Open. But I never
dreamed of winning it twice,'' said Janzen, the defending champion
who is considered a serious threat to add title No. 3 because of
his comfort level with Pinehurst No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Janzen call it his favorite course, he also
finished second at Pinehurst in the 1992 Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain what it is,'' said Janzen, 34, an eight-event
winner on the PGA Tour. ``I just have confidence that I can play
well on this course. I have confidence I will do well in this
tournament. Whatever it is, I've probably looked forward to this
U.S. Open more than any other one I've played in. And that includes
the two I've won.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed for an explanation for his success on Open courses,
Janzen said: ``At the Open, you have got to know exactly how far
you're hitting the ball. If you need to land it four steps on the
green, you have to be able to do that. Maybe I land the ball closer
to the exact distance I'm trying to hit it than the other guys.
Maybe I just have more of a conservative approach. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   This much is known. A victory would allow Janzen to join Hale
Irwin on the short list of three-time Open champions. The record is
four titles, shared by four players, including Jack Nicklaus and
Ben Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
Colonial experience helps
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Ochoa said lessons learned during the 1997 MasterCard
Colonial should help this week at Pinehurst.
</P>
<P>
   Ochoa shot rounds of 71-75 as an amateur at Colonial, missing
the cut in his lone PGA Tour appearance. During his opening round
at Colonial, Ochoa stood 3 under through 13 holes, but carded four
bogeys coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was from a lack of experience,'' Ochoa said. ``I got to 3
under and tried to get to 6 under by shooting at too many pins. You
can't force things to happen out here. I'll learn from that and
won't make the same mistake again this week.''
Seeking the right mix
</P>
<P>
   Heading into his fifth U.S. Open, Tiger Woods has yet to post a
top-10 finish in the event. But Woods, 23, has won twice in the
past month _ once in Germany, and then at the Memorial Tournament _
and said he's finally come to terms with the blend of patience and
aggression to succeed on a layout like Pinehurst No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first couple of Opens, I was too aggressive,'' said Woods,
who altered his approach for 1997, rarely using his driver at
Congressional Country Club. ``Then, at Congressional, I went so
conservative, I played worse. I realize now there's a mixture in
there that you have to find. There's a balance and you have to feel
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said the right mix at Pinehurst might result in an
over-par score by the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would take 72 straight pars. But the reality of that
happening is slim,'' Woods said.
Conversions questioned
</P>
<P>
   Count Davis Love III among the group of contestants less than
thrilled with the U.S. Golf Association's decision to convert two
of Pinehurst's par-5 holes (No. 8, No. 16) into par-4s, measuring
485 and 489 yards, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think changing the par-5s to par-4s have created some
demanding holes, if not unfair holes,'' said Love, whose father
used to teach at the course. ``You'll have to be real patient on
both of those.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
