<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' RODRIGUEZ MISSES GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
NEW YORK _ Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez, who played only one
inning Monday before leaving with back spasms, missed Tuesday
night's game against the New York Yankees and is listed as
day-to-day.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spasms made for a near-sleepless night for Rodriguez, who
``had a very uncomfortable night,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's feeling better, but it still bothers him when he squats
to catch,'' trainer Danny Wheat said. ``It's a possibility he'll
play \RWednesday\S. We'll treat him, and hopefully he'll be ready
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was replaced by Gregg Zaun, who made his first start
in a night game this season. Rangers sign first pick The Rangers
signed Bakersfield (Calif.) College right-hander Colby Lewis, the
organization's first selection and 38th overall in the 1999
First-Year Player Draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers assigned the 19-year-old pitcher to Pulaski, their
rookie-league affiliate in the Appalachian League. The Rangers
would not divulge the signing bonus awarded; Chris Jones, selected
38th overall in 1998 by San Francisco, received $587,500.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Rangers signed right-handed pitcher David Mead,
their second selection and the 47th overall. Rangers scouting
director Chuck McMichael praised area scouts Kipp Fagg, Mike
Paustin and Dennis Meeks for laying the foundation for the quick,
acrimony-free signings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fortunate circumstance for them and for us,'' McMichael
said. Errant ERA With an 8.38 earned-run average after Monday's 8-2
loss to the Yankees, Rangers starter Mark Clark has the highest ERA
among American League qualifiers, but he is not in danger of being
removed from the rotation, Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   However, John Burkett could return to the rotation at some
point, Oates said. Burkett pitched two scoreless innings Monday and
has allowed only one run in his past three appearances covering 7
1/3 innings to drop his ERA from 10.54 to 8.57.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a manager, you're always thinking and looking at all the
possibilities,'' Oates said. ``It's not written in cement that John
won't start again. It's a daily evaluation.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
