<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 08:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7149 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-INNER-GOLF-COX     06-16 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-INNER-GOLF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The game of golf gets a trendy self-help aspect
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News ServiceR
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's 16 hours till the first Saturday morning tee
times, but on the putting green inside Kennesaw, Georgia's
Golfsmith superstore, the mind games are already in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   Am I gripping the club correctly? Are my feet the right distance
apart?
</P>
<P>
   Who am I, really?
</P>
<P>
   That last thought, at least, is what publishers would have you
believe is going on inside golfers' heads. Or should be. From
bookstore shelves to best-seller lists, a new trend is plainly
evident: Golf no longer is just about getting the ball in the hole.
Now it's also about getting in touch with yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spiritual-type books have been the boom for the past four to
five years,'' said Paul Gediman, nonfiction editor for the
``Forecast'' section of Publishers Weekly. ``If anyone can tie golf
to self-help and what people need to know in everyday life, it
probably will do well.''
</P>
<P>
   These ``I putt, therefore I am'' books have arrived just in time
for Father's Day _ to help attract the male audience at which they
clearly seem targeted. Among them are two from self-help's heaviest
hitters:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Golf and the Spirit _ Lessons for the Journey'' by M. Scott
Peck, whose 1985 ``The Road Less Traveled'' remains the
best-selling self-help book of all time.
</P>
<P>
   -- And ``Chicken Soup for the Golfer's Soul,'' the latest from
the ultra-successful, ultra-ubiquitous ``Chicken Soup'' franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's opening up a whole new genre,'' said Chrissy
Donnelly, a ``Chicken Soup'' co-author and avid golfer. ``People
are really linking up to the idea that golf is a metaphor for life
and that you can learn all of life's lessons out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even comedian Bill Murray has gotten into the act. Long revered
by boys of all ages for his 1980 film ``Caddyshack,'' Murray's
book, ``Cinderella Story: My Life in Golf,'' is as much about
inspiration as it is yuks.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you may ask, what keeps a man going when the chips are
down?'' Murray writes in a passage bridging a hilarious account
about a bad day on the golf course and a more revealing section
about his struggles for laughs and attention as one of nine
children.``It's a journey, you animal, not a destination. You just
keep plugging.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's nothing unique about an early summer
onslaught of golf books . Even those that go beyond the how-to or
``how he did it'' genre have some precedence: 1995's ``The Legend
of Bagger Vance: A Novel of Golf and the Game of Life'' was a
surprise hit; Robert Redford's film version starts shooting in
South Carolina this fall. ``Golf in the Kingdom,'' Michael Murphy's
1972 novel about mystical Scottish golf pro is widely considered a
classic.
</P>
<P>
   So consider what's happening now to be the next wave. And
there's good reason _ sales of spiritual books alone are expected
to hit 133 million by next year, a number that could go much higher
if even a small percentage of the estimated 27 million golf-playing
Americans make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Crass commercialism aside, how people react to what happens on
the golf course can teach them a lot about themselves, says Atlanta
sports psychologist James Millhouse. That's because golf is a game
in which one's sense of control can last about as long as it takes
a sudden gust of wind to knock a ``perfect'' shot off course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same in life,'' pointed out Mona Vold, author of the
newly-released ``Different Strokes: The Lives and Teachings of the
Game's Wisest Women.'' ``There is a whole willingness now, I think,
to think further into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But, not to be too blunt about it, does anyone really want to?
</P>
<P>
   Sales figures would seem to indicate yes _ Peck's book on Monday
was ranked 138th among Amazon.com's three million available titles.
``Cinderella Story'' hit No. 13 on this past Sunday's New York
Times' nonfiction bestseller list. And ``Chicken Soup'' was No. 2
on the Times' ``Advice, How-to and Miscellaneous'' paperback list.
</P>
<P>
   But, curiously, it's kinda hard finding a real person who'll
admit to buying any of these ``inner golfer'' titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lovely mindset that golf is like life, but it's not
very practical,'' said Atlantan Mike Lazzo, 41, a self-described
``book obsessed'' person who plays golf about once a week. ``If you
want to improve any aspect of golf or your life, get busy. Get out
there on the driving range of life and work on your swing!''
</P>
<P>
   Lazzo was one of about a dozen golfers informally surveyed last
week, none of whom seemed to have the slightest interest in using
the game to learn more about themselves or life. Let alone reading
about how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they're already using golf to get in touch with
themselves. They just don't know it yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they get something deeper in golf, even though maybe
they won't realize it or say it,'' said Donnelly. ``A lot of them
aren't open with their emotions, but it's filling that need that
they have to be with nature and with themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's not male golfers whom these books are being
marketed to after all. At Phipps Plaza's Doubleday Book Shop,
staffers say most inquiries about Peck's new book come from women
who have no idea it's golf-themed. Indeed, Peck says he wrote
``Spirit'' for his traditional audience ``in the hopes that
non-golfers would become more interested in golf or at least go
deeper into their own spiritual journeys.''
</P>
<P>
   Or at least buy it for their husbands. Woodstock resident Al
Moreno may not have much interest in getting in touch with his
inner golfer _ ``The same four of us have played together for eight
years, and we're just out there to have a good time'' _ but he knew
something about ``Chicken Soup for the Golfer's Soul'' when it was
pointed out to him on Golfsmith's shelf last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife has them all,'' Moreno said of the ``Chicken Soup''
books. ``If she comes over here and sees it, she'll probably buy it
for me for Fathers Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't expect Mike Lazzo to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the golf course really was like life,'' he sighed, ``nobody
would play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 0854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
