 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 434-- June 14, 1999  ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 434 -- June 16, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. 'REAL WORLD' ROMANCE BLOSSOMS IN HAWAII Seven strangers are
thrown together to live in a plantation-style beachfront home in
Hawaii. Their lives are documented 24 hours a day. Whether they're
brushing their teeth or dealing with emotional problems, these
twentysomethings are in front of the camera, fully aware that
millions of people will be observing their experiences each week on
MTV. Welcome to the popular docudrama ``The Real World.'' By Tamara
Conniff. BPI. 800 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
LIVING LA VIDA BUENA Puerto Rican singer Ricky Martin was the
centre of the pop universe, at least for a week. He's a former
child star whose performance at the Grammy Award signaled a flood
of interest in his hip-shaking Latin pop. Martin's English-language
debut album sold 660,000 copies in its opening week. ``Latin music
is going to stay,'' says Emilio Estefan, the dean of Latin
producers. By Steve Morse. The Boston Globe. 1,400 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
DeFOREST KELLEY : THE REAL McCOY In this special column, Ian
Spelling, the noted science fiction writer and author of The New
York Times Syndicate's Inside Trek and Sci-Fi column, remembers
DeForest Kelley, who died on June 11 (Kelley played the irascible
medic Dr. Leonard ``Bones'' McCoy in ``Star Trek.'') ``My legacy is
that I have inspired a great number of people to enter the medical
world,'' said Kelley last August. ``These people are doctors now,
all kinds of doctors who save lives and help other people in other
ways.'' By Ian Spelling. 750 words + photos.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
ROCK'S QUIRKIEST BAND REINVENTS ITSELF After having redefined what
was considered ``modern'' and ``alternative'' rock since 1983, the
members of R.E.M. were afraid it might be time to put their group
to sleep. Their drummer, Bill Berry, suffered a near-fatal double
brain aneurysm during a world tour and retired in 1997. Now the
remaining trio is justifiably psyched about its latest album,
``Up.'' They believe the drastic changes they made actually
strengthened the band. By Gary Graff. 1,000 words + photo. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
------------- 5. JUST MAD ABOUT SAFFRON Ex-model Saffron Burrows
abandoned the fashion runway for the big screen. Burrows, 26, plays
twins who have never met in ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence,'' the
latest film written and directed by Mike Figgis, which is sure to
cause a stir with both its non-linear form and explicit content.
But controversy is something Burrows can handle. Her radical
childhood in London, with strong trade unionist parents, was filled
with it. By Jessica Kerwin. From Women's Wear Daily. 700 words +
photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
'ALIEN'-ATION : SCI-FI'S LANDMARK HORROR FLICK,
</P>
<P>
   20 YEARS LATER The year was 1979. Jimmy Carter, Anwar Sadat and
Menachem Begin signed the Camp David peace accords and Ayatollah
Khomeini replaced the Shah as ruler of Iran. And in space no one
could hear you scream. Believe it or not, it's been 20 years since
Ridley Scott's ``Alien'' scared moviegoers silly with its moody
atmosphere and, of course, the notorious chest-burster sequence,
one of the most viscerally frightening scenes ever filmed. By Ian
Spelling. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
APPLE CORE : 'ER'S' NOAH WYLE PLAYS STEVE JOBS Noah Wyle steps out
of his character as ``ER's'' likable Dr. Carter for a trip through
the computer world as Steve Jobs in ``Pirates of Silicon Valley.''
Wyle's emergence as a sex symbol in ``ER'' still bemuses him as he
values his privacy. By Ivor Davis. 1,300 words + photos. (N/A Great
Britain and Australia.)
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
SARAH McLACHLAN : LILITH'S LEAD LADY IS MOMMY-MINDED Talking about
Sarah McLachlan, the phrase that people keep coming back to is
``one-woman industry.'' McLachlan is as refreshingly direct in
person as she is in her music. By Andrew Ryan. From TV Guide
Canada. 1,300 words + photos.
_____________________________________________________________ 9.
EVERETT'S PEAK Rupert Everett can just see the headline now.
Hollywood's most prominent openly gay actor playing a royal sprite
in a glam film version of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream?'' What else
but ``King of the Fairies.'' Everett has learned to deal with the
vagaries of fame with sharp wit, droll insouciance and the supreme
confidence that comes from his lanky good looks. By Merle Ginsberg.
From W magazine. 1,500 words + photo.
