<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7196 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-RUSSIANS-BOS &LR;      06-16 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-RUSSIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO LETS RUSSIAN TROOPS RESUPPLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The 200 Russian troops who sprinted into Kosovo last
weekend ahead of NATO and then took control of the regional
capital's airport caught the alliance badly off guard. The daring
move also provided a brief surge of national pride for a country
that has grown used to seeing its once-proud military humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, things started getting back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   To make their dash, the Russian troops had to travel light, and
Tuesday their lack of supplies caught up with them. They were
forced to bum cigarettes from local passers-by, and ask for water
from the British troops they still refuse to let into the airport.
</P>
<P>
   This was just what NATO was waiting for. The alliance has gone
out of its way to play down the significance of the Russians in
Pristina and at the same time play up the partnership with their
fellow peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The British happily agreed, and just as willingly supplied a
military escort to a column of Russian trucks filled with food,
water and money from a Russian peacekeeping brigade in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the troops they sent into Kosovo, the generals in
Moscow who gave the orders, with President Boris N. Yeltsin's
approval, were able to score a quick victory but do not have the
resources to compete with NATO over the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has neither the money to pay for a large peacekeeping
force nor the political clout it needs to force NATO to accept its
demands that its troops control a separate sector of Kosovo,
outside of the alliance's comand.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow would like to increase the number of its troops in
Kosovo, and has a paratroop division waiting to go. But Romanian,
Bulgarian and Hungarian officials have refused permission for
Russian military planes to overfly their countries until Russia
agrees with NATO on the role of its peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   If Russia's military chiefs were humiliated by their inability
to stop NATO from bombing Yugoslavia, and by NATO's unwillingness
to agree to their peacekeeping demands, how does it make them feel
to be denied airspace by their former East European allies?
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Russia's civilian leadership, most of which
was left out of the loop when the plan to occupy Pristina's airport
was unleashed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin, doing an admirable job
of hiding the humiliation he must have felt when the orders to move
into Kosovo were given without his knowledge last Friday, said
Moscow had restored order to its Balkans policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we agreed is that all work on the Kosovo
problem should be coordinated,'' said Stepashin after meeting
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin also said he believed ``friction'' with the United
States over Kosovo would be resolved at a series of bilateral
meetings this week. He should hope so: Stepashin plans to meet
Thursday with the International Monetary Fund's managing director,
Michel Camdessus, to discuss new loans to help pay off previous
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday secretaries of state and defense Madeleine Albright
and William Cohen are due to meet in Helsinki with their Russian
counterparts. Tuesday, Russian security chief Vladimir Putin
proposed, in a phone conversation with U.S. national security
adviser Sander Berger, creating a command-by-committee for all
Kosovo peacekeepers in which a Russian officer would decide which
decisions to relay onto Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, which has insisted on a single, unified command, may have
trouble with that. But last week's developments clearly showed,
once again, that Yeltsin, and whoever is giving him advice -- is
capable of pursuing any policy if it meets his short-term political
needs. This is something President Clinton should remember when he
meets the Russian president Sunday at a summit of the G7 leading
industrial nations in the German city of Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kremlin has credited Yeltsin for the bold move into
Kosovo, the president himself has yet to comment on the action his
troops took. Kremlin observers suspect a favorite Yeltsin political
tactic is behind his silence over the Kosovo mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it succeeds, the president can say it was his initiative,''
said Russian legislator Alexei Arbatov. ``If it doesn't succeed, if
the coffins start coming in, if then he can say it wasn't his
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbatov said this is no way for the commander in chief to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be protecting the Russian soldiers who are there,
not the Russian president,'' Arbatov said on Russian television.
``Without a clear statement of policy from the Russian president,
nothing is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The nationalists and Communists who dominate the State Duma,
Russia's lower house of parliament, were elated by the rapid
deployment of the first Russian troops in Kosovo. But now they want
answers as the Serbs, the historical allies Moscow wants to
protect, flee the province in droves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 0953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
