<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7221 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE     06-16 2687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The First Son: A profile of George W. Bush
 &HT;    (For Sunday, June 20. Package includes BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE1,
BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE2, BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE3, BUSH-TIMELINE-COX
and photos. A shorter version of the profile is moving as
BUSH-PROFILE-SHORT-COX. This version is also available for sale as
a full-page layout at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Inculcated, that was the word George Bush used.
He said he had the drive to serve inculcated into him by his
father, the future senator from Connecticut, Prescott Bush, who
believed in noblesse oblige, believed it the solemn obligation of
the elite to serve for the greater societal good. The future
senator inculcated that belief into his second son, the future
president, George Herbert Walker Bush. That son went off to West
Texas, and he raised a family and did some inculcating of his own.
In those days, when the Kennedys reigned as American royalty, the
senior senator's son was on occasion heard to say, ``Just wait till
I turn these Bush boys out.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of those Bush boys _ George Dubya, as he is known in
Texas _ is now poised to continue the family tradition. After
months of conspicuously not running for president, he finally made
it clear in Iowa last Saturday that he is seeking the office.
</P>
<P>
   The first election of the 21st century then, we currently
assume, will be The Clash of the Scions, Al Gore vs. George W.
Bush. One, Gore, went to Vietnam and didn't fight; the other, Bush,
flew fighter jets and didn't go to Vietnam. One toked a little pot;
the other declines to give a full accounting of his youthful
indiscretions and emphatically considers the matter closed. The
public perceives one as exuding the charisma and warmth of a cheap
Formica countertop; the other is regarded, even by his frustrated
political enemies, as impossible to personally dislike. One has
spent decades being groomed for this moment; the other has
strenuously spent at least the last year not running for president,
listening to the whole world tell him it's his to lose.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning: Driving to the moon in a Studebaker
</P>
<P>
   The other officers aboard the aircraft carrier San Jacinto just
loved calling him by his patrician full name _
George-Herbert-Walker-Bush. But he was one of the guys _ even had
his wife's name, Barbara, painted on his plane, and that went
against the rules. So thorough was his inculcation that he joined
the service the day he turned 18. He flew bombers, and one day,
Sept. 2, 1944, over the Bonin Islands in the Pacific, he took heavy
flak en route to his target. He toughed it through the fire, made
his drop, headed back out to sea and ditched his TBM Avenger. The
other two guys didn't make it _ he'd called for them before he
bailed out and heard nothing.
</P>
<P>
   George-Herbert-Walker-Bush _ ``Poppy'' back home _ was rescued
and returned a war hero, although he'd never think to use the term
_ his mother taught him not to brag, to give the other guy credit.
He went to Yale, as his father had, and found time for 16
activities, everything from captain of the baseball team to the
secret society Skull and Bones. At their wedding reception in the
first week of 1945, Poppy told Barbara, or Bar, as she was also
known: ``Enjoy it. It's the last time I'll ever dance in public.''
Or so the story goes.
</P>
<P>
   George Walker Bush was born in New Haven, Conn., on July 6,
1946.
</P>
<P>
   The very senior senator gave George-Herbert-Walker-Bush a red
two-door Studebaker, and the day after graduation in the summer of
1948, Poppy loaded that car up and pointed it west, arranging for
Bar and baby George to follow. They were headed for an outpost so
remote it may as well have been outer space to the Bushes of
Greenwich: Odessa, Texas, where dust storms were major
meteorological events, where George Bush and scores of other
postwar Ivy League grads intended to make their fortunes in oil.
The place was pregnant with the stuff _ you could stick a dessert
fork in the ground in those days and make a major discovery. After
a brief time in California, the family moved 20 miles down the road
from Odessa to Midland, which had one big advantage over Odessa:
There the family could get away from the mother-daughter prostitute
tag team who lived and worked on the other side of the crudely
partitioned shotgun duplex on East Seventh Street. By 1952 _ the
year Prescott Bush, back in Connecticutt, won election to the U.S.
Senate _ Midland was the boomingest boomtown in West Texas, with
$22 million worth of building permits. (By the end of the decade
those homes and businesses would be empty. Welcome to the oil
bidness.) Hank Williams died on New Year's Eve of that year.
Eisenhower was president, Shivers was governor, polio was still a
threat, and one Master Haskell Goebel Harris was heralded in a
full-page ad in the local paper as ``Midland County's first white
baby of 1953.''
</P>
<P>
   It was still a small town, or had been when the Bushes arrived
in 1950. Although Midland would sprout a cluster of tall buildings
as monuments to its sporadic affluence, paved streets in parts of
town remained a near-novelty. Then there was the really baffling
thing about the Permian Basin: no trees. Or rather, a few dejected,
transplanted saplings that looked none too pleased, seemed to be
asking, ``Why me?'' Barbara Bush gave birth to John Ellis Bush, the
future governor of Florida whom the family would call Jebbie, in
February 1953. (Two other Bush boys, Marvin and Neil, as well as a
daughter, Doro, would follow.) But a family tragedy loomed, too:
Pauline Robinson Bush, George W.'s younger sister, would die of
leukemia in October before her fourth birthday. George and Barbara
didn't tell their elder son his sister was dying.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did well enough to move the family into a nice house on
Sentinel with a swimming pool. Young George played Little League in
the neighborhood and attended Sam Houston Elementary School with
his future wife, whom he did not know.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush was in Houston by the time he ran for the U.S.
Senate against Ralph Yarborough in 1964. Yarborough wouldn't
debate, so Bush and his pal Martin Allday came up with the famous
empty-chair debates, with a tape recording on a chair sitting in
for Yarborough. They got a lot of mileage out of that, but LBJ was
in the White House by then and his coattails stretched from El Paso
to Nacogdoches.
</P>
<P>
   Young George W., when home on break from Andover, sat in on
strategy meetings. And on election night, in the Houston ballroom
his dad had rented for the victory reception that never happened,
young George W. wept.
</P>
<P>
   Winter without girls
</P>
<P>
   So this kid from Midland, a town of oil nomads as polite as the
land is flat, goes to prep school in Massachusetts. He enrolls in
Phillips Academy, which sits atop a long, gradual hill stretching
through Andover, Mass. Think of one of those perennially autumnal
places, hundreds of acres of trees and brick and scowling faculty
who will be addressed as ``sir.'' Think Holden Caulfield. Think ``A
Separate Peace.'' Think a young John Irving hanging around the gym
in gray sweats except _ oops _ he went to Exeter, Andover's
cheerfully despised rival.
</P>
<P>
   These young men had gotten into the most prestigious academy in
the United States, and they were going to be punished for it.
</P>
<P>
   Morning chapel was mandatory, as was jacket and tie. The class
work was unrelenting, the faculty unforgiving. The syllabus for
History 4, a course required of seniors and purported to be the
hardest at the school, ran 300 pages. Fear, intimidation and
humiliation were trusted teaching tools. Of one one particularly
imposing math teacher, a member of the class of '64 later told
writer Nina Savin Scott: ``I was awed and entertained by him. There
was something very engaging in the prospect of death.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, no girls. The educational wisdom of the day maintained
that a boy could not have a top-notch education bludgeoned _
inculcated _ into him while in the agitating presence of the fair
sex. Girls from Abbot, the nearby girls' school that would
eventually be absorbed into Phillips, weren't even allowed to write
letters to Phillips boys as late as 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Classmate Tom Seligson, now a producer for CBS-TV: ``I organize
the reunions, and it's like going back to a prison reunion. This
was an atmosphere where there was a lot of cruelty to other
classmates. He never did any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Young George was instead a social creature, one who went out of
his way to make everybody comfortable, even if they weren't in his
clique. It was here that Bush, as much a New Englander as a Texan,
honed an essential political skill: getting along with everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Bush roommate John Kidde: ``George and I played sports _ I
played a lot of sports _ and there are some kids at Andover who are
not very outgoing or socially dialed-in, nerds or whatever you want
to call them. I remember two or three of us would be getting lunch
and there'd be Joe Blow, one of the straight-A students who never
talked and nobody socialized with him, and we'd sit down and start
talking and George would make a joke or a comment and always bring
this guy into the conversation, make him a part of the group. He
was real good at that. He always made people feel very comfortable
around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush arrived perhaps no less prepared than his classmates.
</P>
<P>
   John Kidde, who now runs a food-processing company: ``I don't
know if anybody's prepared to go to that place. I had A's and B's
before, and it still knocked my socks off. It was just really
tough. Really tough.'' Friends remember Bush as a satisfactory
student who worked hard, but who was plainly more interested in
sports than academics.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar said it was the early 1960s, but at Andover it was
still the Cold War '50s. Nine buildings were designated as fallout
shelters, stocked with two weeks' worth of food, water and
supplies. Officials reported that the buildings were sufficiently
resistant to radiation and could be made even more so in the event
of nuclear attack by covering the windows. Pop music was less of a
threat _ there was a campus combo called The Satans, but its
members didn't look much like Marilyn Manson in their natty jackets
and ties. When a few students dared to let their hair shag out like
the Beatles, school officials warned them to shape up.
</P>
<P>
   Students caught with booze could be expelled, but the
student-produced yearbook, Pot Pourri, went out of its way to show
boys in gleeful rebellion against that and other rules. Students
didn't have to work hard to get their pictures in the yearbook with
a can of Budweiser in hand, exaggeratedly scoping a Playboy or
puffing on a cigar. There are no pictures of George W. Bush so
occupied. John Kidde never saw him drink while at Andover.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is instead shown posing with the cheerleading
squad, or outside a phone booth crammed full of boys, or acting as
high commissioner of stickball. Good, clean, boyish high jinks,
corny but not enough political dynamite to blow the good ship W2K
out of the water. In his senior picture, he wears the same
asymmetrical grin both his grandfather and father exhibited. The
eyebrows still needed some growing into.
</P>
<P>
   In the yearbook he was called a BMOC and a wit. He escaped
categorization as an intellectual, cynic, ``butt friend,''
alcoholic or social climber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lip'' came, of course, from his lightning wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was quick with a quip,'' said Jack Morrison, a close
friend from Andover and Yale. ``He always had a twinkle in his eye
and a ready retort in his mouth. He often got the last word in.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush spent that senior year down the hill in America
House, a sizable old Colonial-style dorm that looks like it's a
prime candidate for the next Sears Weatherbeater paint commercial.
It is named America House because there, in 1832, Samuel F. Smith
wrote ``America.'' (``My country, 'tis of thee . . .'' You know
that'll turn up at the convention bio-flick. Better than being from
A Place Called Hope.)
</P>
<P>
   Senior year was when boys found whether they were going to their
first-choice college. If not, life was over. Some 230 boys
graduated that year, and most of them were fed into the best four
or five schools in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Like the old man, George W. Bush was going to Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Everything Falls Apart: New Haven, 1968
</P>
<P>
   They all seemed to loved George W. at Yale. Everybody except
John Lincoln, who lived across the hall from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was a member of Deke, the fraternity known to be the
drinking fraternity,'' Lincoln said. Nor did Lincoln, a computer
graphic artist, find the younger Bush's intellect to be formidable.
When word of Bush's White House ambition got out, ``I said to
myself, `You know, he's not all that smart.' Which is maybe what
the job takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Those on the prep school-Ivy League track were expected to
excel, go to business or law school, put on a suit and run the
world. It had been so for generations. But the academy was on the
verge of huge change in those days. In the early '60s at Yale,
jeans were pressed and worn with a belt. Students recall no more
than a couple of rebels _ out of 4,000 _ with long hair. There'd be
day trips to Vassar, or mixers where buses would park on York
Street and disgorge loads of girls from other schools. Then, just
before the winter break of '66, three guys had the unfortunate
distinction of being the first Yalies busted for smoking pot. It
was a national scandal. Students went home and were confronted with
parents demanding to know, What on earth is going on at that
school?
</P>
<P>
   Jack Morrison was Bush's bridge partner in the unending game at
Davenport College, and he caught Bush's pitches on the Davenport
baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things I remember are the times we would go on road trips
and just be weak with laughter,'' said Morrison, a former Pillsbury
executive who now is a partner in a private investment firm in
Minneapolis. ``We'd pile into a car and head off to some girls'
school up north. Never really got in any serious trouble at all,
but came close a couple of times. There were a couple of times when
you could say we probably consumed more than we should have, but
nothing terribly serious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Binge drinking'' hadn't been coined as a term, let alone
labeled a problem. Getting loaded was a hallowed part of college
life, and the Dekes reveled in the intertwined manly pursuits of
sports and drinking. But what about the rumored dancing naked and
drunk on a bar in New Haven? ``He never danced naked anywhere as
far as I know,'' Jack Morrison said. ``There was a lot of high
jinks, but nothing out of the ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, out in the world, everything was out of the ordinary.
Lyndon Johnson killed the graduate school draft deferment, and
suddenly hordes of young men were hearing the call of divinity
school, one of a dwindling number of legitimate safe havens. Lines
of jittery young men stretched around the block from National Guard
offices. Vietnam, or how to avoid it, was the topic of every other
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The Tet Offensive began Jan. 31, followed six weeks later by the
My Lai massacre, followed by Johnson's stunning announcement that
he would not seek re-election. Four days later, in Memphis, Tenn.,
Martin Luther King was killed. And between the end of classes and
commencement, so was Bobby Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell things were beginning to fall apart our senior
year,'' said Douglas Little, who was in Bush's class. ``This was
not a great time to graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   If political ambition beat in George W. Bush's breast at Yale,
it was well-concealed. Everybody knew where George Pataki _ the
future governor of New York who was a year ahead of Bush _ was
heading. Plenty of outlets were available for politically inclined
students. But George's passions, despite his father's political
proclivities, were sports and beer. And fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
