<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7227 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-SEMINOLES17-COX     06-16 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-SEMINOLES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black Seminoles: 2 cultures forged new life in Texas
 &HT;    By Norma Martin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It was an archaeological project in a South
Texas town that led University of Texas anthropologist Shirley Mock
to a little-known community.
</P>
<P>
   A golf course and houses were being planned in a section of
Brackettville, but before construction could start, the land had to
be excavated excavation for any culturally significant items. And
as part of the project, Mock was hired to interview the older
people who lived near the site. Those initial talks led to more
in-depth ethnological interviews and years of research into the
black Seminoles of Texas and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Singing to the Ancestors: Black Seminoles on the Border'' is
the culmination of Mock's five-year scholarly investigation. The
multimedia exhibit explores the search for freedom and the building
of a culture among a group that formed in the early 1800s, when
runaway slaves took shelter with the Seminole Indians in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the black Seminoles _ the descendants of those
African slaves and the Seminoles _ moved to Oklahoma along with
other Native American tribes as part of the historic Trail of
Tears. But slave bounty hunters were a constant threat forto the
group, and its members headed for Mexico by way of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of them crossed the Rio Grande and that's where Mock, an
anthropologist at the Institute of Texan Cultures, picked up their
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not aware of them being in Texas, but I knew they had a
story that had not been told,'' said Mock, who paid for her
research in South Texas and northern Mexico with a variety of
grants. ``They are forged by the ethnic diversity of their
background and bound together by their dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Many black Seminoles came to Texas as scouts for the U.S. Army
and became legends in Texas and American history for their skills.
But when the land treaties between the United States and Native
American nations were signed, the black Seminoles didn't get the
one they'd been promised, said Mock.
</P>
<P>
   Some went to Mexico to ranch and farm. Others became cowboys,
domestics and migrant workers working in Texas and throughout the
West.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit combines video footage and photographs to tell the
black Seminole story in Texas and Mexico. Mock said she wanted the
black Seminoles to describe their history, traditions and culture
themselves. In part of the video, the group's elders speak in what
they call the ``broken language,'' said Mock. They speak a form of
Gullah, which has Creole origins and uses English, African, Spanish
and Native American words.
</P>
<P>
   Like their language, the black Seminoles' religious traditions
are a blend of their cultural influences. ``They are a very
spiritual people,'' said Mock. One of their most honored religious
traditions is elder women who are called ``dream readers'' _ a
person's dreams and their meaning were taken very seriously among
the black Seminoles, Mock said.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the richness of the black Seminole culture, it is
dying out, said Mock. The language is only spoken by the oldest
elders.
</P>
<P>
   `Singing to the Ancestors: Black Seminoles on the Border'
</P>
<P>
   When: through Aug. 8
</P>
<P>
   Where: The University of Texas Institute of Texan Cultures in
HemisFair Park, 801 S. Bowie St., San Antonio
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $4 for adults and $3 for children ages 3 to 12
</P>
<P>
   Information: (210) 458-2300 or Web site:
www.texancultures.utsa.edu
</P>
<P>
   Norma Martin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
