<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7228 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-CHILLINGWORTHMURD     06-16 1778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CHILLINGWORTHMURDER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's 'Crime of the Century': More than just a murder story
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The voice of the murdered man can be
heard today, rising as if from the very depths of the silent ocean.
What are perhaps the victim's last written words are hastily
scribbled in pencil, on the back of a legal brief, which lies this
morning on a table under lamplight at the Palm Beach Historical
Society.
</P>
<P>
   It is the voice of Judge C.E. Chillingworth, abducted with his
wife 44 years ago, June 15, 1955, from a seaside bungalow in
Manalapan. The judge, 58, and his wife, Marjorie, 47, were bound,
weighted and forced overboard, alive, two miles out to sea, by two
assassins hired by a fellow judge who hated and feared
Chillingworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the crime of the century, at least as far as Palm Beach
County is concerned,'' said Clemmer Mayhew III, archivist at the
Historical Society of Palm Beach County. ``But for us, it's more
than just a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Chillingworth was our founding president. He served for
more than a dozen years. His father was the first sheriff and the
first judge in the county, and his grandfather was a pioneer here.
The Chillingworths were Palm Beach County. They were the
cornerstone. There is much more to his life than his death.''
</P>
<P>
   With this in mind, Mayhew wrote last month to Chillingworth's
daughter, Anne Wright, who lives in Gainesville, asking if she had
any material on her father she would be willing to donate to the
historical society.
</P>
<P>
   He struck gold. Wright sent a large box of material, including
voluminous clippings about the case, a family scrapbook going back
to World War I, family portraits and, most fascinating of all, a
scribbled pencil note on the back of a legal brief in which Judge
Chillingworth announces his desire to retire from the bench on June
16, 1955 _ the very day after he was murdered. The draft is
addressed to then-Florida governor Leroy Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The date appears to be erased and changed to July 1, why we
don't know, but it's a fascinating document,'' Mayhew said. ``It
shows the judge was plainly planning to retire. If the men who
killed him had known this, it might have saved his life. Who knows?
These may be the last words the judge ever wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft reads:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Governor Collins:
</P>
<P>
   ``For over thirty-four years, I have served as a Judge, the last
thirty two years as a Judge of the Circuit Court of the Fifteenth
Judicial Circuit of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of my health and for several reasons, I feel I should
retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having in 1939, elected to take the benefits of F.S. 38.14 and
since then complied with FS 38.17, I now elect to retire, with
compensation, as a Circuit Judge, under existing law and Florida
Constitution Article V Section 49 (46), the retirement to be
effective 16 (erasure) July 1, 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my respect and best wishes, I remain, Sincerely Yours.''
</P>
<P>
   There follows a short annotation, saying a signed copy is to go
to the state comptroller, then another instructional memo at the
bottom of the page:
</P>
<P>
   ``Before sending letter _ correspond with (comptroller) Gay to
ascertain whether $10416.66 per annum will be available etc.''
</P>
<P>
   The erased date is intriguing _ Mayhew says Chillingworth might
very well have written 16 June first, as he was first appointed a
circuit judge on June 15, 1923. The number 16 seems to ghost
through the erasure. In any case, he was plainly planning to step
down from the bench in mid-summer 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``June 15 is a date that echoes throughout his life,'' Mayhew
observed. ``He was appointed judge on June 15, and he was murdered
on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``JUDGE CHILLINGWORTH, WIFE, BELIEVED KIDNAP VICTIMS,'' screamed
The Palm Beach Times in its June 16 afternoon edition, the day the
judge and his wife were discovered missing by a handyman at the
Manalapan cottage. Papers all over the state picked up the story,
and the front pages can still be read in the historical society's
archives:
</P>
<P>
   ``SUSPECTS CHECKED AS HUNT FOR CHILLINGWORTH WIDENS'' (June 16).
</P>
<P>
   ``JUDGE AND WIFE BELIEVED ALIVE'' (June 17).
</P>
<P>
   ``CHILLINGWORTH CASE REACHES DEAD END'' (June 20).
</P>
<P>
   ``$113,000 REWARD'' (June 21).
</P>
<P>
   ``FATE OF JUDGE, MRS. CHILLINGWORTH, CONTINUES MYSTERY'' (June
23).
</P>
<P>
   Years passed. In 1959 the Florida legislature voted to keep the
$100,000 reward it had earlier voted on the books ``for eternity''
or until the case was solved. Finally, after five years, it was.
The solution proved nearly as shocking as the crime itself.
</P>
<P>
   Chillingworth had been ordered killed by a fellow judge, Joe
Peel Jr., who served on the municipal court bench and who was
suspected of shady dealings with moonshiners and bolita racketeers.
</P>
<P>
   Peel was due to appear before Chillingworth on charges of sloppy
law practice. Two divorce cases he handled as a private attorney
had been bungled badly. Peel also had ties to a hoodlum named Floyd
``Lucky'' Holzapfel, who had been in and out of trouble for years
and was hiding in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   One of Holzapfel's buddies, insurance agent James Yenzer, told
police Holzapfel had boasted to him he knew who had killed the
Chillingworths. Yenzer volunteered to lure Holzapfel back to the
U.S. and get him to talk about his crimes into a hidden microphone.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme worked. Yenzer lured Holzapfel to room 127 of the
Holiday Inn in Melbourne where, during a three-day drinking binge,
Holzapfel gradually revealed details of the murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, there's a hole out there in the ocean nobody's found the
bottom of,'' Holzapfel said darkly. Everything he said was recorded
by agent Henry Lovern of the Florida Sheriff's Bureau, on 30 reels
of tape. Lovern was sitting next door in room 129.
</P>
<P>
   Most damning of all, Holzapfel named his accomplice, Bobby
Lincoln, a black man from Riviera Beach who was serving time in a
federal prison for moonshining. Lincoln had run a numbers racket in
Palm Beach County at the time of the murders.
</P>
<P>
   Persuaded to talk in exchange for immunity from all prosecution,
Lincoln finally revealed exactly what had happened in Manalapan on
the night of June 15, 1955. Confronted with Lincoln's story,
Holzapfel broke down and confessed, too. Hearing of their
confessions, Peel fled to Tennessee where he was arrested in
Chattanooga.
</P>
<P>
   The two killers told how, in exchange for $2,500 from Judge
Peel, they had bought a boat and weighed anchor at the Blue Heron
Docks in Riviera Beach and had come ashore right outside the
judge's cottage. There they knocked on the door. The judge
answered, clad in his pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked the man, `Aren't you Judge Chillingworth?' and he
answered, `Yes, I am.' I immediately drew the pistol from under my
shirt and said, `This is a holdup.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The hitmen tied the couple up with tape and marched them across
the empty beach. The nearest neighbor was 700 yards distant.
Marjorie Chillingworth screamed. Lincoln hit her on the head with
his gun, opening a gash. Droplets of her blood were found on the
sand by bloodhounds the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Two miles offshore, in the Gulf Stream, Holzapfel cut the motor.
The judge tried to bargain for the couple's lives, promising
Lincoln he would ``never have to work again'' if he let them go.
</P>
<P>
   But he may have made a fatal mistake. He addressed Lincoln as
``boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln and Holzapfel then strapped weighted army web-belts onto
Mrs. Chillingworth. The doomed couple's last words to each other
were, ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Ladies first,' and pushed her in,'' Holzapfel
testified later. ``She went down with a few bubbles.''
</P>
<P>
   Weighted with a boat anchor, Chillingworth jumped of his own
accord. A Navy veteran and a graduate of Annapolis, he swam
strongly, keeping his head above water despite the anchor, despite
being bound. Lincoln leaned over the side of the boat and smashed
the stock of a shotgun on the judge's head. Chillingworth finally
sank.
</P>
<P>
   Peel was tried first. Holzapfel testified the judge had told
him: ``There's a man who is trying to mess up our business and I
want to kill him.'' The former judge got off with a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``PEEL GUILTY BUT CHEATS CHAIR,'' The Palm Beach Post announced.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln had immunity. Holzapfel cooperated fully, hoping to
escape the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   State attorney Phil O'Connell demanded it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ghost of Judge Chillingworth will not rest until his
killers are shoveling coal in the fires of hell and damnation,''
O'Connell told the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Russell O. Morrow agreed. ``You and your cohorts
participated in a crime or crimes which were gruesome, vicious,
cold-blooded, premeditated in design, and the likes of which the
history of Florida has not seen,'' he told Holzapfel just before
passing sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not just a man's life that was taken. It was Judge
Chillingworth that was taken ... He was a man of honor and, in a
sense, a bulwark in this county and state against the unlawful.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrow sentenced Holzapfel to death. The sentence was commuted
to life imprisonment in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Holzapfel remained in prison until his death on Oct. 12, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln went to Chicago, became a black Muslim and later
returned to Palm Beach County, where he still lives.
</P>
<P>
   Peel served 21 years behind bars, a model prisoner who attended
church regularly and worked on the prison newspaper. He was paroled
in 1982 and died nine days later of cancer. In a deathbed
interview, he said, ``There's no one to blame but myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of Judge C.E. Chillingworth and Marjorie
Chillingworth were never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   An empty double grave with a twin headstone bears their names
today in the Chillingworth family plot in West Palm Beach's Oak
Lawn Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Chillingworth Drive off Okeechobee Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   And there are now boxes of material on the judge's life at the
Palm Beach Historical Society, thanks to Anne Wright's generosity
and the historical society's polite persistence.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's military career, his activities in the community,
old addresses to the Rotarians, social engagements, honors,
recognitions of service, family photographs from his boyhood
onward, hunting and fishing pictures, all are preserved now in the
society's archives _ and with them the early history of Palm Beach
County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together with the murder clippings, they will remind people
that Chillingworth was more than a headline. He was a man,'' Mayhew
said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Browning writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
