<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7230 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN17-COX     06-16 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Only in today's society....
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``How low can you get?''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Dennis Faughn of Enon thought when he learned that
two teen-agers had robbed his 9-year-old son's lemonade stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``How low can you get?''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Detective Debby Branigan of the Butler County
Sheriff's Office thought when she heard about it. ``Here's a kid
willing to go out and work and earn his own money, and other kids
take advantage of him because they're too sorry to work,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there were a
today's-youth-is-going-to-hell-in-a-handbasket crime, this would be
it. But neither the detective's nor Aaron's faith in humanity has
been soured.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Aaron thanked me once he thanked me 10 times,'' Branigan
said. ``It makes me remember why I chose to do this job 17 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The detective's voice mail overflowed with dozens of calls from
irate residents when she came to work Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Has any other $6 theft sparked such an outrcy?
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be it,'' Branigan said. ``People can't believe
thugs would do this to a little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron wasn't so much heartbroken as indignant that anybody would
do this to his business partners, Jamie Curtin and Billy Holger.
``It was all of our money,'' Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon was the first day this the boys set up their
poolside lemonade stand at the Lakota Point Town Homes complex in
Butler County, where Aaron lives. (The enterprise kept them in
Pokemon cards last summer.) Around 4:30 p.m., two teen-agers pulled
up to the curbside stand in a red Chevrolet Blazer and asked for
change for $10. ``I let them count the money'' _ ruefulness creeps
into his voice _ ``and they ran off with it.'' The boys lost $6 _
enough for a pack of 11 Pokemon cards.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, the boys set up shop Friday. ``The attitude was,
'We're a business team here and nobody is going to get us down,'''
Dennis Faughn said.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron was prepared for adversity, but not, perhaps, instant
media celebrity. Now a veteran of countless TV and newspaper
interviews, he's a straight-ahead kid with the voice and manner of
one who cannot tell even a polite lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you tired of talking to reporters?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you as good and polite as Detective Branigan says you
are?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes yes and sometimes not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron garnered an important business lesson: ``Don't give people
your money; ask for their money first.'' He also learned a lot
about people: ``More people are nice than mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Take the response to the lemonade stand the boys set up Tuesday
at a nearby Kroger store. A local radio station did a live
broadcast, and some patrons paid as much as $5 or $10 for a 25-cent
cup of lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to give a dollar amount for what they raised for
fear there will be a rush of lemonade stand robberies reported,''
Branigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron has no such reticence. He said the sale raked in more than
$500.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to Aaron's keen eye for detail, two teens _ 16
and 17 _ apprehended Monday have been charged in the theft. It's
hardly the crime of the century, but it's the kind of thing that
makes folks pronounce today's kids the worst generation of
hooligans since Sodom and Gomorrah.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer to take my cue from Aaron Faughn. He has taught us it's
not enough to ask, ``How low can you get?'' about a handful of
rotten kids. He has shown us how beautifully the ordinary, everyday
kid _ the one with the lemonade stand on the corner _ can rise
above it.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
