<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7231 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINOR-COLUMN17-COX     06-16 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phoners' courtesy disconnects
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Some people I know are worried about Y2K
supplies or cellulite on their upper thighs or getting their
daughter into a good middle school. But I say these people are
self-absorbed and misguided.
</P>
<P>
   I say these people have their priorities all mixed up.
</P>
<P>
   What we all should be worrying about is the millions of
Americans who use cell phones to make calls from the most
ridiculous of places, including bathroom stalls.
</P>
<P>
   By some industry estimates, 26 new cell phone subscribers take
to the street every minute of every day so, yes, there is cause to
be afraid. But remember, these are important, busy people who are
going places, and fast.
</P>
<P>
   These are people who can actually order a pizza from the
interstate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has kind of gotten out of control,'' says businessman Emory
Rayle, 48, in town last week from Greenville, S.C. ``Sometimes I'm
driving down the road and the phone's going and the pager's going
and the radar's going off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rayle, a true traveling salesman, says he's so much more
efficient, so much more productive, because of his cell phone. It's
made his frantic business life manageable.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking about traveling out of the country to escape
the rude madness, forget it. Wireless calling isn't just an
American thing. In Brazil, 1 million people await cell phone
service. So coveted is a cell phone to a Brazilian's self-image
that it has been said that some people actually walk the streets of
Rio de Janeiro talking and chuckling and scowling into a fake cell
phone. In Finland, it's estimated that by the year 2001, there will
be more cell phones than actual Finnish people, although I'm a
little confused about how that whole two-phone-per-Finn theory
works out.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some growth figures from the Cellular
Telecommunications Industry Association in Washington, D.C.:
</P>
<P>
   _ 10 years ago, 2.6 million Americans used cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1996, the number was estimated at 33 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ And today, an estimated 75 million people use cell phones _
probably at a movie theater or restaurant near you.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Nelson, the association's spokesman, explains the
industry's growth like this: In the mid-1990s the Federal
Communications Commission ``auctioned off additional wireless
licenses, PCS services and other digital . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry, but it was at this point that I began to hear nothing
but: blah, blah, money, blah, blah, more money, blah, money, money,
money.
</P>
<P>
   I thanked nice Mr. Nelson and hung up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, before you pick up your cell phone to call and say that I'm
the misguided one. Before you call to say that a cell phone
literally saved your life one night when you were stranded with a
busload of nuns and blind orphans on a hot, dusty road somewhere,
relax.
</P>
<P>
   I realize they're time efficient. I realize they're a business
executive's godsend. I know they're much-needed security for people
with epilepsy and diabetes and heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   But what's bothering me, what's out of control, what's downright
rude, is the way all these people are using their cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   It's like the rest of us didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   A true story:
</P>
<P>
   There I was, using the facilities at a local restaurant, when I
heard this woman chatting away in her little stall. Now, that part
is not that unusual because when a woman is stranded without tissue
in a public restroom she will wail and scream and talk to just
about anyone who strolls in. I figure she needed help, so I shoved
a wad of white fake Charmin under the stall wall.
</P>
<P>
   No reaction, mainly because she was too busy talking to a loved
one on her wireless telephone. This was not a woman in need of
medical assistance, I can assure you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey,'' she was saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come meet me down here. I'm going to have a few beers and I'll
wait for you and. . . .'' Then, silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, don't be mad,'' she pouted. I threw my spare wad of white
tissue in the trash, and left.
</P>
<P>
   I watched her come out; recognized her from the shoes. She
walked up to the booth where she and her girlfriend were sitting.
Then her phone rang and she started to talk and then her
girlfriend's phone rang and she started to talk, too, and then they
both talked, but not to each other, and I watched the whole thing
from two booths over as though they were characters in some weird,
new MTV mini-series, ``Women who go out for beers but never speak
to one another.'' And that's when I realized we've all lost our
minds.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of cell phone manners has caught the eye of Judith
Martin, aka syndicated columnist Miss Manners, who is surprisingly
forgiving:
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who wants to work in an airplane, a hairdressing
establishment or while standing in line at the bank has Miss
Manners' blessing. The offense is not talking on the telephone,
much less in owning the equipment with which to do so. It consists
of intruding on others, or neglecting others, in order to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   I love that woman.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, the industry expert in Washington, says people are only
as polite with their cell phones as they are in other aspects of
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rude people are rude,'' Nelson says. ``And if you put a new
device in their hand with which to be rude, they'll use it.''
</P>
<P>
   But leave it to Californians to put it all in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey done by Pacific Bell, 60 percent of
Californians would rather go to the dentist _ the dentist! _ than
sit next to someone talking on their cell phone at the movies. I
rest my case.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
