<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7233 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARAGESALE-CLASH17-CO     06-16 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARAGESALE-CLASH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The language of Saturday bargaining
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The yard sale begins at 8, but three
women dressed in cottony bright island colors show up before 7 in
the bleakest of Toyotas. They move up the driveway, fan out like a
recon patrol, look over the merchandise, which is still being
lugged out of the garage by the bleary-eyed homeowner.
</P>
<P>
   One of the early shoppers spies a small cast-iron garden pot
bearing a $10 price. She lifts the pot, turns to the hostess of the
yard sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-cent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-cents?'' says the homeowner, her tone saturated with
incredulity. ``It's marked ten dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-cent.''
</P>
<P>
   The homeowner shrugs. Her posture and facial expression say ``no
dice.'' She turns to another early customer. The lady with the pot
says nothing, puts the pot down, moves on to a pile of children's
clothes. She picks up a little dress, marked $2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-cent,'' but nobody's listening.
</P>
<P>
   Why is no one listening? A Haitian made the bid, and frankly,
there is an uneasy truce between newly arrived immigrant shoppers
and longtime area residents who hold garage sales.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple, really. One culture's buying customs clash with the
selling customs of another.
</P>
<P>
   Haitians often arrive first at sales, frequently way before the
sale is to begin. Their approach to merchandise procurement is
simple: Shop till you drop _ the price, that is. Haitians are known
for driving hard bargains. Politely, but insistently.
</P>
<P>
   They are part of an astute Saturday morning shopping swarm where
English is a second language, merchandise is second-hand and
bargaining is second nature. The swarm also comes from far-away
places unfamiliar to many South Floridians, places such as Belize,
El Salvador, Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   They join other shoppers, many retired, who after 30 years on
the Ford line in Detroit or hanging Bell wire in the Northeast know
the value of a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   So join in, meet your neighbors. Bring your wallet, but credit
cards are not accepted. And don't leave home without your
foreign-language phrase books. A yard sale in Palm Beach County can
sound like a debate at the U.N.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dawn, and the Haitians are already out in the yard,''
says Barbie Rener, 32, of West Palm Beach, host of another yard
sale. ``They always show up early. And they always make ridiculous
offers. I don't mind haggling over price, that's part of the fun of
a yard sale. But no matter what price I put on anything, it's
always the same _ `fifty-cent, twenty-five-cent, ten-cent.' Hey,
this is America, sure. Everybody comes from somewhere, but when
they pull into the driveway I prepare for anything. One lady bought
a mirror, dropped it, broke it. She wanted her money back.''
</P>
<P>
   While she's talking, a white guy maybe 30 or 35 walks right up,
dressed nattily in loose blue silk shirt, pleated linen slacks,
soft boat shoes. But he looks seedy _ bloodshot eyes, two-days'
beard. Sort of like Brad Pitt after a really bad night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got any old booze you don't drink?'' he asks. ``Sometimes I
find a case of booze. Cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No booze for sale here,'' says Rener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got any old guns you don't shoot?'' asks the guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noooo,'' says Rener, taking a closer look now at the guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK. Bye now,'' and he's gone, off to greener pastures in a van
full of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Haitians are direct, sometimes a pain,'' Rener says. ``But
they're not nuts. Guatemalans are polite, don't drive a hard
bargain, and you don't see near as many. Then you get the rich
women. White. Big car, big hair, big money. Fight you for every
dime, but they'll pay sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast Florida Center on Aging at Florida International
University projects 13,500 Haitians and 132,500 Hispanics,
including 30,000 Guatemalans, will live in Palm Beach County by
2000, when FIU projects a total county population of 1,066,959, up
from 863,500 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday mornings, many of Palm Beach County's newcomers take
to the yard-sale circuit, repair to the flea market behind Lake
Worth High School, browse the Goodwill store in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Jeantinoble is in the clothes racks at a sale. He's 42,
married with three kids. He left Haiti 11 years ago, lives now in
Lake Worth. He's looking for clothes for his children. And he's
looking for ``tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennis?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, tennis. Michael Jordan.'' He lifts his foot, wiggles his
shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Does he resell the clothes he buys?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. When my children grow too big for the clothes, I give them
away.''
</P>
<P>
   He's shopping in the front yard of Ernesto Rodriguez, 72, former
taxi driver in Havana, and U.S. resident for 41 years. Rodriguez
runs a sale every few months. He gets children's clothes from his
sister-in-law. His yard is better stocked than a Havana dollar
store.
</P>
<P>
   Dinis Martins, 43, is looking the goods over. He's from
Portugal. He's been in Palm Beach County for . . . one day.
</P>
<P>
   One day, and he's at a yard sale? What's he looking for?
</P>
<P>
   ``A wife,'' says Martins.
</P>
<P>
   At a yard sale?
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend said many women go to these sales. Maybe I'll visit
Cuba if I don't find a woman here.''
</P>
<P>
   A while later, at a Lake Worth yard sale, Saincius Martin shows
up with two roommates. They're furnishing a house. Martin has been
in the U.S. three weeks. He was a musician in Haiti, played piano
at churches and religious festivals. Already, he's learned to grab
bargains and resell them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can buy a stereo for $20, sell for $100,'' he says. ``You
must buy for a low price, then sell for high.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to America.
</P>
<P>
   What else does he want to buy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Connie Drosakis, the homeowner, tells Martin a couch in the
living room is for sale. Martin goes into the house. There's a
piano inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much for the piano?'' he yells to Drosakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for sale,'' she calls back.
</P>
<P>
   A pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much for the piano?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin exits. ``I need a piano for my work,'' says Martin, but
nobody is listening.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Jeantinoble arrives seeking kids' clothes. Mr.
Booze-and-Guns arrives seeking alcohol and firearms. The homeowner,
Ms. Drosakis, a music teacher, is thinking maybe there's a lesson
here for someone.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Martin and his pals depart in search of a piano. They won't
find a piano at the flea market in Lake Worth, but they could
furnish a house with the goods for sale in the dusty parking lot
under a bridge behind the high school. Thing is, at this bazaar
it's cash-and-carry, the merchandise is not under warranty and most
of it looks like knock-offs of knock-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Gonzales, 30, is a vendor, one of 60 or more who sell out
of vans, tents and from fold-up tables. He works construction
during the week, tries to supplement his income on weekends by
selling straw hats, Latin American flags and soccer balls. He came
here from Guatemala three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Does he dream of becoming a retail magnate?
</P>
<P>
   ``I dream of going home, to Guatemala, to a farm. Someday I'll
go home,'' he says. ``When I sell enough hats.''
</P>
<P>
   His hats are made in Mexico, sell for $8. His soccer balls sell
for $18, made in Argentina. Not much here is made in the U.S.A.
There are religious icons, Jesus of the Sacred Heart paintings,
hair nets, Roma detergent, Dial Oro soaps and lotions and esponges
delux, all with labels in Spanish. For the collector there are
stamps, coins and Beanie Baby knock-offs. Table fans for those
without AC. Fresh produce is arranged on carts, but the prices are
high. One vendor sells license plates, including one that states:
I'd rather be shopping at Wal-Mart. Victor has never been to a
Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   On a good Saturday he makes $50, Gonzales says.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty dollars will buy much at the Goodwill store on Dixie
Highway in West Palm Beach. This is where yard-sale shoppers end up
when they can't find the right size kids' clothing at any price,
even 10 cents. Many of the customers are young Guatemalans who live
nearby and can't do the yard-sale circuit because they don't own
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the clothing at the Goodwill store is priced between
$1.65 and $2.85, with a couple of racks of ``reduced'' prices. The
store is clean, air-conditioned, full of freshly laundered, used
clothing. And couches, dining tables, high chairs. And Mitch Miller
and Chubby Checker records and old Easter baskets and mini-vacs,
Mr. Coffees and Mr. Teas. But no pianos.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, a bunch of young Guatemalan farmworkers wait
near a lone pay phone, wait for their turn to call home with
calling cards bought at the Cuban restaurant up the street. They
sip papaya drinks purchased at the little Latin American grocery
store on the corner. They wear straw hats of the sort Victor sells.
Some wear cowboy boots, some tennis, maybe knock-offs, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Two of them wait for a favorable light so they can cross Dixie,
take a look-see in Goodwill. Who should drive by but Mr.
Jeantinoble. And right behind him, sitting high and proud in his
van of stuff, Mr. Booze-and-Guns.
</P>
<P>
   It's Saturday. And everybody who is anybody is shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
