<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7237 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ABA-NBA-FINALS-AZ     06-16 1699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ABA-NBA-FINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABA SPIRIT EN DURES  
 SPURS PROUD OF ROOTS IN INNOVATIVE LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By AL TOBY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cumulus cloud-size Afros of Artis Gilmore and Darnell
Hillman have been replaced by the braids of Latrell Sprewell and
Allen Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Erving's assault on the laws of gravity in professional
basketball's first slam dunk contest paved the way for Michael
Jordan's Air-obatics 12 years later.
</P>
<P>
   The bikini-clad ball girls of the Miami Floridians are today's
Laker Girls.
</P>
<P>
   The American Basketball Association is a bygone league long
forgotten by today's generation of professional players. All that's
left of the league are scattered bits and pieces of nostalgia,
bordering between fact and myth.
</P>
<P>
   But every now and then, the ABA will creep back into the
national sports consciousness. This year, it has horned its way
onto the biggest stage in professional basketball, the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs made history when they became the first
team that merged from the ABA to reach the NBA Finals. Visions of
an all-ABA final were shattered when the New York Knicks defeated
the Indiana Pacers in the Eastern Conference finals, much to the
chagrin of former San Antonio Spur and NBA Hall of Famer George
Gervin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted an all-ABA Finals with Indiana,'' Gervin
said. ``Wouldn't that have been something special? But I'm glad
that my guys are in it. It took me 26 years to finally see this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gervin, who works as a community relations representative for
the Spurs, represents a fierce pride that ABA players feel about
their league today. It is a pride that Gervin says is rooted in
today's Spurs, even though they're a generation removed from the
red, white and blue basketball era.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them guys give me nothing but props,'' Gervin, said.
``All they talk about is winning the championship for the Iceman.
We're the foundation for the franchise. They know without us they
wouldn't have the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Gervin is halfway right in crediting the ABA for setting the
foundation of basketball in San Antonio. He should have added that
the ABA was part of the foundation that improved the NBA. &QL; 
Vanilla vs. rainbow swirl
</P>
<P>
   If the two clashing basketball leagues were characterized by ice
cream, the NBA would be a scoop of vanilla in a crystal-clear glass
bowl. The ABA would be a scoop of rainbow swirl topped with hot
fudge, in a Dixie cup.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA was rooted in its traditional center-oriented game, do
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the major difference was the NBA had more big
people,'' said Al Bianchi, former coach of the Virginia Squires and
current scout for the Phoenix Suns. ``The ABA had more of the
little guys who could shoot and run up and down the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Those guards and forwards created a style of play that kept the
scoreboards moving at a pace that sickened staunch NBA
traditionalists. The game featured more dunks, the three-point shot
and fast breaks.
</P>
<P>
   In the ABA's first game in 1967, the Oakland Oaks defeated the
Anaheim Amigos, 132-129. Scores like these kept a modest interest
in the rag-tag league that throughout its existence was hanging on
by threads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our marketing strategy was to play good basketball for people
in the stands to talk about,'' Gervin said. ``So we had to play run
and gun. We didn't have the paper or the cable TV like they do
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The free-flowing game allowed ABA players to showcase their
personality through basketball as seen by the colorful style of
Erving, Gervin, David Thompson, Connie Hawkins, Fatty Taylor,
Lavern ``Jelly'' Tart and Louie Dampier.
</P>
<P>
   It mirrored the counterculture generation's freedom of
expression, says Dan Pattison, former vice president of the ABA
sportswriter's association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ABA gave the players a chance to express their feelings
through their motor skills, like what Dr. J did,'' Pattison said.
``The NBA would've put a stop to the free flowing of their
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   The personalities that shaped the mystique of the ABA played a
significant role in the revival of the NBA after the Pacers, Spurs,
Denver Nuggets and New York Nets were merged into the league in
1976. It supplied the NBA with the star power it had lost once the
careers wound down for Hall of Famers Wilt Chamberlain, Bill
Russell, Jerry West and Elgin Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Sports columnist and author Terry Pluto, whose book ``Loose
Balls'' is heralded as one of the best works on the ABA, said the
merger helped save a league that was in desperate need of stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was the dark ages of the NBA,'' Pluto said. ``At the
time, people just didn't care about basketball. It was the third
sport at the time. I would go so far as to say it was the fourth
sport behind boxing because of Muhammad Ali.''
</P>
<P>
   The infusion of ABA talent in the NBA was evident after the
merger. In the 1977 NBA All-Star game, 10 of the 24 players were
from the ABA. The Denver Nuggets had the second-best record in the
league (50-32). Half of the starting lineups in the NBA Finals
between Portland and Philadelphia were from the ABA.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-ABA head coach Tom Nissalke was the NBA Coach of the Year.
The ABA brought Stan Albeck, Bianchi, Hubie Brown, Larry Brown,
K.C. Jones, Kevin Lougherty and Doug Moe into the NBA coaching
fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   NBC broadcaster Bob Costas, who began his career doing radio for
the Spirits of St. Louis, said it was impossible for the NBA to
avoid the ABA's star influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually the NBA absorbed some of the style of the ABA,
looking at the slam dunk contest, which today has run its course,
the three-point shot and the influence of Dr. J,'' Costas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a guy who could be flamboyant and still be a
winner.'' &QL; 
Selling the game
</P>
<P>
   The Suns Gorilla. Halftime dance shows. Hip hop and R&AMP;B music
blasting in arenas during timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   All of these are entertaining fixtures in today's NBA. During
the league's ``dark days,'' they were non-existent.
</P>
<P>
   But in the ABA, they were a source of survival.
</P>
<P>
   According to one former ABA promotions director and current NBA
marketing official, the ABA's creative and at times outrageous
stunts set the tone for today's marketing in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Hanson, senior vice president for NBA Team Services, which
oversees the marketing strategy for 29 teams, saw firsthand how
influential the ABA was as a promotions director for the Denver
Nuggets in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really did a lot of the stuff the NBA wasn't doing,''
Hanson said. ``Back then the NBA was very traditional. We had to
try a lot harder because of the situation we were in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers had a halftime show where fans and local
media could wrestle a bear named ``Victor.'' The Kentucky Colonels
became the first and only team in ABA history to have a woman play.
Penny Ann Early passed the ball to Bobby Rascoe, who called a
timeout after her in-bound pass. The play that lasted less than
five seconds drew widespread publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson said that once the NBA saw the attendance figures of the
four ABA teams that merged into the league, they took notice of the
ABA's marketing strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider the game to be the centerpiece of the action, but
we wanted to be able to appeal to families,'' Hanson said.
``Everyone isn't into the X's and O's. We wanted in some respects
to do what the ABA did.'' &QL; 
Redemption, recognition
</P>
<P>
   The ABA can take credit for giving players like Gervin a chance
at not just honing their skills, but at redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Before Gervin became the Iceman, he developed a reputation as
someone who couldn't keep his cool. While playing at Eastern
Michigan in college, Gervin punched an opposing player. His actions
resulted in the end of his career at Eastern Michigan and no
possibility of making the NBA. His only chance at professional
basketball was through the ABA.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The ABA) gave me a quick opportunity to play pro ball because
of the situation I was in,'' Gervin said. ``The ABA was there for
me, and I took advantage of it. I just wanted to play pro ball.
Back then, my opportunities were scarce.''
</P>
<P>
   Gervin took advantage of his opportunity. He averaged 21.9
points per game, which is fifth on the ABA all-time scoring list.
After the merger, Gervin won four NBA scoring titles. Only Jordan
and Chamberlain have more scoring titles.
</P>
<P>
   Another noted case involved Connie Hawkins. The New York
playground legend was blackballed by the NBA because of gambling
allegations that were unsubstantiated in court.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to compete in the NBA, Hawkins played two years for the
Pipers franchise, which moved from Pittsburgh to Minneapolis during
Hawkins' second year in the league. Hawkins was the league's first
MVP and led his team to the first ABA championship. He filed an
antitrust suit against the NBA, which was settled out of court
before he signed with the Suns in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Gervin's respect for the ABA comes from the league's willingness
to give him a chance. Gervin said the league deserves more respect
from the NBA hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, they don't even like to talk about us,'' Gervin said.
``They don't want to recognize us and our productions if you look
at the records.''
</P>
<P>
   But the history books are written by the winners, and it was the
NBA that won the basketball war, said former Indiana Pacer Len
Elmore, now a commentator for CBS-TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take a look on a league-wide basis, the NBA is
essentially part of the revisionist history,'' Elmore said. ``None
of the ABA stats are recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gervin, ``I think it's sad that they don't recognize that
part of our careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Rick Barry, the first NBA player to jump to the
ABA in 1967, stands on the other side of the fence. Barry, who
currently coaches the New JerseyShorecats in the USBL, described
his stint in the ABA as ``difficult'' because of the numerous
lawsuits involved with his signing with the Oakland Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   But Barry said he isn't demeaning the league, even though it had
its share of shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was what it was, no more, no less,'' Barry said. ``I
could've done without all the bush league and Mickey Mouse stuff.''
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
