<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7239 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-TAKE     06-16 2084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read an article about a Kenneth Russell of Louisville,
Tenn., identifying him as the World War II parachutist who hung on
the roof of a church in Sainte-Mere-Eglise, France, while German
gunners shot at him. According to a postcard I bought at that
church in 1996, the soldier's name was John Steele. Can you
explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: As many as 13,000 paratroopers were dropped near Sainte-Mere
Eglise and Pegasus Bridge in the early hours of June 6, 1944, so
it's possible that more than one became entangled on a church
steeple. But, as your postcard indicates, Steele is the person whom
most people associate with this incident.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who saw the movie ``The Longest Day'' will recall the
dramatic scene in which Pvt. John Steele was hanging from the
church steeple by the entangled harness of his parachute. From
there, he watched the wholesale murders of his buddies by German
soldiers in the town square below. Actor Red Buttons, in a reversal
from his usual comedy roles, portrayed Steele.
</P>
<P>
   The real Steele, of the 82nd Airborne Division, F Company, got
caught on the steeple just as the movie scene depicted. He tried to
cut himself down, but dropped his knife. Germans using machine guns
were firing at other paratroopers hung up in the trees, so Steele
played dead. Even so, a German saw him and shot upward, hitting
Steele in the foot. His foot kept bleeding, and as a fellow
paratrooper recounted later, Steele was petrified that an enemy
solider would see he was bleeding and shoot him again.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans took Steele prisoner after two hours, but he was
released four days later when the town was liberated by the Allies.
Steele died in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I think Jerry Falwell has really compromised his intellectual
integrity, and I want to write to tell him so. What is his address?
</P>
<P>
   A: Friends and foes alike can contact him by regular mail at
this address: The Rev. Jerry Falwell, Thomas Road Baptist Church,
701 Thomas Road, Lynchburg, VA 24502. Or by e-mail:
jerryfalwell(at)trbc.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: Not long after the movie ``Titanic'' came out, there were
several articles about plans to build one or more replica ships.
What is the status of these projects?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both seem to have sunk. Two competing firms, one with Swiss
and Las Vegas connections, the other based in South Africa, had
said they would build ships identical to the Titanic externally,
but with modern innards. One was to set sail in April 2002 on a
maiden voyage from Southampton, England, to New York, precisely 90
years after the original. The other was to make its initial voyage
this coming Dec. 29, which its backers called ``the eve of the new
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much has been heard since the projects were announced last
year, and for a good reason, according to Fran Golden, a senior
editor for Travel Weekly, a publication for travel agents. No
contracts for either replica vessel ever were signed with major
shipyards. She added that she didn't think the projects for the
replicas ever were taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Another project, calling for construction of the world's largest
oceanliner, has a better chance. But it has nothing to do with the
Titanic. That vessel, if built, would be operated by Cunard, a
subsidiary of Carnival Corp., Golden said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did the most recent space shuttle land in total darkness?
It seems like daylight hours would be safer.
</P>
<P>
   A: Safety is a primary concern, said NASA spokesman John Petty,
but the timing was mandated by Discovery's orbit, which takes it
around Earth every 90 minutes. Not every orbit puts it within range
of landing at the Kennedy Space Center, which NASA prefers so that
the shuttle doesn't have to be transported back to Florida from
California, the alternate landing site.
</P>
<P>
   There are only a few opportunities to land the shuttle each day,
Petty said, and of the two on June 6, when Discovery came down,
both were at night. The first landing opportunity _ the one
Discovery actually used _ was an ``ideal path'' bringing the
astronauts across Costa Rica, Cuba and then almost straight up
Florida's east coast to the landing site. If it had waited just one
more orbit, Petty said, the path would have shifted to a ``less
ideal'' one taking the orbiter northbound across the Yucatan
Peninsula and across Florida just north of St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   This was the 11th time in 94 flights, by the way, that a space
shuttle has returned to Earth in darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I attended the start of the History Channel's Great Race for
vintage cars. How can I keep up with its status?
</P>
<P>
   A: Fans can keep pace with the event on The History Channel.
Each weeknight the network is presenting exclusive daily updates
along the route. Competitors in the 17th annual cross-country
event, which began June 6 in Marietta, Ga., will take about 14 days
to reach California, where the final destination is Anaheim. An
Internet site _ www.greatrace.com/ _ has general information about
the event.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to begin stocking water in case we run into Y2K
problems at the end of the year. How long is store-bought bottled
water good? If I put water into my own bottles or jugs, how long
will it keep?
</P>
<P>
   A: All bottled water carries an expiration date on the
container, so that should be your guide. Most bottled water is good
for up to two years; what is on store shelves now has an expiration
date of 2001. Bottles shouldn't be opened and then resealed,
because bacteria can contaminate the contents. Store the bottles in
a cool, dry place away from sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to bottle your own water, use clean containers _
just run them through the dishwasher first, with no other
sanitizing required _ and label them with the date. The water can
be kept for six months in a cool, dry place. As with the
store-bought product, don't open the bottles and drink from them
and replace the cap.
</P>
<P>
   A general rule for stocking water is to have a gallon of water
per person, per day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where have the hummingbirds gone? In years past we have had
several birds at the feeders from April to late October. This year
we have rarely seen any.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hummingbirds nest and hang around the yard in response to
steady food sources, good nesting habitat and feasible living
areas, said Paul Thomas, a University of Georgia horticulturist. He
added that he knows of no disease or population problem. Perhaps
there has been a change in your area such as fewer trees, more
development, drought-reduced flowering of garden plants or some
other factors that made staying in that area less desirable for the
hummers.
</P>
<P>
   These tips may help you attract the birds back. Have three or
four feeders for the birds to choose from, and keep them clean and
filled. Plant phlox paniculata, Salvia guaranitica, Vitex ``Agnes
Castus,'' Nicotiana and red annual Salvia bedding plants, as well
as Impatiens. ``These are very good attractors and nector plants
that will encourage hummingbirds to stay all summer,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard about a spat between Rosie O'Donnell and Tom
Selleck. What happened?
</P>
<P>
   A: It had to do with guns and was but one of several incidents
involving talk show host O'Donnell. When Selleck appeared on her
program May 19, she launched into a vehement attack on the National
Rifle Association, sending the two into a heated on-air discussion.
Selleck, who said he thought he would be discussing his latest
movie, instead was asked to talk about the gun issue because he's
an NRA member and because he had participated in an ad for the
organization. O'Donnell later said she did ``not apologize for my
feelings,'' but regretted embarrassing or offending Selleck.
</P>
<P>
   After that incident, O'Donnell reportedly asked the cast of
Broadway's ``Annie Get Your Gun'' to change a song lyric in
``Anything You Can Do'' before taping her show, but the performers
refused. Representatives of O'Donnell's program and the musical
subsequently denied the report.
</P>
<P>
   And then Howard Stern accused O'Donnell of being hypocritical by
fighting for gun control while at the same time being a commercial
spokeswoman for Kmart, which sells guns. She responded by saying
Kmart is a responsibile seller of hunting rifles, which are legal
to own.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I haven't seen an update on Charismatic, the horse that broke
its leg at the Belmont Stakes. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Charismatic broke a cannon bone, between the knee and the
ankle in his left foreleg, and the sesamoid bones in the back of
the ankle. Dr. Stephen Selway, who performed surgery for 2 1/2
hours on June 6, the day after the race, proclaimed it a success.
He added that the injury ``was not the worst of this kind I've ever
seen, but it was a nasty one.''
</P>
<P>
   Selway said he believed the colt's cannon bone fractured in the
final furlong, which is where Charismatic was passed, and the
sesamoids fractured as he tried to go on. Three screws were
inserted into the cannon bone, but Charismatic's cracked sesamoid
bones were deemed too fragile for any screws. Selway added,
however, that they would heal naturally, and ``he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know anything about a man in a newspaper article who
builds and repairs windmills? If so, how can I contact him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Write or call Ken O'Brock at O'Brock Windmills, 9435 12th
St., North Benton, Ohio (330-584-4681). O'Brock said he's very much
in demand from people wanting to draw their own water in case of
Y2K water system failures. A 36-page catalog about his company's
products costs $2.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have received three e-mails recently warning that Congress
is about to pass a bill allowing charges for each e-mail. Could
this be true? The bill is 602P, according to one person.
</P>
<P>
   A: Whoever is sending these e-mails is perpetuating a hoax that
seems to have started in Canada, then spread to the United States.
The usual message claims that a ``Congressman Schnell'' has
introduced ``Bill 602P'' to allow the federal government to impose
a 5-cent surcharge on each e-mail message delivered over the
Internet. The money would be collected by Internet service
providers and then turned over to the U.S. Postal Service, the
messages say.
</P>
<P>
   It's a ``completely false rumor,'' the Postal Service says. No
such proposed legislation exists, and in fact ``Congressman
Schnell'' doesn't exist, either. That alone should be a clue that
this whole scheme is a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service addressed the issue with a news release dated
May 21. The release said USPS has no authority to surcharge e-mail
messages sent over the Internet, nor would it support such
legislation. To read the release online, check the Postal Service's
Web site at www.usps.gov and click on the icon titled ``E-mail
rumor completely untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever became of O.J. Simpson's good friend who was
involved in the infamous car chase. Does anyone know what he is
doing now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Al ``A.C.'' Cowlings was the driver of the Bronco during the
famed June 17, 1994, Los Angeles freeway chase, which was televised
live from helicopters hovering overhead. A friend of Simpson's and
a college and professional football colleague, Cowlings most
recently was reported to be working as a sales representative for a
shoe and handbag company. No other details were available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend lost his DD 214 discharge papers from the military.
How can he go about getting a replacement?
</P>
<P>
   A: Duplicate copies of discharge or separation papers can be
obtained by writing to the National Personnel Records Center,
Military Personnel Records, 9700 Page Blvd., St. Louis, MO
63132-5100.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran's full name should be printed clearly or typed. The
request also must contain the signature of the veteran or, if the
veteran is deceased, that of the next of kin. Include the branch of
service, service number or Social Security number, and exact or
approximate dates and years of service.
</P>
<P>
   Use Standard Form 180, ``Request Pertaining to Military
Records,'' available online at www.nara.gov/regional/mprsf180.html
or from Department of Veterans Affairs offices.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
