<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW OPTIONS REMAIN IN BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's official, the Diamondbacks' bullpen situation is
a complete mess, not just a minimal one.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a wreck on the Squaw Peak Freeway, the DPS boys
would have the dang thing shut down for 16 hours, not knowing what
to make of it.
</P>
<P>
   Buck Showalter, the favorite target of the backseat managers at
Bank One Ballpark and the airwaves, has, plain and simple, run out
of options and must be at his wit's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what tomorrow brings,'' he answered when asked
whether his ninth-inning situation is any closer to being cleared
up.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Olson, who started the season as the closer, seems to have
lost all remnants of any confidence he once possessed. Even though
he managed to save Tuesday's victory over the major league-worst
Florida Marlins, it couldn't come without the usual drama.
</P>
<P>
   Olson gave up an RBI single and hit a batter before the very
dangerous Cliff Floyd grounded out while swinging at the first
pitch he saw. Olson did register his third consecutive save, but
his saves seem to come prepackaged with loads of anxiety, and that
simply is not a good mix for a closer.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Nunez, whom Showalter badly wanted to see nail down the
save Tuesday, couldn't deliver, issuing a single and a four-pitch
walk after retiring the first batter in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Nunez was replaced by left-hander Dan Plesac, who struck out
pinch-hitter Mark Kotsay before being replaced by Olson. Plesac has
now retired all five batters he has faced since being acquired from
Toronto and is doing exactly what the Diamondbacks envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   Plesac's role, though, will be that of a situational reliever,
primarily facing left-handed batters and heading to the dugout at
the first sign of a right-hander. At this stage of his career,
Plesac has come to grips with that role, for which he is highly
suited.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Holmes, the best set-up pitcher the club has on its
roster, once again turned in a fine effort. After allowing a
run-scoring single, he struck out Floyd on a nasty split-fingered
fastball and then got the final two outs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes has lowered his ERA to 2.77 and is set up perfectly in
his current role. There is no need to meddle with him. Anyone
thinking Holmes should be moved to closer would be wise to think of
the club's needs in the seventh and eighth innings first.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Swindell, the other left-hander, hasn't pitched since
Saturday and is suffering from soreness in his rib cage. He has not
been available the past three games and will probably won't be
available tonight. If his condition does not progress by Friday,
the club will probably place Swindell on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Byung-Hyun Kim is an intriguing piece to the puzzle but has had
problems pitching consecutive days. He may be best suited as a
setup man or a possible starter down the line.
</P>
<P>
   In order for the Diamondbacks' bullpen to work best, the closer
must emerge from between Olson and Nunez. A bullpen by committee
simply does not work.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Swindell and Plesac as the left-handers, to be used
interchangeably at different stages of the game, is the best
scenario from that standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Holmes in his role is definitely in his and the club's
best interest. That leaves Olson and Nun ez to battle it out for
the closer's role.
</P>
<P>
   The bad karma surrounding Olson these days has too many negative
vibes for him to work at this juncture. The mere fact that he hears
boos drowning out his name over the loudspeakers at his home
stadium puts him in a negative state of mind before he delivers his
first pitch. You can bet it also puts the opposition in a positive
state.
</P>
<P>
   Nunez could be the man. The opportunity is his for the taking
right now, but repeating what he did Tuesday night will not endear
him to the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the closer's job with all my soul,'' Nunez said before
Tuesday's game. ``There is no comparison to how I feel now and when
I came up for the first time last year. I now know I can do the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   All he has to do is seize it and it's his. Showalter is
desperately searching for someone to step forward. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
