<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS17-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about the person who replaced
former Atlanta resident and businessman Edward Elson as U.S.
ambassador to Denmark?
</P>
<P>
   A: Elson's successor is Richard Swett, who was nominated by
President Clinton in April 1998 and confirmed by the Senate three
months later. He presented his credentials to Denmark's Queen
Margrethe Sept. 8, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Swett was born May 1, 1957, in Lower Marion, Pa. He received a
degree in architecture from Yale University in 1979 and is a member
of the American Institute of Architects. A Democrat, he was elected
to the House in 1990. He was re-elected in 1992, but in 1994 lost
his re-election bid to Republican Charles Bass.
</P>
<P>
   Internet users can check www.usembassy.dk for detailed
information about Swett's background.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know the deadline for the lottery for Super Bowl 2000
tickets has passed, but I've been told that people who use
wheelchairs have a separate lottery with a later deadline. Is that
so?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The Super Bowl XXXIV Host Committee says the deadline
for entering the random drawing for wheelchair section tickets is
Sept. 1 (the deadline for the random drawing for regular tickets
was June 1). To request the seats, send a letter, accompanied by
proof of disability, to: Ms. Sunday Billings, Special Events
Coordinator, National Football League, 280 Park Ave., New York, NY
10017. Applicants will be notified of the results in October, with
winners receiving an invoice for one wheelchair seat and one
companion seat.
</P>
<P>
   The Host Committee emphasizes that this drawing is only for
guests using wheelchairs, with disabled guests using other forms of
assistance not eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm sorry Charismatic was injured in the Belmont Stakes, but
I'd like some information about the winner, Lemon Drop Kid. Who is
his owner, trainer, and jockey?
</P>
<P>
   A: The owner is Jeanne Vance, who husband, Laddie Dance, is a
former auctioneer at Keeneland, a track near Lexington, Ky. The
trainer is Scotty Schulhofer, and the jockey is Jose Santos. The
colt, a son of Kingmambo, was named by Vance in honor of a champion
show horse from years back. That horse, incidentally, took its name
from a Damon Runyon character.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid had won only once this year, at Florida's
Gulfstream Park in February. He finished ninth in the Kentucky
Derby and passed on the Preakness. He then ran in the Peter Pan
Stakes at Belmont, finishing third. It's expected that he will get
a break now, probably to surface in several months at Saratoga Race
Course in Saratoga Springs, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   It was jockey Santos' first win in 17 tries in a Triple Crown
race. It was trainer Schulhofer's second Triple Crown victory, the
first coming in the 1993 Belmont with Colonial Affair.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your response to the reader's question about the number of
executive orders signed by President Clinton raises another
question. How many executive orders were signed by recent previous
presidents?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the National Archives and Records Administration
Federal Register, President Kennedy signed 214 executive orders
between 1961 and 1963; Johnson, 324 (1963-69); Nixon, 346
(1969-74); Ford, 169 (1974-77); Carter, 320 (1977-81); Reagan, 381
(1981-89); Bush, 166 (1989-93). And Clinton has signed 289 from
1993 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Executive order tables can be viewed online at
www.nara.gov/fedreg/eo.html
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened in the Synthroid class action suit? I sent
in my paperwork about this time last year, but I've never heard
anything one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   A: There has been no settlement yet. The suit contends that the
drug's manufacturer suppressed for more than seven years the
publication of a medical study whose conclusion was that the drug's
generic equivalent worked just as well in the treatment of thyroid
problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 10, 1998, Judge Elaine Bucklo of the U.S. District Court
for the Northern District of Illinois held a status conference in
this litigation. The court scheduled further proceedings in the
litigation through October 1999. No trial date has yet been set.
And no money will be paid to any class members unless and until a
class is certified by the court, and the class obtains a final
judgment in its favor after trial or a further settlement is agreed
upon and approved by the court. The safety and effectiveness of
Synthroid isn't involved, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet site on the subject _ www.synthroidclaims.com _
advises people who already have filed a claim form that their name
and address will be maintained by the settlement administrator, and
no further action is required. Information: 1-800-853-4853.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the dollar sign?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some people think it evolved from the letter S over the
letter U, with the bottom part of the U dropped off. But that's not
so, according to the Bureau of Engraving and Printing and World
Book Encyclopedia. They explain that $ most likely evolved from the
Mexican or Spanish Ps, for pesos or piastres. The S gradually came
to be written over the P, developing a close equivalent to $. It
was widely used before the adoption of the U.S. dollar in 1785.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I keep seeing ads on TV, usually featuring celebrities, for a
book titled ``Power for Living.'' Do you have any information about
the sponsoring organization?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Arthur S. DeMoss Foundation, established in 1955 by
Arthur DeMoss, a Philadelphia businessman known for his funding of
evangelical causes, is behind the book, which is described as a
Christian self-help guide. The foundation, now based in West Palm
Beach, Fla., is headed by DeMoss' widow, Nancy, and continues to
support evangelical outreach efforts such as Campus Crusade for
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The book is free (1-800-341-2000), and foundation literature
says those who respond will not be called or solicited for money.
</P>
<P>
   An article in The Washington Post reported that the ad campaign
has drawn some concern because of its characterization of religion
as an antidote for depression. But Michael Cromartie of the Ethics
and Public Policy Center, a conservative think tank, defended it.
``There is nothing sinister about it,'' he told the Post. ``This is
a genuine effort to get people to consider the claims of the
Gospel.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the reasoning behind New Hampshire's taking so long
to adopt the Martin Luther King Jr. national holiday?
</P>
<P>
   A: New Hampshire for years has been observing what it called
Civil Rights Day, but until Monday it didn't have King's name
attached. The change to Martin Luther King Jr. Civil Rights Day,
which will be observed for the first time next Jan. 17, ends two
decades of attempts to honor the slain civil rights leader.
Opponents had argued that singling out King would detract from
other American heroes, such as George Washington and Abraham
Lincoln. The Nashua (N.H.) Telegraph also reported that legislative
and other critics had opposed a holiday named for King because of
his vocal opposition to the Vietnam War, allegations of ties with
Communist leaders, and unsubstantiated stories about King's
personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who are the members of Congress who filed a lawsuit to
declare the U.S. bombing of Yugoslavia illegal?
</P>
<P>
   A: Initially there were 17 plaintiffs seeking ``declaratory
relief'' against President Clinton, saying he was
unconstitutionally continuing a military attack against Yugoslavia
without obtaining a declaration of war from Congress. The suit,
filed April 30, was amended later to include 26, then 31, members
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Those initial 17: Reps. Tom Campbell (R-Calif.), Dennis Kucinich
(D-Ohio), Bob Barr (R-Ga.), Roscoe Bartlett (R-Md.), Dan Burton
(R-Ind.), John Cooksey (R-La.), Philip Crane (R-Ill.), Walter Jones
(R-N.C.), Marcy Kaptur (D-Ohio), Donald Manzullo (R-Ill.), Charlie
Norwood (R-Ga.), Ron Paul (R-Texas), Thomas Petri (R-Wis.),
Marshall Sanford (R-S.C.), Joe Scarborough (R-Fla.), Bob Schaffer
(R-Colo.) and Thomas Tancredo (R-Colo.).
</P>
<P>
   Those joining: Reps. Richard Baker (R-La.), Christopher Cannon
(R-Utah), Terry Everett (R-Ala.), Jack Metcalf (R-Wash.), John
Doolittle (R-Calif.), Rick Hill (R-Mont.), Greg Ganske (R-Iowa),
Dana Rohrabacher (R-Calif.), John Duncan Jr. (R-Tenn.), Pat Danner
(D-Mo.); Fortney ``Pete'' Stark (D-Calif.); F. James Sensenbrenner
Jr. (R-Wis.); Van Hilleary (R-Tenn.) and Curt Weldon (R-Pa.).
</P>
<P>
   The suit was dismissed June 8 by a federal judge in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens when an airport closes during a storm?
Presumably, planes aren't allowed to land and take off. If all
airports closed during storms, wouldn't that help prevent crashes
such as the one that occurred at Little Rock, Ark.?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're right to say that when an airport closes, planes don't
land or take off. But there's no universal rule saying all airports
must close during storms. It's up to the individual airport
operators to make that decision. During periods of bad weather, the
Federal Aviation Administration can institute traffic management
procedures that could result in no arrivals and departures for a
period of time, but the FAA itself cannot order any airport to
close. When an airport is open, the FAA gives the pilot information
about the weather when he or she requests clearance to land. Then
it's up to the pilot to make the ultimate decision, said FAA
spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen.
</P>
<P>
   End Take 2 of 2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
