<HEADER>
A7246 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUNCH-WITH-LORETTA17-     06-16 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNCH-WITH-LORETTA17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'AMC' star wouldn't trade his soap life
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ You may've finally nailed an Emmy, Erica
Kane, but I got the real trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Montgomery all to myself!
</P>
<P>
   Sweat flies as we flail, almost in unison, sharing a common
goal. I see bright colors, I hear bells ring. And then ... cries of
bliss! He finishes first.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Willey whipped me at Whack-a-Mole, 220 to 160.
</P>
<P>
   Willey, who plays dashing attorney Jackson Montgomery on All My
Children, joined me in the arcade at Pete Rose's Ballpark Cafe in
Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   The mission, you see, is to crush metal critters with a mallet
as they randomly pop in and out of holes. ``Anticipate the mole,''
Willey coaches, his face comically stern. ``You're not anticipating
the mole!''
</P>
<P>
   Let's play Skeeball already.
</P>
<P>
   The actor, who also does stand-up comedy, was in town last
weekend for a gig at Bocanuts and an appearance at the Downtown
Uptown Flea Market.
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, it's all about game tokens, conch fritters, fried
grouper strips and ... his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marie's the antithesis of myself in a very complementary
way,'' he gushes. ``She's very centered, she's very calm, and I've
never heard her raise her voice. You know, come to think of it,
she's my mother!''
</P>
<P>
   The couple wed in 1994, seven years after Willey landed the role
of Jackson Montgomery, Pine Valley's beefcake barrister with a
voice so deep you could dive in it.
</P>
<P>
   But Marie thought Willey was a cop. Really a cop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jersey City police gave me an honorary badge because I've
been grand marshal of the town's St. Patty's parade for, like, 13
years,'' he recalls. ``I guess I had the badge in my bag or
something, and it fell out when I was at this tanning place. Marie
was working there, and she found it and tracked me down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time I went in, I asked her out. Eventually, she came
to work for me as a personal assistant. Hey, I gave her health
insurance!''
</P>
<P>
   He wooed her with a deductible?
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways the whole thing couldn't have been less romantic,
but at the same time, I'm so in love with this woman. There's no
doubt in my mind in any way, shape or form that we'll be together
for the rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   She's his third wife.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Montgomery and Erica Kane, however, aren't so tight. After
the lustful lawyer ventured to Pine Valley in 1987, he swiped Erica
from his brother, Travis. But they couldn't wed because Bianca _
Erica and Travis' daughter _ was dying and wanted her parents back
together.
</P>
<P>
   Long story short, there remains A Thing between Jack and Erica.
You know, simmering beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the first time he kissed Susan Lucci, who plays
Erica, Willey replies: ``I honestly don't remember, if you can
believe it. My blood pressure sent the memory right out of my
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Willey's earliest memories are from Ottawa, Ill., a rural town
about 60 miles southeast of Chicago. His dad worked the swing shift
at a glass factory (``for 40 years and never complained''), and his
mom, also employed at the plant, became a homemaker after Willey
and his younger sister came along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a half-brother, Billy, a grandmother, Millie, and I'm
Wally Willey. Can you just get over that?!''
</P>
<P>
   Willey, now 48, went on to major in sculpture at Southern
Illinois University, where he dabbled in theater. He worked for a
while at a toy company, then chucked it all for New York at age 30.
</P>
<P>
   After stints on Another World and Ryan's Hope, he became what he
calls ``a breathing prop'' on AMC. And then Jack Montgomery came
along _ and 260 shows a year.
</P>
<P>
   Willey lives in Jersey City, N.J., during taping in New York,
then zips home to Santa Fe, N.M., where his wife runs a bed and
breakfast on a 60-acre farm (complete with pygmy hedgehogs, no
less). They have a son and daughter: Chance, 4, and Merit, 7
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I end up spending more time with my family this way
than if I left at 6:30 a.m. to drive into the city and got home at
9 at night just in time to kiss the kids good night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waltster is aware that soap stars often get razzed as the
Rodney Dangerfields of acting. You know, no respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't find me complaining,'' he says. ``Yeah, we work
really long hours, but there are people working really long hours
at Burger King, too. So no, I don't have any plans to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the way I see it, they can carry me out of Pine
Valley in a pine box.''
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
