<HEADER>
A7247 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NICKELODEON17-COX     06-16 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICKELODEON17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nickelodeon, at 20, is good and fun
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Television's loudest, wildest kid turns 20 this
month and has absolutely, positively NO plans to grow up. No way.
Green slime forever!
</P>
<P>
   The kid in question is Nickelodeon, the first-ever kids'
network, which is celebrating its two-decade birthday throughout
June. For the uninitiated, this is the cable network that gave us
``Blue's Clues,'' the highest-rated children's show on TV; the
wildly popular ``Rugrats''; and Linda Ellerbee's acclaimed weekly
newsmagazine, ``Nick News.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon is the reason a whole generation of viewers don't
distinguish between cable and broadcast channels. They just watch
TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that generation, Nickelodeon legitimized non-network TV,''
said Jennings Bryant, a University of Alabama professor and
nationally recognized scholar on children's TV. ``It took down the
barricade that labeled programming network, PBS, cable or something
else. Children recognized that Nickelodeon is for them, and it came
at a time when the networks were forsaking children's
programming.''
</P>
<P>
   After debuting on a single cable system in Buffalo, N.Y., with
an educational magazine for pre schoolers called ``Pinwheel,''
Nickelodeon became the No. 1 kids' network a decade later. Along
the way, it revolutionized the way children's programming is
produced and the way children watch television. For better or
worse. Besides the lovely ``Blue's Clues,'' Nickelodeon also gave
us the gross-out, bodily-function-prone cartoon ``Ren and Stimpy.''
</P>
<P>
   PBS may be home of the top-of-the-line educational shows, but
Nickelodeon hooks kids with guffaws and goo. Which is not to say
the cable network doesn't also do good deeds. It does, but nobody's
going to confuse Nickelodeon with PBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly been an influential force in television,'' Bryant
said. ``It hasn't been entirely good or entirely bad. One thing it
does better than anyone else is to put themselves into the kids'
perspective. Part of what they do is make sure everything they do
taps into children's psyches in ways others haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence ``Double Dare,'' the game show that celebrated mess in a
big way with lots of lumpy green slime dumped on kid contestants.
The series was a mega-hit when it debuted in 1986. And ``Rugrats,''
with the emotional and physical perspective of a toddler bumbling
through an adult world, is often cable's most popular program.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon started out as a marketing tool to entice families
to subscribe to cable. Early programming was strictly educational.
But kids didn't really pay attention until 1982, when green slime
was introduced on the sketch comedy series ``You Can't Do That on
Television.'' Word of mouth spread faster than a marble on glass,
spread, and kids started flipping to Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985, when the network merged with MTV, the focus shifted
from education to enjoyment. Programmers in the network's bright
green and orange studio in Los Angeles decided to give kids what
they wanted, not what grown-ups thought was good for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done a lot of research to find out about the needs,
wants and wishes of kids,'' Bryant said. ``It was the first
commercial TV entity to engage in research to create a
curriculum-based program with specific child goals in mind. PBS has
done this for many years, but Nickelodeon realized if they were
going to reach young children, they needed to do so with their
parents' approval.''
</P>
<P>
   The most positive impact has been the early-morning
preschoolers' block dubbed Nick Jr. ``Eureeka's Castle,'' which
taught social skills and imaginative play, was the flagship show in
'89. ``Blue's Clues'' is part of the package now, as is the
landmark ``Gullah Gullah Island.'' The former was designed to help
preschoolers develop thinking and social skills through ``flexible
thinking.'' ``Gullah Gullah Island'' is the first little-kid show
set in an African American nuclear family.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon also scores big with hard-to-satisfy older kids in
the 6- to 11-year range. A lot of the shows are smart and
innovative, as well as fun. Nickelodeon's hip-hop, sketch comedy
``All That'' is often way funnier than ``Saturday Night Live'' and
has better musical guests, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We debunked a lot of myths about kids' television _ that boys
wouldn't watch shows starring girls, that you couldn't make scary
shows without delving into a lot of violence,'' said Nickelodeon
president Herb Scannell. ``And we did it by knowing our audience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clarissa Explains It All,'' starring Melissa Joan Hart, was an
instant hit with boys and girls, and ``Are You Afraid of the
Dark?'' spins scary mysteries without a drop of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon's edgy cartoons sparked the animation renaissance of
the '90s. Besides ``Rugrats'' and ``Ren &AMP; Stimpy,'' there are
``Rocko's Modern Life,'' ``Aaahh!!! Real Monsters,'' ``Hey,
Arnold'' and ``Angry Beavers.'' The titles aren't just clever; the
shows are, too.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon is one of the good things that's happened to
children's television at a time when kids don't have much (besides
PBS) to look forward to. Kids have always gotten short shrift in
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a big advertising sector _ only about a $1 billion
business versus about $25 billion for adult programming,'' Scannell
said. ``It's not easy to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nickelodeon has succeeded big-time because kids love it. It
may not be broccoli TV, with only nutritious fare, but it's not
junk food, either. Think of it as a hot dog with salad.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: dholloway(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
