<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7251 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CASEY17-COX     06-16 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CASEY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds glad to have Mighty Casey's bat
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Sean Casey's deep blue eyes flash under his tousled
hair and he speaks in his gee-whiz conversational tone no matter
where he is, what he is doing or to whom he is talking.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after his 34-inch, 32-ounce bat tore a path of
destruction through Kansas City for two days _ 10 hits that
included two home runs, a double and seven RBIs _ Casey thought
about last weekend's series against the Cleveland Indians and it
was as if somebody dropped a concrete block on his size 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you realize that if I were still in the Cleveland
organization I'd still be playing at Triple-A Buffalo?'' Casey
said. ``That's the truth. Since I can only play first base and they
wouldn't let me be a designated hitter, I'd still be playing in the
minor leagues because they have Jim Thome and Richie Sexson.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Casey and the Cincinnati Reds, the Indians
needed a starting pitcher and reluctantly traded the 24-year-old
first baseman for Dave Burba less than 24 hours before Burba was to
pitch Opening Day 1998 for the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of shuffling off to Buffalo, Casey is dealing in
Cincinnati _ a league-leading batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were criticized for the trade and ripped for giving up a
guy like Burba for a rookie,'' manager Jack McKeon said. ``But you
have to know what you are getting and we knew.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Jim Bowden drew laughter when he said the day of
the trade, ``This may go down as the best trade the Reds have made
since we got Joe Morgan from Houston (1972). Then he put Casey in
the same playing class as Tony Gwynn, Robin Ventura, Jeff Bagwell
and David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   And now? It may go down as the best trade the Reds ever made,
The Trade of the Century.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't come around often like this guy,'' McKeon said.
``We were fortunate to get him and I'm fortunate to get to manage a
guy like this. I've had some good hitters in my time _ four real
good ones in Tony Gwynn, George Brett, Tony Oliva and this guy and
they all rank right up there. I can't separate them because they
all have their strong points.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that I don't know where we'd be without him,''
McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins when Sean Casey was a pudgy 14-year-old kid and
a freshman in high school. Casey, always a star in youth leagues,
found himself sitting on the bench his freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't understand it,'' Casey said. ``I thought, `Am I not
good enough to play high school ball?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The message registered later. The baseball coach also was the
wrestling coach. The kid who played first base ahead of Casey was a
wrestler. Casey didn't wrestle, so he found himself pinned to the
bench, but not down-and-out on the mat.
</P>
<P>
   A chat with his father, Jim, changed his life. Hard work, dad
said, was the answer.
</P>
<P>
   He purchased his son packets of 40 tokens, fifty cents a token
for 12 baseballs at the Grand Slam, USA batting cages in Bethel
Park, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit every day after school, every day. Never missed,'' Casey
said. He and a friend, Tony Raspanti, wore out the machines.
Raspanti took it a step farther and began seeing a batting
instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me? I already knew it all. I'm a man of the world,'' Casey
said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   His mind changed three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, Tony couldn't hit worth a dump, he was awful,'' Casey
said. ``Three weeks after his first lesson, Tony came out raking,
hitting missiles. I was stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   It was time to see dad, again, because if batting instructor
Frank Porco could work miracles with Tony Raspanti, what could he
do for Sean Casey?
</P>
<P>
   Jim Casey gave his son $15 for a trial half-hour lesson to see
if Sean liked it and if it worked. It was a $15 investment in one
huge future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned more about hitting in that half-hour than I had
learned my entire life,'' Casey said. ``Without Frank Porco, I may
have played in college, but that's it. It was all about using your
hands to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Every Monday, 7 to 7:30, Casey worked with Porco, $15 a pop.
``Then I'd take what I learned from him and hit at Grand Slam, USA
in the cages for seven hours,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Casey consults with Porco often and he knows Casey's swing by
rote.
</P>
<P>
   ``One look and he knows if anything the least little bit is out
of whack,'' Casey said. ``Dad was right. Hard work paid off, but
hard work with Frank Porco paid off even more.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, there have been no slumps _ a three-month odyssey of
line drives that avoid defensive players as if radar is stitched
inside the baseballs.
</P>
<P>
   The effervescent, gregarious Casey loves people as much as he
loves the sweet feel of a double reverberating off his bat.
</P>
<P>
   He never says no to a writer, a broadcaster, a fan or a parking
meter. He'll talk to anybody and smile as he does it.
</P>
<P>
   Every media person wants large chunks of his time and the aim is
to explain The Sean Casey Phenomenon. One writer said she was in
town to do the, ``The definitive Sean Casey story.'' Can't be done.
There is too much to this guy.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Aaron Boone listens to the interviews and puts his own
twist on Casey. ``Great personality, can really rake, end of
story,'' Boone said.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, in the batters box, in the dugout, Casey talks and
talks and talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to holler at him to get his attention,'' McKeon says.
``He'll have conversations with umpires, runners at first base. I
yell at him from the dugout, `Just take the guy out to dinner and
talk to him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Barry Larkin isn't one to spread praise easily. Show
him. Earn it. It didn't take Casey long and the attention Casey
soaks up brings no jealousy out of Larkin, who merely sees a
germinating superstar who makes the Cincinnati Reds dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey is successful at such a young age because he gives
himself a chance on every pitch,'' Larkin said. ``A lot of guys
give a half-hearted swing and when you ask them what they were
thinking, they say, `I was thinking fastball away and it was a
fastball in and I still swung.' I couldn't do at his age what Casey
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples of Casey's zest for major-league life and his unforced,
honest aw-gee demeanor abound.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon believes before Casey leaves Cincinnati he'll leave the
impact and the imprint of Pete Rose, without the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be the most popular guy outside of Pete Rose in
Cincinnati and he has a chance to supplant Rose,'' McKeon said.
``He has charisma, personality, attitude . . . he is a fan favorite
already. He is always smiling, always having fun. He is like an
All-American Boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He outwardly enjoys the game, you can see it,'' McKeon adds.
``He never comes to the park grouchy or mad at the world. Nothing
bothers him.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey is just a big kid _ a big kid with a big bat, a big heart
and a giant future. Everything seems a delight to him. Even a
children's Reds jersey with his name on it.
</P>
<P>
   He and fiance, Mandy Kanka, were walking in a Cincinnati mall
when they passed a shop with a display of children's Reds jerseys
in the window, C-a-s-e-y on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a thrill,'' Casey said. ``Mandy said, `Hey, look at
those.' We went in and bought some for Mandy's nephews and nieces.
I'll tell you what, that was one of the biggest thrills of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   And he meant it.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, another mall. This one in Phoenix when he and
Mandy spotted Tony Gwynn eating lunch. Said Casey, playing in the
Arizona Fall League at the time (1997, a couple of months before
his trade to the Reds), ``I know people don't like to be bothered,
so I waited until he was done eating and told him, `Mr. Gwynn, I
play in the Arizona Fall League. I really enjoy watching you play.
I really admire you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn didn't know Casey from a hot tamale that day in Arizona,
but after watching him go 4 for 4 with a home run in the first game
against the Padres this year, Gwynn knows who he is, ``A kid who
can really hit and knows what he is doing up there. I like him, but
I'll like him a lot better when he isn't playing against us.''
</P>
<P>
   He reads his Bible every day and even though there is Sunday
chapel in the clubhouse, home and away, he rushes from the hotel
for the nearest cathedral on the road.
</P>
<P>
   His strongest epithet is, ``Dang it.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a turn-the-other-cheek guy and a
do-unto-others-as-you-want-them-to-do-unto-you person.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father impressed in me that I should always treat people
the way I want them to treat me,'' Casey said. ``And he always told
me a man is only as good as his word, but those were on days he
wanted me to mow the lawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Eddie Taubensee is a devout man, a guy capable of
spotting a phony like a bank clerk checking a $100 bill for red and
blue threads. He says Casey is the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see and hear is real, nothing fake, nothing phony,''
Taubensee said. ``I liked him from the start and the more you see
and hear from him, the more you like him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds like what they see and hear, especially for the
$220,000 it cost. It's a price that will rise quickly and
dramatically and Sean Thomas Casey is one baseball player who
almost will be worth every quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
