<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GEORGE-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs' Johnson a USBL (Sting)ray of hope
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Go back exactly 11 years. It is
mid-June, so steamy that birdbaths bubble. In a Palm Beach County
motel room sits a pro basketball player, his eyes on the NBA
playoffs, his dream captured inside a 19-inch TV screen. Truly the
United States Basketball League, a summer option for players who
just won't quit, is death by disassociation.
</P>
<P>
   No one back in 1988 would have associated Avery Johnson with the
NBA Finals. Then he was a sometimes-starter for the USBL's Palm
Beach Stingrays. The leap was just too far, the concept of playing
before 100 somber spectators at the West Palm Beach Auditorium too
bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   No one back in 1988 would have associated Avery Johnson with
Magic Johnson, three times an NBA Finals MVP. Same surname,
different galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the San Antonio Spurs take the court Wednesday for Game
1 of the NBA Finals, it will be Avery Johnson pounding the ball up
the court as a trusted associate of Tim Duncan and David Robinson.
It is mid-June in 1999 and everything has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Everything except the heat and the humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this profession, people have mistreated me but I still love
them,'' said Johnson, who came to the Stingrays as an undrafted
free agent who played at three colleges and rode the bench in high
school. ``I don't hold grudges against people who made those
decisions. Those decisions benefited me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, too, to the coaches and personnel people who kicked
Johnson around the NBA. At the conclusion of that one glorious
Stingray summer, the skinny 5-foot-11 kid with the squeaky, cartoon
voice went from Seattle to Denver to San Antonio to Houston to San
Antonio again to Golden State and to San Antonio once more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for him,'' says a voice you would never associate
with the glory of San Antonio's current post-season run. ``He had
to take a lot of roads to get where he wanted to go, just like a
lot of athletes have to do. That's the main thing, to stay busy, no
matter what the league is, no matter what the money is. Hopefully
it will pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice belongs to George Banks, a second-round draft pick of
the Miami Heat in 1995. Since then he has played professionally in
Italy and Greece and Israel and the CBA, too. Today Banks lives in
a Howard Johnson motel near Lake Worth beach, passing the time
between games with the Florida Windjammers of the USBL.
</P>
<P>
   The Windjammers' offices are in St. Petersburg and their games,
advertised by word-of-mouth alone, are played at the Palm Beach
Community College gym. Twelve home games have come and gone very
quietly since the season opener on May 1 and one remains, June 23,
against the dreaded Kansas Cagerz. Banks will be there, regardless
of whether anyone else is. He is one of just four players who have
been with the Florida team all season.
</P>
<P>
   This is the hiccuppy history of the USBL, yet Banks prefers to
focus on the fact that Avery Johnson played his first pro games in
Palm Beach County. New York Knicks' Charlie Ward and Chris Childs,
they're USBL veterans, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything as being all that bad,'' Banks said. ``I
see all this as a learning experience for me, learning how to play
pro-style, having fun every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell him you can't get there from here. Don't tell him
anything at all. It's mid-June and Avery Johnson, who once sweated
out a seemingly pointless summer with the Palm Beach Stingrays, is
in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Dave George writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
