<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TKACHUK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK GIVES THUMBS UP TO SMITH'S PICK FOR COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Everybody take a chill pill and relax.
</P>
<P>
   That was Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk's advice Tuesday, a day
after it was learned a relatively unknown NHL assistant will become
Phoenix's new head coach.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Bobby Francis and he'll be introduced as the
Coyotes' coach at a 1 p.m. news conference Wednesday in Scottsdale.
Terms have not been disclosed, but it is believed Francis has
agreed to a three-year deal worth at least $350,000 a season.
</P>
<P>
   Like most players, Tkachuk didn't have the foggiest idea that
General Manager Bobby Smith would settle on Francis, 40, who has
spent the past four seasons in the Boston Bruins' organization, the
past two as an assistant to Coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard something was going on yesterday, but Bobby (Smith)
called me this morning and told me who he was bringing in,''
Tkachuk, the team's three-time All-Star left wing, said Tuesday
from his summer home near Cape Cod, Mass. ``I don't know much about
him, but he's been around for a while and if Bobby (Smith) thinks
he can do the job, he must be a good coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, he's worked for Pat Burns and Pat Burns is one of the
greatest coaches in the world, so the guy's got to be decent.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players, however, privately seemed to be pulling for
Coyotes assistant John Tortorella to get the job. And more than a
few indicated they expected to be somewhat consulted by Smith
before a final decision was made, mostly just to gauge their
interest and opinions.
</P>
<P>
   When they were not, some were disappointed. A few were upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should they be upset?'' Tkachuk said. ````I'm'' not upset.
Look, they don't make the decisions. That's Bobby Smith's choice
and he's got the hardest job in the world. I've got no problems
with the way he's gone about things. You know, sometimes players
get too involved anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Smith earmarked Francis, who has only his two years with the
Bruins as experience behind an NHL bench, remains a mystery that
will begin to unfold during today's press conference. For now, both
Smith and Francis are declining interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   After it was confirmed Monday that he had the job, Francis still
sidestepped the issue when contacted by the ``Boston Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they've expressed some interest,'' he said of the
Coyotes. ``I talked with Bobby a couple of weeks ago and he
suggested that I was a candidate, but I haven't heard anything
beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he had to have some idea he was about to become the
Coyotes' third head coach in four years because he finalized
contract negotiations earlier that same day.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins backup goalie Rob Tallas, who played for Francis for two
seasons at Providence, R.I., in the American Hockey League, when
Francis was the head coach there, didn't play dumb when asked about
his friend's future in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy for him,'' Tallas told the ``Globe.'' ``That's
excellent. I'm really fond of him.''
</P>
<P>
   So must be Smith, or he wouldn't have tossed Tortorella from
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate about John,'' Tkachuk said, ``because John's
a great guy and all along, after (Jim Schoenfeld) got fired, I
thought they were going to name Tortorella. A lot of us did, I
think. But players can wish and want all they want, but ultimately,
it's not the players' decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is important what the players think, especially about the
direction their club is heading. To many in the NHL, the Coyotes
are a nice, little hockey team with a pretty good roster that can
compete, but not really challenge for a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that is because the club operates in the bottom third of
the league in payroll and is generally perceived as still being a
few talented players away from competing with teams like Dallas,
Colorado and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're heading in the right direction,'' Tkachuk said.
``We made a lot of positive strides last year. We're going to have
a new coaching staff again and obviously, it's going to take some
time to adjust, but we'll be ready. It depends on the situation,
the players, some contract stuff that usually surfaces during the
summer, but I'm looking forward to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we were still playing.''
</P>
<P>
   If they were, Schoenfeld would still be coaching. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
