EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, June 16, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-NOTES (San Francisco) _ Taking aim at a growing campus
product, the University of California has gone to court to stop
professional note-takers from infiltrating classrooms and peddling
lecture notes to students. By VICKI HADDOCK.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (San Francisco) _ A drug given to post-menopausal
women to combat bone disease has been found to dramatically reduce
breast cancer. In an international study of 7,705 women with
osteoporosis, the drug raloxifene lowered the risk of all types of
breast cancer by 76 percent, according to the study. By MARIANNE
COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (San Francisco) _ While Vice President Al Gore
attracts worldwide attention Wednesday when he announces that he's
running for president, his chief Democratic rival is just hoping to
get noticed. Bill Bradley, the former New Jersey senator and New
York Knicks basketball star, is campaigning in California. By
ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-READY (Altamont, N.Y.) _ A computer consultant who once
stocked up on food and purified water in preparation for electronic
doomsday is now more optimistic that the sky won't fall on Jan. 1,
2000. There are ``still many unknowns,'' Barry Pardy says, but
these days he helps companies prepare for computer glitches and
worries less about a cataclysm. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   With: Y2K-INFO
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-PCs (Albany, N.Y.) _ Forget the office equipment. Who among
individuals should worry about making sure their personal computers
and software are Y2K compliant? If you're a Macintosh user, rejoice
_ Macs are in sync with the date change. For everyone else, here's
how to make sure your PC is ready for 2000. By WILLIAM M. DOWD.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ADIRONDACKS-PEAKS (Adirondacks Park, N.Y.) _ What began in the
1920s with the 46ers _ people who have climbed the 46 High Peaks of
the Adirondacks, all over 4,000 feet in elevation _ has expanded
around the Adirondacks. Now some hikers and environmentalists fear
that this nature-by-numbers approach is detrimental to the bucolic
vistas. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MOVIES (San Francisco) _ There's a host of things scheduled
to happen during the 10 days of the 23rd Lesbian and Gay Film
Festival _ which runs June 17-27 at the Castro, the Roxie and the
Victoria theaters in San Francisco. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (San Francisco) _ Both sides in the 49ers' ownership
dispute have agreed to continue talking, under the supervision of a
federal judge in Ohio, according to spokesmen for Eddie DeBartolo
and his estranged sister, Denise DeBartolo York. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
