<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL-HELP SOFTWARE IS GETTING BETTER AND GETTING ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About a year ago, a judge in Texas issued a summary judgment to
stop the distribution of Quicken Family Lawyer '99 in that state.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can quote me: This is sick,'' said Ann Stephens, president
of PC Data, a company that tracks the sale of software for personal
computers. ``Boy, these lawyers are sticking up for their own,
aren't they?''
</P>
<P>
   The battle is still going on, although not all lawyers are
``sticking up for their own.'' Rulings banning legal-help software
have been overturned on appeal. And about two months go, the
Supreme Court of Texas told the state bar's grievance committee,
which has been trying to run legal self-help software out of the
state, to stop hiding behind secretary rulings that no longer
apply.
</P>
<P>
   Nolo Press, a company that distributes self-help books and
software, said the ruling was a major victory and something it had
requested in previous pleadings.
</P>
<P>
   While lawyers argue, legal software keeps getting better and
better. Software companies have been producing such programs for
about a decade now, and they're building on experience.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say that you shouldn't consult with an attorney.
Nor does it mean that all wills can be drawn up using $30 software
and be able to withstand the attack of an irate nephew cut from the
inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   Quicken Family Lawyer 2000 Deluxe goes beyond simple will
making. It contains thousands of documents, but narrows down the
ones needed through a series of interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The program ($30; Windows) has an estate-planning section and a
``plain language'' law dictionary with more than 7,000 legal terms.
A book, ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to Wills and Estates,'' is
also included. The program also has a multimedia section where
Harvard Law School Professor Arthur Miller answers frequently asked
legal questions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the documents included are: wills (eight basic
circumstances, including with or without children); consumer
(complaint letters to companies, credit card lost or stolen, small
claims worksheet); landlord/tenant; credit; health and medical
(living wills, organ donation, Medicare peer review); family and
personal; and government letters.
</P>
<P>
   An estate planning section allows custom plans tailored to
specific needs. Estate planning tips pop up each time a user goes
to the estate-planning section.
</P>
<P>
   It provides additional suggestions on which documents may be
helpful in protecting an estate, gives advice on how to avoid
probate expenses and has a guide for calculating net worth.
</P>
<P>
   For those with a small business, Quicken Business Lawyer 2000
Deluxe ($40; Windows) offers both legal documents and more than
1,000 business letters for business owners.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM contains business and marketing plans, cash-flow
projection work sheets, and lease agreements. (If all these don't
help out enough, there's a bankruptcy work sheet available, too.)
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Broderbund, the company that acquired the
Quicken line, said there were 11.6 million people in the United
States who reported self-employment earnings in 1995; the average
small business spends between $5,000 and $15,000 a year in legal
fees.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-12-99 0002EDT &QL;
</P>
