<HEADER>
A7276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-PETS-MICROCHIPS-A     06-16 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PETS-MICROCHIPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MICROCHIP, AN OWNER'S BEST CHANCE OF FINDING A LOST DOG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODINVILLE, Wash. _ Wilbur ran away one day last summer.
Distraught, Debbie and Jim Pittman tried everything to find him.
They put up ``lost dog'' fliers on hundreds of telephone poles, and
they checked with nearly every pound around Puget Sound. Nothing.
``But we never gave up hope,'' said Mrs. Pittman. ``We knew he had
his microchip.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, out of the blue one recent day, 11 months after the black
Labrador disappeared, a call came. ``My heart leapt,'' said Mrs.
Pittman. ``I 911'ed Jim on his beeper right away. I told him,
`Honey, Wilbur's coming home.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Pittmans' dog had been found, and a scan by Hooterville, a
local pet shelter, turned up the tiny microchip that had been
implanted inside Wilbur when he was a puppy. Embedded in the chip
was a 10-digit number linked to a national database with
information about the dog, including the Pittmans' telephone
number.
</P>
<P>
   The microchip involved in Wilbur's high-tech, homeward-bound
journey is not new gadgetry _ as far back as 10 years ago, the
Marin Humane Society in Northern California became the first
shelter in the country to implant the chips in all animals put up
for adoption and since then, the technology has reunited more than
1,000 pets _ 820 dogs, 340 cats and one rabbit, to be exact _ with
their owners there.
</P>
<P>
   But the practice has taken off in recent years, as the three big
manufacturers have tried to overcome proprietary squabbles and move
toward an industry standard, and as many humane societies and
veterinarians have urged pet owners to implant their pets with the
identification devices.
</P>
<P>
   At least 1.6 million American pets now have these chips in their
shoulders and dozens of shelters, including the n one in Manhattan
run by the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to
Animals, have them automatically implanted when animals are
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who see all this microchipping of pets as a sign
of premillenial excess, and the Whole Dog Journal, a newsletter for
holistic dog care based in Greenwich, Conn., reported late last
year that many pet owners were bothered by the creepy `` `Big
Brother' aspects'' of the practice and refused to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is an ethical problem posed by the fact that the
microchip technology, which operates roughly like a grocery market
scanner, actually works extremely well.
</P>
<P>
   The chips, the size of a grain of rice, implanted painlessly and
within seconds, could be used in humans, posing obvious
invasion-of-privacy issues versus some very real benefits: no more
baby mix-ups in the hospital, a powerful new tool to track down
kidnapped children, runaway teen-agers, or even deadbeat dads.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pittmans are just happy to have Wilbur home.
</P>
<P>
   Just what happened to the dog in the past year, and to the
old-fashioned dog tags that had been around his neck, remains a
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur seems to have been well-cared for. A few weeks ago,
Wilbur apparently ran away again, and he was found wandering around
a park-and-ride station in Bothell, which, like Woodinville and the
Pittmans' hometown of Redmond, is just east of Lake Washington in
the Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   Two youngsters who found Wilbur took him home. ``The kids said,
`Maybe there's a microchip inside, let's have him scanned,' '' said
Mrs. Pittman, a nail specialist for a salon in Kirkland, Wash. `The
mother said, `I've never heard of it, but OK' ''
</P>
<P>
   Many shelters now implant the chips for free or a nominal fee.
They still recommend traditional identification tags as part of a
``belt and suspenders'' approach to pet protection, said Stephen
Zawistowski, senior vice president and science adviser at the
ASPCA.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike tags, which can fall off or be removed, or tattoos, which
can fade or be covered up as hair grows, the microchips are
virtually unalterable.
</P>
<P>
   The chip technology was first used in this country to monitor
salmon, and has been used for wildlife research and to counter
ostrich rustling. But it has caught on for domestic pets, spurred
in part several years by a bizarre epidemic of kidnappings of pets
for ransom that garnered wide attention in Southern California. In
one 1993 case, a widow in Corona del Mar agreed to leave $2,500 in
a phone booth for the safe return of her toy poodle, Ginger.
</P>
<P>
   Early last year, the Los Angeles Department of Animal Services
announced that it would like to see every pet in the city
microchipped as part of a campaign to reduce the 60,000 times a
year when it had to euthanize stray or lost animals, although
officials said they would not require the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something spooky about it,'' a senior official said
at the time, ``and everyone realizes it.''
</P>
<P>
   The implants so far are still in just a fraction of the 120
million domestic dogs and cats in the country. But spokesmen for
the companies that make the three main products in use _ HomeAgain,
Infopet, and Avid (for American Veterinary Identification Device)
_- say they believe use of the chips will take off as more and more
people become aware of them and scanning of lost animals becomes
standard practice.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every day, somewhere in the country, pets are reunited
with their owners because of the chips. In Marin County, where all
field services trucks are equipped with hand-held scanners,
``people are so grateful, they'll say this saved my cat or my dog's
life,'' said Jason Willett, a spokesman for the humane society.
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur, for one, is back home at the Pittmans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take him to the dog park, and he won't go 20 feet without
turning around and looking for us,'' said Mrs. Pittman of her dog,
who will soon be 2 years old. ``He's always checking. Now he
doesn't want us to leave his sight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-11-99 2029EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
