<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB LANGUAGE CAN SPELL TROUBLE IN HTML
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: When I send e-mail to someone on America Online, they tell me
they get strange markings and the sentences are broken up. ``BSP''
is at the end of each sentence. Question: Do I have to do something
different when sending e-mail to someone on AOL? I use Netscape
Communicator as my browser and e-mail program.
</P>
<P>
   A: Newer e-mail programs such as Netscape Messenger _ the e-mail
module that comes with Communicator _ and Outlook Express from
Microsoft all have the ability to compose and send e-mail in HTML,
or Hypertext Markup Language. That's the language that Web pages
are written in. So, when you send an e-mail using that feature, you
are essentially sending a Web page to the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a problem here. Many other e-mail programs can't see
HTML pages. That includes the one used by America Online and its 17
million subscribers, as well as the freeware version of Qualcomm's
Eudora, which is generally considered to be the most popular e-mail
program used on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that these programs end up showing their
recipients lots of control codes that may get in the way of what
you are trying to say. Generally, if you don't know whether or not
someone can see an HTML-based piece of e-mail, send the message in
text-only format.
</P>
<P>
   To change to text-only in Communicator 4 and later, go to Edit,
then Preferences, then Mail &AMP; Newsgroups, then Formatting. Click
the box that lets you use the plain text editor, then click OK.
</P>
<P>
   In Outlook Express 4 and 5, click on Tools, Options, Send. Click
the Plain Text option.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial version of Eudora, Eudora Pro, handles this
beautifully. You can have Eudora ask you each time whether you want
to send plain or, as this software terms it, ``styled'' text. To
enable this feature in Eudora Pro 4 or later, go to Tools, Options,
then Styled Text. Make sure the Ask Me Each Time box is checked.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Each time I compose a letter in Microsoft Publisher, I give
it a name. When I press my print key I get a box that indicates
that my printer name is ``MS Publisher Color Printer.'' If I do not
change this to the name of my real printer _ Canon BJC-250 _ I get
a box called ``Print to File'' with a file name of .prn. How can I
get my current printer to automatically be listed in the name
section instead of ``MS Publisher Color Printer''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Open My Computer, then the Printers folder. Find your Canon
printer, right-click on it and choose Set As Default.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Re: the Help Line ``turning off the modem sound'' on May 28.
Instead of turning the volume down, you can turn it off. Navigate
to: Control Panel, then Modems, Properties, Connection, Advanced
and add ATM0 to the ``Extra Settings.'' Most modems support the AT
commands.
</P>
<P>
   A: Thanks for the tip. Several readers reported that with the
steps printed in that Help Line, they still couldn't turn the modem
sound off. This should help most of them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My modem was working fine. I decided to upgrade to Windows 98
from Windows 95, and now it will not work. I've tried everything I
know. Is it possible that it will never work again with 98?
</P>
<P>
   A: Quite a few modems ``broke'' when Windows 98 was introduced,
but it was simply a matter of acquiring new drivers for them. By
now, most manufacturers have updated their drivers, so check at the
Web site of your device's manufacturer. Download the drivers and
install them. That should fix your problem.
</P>
<P>
   You can find out who made your modem by looking in the Windows
Device Manager. Right-click on My Computer, then Properties, then
Device Manager. Double-click on the Modems item to see what kind it
is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-11-99 1728EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
