 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Computer adventure: Wiring a home network 
By Gerry Yandel  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When's the last time you found yourself installing
computer hardware with a drill?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I was using a 3/4-inch router bit, which does a great
deal more damage than a normal drill bit. Of course, I wasn't doing
anything inside my computer. Instead, I was standing in the frame
structure of my soon-to-be house with several boxes of Cat 5 cable
preparing to wire an ethernet network in the walls. I had done my
homework.
</P>
<P>
   I talked with one of the LAN pros at the AJC, who assured me
there was nothing to worry about as long as I kept my cables 6
inches away from the electrical wiring and didn't have any cable
runs longer than 300 feet. I also conferred with my father-in-law,
Bill, who sells telephone systems. He cautioned me not to make any
sharp turns, angles or bends in the wire as I laid it out through
the house, and he suggested following the phone lines as much as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   I chatted up the brother-and-sister team that was wiring almost
everything else in my house _ phones, alarm system, electricity,
cable TV, thermostats _ and I picked up a few pointers while
watching their technique. To be in the proper frame of mind, I had
even gone back into the Wired magazine archives online and dug up
Neal Stephenson's mesmerizing 56-page epic about the world history
of wire and the huge backbone cables lying across ocean floors that
make the Internet possible.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, nobody told me to bring a ladder.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm not Bob Vila.
</P>
<P>
   There are many good reasons _ among them the ability to share
files and programs, hard drive space, printers and Internet access
_ for using a network inside your home.
</P>
<P>
   My motives were a little more pedestrian: I initially decided to
put the network in so I wouldn't have to put cable modems, at $40 a
month each, on three computers.
</P>
<P>
   As I did my research, other benefits became obvious. With a
network, I wouldn't have to put a bunch of new hardware into the
old 486/SX2 that my daughter got from her grandparents _ she could
just use devices across the network. (Of course, using the CD-ROM
would mean she'd have to run between rooms to pop discs in and out
of the drive. But she's young and full of energy.)
</P>
<P>
   So _ with my ladder _ I was physically and mentally ready.
</P>
<P>
   While re-reading Stephenson's excellent article, my own wire
adventure began to take on a more profound and meaningful purpose,
like it was a metaphor for the infrastructure of life. But, after
sweating it out for a couple of hours in 90-degree heat, crawling
among the rafters, pulling cable, banging my shins and wiping
sawdust out of my eyes, I didn't care if it was the key to the
universe as long as I finished before dark.
</P>
<P>
   The process is really quite simple. In fact, a large part of it
is just mapping the network through your house. I tracked the paths
of my wires beam by beam to each room in the house, which avoided
dozens of nasty little surprises and tricky maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   One good tip: No matter if you are wiring a house frame or an
existing house, start in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Decide where your hub is going to be and work outward. Surfing
some Web sites with how-to pages on network wiring, I found there
are two kinds of networks and two primary network layouts. Either
type of network _ peer-to-peer or client-server _ works for home
networks, but that's a topic for a future column.
</P>
<P>
   A ``backbone'' network layout, a straight line of coaxial cable
with computers coming off the sides, is more suited for businesses
with a lot of terminals. Home networks typically use a ``star''
layout, which has a hub and terminals radiating outward on
telephone-type wires. (Actually, I may have created a third
configuration called the ``Silly String'' layout.)
</P>
<P>
   The cable comes in various categories, based on the data they
can push. Ordinary telephone wire is Cat 2 and has two pairs of
wire inside the cable. Cat 3 cable can also be used for an ethernet
and is capable of up to 10 megabytes, and Cat 5 cable _ which is
four pairs of wire _ is capable of up to 100 megabytes. (The plugs
for my Cat 5 cable ends are basically the same as phone jacks, only
bigger, and will require different wall plates.)
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the two ethernet speeds aren't interchangeable. And
mixing them requires special switching hubs that are, naturally,
more expensive. But 10 megabytes should be plenty fast for a home
network. Don't forget that cable modem access, the speediest
available, hits only 3 megabytes _ although I've heard from plenty
of cable modem subscribers who say actual and advertised speeds
vary greatly.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the hub near your source of Internet access _ a
telephone jack or cable TV outlet _ should make things easier. I
added an extra cable jack about 6 feet up on the laundry room wall,
after some alert readers sent e-mail about possible moisture and
temperature extremes in the garage, my original location. I'm also
putting in a shelf for the cable modem, the hub and a small
computer to use as a server, if I need it.
</P>
<P>
   I did end up finishing my job before dark. My eight cables came
together in a beautiful thick bunch that follows one of the big
pipes through the upstairs bathroom floor along the ceiling over
the washing machine.
</P>
<P>
   The Monday after my wiring job, my wife stopped by the house to
check its progress. A new subcontractor, who was wiring my light
fixtures, asked if we were doing some of our own wiring work. When
she told him I had wired up a computer network, he said, ``Well, he
sure knew what he was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's profound enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Screwdriver PC postscript: According to my e-mail _ which was
filled with tales of frustration _ many readers have been victims
of shoddy service from screwdriver PC shops. Surprisingly, almost
every person's problem was with the same outfit. My advice still
stands, no matter which one you buy from: Buyer beware.
</P>
<P>
   Wired world
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) www.wired.com/wired
</P>
<P>
   /archive/4.12/ffglass.html
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) www.mkdata.dk/click/
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) pcmech.pair.com
</P>
<P>
   /networking.htm
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) www.windows95.com
</P>
<P>
   /howto/peercon.html
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) www.linksys.com
</P>
<P>
   /support/faqs/howbuild
</P>
<P>
   /default.htm
</P>
<P>
   These Web sites offer information about networking and
do-it-yourself wiring:
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-14-99 1119EDT &QL;
</P>
