<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS15-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
World Book on DVD fails to forge proper links 
By Jack Warner  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ IBM's venture into the world of DVD, the 1999 World
Book Family Reference Suite, is a pretty good tool hampered by
exceptionally poor organization.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than simply expanding upon the entries contained in the
paper version of the World Book Encyclopedia, IBM opted to fill out
the vast space afforded by DVD-ROM with the Merriam-Webster
Dictionary and the latest Information Please almanac.
</P>
<P>
   This was a pretty good decision _ especially for kids struggling
with homework. The Merriam-Webster dictionary is always active, and
one need only double-click on any word in an article in the
encyclopedia to get a complete explanation of it.
</P>
<P>
   There is lots of multimedia, including especially good movie
clips in fairly large format. Strangely, every last one of them
seems to be silent. There are lots of sounds, just not moving
picture sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Musical illustrations for the great composers are adequate in
number, although disappointingly brief. They are, however,
presented by the appropriate instruments rather than a synthesizer
or MIDI translation.
</P>
<P>
   I checked my usual out-of-the-way articles and found them
accurate, if not very enlightening. Longer, more mainstream
entries, such as that for Australia, are quite adequate for most
purposes, including homework, and well-written.
</P>
<P>
   There was even a brief separate entry under didgeridoo,
explaining that it is a musical instrument of the Australian
Aborigines. This is good, because only a few electronic
dictionaries include it. I was disappointed not to find a musical
example linked to it, which leads to my chief complaint about World
Book.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever branch of the publisher charged with organizing the
material and providing cross-links appears to have been permanently
out to lunch. There is, in fact, a musical example of the
didgeridoo. You can find it in the general article on Australia. I
can think of no reason why it wasn't also included with the brief
article on the instrument itself.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of thing abounds. The article on flamenco offers no
examples. Yet the article on Spain, under arts, provides two aural
examples, portions of a fandango de Huelva and tientos. The former
is listed as a ``traditional fandango'' (it is not) and the latter
as a ``traditional dance.'' I supposed that whoever put together
the section simply didn't know much about it, but this sort of
thing is far too endemic throughout the book to be accounted for
that way.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if you ask for information on the Second Amendment
to the U.S. Constitution, World Book provides the text of it and a
discussion of the controversy surrounding it. If, however, you ask
for the Fourth Amendment, all you get is an article on wiretapping
which mentions the amendment in passing without giving its text.
</P>
<P>
   All the articles are signed, which is good. Some are written by
big-time experts in the field at issue; most are relatively
obscure.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, navigation is simple, although if you have
been browsing through articles and decide you want to look at a
list of videos on the disc, you're going to find you can't get
there from here. At least I couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to go through the ordeal of ``teaching'' the
software how you speak, or if you have difficulty typing, you can
even navigate with IBM's ViaVoice technology and a provided
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   The search list hides the icon that indicates what multimedia
items, if any, are associated with an article. You wouldn't even
know it's there unless you look.
</P>
<P>
   There are ``wizards'' to help with things like Web pages and
homework, and a timeline feature which most users will find next to
useless because of its lack of organization. There is the
obligatory online link, but in this case obligatory is quite apt.
Unlike Microsoft Encarta, for instance, relatively few articles are
linked to Internet information, even when a wealth of it is
available.
</P>
<P>
   Information Please is a useful almanac for lists and records and
so forth, as well as 1998 events.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot to like about World Book. The pity is that if it
had been given the kind of organizational attention that every
other electronic encyclopedia has, it would be outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-14-99 1118EDT &QL;
</P>
