u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-METROWERKS-GALANO     06-16 1936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-METROWERKS-GALANOS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIGH-TECH STRATEGY FOR ROLLING WITH THE PUNCHES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As high-technology business strategies go, it was a classic,
perfectly executed: find a technological ``discontinuity,'' race a
new product to market and dislodge an entrenched competitor.
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely what Greg Galanos, the founder of the tiny
software company Metrowerks Inc., did in 1991. Realizing that Apple
Computer and Motorola Corp. were allying with IBM to shift to a new
microprocessor chip called the Power PC (the discontinuity), he
quickly developed a type of software tool known as a compiler (the
new product) for use by programmers writing software for Apple
Macintosh Power PC computers.
</P>
<P>
   When the dust settled, Galanos found that his Code Warrior
compiler software had a 95 percent share of the market for Apple
Macintosh programming tools. The dislodged competitor in this case
was the larger, less nimble Symantec Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately there was just one flaw in the strategy:
Metrowerks had seized the commanding lead of a shrinking market.
The grand alliance that Apple and IBM envisioned never jelled, and
Apple's share of the personal-computer market began to collapse
from a peak of about 13 percent to around 3 percent, where it
bottomed out last year.
</P>
<P>
   Metrowerks' compiler software continued to play a crucial role,
enabling programmers who designed applications for the Macintosh to
convert their instructions to machine language. Trouble was, fewer
programmers were interested in creating new Macintosh applications.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Galanos scanned the horizon for the next big
technological discontinuity. And the 41-year-old Metrowerks
president may have found it: the increasing fragmentation of
computing from its desktop-PC foundation to a new, pebbly terrain
of digital consumer-electronics devices that include video-game
machines and ``smart'' voice and data cellular telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with three years ago, when Metrowerks was developing
software entirely for the Macintosh, 60 percent of the company's
projected $30 million in revenue this year will come from sales for
software tools used to program the processor chips that are at the
heart of the consumer electronics market.
</P>
<P>
   This coming post-PC era, as it has been called, does not play to
the strengths of the software giant Microsoft, which currently
leads the esoteric but crucial market for software tools _ the
programs that programmers themselves use when creating software.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, with more than $200 million in annual tool sales, is
the leader in this field because it sells the primary tools used in
making programs for the industry-dominating Microsoft Windows PC
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   But the post-PC shift toward computerized consumer electronics
products _ which employ many different operating systems and so
require many different kinds of programming tools _ is creating a
new opportunity for a raft of smaller software tool makers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Metrowerks, the noteworthies include Cygnus, Greenhills
Software, Imprise, Integrated Systems and Wind River Systems. But
none of these other companies offer the range of products across
different chip families that Metrowerks does.
</P>
<P>
   And Metrowerks has distinguished itself by making significant
inroads in the market for hand-held computing and wireless devices.
The company is the leading software tools vendor for the popular
Palm Pilot organizer. And Metrowerks recently struck a deal with
Motorola to provide software tools for Motorola's new Mcore
microprocessor family of chips for digital cellular phones and
similar computerized communications devices.
</P>
<P>
   Metrowerks' biggest coup, though, has come in the video-game
field. All three of the major game makers _ Nintendo, Sega and Sony
_ have announced that their next generation of game machines
scheduled for release later this year will use chips and operating
systems that rely on Metrowerks software development tools.
</P>
<P>
   Having a single software development environment is something
that is highly prized by video-game developers, who must gamble on
which system will be most popular and then be prepared to quickly
rewrite, or ``port,'' their programs to a competitor's gaming
system.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it also means that any developer creating games
for these new machines will have to use Metrowerks tool kits. It is
perhaps the most valuable validation yet for the strategy that
Galanos and Metrowerks are now pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the business of creating developer communities around
post-PC devices,'' Galanos said in his office in Cupertino, Calif.
``The games business is defining the software industry today.''
</P>
<P>
   Metrowerks' strategy is a concept akin to Microsoft's practice
of offering outside programmers the company's applications
programming interfaces, or APIs _ computer-code pathways into and
out of the operating system to which programmers connect their
software.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying this idea to consumer electronics, Metrowerks is now
finishing work on a tool kit _ called Powerparts _ that is supposed
to make it simple to adapt programs for one type of device for use
on another device, as well as offering programmers a library for
quickly creating visual control panels for consumer devices. A
scheduling program created for a hand-held electronic organizer,
for instance, might be easily translated to a version used on a
smart cell phone with a screen.
</P>
<P>
   With Metrowerks having established its bona fides in the
Macintosh tools market, and now gathering steam in the post-PC
market, Galanos is finding enthusiastic supporters from many parts
of the computer industry _ particularly among executives who like
nothing better than to see upstarts flying successfully beneath
Microsoft's radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's managed to build a software developer business in spite
of all the Microsoft positioning,'' said Eric Schmidt, chairman and
chief executive of Novell Corp., a leading network software company
and Microsoft competitor. ``And he's done it with good products in
a difficult market.''
</P>
<P>
   Although compilers are remarkably complex programs that are
largely invisible to typical computer users, they play a crucial
role in the computing world. The quality of a compiler can
determine how quickly programs run, how easy is it to write
programs and whether those programs are more or less error free.
</P>
<P>
   And a fast compiler can sharply improve a programmer's
efficiency _ no small consideration, since complex programs might
contain millions of lines of programming instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you impact the efficiency of software development, then you
impact time to market,'' Galanos said. ``And time to market is
everything today.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, the company's forward momentum has not carried
over to its balance sheet or stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Although revenues have followed an upward trend, Metrowerks,
which ends its financial year in July, has eked out profits in only
four financial quarters since the beginning of fiscal 1996. And any
gains have been more than offset by the losses during that stretch,
as the company has invested heavily in its new strategy. Investors,
meanwhile, have shown little appetite for Metrowerks' shares, which
were trading above $9 in early 1998, but closed last Friday at $3.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The market hasn't been good for small and micro-cap stocks,''
said David Kaminer, an analyst at RBC Dominion Securities in
Montreal. ``But now their strategy is paying off in market
positioning,'' he said of Metrowerks, ``and I expect profitability
to return soon.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to many other software wunderkinds like Bill Gates
and Steve Jobs, who embraced computers as teen-agers, Galanos came
relatively late to this line of work. At age 17, after dropping out
of high school, Galanos left his native Australia in 1974, and for
the next two years traveled by foot, bus and car in Asia and
Europe. His adventures included encountering unfriendly Khmer Rouge
soldiers in Laos in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Vientiane, and American tourists were the targets for
roaming soldiers,'' he recalled. To ease his discreet withdrawal
from Laos, he said, ``I quickly added an Australian flag to my
backpack and threw greenbacks at the soldiers at all the
roadblocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, his wandering took him to Montreal, where he settled
in 1976 and became a self-taught programmer working for the
electric utility Hydro-Quebec. While there, he became manager of
the environment department, where despite a a ban on the use of
non-IBM personal computers he orchestrated the covert rental of
Macintosh computers by the department's scientists.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the accountants discovered his ploy in early 1985,
the group had one of the largest Macintosh networks then in
existence _ some 60 of the machines.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until the age of 28 that Galanos started college,
studying computer science at the University of Quebec, in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   He became intrigued with the work of Nicholaus Wirth, a Swiss
computer scientist who invented the Pascal and Modula programming
languages, and after graduating, Galanos founded Metropolis
Computer Networks in 1986 as a company that sold a Modula compiler
to colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   The modest success of that business attracted the interest of a
French venture capitalist, Jean Belanger, who supplied $100,000 of
financing in 1989 that helped Galanos found Metrowerks as a more
broadly based tools provider _ a relationship that eventually
resulted in Belanger's becoming chief executive three years ago,
freeing Galanos, still president, to also become chief technology
officer.
</P>
<P>
   As the Macintosh tool kit started taking off, Galanos took the
company public in 1994 and subsequently moved Metrowerks to Austin,
Texas, to be closer to the locus of Power PC chip development and
to take advantage of the engineering labor pool in that emerging
technopolis.
</P>
<P>
   Several years later he set up an office for himself and a small
group of the company's best programmers in Cupertino, in Silicon
Valley, to be close to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Galanos acknowledges that the software tools market is a
difficult one. But he says he is confident that Metrowerks will
return to profitability this year, now that its new business model
is taking hold.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for his optimism has been Metrowerks' ability to
raise prices for the software tools it sells to its 150,000
licensees.
</P>
<P>
   Price pressures had been tremendous in the desktop computer
market, given Microsoft's commanding market share in both operating
systems and tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Operating-system vendors want to give away compilers to
encourage people to write applications for their operating
system,'' said Richard Smith, a software industry executive who is
president of Phar Lap Software in Cambridge, Mass. ``But Metrowerks
has a good technology philosophy of being able to build good
software and retarget to many different chips.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Galanos, having spotted the next big discontinuity, is
banking on his Powerparts strategy to turn Metrowerks into a major
player in the post-PC world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very long and arduous task to transition from
being a Mac company,'' he said. ``You suck it in, invest a lot in
R&AMP;D, and push to make sales catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-13-99 1751EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
