<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SILICON-VALLEY-AR     06-16 1517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SILICON-VALLEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILICON VALLEY STARTS TO WONDER WHEN THE BUBBLE WILL BURST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic on home
prices, jobless rate and wage in Silicon Valley and U.S. overall is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ In Silicon Valley, these are the days of
miracles and wonder.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the longest sustained boom in the nation's
high-technology heartland, there is a palpable air of unreality
that has come to color the outlook of the computer engineers,
venture capitalists and software hackers who make up the valley's
rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Wage rates in the region are about 60 percent above the national
average and are growing far more quickly than average. Driven by
the vast new wealth created by a wave of Internet-related start-up
companies and the increasingly vast inflows of venture capital,
good times have arrived with a vengeance and have stayed longer
than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   The good times have led so many valley workers to sports car
showrooms that Raymond Lane, the president of Oracle, the giant
data base company, complained recently that he could not find the
new Porsche he wanted in Northern California; one local dealership
had a six-month waiting list. (He ordered one from a Southern
California dealer through the Internet.)
</P>
<P>
   And in meetings at power breakfast spots in Palo Alto like Il
Fornaio or Bucks in Woodside, executives shake their heads over
stories such as the one about the home in a comfortable Palo Alto
neighborhood that sold in April for $1 million more than the $2.4
million asking price.
</P>
<P>
   But indicators like those have in turn led to a growing sense of
unease among many valley longtimers who oscillate between a faith
in what has been called the ``long boom'' and the knowledge that
each of the valley's booms in the last half-century has inevitably
been followed by a bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``The valley is now divided into two camps,'' said John Shoch, a
partner at Alloy Ventures, a venture capital firm based in Palo
Alto. ``There are those people who are firmly inside a
reality-distortion field and there are the rest of us who realize
that this is going to end but who can't help going along for the
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk at the restaurants and sports clubs is frequently of
the power of ``Yahoo dollars'' or ``Weimar currencies,'' the fruits
of a stock market that seems to have a bottomless appetite for
Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, stock certificates have in many ways become the
currency of the valley _ to such an extent that the Menlo Park
Presbyterian Church receives a significant share of its tithing in
stock instead of money. And St. Joseph's, a Roman Catholic school
in Atherton, devotes part of its endowment to its own venture
capital fund.
</P>
<P>
   While the booming stock values have allowed companies to attract
and retain the best and brightest employees and acquire other
companies, there is also a growing perception that the excesses of
the Internet commerce boom may have permanently undermined the
valley's traditional no-nonsense, utilitarian, engineering-driven
culture.
</P>
<P>
   At the Palo Alto office of R.R. Donnelley, the venerable
printing company that publishes the financial documents known as
``red herrings'' that are a key part of the rite of going public,
the valet parking, the pool table and the cigars in a thermidor
occasion more than one raised eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   And such is the cash rattling around that an editor at the
high-speed Internet service At Home recently purchased a new
$625,000 home on his debit card.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one consensus is that this unrivaled wealth creation has
led to a stock market bubble that will certainly end, but nobody
knows when or how.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who are making the case that the
Internet has changed the law of physics,'' said Fred Hoar, a
longtime Silicon Valley publicist. ``But this is still a Newtonian
world, and when you throw something up in this world, it's going to
come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring that point, the book that is on everyone's lips is
not a Silicon Valley best seller like Geoffrey Moore's ``Crossing
the Chasm,'' but rather Charles MacKay's 1841 book ``Extraordinary
Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds,'' which among other
events described the Dutch tulip speculative craze of the 1600s, a
legendary example of a market mania.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what has made the current boom so unusual is that it
has gone on for so long. It has been more than six years since the
valley has seen tough times, a fact that has caused memories here
to grow hazy and has led some longtimers here to look for ways to
cling to a past that seems increasingly distant.
</P>
<P>
   Roger McNamee, a fund manager at Interval Partners in Menlo
Park, has followed the valley's ups and downs since the beginning
of the PC era. Now he points across a parking lot at his Toyota
Camry, a modest car contrasting with the more typical turbo-charged
luxury cars. He says he hangs onto the car as a touchstone to a
world he is in danger of losing contact with.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and researchers who are trying to understand the
apparent disappearance of the valley's boom-and-bust cycle point to
the convergence of two separate trends that set the economy into a
sustained period of overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   The semiconductor industry, which has long been the bedrock of
the Silicon Valley economy, was just beginning to recover in 1993
when the demand for Internet communications gear started its rapid
acceleration. Then in 1995 the Web economy kicked in, creating a
remarkable business spiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it was coincident with the commercialization of the
Internet,'' said Douglas Henton, president of Collaborative
Economics, a consulting firm in Palo Alto. ``But the real growth in
jobs has been in computer networking.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, although there have been booms before, this one has
permanently altered the valley's entrepreneurial culture, in ways
that are viewed as negative by many of the region's longtimers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a corrosive effect on the valley parallel to Wall Street
in the mid-1980's,'' said Eric Schmidt, who was the chief
technology officer at Sun Microsystems before decamping to Utah two
years ago as president and chief executive of Novell. ``The level
of expectation is well beyond the norm, even in Silicon Valley.
People have very short attention spans when it comes to their
careers. It is a youth phenomenon, a new generation of
entrepreneurs who have not had to concentrate on building
institutions that endure. Moreover, the venture industry has no
longer had to build a long-term business. The corrosive effect is
in creating a short-term versus long-term way of thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   And the wild successes of Stanford students like Jerry Yang of
Yahoo or Joe Kraus of Excite have now made it common for graduates
to choose Silicon Valley start-ups first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today 75 percent of my students are joining emerging
companies,'' said John Hennessey, the dean of the school of
engineering at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   That is a sharp turn from the days when the normal career
pattern was to join an established high-technology company like
Hewlett-Packard or Intel before setting out on a start-up venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got this funny psychology in which the reality and the
unreality coexist,'' said Michael Borrus, a managing director at
Petkovich &AMP; Partners, a San Francisco investment firm. ``These kids
really believe they're going to get wealthy and this youthful
optimism is overriding the fact that maybe 9 out of 10 of them
won't have an IPO in their lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, an economy in which several generations of new
workers have never known anything but explosive growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the semiconductor, we've known historically that every four
years we get hit cross the lip,'' said Hoar, the publicist, who was
an early employee at Fairchild Semiconductor, a pioneering chip
maker. ``There is one group that has seen it all and they have the
scars. On the other hand you have this group that says, `Every
breath I take is golden.''' That latter view rankles some valley
pioneers like Andrew Grove, a founder of Intel, and Steve Jobs,
Apple Computer's co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   Grove said that only in the recent past had he begun to hear the
phrase ``exit strategy'' _ do we want to be acquired or aim to go
public? _ which is now routinely part of the planning for tiny
start-up ventures that may not yet have sold their first product.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not reality,'' Jobs said. When Apple started, he said,
his role models were William Hewlett and David Packard, who had set
out to build an institution rather than an overnight gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   And ignoring that reality will ultimately bring its own
reckoning, Hoar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one chapter that keeps repeating itself in this
valley, and that's Chapter 11,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-15-99 1856EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
