<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SILICON-REPUBS-NY     06-16 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SILICON-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH GATES ON THE HILL, THE GOP IS ON THE MAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore may not have invented the Internet, but he
and President Clinton clearly perfected the skill of extracting
political contributions from Silicon Valley. Now, in a three-day
``High-Tech Summit'' on Capitol Hill, Republicans are trying to
show that they have the capacity to be even better friends of Bill
Gates and his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning Gates, his once-sharp barbs about Washington
lawmakers replaced with deferential comments like ``you've raised
an interesting issue, Senator,'' was filled with prognostications
about how the Web, wireless networks and electronic commerce would
turn ``consumers into big winners.''
</P>
<P>
   And the members of the Congressional Joint Economic Committee,
led by Republicans, were so filled with praise for Microsoft Corp.
and its entrepreneurial ilk that they only once, and then only
obliquely, raised the uncomfortable question of how antitrust laws
were applied to the world's most powerful software company. Left
unsaid, but understood, was that it is President Clinton's Justice
Department that is pursuing Microsoft in court a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the subtext of the three days of hearings, which began
with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and ended Tuesday with
Gates' appearance, is that Republicans are eager to get the
government off the Valley's back. Sure, many actual denizens of
Silicon Valley would be happy to see Microsoft get its hand slapped
by the government. But that didn't stop heads from nodding Tuesday
when Gates talked about how keeping ``a light hand'' on regulation
of technology industries ``is working very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Gates finished talking than the Senate voted to
lighten the touch even more: Over the administration's objections,
on Tuesday it approved a bill that would limit the liability of
high-technology companies for any damage by the Year 2000 bug.
President Clinton has pledged to veto the legislation, a version of
which has already passed in the House, giving yet another wedge for
Republicans who argue that the White House is the Valley's
fair-weather friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things going on here,'' a Republican member of
the committee said after Tuesday's hearings, asking not to be
further identified. ``There are real issues we'll have to deal
with,'' he said, among them congressional hearings on Internet
privacy, data encryption, support for basic research. ``And there
are questions of political funding. Which of those goes first, that
will depend on how cynical you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates once reveled in his apolitical nature. Until a few years
ago, Microsoft maintained only a small presence in Washington,
eschewing professional lobbyists and suggesting that the importance
of what happens in hearing rooms pales in comparison to what
happens in software labs. Meanwhile the Republican leadership, or
at least those leaders without significant high-technology
constituencies, largely ceded the territory to Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday they see an opportunity. Software makers are still
haggling with the administration, and Gore in particular, over U.S.
rules limiting the export of programs that offer high-level
encryption of data _ which U.S. intelligence agencies fear will be
exploited by potential enemies. At Tuesday's hearings, Network
Associates Inc. president William Larson described how the company
is about to lose ``a seven-figure deal'' to provide such software
to Chrysler, after its new parent,  &UR; DaimlerChrysler &LR; , insisted on
purchasing programs that could be shipped around the world. The
business is likely to go to a German competitor, Larson said.
</P>
<P>
   Others used the moment to lobby for an extension of the research
and development tax break. Charles Vest, the president of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, warned against what he
termed ``growing complacency'' about U.S. high technology
superiority, noting that federal funding for basic research and
development was declining. He said that at this point ``the United
States is living off of historical assets that are not being
renewed.'' The Internet's origins lie in a system developed by the
Pentagon and used for years, largely in obscurity, by academics.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly the big draw Tuesday was Gates, who received the
gentlest of handling all around. There were no tough questions
about charges that have arisen during the antitrust trial. In fact,
there were no tough questions at all _ either from the senators or
from students who were asking questions, via an Internet link, from
university and high school projects that Microsoft is backing.
</P>
<P>
   While it was never discussed, the Republican-dominated panel was
clearly aware that Microsoft greatly increased its giving to
political causes in the 1997 and 1998 election cycles, and the
expectation is that the sum could increase dramatically for the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The company and its employees gave about $1.3 million in
unregulated ``soft money'' over the last two years, putting them
among the top dozen or so in this category.
</P>
<P>
   It was listed as a ``table sponsor'' for the Republican
Congressional Committee dinner last week. While tables sell for
only $25,000, the move was viewed as a sign of things to come as
Republicans seek to exploit Microsoft's unhappiness with its
treatment by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has increased its permanent lobbying staff in
Washington and has also reached out to some of the capital's
longtime consultants. Among the lobbyists under contract to
Microsoft is former Republican National Committee chairman Haley
Barbour.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly two-thirds of Microsoft's political spending already
goes to Republicans, a figure that a senior employee at the
company's Redmond, Wash., headquarters said ``would probably come
as a surprise to most Microsoft employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates did everything he could Tuesday to steer clear of
controversy. He talked about forthcoming inventions that would help
members of Congress in their work, including new types of portable
digital devices that would help them ``access your own `digital
dashboard' '' even when they are out of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He banished from his vocabulary almost all his usual tech-speak,
talking as if he was giving a speech to an interested but somewhat
unsophisticated chamber of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Invited to give his views on the state of U.S. antitrust laws,
he said that ``the laws as they are currently written are fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The implication he left is that they are being wrongly
interpreted in Microsoft's case. But he carefully dodged specific
mention of the litigation, other than to say ``things like
integration of new features are one of the freedoms companies
have'' under those laws.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Microsoft case hinges on the question of whether the
company is integrating its Internet browser into the Windows
operating system in a way that undercuts the ability of competing
browsers to operate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-15-99 2105EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
