<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7307 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SILICON-STRUGGLE-     06-16 1593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SILICON-STRUGGLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR VIEWS COMPUTER RIVALRY AS CLASSIC STRUGGLE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pizza boxes and caffeine, bad hygiene, ill-fitting
suits and screaming fits, all bathed in the soft cathode-ray glow
of computer screens hardly seems the stuff of a classic yarn.
</P>
<P>
   Except to Martyn Burke, who thinks a certain much-celebrated
bard might have written about Apple Computers' Steve Jobs and
Microsoft's Bill Gates, had the rise of the personal computer
happened when Elizabeth I, not Elizabeth II, was queen of England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Shakespearean nature of the story of these two men,''
said Burke, who wrote and directed TNT's ``Pirates of Silicon
Valley'' about the two ubergeeks of the computing world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's `Hamlet,' `Macbeth' and `Richard III' combined,'' Burke
said. ``There's a scene in `Richard III' where his enemies have
laid siege to all around, and he says, `My kingdom for a horse.'
That's what I thought of when I read about Steve Jobs' 30th
birthday party. Jobs is basically Richard III to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Burke is too much the veteran of Hollywood features
and documentaries to try to sell the story to development execs
without a more modern conflation of reference points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a story that transcends all the boundaries,'' Burke
said. ``In that kind of Hollywood shorthand, it was `Diner' meets
`Citizen Kane.' There was more drama in this than I've seen in a
lot of other stuff. That was what attracted me.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the movie traces the somewhat similar upward trajectory
of Jobs and Gates from the early 1970s through the mid-1980s, Burke
said the two are substantially different kinds of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no particular ax to grind when I came to this story,''
Burke said. ``I let the story write itself on the basis of
research. Gates emerged as a guy who's completely different from
Jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The research is partly based on the Paul Freiberger book, ``Fire
in the Valley,'' as well as much other material compiled by Burke
and the film's actors, particularly Noah Wyle, who became
passionate about the role after Burke sent him a documentary cued
to Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched 10 seconds and knew I'd kick myself for the rest of
my life if I didn't play the part,'' said Wyle, who worked
seven-day weeks to finish both the film and his starring role on
``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Michael Hall, the long-lost Brat Packer who played
Gates, called his part ``the role of a lifetime. Gates is like the
Henry Ford or John Rockefeller of our generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The portraits that emerge are of extraordinarily intense people
who through luck, brains, insane work habits, smart friends and
stupid competitors changed American business.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs is a charismatic seeker trying to fill some existential
hole in himself and driving those around him mercilessly, exhorting
them to be ``insanely great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jobs) has these furies he's coping with all the time,'' Burke
said. ``He was always at a remove from everyone around him. Gates
did not personalize his furies the way Jobs would do.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke shows Jobs _ an adopted child who hires a private
detective to find his natural mother _ trying LSD and many Eastern
religions and alternative spiritual practices.
</P>
<P>
   Later, still driven but bolstered by fabulous success, his
almost classically Greek hubris nearly undid him _ and his company.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he got more power and became more of a guru in his own
right, whatever the brakes were on his behavior fell away,'' Burke
said. ``He went crazy on his employees all the time. The thing that
created the success of Apple was also the source of its problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In one particularly painful scene, the movie shows Jobs verbally
savaging a job applicant who wears the virtual uniform of IBM:
pressed white button-down Oxford shirt, conservative tie, slacks
and close-cropped hair. The man doesn't belong and will never fit
in, Jobs says.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, on the other hand, comes across as the consummate poker
player, literally and figuratively. Anthony Michael Hall, like Wyle
a ringer for his subject, plays Gates as a Machiavellian snake who
uses whatever advantage he can to win a card game _ or a business
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he's far goofier than Jobs, having ``dates''
with venture capitalist/longtime buddy Anna Winblad where they
simultaneously would attend a movie and then, because they happened
to be in different cities, talk about it on the phone afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Gates comes off as classic nerd, but how many nerds do
you know who steal bulldozers in the middle of the night, as he did
in Albuquerque?'' Burke said. For that matter, how many geeks
commandeer their buddy's new car, go speeding through the night and
wind up in jail?
</P>
<P>
   But it's Gates' high-stakes poker mind that is most distinctive
in the film, as Gates tells his college buddies (and Microsoft
colleagues) Paul Allen and Steve Ballmer that the key to successful
negotiating is getting a person to believe they want what you have,
and only you can provide it to them.
</P>
<P>
   We see him squeeze his first computer maker to double the
nascent Microsoft's royalty payments for the operating system he
and Allen had hurriedly written in their Harvard dorm room. Without
the operating system, he tells the hardware maker, his
``brilliant'' machine is just a bunch of blinking lights in a box.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of argument worked on the big boys, too, as IBM agreed
to buy an operating system for the IBM PC that Gates and Allen
hadn't yet created. The result, MS-DOS, became the dominant system
for running personal computers, thanks to IBM's still-magic name in
the business world.
</P>
<P>
   And ultimately, Gates talked Jobs into giving him three
prototypes of Apple's crown jewel, the paradigm-shifting Macintosh.
The result was Microsoft's Windows, a new operating system that
made ugly old PCs run like a Mac without needing to be one.
</P>
<P>
   Though it took several tries (and a successful fending off of
Apple's ``look and feel'' technology infringement lawsuit),
Windows' latest versions run more computers than any operating
system in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Windows came out, that's what absolutely floored Jobs,''
Burke said. ``The one person he had trusted came back to haunt him.
Jobs had this kind of Achilles heel. He had this one area of
weakness and was looking for something. Gates, for some reason,
understood Steve Jobs better than anybody, consciously or
unconsciously.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly $50 billion later, Gates is the world's richest man,
while Jobs first had to humiliate himself on stage before Apple
faithfuls, declaring in 1997 that the age of competition with
Microsoft was over, then trying to save the lurching company he'd
left a dozen years earlier from bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Burke doesn't admire his subjects in many ways, for all
the warts his movie shows on their public portraits.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, after a massive underestimation of the Internet's impact,
has spent billions positioning his company to dominate that area,
too. And Jobs has not only returned Apple to profitability and
hipness as its interim CEO but also owns computer animation studio
Pixar, which produced Disney's ``A Bug's Life'' and ``Toy Story''
to huge acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's one of the more amazing characters in American
public life,'' Burke said of Jobs. ``He proves that (F. Scott)
Fitzgerald was wrong when he said there were no second acts in
American lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman John Pinette said the movie's makers took
some substantial liberties with the historical record in making
``Pirates,'' but that the company would let viewers make their own
decision about what to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our reaction is this is a made-for-TV movie, and that says
enough,'' Pinette said. ``In the end, it's a movie about the
graphical user interface, and you have to take some liberties to
make that interesting. We're basically going to let other people
decide its merits.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple did not return calls seeking comment on the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Burke has one final metaphor for what Gates and Jobs wrought:
Vietnam, and the American combat involvement there that was ending
just as the personal computer revolution was starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the old days of the student radicals who were
determined to overthrow the power structure, they failed,'' Burke
said. ``And these guys, who were ignored by everybody, succeeded.
The techies, the nerds, basically undermined the way business was
done in America.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more engaging parts of ``Pirates of Silicon Valley''
is the series of culture clashes between execs of major technology
corporations such as IBM, Xerox and Hewlett-Packard in the early
days of Apple and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Where those companies (much like the American military of that
day) were heavily bureaucratic, top-down and unable to envision any
personal use for the computer, the then-tiny Microsoft and Apple
were agile and forward-thinking enough to outstrip the big
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't care about structure and hierarchy,'' Burke said.
``It was almost a metaphor of what was going on in Vietnam.
American business is kind of small-scale guerrilla warfare all the
time. HP (Hewlett-Packard) and Xerox and IBM were actually missing
the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   (To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information
on the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail
him at davidbloom(at)earthlink.net, or call (818) 713-3678).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-15-99 1915EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
