<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7309 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-EBAY-ADDICT-TEX &LR;      06-16 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-EBAY-ADDICT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP YOUR HAND OFF THE MOUSE, AND NO ONE WILL GET HURT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By BEVERLY BUNDY  
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stop me before I double-click again.
</P>
<P>
   My eyes are bloodshot, my wrists are sore and my back aches. But
I'm so entranced, I can't stop.
</P>
<P>
   My husband's car breaks down, and he has to walk three miles in
90-degree heat because he can't call home, the line is busy. I'm
making a buy.
</P>
<P>
   It started, like most habits do, with curiosity. One online
purchase certainly wouldn't be a gateway to sin. One hundred
personal checks later proves otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   I'm an eBay junkie _ addicted to an auction house in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Software engineer Pierre Omidyar had only the sweetest
intentions when he started eBay three years ago. He set up a
personal World Wide Web page as a forum for his girlfriend to trade
the Pez dispensers she collected.
</P>
<P>
   Now his simple page has morphed into a 2.25 million-item
inventory covering 1,627 categories with 3.8 million registered
users. The beauty of the system is that the company does not own
the inventory _ it belongs to the sellers who pay eBay a listing
fee and a percentage of the sales price to offer their goods
through the whiz-bang of computer land.
</P>
<P>
   The result is garage-sale heaven. Just a five-minute perusal of
the site clicks up 135 listings of Mexican pottery, 1,563 of
Depression glass, 3,858 dolls, 484 African-American art objects,
and, heaven help us, 8,572 Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   A woman in Idaho is offering gently worn cowboy boots, a
Hawaiian seller is selling earrings made in India and a woman in
England is advertising toast forks. And you can see what you buy _
most of the listings include one or more color photographs of the
item, pointing out flaws or details.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't QVC, where you buy a cubic zirconium that you'll see
coming and going at Wal-Mart. No sir, these are genuine,
one-of-a-kind ``objets.''
</P>
<P>
   No more pawing through formula-stained Onesies, Dallas Cowboys
coozies and lidless crockpots to get to the Steuben vase. No more
Saturday mornings of crack-o'-dawn alarms to beat out the other
garage-salers. No more trying to juggle the children, the traffic
and the marked-up classifieds.
</P>
<P>
   And the eBay facilitators make the shopping as pleasant as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The system is set up like any live auction. Items are offered in
categories, shoppers click on entries that catch the eye
``GENUINETURKISH VASEHAND PAINTED'' and look at the description as
well as the photograph.
</P>
<P>
   If you care to bid, look at the last bid, figure what you'd like
to pay, enter the amount and submit the bid. When the auction is
completed (most are scheduled to run five days) the high bidder is
notified by e-mail from eBay. Seller and buyer have three days to
get in touch by e-mail, and the buyer sends off a check or money
order, including the purchase price and usually, postage.
</P>
<P>
   Like a real-deal auction, there is technique to be learned. Most
heavy bidding seems to occur within an hour or two of the item's
close time. Sometimes the seller sets a reserve price, meaning it
won't sell unless a certain price is met.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I blame my addiction _ as many people do _ on the stress of my
job. I was compiling information for a yearlong ``food through the
century'' project. I needed old recipes, old photographs, just
plain old stuff to help me get a handle on the way we've been
eating for the past 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   After tackling the local libraries and my own collection of
cookbooks, on the advice of a co-worker, I turned to eBay.
</P>
<P>
   My first purchase was Item 887792861: Jell-O Recipe Booklet _
Work of Art!!! 1925 (I was the high bidder at $6). I followed that
with Item 88541687: RECIPES The House of Chan Cookbook 1952 ($3).
Then came Item 88282989: 500 Delicious Salads (recipes) Cookbook
OLD ($2). This, I've gotta say, rocks.
</P>
<P>
   By now I was a regular. I knew my way around the site. (''It's
like crack,'' said one co-worker. ``Walk away and just say no.'')
Now I could peck around for things I used to buy at flea markets
before I had a house payment and a child and a college fund to
build.
</P>
<P>
   First I bought treasures for myself. Item 88911475: Gorgeous
Colors! _ Bakelite (?) Old Jewelry Box ($10.49). Then came Item
90691226: Old Dip Bowl w/ Recipes on Outside Gold Trim ($1.50). I
followed that with Jade/Jadite lamp No Reserve ($29.52).
</P>
<P>
   It got to the point that I was firing up the laptop as soon as I
walked in the house after work. Dinner was left to the boys to
perform. I had tchotchkes to track down. But a little guilt did
start to seep in around the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Item 96695543: SOAP ``MADE IN SPAIN'' (3) SEE PIC!!! ($4.99)
will send my mother-in-law over the moon come Christmas. She loves
Macedonia glycerin soap and hasn't been able to find it since a
trip to Europe 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Item 95919386: WOW 3 MINT HESS TRUCKS 1992/93/94 IN BOXES
($74.95) filled in the holes in my son's green-and-white truck
collection.
</P>
<P>
   But my sacrificial buys didn't help my case _ the phone became
an issue. My son's friends couldn't get through, my husband's
office couldn't reach him, my parents wondered whether Fort Worth
had been hit by another hailstorm.
</P>
<P>
   My husband insisted on a cable modem to free up the phone. Add
$30 a month to the household budget. My 6-year-old knew to tell a
playmate that a word processor ``doesn't get eBay.'' The household
schedule was being affected. Lots of the auctions end around 7-9
p.m. Pacific time _ two hours later here _ time I should be using
to get ready for the next day.
</P>
<P>
   But all will be forgiven. Wait until next week when the mailman
drives up with Item 111100650: Wooly Mammoth Skull with Ivory
Tusks.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   GETTING STARTED: THE EBAY ESSENTIALS
</P>
<P>
   Getting started on eBay is frighteningly simple.
</P>
<P>
   Type www.ebay.com to get the site. If you want to window-shop,
simply type your particular interest in the Search bar and press
Enter.
</P>
<P>
   For a full explanation of the site, go to the New User section
and click. If you want to bid, you'll have to go to the Register
area, also on the home page.
</P>
<P>
   To register, you must be at least 18 years old. The form will
ask for your e-mail address, your name and street address. A
primary phone number is also required. No credit card information
is required.
</P>
<P>
   If you wish, you can supply such information as your sex, age,
education and income level.
</P>
<P>
   Within 24 hours, eBay will e-mail you a confirmation code, and
you're ready to bid dot com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Safety first
</P>
<P>
   A 13-year-old New Jersey boy had his Internet privileges yanked
after he racked up almost $3 million in eBay bids on a red 1955
Ford convertible, a van Gogh painting, an antique bed, a copy of a
Viking ship and a Superman comic book.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a stern ``You must be 18 years old'' reminder (in red)
on the top of the auction site's registration form, he went ahead
and registered. And bid, and bid, and bid.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Pursglove, eBay spokesman, said the company has a strict
policy against bidding by anyone younger than 18. But he said eBay
mostly works on the honor system; it's up to users to report
deadbeat bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The number of consumers complaining that they were defrauded
online went from 1,280 in 1997 to 7,752 in 1998, according to
Internet Fraud Watch, an online fraud reporting system created by
the National Consumers League.
</P>
<P>
   But as e-commerce mushrooms, the Internet companies are coming
up with options to protect the mostly honest shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   On eBay, there's payback if buyer or seller is less than honest
or prompt. The ``Feedback'' forum allows buyers and sellers to
leave messages about their transactions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company offers i-Escrow, a service that acts as
the third-party agent in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. The buyer and seller agree on a price. The
buyer sends credit-card information (MasterCard, Visa, American
Express, Discover, Diners or Carte Blanche) or a check or money
order, to i-Escrow. Meanwhile the seller sends the item to the
buyers. When the buyer lets i-Escrow know the item has arrived and
is as advertised, i-Escrow forwards the money to the seller.
</P>
<P>
   This service costs the buyer 5 percent of the purchase price
(with a $5 minimum) for objects up to $5,000. Items priced at more
than $5,000 get a discount rate.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
