<HEADLINE>
FCC SAYS IT SHOULD REGULATE HIGH-SPEED ACCESS TO INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anxious cable companies got a boost Tuesday when the chairman of
the Federal Communications Commission, William Kennard, said his
agency, not local governments, should regulate high-speed Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the FCC and Congress have declined to regulate cable
Internet services. Kennard, in a speech to the National Cable
Television Association in Chicago, was responding to a federal
court ruling in Portland, Ore., two weeks ago affirming the
authority of local governments to require AT&AMP;T Corp. to allow
competing Internet service providers onto the cable system it
acquired in its purchase of Telecommunications Inc. this year.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has said it will appeal the decision, but cable executives
want assurance that if they spend billions upgrading their cable
systems, they will be able to use their own high-speed Internet
access providers. AT&AMP;T is a majority owner of the cable-Internet
service Excite(at)Home, while Time Warner Inc. owns the Roadrunner
cable modem service.
</P>
<P>
   America Online and other Internet service providers are lobbying
the FCC and local governments to force the cable companies to open
their systems to them.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said he was studying his options for getting involved in
the Portland case. Cheryl Leanza, deputy director of Media Access
Project, a nonprofit telecommunications law firm, said that
generally courts had tended to defer to the FCC in complex
regulatory matters.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland case was widely followed because it set a precedent
for how other local governments might behave.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is a power struggle that goes back to the
Civil War,'' said Howard Anderson, president of Yankee Group, a
consulting firm. ``It is a question of whether the federal
government or the state government will have control. For the cable
operators, it is not so much about money, as about power. What they
want to do is to exclude the other Internet providers.''
</P>
<P>
   News that the FCC might intervene in the matter sent stocks of
cable operators up Tuesday. Time Warner shares rose $4.625 to close
at $66.687, Comcast rose $1.93 to close at $32.875 and Adelphia
jumped $6.875 to close at $62.875.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner stock also benefited from its bid to focus attention
on its Internet-related business. Yesterday it named Richard
Bressler, who has been the company's chief financial officer since
1995, head of its new online unit, Time Warner Digital Media, which
includes all the company's Internet presence, including electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's chairman, Gerald Levin, described the new entity
as the company's ``single most important growth area.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-15-99 2054EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
