<HEADER>
A7315 &Cx1f; ttx-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-RELIGION-INTERNET     06-16 1868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-RELIGION-INTERNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS LEADERS EXPAND THEIR MINISTRIES TO THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By TARA DOOLEY  
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ From the front bedroom of his Fort Worth
home, Brian Oakes can enter a Christian mission field.
</P>
<P>
   With the flip of a switch on his computer, Oakes can join a
gathering of about 300 Christians from a registration list of
15,000 to discuss everything from Jesus Christ to the latest trends
in Christian music to the politics of a church youth group.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't think this type of ministry is relevant,'' said
Oakes, 23, a self-described computer geek and founder of the
Christian Chat Network. ``But let's look at people's lives. What do
people do? They spend most of their time on the Internet. If the
church is not willing to embrace it, then the church is going to
get left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Though perhaps not a place where people spend ``most of their
time,'' the Internet has affected how many people do business, and
the business of religion is increasingly no exception. More
Christians are going online, changing the ways that spiritual
communities interact and discuss matters of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders are e-mailing congregation members, preachers are
broadcasting sermons, peddlers are selling their religious wares,
and individuals, such as those gathered by Oakes, are reaching out
to one another for solace and inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is as significant a new medium as the printing
press was, and we know now what the printing press did,'' said Fran
Maier, chancellor of the Catholic Archdiocese of Denver, making
reference to the Protestant Reformation that was propelled by the
printed word. ``We want to be ahead of the curve rather than behind
it the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   As Christians strive to stay ahead of the curve, however, many
religious leaders are concerned that widespread Internet use could
erode the church's calling to bring people together, physically and
spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try to say is, `If you use the Internet, you need to
use it as a tool to move people toward embodied relationships,'''
said Robert DeVargas, an assistant professor at Southwestern
Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth, who is creating an
ethics and technology course on the Internet and ministry. ``That
means first in a relationship to God, to the church, and in a
relationship with friends and family.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there appears little danger that disembodied multitudes
will forsake the pews for their computers, according to a 10-month
survey of religion online conducted for a division of the United
Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a lack of people saying, `Oh good, I don't
have to get up and get dressed and go to church. I can log onto the
Internet and go to church,' '' said the study's author, Ken Bedell,
vice president of the Forum Foundation in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Internet users, those using the technology for
religious matters log on to improve communications and find
information, according to the study, which was completed last year.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the movement toward the Internet is part of a
progression starting with radio and television that has led
religion away from the pulpit or the camp meeting ground and into
the home. But the difference now is that the Internet also allows
for more individual autonomy and privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not unique to the Internet but, because of the
interactive nature, it is more compelling to be disembodied,''
DeVargas said.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that it allows users the chance to attend an
online Bible discussion or hear a sermon that a child's soccer
practice or other commitments might have pre-empted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can sit down at your computer once the kids are in bed and
everyone is settled down ... and listen to it while you are paying
your bills,'' said Paula Golway, marketing manager for the
Dallas-based Lightsource.com, which provides Christian programming
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Lightsource.com, run by an advertising agency that specializes
in Christian ministries, funnels popular Christian radio programs
such as Focus on the Family onto the Internet and broadcasts
services from churches such as Preston Hollow Presbyterian Church
in Dallas onto the personal computer, making it available for
consumption at the user's discretion.
</P>
<P>
   The number of possible people accessing the programming has also
expanded. Since January 1997, Lightsource.com has had an exclusive
contract to provide Christian programming for Broadcast.com, which
was recently bought by Yahoo!. And that will provide an
evangelizing link to one of the busiest sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when Christ walked the Earth, he did it via himself and
12 disciples,'' Golway said. ``Now we have a way of expanding it
around the world in milliseconds. It's a very interesting and very
hip way of doing what people have been doing for 2000 years.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, the possibility that the technology will not
only enhance but alter what people have been doing for 2000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Archdiocese of Denver sponsored a four-day
seminar examining how emerging technologies will affect the ways
faith is communicated in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   It included computer industry professionals, theologians and
church leaders who looked at how to use technologies such as the
Internet to ``make disciples of all nations.'' But it also looked
at the social implications of the new technology, Maier said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology has to do with how we deliver the message,'' he
said. ``The psychological implications have to do with who it is
that we are reaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet use at Calvary Lutheran Church in Richland Hills is
probably most typical of how the technology is used by churches to
reach people.
</P>
<P>
   The church's leaders use e-mail to keep in touch with
denominational leaders and congregation members and to reach
potential newcomers. The church's Web site provides basic
information through its online newsletter and listings of weekly
services and events such as The Calvary Cafe, a weekly dinner
prepared by the Rev. Phil Heinze, the church's associate pastor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, church members and Web site visitors can e-mail
prayer requests, read devotionals and join a discussion board where
topics range from a sick child in the community to a recent sermon.
</P>
<P>
   For example, by logging onto the Web site, congregation members
can keep up with the progress of 4-year-old Mason Renner, who has
leukemia, and send prayers for the child and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Though his use of the Web site has slowed since Mason's illness,
the child's father, Dan Renner, said he had participated in an
online discussion group that tackled topics such as Thomas the
Doubter and Lazarus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is somewhat different because people generally have to
gather their thoughts together instead of rambling on and on,''
Renner said. ``I think you get more concise thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's Web site also provides links to online resources
such as the Internet Christian Library, a selection of Bibles and
Bible tutorials, and The Desperate Preacher,' a lectionary
discussion site for preachers preparing sermons.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have at Calvary is a Web site, and it's a reflection
of our real community at Calvary Lutheran Church,'' said Michael
Middleton, a computer professional and congregation member who
helped design the Web site. ``It's an invitation for people to join
us. It wouldn't exist if we didn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Oakes' Christian Chat Network has produced
Christian relationships that exist because of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Oakes steers clear of calling those who enter the network's chat
rooms a community, he said, because he believes that term should be
reserved for gatherings in rooms with pews.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what term he uses, Oakes has created an Internet
assembly that allows Christians to discuss religious convictions
and secular concerns while offering a way to forge friendships.
</P>
<P>
   The user can enter the network by signing on with a self-chosen
name. The user enters a ``lobby'' and can stay there and talk for a
while or head into specialty sections for teen-agers, single adults
or women, Oakes said. Some users will schedule times to meet online
and chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, it is not the most outgoing person on the
computer,'' Oakes said. ``With the anonymity, that baggage can be
taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakes also rebroadcasts a Christian music radio show online and
broadcasts a call-in show that he moderates over the network.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Lee, a divorced mother of four from Cedar Lake, Ind.,
found out about Oakes' network from a friend.
</P>
<P>
   In the confines of chat rooms protected by a filtering system
that will eject any user that contributes inappropriate material,
Lee said she has spent many evenings discussing spiritual issues
online and has made friends. She is now a monitor for two All
Singles Believers chat rooms on the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of fun,'' she said. ``But some of it is serious.
Sometimes people come in and have a problem, and they want to talk
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Enhancing the virtual with the real, Lee has physically met and
made friends with chat network users in Michigan and Illinois, she
said. A group of the users is planning to gather in Florida in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Bedell found that the people he surveyed believe that the
Internet will likely play an even more important role in religious
life in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But how it will change and help shape spiritual matters is
unclear, said Bedell, a sociologist and ordained United Methodist
minister.
</P>
<P>
   The potential exists for meaningful theological discussion to
take place on the Internet, he said, especially because it is a
means of communication worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing it simply as a tool for the local church may be to
underestimate its effects and potential, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real possibility that the future of spirituality
and religion will get worked out on the Internet,'' Bedell said.
</P>
<P>
   But even enthusiasts approach that era cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   Taking into account concerns about disembodied spiritual
communities, Oakes said he personally makes sure that he doesn't
become mesmerized by his computer screen and forsake the rest of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Oakes said he spends a chunk of most weekday evenings online,
but he also has a demanding job as a protocol engineer for a
computer company, a fiance and Kruger, his attention-hungry hound.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Chat Network operates through donations and the
fees Oakes collects for hosting Web sites, mostly for Christian
ministries and bands.
</P>
<P>
   Some months, it breaks even. Some months, Oakes uses part of his
paycheck from his regular job to pay the network's bills, which run
about $1,200 a month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the network is Oakes' contribution to Christian
ministry, his way to give something back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is truly the last open mission field,'' Oakes
said. ``I can get past the door into the bedroom and tell people
about Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-15-99 1929EDT &QL;
</P>
