r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-READY-HNS &LR;      06-16 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-READY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K CONSULTANT NO LONGER ALARMED ABOUT DATE CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTAMONT, N.Y. _ Barry Pardy went all out when he first heard of
the Y2K bug two years ago. The computer consultant and his wife
bought a year's worth of food _ long-term storage stuff like
unground wheat, powdered milk and food specially canned by Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   They bought a water purifier good for 13,000 gallons, and bleach
in case they needed to treat more. They installed heavy-duty locks
on their house to keep out rioters, put in a generator, and are now
looking for a wood burning stove. All in preparation for the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Pardy is still worried about the Year 2000 (Y2K) computer
glitch. But now, he's more realistic about its impact. Today, he
doubts he'll be touching his drums of wheat, although he doesn't
regret buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still many unknowns,'' he said. ``But because so many
people are doing good work, I feel more optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Months after the millennium computer bug began to make news all
over the country, much has been done to fix the problem. Companies
are spending billions of dollars to reprogram computers or replace
them. Government offices have made citizens aware of how much work
they're doing to solve their problems. Banks say money is safe;
utilities say power will stay on after midnight on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   While some still think New Year's Eve will bring disaster, many
others _ even those who were once terrified of Y2K _ are beginning
to relax. Whatever computer problems the new year may bring, they
don't seem as bad as they did only a short time ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K bug, of course, refers to a computer's inability to
understand that next year is the 2000. When many date-sensitive
computers or their programs were built, only the last two digits of
the year were used. So some computers may read the ``00'' in 2000
as ``1900,'' causing them to crash or spew out incorrect data.
</P>
<P>
   When 1999 was three decades away, that didn't seem like a
problem _ especially since programmers thought their programs and
clattering equipment would eventually be replaced, long before the
turn of the century. Only, in most cases, it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Some programmers tried to warn others early, but most didn't
take Y2K seriously until the early 1990s. That was when major
government agencies like Social Security and the Department of
Defense began to do their own Y2K remediation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a few people began to look at the worst-case scenario
of what Y2K could do. They called it The End of the World As We
Know It, or TEOTWAWKI. And using the World Wide Web, people like
Gary North _ a historian, economist and Christian reconstructionist
who has written several books about the end of the world _ began to
preach the death of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Word was that Y2K problems could cause planes to fall out of the
sky, could cause cars to stop working, could shut down pacemakers
and ATM machines and every other facet of modern civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Pardy, a consultant from Altamont who helps companies prepare
for Y2K, started researching the millennium bug 2 1/2 years ago. He
scrolled through Web sites and talked to experts, and began to
realize that a widespread computer failure would be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I immediately thought about all of the computers I'd worked on
over the years,'' he said. ``And the time I'd seen businesses be
flat down because of one simple problem on the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been evidence since then that the problems may have
been exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, some Y2K-related failures that were to have
happened _ so-called ``trigger dates'' _ were rather anticlimactic.
April 9, 1999 was supposed to have been a big bump in the road. The
concern was it might be seen by some computers as the code
``9999,'' which many programmers have used to signal a program to
end. But few problems were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the embedded chip problem. The concern was that
modern computer chips used in all sorts of machinery might include
a date-recognition code that could cause it to stop working. As it
turned out, problems of this sort are very rare.
</P>
<P>
   Many concerned about Y2K were most concerned about panic. Panic,
they say, is more likely than computer glitches to cause bank runs,
food hoarding and even riots.
</P>
<P>
   Today, while it's still a concern, it seems unlikely that people
could panic over something that's been discussed over and over
again for so long. Some people even say the media is paying too
much attention to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's happening is just about everybody's made up
their minds already,'' said Dick Mills, a computer consultant and
head of a Y2K interest group in upstate New York. ``Either they've
fixed the thing and they think they're ready, or they don't want to
do anything anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
