<HEADLINE>
INTERNET OFFERS PRIMER ON MILLENNIUM GLITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer experts fear that computers and other electronic
equipment originally programmed to recognize only the last two
digits of a year will fail or malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, when the
machines will assume it is 1900. This is known as the Year 2000
(Y2K) problem or the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for more information on Y2K? Here is a list of Internet
addresses, including government information sites:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.y2ktimebomb.com (an information-packed page run by
expert John Westergaard)
</P>
<P>
   http://www.year2000.com (page has accent on technology and a
library of thousands of Y2K articles)
</P>
<P>
   http://www.y2ktoday.com (another informative page)
</P>
<P>
   http://www.y2knewswire.com (good source of Y2K news clips)
</P>
<P>
   http://www.yourdon.com (Web page of Ed Yourdon, author of the
Y2K bible ``Time Bomb 2000'')
</P>
<P>
   http://www.y2k.gov/text/index.htm (the White House Y2K council
homepage)
</P>
<P>
   http://www.senate.gov/y2k/index.html (U.S. Senate Y2K committee)
</P>
<P>
   http://www.house.gov/reform/gmit/y2k/index.htm (Federal report
card from Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Calif.)
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bog.frb.fed.us/y2k (Federal Reserve Board)
</P>
<P>
   http://www.fema.gov/y2k (Federal Emergency Management Agency)
</P>
</TEXT>
