<HEADLINE>
MAC USERS HAVE FEWER WORRIES AS 2000 APPROACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM M. DOWD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Forget the workplace equipment. Who among
individuals should worry about making sure their personal computers
and software are Y2K compliant?
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Macintosh user, rejoice. Macs are in sync with the
date change, although there can be software problems.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the date and time utilities that Apple Inc. has used in
its Macs since 1984 should work right up to 6:28:15 a.m. on Feb. 6,
2040 _ although it never hurts to have the latest version of
operating system software (now Mac OS 8.5) just to play it extra
safe.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else should be wary.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar progression from Dec. 31, 1999, to Jan. 1, 2000,
will create a double whammy for date-dependent programs.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will some not know the difference between 1900 and 2000
because they rely on reading only the two final digits of the year,
they'll be all bollixed up because of the day-of-the-week problem:
Jan. 1, 1900, was a Monday. Jan. 1, 2000, will be a Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In checking your vulnerability quotient, look at three basic
areas to see if your equipment and software (particularly
date-reliant programs such as accounting and spreadsheet programs)
can display a four-digit year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hardware: More than 90 percent of PCs with a basic input-out
system (BIOS) built before 1996 are not Y2K compliant. That
non-compliance drops to only about 10 percent of those built from
1998 to now. To find out if yours is a bad one, match your PC's
model number and BIOS version (as listed in your owner's setup
manual) with the Y2K compliance list the manufacturer will have on
its Web site. You should be able to obtain BIOS upgrades from the
PC maker.
</P>
<P>
   You can get free utilities for checking your PC from
http://inflorida.net/y2k/download.htm, a good Web page with plenty
of site names and direct links.
</P>
<P>
   _ Software: Y2K compliance can be a problem with both Macintosh
and PCs. In a massive effort to keep from alienating the market,
most major software companies already have issued upgrades or
patches to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest problems, however, may be with freeware or
shareware. Those, for the most part, are programs created by
independent programmers and distributed for free or at minimal
charge over the Internet. They are so varied it's a virtual
certainty many of them will go haywire. But for mainstream
``store-bought'' programs, contact the software company for
compliance information if you haven't yet seen a fix being issued.
</P>
<P>
   _ Operating Systems: The Mac systems are OK. Microsoft has a
variety of operating systems: MS-DOS, Windows 3.x, Windows 95,
Windows 98, Windows NT. Compliance varies.
</P>
<P>
   Win 3.x and Win 95 require fixes or patches. Users of MS-DOS
will have to set the systems for a four-digit year display. How you
do it will vary from one PC manufacturer to another; some will let
you access it through ``tools,'' some through ``date and time'' in
the control panel _ check your user's manual. (When you do that,
the date may look garbled for Windows 3.1, 3.1.1 or 95 users.
That's only cosmetic; you can download a patch from the Microsoft
Web site to fix it.)
</P>
<P>
   Even if you have Win 98, there could be a problem. Microsoft has
already released a patch for it because of a garble problem that
may not affect data but can make some operations confusing. You can
download a patch from the Web site
(http://www.microsoft.com/ms.htm) or order a free CD (with a 4- to
6-week wait) by calling 800-363-2896.
</P>
</TEXT>
