<HEADLINE>
HIKING THE ADIRONDACKS, PEAK BY PEAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADIRONDACKS PARK, N.Y. _ Few hikers ever attempt Blue Ridge in
the Central Adirondacks, a 3,820-foot mound that requires a
bushwhack of several miles. After ducking under fallen trees,
crossing a muddy marsh and then climbing 500 feet of steep woods,
hikers find slim reward: a stand of trees so thick as to almost
obscure the sky.
</P>
<P>
   But on a recent sunny Sunday, Al Peters, his wife Joan and their
friend Walt Hayes set out on the 8-mile journey. The reason: Blue
Ridge is number 56 of the 100 highest peaks in the Adirondacks, and
the three are trying to climb them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really do it for sense of accomplishment,'' Peters, who is
from Charlton, said before starting out. ``There's almost never any
reward, in terms of a view.''
</P>
<P>
   For an increasing number of people, just heading into the woods
isn't enough. Better, it seems, to have a list to complete,
something to tick off after a hard day's journey.
</P>
<P>
   What began in the 1920s with the 46ers _ people who have climbed
the 46 High Peaks of the Adirondacks, all over 4,000 feet in
elevation _ has expanded around the Adirondacks, New York, New
England and, depending on climbers' skills, the world. (Several of
the peaks have been determined to actually be below 4,000 feet, but
remain on the list for historical reasons.)
</P>
<P>
   In the Adirondacks, beyond the 46ers, there are the winter
46ers, those who have climbed the 100 highest and the fire tower
peaks _ mountains that have or at one time had fire towers on the
summit. One group is climbing every peak surveyed by Verplanck
Colvin, who measured the height of hundreds of mountains in the
late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   Some put their own spin on hiking, like the man who is currently
doing the 46 barefoot. Others are legendary. Fred Hunt, a retired
college professor now living in Vermont, has climbed all 46 peaks
at night, and, in the early 1970s, during every month of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way to keep me from going mad when the four walls
began to close in on me,'' said Hunt, now 75, who was known as
``Cat Eyes'' and ``Moonlight Mountaineer.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's John E. Winkler, who bushwhacked up all 46 peaks
from the late 1970s to the early '80s after climbing them on the
normal routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kinda complicated,'' said Winkler, author of two books
about the Adirondacks. ``But it was a good thing. As far as I know,
I'm the only person who's ever done it.''
</P>
<P>
   This nature-by-numbers approach has some hikers shaking their
heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hike for lists,'' said 67-year-old Barbara McMartin,
author of the 11-book ``Discover the Adirondacks'' series, who
purposely never became a 46er because some of the mountains have no
views.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-increasing popularity of such lists as the 46 worries
some. The number of those who have climbed the High Peaks 46 has
nearly doubled in 10 years, from 2,582 in 1988 to 4,447 in 1992,
according to the Adirondack 46ers, hikers who volunteer to keep
track of such things. And the number of hikers who visited the area
doubled as well in that time, to 140,000.
</P>
<P>
   So many hikers flock to the 46 that the state last month adopted
new rules for the area.
</P>
<P>
   The High Peaks Unit Management Plan limits group size and the
number of cars parked at various trailheads. It also approves, for
the first time, the marking of routes up ``trailless peaks.'' Such
peaks had numerous ``herd'' paths carved by hikers trying to find
the best route to the top. Beginning this summer, volunteers will
flag the correct route and block off false paths to keep erosion to
a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind the idea of climbing all 46
peaks is motivation for some people to climb mountains,'' said Stu
Buchanan, director of Region 5 of the New York Department of
Environmental Conservation. ``Our hope is to get some control on
visitor use in the High Peaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter the relatively new lists, like the Adirondacks 100.
Meeting that goal is a reason for hikers to get away from the High
Peaks, and visit mountains few have even heard of. And that's a
good thing, some say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 46 are just too popular,'' said Jack Freeman, an avid
hiker and spokesman for the Adirondack Mountain Club. ``There are a
lot of unused areas, outside the High Peaks. We wish people would
really explore and discover these nice, wild areas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Adirondacks were at first ignored by New York state and then
exploited for its timber and iron ore in the late 1800s. In the
tail end of that century, the peaks were first climbed by surveyors
and mountain guides taking rich tourists on hikes into the
backcountry.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until the 1920s that hikers thought of completing the
challenge of summiting all 46 peaks.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1930s, members of a church organized the first group
dedicated to climbing the 46. A few years later, the club ``Troy
46ers'' was born. By the end of World War II, more than 40 people
had completed the 46.
</P>
<P>
   Trails have improved much since those days, as has technology
useful for bushwhacking.
</P>
<P>
   The Peters and Hayes, who is from Glenville, never head off
trail without taking a satellite-based Global Positioning System
unit with them. Using the cellular-phone-sized piece of equipment
and a topographic map, bushwhackers can find their position
anywhere on the globe, down to a few hundred feet.
</P>
<P>
   While GPS has made it easier for hikers to find their way to the
right peak, hiking off-the-beaten-track mountains like the
trailless Adirondack 100 will always be an adventure. Al Peters
discovered that firsthand last fall, when he took a tumble two
miles from the road and dislocated his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Five hours after starting out, Hayes, Peters and his wife
reached the flat summit of Blue Ridge. With some difficulty, they
found a summit marker, a plastic peanut-butter jar left in 1992.
Inside was a tiny log, which included the names of fewer than 10
visitors who have arrived since then.
</P>
<P>
   On the peak, the trees were so thick that when the three walked
a few yards to the side of the mountain to search for a view, it
took them 10 minutes to retrace their steps to the top. Mosquitoes
and several types of biting flies swarmed by the hundreds, landing
on backpacks and the hikers' hair. Peters and his wife quickly
donned headnets. Hayes just brushed them away.
</P>
<P>
   Peters and his wife have 21 peaks left to do. Hayes has 22, and
he's already planning what he'll do next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep climbing,'' he said. ``I've got a list of
150 more peaks I'd like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters is more pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this,'' he said, ``we're gonna do fun things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
