<SLUG> BC-GAY-MOVIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY FILM FESTIVAL OPENS IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There's a host of things scheduled to happen
during the 10 days of the 23rd Lesbian and Gay Film Festival, which
runs June 17-27 at the Castro, the Roxie and the Victoria theaters
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Breakups. Breakdowns. Break-ins. Breakthroughs. Cloudbreak,
heartbreak, broken skin, broken records, broken bones. But only one
image breaks like the dawn.
</P>
<P>
   It's a smile _ one of the truest, most sincere expressions of
joy you'll ever see _ and it belongs to Christian Campbell who
stars in ``trick,'' Jim Fall's opening-night feature, Thursday at
the Castro. It's a great way to jump-start a festival, particularly
one accentuating the positive, exhilarating aspects of an
international lesbian-gay cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Fall's debut is a wholly conventional boy-meets boy,
boy-looks-for-place-to-shag-boy love story with an assortment of
robust caricatures trying to abet and deter Campbell's love-struck
showtune composer from getting it on with a go-go stripper (John
Paul Pitoc), including an interestingly human Tori Spelling who
wanders out of self-parody and into a performance as Campbell's
self-obsessed pal. But alas it's that blazing smile that could make
the sun jealous and captures the contagious ecstasy of a
reciprocated crush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trick'' is but one of an overwhelming number of films feasting
on gays, lesbians and bisexuals way below a certain age.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's sophisticated, excited ``Show Me Love'' (June 27,
Castro), which closes the festival, takes its title from Nordic
soulthang Robyn's demand that she be shown ``what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely what high-schooler Agnes (Rebecca Liljeberg)
does for punky, prissy fellow pupil Elin (Alexandra Dahlstrom), who
equates being a lesbian with choosing a major. The film has that
shot-on-Hi-8, Dogma '95 look that a handful of Danish filmmakers
are crazy about that says you-are-there, and when the girls have
their sweet first kiss to a Foreigner tune you're kinda glad you
were there _ to chaperon, of course.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine days between opening and closing night, young gay
hormones are raging in films like the Canadian ``Better Than
Chocolate'' (Friday, Castro) and Spain's ``Don't Tell Anyone''
(June 26, Castro) with the reckless facility of their straight
teen-age peers.
</P>
<P>
   You know being young and gay (or at least ``bi'') has gotten
out-of-control hot when none other than Jonathan ``JTT'' Taylor
Thomas makes a few home improvements of his own when he dims his
sunshine act to play a hustler in the occasionally surging
``Speedway Junky'' (June 22, Castro). But in this comprehensive,
masterfully programmed festival, nearly every sexual experience is
substantially represented, and there are plenty of offerings from
filmmakers of color.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to rally around the festival's youth bent, perhaps
because it signals some gradual normalization or acceptance that
begins between classes in high school. Still, there's an impressive
array of films either about or featuring a wiser, less
reckless-and-charged perspective (if not in age, then in
experience) _ from ``Living With Pride'' (June 25, Victoria), about
centenarian activist Ruth C. Ellis, to the poignant double bill of
``Golden Threads'' and ``I Know a Place'' (Sunday, Victoria).
</P>
<P>
   All three films, plus several others _ including the torpid,
inert ``Beloved/ Friend'' from Spain _ assert a more vital place in
the lesbian-gay spectrum than condescending ``twilight-years''
retrospection.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous films in the festival line-up handle sexuality with
care, just as others simply revel in sensation. But AIDS is rarely,
if ever, used as a narrative subject or a plot point.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the features or the programmed shorts would
purport to be post-AIDS or HIV, taken as a whole they also manage
to take homosexuality into more fantastic, experimental,
transcendent realms that refuse to give in to the disease and would
rather be spooked by more cinematic (or literary) ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   But when sex isn't enough, or when it gets old _ as it
intermittently does throughout the non-stop,
must-be-seen-to-be-believed British soap party ``Queer as Folk''
(June 21-24, Victoria), for example _ there's love. The plausible
kind.
</P>
<P>
   Nisha Gantara's dismally titled, wonderful to watch ``Chutney
Popcorn'' (June 25, Castro), about a New Yorker who upsets her
girlfriend by agreeing to have her infertile sister's baby, has a
likable ease _ while entertaining the suspicion that love may be as
temporarily beautiful as the henna tattoos its conflicted Indian
paints on anonymous bodies. It also touches on the dilemma of being
an Indian lesbian with a white girlfriend and stubborn mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Popcorn'' highlights the upside of establishing an indie-rock,
sitcommish rapport between characters and contains some of the
freshest throwaway retorts you'll hear. (``Oh please. That
bi-phobia thing is so '95!'')
</P>
<P>
   Gantara also offers the comic realization that the border
distinguishing heterosexual values and relationship traits from
homosexual ones has begun to erode as if the difference had been a
construct all along. That suspicion is expressed in a surprising
number of films that don't warp genders so much as they question
the very idea of a single orientation.
</P>
<P>
   If Monica Treut's film ``Gendernauts'' (Sunday, Castro) looks
into the elimination of gender, then Rose Troche's quizzical, funny
``Bedrooms and Hallways'' (Saturday, Castro), manages to make a
quiet farce of the malleability of sexual orientation when love is
the drug and not the libido.
</P>
<P>
   For non-white members of the gay community, finding any visual
representation is a challenge that not even the progressiveness of
a grown-up gay cinema has done much to enhance.
</P>
<P>
   A series of panels and programs will seek to address those
concerns while bellowing a heartfelt shout-out to the late Marlon
Riggs _ whose ``Tongues Untied'' (Sunday, Castro) turns 10 years
old _ and bestowing the Frameline Award for ``outstanding
achievement in lesbian and gay media arts'' (Sunday, Castro).
</P>
</TEXT>
