<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7415 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FATHERSDAY-RECIP     06-16 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FATHERSDAY-RECIPES1STTAKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Game for something good? Try low-fat meats
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Game tastes good, hasn't been commercially available in 100
years and is nutritionally impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Cookbook author Janie Hibler says these reasons are driving a
resurgence in game cooking that is bringing game into supermarkets
and has helped sell 20,000 copies of her James Beard Award-winning
book ``Wild About Game'' (Broadway, $30).
</P>
<P>
   While promoting the book, Hibler said she found two kinds of
game eaters: Those who grew up eating wild game and now prefer its
stronger taste; and people just being introduced to game, who
should start with the milder taste of farm-raised meat from New
Zealand or America.
</P>
<P>
   Besides taste, the main difference between domestic meats and
game is fat content.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fat in domestic meat is marbled and in game it's around
the muscle. That's why, when you buy game, you won't see any fat or
if you do it's only on the outside,'' Hibler said.
</P>
<P>
   That means game cooks quickly.
</P>
<P>
   And even though their nutritional profiles may beat those of
traditional red meats, bison, venison and ostrich are treated like
any other lean red meats by the American Heart Association. It
recommends adults should eat no more than three 3-ounce cooked
portions a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red meat is a healthy part of an adult's diet, and it should
be the complementary part of the meal, not the main part,'' says
Leslie Stewart, nutrition educator for the Fuqua Heart Center at
Piedmont Hospital and spokeswoman for the AHA.
</P>
<P>
   What game meats offer is a healthy alternative _ a way to stick
with red meats while shaking up menus in restaurants and at home.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're game for cooking game, try one of the recipes below
from local chefs who created them with you in mind.
</P>
<P>
   BISON FACTS
</P>
<P>
   It's rich _ not gamey _ lean and sturdy, best served pink in the
middle. Canadian Vern Jackson, who once organized a traveling bison
barbecue, is quoted in the book ``Barbecue America'' as saying
bison tastes like beef wishes it did.
</P>
<P>
   If you can cook beef, you can cook bison, insists Richard
Lindamood, chef at Buckhead Beef.
</P>
<P>
   To enjoy bison for the first time, keep it simple and don't
overcook it. This meat is often so lean it will dry out easily if
cooked too long. A bison steak the same size as a beef steak will
cook far more quickly, because the additional fat in the beef acts
as insulation. Because bison is denser, it will fill you up more
quickly, too.
</P>
<P>
   The National Bison Association recommends these grilling or
broiling ideas for steaks and ground bison:
</P>
<P>
   Grilled bison steak: Rub a 6-ounce cut (1 inch thick) with a bit
of garlic salt, cooking oil and lemon pepper. Grill 4 to 6 inches
above medium-hot coals 6 to 8 minutes for rare or 8 to 10 minutes
for medium.
</P>
<P>
   Bison burger: To make 4, shape 1 pound of lean ground bison into
four 1/2-inch-thick patties. Grill, covered, 4 to 6 inches above
medium-hot coals, turning once. (U.S. Bison recommends cooking to
160 degrees, the same temperature recommended for beef, but
recognizes that may be too well-done.) Season with salt and pepper
to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Bison franks: Hot dogs, just like those served at Turner Field,
will soon be available at Publix markets in the Atlanta area. Grill
as you would any hot dog _ until heated through.
</P>
<P>
   VENISON FACTS
</P>
<P>
   The USDA recommends cooking to 160 degrees, but recognizes
``tenderness issues'' and says cuts like racks, steaks, chops and
roasts may be cooked to 145 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Several cuts of fresh venison are available at Harry's Farmers
Market in Alpharetta, Whole Foods Market, Harris Teeter and other
well-stocked supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   OSTRICH FACTS
</P>
<P>
   Ostrich meat is so low in fat (see chart), it's becoming popular
for athletes in training and fitness enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Because all the meat comes from thigh muscles, some cuts don't
look like traditional red meat cuts. For that reason, you should
always buy from a reliable source.
</P>
<P>
   The only trick is remembering that they are very lean and should
cook very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Ostrich, fresh or frozen, is available in many major
supermarkets including Harris Teeter, Harry's Farmers Markets and
Whole Foods. For more information, contact the American Ostrich
Association, 817-232-1200. E-mail aoa(at)flash.net; ask for meat
suppliers' list or restaurant and market list.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   For any particular cut, it's best to call your market first to
see if it's in stock. If not, many will order for you from Buckhead
Beef for delivery the next business day. Or search the Web. Most
kinds and cuts of game are available fresh with one- or two-day
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Mail delivery is available from Broadleaf Venison,
1-800-336-3844, Ext. 101; D'Artagnan, www.dartagnan.com; and
Seattle's Finest, www.exoticmeats.com.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Ostrich Panang
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Served with a pot of rice, this recipe from Thai Chili chef
Robert Khankiew makes a full meal. If you can't get fresh ostrich
steaks, you can use frozen filets. Remember to cook quickly and
slice thinly.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ostrich steaks, cut in 4-ounce portions
</P>
<P>
   14 ounces coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons panang curry paste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped Kaffir lime leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup roughly chopped sweet basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Grill ostrich steaks over medium-high heat until medium-rare.
Slice meat thinly, as with London broil, and serve on top of sauce.
Garnish with basil leaves.
</P>
<P>
   To make the sauce: Heat a saucepan or wok over high heat until
it is nearly smoking. Dip the solidified coconut milk off the top
of the can and toss in skillet, stirring constantly. Add the panang
curry paste, and continue stirring to combine. Reduce heat to
medium, and cook about 5 minutes. Slowly add the remainder of the
coconut milk; then the fish sauce and sugar. Stir well. Cook until
sauce thickens, about 10 to 15 minutes; add the Kaffir lime leaves
and cook 2 to 3 minutes. Taste and adjust seasonings, adding salt,
sugar, fish sauce or curry paste to taste (more curry paste will
make it spicier).
</P>
<P>
   When you're ready to serve, toss basil leaves into sauce, remove
from heat and stir.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 670 calories, 31 grams protein, 30 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 69 grams carbohydrates, 59
milligrams cholesterol, 515 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Red Chile Grilled Cervena Skewers With Parmesan
</P>
<P>
   Cabbage Slaw
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 main-dish or 8 appetizer servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 to 4 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Rathbun, chef at Nava, adds a Southwestern-inspired spice
rub to pretty skewers of sliced venison and serves them with shaved
cabbage slaw.
</P>
<P>
   For the venison:
</P>
<P>
   24 10-inch wooden skewers (water soaked)
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds venison leg meat, cut in 2-by-6-by- 1/4-inch strips,
approximately
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   For the barbecue spice:
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   For the slaw:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound red or white shaved cabbage (or combination)
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion, shaved thin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   For the venison: Preheat grill to high. Weave venison portions
onto skewers. Lightly oil, then generously coat meat with barbecue
spice. Grill about 1 minute on a side or until done. Do not
overcook. Serve with the Parmesan slaw.
</P>
<P>
   For the spice: In a small bowl, combine cayenne, sugar, chili
powder, paprika, garlic powder, thyme, salt, pepper and cumin.
</P>
<P>
   For the slaw: In a large bowl, combine cabbage, onion, oil,
vinegar, sugar, cilantro, salt, lime juice and cheese. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per main-dish serving: 422 calories, 48 grams protein, 20 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 42), 12 grams carbohydrates, 170
milligrams cholesterol, 991 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
