<HEADER>
A7416 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FATHERSDAY-RECIP     06-16 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FATHERSDAY-RECIPES2NDTAKE </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Mustard Seed Grilled Bison Filet
</P>
<P>
   With Mango-Orange Vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 15
minutes Also a consultant for U.S. Bison, Kevin Rathbun developed
this easy recipe for backyard grilling. Try to save as much of the
seeded rub as possible from falling through the grill _ it adds a
crunchy bite to the tender filet. For more heat, add extra jalapeno
pepper to the rub. It will be well-balanced by the sweet-sour
Mango-Orange Vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   4 (6-ounce) bison filets
</P>
<P>
   For the mustard rub:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons yellow mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons whole coriander seeds, cracked
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons dried cumin powder
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons paprika, ground
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons ginger powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   For the vinegar:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh mango, peeled and chunked
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup distilled vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   Cut bison into portions and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   For the mustard rub: Place all ingredients in a food processor.
Pulse until well-macerated but not completely smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Coat bison medallions generously with spice mixture and let
marinate in refrigerator for 1 to 2 hours until ready to grill. (Do
not marinate too long, as the salt in the rub will draw out too
much moisture.)
</P>
<P>
   Prepare grill to medium heat. Grill bison to desired
temperature, preferably medium-rare or 145 degrees. This will take
5 to 7 minutes per side, depending on thickness of the filets.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mango-Orange Vinegar: Place all ingredients in a small
pot over medium-high heat and bring to a boil. Transfer to a
blender and blend until smooth. Serve 2 tablespoons sauce with each
portion of steak.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with vinegar): 359 calories, 36 grams protein, 13
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 33), 26 grams carbohydrates,
93 milligrams cholesterol, 959 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Horseradish Bison Burger
</P>
<P>
   With Black Pepper Boursin Cheese
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time:
about 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's best to add fat to lean game, but Kevin Rathbun
adds only an egg as a binder here. If you overcook this burger, it
will crumble. After three attempts, our best advice is to measure
carefully, take extra care to turn them only once on the grill and
remove them when medium-rare. If you want them cooked further for
those who like their burgers brown, try heating for a minute in the
microwave. It worked for us.
</P>
<P>
   For the burgers:
</P>
<P>
   24 ounces ground bison
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons prepared horseradish
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons ketchup
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon green Tabasco
</P>
<P>
   1 small egg
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   For assembly:
</P>
<P>
   4 sourdough buns
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1 tomato, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1 package black pepper boursin cheese (see note)
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix bison, horseradish, ketchup, garlic, green
Tabasco, egg, salt and pepper. Separate into 4 equal portions of 6
ounces each. Lightly oil burgers to prevent sticking on grill. Heat
grill to medium-hot. Grill bison burgers on both sides to desired
temperature, medium-rare or medium. This will take 5 to 6 minutes
per side. Warm boursin cheese in microwave or place on top of
burgers for 1 minute or until warm. Serve on buns with onion and
tomato.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Boursin cheese is available in supermarkets with
well-stocked cheese departments. If you have trouble finding it, a
good substitute is Alouette with garlic and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without boursin cheese): 399 calories, 40 grams
protein, 10 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 22), 36 grams
carbohydrates, 173 milligrams cholesterol, 1,351 milligrams sodium,
2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue Cervena Venison Rack 'n' Fiery Crust With Sweet Potato
Hash and Wild Blueberry Barbecue Glaze
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 1 1/4 hours Cooking time:
45-55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lindamood, chef at Buckhead Beef, offers this recipe for
beginning game cooks. He says if you can cook a rack of lamb, you
can cook a rack of venison. Don't let the long list of ingredients
put you off _ it's worth every step.
</P>
<P>
   1 venison rack (8 bones, about 3 1/2 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   For the sweet potato hash:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 large sweet potatoes, peeled and cut in 1/2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 large Vidalia onion, peeled and cut in 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   2 large portobello mushrooms, trimmed and cut in 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   For the sauce:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 large poblano pepper, cored and seeded
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup wild or cultivated blueberries
</P>
<P>
   1 large lemon
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to high and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Open the
Cervena rack package and let rest 10 minutes. With a very sharp
knife, remove silverskin from meat. Mix pepper, coriander, chili
powder, cumin, cayenne, salt and thyme in a small bowl. Heat grill
to high, rub rack with olive oil and coat with seasoning mix. Cover
bones with aluminum foil. On hot grill, sear meat well on all
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Remove rack from grill and place in roasting pan in oven for 15
to 20 minutes. Remove and let rest.
</P>
<P>
   For the sweet potato hash: Heat saute pan to medium-high and add
olive oil. When hot, add sweet potatoes. Stir frequently until
golden brown, then add onions and mushrooms. Cook 4 to 5 minutes.
Season with salt, pepper and cilantro. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   For the sauce: Heat olive oil in saute pan. Add onions, garlic
and poblano pepper. Cook slightly, then add spices and brown sugar
and caramelize. Place ingredients in a blender and add ketchup,
honey, vinegar, blueberries and juice from lemon. Blend until
smooth; adjust seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Slice one chop and add one without bone. Place hash
in center of plate. Place venison on top, drizzle sauce around and
garnish with fresh herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 719 calories, 45 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 32), 82 grams carbohydrates, 144
milligrams cholesterol, 1,830 milligrams sodium, 7 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
