<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7417 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FATHERSDAY17-COX     06-16 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FATHERSDAY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will home cooks sink teeth into ostrich, bison and venison?
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Listen.
</P>
<P>
   That rumble is a herd gathering from the far reaches of Montana
and Utah, New Zealand and Arkansas, and it's headed straight for
your supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Fitted with marketing campaigns touting their hearty red-meat
taste yet remarkably low fat content, once exotic-sounding products
like bison, ostrich and venison are poised to stake a substantial
claim on the American dinner plate.
</P>
<P>
   Farm-raised to tame their wild reputations, these game meats
already have won the hearts of restaurant chefs _ from the top of
the Atlanta Hilton at ultra-plush Nikolai's Roof, where ostrich is
cooked with dried dates and served alongside yucca root puree and
poached leeks, to the ground floor of CNN Center, where at sports
bar Jocks &AMP; Jills you can opt for bison burgers instead of chicken
wings with your beer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the time has come to see whether home cooks will bite. And
just in time for Father's Day _ providing a healthier way for Dad
to have his steak and eat it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the fledgling company U.S. Bison enters the big leagues
as 64 area Publix supermarkets begin selling its fresh ground
bison. And bison franks, the kind previously available only by
special order or on a game day at Turner Field, will appear in the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Bison products from other suppliers are available sporadically,
but this is a first on such a scale. The company Ted Turner founded
in 1997, that's headed by son R.E. ``Teddy'' Turner IV, moves into
the supermarket arena with products from North American Bison
Cooperative, with access to the senior Turner's 15,000 bison and
the herds of other members.
</P>
<P>
   Many Braves fans have already sampled a bison frank at a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a very popular item and draws a lot of
attention,'' Braves vice president and director of marketing and
broadcasting Wayne Long said.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Atlanta, U.S. Bison also has signed the services of
well-known Atlanta chef Kevin Rathbun of Nava to develop recipes
and offer culinary advice to chefs and home cooks on using the
unfamiliar products.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just bison closing in _ there's venison and
ostrich, too, each offering a different taste of red meat, all with
fewer calories, far less fat and, often, less cholesterol and more
nutrients than beef. They may still sound exotic _ but then, so did
kiwi fruit a couple of decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful that health-conscious Americans are
being encouraged to raise these leaner meats and give us more
options,'' says Kathleen Zelman, Marietta dietitian and spokeswoman
for the American Dietetic Association.
</P>
<P>
   The nutritional numbers sound too good to be true: A 4-ounce
serving of ostrich, for example, has 112 calories and 1 gram of
fat; the same size serving of bison has 124 calories and 2 grams of
fat. Compare that to a similar beef tenderloin serving, which
weighs in with 179 calories and 8 1/2 grams of fat.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy numbers, though, may not be enough to convince us to
shell out $15 or more for a 1-pound package. It has to taste good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to see it become more readily available to the
public. The fact that it's also incredibly delicious, that's what's
exciting,'' says Janie Hibler, author of ``Wild About Game''
(Broadway, $30), a James Beard single-subject award winner
published in October that has already sold 20,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   But folks want to know what it tastes like before they attempt
to cook it, says Kirk Halpern, chief operating officer at Buckhead
Beef, which supplies game in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   And restaurants aren't the only ones offering a sample. Even the
World Wrestling Federation has jumped in, signing its name over to
a new ostrich meat snack stick to be available to a mass market in
August.
</P>
<P>
   After restaurant introduction, the usual route is to magazine
stories, Halpern said. That, too, is happening. The December issue
of Saveur included a major story on venison, the April edition of
Cucina Italiana featured ostrich, and bison recipes roam the pages
of the current Food &AMP; Wine.
</P>
<P>
   If the marketing doesn't fizzle, as it did with buffalo a decade
ago, ``somewhere in the next few years these three will be
everywhere in retail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So what does it taste like? Well, for once, not chicken. Even
ostrich _ the only bird in the group _ is considered a red meat.
Ostrich Panang is the current ``healthy alternative'' chef Robert
Khankiew rotates on his menu every few months at Thai Chili. It has
all the substance and even the look of London broil served with a
highly spiced curry sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like it very much,'' Khankiew said, adding he sells at
least 10 orders a day.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's a bird, ostrich is the most often misunderstood of
the lot. The meat comes from the animal's thigh area, and cuts do
not correspond to either poultry or livestock cuts. That makes it
the most difficult of the three for home cooks to buy and prepare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may seem the most intimidating because it seems so
foreign,'' Hibler said. There are simple cooking techniques, she
added, that can be applied for all game:
</P>
<P>
   ``Either cook it hot and fast or slow and low. The way you know
which is the most tender meat _ farthest away from the antlers and
hooves like the backstrap or chops or steaks _ would be hot and
fast like grilling or sauteeing; and the tougher cuts _ the
shoulder, neck and shank _ need slow and low braising and
stewing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ostrich, except when ground, falls into the hot and fast
category, she said. It contains so little fat, which acts as an
insulator, that cooking time is reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Even chefs who know something about the product still sometimes
have a hard time finding what they need, but suppliers are picking
up on the weak spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to visit purveyors and taste new things,'' Louis Spost,
executive chef for the Atlanta Hilton, said. Last week he attended
a show on international food concepts and found a supplier offering
to sell just an ostrich cut called the fan, one that many chefs
agree is the most tender. ``A lot of times you have to buy a pack
with different cuts, and a lot of chefs don't like that,'' Spost
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bison and venison will be more familiar to home cooks, though,
because a bison filet looks like a beef filet and a strip steak is
a strip steak. ``Anyone who's cooked a rack of lamb can cook a rack
of venison,'' insists Richard Lindamood, chef at Buckhead Beef,
which sells fresh Cervena venison from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   The big secret? Don't overcook.
</P>
<P>
   After working with bison, venison and other game, Spost has
altered his technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago most chefs were taught to sear meats at high
temperatures until they were crusted on the outside. Now chefs are
learning to cook slower, so it's not so rare in the middle like a
bull's eye,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For him, and most chefs, optimum is medium-rare.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA Meat &AMP; Poultry Hotline recommends cooking ostrich
roasts, steaks and chops to at least an internal temperature of 145
for medium-rare. For venison and bison, the official recommendation
is to cook to at least 160 degrees. Even so, Bessie Berry with the
hotline office said there are some ``tenderness issues'' with large
cuts and in those cases 145 degrees is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Still other chefs prefer leaving the red meats redder but will
honor diners' preferences, Spost said.
</P>
<P>
   Buckhead Beef's Halpern points out that the safety concerns with
rare steak are minimal. ``Bacteria is on the outside, so when you
throw that steak on the grill, that temperature will kill the
bacteria. Where you run into problems is with ground products.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansell Roddenberry, president and CEO at U.S. Bison, has
quickly become the Bisonic Man _ eagerly working with chefs until
he is satisfied the product is being handled safely and can be
offered medium-rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found the product basically speaks for itself, but with
it being as lean as it is, it requires proper preparation. In other
words, it really does not need to be overcooked,'' Roddenberry
stresses.
</P>
<P>
   Could Bisonburger Helper be in our future?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
