<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Different icebox pie at least is cool treat
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Both Betty Marion and Kevin Owens e-mailed this easy
icebox pie in response to Sally Angevine's request for something
like lemon and chocolate icebox pies served at the former Char
House in Sandy Springs (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   The day her request was published, Angevine called to say that a
man whose family had owned the restaurant called her to say that
while he wouldn't divulge any recipes, he would make her a pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if anybody sends in a recipe, I would love for you to
publish it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This pie, which can be chilled several hours or frozen, is
undoubtedly not like the restaurant's. But it is quick, easy and
satisfying _ if you're a fan of whipped topping.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, we're still looking.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Lemon
</P>
<P>
   (or Lime)
</P>
<P>
   Icebox Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: several hours to overnight
</P>
<P>
   1(14-ounce) can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   1(6-ounce) can frozen limeade or lemonade, thawed slightly
</P>
<P>
   1(8-ounce) container whipped dairy topping, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1pastry shell or graham cracker crust, baked
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, combine condensed milk, lemonade or
limeade and dairy topping. Mix well. Pour into baked pie shell.
Chill several hours to overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 417 calories, 6 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 41), 57 grams carbohydrates, 17
milligrams cholesterol, 158 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe request
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Donna Murphy's e-mailed request is for a beer cheese soup that
was served with hot garlic bread in a Smyrna restaurant called
Caperni's in the mid-'80s. The restaurant is gone, but the memory
of that soup lingers.
</P>
