<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7423 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-HNS &LR;      06-16 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OTHER DEMOCRATIC CANDIDATE COURTS VOTERS IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While Vice President Al Gore launched his
presidential campaign Wednesday from his hometown in Tennessee, his
rival for the Democratic nomination was in California trying to get
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, the former New Jersey senator and New York Knicks
basketball star, is using a 10-day trip through California to draw
attention to his uphill bid for the Democratic Party's presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore holds a strong edge in early polling. The most recent
Time/CNN poll showed that 71 percent of Democrats expect Gore to be
their nominee, while 13 percent said Bradley would win the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the nomination is Al Gore's to lose,'' said
Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political analyst in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley has a strategy he believes could upset the vice
president: connecting one-on-one with Democratic voters in an
empathetic style reminiscent of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was in San Francisco on Tuesday talking to two groups
that traditionally have been Democratic stalwarts _
environmentalists and advocates of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does anyone have a particular story they want to share with
me?'' Bradley asked a dozen staff members at Planned Parenthood in
San Francisco Tuesday afternoon, an event where reporters and
photographers outnumbered participants.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a circle of chairs next to his wife, Ernestine, the
6-foot-5-inch former senator listened as Planned Parenthood staff
members told of almost daily protests by anti-abortion rights
activists outside their clinics, threats of violence against
doctors and lawsuits filed against employees for alleged civil
rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``So basically what you're facing are multiple levels of
assault,'' said Bradley, a supporter of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   He used a similar approach in a morning session with
environmentalists on how to divide California's limited water
supply between competing factions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are your thoughts?'' he asked a larger circle of three
dozen, mostly members of local conservation groups who were invited
to the event.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley largely avoided bashing the vice president. Pressed by
reporters on what made him different from Gore, Bradley would say
only that he had ``a more varied life experience'' than the vice
president, who has spent most of his career in government in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed to a difference in leadership style. While the
two men were in the Senate, Bradley said he tackled the
controversial issues of tax reform and international trade. Gore,
he said, ``has been more cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   The perception that Gore, 51, has been stumbling as he launches
his campaign has helped Bradley, Jeffe said. But while Bradley, 55,
has a ``celebrity aura,'' he cannot match the vice president's
party ties and prodigious fund-raising ability, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley to win the nomination, Jeffe said, it would take ``a
really dramatic stumble on the part of Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Gregory, a board member of the Save San Francisco Bay
Association, said she would be pleased with either of the two
Democrats as the party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both strong on the environment,'' Gregory said. ``It's
a tough one.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates will be in California on Friday, and will be
plowing similar thematic ground.
</P>
<P>
   Gore flies to Los Angeles that morning for a summit on guns and
school violence at a high school gym. Bradley will be in San
Francisco that day for speeches, also addressing guns and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley represented New Jersey in the Senate for three terms,
from 1979 to 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
