u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CAMBY-DUNCAN-BOS &LR;      06-16 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CAMBY-DUNCAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE AT STAKE THAN EVER FOR DUNCAN, CAMBY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want to know about the most intriguing matchup in the NBA
Finals? Ask John Calipari. Surely the former New Jersey Nets and
University of Massachusetts coach won't be a casual observer when
the New York Knicks meet the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Not when you consider that he coached budding Knicks star Marcus
Camby in college and helped him prepare to face then-Wake Forest
star Tim Duncan in a Dec. 5, 1995, contest that was one of the most
eagerly anticipated big-man matchups in college basketball history.
</P>
<P>
   That game showcased what many figured to be the future of the
NBA post game. And here they are, meeting in the Finals. Calipari,
who also coached against both players while he was with New Jersey,
is not surprised that they meet again with basketball's biggest
prize on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Duncan is one of the best strong-side players in the
game,'' said Calipari. ``He is the kind of player you get the ball
to and he scores and he blocks shots at the other end and makes
everyone around him better. He is better on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus is better off the ball. I thought the last two years in
the NBA that Dennis Rodman was the best weak-side player. When it
came to rebounding, defense, scoring, he was ridiculous. But now
he's gone, and now Marcus Camby is the best weak-side player in the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Knicks ran no plays to him and he had 36 points against
Indiana last week. Everything the Pacers did, they had to keep
looking around, going, `Where's Camby?' The Knicks were getting
their butts handed to them by Indiana, and then Marcus would come
in and the Pacers started getting their butts handed to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Question is, who will have the upper hand? Back in 1995, Camby
emerged the victor. Bolstered by a partisan sellout crowd at
Amherst, he led the third-ranked Minutemen to a 60-46 victory over
10-ranked Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   It was billed as the biggest big-man matchup in the regular
season since Virginia's Ralph Sampson faced Georgetown's Patrick
Ewing on Dec. 11, 1982.
</P>
<P>
   According to UMass players, Camby downplayed the matchup, at
least on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he was excited to play against Tim Duncan, but he just
was telling guys to just go out there and play and not feeling any
pressure,'' said former UMass forward Donta Bright, who was the
game's leading scorer with 22 points. ``He didn't worry about the
matchup between him and Duncan. He just went out there and let
everyone judge for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   While Camby might have been telling his teammates it was just
another game, he didn't approach it that way, according to
Calipari.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he prepared for that game well,'' said Calipari. ``He
knew how important it was for him to play well against Duncan.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither player was spectacular. Duncan scored 9 points on
4-of-18 shooting from the floor, though he did grab 12 rebounds and
block 4 shots, and even sank a trey. But he struggled in the one
area many people were wondering about before the game: intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for Camby. Though he wasn't much better numberswise (17
points on 6-for-19 shooting, 9 boards, 3 blocks), he was emotional
and energetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I remember, Camby played with more bounce _ his legs were
more alive,'' said Wake Forest coach Dave Odom. ``For Tim, it was a
great learning experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom noted that Duncan had faced other dominant centers in the
Atlantic Coast Conference, including North Carolina's Rasheed
Wallace. But the contest against Camby was different because of the
media attention and because it marked the first time a Duncan-led
team headed to the Northeast for a major game.
</P>
<P>
   Odom said he stayed with Duncan in the locker room following the
contest until everyone else had left.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely disappointed with his performance after the
game, and I was disappointed we didn't get ball to him more,'' said
Odom. ``I remember we sat in chairs in the locker room and we both
had our heads down. And then we both raised our heads at the same
time and looked at each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'll never forget this as long as I live: He said, `Do you
still love me?' And I said, `I think I would have loved you more if
you had played better and we won, but yes, I still love you.' Then
we laughed and got ready to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The career paths of Duncan and Camby were different. Duncan
stayed in college for four years and was the first overall pick in
the 1997 NBA draft, by the Spurs. He was named Rookie of the Year
last season and was a finalist for Player of the Year this season,
helping San Antonio reach the Finals for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Camby led UMass to the Final Four of the 1995-96 season, then
left school early and was the second overall pick in the 1996 draft
by Toronto. The Raptors hoped he would be a building block, and he
showed occasional glimpses of greatness, but he had many detractors
in his first two injury-plagued seasons. Toronto traded Camby to
New York last offseason, and after a sluggish start he has returned
to the form that helped bring unprecedented success to UMass.
</P>
<P>
   This has left Calipari wondering what would have happened if the
Nets brass had listened to his pleas to acquire Camby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to trade for him 10 times,'' said Calipari, who was
fired by the Nets during the regular season. ``The people in the
Nets organization kept saying, `He's not good enough. You're
putting yourself on the line. You just want to bring in your former
players.' And I kept telling them, `You're nuts.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Duncan found a good team coming out of college. Camby went to
an expansion team. And at that time, I told Isiah (Thomas, then the
Raptors general manager) that you can't expect him to be a
dominating center, but if you put him with good other good players,
he'll make it an outstanding team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for him, because when he first arrived here,
everyone was so down on him, and it seemed as if I was the only one
saying he was going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, many people are echoing Calipari's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   According to Odom, Camby, Duncan, Wallace (now with Portland),
and Kevin Garnett of Minnesota represent the future of the NBA post
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of circumstances, and both continue to
amaze me,'' said Odom. ``I don't think you would be talking about
Camby if Patrick Ewing or Larry Johnson were healthy. Even though I
think Camby is better than both, (Knicks coach) Jeff Van Gundy
would have to play Ewing and Johnson ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim's situation was drawn out from a cluster of Ping-Pong
balls and then he fit into the situation. But I think those four
centers have 10 good years each ahead of them if they just
concentrate on the game and winning and don't worry about the money
and endorsements and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Calipari had a better supporting cast around Camby in college,
and if he were Van Gundy, he would play Camby only on Duncan, with
the hopes that the two would negate each other and the Knicks would
win the matchups at the other positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say to Marcus, `We don't want to double-team Duncan;
you have to play him alone,' '' said Calipari. ``I would get the
other big guys to beat up David Robinson. And then I would hope
that Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston would bet the better of
Mario Elie and Sean Elliott.''
</P>
</TEXT>
