<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER NOW TAMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ It was evident two weeks ago at the Memorial
in Dublin, Ohio, where Tiger Woods won for the second time in three
weeks, that his demeanor has changed. Now his sights are set on the
99th US Open, which begins Thursday over the hallowed No. 2 course
at Pinehurst Resort &AMP; CC. What did Woods do last week? Relax and
practice.
</P>
<P>
   He is at ease in these surroundings, on a course in the
sandhills designed by Donald Ross.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it a lot,'' said Woods. ``The golf course is playing a
little more friendly than I thought it would. I thought the rough
would be higher, the fairways narrower.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, whose best finish in this championship was joint 18th a
year ago, has won twice on the PGA Tour this year and also captured
the Deutsche Bank Open in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my game is definitely better than it was at the
Memorial,'' Woods said. ``I've been doing a little work, and I saw
things that we didn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   He and swing guru Butch Harmon watched tapes of his two straight
wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We analyzed both swings and saw a big difference,'' said
Woods. ``We made those changes, and they're starting to come
together. It's posture, swing plane, the way I was coming down.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not his more relaxed demeanor that has many thinking Woods
is on target to win his second major; there has been a general
improvement in his game, and the Pinehurst course has been softened
by rain the past two days. He can bust it here, something he
couldn't do at the last two US Opens, at Congressional and the
Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hit the ball poorly in US Opens, you're not going to be
around,'' said Woods. ``Fortunately I was able to chip and putt and
get it around good enough where I was making cuts, but I wasn't in
contention. That's also one of the reasons I changed my game, to
become more consistent, to shape the shots correctly. When I do
miss it, it's not fairways like it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning how to play the game. I'm only 23, and I have a
long way to go. I recognize that. I've come a long way as well, and
I've learned by watching other players play. I'm not afraid to go
out on the golf course and apply what I've learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who won a junior tournament on Pinehurst No. 2 when he
was 16, said the course has changed a lot, with new greens, and
strategy will be important.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course from tee to green is very simple,'' he said.
``It's around the greens where it becomes complicated, and because
of that I think you need to spend extra time chipping and putting,
not just on the course but on the practice green, to try to get a
feel of the shots you're going to have to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Wider fairways and rough that at 3 inches seems negligible favor
Woods and the longer hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the wider landing areas, it provides an opportunity for
you to use a longer club,'' said Woods. ``You can use a driver or
3-wood and not necessarily an iron off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fairways are a little softer, so you can hit it out there
and know if the ball lands in the fairway it's going to stay. If
you get the ball in the rough and you have a difficult lie, you've
got to be conservative and leave the ball short so it's not going
to zip over the green. It's not good over the green, and that's the
way it's been designed. Short is fine. You can get up and down from
short of the green.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that these greens will be similar to
those at Augusta National, where Woods won the Masters in
record-setting fashion two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Augusta is different,'' he said, ``because they have quadrants
to hit to. Their quadrants are smaller, and their slopes are
steeper. Here the greens aren't that severe once you get on the
putting surface.''
</P>
<P>
   In every interview this year, Woods is asked about his
``rivalry'' with David Duval, whom he will meet in a head-to-head
match this summer in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either he's played great and I haven't played so good, or it's
vice versa,'' said Woods. ``We haven't done it together in the same
tournament. It will happen one day. The odds are in our favor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1345EDT &QL; 
