<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FROZEN-BOS &LR;      06-16 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FROZEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISH THE TV DINNER A HAPPY 45TH, ONLY DON'T CALL IT THAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the beginning, there were frozen turkeys. There were 10
railroad cars filled with frozen turkeys. Or maybe there were 12.
Or 11. Gerry Thomas really isn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that there were a mess of them and we couldn't
find a home for them,'' the 77-year-old Thomas recalls, referring
to the January day in 1954 when he had a stone cold problem on his
hands. It seems that Thomas's employer, Omaha-based C. A. Swanson &AMP;
Sons, needed to get rid of a passel of turkeys that hadn't made the
holiday cut. His solution: a frozen dinner consisting of turkey,
dressing, gravy, cornbread, peas, and sweet potatoes, all ladled
with ice cream scoops into a partitioned metal tray. His idea for a
name: the ``TV Dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought I was crazy,'' muses Thomas, who now lives
in Arizona. ``It was a huge gamble, and it never should have
succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   Success? Only 5,000 to 6,000 of those original 98-cent TV
dinners were produced. Within a year, Thomas recalls, 10 million
more had been shipped. As many as 300 million were annually turned
out in subsequent years. A uniquely American cuisine _ if that's
the right word _ had been born. Swanson dropped the name ``TV
Dinner'' in 1960, but has resurrected it (through the end of June)
in honor of its 45th anniversary, along with the original six-color
packaging that features a wood-grain TV and plastic knobs. In
March, Thomas was rewarded for his contribution when he placed his
handprints in the sidewalk outside Mann's Chinese Theater in
Hollywood, right between those of Ron Howard and Sean Connery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just trying to get rid of turkeys, not build a
business,'' says Thomas. ``It's an incredible story.''
</P>
<P>
   It is incredible, too, that the type of meal Thomas begat is
still a staple of supermarket frozen-food cases 45 years after its
accidental birth. Frozen dinner receipts exceed $1 billion a year,
their sales curve neither rising sharply nor dropping
precipitously. They are just kind of there, quietly selling about
600 million units annually despite the explosive popularity of
fresh, grab-and-go ``home meal replacement'' fare being peddled
over the counter by food stores. Roughly half of us buy at least
one frozen dinner each year, whether we admit it or not. Sales have
been helped considerably through the years by the proliferation of
microwave ovens, the emergence of the working couple, and the
frantic pace of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the TV dinner _ and who can resist still calling it that?
_ has always had an image problem. Remember the old joke _ that the
best way to consume one of these things was to throw away the food
and eat the package? ``There's been a certain stigma associated
with the trayed meal over the years which is hard to shake,''
points out Warren Thayer, editor in chief of Frozen Food Age, a
trade publication. ``Still, there'll always be a place for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most frozen-dinner processors _ the major players are Nestle
USA, ConAgra Frozen Foods, and Vlasic Foods International (Swanson)
_ would rather discuss trendier products. Mention the D word and
they are likely to change the subject to more upscale frozen
entrees. (A frozen dinner is defined by the US Department of
Agriculture as having at least three components, consisting of
meat, poultry, cheese, eggs, vegetables, fruit, potatoes, rice, or
other cereal-based products. An entree is a principal dish or main
course, and can include a single vegetable.) Few companies actually
label their dinners ``dinners,'' in part because they don't want
the product seen as something that can be eaten only around
sundown. Until this year, Swanson hadn't run a television ad for
its frozen dinners in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do meals, not dinners,'' emphasizes Roz O'Hearn, director
of division and brand affairs for Nestle USA's frozen business,
which includes the Stouffer's and Lean Cuisine lines.
</P>
<P>
   And when they're talking about those frozen meals, executives
such as O'Hearn would prefer to focus on newer products _ such as
``skillet'' meals, ``bowl'' meals that can be microwaved, and
large-portion meals suitable for feeding a whole family _ rather
than the trayed descendants of the TV dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when you meander along the frozen-food cases of your
local supermarket, you won't find a shortage of such reliable
dinners-in-trays as chicken, turkey, and Salisbury steak. (With the
likes of pot roast, beef tips, and meatloaf mixed in.) Ethnicity
tends to run along the lines of lasagna or enchiladas. Exotica
generally involves tinkering with chicken: chicken Dijon, glazed
chicken, herb-roasted chicken, etc. And the taste? ``Generally just
so-so,'' declared Consumer Reports in a recent test of frozen meals
and entrees.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen dinners tend to have broad appeal, but some of us enjoy
heating and eating them more than others do. Least likely to reach
for them are young singles, childless couples, and new families.
They're also less popular with African-Americans than with whites.
Blue-collar families, older couples, and elderly singles are strong
buyers, as well as a group that a recent National Frozen Food
Association survey described as the ``Hectic Have-Tos'':
convenience-dependent folks who lead fast-paced lives. On the other
end of the scale in this study were the ``Frozen Rejectors,''
a.k.a. ``confident cooks.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gerry Thomas concocted his TV Dinner 45 years ago, frozen
foods had already been around for nearly a quarter of a century. A
few airlines had even tried feeding frozen dinners, called
``Strato-Plates,'' to passengers during the 1940s. But it was
Thomas who brought precooked meals to the masses. ``Even back then,
women were working outside the home in greater numbers,'' he says.
``They were looking for something fast to fix for their kids,
something that wouldn't give them a guilt complex. And, of course,
there were no fast-food chains.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of frozen dinners eventually flattened out during the late
1970s, but rose again in the 1980s with lower-calorie offerings.
And the baby boom kids, who had been trained on TV dinners, liked
them just fine. The dinners persevere today, the vast majority
still in trays, even with innovations such as bowls and bags. They
are an enduring slice of American pie that won't go away, despite
their image problem and an industry that often seems to treat them
like . . . well, like an unwanted guest at the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I could never find a man that admitted eating a TV
Dinner,'' Thomas says. ``Women would admit it, but not men. My
conclusion was that we had an awful lot of closet TV Dinner
eaters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
