<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7475 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-BARAK-BOS &LR;      06-16 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BEIRUT, PONDERING BARAK AS PEACEMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ On an April night 26 years ago, an Israeli commando in
a brunette wig, blue eyeshadow, and a long dress that concealed a
machine gun snuck into the heart of this city and led an operation
to assassinate three top Palestinian guerrilla leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Long-time residents of the street in the fashionable Verdun
district remember the brazen raid, and are shocked to learn that
the commando in drag who led it will become prime minister of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Barak's role in one of Israel's boldest undercover
operations was just one of many exploits that would make him the
most highly decorated soldier in Israel's history and help pave his
path to power.
</P>
<P>
   Some people on this Beirut street and others throughout the Arab
world wonder if a man so steeped in war can make the transformation
to statesman. But in a region where often only a fierce fighter is
trusted to make peace, there are many Arabs as well as Israelis who
said they believe Barak will follow the region's other
warriors-turned-peacemakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's still Rambo, maybe he's not. We can only hope he's
changed,'' said Minhaim Abu Al Muna, who was concierge of the
building when the commandos stormed it in the predawn on April 10,
1973.
</P>
<P>
   During the raid, the Barak-led unit landed under cover of
darkness on a beach in Beirut. The commandos, three of whom were
disguised as women, stormed a block of buildings and killed PLO
political leader Mohammed Al Najjar, whose nomme de guerre was
``Abu Yussef,'' Kamal Adwan, who headed the PLO's West Bank
resistance, and Kamal Nasser, a PLO spokesman and poet.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese officials stated that nine others were killed in the
operation. They included Najjar's wife, two Lebanese policemen, two
Lebanese civilians, three Syrian workers, and an Italian woman.
Some 20 other Lebanese citizens were wounded, according to press
reports.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, Muna, the former concierge, played
backgammon inside his electrical shop on the ground floor of the
apartment building and recounted the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the gun shots. I hid my wife and two children under a
table. There was shooting and screaming and confusion,'' he said.
``After the shooting, I came out and helped bring the wounded out.
There was blood everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For years everyone has talked about the women who were
involved _ a blonde and a brunette,'' said Muna, who said he was
hiding during the raid. ``But I never knew one of these men with
the wig was Barak. It surprised everyone here.'' A report in a
local paper was the first to publish the connection after Barak's
electoral victory in Israel on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   As Barak begins to build a coalition before being sworn in later
this month, Israeli observers said the success of his government
will depend on whether he can forge his military past into the
policies of peace and unity that he promised. They are big
promises. Barak has vowed to withdraw Israel's troops from its
self-proclaimed ``security zone'' in south Lebanon within one year
and to restart the long deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Reports that he has chosen three top generals to head his
negotiating team have some analysts concerned that they will be
unlikely to take the bold steps necessary to break the impasse. But
other analysts indicated Barak and his generals can be trusted to
ensure Israeli security while negotiating withdrawal from Lebanon,
a deal with Syria over the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights, and the
turnover of more land to the Palestinians under the 1993 Oslo peace
accords.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it is very clear that a person who had a personal
involvement and risk in an operation like the one in Beirut is much
more likely to have the guts and the courage to move forward to end
the conflict,'' said Avshalom Horan, who was a member of Barak's
commando unit on dozens of raids and served alongside him for more
than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can say that he doesn't understand the operations, or
he is removed from the reality on the ground,'' added Horan, now a
high-tech entrepreneur who remains a close friend to Barak and
played a role in his election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a love of the land and fighting for what you believe
is right'' that is ``required to storm a building like that,'' said
Horan, who was not involved in the raid but has discussed it many
times with Barak. ``These values mean a great deal in this region,
to both sides of the conflict. And that is why you find respect for
Barak on the street in Beirut and in Tel Aviv.''
</P>
<P>
   The raid catapulted Barak's military career.
</P>
<P>
   It became the stuff of military legend, and his account of the
incident is featured in a recently published biography under the
chapter heading ``Brunette in the Heart of Beirut.''
</P>
<P>
   The raid was described by Israeli press reports at the time and
by historians today as ``brave'' and ``daring,'' a crushing blow to
the most militant and murderous faction of the PLO.
</P>
<P>
   But Lebanese and Palestinian scribes described the raid as a
glaring example of the Israeli military flouting territorial
sovereignty and international law.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Najjar, the son of Abu Yussef, was 11 years old at the
time. He remembers waking to the gunshots and hearing the front
door of the family home explode off its hinges as six Israelis
stormed in. One commando held a gun to his head while he watched
through a crack in the door as his father was cut down by machine
gun fire. His mother, who tried to protect his father, was also
gunned down.
</P>
<P>
   His 16-year-old brother fled down a telephone pole in the back
of the apartment and spotted a commando in a brunette wig with a
machine gun who shot him twice in the arm. This, Najjar believes,
was Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells you something about'' Barak's ``character, that he
went inside a home with women and children,'' said Najjar, who is
now the director of the Palestinian Authority's Ministry of
Economic Planning and lives in Gaza. ``The two sides were at war, I
accept that, but there were many opportunities to kill my father in
the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a macho exercise for the Israelis. That Barak
led it, shows he's part of that macho mindset. I think the way he
was as a soldier will be the way he is as a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Farouk Nassar, a Lebanese reporter for the Associated Press who
covered the story, found the PLO's Nasser lying on the floor in a
pool of blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullets were fired into his mouth because he was the
spokesman,'' said Nassar, who later became AP bureau chief in
Beirut and is now retired. ``It was carried out with surgical
precision.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if a leader of such an operation could also pull the
troops out of Lebanon and end the last active war in the Middle
East, Nassar responded, ``Who would have believed that'' slain
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak ``Rabin would make peace and shake
hands with'' Palestinian leader Yasser ``Arafat. . . . Why
shouldn't Barak be in the same footsteps?''
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim Abouhjeili, 57, owns a barber shop on the Beirut street,
and he remembers arriving to open it that morning and seeing the
blood on the street and the chaos and confusion of the Lebanese
police and PLO bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since that incident, we've had 20 years of war, we've had
worse things happen. . . . People change after all those years,''
he said. ``I think Barak has changed. I think he wants Israeli
troops out of Lebanon, and I think he knows it's time for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Gathering around the barber shop, residents began sharing their
memories. The owner of the dry cleaner next door remembered the day
of the raid vividly, but refused to give his name to a reporter,
saying, ``Israel can still come here and kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, in his early 40s, said he was confident Barak would
withdraw the troops and end the conflict in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fighter who goes into battle,'' he said, ``knows the meaning
of peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
