<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7480 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TOWN-BOS &LR;      06-16 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIDING OVER, COMMUNITY VENTURES FORTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DJAKOVICA, Kosovo _ Tahir Nikolici, like so many victims of the
war in Kosovo, was too weak to escape. The paralyzed 67-year-old
Nikolici was in his wheelchair, at home with his daughter on a
usually quiet, cobblestoned street here, when Serb paramilitary
fighters barged in on April 13 and demanded that everyone leave,
neighbors say.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolici couldn't move without help. His daughter pleaded with
the Serbs to allow her to take out her disabled father. They
refused, she said, and burned the house down with her father
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my neighbor. I knew him 50 years. And I buried him here
with my own hands,'' said Fatmir Gola, 61, gesturing to a fresh
mound of dirt in what used to be Nikolici's garden.
</P>
<P>
   The house is demolished, reduced to a pile of red roof tiles and
smashed bricks.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Djakovica was on the front line of the war, and it
looks it. The old section of town _ once a pretty neighborhood of
small cafes, boutiques, and a historic mosque _ is now row upon row
of blackened shells of buildings. Shops are all closed, and there
is little food available.
</P>
<P>
   Only a fraction of Djakovica's structures _ including the
Serbian Orthodox church, and some curtained, now-abandoned Serb
houses _ were left untouched by the killing and arson.
</P>
<P>
   Most houses are roofless, and what wasn't stolen was set afire.
The colorful, well-kept gardens, where old women chatted over thick
Turkish coffee and children played, have commonly become graveyards
for the war dead. Residents were too afraid to take the bodies to a
cemetery for a proper Muslim burial.
</P>
<P>
   After months of hiding in terror inside their houses, ethnic
Albanians came outside this week, some to meet for the first time
since the NATO bombs dropped in March and triggered what they
describe as a Serb siege of terror. Since their cars were stolen,
they have been pedaling around town on bicycles, assessing the
damage in horror.
</P>
<P>
   When they meet, they rush to embrace. They exchange tales of
terror and murder, and they all have the same questions.
</P>
<P>
   Have you seen my husband? Do you know what happened to my sons,
my uncle, my nephew?
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we find this out?'' asked an anguished Selemet Peni,
49. ``Everyone now is asking for their relatives, but who knows
where they are? Are they dead? Are they in prison? How can we even
get the information?''
</P>
<P>
   Local residents estimate that 1,200 people _ mainly young men _
are missing. Some are believed to be dead. No one knows how many.
</P>
<P>
   People here say the modus operandi of the Serbs was to kill
first, then burn. With the evidence often in ashes, it is
impossible to know for certain whether the missing residents of
Djakovica made it to refugee camps, starved in the mountains, were
taken to prison, or were killed and burned by the Serb military.
</P>
<P>
   Afijet Zhuja wants to know what happened to four of her male
neighbors, but she is afraid to find out.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb paramilitary forces came through her neighborhood on
April 9, she recalled, separating out the men and ordering the
women and children to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The house of the Grqari family was burned, and their neighbors
fear that the men _ the father, Sylemon Grqari, and his three sons
_ are still inside, murdered.
</P>
<P>
   On the rare occasions when ethnic Albanians ventured out to find
food, the Serb paramilitaries refused to allow them to walk down
the Grqari's street. But once the Serbs left Djakovica, Zhuja
stepped a few inches inside, then drew back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid of what I would see. I was afraid it is really
true,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She approached the Italian soldiers who make up part of the
peacekeeping Kosovo Force (KFOR), asking their help.
</P>
<P>
   They told her to avoid the house, as it may be booby-trapped. So
now Zhuja waits and wonders.
</P>
<P>
   No one can tell yet how many people escaped Djakovica, and how
many remained out of fear or force.
</P>
<P>
   What diplomats proclaimed as peace meant a final, rage-filled
spasm by the Serb military, who, locals said, stole cars, looted
houses, and burned others in the last days before Tuesday's
deadline for a full military withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   They burst into the back window of the Hasimja family's house on
Saturday, family members said, making physical threats and
demanding money and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   They put a gun into the mouth of a 25-year-old recent medical
school graduate, Delvina Hasimja, she said, and beat her father and
her uncle. Her blind grandmother cowered in fear as the
black-masked Serbs emptied the house of valuables.
</P>
<P>
   There was already another family staying in the house, since the
Serbs had burned the next door neighbor's house weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that a human being can do that,'' said Delvina
Hasimja, sitting on a carpet in her nearly empty house.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the peace deal came down, they became very angry. They
burned houses, they killed people who were intellectuals,'' she
added. A fellow medical school graduate is missing, and Delvina
Hasimja fears he is dead.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Djakovica appears safe. The Serbs _ civilians as well
as militia _ have largely left, and the city is now patrolled by
KFOR and by uniformed, armed members of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
Both are cheered enthusiastically by people on the street.
</P>
<P>
   But with Djakovica largely in rubble and the whereabouts of many
of its men unknown, residents wonder what comes next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are figuring out how to survive and how to build our
future,'' Delvina Hasimja said. ``I had dreams of being a good
doctor. Now, I just want to be alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
