<HEADER>
A7481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-VILLAGE-BOS &LR;      06-16 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VILLAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVILIANS PONDER NEXT MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAPLJE SELO, Yugoslavia _ Zika Jovovic is the land, and the land
is Zika Jovovic. That is why the 55-year-old Jovovic rises at 5
every morning to tend to his cattle, his chickens, his
strawberries, and his walnut trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This land means everything to him,'' said his 20-year-old son,
Andrija, as Jovovic showed a visitor the 250-year-old mill that is
powered by a stream that runs through the family farm. ``To leave
this land would be like a slow death to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time in four centuries, when the Jovovics
began living off these eight acres of rustic land in central
Kosovo, they are seriously considering leaving it. Their bags are
packed for a quick getaway, and every night, Zika Jovovic sits up,
listening for approaching cars.
</P>
<P>
   His great fear is that it will be the rebels of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, bent on exacting revenge for the atrocities
committed against ethnic Albanians by Serb forces. The Serb troops
have pulled out, the last in this area leaving Tuesday from the
local school they were using as a base. A young woman who watched
them pull out before Tuesday's deadline stood on the side of the
road, crying.
</P>
<P>
   The Jovovics' mill is a national heritage site, protected by the
government. The Jovovics, however, are not. Nor can they protect
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no weapons. All I could do is run for the car,'' Zika
Jovovic said, drawing hard on a Malboro. ``I didn't harm anyone. It
would be very unfair if someone slaughtered us.''
</P>
<P>
   Momcilo Trajkovic, leader of the Serbian Resistance Movement,
who is trying to persuade Serbs to stay in Kosovo, runs a farming
cooperative in Laplje Selo. It is the quintessential Serb village,
he says, and if the Serbs of Laplje Selo leave, there is no hope
for any of the 200,000 Serbs left in Kosovo. As Laplje Selo goes,
so go the Serbs in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Just five miles south of the capital of Pristina, Laplje Selo is
a rural village of 450 homes, all of them Serb. The 2,500 people
here have made a pact. Either they all stay, or they all go. So
far, they've stayed.
</P>
<P>
   The raging tug of war between Serbs and Albanians over Kosovo
largely bypassed Laplje Selo, mostly because there were so few
Albanians here. The last two Albanian homes were torched last year.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also no denying that many people here are gentler
than the bellicose Serbian nationalists who get most of the
attention. They do not speak about Albanians in racist terms.
</P>
<P>
   They measure the time in seasons, and when the women are
pregnant for the first time, as 20-year-old Zorica Petkovic is,
they pray for a boy, so there will be a male to inherit the land.
</P>
<P>
   Petkovic's husband, Vladimir, 25, took over the land when his
father died last year. He runs a gravestone workshop in front of
his home and grows crops out back.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family has been here for 400 years,'' Vladimir says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five hundred,'' his grandfather, 73-year-old Miladin Petkovic,
corrects him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't packed,'' Vladimir continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone will leave together, or stay together,'' his
78-year-old grandmother Jelica chimes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not leaving,'' Vladimir says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he knows that if KLA gunmen pound on his door, he would have
little choice but to load his grandparents and his pregnant wife
into a car and go.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, as the road north to Pristina was choked with
the overflowing cars and tractors of Serb refugees from Prizren,
the people of Laplje Selo came face to face with their possible
fate, and it chilled them to the bone. The convoy was just 100
yards from the Jovovic house. The Petkovics had a panoramic view of
the exodus from a quarter-mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Trajkovic says at least 30,000 Serbs have fled Kosovo. He said
it is a ``great irony'' that the ability of Serbs to remain in
Kosovo now rests in the hands of foreign troops.
</P>
<P>
   Trajkovic said that with Serb forces withdrawing, and the
government of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic effectively
ceding control of Kosovo to the international community, the fate
of Serbs in Kosovo rests with K-FOR peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   Here as in other isolated Serb villages, people say they hope
that K-FOR will protect them, but they are uneasy about the cozy
relationship between the KLA and NATO, whose soldiers account for
the bulk of K-FOR peacekeeping troops. They want to see more
evidence of NATO troops disarming and arresting KLA fighters.
</P>
<P>
   No one from the village has yet approached K-FOR troops to ask
for protection. Tuesday, for only the second time, British troops
drove through the village in a Warrior armored vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If K-FOR disarms the KLA, everything will be OK,'' said Zika
Jovovic. ``We used to live with ordinary Albanians. We don't need
weapons here. Most of the houses around here don't have weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, as in other Serb hamlets, perception is reality, and
perceptions are shaped by pieces of information gleaned from the
news, but mostly from the frightening rumors that spread faster
than any fungus on the locally grown produce. Some of the rumors
turn out to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the family living across the street from the Jovovics
found out that one of their relatives was killed by the KLA when it
stormed a Serb apartment block in Pristina, shooting one man dead
and wounding another. K-FOR officials said British troops arrested
five suspected KLA members in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several kidnappings of Serbs by the KLA in
Pristina, and Zika Jovovic was so worried that he insisted on
accompanying his son to Pristina while Andrija took his music
composition exams Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I would be very pleased to see K-FOR troops
patrolling on my street,'' said Zika Jovovic. ``They have to
protect everybody, Albanians and Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, word came that the KLA was putting Serb families
out of the Sunny Hill section of Pristina. The last of the Serb
army units were heading out to meet the midnight deadline of
withdrawing from the Pristina area. Fear is spreading among Serbs,
as it spread among Albanians three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Jovovics have survived many wars on this land. A bullet
fired by Ottoman Turks is still lodged in the wooden door to the
mill. Zika Jovovic was born in 1943, as World War II raged. His
14-month-old grandson Nikola's first words, spoken last week, were
``plane, boom boom,'' a sound he learned as the family huddled in a
damp, musty basement through 78 days of NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Squinting in the sun, Zika Jovovic looked up and said, ``This is
my home. I don't want to leave it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the village, Vladimir Petkovic believes he
will be here in November, when his first child is born.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, people didn't believe the land would ever be free
of Turks. But it is. The same goes for today,'' he said. ``You have
to believe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
