<SLUG> BC-EILEEN-MCNAMARA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE CHOICES: DUMB &AMP; DUMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't embarrass easily, but I was grateful for the dim
lighting in the theater the other night while watching ``Austin
Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   All around me, pre-pubescent boys were snickering at the bosomy
babes, howling at the bathroom jokes, and elbowing each other
during the bedroom scenes. Two of them were my sons, sneaking a
sidelong glance now and then to see if a less-than-subtle sexual
innuendo had eluded Mom.
</P>
<P>
   New Line Cinema released this sequel to Mike Meyers's 1997
sendup of '60s pop culture the same week President Clinton urged
theater owners to card teenagers to thwart the under-17 set from
sneaking into R-rated movies. If the president thinks troublesome
content is limited to movies with R ratings, if he thinks the
rating system itself is anything other than a sham, then it has
been too long since he visited his neighborhood multiplex.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton last week led one to wonder whether the White
House is hermetically sealed after he ordered the Federal Trade
Commission to investigate ``whether and how video game, motion
picture, and recording industries market to children violent and
other material rated for adults.''
</P>
<P>
   He needs a federal inquiry to determine the obvious?
</P>
<P>
   A trip to the mall should have sufficed. In the window of the
Warner Brothers Store, promotions for ``Austin Powers'' _ the
PG-13-rated adventures of a time-traveling, libidinous spy _ sit
alongside the Tweety Bird and Bugs Bunny merchandise. As best I can
figure, Hollywood rates the movie as relatively inoffensive because
its raunchiness is only a spoof of really raunchy movies.
</P>
<P>
   There's a logic there. Somewhere. The problem is not just
``Austin Powers.'' Mike Meyers, like Jim Carrey, is a comedic
talent. He has a clown's gift for mannerism and physical comedy.
But watching ``Austin Powers'' was a little like imagining Jerry
Lewis overdosing on Viagra _ what begins as naughty but nice
descends rapidly into crude and lewd.
</P>
<P>
   Adults respond to ``Austin Powers'' in much the way parents
respond to ``Sesame Street.'' The writers for ``Sesame Street''
always work on two levels, one aimed at preschoolers, the other at
the parents in the playroom with them. ``Austin Powers'' works that
way, too, with a subtext that appeals to adults and an earthiness
that appeals to kids. My sons missed the sendups of old movies, but
they roared (and I cringed) when the fembot's nipples sprouted gun
barrels. The gerbil joke sailed right passed them, but they hooted
(and I groaned) when the fat bagpiper passed gas.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not that Hollywood is awash in cultural
pollution. It is that it is steeped in corporate greed. ``Austin
Powers'' broke box office records for a comedy its first weekend
because it exploits a winning formula with the middle school crowd
(See ``Ace Ventura: Pet Detective'' and ``Dumb and Dumber.'')
</P>
<P>
   No one _ except perhaps William Bennett _ wants to ban
sophomoric humor from the silver screen. It would just be
refreshing to have the movie industry stop urging parents to steer
their kids away from inappropriate material and to acknowledge that
not much else is out there for young people who are beyond the
Disney cartoon stage. The phrase ``parental guidance'' is
meaningless when Hollywood offers so few alternatives to the
formulaic scripts now aimed at teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that even as moviemakers pander to the lowest
common denominator, more and better fiction is being written for
young adults. Instead of the novels of Sharon Creech or Edward
Bloor or Lois Lowery, Hollywood gives us ``I Know What You Did Last
Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Political initiatives to protect children from violent or
sexually explicit movies mirror the halfway measures that would
deny them access to lethal weapons. Stationing a police officer
outside every movie theater will stop teenagers from seeing R-rated
movies about as well as stationing security guards in the halls
will stop high school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   If Bill Clinton really wants to challenge the Hollywood movie
moguls whose profits have lined his campaign coffers all these
years, he ought to demand that his friends give our childen the
quality films they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   We don't need more culture cops. We need more consumer choice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
