<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISE THE AGE ON BUYING GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the inexplicable debates in the insensate debacle on guns
is whether the minimum age for handgun possession should go from 18
to 21. There would be no debate if one remembered 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, the political movement against drunken driving forced
the conservative President Ronald Reagan to sign a bill that
threatened states with the loss of federal highway funds if they
did not raise the minimum drinking age to 21.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan, who earlier opposed the bill, said in his Rose Garden
signing ceremony that it was ``a simple measure that will save
thousands of young lives.'' Reagan, who led the GOP assault on big
government, said that drunk driving was ``bigger than the
individual states.'' He said, ``With the problem so clear-cut and
the prudent solution at hand, we have no misgivings about this
judicious use of federal power.''
</P>
<P>
   The statistics behind Reagan's change of heart were undeniable,
even for a conservative. Several states where the legal age had
already been raised to 21 had seen sharp declines in fatal car
crashes. One such state was New Jersey. Tom Kean, then the governor
and a Republican, said, ``When people are going to be killed, when
people are going to be maimed, when people are going to be ruined
for life, then states' rights or any other abstraction is not going
to stand in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's pen saved lives. In 1994, the Centers for Disease
Control found that alcohol-related traffic fatalities dropped from
25,165 in 1982 to 17,461 in 1993. Fatalities suffered by people
aged 15 to 20 dropped 59 percent between 1982 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC has attributed the drops to a wide range of factors,
society's disdain for intoxicated driving, tougher enforcement of
laws, greater use of safety belts, overall decreased alcohol
consumption, and raising the minimum drinking age to 21.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence was so convincing that in 1994, when Governor
William Weld of Massachusetts signed a law that banned handgun
possession for people under 21 in Boston, his analogy was alcohol.
``That's an easy issue, because if you raise that age to 21, it
will be like drinking,'' said Weld, who was hardly antigun, being a
hunter who owns several rifles. ``You'll make it harder for the
kids 13, 14, 15 16 to get a handgun, and they're the ones who have
them now.''
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, a year after Weld signed the law, Boston,
riddled with youth murders in the early 1990s, began a
two-and-a-half-year spell without a gun murder of a child under 17.
</P>
<P>
   Little of that history has informed the debate on guns on
Capitol Hill. Current law forbids the sale of handguns from
federaly licensed dealers to people under 21. But the law does not
cover private sales or gun shows. Several of the handguns and
rifles used by teenagers in the nation's schoolyard shootings were
purchased at licensed gun stores or gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   When the Senate passed its mild proposal to restrict gun sales,
there was no mention of raising the limit on handgun possession
from 18 to 21. In the House, there is such a proposal, but nothing
close to a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton wants to raise the age for buying and
possession of handguns. But the National Rifle Association, which
has sprung back to life after Littleton forced it into a momentary
crouch, has placed its heavy hand on Congress. Republican House
majority leader Dennis Hastert supports raising the age for
purchase but not for possession. Many Republicans and some
Democrats still opposes any rise in the minimum age.
</P>
<P>
   New evidence should end the debate. The Treasury and Justice
Departments this week released a study that found that 18 to 20
year olds, 4 percent of the population, account for 24 percent of
gun murders in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Vice President Al Gore, Justice Deputy Attorney
General Eric Holder and Treasury Undersecretary James Johnson
called for a ban on handgun and assault rifle possession and sales
to people under 21. Holder and Johnson said they found that over 40
percent of crime guns recovered by police from 18 to 20 year olds
had been purchased within the last three years from a licensed gun
dealer. Most of those guns were handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If possession of and access to firearms among this age group
are reduced, deaths from armed crime will likely be reduced,''
Holder and Johnson wrote. ``It is also reasonable to expect that by
reducing access to firearms by this age group, it will also make it
more difficult for their younger siblings, classmates, and friends
to obtain guns illegally, reducing gun violence among juveniles
under 18.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the reasoning Reagan was forced to use in raising the
drinking age. That is the logic that Weld used to sign the handgun
ban in Boston. To borrow from Reagan and Kean, the problem of guns
is clear-cut. The prudent solution at hand.
</P>
<P>
   This is about people being killed, maimed, and ruined for life.
The National Rifle Association should not stand in the way.
Congress should have no misgivings about its judicious use of
federal power. Its hesitation to raise the handgun age to 21 is not
only inexplicable and insensate. It is unconscionable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
