<HEADLINE>
GRASS-ROOTS CAMPAIGN TACKLES WEALTH GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A rising tide lifts all boats. So goes the cliche.
</P>
<P>
   But that's certainly not been the case during the current
economic good times that have fed an explosion of sales of
big-ticket items, from bigger sport-utility vehicles to $200 meals
at fancy French bistros.
</P>
<P>
   While these have been flush years for the wealthy, those at the
bottom of the financial ladder have not only been left out of the
economic surge _ they've actually fallen several rungs.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one solid piece of circumstantial piece: In the 1970s,
the richest 10 percent of the American population controlled 50
percent of the wealth, while the rest of the population divided the
remaining 50 percent, according to U.S. government data.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the most equitable economic picture, but far better
than what's happened in the ensuing 20 years. During the 1990s, the
percentage of wealth enjoyed by the richest 10 percent has climbed
to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It is this kind of skewed distribution of wealth that is
mobilizing a growing grass-roots campaign to find ways _ by raising
the minimum wage, revamping the tax code, among others _ to create
a more equitable economic system.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend at Boston College, United for a Fair Economy, a
national group based in Boston, hosted a conference designed to
enlist religious congregations _ natural allies, perhaps, given
their moral underpinnings _ in this expanding campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great and wondrous economy,'' said Chuck Collins,
codirector of United for Fair Economy. ``There are some really good
things happening, with low unemployment and exploding stock
portfolios. And if we can't address issues of poverty and
inequality in this economy, when will we? When two big growth
industries in this country are prisons and gated communities, you
have to ask if this really is the kind of economy we want to
create.''
</P>
<P>
   Religious leaders worldwide recently have begun to sound the
alarm bell over the widening gap between rich and poor not only in
the United States, but around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, the Dalai Lama and the World Council of
Churches have called for international lending institutions,
including the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, to
cancel the unpayable debt _ estimated at as much as $300 billion _
of developing countries in Latin America, Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Burdened by massive loan repayments, many countries have slashed
spending on education, health care and welfare, exacerbating the
already bleak outlook for their poorest populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The millennium should be something more meaningful than
worrying about our computers and popping champagne corks,'' said
David Bryden, communications and outreach coordinator for Jubilee
2000/USA, a Washington-based group advocating debt forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul has declared next year, the 2,000th anniversary of the
birth of Jesus, a jubilee year and a cause for religious
celebration. But in biblical terms jubilee has a special resonance.
In the book of Leviticus, God instructs the Israelites to celebrate
a jubilee every 50 years by, among other steps, forgiving debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Roman Catholic Church speaks very clearly on social
justice,'' said Charles Derber, a sociology professor at Boston
College and one of the speakers at this weekend's conference.
``There is a really well-articulated and well-reasoned discussion
of human decency and dignity. These aren't just whimsical
ideological statements. They have concrete implications, if you
take them serious, for the organization of economic systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the conference hope to motivate more religious
congregations to become involved in issues of economic equity by
lobbying Congress members and incorporating themes of the gap
between rich and poor into worship services and religious education
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economists have become secular priests who dictate economic
arrangements in a way that is not senstive to the values of most
religious folks,'' Derber said. ``They have managed to persuade
most Americans that a wide division between rich and poor is the
price that has to be paid for having a prosperous economy. . . . We
have to challenge that theology.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Church of Scientology has issued an updated edition of
``What is Scientology,'' which describes the practices, programs
and organization of a church that claims 8 million members
worldwide. With more than 1,000 pages the hefty tome is available
at most public libraries.
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
