<HEADLINE>
SERBS, BEWARE! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A &UR;  &LR; word of advice to Serb troops, their paramilitary brethren,
whose reputation is as black as their uniforms, their Russian
comrades-in-arms, and to anyone else with a gun and a grudge as
NATO moves its men into Kosovo: Don't mess with the Gurkhas.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the fighting men from the mountain kingdom of Nepal,
whose male antecedents have served in the British Army for 180
years. You'll know them by their short and sturdy stature, their
jungle hats, and most of all, by the curved daggers _ the kukri _
that are their in-close weapon of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Recruited as teenage boys by British officers, the hardy hillmen
and herdsmen of the Nepalese mountains east of Katmandu have left
their mark on foes from the Falklands to Burma. So it was not by
chance that General Michael Jackson, the NATO commander of the
Kosovo liberation force, selected 660 men from the 1st Battalion,
Royal Gurkha Rifles, to join 1,400 British paratroopers for the
initial NATO push into the embattled province.
</P>
<P>
   The infantryman's role is the hardest job in combat. The man on
the ground with a rifle and a bayonet is the ultimate ``sharp end
of the stick,'' in the laconic British diplomatic phrase for what
happens after push has come to shove. When the sharp end of the
stick includes skilled skirmishers packing whetted kukris, Serb
bullyboys had best beware.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs had their way with the unarmed farmers and townsmen of
Kosovo, separating out and from time to time killing the men,
raping women, brutalizing the old, robbing and destroying with
impunity, fearing only retaliation from 15,000 feet up.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a new game on the ground as well as in the skies.
</P>
<P>
   The audacious move of 200 Serb-sympathizing Russians into
Pristina's airport was a nasty and embarrassing surprise for NATO.
The gambit may not look so funny in January if the West can't seem
to find the paperwork for the next $4 billion transfer of cash to
the wobbly Russian economy. But Battlin' Boris and the Krazy Kops
running the Kremlin can't seem to think beyond next week. When our
Russian friends run short of World Bank credits this winter,
someone may idly mention the sneaky end run into the Pristina
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Russians playing roulette with their Slavic soul
brothers, the Serbs, the tide is now running with the West. A
Chicago Tribune correspondent with NATO forces in Kosovo Saturday
reported:
</P>
<P>
   ``Some NATO troops did more than just move Saturday. Gurkha
soldiers stopped private vehicles in which Serb police were
traveling. They searched the cars, searched the men and, while
cameras rolled, relieved the police of their weapons. Among the
guns confiscated were pistols, Kalashnikov rifles, and Thompson
submachine guns. Asked whether the police had put up a fuss, a
typically reticent Ghurka responded, `Not a worry.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A Dallas Morning News account described Gurkha riflemen ``who
defused land mines found along Route Hawk, the main road into the
province.'' A Gurkha patrol ``moving north had run into a column of
Yugoslav army trucks that wanted to move south to retrieve
equipment hidden in the woods. The Gurkhas, under orders not to let
armed men down the road, blocked the way with three combat
reconnaissance vehicles.'' That incident ended without gunplay.
</P>
<P>
   There will be hundreds of similar encounters as Kosovo gives
over military control from Serbs loyal to Milosevic to NATO forces.
Having the discipline not to shoot, not to be provoked, is what
separates the NATO forces from the Serbs, who had things all their
own way till the first NATO strike signaled the beginning of the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting wars thousands of miles from their homeland is what
sets Gurkhas apart. For details of this century's efforts, see
``History of 7th Duke of Edinburgh's Own Gurkha Rifles,'' by Col.
J.N. MacKay (Wm. Blackwood &AMP; Sons, 1962) and ``East of Katmandu,''
by E.D. Smith, (Leo Cooper, 1976).
</P>
<P>
   Sir Ralph Turner, a Cambridge professor of Sanskrit and a Gurkha
officer, memorialized these ``stubborn and indomitable peasants of
Nepal. Once more I hear the laughter with which you greeted every
hardship. I see you in your bivouacs, shivering with wet and cold,
now scorched by pitiless and burning sun. Uncomplaining, you endure
hunger and thirst and wounds; and at the last your unwavering lines
disappear into the smoke and wrath of battle. Bravest of the brave,
most generous of the generous, never had a country more faithful
friends than you.'' Faithful friends, but pitiless foes.
</P>
<P>
   So, a word to the wise among Serb gunslingers swaggering around
Kosovo: Before the Gurkhas arrive and set up their tents, before
they start patrolling and looking out for troublemakers, point your
nose in the direction of Belgrade and set off smartly in that
direction. Because the quiet soldier who comes to work with jungle
hat and kukri tucked in his belt is not a man to mess with.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
