<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. FUSSY GOES TO THE BOOKSTORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (With apologies to the late Roger Hargreaves, creator of Mr.
Fussy, Mr. Nonsense, and 42 other delightful children's book
characters.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fussy's family has sent him to the bookstore to buy a
Father's Day present for himself. Mr. Fussy would rather not have a
Father's Day present. All things being equal, Mr. Fussy would
rather not have Father's Day, when everyone tries to make him
``happy.'' If they wanted him to be happy, they would do away with
these ridiculous ``days.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming to the bookstore was a mistake. Perhaps he should have
settled for a necktie. Or for one of those Brookstone barbecue
forks that tell you the temperature of what you are grilling. Vice
President Al Gore would like one of those. Last year, Mr. Fussy
heard the vice president deliver a stirring July Fourth address on
the importance of grilling red meat to over 160 degrees. Mr. F.
felt his vote sway GOP-ward inside him.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fussy likes to read, but he is very fussy about books. Most
fathers must be less fussy than he, judging by the many special
shelves replete with Father's Day offerings: books about golf and
barbecuing, two activities Mr. F. cannot abide. Then there were the
usual Grishams and Clancys _ booksellers talk about them as if they
were deli items, like ``turkey'' and ``Swiss'' _ and tales of
Arthurian valor from our not-so-distant past, most of them
springing from the pen of literary Stakhanovite Stephen Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   How to choose? Mr. Fussy has his own rules for books. Size
matters. Mr. Fussy likes his books the way he likes his voice mail
messages: brief, cogent, and to the point. Twenty seconds into a
voice mail screed, Mr. Fussy puts down the receiver and waits for
the dial tone. He likes short books, the way he likes short
parties. ``Bring the wine, leave by nine,'' he used to tell his
dinner guests. Now that he lives in what passes for polite society,
Mr. Fussy has to keep his feelings about hospitality to himself.
</P>
<P>
   But don't you love a good, short book? Michael Cunningham's
``The Hours,'' 230 pages _ perfect! Dava Sobel's ``Longitude,'' 184
pages _ bingo! The short list could go on and on. They say there
are books so good you never want them to end, although none comes
readily to mind. (The best book ever written, Cecil Woodham-Smith's
``The Reason Why,'' is only 292 pages long.) Locked in short-term
memory is Mr. Fussy's recent slog through Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in
Full,'' which seemed more like assigned reading than fun.
</P>
<P>
   Rule Number Two: Always judge a book by its cover. The most
beautiful book cover Mr. Fussy ever saw was the lovely illustration
for Michael Dorris's ``A Yellow Raft in Blue Water.'' Nowadays,
booksellers seem anxious to cloak their covers in a luxuriant
cerulean color (see Charles Frazier's ``Cold Mountain'' or Chris
Bohjalian's ``Midwives'') that Mr. Fussy calls ``selling blue.''
That Mr. Fussy has neither bought nor read any of these three books
undermines his credibility on this point.
</P>
<P>
   In principle. Mr. Fussy wants to read only good books. Some
people will read only books that have survived for over a century.
But then Mr. Fussy would have to read Walter Scott and ignore
Robertson Davies; what's the point of that? And of course, it all
depends what one means by good books.
</P>
<P>
   Do you mean good-good books, like Paul Auster's ``Mr. Vertigo''?
Or good-bad books, like the gossipy Hollywood tripe that Mr. Fussy
devours? Examples given: Charles Fleming's impossibly awful ``High
Concept,'' or the superb Nancy Griffin-Kim Masters expose of
Columbia Pictures, ``Hit and Run.'' A good-bad book is one that has
no redeeming social value, but is fun to read. Then there are
bad-bad books, which are gruesomely written and hell to read.
That's where Messrs. Clancy and Ludlum come in.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are good books with bad elements, like the Louis
Begley novels, ``The Man Who Was Late'' and ``About Schmidt.''
These are engaging and beautifully written, but reveal the author
to be a dirty old man. Put another way, Begley gets a lot right,
but he gets sex wrong. He should talk to Diane Johnson, author of
``Le Divorce.'' She gets sex right. How does Mr. Fussy know? He'd
rather not say, but he knows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
