<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7505 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-DUCKTRAP-2TAKES-     06-16 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-DUCKTRAP-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING FISH INTO GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Maine _ There's a story Desmond FitzGerald likes to
tell about the early years of Ducktrap River Fish Farm. It's a tale
about a dowser, a ``water witch'' who uses a divining rod to seek
out underground water, and FitzGerald begins it slowly, easing
himself deeper into his chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``His name was Edgar Libby,'' he says. ``He was 75 at the
time.'' It was 1977, and FitzGerald had called Libby because he
needed more water for his trout farm, then located along Kendall
Brook, a tributary of the Ducktrap River, in Lincolnville, about 7
miles from where the farm is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pulled up in his Buick Electra and took out a wooden case
lined with velvet. He had a stainless steel divining rod,''
because, he told FitzGerald, the more traditional applewood
``shatters in my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   With the rod, Libby used a chain with a silver pendant, which
circled madly over one spot on the ground. The dowser declared that
FitzGerald would find water there, 150 feet down. FitzGerald had it
drilled, and there was water _ just below 150 feet. Tons of water
gushed out of the 6-inch hole with such force that it reminded
FitzGerald of an old Texas oil-well movie.
</P>
<P>
   Luck, mystery, and a deep connection with the land: The moment
has all the elements that FitzGerald focuses on when he's talking
about Ducktrap River Fish Farm. FitzGerald is self-deprecating in a
way that only someone with real confidence can be. His explanation
of how a small trout farm grew to a $19 million fish-smoking
business is this: ``I wouldn't discount luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The people he supplies would disagree.
</P>
<P>
   He worked and reworked his salmon, they say, then personally
delivered samples around the country. Every Ritz-Carlton hotel menu
in the country offers salmon that Ducktrap smokes exclusively for
Foley Fish Co. of Boston and New Bedford. Owner Michael Foley says
FitzGerald ``had a belief that there's a better product to be made.
And he delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a good company,'' agrees Stephanie Stathe, seafood
coordinator of Bread &AMP; Circus, whose stores have been selling
Ducktrap products for 17 years. Whole Foods, the parent company of
Bread &AMP; Circus, packages Ducktrap smoked salmon under a Whole Foods
house label for national distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Though it began as a farm, Ducktrap is now exclusively a smoking
operation. Its trout comes from Idaho; its mackerel for the popular
smoked-peppered mackerel fillets is flown in from the Shetland
Islands, off the coast of Scotland. Plump mussels come from local
waters (``blue mussels from Maine are the best in the world,'' says
FitzGerald), and succulent cold-water shrimp the size of a pinkie
are fished in Maine, too. White sturgeon from Oregon goes into the
smokers, along with loins of yellowfin tuna from the Pacific.
Ducktrap's smoked trout pate is widely imitated, and among the
latest of the 35 products is smoke-roasted salmon in individual
packages, intended for the microwave and ready for the table in
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the early years, when FitzGerald was trying to raise fish,
his half-sister Frances ``Frankie'' FitzGerald, the Pulitzer
Prize-winning author of ``Fire in the Lake: The Vietnamese and the
Americans in Vietnam,'' came up from Manhattan to visit him. ``This
is absolutely the end of the earth,'' she declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a matter of where you live,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   FitzGerald, 47, lives in Maine _ as he has for 20 years. He
wandered up here armed simply with a love of marine biology, a
Harvard degree (class of '74), and a crash course in aquaculture
that he laughingly calls ``Berlitz fish.'' He came for the
lifestyle, he says, and though he has replaced the romantic days of
a rural Maine trout farmer with the hectic schedule of a CEO in a
24-hour plant, the role seems to suit him.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Ducktrap became too big for FitzGerald to
continue pumping money into _ especially, as he says, with four
children ``edging in on boarding school and college.'' So he gave
up his controlling interest in exchange for corporate backing.
Earlier this spring, Ducktrap and its salmon supplier of eight
years, Atlantic Salmon of Maine, formed a holding company,
ContiSea, of which FitzGerald is CEO. The state-of-the-art Belfast
plant has just been renovated to accommodate Atlantic Salmon's
offices, make separate areas for raw fish and smoked seafood (for
sanitation reasons), and expand freezing and cooling areas.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are part of ContiGroup, formerly Continental
Grain Co. By having his company acquired, FitzGerald thought he was
getting rid of all his financial headaches, but it turns out not to
be quite that simple. ``You can't walk up to the candy man and ask
for money,'' he says. ContiGroup didn't, for instance, sign the
lending agreement for the new facility.
</P>
<P>
   As he explains this, he has one eye on a construction crew about
to dig up some young trees outside his office window. It's so
painful to watch, he has to jump up from his chair and close the
blinds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company remains essentially the same. ``If you asked
anyone here what has changed, they might say, `Well, Des is in a
better mood.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Desmond FitzGerald and his wife, Lucinda Ziesing, an actress,
live in Camden with four children, ages 5 to 14. When they married,
he says, the wedding announcement in The New York Times was
headlined, ``Fish farmer marries actress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a kick out of that.''
</P>
<P>
   FitzGerald grew up in the fashionable Georgetown section of
Washington, D.C., and attended Potomac School and St. Mark's in
Southborough before Harvard, where he majored in biology. His
father, for whom he was named, was deputy director of the Central
Intelligence Agency. The family connections could have opened
doors, no doubt, but after college, FitzGerald lit out for Alaska,
where he had been a number of times.
</P>
<P>
   On the way, in 1975, he met Richard Mack, who owned a trout
farm. Aquaculture fascinated FitzGerald, so he enrolled at the
University of Washington's College of Fisheries for his crash
course in fish farming. ``I didn't get a degree, I just
cherry-picked graduate courses,'' he says. Soon after, he headed
for Maine. He had summered on Mount Desert Island and had ``fond
childhood memories of Maine,'' he says. ``I moved to Maine as a
lifestyle choice, not to make money. I was more interested in
escaping the city and being in a rural area.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1407EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7506 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-DUCKTRAP-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     06-16 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-DUCKTRAP-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BELFAST, Maine: ... a rural area.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The move, not to mention the trout farm he planned, took his
family by surprise. ``This is certainly not what my father expected
me to do,'' FitzGerald says. And Belfast, the town he chose, was
hardly a resort like Mount Desert.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of those charming Maine seacoast towns, east of Augusta
and south of Bangor, where 19th-century white clapboard houses line
the small roads, and restaurants like the Clam Hut announce,
``Today's special: Clams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a manufacturing town gone fallow,'' explains Dusty
Batley, Ducktrap's production manager. The chicken processors who
thrived here 25 years ago are gone; so are the shoe manufacturers.
To Batley, who joined Ducktrap 15 years ago, that meant ``high
unemployment among people who understand the production world.'' He
hired 150 employees, who work with such precision that they know
there are 28 pin bones to pull out of each fillet of salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Ducktrap began slowly _ and inefficiently, it seems. The way
FitzGerald tells it, he bumbled along, often making the wrong
decisions for the right reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may not work,'' he decided early on, at a moment when he
was feeding fingerling trout for an hour each day. ``I loved the
routine of husbanding these critters along,'' he says now. ``The
farming piece was punctuated by tragedy.'' He kept losing fish.
</P>
<P>
   The smokehouse, now the heart of the business, began as a
sideline. Trout farming alone wasn't making enough money to keep
him going.
</P>
<P>
   He built a 4-by-4-foot smoker from directions in a government
pamphlet. ``It was a little shed with no control.'' In 1981, he
bought a real smoker from England that held 20 sides of salmon.
Ultimately, he gave up trout farming _ but only when Batley
declared, ``You can't expect us to feed trout and smoke fish.''
</P>
<P>
   After a trip to England and Scotland, FitzGerald set his sights
on a product you might see as part of an old-fashioned British
breakfast, along with broiled tomatoes, fried eggs, and dark slices
of buttered toast: a glistening, golden brown, smoky fillet of
trout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That trout would become Ducktrap's first signature item. But
today salmon has edged out trout, with 65 percent of sales coming
from three grades of salmon. The top of the line is Kendall Brook,
named for the old property in Lincolnville, which Ducktrap left in
1992 because ``it wasn't a place to do manufacturing in any kind of
scale. You've got to be hooked up to city water, be accessible to
roads,'' FitzGerald says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kendall Brook is the most worked product in the system,'' he
says, Atlantic Salmon's fillet trimmed so that slices resemble a
loin; 4 ounces cost about $6. Winter Harbor smoked salmon uses the
same fish, but it's not trimmed as well; it costs $1 less than
Kendall Brook. (Winter Harbor is the salmon used in Whole Foods'
house brand, and it's also the one many chefs use.) A third
product, labeled Spruce Point, is Chilean salmon and costs about $4
per 4 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon production is closely coordinated with fishing. The way
Ducktrap and Atlantic Salmon work is that Ducktrap knows when
Atlantic is pulling the salmon out of the water. ``If the fish is
four days old, it is going to take salt up much faster than
Tuesday's fish,'' says FitzGerald. He really wants fish ``at the
point just on the other side of rigor.''
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturing end of the plant is carefully protected from
contamination. No visitor can enter without donning a lab coat,
hairnet, and knee-high boots. A visitor also has to scrub up and
dip her boots into disinfectant at the entrance to each new area.
</P>
<P>
   A tour begins, as some plant tours do, at the end, with the
finished product. As we watch women at a table, packaging slices of
salmon on pieces of cold, foil-surfaced cardboard, Dusty Batley
outlines the process. ``Most smoking technology comes out of
Europe,'' Batley says. Most of Ducktrap's machinery is European,
and so is the style of smoking for which the company is known.
</P>
<P>
   The fish start out in a brine of salt, spices, and dehydrated
cane juice _ ``Myer's Rum in granulated form,'' jokes FitzGerald.
</P>
<P>
   Then it is rinsed and chilled until a pellicle forms _ a
``skin'' on top of the fish that prevents drying during smoking.
Still on tall racks, the salmon heads for the smokers, called
kilns, which look like stainless steel, institutional refrigerators
with a few more thermostats. The salmon goes through a cold smoke
process _ the temperature doesn't go above 90 degrees _ so the
smoked fish has nearly the same translucent texture as uncooked
salmon, and it's easy to slice thinly on German slicing machines.
FitzGerald likes its ``peach melba'' color.
</P>
<P>
   Trout is given a hot smoke, as are juicy Maine mussels.
</P>
<P>
   A mixture of oak, hardwood, and fruitwood chips fuels the fire,
which circulates through the kilns. Ducktrap's newest kiln is one
of five in the world. ``Instead of air to dry out the kiln, it uses
a refrigeration cooler to pull moisture out of the air and
recirculate it,'' Batley says. The machine cost $180,000 and can
process 2,000 pounds of salmon at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're after is as little flame as possible,'' says
FitzGerald. ``A smoldering fire that gives us a maximum amount of
smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Batley calls it a ``smudge'' fire. ``In the old days, they lit
smudge fires to keep the bugs away,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, FitzGerald left the smoke and salmon behind to attend
his 25th Harvard reunion and catch up with the classmates he calls
his ``outlaw friends.'' The '70s, he says, were a great time to go
to college, ``but you couldn't say we were the most responsible
people in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Like FitzGerald, like his business, and like life in general,
the friends have changed. ``I didn't perceive a whole lot of outlaw
left in them,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
