<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7508 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      06-16 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ANSWERS ON `EYES WIDE SHUT' FROM US; NEW YORKER'S STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't take the bait on the cover of the July issue of Us. Over a
photo of Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, the magazine asks, ``The
Sexiest Movie Ever?'' as if it has some kind of answer, as if
someone somehow affiliated with the magazine has seen more than the
trailer of ``Eyes Wide Shut'' and is going to tell us something _
anything _ about it. But the story is just regurgitated quotes
about how long the filming took, the close relationship between
among Kidman, Cruise, and ``control freak'' Stanley Kubrick, and
the source of the script, a 1926 novella by Austrian writer Arthur
Schnitzler. Maybe the fictional truths of Cruise's nemesis, the
National Enquirer (``TOM CRUISE &AMP; NICOLE'S SEX FILM SHOCKER''),
would be more fun than this artificially sweetened juice.
</P>
<P>
   The summer fiction issue of The New Yorker for June 21 and 28
looks like a keeper for the beach this summer, despite its silly
concept: ``20 Writers for the 21st Century.'' The 15 men and 5
women who contribute stories (five of which are excerpts of stories
that will appear in their entirety in future issues) include Ethan
Canin, David Foster Wallace, A. M. Homes, William T. Vollmann,
Michael Chabon, and Allegra Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   Fiction editor Bill Buford writes an introduction to the issue
that nicely defuses the absurd idea of choosing 20 of today's
``best'' young fiction writers _ and then offers this very clever
summary of what happened to the novel in the 20th century: ``It
would be politicized, existentialized, modernized, post-modernized,
post-post-modernized, deconstructed, and reconstructed. It would be
paperbacked, mass-marketed, pulped, and Oprahed. It would abandon
narrative, imitate thought, abandon thought, imitate formless
thought, abandon formless thought, imitate formlessness, abandon
formlessness, and rediscover form. It would become exhausted, then
die, and then somehow survive its Wake, and its many imitations. It
would be pinched by Borges, puffed out by Grass, reshaped by
Calvino, and, finally, come to rest, poised on the eve of another
century.'' Bravo!
</P>
<P>
   Will Smith seems like a nice guy, even if he does own four
sports utility vehicles, enough automotive mass to plow down the
army of a small country. (Maybe Steven Spielberg should remake his
renegade truck thriller, ``Duel,'' for the millennium, featuring a
teen on a car phone driving a SUV with tinted windows and chasing
down a sweet little old lady in a new VW bug?) Anyway, the July
Vanity Fair puts Smith on its cover, since he has gained a
reputation as the July man at the box office with summer hits
``Independence Day,'' ``Men in Black,'' and the forthcoming ``Wild
Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   The upbeat Smith is so popular, it's easy to forget that he has
appeared in only five movies. He portrays himself as a happy family
man and a casual actor except during the making of ``Six Degrees of
Separation,'' when he became too consumed with his role: ``It was
the only film I did that I didn't have fun. Just completely lost
myself _ to the point that when I came back to `The Fresh Prince'
the next year, I wasn't funny. I couldn't tell a joke to save my
life.'' He's more comfortable trying to negotiate mainstream
America through comedy, about which he has some elaborate theories:
``Black people like very real, very raw comedy. Black people like
to find comedy in what is. White people like to find comedy in what
should be or could be or would be. . . . Meaning white people look
more to escape reality in comedy. And I think a lot of it has to do
with people of oppression. Because Jews really appreciate raw, real
comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in VF, there is a long story about Ernest Hemingway
and a married woman named Jane Kendall Mason, with whom he may have
had an affair, and whom he used to create a few of his characters.
The article is written by Mason's granddaughter, based on the
letters she found in an old steamer trunk. Aside from the VF-style
literary porn aspect, which includes a photo of the old man, the
sea, and a very full moon that's not in the sky, the story becomes
increasingly interesting as Mason's therapist writes an article
that trashes Hemingway and as Mason herself ends up a tragic figure
in Greenwich Village, struggling against possession by multiple
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   In the Rolling Stone for June 24, Marilyn Manson offers up an
impassioned defense against accusations that he and his band are
somehow at the root of the youth violence that led to the Columbine
tragedy. He notes that Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold were not
Manson fans, that he became a scapegoat in the face of the
irrationality of the murders, and that humans don't need
entertainment to feel murderous. ``The day that Cain bashed his
brother Abel's brains in, the only motivation he needed was his own
human disposition to violence,'' he writes, going on to look at the
value of rock artists to youth and the fact that while two were
guilty in Colorado, we are all responsible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
