<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7509 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-16 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EQUALITY ON THE HOMEFRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before gender equality became part of the PC lexicon,
Francine M. Deutsch knew her own marriage would be a full
partnership. As far as she was concerned, there was no other way.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old Mount Holyoke social psychologist had watched
her mother push personal desires aside to satisfy the family's
needs while doing most of the work at home.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch's mother eventually found a job as a clerical worker and
became part of that second wave of women who descended on the
workplace in the 1960s. Still, the message Deutsch received from
her mother was, ``You can do more. You can have a career. You can
achieve in school. . .'' and manage a family and a home, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Deutsch wasn't sure she wanted to. ``I knew I did not have
it in me to do all the hard work at home,'' she said. ``I just did
not see myself as a super woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The women I knew growing up did not consider themselves super
women, but they were. Those who worked outside the house returned
home eight hours later to work running the home. In some cases,
husbands pitched in.
</P>
<P>
   With images of their mothers still fresh in their minds, the
daughters of those women were bent on having different lives. And
they did. Unlike their own mothers, they grappled with balancing
full-fledged careers with the demands of child care and homework.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the daughters of those super women are remaking the
rules. But role reversals don't happen overnight. And Deutsch, who
has spent 10 years studying how working couples divvy up child care
and homework, can attest to that.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, she began hearing stories about how life had
changed for women. But when she ventured past their work lives and
into their personal lives, she saw how little things had changed.
Working women, particularly middle-class professional women, were
still very much in charge of parenting.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after delving into the lives of 300 middle-class and
blue-collar couples, Deutsch has written a book that shatters some
popular myths. ``Halving It All: How Equally Shared Parenting
Works,'' (1999, Harvard University Press, $24.95), examines various
ways couples in the study chose to handle work, parenting, and
home.
</P>
<P>
   One of her key findings: Among professional, two-career couples,
the woman is still expected to shoulder much of the parenting
responsibilities. Blue-collar couples are ``the people who are
making the real changes in gender equality.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular views, she found blue-collar or
working-class couples more likely to equally share parenting than
middle-class professionals, who tend to pay outsiders to care for
their children and their homes. While professionals often have more
autonomy at work, they also spend long hours on the job and at
meetings, conferences, and other career-enhancing activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at men who are responsible for caring for
children under three, it is disproportionately blue-collar men,''
said Deutsch. ``When you look at professionals, you'll find that
nurses very often change their schedules to fit the needs of
children and child care, but other professionals are less likely
to. And, even when you look at nurses, you'll find that very often
they are married to blue-collar workers who are caring for the
children when they are working.'' Nurses and blue-collar workers
are more likely to have the option of working different shifts than
are many professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the blue-collar couples Deutsch talked to were loathe to
leave their children with ``strangers.'' They did not consider day
care an optimal form of care. Instead, they turned first to
relatives. When relatives were not available, they turned to each
other. And men in these families were more apt to change their
hours to meet their children's needs than were professional men.
Many surveyed told Deutsch the cost of day care was not a factor in
their decision to provide care within the family as opposed to
using outside providers.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of family circumstances or economic standing,
Deutsch found, women tend to do more negotiating with employers for
flexibility than men. And women were still more likely to choose
part-time work as a scheduling option than men.
</P>
<P>
   That disturbed Deutsch. ``When only one parent is doing all the
cutting back, it has long-term negative consequences for women in
the workplace. It spirals. Women end up with worse jobs, making
significantly less money than their husbands, who are taking
advantage of all the opportunities at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result,'' she said, ``his job will be more rewarding, he
will make more money, and, because he has been consistent and has
not taken time off, he will be more likely to move into a better
job.''
</P>
<P>
   In families in which husbands and wives took turns cutting back
in order to spend more time as parents, such uneven job and career
development rarely occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at her own experience, Deutsch acknowledges that
her career at a women's college and her husband's job as a
professor have made it easier to achieve the flexibility and
equality she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had very favorable circumstances,'' she said. ``Mount
Holyoke put in a maternity leave policy the year I became a parent,
back in 1986. I not only had family-friendly policies, but my
husband is a professor, too. So he had flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing, Deutsch reflected on her study's findings. ``It is
possible to create a balance,'' she said. ``Yet we often talk about
families in ways that indicate that women are always struggling to
get men to do more. That does not have to be the case, and it isn't
in some families.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating balance and deciding how parenting will be shared is
far more complex than the so-called gender wars. Instead, noted
Deutsch, what happens at work, with our friends, at home, and in
other aspects of our personal lives all influence how easy or hard
it will to be create equality at home.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis's e-mail address is work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
