<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7510 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOTECH-LEVIN-ART-BOS     06-16 1912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-LEVIN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVIN IS THE PIED PIPER OF BIOTECH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON -- Mark Levin is a television junkie who likes to
gamble and dress in drag for Halloween; last year he was a French
maid whose off-the-shoulder dress exposed a sea of moles.
</P>
<P>
   He's also the Pied Piper of the biotechnology industry.
</P>
<P>
   A cancer-research director sacrificed a joint appointment at
Massachusetts General Hospital and Harvard Medical School to follow
Levin to his new company. A Harvard professor led an exodus of nine
graduate students from his lab to work for Levin. One of Abbott
Laboratories' top scientists traded security for Levin's unproven
venture. And no fewer than six members of the National Academy of
Sciences have agreed to sit on his company's advisory board,
including Eric Lander, director of the Whitehead/MIT Center for
Genome Research.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, the founder and chief executive of Millennium
Pharmaceuticals Inc., is an unlikely man to have assembled this
stable of thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   But he has a cult-like following among the pedigreed scientists
streaming into the labs of Millennium, a Cambridge, Mass. company
whose payroll has reached 800 employees in just six years.
</P>
<P>
   What attracts them to Levin is his ambitious plan to build a
company around a yet-unproven technology. They're using discoveries
emerging from the human genome project _ a worldwide research
effort that is near its goal of mapping the 100,000 or so human
genes and billions of DNA building blocks _ to search for drugs
that will treat everything from cancer to obesity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the fundamental change'' that Millennium's research could
bring to ``biotechnology research that brought me here,'' said
Robert Tepper, who left a joint posting at Harvard and Mass.
General to join Millennium as chief scientific officer.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, whose resume includes stints as a shoe salesman, chemical
engineer, and venture capitalist, has used the golden credentials
of his scientific team to attract huge amounts of money from the
world's pharmaceutical giants to share the cost of this expensive,
cutting-edge research.
</P>
<P>
   When most biotech companies are scraping for funds, Millennium
has won commitments for $1.25 billion, spread over several years,
from the likes of Bayer AG, Eli Lilly &AMP; Co., Pfizer, and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millennium is not the only company'' raising money through
such partnerships, said Stephen Pagliuca, managing director of Bain
Capital, a Boston investment firm with no stake in Millennium.
``But they're probably doing it bigger and better than most.''
</P>
<P>
   Millennium, like any new biotech company, is hugely risky. The
company posted $10.3 million in profits last year as a result of
its pharmaceutical deals, but it has no products on the market and
its scientists are burning up $200 million a year on research.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Question unanswered
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate question for Millennium _ and Levin _ is no
different from that for any fledgling biotech firm: Can it one day
produce a drug that will make it onto pharmacy shelves?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no proof in the pudding yet,'' Pagliuca said.
</P>
<P>
   But Levin's ability to raise so much money, aided by his chief
dealmaker _ Steven Holtzman, a former Rhodes scholar who quotes
Wittgenstein around the office _ has given them the resources they
need to do their work.
</P>
<P>
   At Millennium, scientists say they can do more than they did
working for universities, while being free of the stifling
environment of well-funded US pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not limited at all. Whatever it takes,'' said Jose
Carlos Gutierrez-Ramos, senior director of inflammatory-disease
research, who marvels at his access to some 150 gene-sequencing
machines that run around the clock at Millennium. Harvard Medical
School, his previous employer, had only two.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason spectacular scientists want to come to Millennium
is because spectacular scientists work at Millennium,'' Lander
explained. ``Mark saw that from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   There is so much adrenaline pumping through Millennium that
employees admit that work can be chaotic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A series of obsessions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the hubbub is Levin, the team's inspirational
leader. Levin's mantra _ ``We believe that nothing is impossible''
_ is on every employee's mouse pad.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium's chief executive has a beachcomber persona. Though
the 48-year-old Levin likes to watch television, his life is a
series of obsessions with ever-bigger projects; it took him a
decade to renovate a turreted Victorian mansion in the
Haight-Ashbury section of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   His wit, delivered in a flat Midwestern voice, is disarming. In
a second, he becomes serious. He was determined to win a candlepin
bowling match he entered to raise college money for inner-city
students, and so he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is far more shrewd than he appears,'' said a former
employee.
</P>
<P>
   Levin's life has not followed a straight path. As a youth, he
seemed destined to follow in his father's footsteps as a St. Louis
shoe store owner.
</P>
<P>
   Levin shares his father's passion for shoes and gambling. He
owns dozens of pairs of shoes, and he recently took his wife and
baby daughter, Samantha, to the horse track at Suffolk Downs in
East Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But a painful event when he was a teenager sent his life in a
different direction. At age 16, Levin's mother died of cancer,
leaving him to care for three younger sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid just dug in, went to his books, took care of his
sisters,'' said his father, Martin Levin. ``He took care of
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   After high school graduation, Levin hung around his hometown for
a while, earning a master's in biochemical engineering from
Washington University. He sold more shoes, but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time chemical engineers were making $13,000 to
$14,000, and he was paying me, like, $7,000,'' Levin deadpanned.
``I thought maybe this isn't the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Right before leaving his hometown and close-knit family, Levin
met his future wife, Becky Levin, whom his father had hired for the
summer to work in the shoe store.
</P>
<P>
   Levin's first engineering job, in 1976, was working for Eli
Lilly in Indianapolis, but he drove home weekends in his yellow
Triumph TR-7 to see his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a statute of limitations?'' he asked, revealing that
she was 16 when they began dating. He was 24.
</P>
<P>
   At Lilly, Levin worked under William Young, a chief engineer who
would later go to Genentech, a California biotech company. Levin
``interviewed without socks,'' Young recalled, adding that Lilly
executives thought he was ``a little weird.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good at thinking differently
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Young stood by him. ``Mark _ even then you could see it _ is
good at thinking a little differently about things,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   The Levins moved to Eden, N.C., where he worked for Miller
Brewing Co. and she attended the University of North Carolina. The
move was a success, despite the ill-advised purchase of a doughnut
shop. Next, Levin worked briefly for the Foxboro Co. in Foxborough,
selling computers to the biotech industry. Among the clients he
courted was Young, who had by then moved on to Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Levin recalled saying to Young: `` `Would you be interested in a
process control system for Genentech?' And he said, `Would you be
interested in joining Genentech?' That's how I got into biotech.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, when Levin moved to the San Francisco Bay area for
Genentech, he found himself at one of the most exciting companies
in the industry's heyday. He was eventually promoted to manager of
various drug projects _ working under David Goeddel, a pioneering
scientist in the early years of biotech _ and he developed a knack
for managing complex projects.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Levin went to the Mayfield Fund, a San Francisco
venture capital firm, where he founded many companies. Millennium
was his last.
</P>
<P>
   His concept was so unusual that his wife, who is an executive
search professional, concluded after a nine-month hunt for a chief
executive that her husband was the only one with the vision _ or
understanding _ to run the company he had created. He took the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear Mark had a vision for this company that wasn't
going to translate well to someone else,'' Becky Levin said over
lunch at the Four Seasons, around the corner from the couple's
apartment on the Public Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After Levin created Millennium, it continued to evolve. The germ
of an idea for the company started with Raju Kucherlapati, who
approached Levin at the Mayfield Fund about financial backing.
Kucherlapati, now chairman of the molecular genetics department at
the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in New York, had already
founded one small company with Levin's help.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, a company that would develop gene-derived
drugs was still a novel idea. Levin became fascinated with
genomics, diving into scientific papers on gene identification. He
organized marathon brainstorming sessions with Kucherlapati,
Lander, and Jeff Friedman, a geneticist who discovered leptin, a
gene linked to obesity.
</P>
<P>
   While the scientists could see the potential for one day
understanding diseases _ and therapies _ in terms of genes, it was
Levin who translated their ideas into a commercial venture,
explained Friedman, a professor at the Howard Hughes Medical
Institute at Rockefeller University. ``I learned an enormous
amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Lander, a world-renowned biologist, was being courted by
numerous biotech firms. Levin won him over.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium's headquarters _ a few blocks from the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology _ was chosen to be close to its scientific
founders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Relentless in pursuit
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once Levin decides he wants a scientist to work at Millennium,
he is relentless. Louis Tartaglia was doing postdoctoral work for
Genentech when Levin decided he wanted him as Millennium's first
scientist. Many companies were in hot pursuit of Tartaglia; he
agreed to take the job after Levin offered the struggling student a
$10,000 signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Tartaglia's work on obesity is among the company's most
promising avenues for delivering a drug for clinical trials,
according to the company. His colleague, Karen Moore, published a
paper in March in the journal Nature reporting that her group had
successfully cloned a gene, mahogany, that suppresses obesity in
mice that overeat.
</P>
<P>
   But obesity research is but one of dozens of research projects
Millennium is pursuing. What has distinguished Millennium from
others pursuing gene-derived drugs is less their products than
their process.
</P>
<P>
   Levin's ultimate goal is to make drug discovery efficient and
productive, much like the industrial beer brewery he built for
Miller in his early career as a chemical engineer.
</P>
<P>
   The glue holding all this together is the ``bioinformatics''
group, which is using computers and data analysis to make sense of
the streams of data Millennium scientists churn out.
</P>
<P>
   Only Levin could have put it all together, say those who have
worked with him. And only Levin may know where it's going.
</P>
<P>
   Said Michael Levinthal, a Mayfield partner, ``Just give him an
office and hire him and see where it goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7512 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-RAIL-CSX-BOS &LR;      06-16 1550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-RAIL-CSX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSX BUFFS UP RAIL LINES AFTER CONRAIL TAKEOVER  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Since CSX Transportation took over Conrail's 470 miles
of rail lines in Massachusetts 12 days ago, officials have expected
that hundreds of Bay State companies would give rail shipping a new
look. Greg Conigliaro is proving them right.
</P>
<P>
   Conigliaro, president of a 10-year-old Framingham recycling
business that bears his family's name, is so excited about the
prospect of single-line access to the entire eastern United States
that he is arranging to have a rail siding built to his Fountain
Street plant, so he can start shipping by gondola cars, instead of
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Each month, Conigliaro Industries grinds up as much as 200,000
pounds of plastic for reprocessing. That includes old computer
housings that are turned into a pothole-patching material, as well
as huge piles of wood, paper, and cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a great way to move huge quantities of freight,''
Conigliaro says of the rail cars he hopes to be parking outside the
plant by year's end, each of which can hold as much as four truck
trailers. ``Anything we can do to remove the trucking aspect of
this business will be great.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years of planning, CSX and Norfolk Southern formally
took over their respective halves of the old Conrail on June 1. The
$10.3 billion takeover of the freight line created in 1976 from six
bankrupt lines in the Northeast has gone smoothly so far.
</P>
<P>
   CSX inherited all the Conrail lines in Massachusetts, including
the main line from Allston to Pittsfield. Norfolk Southern will
have competing access to the region through a connection with the
1,500-mile Guilford Rail System _ which includes the old Boston &AMP;
Maine _ at Mechanicsville, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials say the CSX takeover could revolutionize rail
traffic in the Bay State by offering local shippers for the first
time good single-line north-south service to as far away as Florida
and Louisiana. Conrail focused chiefly on east-west service to
Cleveland, Chicago, and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as a very positive step for Massachusetts,'' said
Michael P. Hogan, head of MassDevelopment, a quasipublic industrial
development corporation that issues bonds and runs a business park
at the former Fort Devens in Ayer. ``It opens up new territory and
allows for greater rail access to the South at much more
competitive prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, there are signs that the CSX takeover could lead to
increased use of the 1,058 miles of rail line in Massachusetts:
</P>
<P>
   --Braintree-based Bay Colony railroad, which runs five branch
lines feeding into CSX, has customers looking into new inbound rail
deliveries from South Carolina and outbound to Alabama, which can
be handled entirely by CSX.
</P>
<P>
   Those deals would have been hard sells if Bay Colony were still
linked to Conrail, because ``its heart was in east-to-west'' and it
had little appetite for attracting shipments requiring transfer to
a southern line, said Bernie Reagan, Bay Colony's senior vice
president for marketing and sales. He declined to identify the
customers, for competitive reasons.
</P>
<P>
   --Guilford, which already offers a ``Press Runner'' train
shipping Maine paper to Pennsylvania and Illinois, has found
enthusiastic response among Maine paper plants and other shippers
looking to move southbound shipments from trucks to rail, said
executive vice president David Fink.
</P>
<P>
   Through its New York connection to Norfolk and links to CSX at
Worcester and Springfield, Guilford customers ``now have two
choices, and all the people we have spoken to are very, very
happy,'' Fink said.
</P>
<P>
   --Several electrical parts handlers and frozen food dealers and
distributors are working to expand or locate at the Myles Standish
Industrial Park in North Taunton. The park is served by a private
spur to CSX and includes 150 as-yet-undeveloped acres open to rail
service, said Richard L. Shafer of the Taunton industrial
development commission.
</P>
<P>
   --CSX industrial development officials are helping Bay Colony
generate interest in trackside parcels along the line in locations
such as Medfield, Middleborough, and Millis, according to Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is a harder market than many other states for
railroads to crack, because there are few big industrial facilities
like chemical plants, paper mills, or auto factories, which are
well suited to train service. Both of the state's big coal-fired
power plants, in Salem and Somerset, which would otherwise be ideal
rail customers, are served by barge.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the last year for which the Association of American
Railroads has statistics, 451,076 carloads of freight moved through
Massachusetts, the equivalent of 24 50-car freight trains every
day.
</P>
<P>
   That figure includes 2.5 million tons of freight originated
within the state _ including scrap metal, containers, and mixed
freight _ and 9 million tons delivered in the state, including
piggyback trailer-on-flatcar trains.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts railroads also handle a considerable fraction of
the 3.3 million tons of pulp, paper, and lumber products shipped
from Maine to US destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation officials say the CSX takeover of Conrail offers
huge possibilities for moving truck trailers off Interstate 95 and
onto intermodal trains of the kind often seen coming to the Allston
rail yard.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Howarth, vice president of commercial operations for CSX in
Selkirk, N.Y., said CSX officials envision new markets for shipping
food, paper, packaging, structural steel, limestone, and basic
chemicals into New England from the Southeast, including clays used
in Maine paper mills.
</P>
<P>
   New outbound markets could develop for hauling scrap metal and
recyclables to Deep South processing, as well as container traffic
and general freight now riding southward in trucks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rail shipping may not turn out to be for everyone, especially
not retailers or high-tech manufacturers, which count on the rapid,
super-dependable delivery trucks can offer.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Abreu, plant manager for Northeast Refrigerated Terminals in
Taunton, a frozen food warehouse that gets deliveries from around
the United States through Bay Colony, said businesses considering
rail can save a lot of money but need to manage inventories and
schedule deliveries more carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes two or three times as long to get product, but if you
plan ahead well, you can save a lot of money,'' Abreu said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether CSX has an estimate for the possible growth of
rail shipping in Massachusetts, Howarth said: ``The truth is, we
don't know. We don't have an internal number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is really on converting the long-haul business from
truck to rail,'' Howarth said. Given the huge premium CSX paid for
its half of Conrail after an initial bidding war with Norfolk
Southern, Howarth said, ``We're going to essentially pay for this
merger with new business, and that means providing better service
and better equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   CSX plans what Howarth calls major capital investments locally,
adding switches and spurs and perhaps reinstalling second tracks
that were removed on some mainlines as rail traffic dwindled in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Sedares, general counsel to the 545-mile Providence &AMP;
Worcester railroad, said of CSX: ``They clearly are interested in
growing business in the region. They have a fairly aggressive
marketing strategy, which they have asked us to work on. Overall,
we think it's positive for the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the P&AMP;W saw a 9.3 percent increase in container
loads, to 47,000 containers, and a 14 percent increase in
freightcar traffic, to 34,800 carloads. P&AMP;W officials are hopeful
their connection to CSX in Worcester can help boost growth further.
</P>
<P>
   Conrail _ now dubbed ``GoneRail'' by some industry insiders _
earned high marks for creating profitable and reliable service from
once moribund Northeastern lines, such as the Penn Central. But
many see a much more gung-ho attitude toward attracting new
business from CSX.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conrail was a good company with good people, but CSX is
bringing in a whole new level of marketing and expertise,'' said
Conigliaro, the Framingham recycler. Four years ago, he considered
having a siding installed, but Conrail's price was far higher than
CSX is proposing.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Cogley, economic development director for the MetroWest
Chamber of Commerce in Framingham, said area business people were
impressed with the enthusiasm of CSX officials when they held a
rail-shipping conference earlier this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the railroads have kind of woken up and realized they
are in the transportation business, and they better start
competing,'' Cogley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Colony's Reagan, who worked for Conrail in the 1970s, said
he already sees from CSX ``a new, fresh look at north-south
traffic, a different attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With Conrail, they'd say, `We'll talk to you after we get
through with the Chicago guys,' but then they never got through
with the Chicago guys and just didn't care'' about shippers looking
to move goods to or from southern destinations, Reagan said. ``It
was just not what they wanted, and they just didn't think it was
what God wanted them to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
