<HEADLINE>
MELTDOWN OF NET STOCKS DOESN'T DROWN MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since the Internet stocks began their meteoric rise,
investors have lived with one overriding fear: that when the stocks
collapsed, it would be like the assassination of Archduke
Ferdinand, the trigger for much wider carnage. (Think World War I.)
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks haven't totally collapsed, but they have fallen
a long way. Most are down 40 to 50 percent in the past two months.
But guess what? The stock market as a whole has largely ignored the
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the major market averages have dropped since Internet
stocks peaked in early April, but the declines have been modest and
most of the loss can be attributed to rising interest rates. So far
at least, the Internet damage has been confined to the Internet
sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very positive development,'' says Philip Schettewi, a
money manager for Loomis Sayles in Washington. Rather than head for
the hills, says Schettewi, investors have simply moved their money
to other places. Economically sensitive stocks have attracted more
money; so have small and mid-cap stocks; even certain technology
stocks have done better.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've had a whole series of separate games going on in the
stock market,'' says Larry Haverty, senior vice president for State
Street Research. ``It turns out that the Internet game was only one
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet game has not been much fun to play since April when
reality began to set in. Amazon.com contributed to the mood shift
in late April when it announced it would take longer to achieve
profitability than previously anticipated. Internet investors to
that point had been very tolerant of losses, but the Amazon news
made them wonder whether they had been too trusting.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates have hurt too. Because Internet companies
will earn their money sometime in the future, higher rates make
those earnings worth less in today's dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the electronic brokerage stocks took a nasty tumble when
Charles Schwab said its on-line trading volume declined in May.
America Online, the closest thing to an Internet blue chip, has
been hurt by suggestions that its membership numbers are not
climbing as fast as they once were.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together and what you get is a major correction.
Amazon is down 55 percent from its springtime high; America Online
is down 43 percent; CMGI, an Andover company with stakes in a group
of Internet companies, is off 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So why hasn't the stock market collapsed in sympathy?
</P>
<P>
   Ned Riley offers one possible explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet buyer has always been a different breed of cat,''
says Riley, chief investment officer for BankBoston. According to
Riley, Internet stocks have been driven by individual investors,
rather than institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   The amateurs fell in love with the Internet, he says, and they
are the ones who have had their hearts and finances broken while
the professionals have mostly watched from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The institutions haven't felt the pain,'' says Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Haverty makes much the same argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a certain group of people have been investing in the
Internet area,'' he says. ``You've had some very aggressive funds
and an enormous amount of public speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, big-time investors haven't avoided all the pain.
Statistics gathered by Thomson Financial Securities Data show that
Fidelity Investments has bought its share of Internet stocks. As of
the end of the first quarter of 1999, Fidelity owned 3 percent of
America Online, 8 percent of CMGI, and 2 percent of Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   There's another possible explanation for the market's relative
indifference to the Internet meltdown. Simply put, this is one
awfully resilient stock market. Over the past two years the market
has managed to survive the Asian financial crisis, the Russian
financial crisis, the near-impeachment of a president, a war in
Europe, and several inflation scares.
</P>
<P>
   The market has sagged, but it has never collapsed. Investors
still apparently believe that the US economy can continue to grow
at a decent pace without generating much inflation. That assumption
may yet prove incorrect, but until it does the stock market is
likely to hang around.
</P>
<P>
   Given their lofty valuations, Internet stocks could still fall a
long way from here. If the recent past is any guide, however, the
rest of us won't have to fall along with them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
