<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BIOTECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY TOUTS BAY STATE'S POTENTIAL AS MAJOR DRUG DEVELOPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- As pharmaceutical companies look past their own
laboratories for breakthrough drugs, Massachusetts _ with its
world-renowned medical research community _ is attracting
significant industry investments and has the potential to become an
international player in drug development, concludes a new report.
</P>
<P>
   Government money has been pouring in as well, according to the
report by Anurag Sharma, an assistant professor of management at
the University of Massachusetts at Amherst. Last year,
Massachusetts received $1.2 billion of the $11.2 billion the
National Institutes of Health awarded nationwide, trailing only
California in funding.
</P>
<P>
   But Massachusetts, relatively weak in drug manufacturing, had
better watch its back, as New York, Pennsylvania, Maryland, and
North Carolina look to attract major drug firm research and
manufacturing, the report warns.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``The Economic Impact of the Pharmaceutical Industry in
Massachusetts,'' Sharma's work was funded by industry trade group
Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role that Massachusetts will play in the pharmaceutical
industry of the next millennium will be driven by the strength of
research in its universities and institutions and by the ability of
the general economic infrastructure to support investments,'' the
report concludes. ``Conversely, the economic impact of the
pharmaceutical industry on the Commonwealth will be greatly
influenced by the perception about how attractive it is to make
investments in the
</P>
<P>
   state and local economies.''
</P>
<P>
   That bullish outlook stems from rapid changes within the large
pharmaceutical firms, which have recognized that the next
generation of medicine will come from research-intensive areas such
as Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Already, pharmaceutical giants such as Pfizer Inc. have
established research facilities in Cambridge, while Merck &AMP; Co. is
reportedly looking to build its own laboratories in Boston's Fenway
area, not far from the Longwood Medical Area.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Amgen Inc., the nation's largest biotechnology firm,
will break ground on an eight-story research center in Cambridge's
Kendall Square, next door to Genzyme Corp., the state's largest
biotech company. And last week, American Home Products broke ground
for a second research facility in Cambridge for its Genetics
Institute subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, according to Sharma's report, could become ``the
center of gravity for the global pharmaceutical industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, many big US and foreign drug companies have made hefty
investments in local emerging biotechnology firms to gain access to
promising new drugs and collaborative relationships with Boston
area research universities and teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The UMass study _ based in part on a survey mailed to 210
biotechnology and pharmaceutical firms operating in Massachusetts _
noted that of the 32 that responded, nearly all had significant
links to research universities in Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $1.2 billion federal funding Massachusetts received last
year, $630 million went to a wide range of universities, teaching
hospitals, and other research organizations in Greater Boston, well
ahead of the amounts received by New York, San Diego, Philadelphia,
and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Private industry and venture capitalists also spent a hefty
amount in the growing biopharmaceutical industry, which employs
more than 12,500 in Massachusetts in drug-related commercial
research. Combined with the nonprofit sector, 25,000 people do
medical research-related work in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Bay State's biopharmaceutical community is to
prosper, says Sharma, it must address shortcomings in
biomanufacturing and remain competitive with other states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
