<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7517 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-BLACK-MEN-BO     06-16 1601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-BLACK-MEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CODE FOR MEN OF COLOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Kohls makes it his business to look for gaps in the magazine
market. He found one a year and a half ago as he perused men's
fashion magazines at airport newsstands. He saw industry stalwarts
like GQ and Esquire. He spied young upstarts like Maxim, Gear,
P.O.V., and Men's Health.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to a style magazine focused on the interests
and needs of black men, there was nothing. Zilch.
</P>
<P>
   So Kohls headed back to the Los Angeles office of Larry Flynt
Publications (better known as LFP), where he is president. Soon he
was pitching the idea of launching a black GQ to Flynt, who's best
known for publishing Hustler.
</P>
<P>
   LFP put together an editorial team headed by A.G. Britton, a
magazine veteran who launched Mirabella, Marie Claire, and Mode;
and Quincy Troupe, a poet, writer, and professor. On June 1, Code
began popping up on newsstands nationwide with a dapper Samuel L.
Jackson gazing from its cover.
</P>
<P>
   A glossy monthly style magazine, Code showcases a dazzling array
of chocolate-covered eye candy sporting long nubian locks, short
Afros, and bold baldies. It slaps poetry next to fashion
photographs of Saul Williams, a poet who starred in the recent
indie film ``Slam.'' It pairs luxurious Dolce &AMP; Gabbana suits with
less pricey BCBG shirts. It hilariously delves into the subject of
women stalkers and more somberly explores the relationship between
fathers and sons.
</P>
<P>
   Troupe, Code's editorial director, says it's the kind of
magazine he and other black men have been looking for for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at myself as a barometer for all the ingredients that
should go into this magazine,'' says Troupe, 59. ``I like great
food. I like to travel. I like great art. I like great books. I
like to look at beautiful women. I like style and clothes. I like
really interesting discussions and debates. And I like to talk
about money and health.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's the kind of magazine I'd like to see produced,''
Troupe continues. ``For many many years I've had to go to GQ and
Vanity Fair and Esquire to get what I have not been able to get at
any black magazine. I think there's a lot of men out there like
me.''
</P>
<P>
   A professor at the University of California-San Diego (he's on
sabbatical until September 2000), Troupe spoke about the magazine
from his La Jolla, Calif., home. His enthusiasm was initially
tempered after laser eye surgery for cataracts left a bandage over
his left eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be a great pirate with a patch,'' Troupe jokes, before
his inner editor takes over. ``I could make a style statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Troupe was hired for his fashion sensibilities. Britton, who
could be a voice double for Fran Drescher, speaks admiringly of
Troupe's ability to mix an ``Armani suit with some fantastic piece
of leather and shells on his wrist just to give it a twist.''
</P>
<P>
   Britton, Code's publication director, also wanted Troupe for his
connections. ``He knows everybody,'' she says. ``And you want an
editor with a big ole fat Rolodex of writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Having been down the black magazine road before, Troupe
initially resisted Britton's advances. In the 1980s, he had tried
to start two fashion magazines for black men. But cutthroat
experiences in New York's magazine industry turned him off, so he
started work on ``Miles: The Autobiography,'' his acclaimed book
about jazz man Miles Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ensconced in LFP's Los Angeles office, Britton and Troupe
have found a magazine world in which they can exhale. As the team
scrambles to shape Code to readers' approval, Britton says she's
happy she's not in New York where editors must parade in Prada
pumps to work the fashion industry. And Troupe rapturously talks
about the ``harmonious'' office where he and Britton make editorial
and style decisions.
</P>
<P>
   While Code is LFP's first upscale lifestyle magazine, it's not
its first mainstream title. About half of LFP's stable of more than
20 magazines focus on subjects such as hip-hop, skateboarding,
video games, boating, and police tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a diverse lineup of focused special-interest
magazines,'' says Tony Silber, editorial director of Folio, a trade
magazine examining the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Now LFP is taking on the tough niche market where
African-American magazines such as Ebony, Black Enterprise, Vibe,
and Essence reign. How tough is it? Five years ago Roy S. Johnson,
an editor-at-large at Time Inc.'s Fortune magazine, pitched the
idea for Savoy, a Vanity Fair-style magazine aimed at affluent
African Americans. The project remains in limbo because Time
executives are worried about finding an audience, says Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of publishers are reluctant to jump into the fray for
whatever reasons,'' he says. ``But there are a lot of younger,
bolder entrepreneurs and publishers who are not afraid to see if
there's a portion of that market that would be interested in
something that they have to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   One such title, Honey, aimed at young black women, debuted in
February. But for every Honey there's an Ebony Man, which ceased
publication last year when Johnson Publishing Company decided to
fold men's features into Ebony, its popular title.
</P>
<P>
   Britton thinks Ebony Man made its own deathbed. ``There are
things you have to pay for in order for consumers and advertisers
to take you seriously,'' she says. ``One is paper, the other is
photography and all that goes into it, meaning the stylist,
location, etc. Ebony Man just did not do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Code definitely does. LFP will spend about $500,000 to $1
million on each issue, says Britton. It's a substantial investment
in a business where a modest start-up may cost $80,000 for six
issues, says Silber.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing African-American magazines don't do is introduce
new editorial talent, says Troupe. ``We wait until the dominant
culture says OK, then we do something with them.'' But Code plans
to introduce new faces (and veteran ones you didn't know about)
before mainstream publications make their moves. In the first issue
Code featured Jesse Allen, a young Los Angeles fashion designer,
and Paris Barclay, an award-winning African-American director and
supervising producer of ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach seems to be working. Although Code officially hit
newstands June 1, some stores put it on display earlier.
</P>
<P>
   At a Borders Books Music &AMP; Cafe in Washington, D.C., which
Troupe visited in May for a poetry reading with Nikki Giovanni, a
woman attending the event discovered Code in the store. ``She said,
`It's beautiful; you have to go see it' '' to others in the
audience, recalls Troupe. ``It started a stampede of people trying
to get this magazine. They bought every one within an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   That enthusiasm seems to be catching. ``Where we got it out
early it either sold out immediately or in a couple of days,'' says
Perry Grayson, LFP's vice president of advertising. ``The magazine
has really been noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Code has an initial circulation of 500,000. LFP's circulation
powerhouse, Hustler, sells between half a million to a million
copies a month. If Code remains this hot, ``there's a potential
this could be the biggest magazine we publish,'' says Grayson.
</P>
<P>
   But Code still has the fickle male consumer to contend with.
</P>
<P>
   ``While (GQ and Esquire) are successful magazines, none of them
comes close to the typical successful women's books,'' says
Johnson. ``It's a risk whenever you aim your editorial at men that
you won't get to a certain target.''
</P>
<P>
   But Britton believes the style savvy of men of color will keep
them addicted to Code's pages. Both she and Troupe hitch Code's
growth and survival to its editorial content. There's plenty of
talk about bringing Code's writing up to New Yorker and Vanity Fair
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Editorial quality is really critical for us,'' says Britton.
</P>
<P>
   For upcoming issues Troupe has secured exclusive excerpts of new
work by Walter Mosley, Ishmael Reed, and John Edgar Wideman. He's
pulling in young black writers such as Nelson George and Kevin
Powell, and experienced African-American journalists such as the
Los Angeles Times's Sam Fulwood 3d, New York Times sports columnist
William C. Rhoden, and perhaps even syndicated columnist Clarence
Page, who slipped Troupe his business card after flipping through
Code during Troupe's Borders appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Troupe wants to publish stories about the black community not
seen in the mainstream press. For example, a profile of Mike Espy,
the beleaguered former Agriculture Secretary recently acquitted of
corruption charges; and Death Row Records founder Suge Knight's
possible role in the shooting deaths of hip-hop artists Tupac
Shakur and Notorious B.I.G.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to look at every aspect of American life that affects
us critically,'' says Troupe. ``Some of it is not going to cast
(blacks) in a good light. But we want to hang dirty laundry out. I
think we can deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, well-dressed celebrities aren't left out of the mix. The
September issue features an interview and cover shot of Danny
Glover. And Troupe drops the names of film icons, basketball stars,
and politicians _ from Charles Rangel to Allen Iverson _ as
possible Code cover guys.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next year when Troupe returns to the university?
Plans are being made to hire an editor and retain Troupe as
editorial director. ``The three of us will kind of run it,'' says
Troupe, adding tenaciously, ``I'm going to be involved in this
magazine until they kick me out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
