<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7520 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WAR-CRIMES-HN     06-16 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WAR-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDE CONCEDES MILOSEVIC MAY GAIN SAFE HAVEN IN SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A White House spokesman Wednesday welcomed the Serbian
Orthodox Church's call for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to
resign but conceded that the indicted war criminal might obtain
safe haven inside his own country if he steps down.
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, spokesman for President Clinton's National Security
Council, said Milosevic should step aside as demanded by Serbia's
influential Orthodox Church because he remains ``an international
pariah.''
</P>
<P>
   Leavy added that Serbia won't receive international help in
reconstruction as long as Milosevic remains in power. ``The only
question is how far are the Serbian people going to let Milosevic
drag their country down before they replace him,'' Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Holy Synod of the Serbian Orthodox Church demanded
Milosevic's resignation Tuesday ``in the interest of the people and
their salvation.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's governing body said the Serbian people have to
accept that the ``isolation of our country on the international
scene cannot be solved or overcome with this kind of government and
under the present circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The 15-nation European Union and the 19-nation North Atlantic
Treaty Organization have vowed to withhold all reconstruction
assistance from Serbia until Milosevic steps down. Estimates for
reconstruction costs for the region exceed $50 billion over the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and his top aides were indicted last month on war
crimes' charges by the International Criminal Tribunal for the
former Yugoslavia (ICTY) headquartered in the Hague, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal for Milosevic's resignation came as the British-led
Kosovo security force (KFOR) found more suspected mass graves in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The graves are believed to contain the remains of hundreds, if
not thousands, of victims of Yugoslavia's murderous campaign of
``ethnic cleansing'' against ethnic Albanian Muslims who have
occupied Kosovo since the Ottoman Turkish invasion of the Balkans
in the 14th century.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs' campaign that began in March uprooted 1.6 million
Kosovars, including more than 800,000 who fled to neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
   NATO under U.S. leadership carried out a 78-day bombing campaign
against Yugoslav forces to force cessation of the ethnic cleansing
and clear the way for the return of ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Leavy said the 50,000-member NATO force moving into the Yugoslav
province of Kosovo is ``gathering evidence'' of war crimes that
will be presented to the international war crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Troops are assigned as well to arrest indicted Yugoslav war
criminals if they are identified among the retreating troops. No
arrests have been made so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incumbent on all nations coming into contact with war
criminals to bring them into custody,'' Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House official declined to discuss any plans for
seizing Milosevic or his lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials conceded, however, that NATO
forces operating in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo will not be in
a position to seize Milosevic if he remains inside Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces in Serbia remain heavily armed, officials said,
making it virtually impossible for the allies to stage a guerrilla
raid on Belgrade or other Milosevic strongholds to seize indicted
war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   One official conceded: ``I don't see us going into Belgrade to
grab up Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite long-standing indictments against alleged war criminals
from the four-year war in Bosnia, Bosnian Serb leaders Ratko Mladic
and Radovan Karadic remain free inside Serbian-controlled territory
in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Robin Clifford, a spokesman for KFOR in Kosovo, said
Wednesday that allied forces are finding ``a number of burial
sites'' but have not compiled an overall list of suspected graves
or suspected victims.
</P>
<P>
   When suspected burial sites are found, Clifford said, ``We
secure the area to ensure that nobody else can get in there to
disturb any evidence there may well be, but also of course to
ensure that the area is clear of any possible mines or booby traps
there might be there.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea, speaking at alliance headquarters in
Brussels, Belgium, said that ``one of the more harrowing aspects''
of KFOR's deployment has been the discovery of more mass graves
than NATO had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Allied forces also are finding evidence of ``atrocity sites,''
Shea said, referring to buildings where ethnic Albanians were
killed and their bodies left without burial.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said about 300 war crimes investigators are due in Kosovo
in coming days to ``get on the site quickly to gather the evidence
before refugees return or before people have a chance to tamper
with that evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Bureau of Investigation has joined the effort to
unearth war crimes' evidence in Kosovo. FBI Director Louis J. Freeh
announced in Washington, D.C., that 25 FBI investigators and
forensic specialists are being sent to Kosovo to collect evidence
of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The team will assess the need for more personnel from the FBI
and the U.S. Armed Forces Institute of Pathology to carry out the
task of proving crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI routinely investigates mass murders in the United
States. FBI agents also took part in war crimes' investigations in
Rwanda and Bosnia, as well as investigations following terrorist
bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
