<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, June 17:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 3 pages of Kosovo-related stories:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Vermitca) _ Some 30,000 deliriously happy
refugees pour over the border from Albania. Overwhelmed, the U.N.
refugee agency gives up trying to register them. By Elisabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RETURN (Sopi) _ A vignette on the return of one refugee
to his burned-out home. Formerly well off, he finds everything now
been looted or burned. He will bring his family from Albania and
set up a tent where his house once stood. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina) _ Developments: NATO gives the Serbs an
extra 24 hours to pull out of the Pristina area since roads are
clogged with refugees; the Russian resupply convoy is heading to
the airport; the Albanian rebel group, the KLA, says that the
Russians are enemies and there can be no peace until they leave. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Helsinki) _ Defense Secretary Cohen is in Finland
for talks. The Russians say the KLA must be disarmed because of its
``enemy'' comment. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Thomas R. Pickering, the undersecretary
of state, holds talks with the Chinese on the Embassy bombing in
Belgrade. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ The Kosovar capital is flickering
back to life as Albanians open shops and restaurants and return to
the streets. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Britain is proposing a resolution
that could result in the lifting sanctions against Iraq. By Judith
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-INAUG (Pretoria) _ Nelson Mandela retires as Thabo Mbeki
is inaugurated as South Africa's president. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM (Washington) _ On the eve of the Richard
Holbrooke confirmation hearings, a look at the controversies
surrounding his appointment as the U.S. envoy to the United
Nations. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-QUAKE (Puebla, Mexico) _ Folo on the earthquake: 15 are
reported dead, 200 injured. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LABOR (Paris) _ Appealing for a ``human face'' on the
global economy, President Clinton urged the International Labor
Organization to adopt a treaty that would ban the most abusive
child labor practices, including the use of children in pornography
and prostitution. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA (Seoul) _ North Korea says it is suspending visits between
North and South. U.S. warplanes join South Korean aircraft in
patrols. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSENT (Beijing) _ Chinese authorities arrest some
leaders of a large farmer demonstration held last February. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   POPE (Dateline to kum, Poland) _ Pope John Paul II, after a sick
day, resumes his schedule, but doesn't deliver a planned homily. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOMSDAY (Dublin) _ Bloomsday in Dublin, celebrating James
Joyce's novel ``Ulysses,'' and the travels of its protagonist,
Leonard Bloom, around Dublin on June 16, 1904. And a look at David
Norris, a Protestant who does a one-man Joyce show and is the
national champion of gay rights in Parliament. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ Voting planned today on the
juvenile crime bill and 44 amendments on everything from school
prayer to the banning violent books. By Alison Mitchell and Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS-DINGELL (Washington) _ The leading Democratic
opponent to gun control, Rep. John D. Dingell, is one of the
most-feared members of the House. A profile, with special attention
to the Dingell amendment. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS-SCENE (Washington) _ A Capitol Hill sketchbook:
The long day's miasma of guns, movies, politics. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED-INSURE (Washington) _ Senate passes bill that will
allow disabled people to keep their federal health insurance when
they return to work. A similar bill enjoys wide support in the
House. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-WEALTH (Washington) _ Members of the House of
representatives issue their annual financial disclosure forms. By
Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Carthage, Tenn.) _ Signaling his independence
from Bill Clinton, Vice President Al Gore formally begins his
pursuit of the presidency, promising to make the crisis in the
family the centerpiece of his campaign. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (San Francisco) _ Bill Bradley has campaigned
up and down California this week: personally, peacefully, almost
obliquely. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SUV-BUMPERS (Detroit) _ The Institute for Highway Safety issues
a report saying that sport utility vehicles have such weak bumpers
that any small crash is really expensive. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-BAPTISTS (Atlanta) _ Southern Baptists criticize
President Clinton for appointing gay ambassadors and other
policies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ In a report that may influence the Fed's
decisions on interest rates, the Commerce Department said consumer
prices held steady in May after an April jump that was the largest
in nearly nine years. Commerce also reported that construction of
new homes and apartments posted a significant increase of 6.3
percent in May, after a drop of 9.7 percent the month before. And
the Federal Reserve reported that industrial production rose in May
for the fourth month, slightly slower than analysts had projected.
Stocks and bonds both rose solidly in the wake of the reports. By
Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the Dow industrial average was up
171 points, or 1.6 percent, and the Nasdaq index up 90 points, or
3.7 percent. Elsewhere, prices fell 0.4 percent in Tokyo and rose
1.7 percent in Hong Kong. They gained 0.7 percent in Frankfurt,
rose 0.8 percent in London, increased 3 percent in Brazil and
soared 5.3 percent in Mexico. On the American debt market, the long
bond was up 22/32 point, with the yield at 6.05 percent. By Robert
D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-FRAUD (New York) _ The U.S. attorney in Brooklyn charges
nine brokerages with fraud and corruption in the bilking of small
investors of more than $100 million. By Joseph P. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EUROPE (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Developments in the recall of
Coca-Cola products in Europe. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developments at the Microsoft
antitrust trial. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   SOTHEBY-AMAZON (New York) _ Five months after Sotheby's started
its own on-line auction business, it has entered into a strategic
alliance with Amazon.com. The two will begin selling art and
collectibles later this year. Under the agreement, Amazon is making
a $35 million investment in the York Avenue auction house. By Carol
Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-TELECOM (Tokyo) _ Having won a hostile takeover battle for
the International Digital Corp., Cable and Wireless PLC, the
British telecommunications company, said it was in talks to gain
access to domestic telephone lines in Japan, either through the
purchase of or alliance with a domestic telephone business. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-OIL (Sao Paulo) _ Brazil concludes a two-day oilfield
auction. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By
Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   William Safire's ``Essay'' and Bob Herbert's ``In America.''
</P>
