<SLUG> BC-HOME-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, June 17:
</P>
<P>
   TIFFANY-WINDOWS (New York) _ The colors are warmest in winter,
when the sun's rays are low in the sky and envelop the
stained-glass horizon in amber light. ``This window is certainly
alive,'' Rev. Gerald Johnson was saying the other day, sitting in
the pews of the Sage Memorial First Presbyterian Church in Far
Rockaway, Queens, contemplating the unsung Louis Comfort Tiffany
masterpiece with great gnarled branches. Tiffany designed stained
glass windows such as this ``Tree of Life,'' his largest landscape,
to be sacred. They still are _ not only in distant urban reaches
like Far Rockaway _ but in thousands of quiet corners of the
country. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-ENTRY (Undated) _ A gateway, or introduction, to a garden
can create a sense of drama or stir curiosity about what lies
beyond. And as in an interior foyer, the first impression created
by a garden entrance depends on what you want to make it. By Martha
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   OLMSTED-BOOK (New York) _ As boaters clunked their oars on the
lake, Witold Rybczynski folded his big frame onto a little chair by
a tiny cafe table at the boathouse and talked about how he came to
write about the man who created Central Park almost a century and a
half ago. ``I think I thought about the notion of biography
first,'' said Rybczynski, whose new book, ``A Clearing in the
Distance: Frederick Law Olmsted and America in the Nineteenth
Century'' (Scribner), takes an intimate look at the man who first
joined the two words, landscape and architecture, and made it an
art. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
