<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Confessions of a second-generation
newspaper addict
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: For Father's Day, June 20.)
</P>
<P>
   (``Dispatches from Dreamsville`` is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox senior writer Joe Murray their
memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or at
least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Lois Oller Nasados
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   An old Strickland Gillilan poem ends with the words, ``I had a
mother who read to me!''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, many of us can also say, ``I had a father who read to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   I remember sitting on my father's knee _ very quietly _ while he
read the Chicago Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The next-to-last page was my page, the comics. He would read
them to me using a full range of voices and facial expressions that
never failed to delight me.
</P>
<P>
   My mother had her doubts about reading to me from the newspaper,
with all its crime and violence and s-e-x.
</P>
<P>
   But how could she object when her darling daughter was almost
falling off Daddy's lap, laughing at the antics of ``Li'l Abner''
or breathless to learn what new dangers awaited ``Brenda Starr,
Reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, waiting for the comics page to appear, I'd ask about
a picture that caught my eye, usually a photo of a child or an
animal.
</P>
<P>
   My daddy's explanations were, I'm sure, carefully edited, but
there was always an answer.
</P>
<P>
   As I began to learn my alphabet, he would share his adult-sized
pencil, and as he directed, I would carefully enter a capital
letter in a tiny square on his crossword puzzle. Did I feel smart!
</P>
<P>
   In these days of 24-hour newscasts in living color, my day still
includes at least one newspaper, and when I travel there's no
better way to learn about a new community than by reading the local
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   I mourn each time another big-city daily ceases publication, yet
I'm firmly convinced that there are enough newspaper addicts
breeding more newspaper addicts that we needn't worry.
</P>
<P>
   Until someone invents a laptop computer that feels as good in
the hand as unrolling the morning paper, there will always be a
real newspaper to flavor our morning coffee.
</P>
<P>
   (Lois Oller Nasados makes her home in Longview, Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to Dispatches from
Dreamsville, c/o Joe Murray, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915.
If your article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
