<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7548 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS &LR;      06-16 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONE DRUG MAY LOWER RISK OF BREAST CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A drug given to post-menopausal women to combat
bone disease has been found to dramatically reduce the risk of
breast cancer, according to a study published Wednesday in the
Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   In the international study of 7,705 women with osteoporosis, the
drug raloxifene lowered the risk of all types of breast cancer by
76 percent, said Dr. Steven Cummings of the University of
California at San Francisco. Cummings headed the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The drug was even more effective on the form of breast cancer
common among older women, he said, reducing by 90 percent the type
of cancer associated with estrogen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In medicine, we don't see 90 percent reductions in the risk of
a disease,'' Cummings said. ``The magnitude of the effect has been
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cummings and a Journal editorial cautioned that the drug _ a
designer estrogen that sells under the brand name Evista _ is not a
silver bullet cure and should not be used by the general population
to reduce the risk of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   As with all medicine, there are side effects. And more research
is needed, said Cummings, to determine the drug's effectiveness
over the long term, its impact on menstruating women and on those
not suffering from osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Medical researchers have long sought ways of reducing breast
cancer _ the most common form of cancer and the second leading
cause of cancer death among women.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 175,000 women in the United States will be
diagnosed with cancer this year, according to the American Cancer
Society. About 43,500 U.S. women died of breast cancer in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen, a drug related to raloxifene, has been approved by
the Food and Drug Administration to fight breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen has been shown to be effective among women who have a
high risk of breast cancer, but most breast cancers occur in women
who are not identified to be at a high risk, according to the
study.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, studies have shown that tamoxifen increases the
risk of uterine cancer, a side effect not true for raloxifene.
Tamoxifen has not been studied for osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   Both raloxifene and tamoxifen can increase blood clots in the
veins, which can be fatal if they travel to the lungs. Like
estrogen, the drugs are therefore not recommended for women with a
history of vein or blood-clotting diseases.
</P>
<P>
   A head-to-head comparison of tamoxifen and raloxifene was
recently launched under the auspices of the National Cancer
Institute. Some 22,000 women are expected to take part.
</P>
<P>
   In the raloxifene study, the women were tracked for a median of
40 months. Twenty-seven of the 2,576 women who were given a placebo
sugar pill were diagnosed with breast cancer compared with only 13
cases among the 5,129 women given raloxifene. The cancer rate among
the raloxifene women was the same whether they received daily doses
of 60 mg or 120 mg.
</P>
<P>
   Hot flashes, flu-like symptoms, water retention and leg cramps
were reported more frequently in the raloxifene group than in the
placebo group. There was also a higher rate of deep vein thrombosis
and pulmonary embolism, clots blocking a vein, (55 cases, or 1
percent) among the raloxifene users than in the placebo group
(eight cases, or 0.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The study was originally intended to determine whether a
three-year treatment with raloxifene was effective in reducing the
risk of bone fracture in postmenopausal women with osteoporosis.
The results of that study will be published soon, Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Lilly &AMP; Co., the drug company that manufactures Evista,
sponsored the study. The 7,705 participants in 180 clinical centers
across the United States and in two dozen European countries were
also monitored for breast cancer as a secondary mission of the
study, Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the participants were white. Women who had a history
of breast cancer or who were taking estrogen were excluded. The
study will now be extended with the same control group for an
additional four years to track the long-term effects of the drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
