<HEADER>
A7575 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT17-COX     06-16 1800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, June 17,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ CARTHAGE, Tenn. _ Vowing moral leadership, Vice President
Al Gore formally announced his presidential candidacy Wednesday
with a family-oriented speech that put some distance between him
and President Clinton. (Shepard, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (p) politics and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ MORINI, Albania _ Thousands of Kosovar Albanian
refugees, despite NATO warnings about landmines and boobie trapped
houses, are crossing the border here to return to their homes in
Kosovo. The Yugoslav withdrawal from the zone extending from
Pristina to the southern border was largely completed by its
midnight deadline, except for isolated cases of soldiers in
broken-down vehicles. NATO gave the Serbs anouther 24 hours.
Meanwhile, U.S. and Russian foreign and defense ministers meet in
Helsinki to hammer out Russia's role in Kosovo peacekeeping.
Developing. (Albright-Kunstel, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MASSACRE _ KORENICA, Yugoslavia _ It is likely the worst
massacre of the Serb ethnic cleansing campaign. Mark Barishe died
because he couldn't drive a tractor. Vengeful Serb troops were
going to let the 68-year-old man get away. But when he told them
that he couldn't drive a tractor, they took him back into his house
with five others, lined them up against the bedroom wall. ``Aren't
you people too,'' he pleaded. But when the Catholic Albanian began
to cross his heart, a Serb soldier said, ``It's too late for you
now.'' And now five charred bodies mark the most gruesome scene
from a rampage in which up to 300 Kosovar Albanians were massacred
to avenge the death of five Serb policemen. (Kaplow, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ MORINI, Albania _ Why are the refugees risking
life and limb to retun to a perilous Kosovo province ahead of NATO
approval? We ask some of them for their very personal stories.
Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DEATHS _ KUKES, Albania _ Peace did not come soon enough
for Halil Emini. He did not get killed by Yugoslav forces or NATO
bombs. He just drowned last Friday while swimming with his children
near their refugee camp. Now, instead of planning a return to his
homeland as many are Tuesday, Emini lies under a mound of dirt on a
plateau with 140 other deceased ethnic Albanians who fled Kosovo
during the Serbs' ethnic cleansing campaign. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Updating, re-sending for Cox papers.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ GENEVA/PARIS _ President Clinton addresses
International Labour Organisation annual conference. He will also
meet Swiss President Ruth Dreifuss before travelling on to visit
French President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin in
Paris to discuss bilateral ties and Kosovo. (Deans, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-REACT _ GENT, Belgium _ Talk about an image problem.
Coca-Cola Co., the Atlanta-based soft drink giant, couldn't have
picked a worse time to endure the embarrasing exposure of Belgium's
ban on its products because of concerns about its safety. Europeans
are growing increasingly worried about the wholesomeness of the
food and beverages they eat and drink after a series of highly
publicized episodes ranging from mad cow disease to genetically
modified foods _ known in Britain as Frankenstein foods. This
attitude reflects a
</P>
<P>
   growing feeling of distrust among Europeans toward the
governments that are supposed to protected them from contaminated
products. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE _ WASHINGTON _ House to begin debate on gun control
bill. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GULFTRAIT _ WASHINGTON _ Texas researchers reported Wednesday
that they have found a genetic trait that appears to have made some
persons more vulnerable to ``Gulf War Syndrome.'' (Nesmith, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE _ WASHINGTON _ Concluding a three-day round of events
involving the high-tech industry and the federal government, the
Business Software Alliance releases a report on the contributions
of the U.S. software industry to the economy and high-tech public
policy issues, including encryption, privacy and the Y2K bug.
(Glass, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS _ ATLANTA _ Live coverage of second, and last, day of
annual meeting of the Southern Baptist Convention. Reggie White,
the ex-football player and fundamentalist Christian, speaks at 6:30
p.m. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-NOTES _ ATLANTA _ Notebook from the Southern Baptist
Convention. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CDC-POLIO _ ATLANTA _ CDC is expected to change its
recommendations on nationwide polio inoculations Wednesday,
requiring only the shot - and not the oral vaccine that has been
implicated in some cases of polio. (McKenna, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Also moving in the (l) Lifestyle category.
</P>
<P>
   FAULDER _ LONGVIEW, Texas _ Setup piece for the Faulder
execution scheduled for Thursday. (Longview News-Journal).
</P>
<P>
   INNOCENT _ Calvin Johnson, the man who walked out of prison
after serving 16 years on a rape charge, rode in a limousine
Wednesday and spent his first day of freedom getting attention from
the media, five to 10 job offers and a solicitation of at least one
date. Johnson appeared Wednesday on a morning TV show and says he
might appear on Johnnie Cochran's talk show. Johnson, who says he's
not bitter, was convicted by an all-white jury. ``Everyone was
white,'' he said. ``It's hard for them to picture me as anything
but guilty.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   HITCHED _ Alabama's chain gangs are gone. But prison hitching
posts _ which trace their history to pillors and stockades _ may be
back. They're not used anywhere else in the country. Endorsed by
Gov. Don Siegelman, Alabama prison commissioner Mike Haley argued
in federal court this week to reinstate the practice of shackling
inmates who refused to work to hitching posts, horizontal metal
bars placed at 50 inches and 45 inches above the ground, to
accommodate inmates of different heights. Today in a conference
call with U.S. District Judge Myron Thompson, attorneys from the
Southern Poverty Law Center, representing five inmates, and the
state corrections department will discuss remaining legal
arguments. While Thompson contemplates his decision, the hitching
posts remain unused. Alabama has had a checked past with its
prisons. Feds took over the system in 1979 after prisoner abuse.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CHILLINGWORTH-MURDERS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The voice of
the murdered man can be heard today, rising as if from the very
depths of the silent ocean. What are perhaps the victim's last
written words are hastily scribbled in pencil, on the back of a
legal brief, which lies this morning on a table under lamplight at
the Palm Beach Historical Society. It is the voice of Judge C.E.
Chillingworth, abducted with his wife 44 years ago, June 15, 1955,
from a seaside bungalow in Manalapan. The judge, 58, and his wife,
Marjorie, 47, were bound, weighted and forced overboard, alive, two
miles out to sea, by two assassins hired by a fellow judge who
hated and feared Chillingworth. (Browning, Palm Beach Post) 54
INCHES. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-SEMINOLES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ It was an archaeological
project in a South Texas town that led University of Texas
anthropologist Shirley Mock to a little-known community. A golf
course and houses were being planned in a section of Brackettville,
but before construction could start, the land had to be excavated
excavation for any culturally significant items. And as part of the
project, Mock was hired to interview the older people who lived
near the site. Those initial talks led to more in-depth
ethnological interviews and years of research into the black
Seminoles of Texas and Mexico. ``Singing to the Ancestors: Black
Seminoles on the Border'' is the culmination of Mock's five-year
scholarly investigation. The multimedia exhibit explores the search
for freedom and the building of a culture among a group that formed
in the early 1800s, when runaway slaves took shelter with the
Seminole Indians in Florida. (Martin, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WOODPECKER _ PINEHURST, N.C. _ During the U.S. Open, to be
played at the legendary Pinehurst No. 2 golf course, federal
wildlife officials will tout the success of a four-year-old program
to protect the habitat of the endangered red-cockaded woodpecker.
The ``Safe Harbor'' program, which began at Pinehurst No. 2, has
since been adopted by 24 more landowners in the North Carolina
Sandhills _ including nine golf courses _ and is being rolled out
as a national model. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
