 Wednesday, June 16, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Thursday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (Adds: DISABILITIES-AID.)    (The
``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-2000 (Carthage, Tenn.) _ Vice President Al Gore, in
formally announcing his candidacy for president, takes small steps
to distance himself from Bill Clinton by using such phrases as
``moral leadership'' and ``my own values and faith and family.''
Story will be updated from Iowa City, Iowa. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WAR CRIMES (Paris) _ The Clinton administration welcomes
the Serbian Orthodox Church's call for the resignation of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic and concedes that the indicted war
criminal might gain safe haven inside his own country if he steps
down. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FED-INTEREST-RATES (Washington) _ Pressure is now off the
Federal Reserve Board to raise interest rates later this month as a
new report on consumer prices shows that inflation remains low. By
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   ACID-RAIN (Washington) _ Northeast lawmakers urge Congress to
pass a bill to reduce acid rain. A recent federal study concluded
that despite cuts in air pollution, acid rain remains a serious
problem in the Adirondacks and is a growing threat to forests and
watersheds in the southern Appalachians, Colorado's Front Range and
parts of the Southwest. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   PROSTATE-CANCER (Washington) _ Three high-profile prostate
cancer survivors _ former Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole,
onetime junk bond king Michael Milken and New York Yankees manager
Joe Torre _ urge a Senate panel to boost prostate cancer research
funding. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   DISABILITIES-AID (Washington) _ The Senate unanimously approves
a bill that would make it easier for people with disabilities,
including AIDS, to return to work without losing federal benefits.
By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ If he were still alive, President
Harry Truman would recognize the political games played by today's
naysayers, who refuse to admit they were wrong about the air
campaign that forced Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to
capitulate and who decline to commend Bill Clinton for his
steadfast support of that campaign. Truman faced similar myopic
politicians 50 years ago. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
