<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-NOTES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY SEEKS TO STOP COMPANY SELLING CLASS NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICKI HADDOCK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Taking aim at a growing campus product, the
University of California has gone to court to stop professional
note-takers from infiltrating classrooms and peddling lecture notes
to students.
</P>
<P>
   Some student customers say that without the distractions of
having to scribble down their own notes, buying the notes actually
make them pay closer attention in class. Others simply buy the
notes and skip classes.
</P>
<P>
   The university system's lawsuit, filed in Alameda County
Superior Court, accuses the elusive R&AMP;R Corp. of making
unauthorized use of the university name, trespassing on UC campuses
to ply its trade and violating UC regulations against unauthorized
commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are one very overbearing outfit,'' said Eric Behrens, a
lawyer for the state university system. ``A lot of professors have
complained, and so did the students.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims R&AMP;R regularly stiffs its employees and
customers, while attempting to silence critics with legal threats.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkeley and other UC campuses report that complaints began
about four years ago, when the company started taking notes at
assorted classes in the history, anthropology, chemistry, biology,
political science and economics departments.
</P>
<P>
   A judge has rejected UC's request for an immediate temporary
restraining order to halt R&AMP;R's practices. A hearing on UC's motion
for a preliminary injunction to stop R&AMP;R is scheduled for July 6.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the company, which operates under various
names, could not be reached for comment. UC lawyers say they have
been unable to locate R&AMP;R to serve it notice of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says Berkeley's Student Conduct Code prohibits ``the
selling or distributing of course lecture notes, handouts, readers
or other information provided by an instructor, or using them for
any commercial purposes without the express permission of the
instructor.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit adds that the notes, which cost between $22.95 and
$55.50 per course, are often of poor quality. One professor quoted
in the lawsuit characterized R&AMP;R's notes of his lectures as ``a
pathetic rendition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
