<HEADLINE>
TOMATO FEST: ALL THE JUICY DETAILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you believe it? It seems like just yesterday when it began,
and already the 15th annual Tomato Fest is history.
</P>
<P>
   It happened last weekend in Jacksonville, Texas, and we missed
it. I'm sorry.
</P>
<P>
   But if it makes you feel any better, the Battle of San Tomato
did not take place this year, making me wonder whether the 1999
version of the festival should really count in the record books.
</P>
<P>
   The Battle of San Tomato, you might already know, is when two
sides face off in the Tomato Bowl and throw tomatoes at each other.
The field slowly becomes one big, slushy mess of tomato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   If the event had occurred back at the turn of the last century,
the Battle of San Tomato would have no doubt been called the peach
pit pitch-off. Jacksonville was a leading center of peach
production in the United States. After, say, about 1915, the local
farmers switched over to tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, the town became known as ``the tomato capital of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it must be said, the biggest local industry is
``plastics.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the local high school football stadium is really called
the Tomato Bowl. This year, instead of hosting the Battle of San
Tomato, the festival organizers hosted a gospel concert featuring
18 groups. Not quite as exciting, but infinitely cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   The wildest event this year was the ``bucket war.'' It is an
event where the local fire departments turn on their hoses and try
to move a bucket suspended on an overhead line.
</P>
<P>
   Since the football stadium had gospel singers in it, the bucket
war had to be held in the rodeo arena.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a ``power jam.'' This is a noisy event in which
individuals crank up their car stereos to see who could jam the
loudest. A common occurrence on our city streets.
</P>
<P>
   Two TV news personalities from Tyler entered the tomato-eating
contest.
</P>
<P>
   There was, after all this ballyhoo, a tomato contest for the
best home-grown variety. Strangely, the tomatoes are judged on
appearance and size, not taste. Those seem to be the same criteria
the supermarkets use.
</P>
<P>
   The cooking contest is where the taste comes in. It is still too
early to get any of the recipes from this year's contest, but
festival organizers did provide a recipe from the past.
</P>
<P>
   It is a quiche recipe, and don't even start with that ``real
men'' thing. Real men will eat anything.
</P>
<P>
   FRESH TOMATO AND BASIL QUICHE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 6
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 regular pie shell
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup shredded, part-skim mozzarella
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (1/4-inch thick) sliced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup shredded fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup evaporated skim milk
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 egg white
</P>
<P>
   Coat nonstick skillet with cooking spray. Add oil and heat over
medium heat until hot. Add onion and garlic and saute 8 minutes or
until lightly browned. Spread onion mixture on bottom of prepared
crust, sprinkle with cheese. Arrange tomato slices over cheese. Top
with basil. Combine milk, cornstarch, pepper, eggs and egg white in
blender. Process until smooth. Pour over tomatoes. Bake 350 degrees
for 45 minutes or until knife comes out clean. Cool 10 minutes
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 282 calories, 15 grams fat, 24
grams carbohydrates, 12 grams protein, 80 milligrams cholesterol,
312 milligrams sodium, 49 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
