<HEADLINE>
A FATHER'S HOW-TO FOR GETTING FOOD ON THE TABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get one thing straight from the start: I'm a dad who can
cook.
</P>
<P>
   And you know what? Like the others, I'm pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   I'll stack my fried chicken against yours any day. My Italian
cream cake will rock your world. My chicken salad? Suffice it to
say that women have begged me for the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   We dads may not all cook the way you moms do, but we believe the
process isn't important _ the product is.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares if we don't always measure spices? If we use whatever
mystery meat is in the freezer? If we start with one ethnic recipe
and swerve across entire continents to fill in the pantry gaps?
</P>
<P>
   I admit that we don't always leave our egos at the pantry door;
the truth is, I have named recipes after myself.
</P>
<P>
   My wife will tell you that Larry's Excellent Chicken is really
chicken marsala, that Larry's Excellent Chicken II is another name
for chicken divan. She knows, after five years of marriage, that
you soak the bird in buttermilk for Larry's Excellent Fried
Chicken.
</P>
<P>
   You see, dads of my generation taught ourselves to saute and
flambe, so forgive us if we're an arrogant lot. We overcame
stereotypes, we mastered pie dough, we tried making biscuits again
and again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Then a funny thing happened as we learned our way around the
kitchen: We discovered that cooking can be relaxing, rewarding, and
you know what else?
</P>
<P>
   Chicks dig it.
</P>
<P>
   So we wipe the sweat from our brow and soldier on.
</P>
<P>
   With Father's Day coming, here's a look at three cookbooks to
make the journey smoother.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``Boy Meets Grill'' (Hyperion, $32.50)
</P>
<P>
   The scoop: Author and chef Bobby Flay is host of three Food
Network shows including ``Grillin' and Chillin,''' and he owns two
upscale New York restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The skinny: This cookbook is for yuppies. Labor-intensive
recipes will have dads looking for mango nectar, cascabel chile
powder and brie cheese to stuff inside a turkey burger. But every
recipe is mouth-watering.
</P>
<P>
   Skill level: Advanced. Expect Dad to whisk up a meringue,
butterfly a chicken and cut basil into ``chiffonades,'' or fine
ribbons, as Flay explains.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``A Guy's Guide to Great Eating'' (Houghton Mifflin, $17)
</P>
<P>
   The scoop: Big guy Don Mauer, newspaper columnist and
motivational speaker, lost 100 pounds by trimming 25 percent of the
fat from meat-and-potatoes-style recipes.
</P>
<P>
   The skinny: Mauer's motto: ``When I think of real meals, I think
of meat. There's nothing so gratifying, so flavorful, so
straightforward.'' Be warned: He makes his macaroni and cheese with
Velveeta Light.
</P>
<P>
   Skill level: Novice. This is cooking for dummies, so it's a good
place for beginning dads to start. The only time Mauer gets
complicated is when he's grinding and seasoning sirloin to make a
better burger.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Title: ``A Man and His Pan'' (Andrews McMeel, $16.95)
</P>
<P>
   The scoop: Cookbook author John Boswell brags that this is the
first collection of his own recipes. He says all were tested and
tried on his family; there's even a section devoted to cooking for
kids.
</P>
<P>
   The skinny: Dads who get stuck doing dishes will like Boswell's
gimmick: 140 recipes for your nonstick skillet. Boswell runs the
gamut from gourmet crepes and souffles to traditional steaks and
chops.
</P>
<P>
   Skill level: Intermediate. This is how it would sound if your
big brother taught you to cook. Boswell gently explains why
``challah'' makes better French toast, what different mushrooms do
in recipes and which cuts of meat he prefers.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MANGO GLAZED TUNA STEAKS WITH BLACK BEAN SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   Dressing
</P>
<P>
   1 mango, peeled, pitted and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup coarsely chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cumin
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Place the mango, lime juice, garlic, onion, cilantro and cumin
in a blender and blend until smooth. With the motor running, slowly
add the olive oil until emulsified. Season with salt and pepper.
May be refrigerated, covered, for 1 day; serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Black bean salad
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dry black beans, cooked according to package directions,
or 5 1/2 cups canned black beans, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 scallions, with 3 inches of the green left on, thinly sliced
on the diagonal
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe mango, peeled, pitted and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe tomatoes, seeded and finely diced
</P>
<P>
   Mango dressing
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine the beans, garlic, scallions, mango and tomatoes in a
large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Toss with the mango dressing and season with salt and pepper.
Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Mango glaze
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely chopped Spanish onion
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 serrano pepper, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peeled and coarsely grated gingerroot
</P>
<P>
   4 cups mango nectar (available in supermarkets in the canned
juice section)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Preheat a gas or charcoal grill to medium, or use a side or
stove burner.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in medium nonreactive saucepan until almost
smoking. Add the onion and garlic and cook until soft. Add the
serrano pepper and ginger and cook for 2 minutes. Add the nectar
and brown sugar, bring to a boil, and cook until reduced to 2 cups.
Place the mixture in a food processor with the vinegar and process
until smooth. Season with salt and pepper. Let cool at room
temperature. May be refrigerated for 1 day; use at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
