 ART ADV.: Photos with BIOTECH-LEVIN, FOOD-DUCKTRAP and WAR-RAPE are
being transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SETTLEMENT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TOWN (Djakovica, Kosovo) _ In the virtually destroyed
town of Djakovica, people who have hidden in basements for months
are now coming out. By Susan Milligan. 980 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VILLAGE (Laplje Selo, Yugoslavia) _ In an all-Serb
village, the 2,500 residents have vowed to stay on the land their
families have farmed for centuries. By Kevin Cullen. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-BARAK (Beirut) _ Older residents here still remember a
brazen Israeli raid that killed three top Palestinian guerrillas,
but they are shocked to learn that the commando in drag who led it
is the new prime minister of Israel. By Charles Sennott. 1390
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOATS (Laguna Beach, Calif.) _ Hundreds of goats are
chomping dry grass and brush in southern California, animals
brought there in herds to help reduce the annual fire threat. By
Lynda Gorov. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCNAMARA-COLUMN (Undated) _ If the president thinks troublesome
content is limited to movies with R ratings, then it has been too
long since he visited the multiplex. By Eileen McNamara.
</P>
<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- A word of advice to Serb troops, and
to anyone else with a gun and a grudge as NATO moves its men into
Kosovo: Don't mess with the Gurkhas. By David Nyhan.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ One of the inexplicable debates about
guns is whether the minimum age for handgun possession should go
from 18 to 21. There would be no debate if one remembered 1984. By
Derrick Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) -- The US gap between the have and
have-nots is mobilizing a grass-roots campaign to find ways to
create a more equitable economic system. By Diego Ribadeneira.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Martin F. Nolan's column is unavailable today.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WAR-RAPE (Boston) _ The story of a woman named Patience speaks
for thousands of women who have been silenced for centuries. ``Rape
is one of the oldest weapons of war,'' says a Boston social worker.
By Patti Hartigan. (2 takes; l and i coding) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) -- Mr. Fussy's family has sent him to the
bookstore to buy a Father's Day present for himself. Mr. Fussy
would rather not have a Father's Day present. By Alex Beam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE-BLACK-MEN (Undated) _ A glossy monthly style magazine
for men of color, Code showcases a dazzling array of
chocolate-covered eye candy sporting long nubian locks, short
afros, and bold baldies. By Vanessa E. Jones. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE-REVIEW (Undated) _ No answers on ``Eyes Wide Shut''
from Us; New Yorker's stories. By Matthew Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD (d) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-DUCKTRAP (Belfast, Maine) -- Luck, mystery, and a deep
connection with the land: The moment has all the elements that
Desmond FitzGerald focuses on when he's talking about Ducktrap
River Fish Farm. By Sheryl Julian. (2 takes) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-FROZEN (Undated) _ People thought Gerry Thomas was crazy 45
years ago when he created a frozen dinner of turkey, dressing,
