<P>
   FROM HERE TO ETERNITY: THE LATEST HIGH-TECH TELESCOPES
</P>
<P>
   DEADLY KNEE BENDS
</P>
<P>
   These are stories that clients of DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE recently
received.
</P>
<P>
   DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE, which is available through The New York
Times Syndicate, captures all the wonders of discovery in the
environment, medicine, prehistory, space and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, Discover News Service delivers fascinating,
trustworthy coverage in two tightly edited features (available in
Spanish, too). Plus superb color art brings all the discoveries to
life.
</P>
<P>
   The features described below are available for ONE-SHOT PURCHASE
by contacting Debra Weydert by phone, (732) 390-4480, or fax, (732)
390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   ALL THE ART IS FREE OF CHARGE AND AVAILABLE ELECTRONICALLY.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FROM HERE TO ETERNITY: THE LATEST HIGH-TECH TELESCOPES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By MICHAEL D. LEMONICK &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Japan's wafer-thin 8.3-meter Subaru telescope collected its
first images from space in January. The Gemini North, an 8.1-meter
telescope built by a seven-nation consortium that includes the
United States, is scheduled to begin scanning the heavens any day.
These telescopes are part of the elite new generation of optics
that promises to lead mankind beyond the solar system into
unexplored regions of space. Michael D. Lemonick, a senior science
writer at Time, reports.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-OTHERWORDLY-VIEWS-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEADLY KNEE BENDS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR SLIDE IS AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By TONY DAJER &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When Mr. Kelly said his legs were killing him, he was right. A
prisoner in New York City jail, Mr. Kelly participated in a deep
knee-bend competition judged by fellow inmates. His winning lift:
1,134 pounds. What he didn't realize was the damage he had done to
his leg muscles _ and consequently his kidneys. Tony Dajer, who is
at work on a book about medical mistakes and the science of
diagnosis, reports.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-DEADLY-KNEE-BENDS-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   Both stories are also available in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
