<HEADLINE>
FEUDING SIBLINGS AGREE TO KEEP TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Both sides in the 49ers' ownership dispute have
agreed to continue talking, under the supervision of a federal
judge in Ohio, according to spokesmen for Eddie DeBartolo and his
estranged sister, Denise DeBartolo York.
</P>
<P>
   Ordered last month by U.S. District Judge Daniel Polster of
Akron, Ohio, to try to iron out their legal differences, DeBartolo
and York returned to court Monday to report on the status of their
talks.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication whether progress had been made, but
Polster ordered them to continue talking and report back to him
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge asked both sides to keep the discussions private,''
said York spokesman Sam Singer. ``That's all I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   In lawsuits threatening to sidetrack plans for a new stadium in
San Francisco, DeBartolo and York are suing each other.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo says his sister breached a contractual agreement with
him and engaged in ``oppressive and malicious'' conduct by trying
to keep him out of family businesses.
</P>
<P>
   He also accused her of trying to ``pressure him financially into
compromising his rights for pennies on the dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, suing York in Ohio, is seeking $150 million in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   York, suing DeBartolo in San Francisco Superior Court, accused
her brother of reneging on a $94 million debt to the family
corporation they co-own, Edward J. DeBartolo Inc. of Youngstown,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Litigation in both cases was suspended last month when Polster
called for talks.
</P>
<P>
   If the warring siblings are able to resolve their differences,
it could prepare the way for a peaceful financial split.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, would make it possible for whoever remained in
control of the 49ers football team to move ahead on the
long-stalled plan to build a new stadium and adjoining commercial
center. The project was approved by San Francisco voters two years
ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
