<HEADER>
A7656 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-CLASSICAL17-COX     06-16 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-CLASSICAL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Levi and company put fresh lyricism into Mahler cycle
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conductors who used to do Beethoven cycles now do Mahler cycles.
Both for Atlanta Symphony Orchestra audiences and collectors of
Mahler symphony sets, it's too bad Yoel Levi's contract with the
ASO expires before he finishes his. With previous CDs of the fifth
and sixth, the newly issued No. 4 takes him a third of the way
through the nine finished works. For this, the gentlest and most
intimate of Mahler's epic works, Levi leads a spacious reading
without neglecting brilliant orchestral touches such as the acid
clarinet, peculiar to Mahler, played here by Laura Ardan. The
scherzo is particularly eccentric and fresh. In the fourth
movement, mezzo Frederica von Stade sings of husbandry in heaven
with a full, glinting sound. Telarc fills out the disc with von
Stade singing ``Songs of a Wayfarer,'' four bittersweet ballads
that became raw material for Symphony No. 1 and even ``Das Lied von
der Erde.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Mezzo Virginia Dupuy of Southern Methodist University, who sang
the Mozart ``Requiem'' with Atlanta Ballet in March, has recorded
all the published songs of Alma Schindler, written before she
married Mahler in 1902. Rich and luscious, as is Dupuy's voice,
they are notable for the breadth of the poets she set, from Rainer
Maria Rilke to Franz Werfel (who became her third husband in 1929).
Pianist Simon Sargon partners her beautifully, and these
accompaniments are not easy.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   Mahler Symphony No. 4/ ``Songs of a Wayfarer''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, Yoel Levi, conductor, with
</P>
<P>
   Frederica von Stade, mezzo. Telarc.
</P>
<P>
   8 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs of Alma Mahler''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Dupuy,
</P>
<P>
   mezzo; Simon Sargon, piano. Gasparo Gallante. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _ Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
