<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7657 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS17-COX     06-16 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of recently released CDs
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Shane Harrison, Kathy Janich and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Astro Lounge''
</P>
<P>
   Smash Mouth. Interscope Records. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Sixties party rock, with its hip-shaking, often organ-fueled
grooves has been canonized, anthologized and plagiarized for so
long that you'd be forgiven for thinking it's an exhausted
subgenre. What a shock then, to find it sounding so fresh, as
played by this cool California quartet. Smash Mouth first attempted
the '60s thing on ``Walking on the Sun,'' the hit from its 1997
debut ``Fush Yu Mang.'' But the rest of the album was sloppy
ska-thrash nonsense. Here, the band expands the retro party,
reaching a peak with the perfect summer anthem ``All Star.'' Like
most soirees, the momentum occasionally flags, but the album ends
on a high note with a deliriously groovy cover of the chestnut
``Can't Get Enough of You Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is My Truth, Tell Me Yours''
</P>
<P>
   Manic Street Preachers. Virgin. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The Manic Street Preachers roared out of South Wales in the
early '90s, spouting lyrical obscenities at queen and country. The
band was soon huge, selling out U.K. arenas throughout a bumpy
career that includes the mysterious disappearance of original
member Richey James Edwards. Those stinging lyrics are now buoyed
by gorgeous melodies and expansive arrangements. Guitarist James
Dean Bradfield's voice generates much of the power in this album's
first two U.K. singles, ``If You Tolerate This, Then Your Children
Will Be Next'' and ``The Everlasting.'' Few bands have matured with
this much style and elegance.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BROADWAY
</P>
<P>
   ``Fosse''
</P>
<P>
   Original cast. RCA Victor. 21 tracks. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   You'd think a dance musical such as ``Fosse'' would be better
seen than heard, but that's not necessarily so. The score of this
1999 Tony-winning show is so evocative that visions of dancers with
shoulders slouching, heads popping and toes turned out a la Bob
Fosse (1927-1987) leap to mind whenever the horns bray or a
percussionist's brush dances atop a cymbal. The vocals are
flawless: ``Big Spender,'' ``Steam Heat,'' ``Bye Bye Blackbird''
and ``Razzle Dazzle'' among them. Fosse, with the help of this
show's re-creators, has indeed left ``footsteps on the sands of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   _Kathy Janich
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Double Up''
</P>
<P>
   Ma$e. Bad Boy. 18 tracks. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   First Ma$e was the mumbling rapper whom people couldn't
understand. Now what the Atlanta transplant is saying is quite
clear. It just might not be what people want to hear. ``Double Up''
is often a downer, the work of someone nearly opposite from the
smiling, infectious sidekick introduced by Sean ``Puffy'' Combs on
their rah-rah 1996 single ``Can't Nobody Hold Me Down.'' Three
years later, after selling 4 million copies of his debut, ``Harlem
World,'' Mase is threatening to shoot people (``Stay Out of My
Way'') and is suspicious of women attracted by the money he's
always talking about (``Oh Daddy''). Sample-heavy party songs such
as ``Get Ready'' are now the exception. Ma$e won't discuss why he's
quitting rap to do God's work. But the mood of this album says it
all.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton, Shane Harrison, Kathy Janich and Sonia Murray
write for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
