<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7658 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-POP17-COX     06-16 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newman back to satirical self
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once pop's supreme satirist, Randy Newman the double-edged
tunesmith gradually became Randy Newman the prolific movie
soundtrack composer. While the distance between the politically
incorrect ``Short People'' and the sentimentally feel-good music
for, say, ``Toy Story'' and ``James and the Giant Peach'' is one
measured mostly in degrees of attitude, it seemed Newman no longer
needed to indulge his winningly darker side.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Bad Love'' triumphantly testifies, he was only giving it a
long break. This jaunty song cycle signals the return of a socially
incisive sensibility, one who spoofs ossified dinosaur rock stars
one moment (``I'm Dead''), only to ponder the plight of the young
Karl Marx a few tunes later (``The World Isn't Fair''). He shapes
his clipped, cramped nasal voice to the hipster patois of a New
Orleans pimp (``Shame'') and fancies himself a cowboy (``Big Hat,
No Cattle''), but he succeeds best when he reaches the most. The
album's highlight, a lesson in human nature called ``The Great
Nations of Europe,'' surveys centuries of imperial rape and pillage
in rollicking rhyme. It's as if the angel of history was, in fact,
a piano player in an old vaudeville house. That's Newman's great
gift, to marry pop pastiche to a kind of political cartooning.
What's new and surprising is his willingness to play it straight.
It's only for one song, a message of affection to his ex-wife, but
is all the more jarring because of that. When Newman sings ``I Miss
You,'' the only role he's playing is himself, and what could be
cloying becomes a moving instance of emotional candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad Love''
</P>
<P>
   Randy
</P>
<P>
   Newman. DreamWorks. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
