<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ENEMY17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Paranoid thrills from taut `Enemy'
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   ``Enemy of the State'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   George Orwell's Big Brother had nothing on the snooping tactics
of the U.S. National Security Agency. According to this paranoid
thriller, your wardrobe can betray you, thanks to tracking devices
hidden in buttons, watches and fountain pens.
</P>
<P>
   Recycling paranoia plot devices from other movies (``The
Conversation,'' ``Three Days of the Condor''), ``Enemy of the
State'' keeps Will Smith (as the innocent guy caught in the middle)
and Gene Hackman (as an old espionage pro) on the run from big
government bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp cast and slick production compensate for the movie's
occasional lapses in logic. Director Tony Scott (``Crimson Tide'')
keeps the tension tight with inventive chases through tunnels, over
rooftops and through busy hotels. Unlike other overblown epics from
producer Jerry Bruckheimer (``The Rock'' and ``Armageddon''), this
movie maintains a relatively human scale. Its action scenes are
shot and paced with precision. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
