<HEADER>
A7660 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-MINIS17-COX     06-16 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``In Dreams'' (R) _ In what could be called ``Nightmare on Elm
Street'' meets ``The Eyes of Laura Mars,'' a psychic woman (Annette
Bening) is harassed in her dreams by a child-murdering psycho. For
at least an hour, the movie is truly eerie and disturbing, but an
overly long encounter between Bening and the madman proves
damaging. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``My Name Is Joe'' (R) _ The titular Joe (Peter Mullan) is
another of director Ken Loach's sturdy working-class blokes. A
recovering Glasgow alcoholic, Joe begins a tentative and touching
affair with a good-hearted social worker (Louise Goodall). But his
fragile peace with his past becomes achingly clear, threatening
their relationship. A slight but affecting film anchored by
Mullan's great performance (he won best actor at Cannes) and
Loach's evocative direction. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Faculty'' (R) _ Think of it as ``Invasion of the Body
Snatchers'' enacted by the cast of ``Scream,'' and you'll be close.
In this enjoyably dumb B movie, Elijah Wood and fellow high
schoolers battle an outer-space whatsit that's turning their
teachers (including Jon Stewart and Famke Janssen) into oozy pod
people. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Little Voice'' (R) _ When Little Voice (Jane Horrocks) opens
her mouth, out come Garland, Streisand, Dietrich. She's an uncanny
vocal (and physical) impersonator. But when she's not performing,
this film of the British stage play can be unbearable. Brenda
Blethyn goes over the top as Horrocks' slatternly mother, and Ewan
McGregor is wasted playing a mild-mannered pigeon lover. Luckily,
Michael Caine, as a small-time talent scout, keeps his scenes
churning with venom. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' (PG) _ This week's second example of a
stage play that fails to make a smooth screen transition. Meryl
Streep heads an ensemble cast in this memory play about Irish
sisters fighting repressed passions and trying to make ends meet.
It's well-acted but remote. Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   THE VIDEO COLLECTOR
</P>
