<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking Along Bookmarks
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there any way I can convert my America Online 4.0 Favorite
Places so that I can use them with Internet Explorer 5.0?
</P>
<P>
   A. Favorite Places, AOL's version of bookmarks, is a database
file that is specially coded to save space. Other programs can't
read the AOL code, so just copying the Favorite Places file into
your new browser won't work.
</P>
<P>
   Although time-consuming, perhaps the simplest way to transfer
favorite Web site locations from America Online to Internet
Explorer 5.0 is to copy them one by one.
</P>
<P>
   To copy a URL from your Favorite Places without starting up the
AOL browser, click on the Edit button (or right-click on the
Favorite) to see and copy the address; then switch to Explorer, and
paste the URL into the Address box. Hit Enter to go to the page.
Open the Favorites list in Explorer, and click on Add.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to copy Web site URLs only, skip the addresses that
have ``aol://'' at the beginning. They point to internal America
Online content. If you do want to copy some AOL-page bookmarks,
they will be accessible only if you continue to have an AOL
account.
</P>
<P>
   If you have bookmarks saved in Netscape Navigator that you want
to transfer to Explorer 5.0, there is a new feature that makes it
easy. In Explorer, go to the File menu, select Import and Export
and follow the instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com or postal mail to Questions, Circuits,
The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959.
This column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
