<HEADLINE>
HELLO, KITTY. IS IT REALLY YOU? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.C. HERZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hello Kitty's Cube Frenzy, published by New Kid Co; for Sony
Playstation; $39.95; for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   I was in third grade when Hello Kitty landed.
</P>
<P>
   First there was nothing, and then, suddenly, the Japanese
cartoon kitten was everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Hello Kitty's cuteness was irresistible. Her eyes, wide-spaced
black jellybeans, seemed to stare plaintively from a round white
face that had no mouth. Her whiskers weren't planted near her nose,
as they are on a normal cat. They sprang incongruously from the
sides of her head. ``Help!'' she seemed to plead. ``This is all
wrong! But I can't speak! I have no mouth!''
</P>
<P>
   Hello Kitty was soft, round, toothless, clawless and mute. She
was totally helpless, and that inspired a certain protectiveness
and affection and spurred a cultlike following among 8-year-old
girls.
</P>
<P>
   A tide of licensed merchandise inundated the school: Hello Kitty
combs, mirrors, pencil cases, notebooks, barrettes, coin purses,
watches, stickers, nail care kits, address books, packages of
tissues. Birthday parties became Hello Kitty swap meets where Hello
Kitty presents were given and Hello Kitty party favors were taken
away. No one could get enough.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, Hello Kitty has generated more than a
billion dollars in revenue for her Japanese parent, the Sanrio Co.
About 15,000 Hello Kitty products are on the market worldwide,
including a video game published by New Kid Co, Hello Kitty's Cube
Frenzy for the Sony Playstation.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Hello Kitty has no mouth. Because if she saw
this game, the corners would fall into a sad, sad frown, and small
crystal-blue tears would drop out of her jelly-bean eyes. It is a
shallow, slapdash, boring little game, apparently thrown together
with no time and even less money.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, the game play is second-rate. Cube Frenzy is
a puzzle game with falling cubes in which Hello Kitty gets to
collect prizes. But despite the apparent similarities, Cube Frenzy
is to Tetris what Wonder Bread is to a French baguette.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are a lot of licensed titles that don't measure
up as thumb candy. But their mediocre game play is typically
mitigated by great graphics, whereas Cube Frenzy looks like bad
shareware _ or like a Game Boy cartridge blown up to television
size.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than the low resolution is the color scheme, which is
garishly awry. When you see Hello Kitty on a backpack or a piece of
stationery, a set of colors establishes the authenticity of the
product. It's immediately recognizable, just as a particular yellow
and a particular red add up to McDonald's. The video game jewel
tones in Cube Frenzy look nothing like the Hello Kitty palette, so
the whole experience feels somewhat off kilter.
</P>
<P>
   The whole point of a licensed video game is that it looks like
the thing it's based on. When designers miss the mark, it
disappoints the little kids who gobble up images of a well-loved
character and the nostalgic young adults who gobbled up those
images 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And with a character like Hello Kitty, it's especially
disappointing because Hello Kitty merchandise has usually been very
high quality. Nothing cracks or fades; all the snaps and closures
are snug. You pay more, but you get more _ in general, if you buy a
Hello Kitty comb or pen, it will be better than a generic comb or
pen.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the case with Cube Frenzy, which is a subpar video
game selling for a premium price, $39.95. Which is senseless
because you can get a much better Hello Kitty experience free on
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Sanrio's home page in Japan is a jewel box of Hello Kitty-ana,
with profiles of Hello Kitty and all her friends, comic strips, a
fortune teller and digital games and puzzles lifted from Hello
Kitty CD-ROM's that are available only in Japan
(www.sanrio.co.jp/english).
</P>
<P>
   There is also Psychology Fun Corner, a series of questions
designed to give you a better look at your own personality and your
relationships with others. (``You are playing hide-and-seek, but
you've hidden so well that no one can find you. How do you feel?'')
For kitsch, you can't beat a cartoon baby's heartfelt reading of
your inner life.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Sanrio headquarters, there are dozens of Hello Kitty
fan sites on the Web where you can dress up the characters and read
stories about them and chat and send postcards to your friends,
which is what 8-year-old girls want to do with Hello Kitty in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   When you survey the mammoth array of Hello Kitty products that
have been produced over the years, most of them fall into two basic
groups: things that have to do with personal appearance
(toothbrushes, barrettes, etc.) and things that have to do with
communication (pencils, pens, stationery and the carrying cases
that contain them).
</P>
<P>
   Among grade-school girls, stickers are a means of
self-expression and a tradable commodity. A Sanrio address book or
wallet may be a girl's first experience of keeping track of
information about other people or carrying money, which are adult
activities.
</P>
<P>
   The infantile cartoon characters may seem decorative, but
they're really functional. They're visual training wheels that
connect the world of grown-ups to the world of little kids. A Hello
Kitty pencil makes it easier for an 8-year-old to write a letter or
jot down a phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, a Hello Kitty compact makes it easier for a
20-something not to take herself too seriously. In both cases, the
character makes the experience more comfortable and friendly. The
most important word in the Hello Kitty universe is ``hello.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frenzy'' is not part of the lexicon.
</P>
</TEXT>
