<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY REVIEWS OF BUSH'S SHOW LOOK PRETTY GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The naysayers were ready to pounce, poised to derail the
campaign before it ever got rolling. The pundits were figuring that
they might shut down the presidential ambitions of George W. Bush
the same way that theater critics sometimes force an overhyped
Broadway show to close after one performance.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Texas governor foiled the critics' plans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's detractors in politics and the media have been
underestimating him since the day he decided to take on the
allegedly unbeatable Ann Richards in the 1994 race for governor.
Bush beat Richards without breaking a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Bush was re-elected with nearly 70 percent of the
vote. He racked up enthusiastic support from just about every
category of voter for whom a category exists. He followed his
election victory with a successful legislative session that saw
most of his campaign promises enacted into law.
</P>
<P>
   And still the skeptics scoffed at the polls declaring Bush the
front-runner for president _ not just among Republicans seeking
their party's nomination but in head-to-head matchups against
Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley. He's untested outside Texas,
they said. Nobody knows what he stands for, they said. He hasn't
felt the heat of the national media spotlight, they said.
</P>
<P>
   So Bush boarded an airplane dubbed ``Great Expectations'' and
set out to see how his message would play in Peoria. Well, not in
Peoria just yet, but in Iowa and New Hampshire. And it played just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most skeptical media types had no choice but to report
that Bush's opening foray into the arena of presidential politics
was successful. Big crowds showed up at every stop to look him over
and listen to what he had to say. The crowds liked what they saw
and heard.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one trip, of course. There are lots more trips to
come, more states to visit, more hands to shake, more backs to pat,
more reporters to joust with.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush keeps reminding us: It's a long way till voting time.
</P>
<P>
   But rarely has a candidate commanded so much attention so early
in the process. Or so much fear, where his rivals are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   According to news reports, Democrats have been following Bush
around on the campaign trail, launching verbal hand grenades and
hoping to catch him in a blunder. Republicans are sniping at him as
well, perhaps in the futile expectation that the sparks given off
by the Bush juggernaut will ignite their dormant campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The most persistent criticism of Bush is that he hasn't been
specific enough in articulating his positions on various issues. He
has acknowledged the criticism but has stuck to his plan,
describing his philosophy in general terms and promising to deliver
details ``on my timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how Bush operates. He cannot be pressured into doing or
saying anything that he is not ready to do or say.
</P>
<P>
   And this we know from past performance: His proposals on issues
such as taxes, education, crime, etc., will be detailed and more
than specific enough to satisfy voters, if not the media. When the
people of Texas elected Bush governor in 1994 and again in 1998,
they knew exactly what he intended to do.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign rhetoric and political punditry aside, the American
people will have no doubts where Bush stands on the issues when the
time comes to choose a new president.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, these people who are counting on Bush to stumble _
to lose his temper or lose his cool or lose whatever it is they
expect him to lose _ would be wise not to hold their breath. Ann
Richards tried every trick in the book to get Bush's goat in that
first gubernatorial campaign, and he just plain refused to play her
game.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has shown repeatedly that he can deal with relentless
scrutiny by the media, cheap shots from opponents and tough
questions from the public. He wasn't rattled by hecklers in New
Hampshire, and he won't be rattled by carping pundits or braying
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine featured the words on its cover: ``President
Bush?''
</P>
<P>
   The question mark is temporary.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
