<HEADER>
A7731 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     06-16 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV04-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JULY 4, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My bedroom door sticks when I try to close it due to swelling
of the wood, so I want to take the door off and plane down the
edge. When I tried this before I had a lot of trouble holding the
door on edge while I worked, so I had to enlist my wife to hold it
in position while I planed it. That didn't work too well. How can I
do the job this time while working by myself?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are two methods often used when planing or sanding the
edge of a door. One method is to lay the door on edge, then push
one end of the door into a corner of the room while planing from
the other end. The second method is to use a couple of carpenter's
handscrew clamps similar to the ones shown here _ which enables you
to plane the full length of the door without having to turn it
end-for-end about half way through the job. Lock two of these
clamps firmly onto the bottom edge of the door (the edge that is
resting on the floor) then lay the door on edge with the clamps on
the floor. This will support the door so you can plane or sand the
full length of the door.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a steam heating system and the large radiator in my
upstairs hall makes a banging noise when the heat comes up. Also,
it often makes a bubbling sound, something like water gurgling,
while the heat is on. Can you tell me what causes this, and is
there anything I can do about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: After the steam enters the radiator and releases its heat
some of it will condense into water which then accumulates inside
the bottom of the radiator. This water is supposed to run out of
the radiator and then flow back to the boiler through the same
pipes. If the radiator slopes the wrong way, or if the main inlet
valve is not fully open, water can get trapped inside the radiator
and cause the gurgling noise you describe. In some cases there will
also be a banging sound as the incoming steam comes against the
water inside the radiator. You can often correct this problem by
shimming up the end of the radiator that is opposite the inlet
valve so that it slopes slightly toward the inlet valve.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am building a wood deck and shed and have to drive a number
of long, heavy wood screws through some large beams. I am working
in a rural area, I don't have electricity for power tools, and
can't afford to buy a heavy duty cordless screwdriver that I may
never need again (assuming one of these would do the job). Driving
each screw in by hand is so hard that I get blisters and have to
rest after each screw. Is there anything you can think of that will
make the screws penetrate more easily?
</P>
<P>
   A: It sounds as though you are not drilling pilot holes of the
right size for each screw. For such large screws you may need a
larger clearance hole where the screw goes through the first wood
member, and then a smaller pilot hole in the second member. This
makes it easier to drive the screws in and helps prevent splitting.
It is a good idea, too, to rub the screw threads over a cake of
soap beforehand in order to lubricate the threads, and thus also
make the screws easier to drive in.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our bathroom vanity sink is made of a ``cultured'' or
synthetic marble with the sink molded in so that the whole top is
one piece. The bottom of this sink has numerous stains in it that
won't come out with regular detergent. I don't want to spend the
money to replace the entire vanity and sink. Is there any
suggestion you can offer to clean up or just replace the sink?
</P>
<P>
   A: You might try scrubbing the stains out with a mildly abrasive
cleaner such as Soft Scrub or similar product that also contains a
bleach. Or, you could try using just a bleach alone. In extreme
cases stubborn stains can even be removed by using an abrasive type
fiberglass cleaner or auto cleaner, or even a kitchen abrasive pad.
These will dull the finish a little, but you can restore the luster
with a waterproof wax _ the kind that is used on fiberglass boats
(any wax will wear off and have to be renewed in time).
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING HANDSCREW CLAMPS TO PROP UP
DOOR'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Large clamps will hold door in vertical position while
planing opposite edge.
</P>
