<HEADER>
A7741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-ENTRY-NYT &LR;      06-16 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-ENTRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN NOTEBOOK: MAKING AN ENTRANCE INTO AN EDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARTHA BAKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to forget that the domestic doorway was once a humble,
utilitarian affair, innocent of any attempt to make a good first
impression or, for that matter, any impression at all. In medieval
castles, entrances were simply holding tanks designed to check the
advance of sudden callers bearing arms and a grievance. Equally
functional (and hardly more welcoming) was the cupboard-size entry
porch common to early New England. It was, in fact, a barrier
against front-door drafts, as well as the only sensible place to
put the staircase. Even in a less buttoned-up age, the front hall
is likely to be the family repository of umbrellas, coats and the
odd 10-speed.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, homeowners are increasingly conscious of
the first-impression potential of these little entry rooms, and
where trends in interiors go, garden style follows. The notion
makes perfect sense: a gateway, or introduction to a garden can
create a sense of drama or stir curiosity about what lies beyond.
And as in an interior foyer, the first impression created by a
garden entrance depends on what you want to make it.
</P>
<P>
   For the owners of a seaside property in Montauk, N.Y., the
gateway is the garden, the serendipitous result of a plan to
relocate an inconvenient driveway. As the driveway was originally
configured, arriving guests confronted the bedroom cottage. But
when Craig Socia, a landscape designer, was asked to divert the
drive to a lower level so that it would lead, more logically, to
the living and dining complex, he also connected the two points
with a special kind of garden and a stairway rooted in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Using plants and materials indigenous to the hostile Montauk
environment, with its salt spray and Atlantic gales, Socia laid a
pathway of hardwood mulch, then created a border with shad trees
and plantings of summer sweet, which bear spires of pale pink
flowers. Next, he built a stairway with grass treads and risers of
rubble stones, which former owners had gathered from the beach and
scattered through the woods, a lucky find, as it's now illegal to
remove such stones from the shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors step off the drive onto a mysterious path, where Gothic
tree limbs thrash against the sky, and a stairway entices them
upward until they discover the surprise payoff in a spectacular
view of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   On the Sagaponack, N.Y., property of David Seeler and his wife,
Ngaere Macray, who own Bayberry Nursery, there's another garden
entrance that doesn't lay all its cards on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's meant to be a transitional space, like a foyer to the
garden,'' Seeler explained. The design is simplicity itself, a
solid wood gate with a curved top joining two beech hedge walls,
but the impact is powerful. Beyond the gate lies another hedge
wall, the first in a series of mazelike arrangements at whose core
is the garden itself.
</P>
<P>
   Some entryways frame a portion of the garden as a kind of
horticultural hors d'oeuvre to whet the appetite for what's to
come. Such is the case in a Dutchess County, N.Y., garden where the
owner has put a classically rendered entrance gate to offer an
elliptical view of the garden's focal statuary and the plantings
that surround it.
</P>
<P>
   Another framing device is a Chinese-inspired cutout, a portal
with a novel shape hewn from a solid border or dividing wall. One
especially charming example is a circular moon gate discovered on a
family estate in Seal Harbor, Maine Separating a sunny
Western-style flower garden from a tranquil enclave for Eastern
sculpture, the gate draws the viewer from light into shade, allegro
to adagio. The agreeably befuddling sensation of the transition is
pure Alice.
</P>
<P>
   Spirit screens, unrevealing blank walls, are another Eastern
innovation, once the means of entry to China's minute medieval
gardens. Spiritually, they were a signal for visitors to abandon
all negative thoughts. Strategically, they directed entrants to the
right, then onto a pattern of walkways leading up, down and around
the garden, a virtual reality ploy that made the garden seem larger
than it actually was.
</P>
<P>
   Often, a garden's site will be the best guide to the choice and
placement of a gateway. In a seaside locale, for example, a
gardener might choose an open-work design, which captures the
seascape, as the owners of an Asian-themed garden did in Pemaquid
on the Maine coast. After establishing their waterside boundary
with a see-through fence and a striking latticework dragon gate,
they fashioned a doorway that visually enlarges their garden space
by appropriating the seascape behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of an entry suited to its setting can be seen on
a multileveled property in Westchester County, N.Y., belonging to
James Huniford and Stephen Sills. Having recreated a classic
17th-century parterre on a terrace, they devised a stone stairway,
capped with two stone finials threaded with vines. What makes the
stairway the perfect access for this garden is its classic air,
which serves as preamble to the formal garden.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the whimsical side of classic, which is a fitting
description of an Old World garden that Michael Trapp, a landscape
architect, improvised on his property in Connecticut. For the
entryway, he assembled architectural remnants _ arched, louvered
doors and two ancient-looking Ionic columns _ then bedecked his
contrivance with a mismatched pair of potted plants. The effect
suggests a faded grandeur that's as welcoming as a smile.
</P>
<P>
   As a landscape artist, Lisa Stamm believes that garden entrances
should be strong directional statements that leave visitors in no
doubt about where they're supposed to go. As the owner of nine
acres of heaven on which the driveway stops well short of the
garden that surrounds the house, she's doubly convinced of it.
</P>
<P>
   Her solution was an entryway designed and built by Dale Booher,
an architect who is her husband and her partner in a landscape
design business on Shelter Island in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Cushioned between two wings of a high privet hedge, an arched
gate (once the front door of their 200-year-old house) and its
squared-off frame are painted the same Benjamin Moore chrome green
as the trim on the house, visually uniting them. ``I like the
contrast of the small, narrow gate with the large expanse of garden
it opens into,'' Booher said.
</P>
<P>
   Hung from the gate are old bells, which announce callers.
Flanking it are two Spanish olive jar planters. Ms. Stamm restocks
them yearly with one or another of her favorite plant varieties,
which are all structured, long lasting and suited to shady growing
conditions. Put it all together, and you've got a garden entrance
whose function is unmistakable, and utterly compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, anyone who's intent on keeping all entrances covered
might draw inspiration from the Manhattan penthouse terrace of
Samuel Sachs, director of the Frick Collection. Perched on each of
the two brick columns marking the fire escape exit from his garden
is a cheery urnful of lobelia. Which only goes to show that in new
age castles, even uninvited callers rate the courtesy of an
inviting entryway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
