<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLMSTED-BOOK-800&AMP;add-     06-16 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLMSTED-BOOK-800&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN OLMSTED'S FOOTSTEPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As boaters clunked their oars on the lake, Witold
Rybczynski folded his big frame onto a little chair by a tiny cafe
table at the boathouse and talked about how he came to write about
the man who created Central Park almost a century and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I thought about the notion of biography first,'' said
Rybczynski, whose new book, ``A Clearing in the Distance: Frederick
Law Olmsted and America in the 19th Century'' (Scribner, $28),
takes an intimate look at the man who first joined the words
landscape and architecture and created an art.
</P>
<P>
   ``My books tend to ramble on about things,'' said Rybczynski,
56, an architect who has written eight personable, philosophical
books, including ``The Most Beautiful House in the World'' (Viking,
1989), in which the writer falls in love with the idea of building
a boat, which then needs a boathouse, which somehow turns into a
house, and on and on like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last the house gets built,'' said Rybczynski (pronounced
rib-CHIN-skee), staring down at his salmon over wilted greens, with
a contemplative air. ``And with a biography, at last the person
dies at the end, and the book stops.''
</P>
<P>
   The waiter arrived with the fresh pepper. ``What kind of greens
are these?'' Rybczynski asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arugula,'' the waiter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' Rybczynski said, tucking this new information behind his
high, broad forehead.
</P>
<P>
   So then, the question was, whom to write about without getting
bored halfway through researching this person's life.
</P>
<P>
   Rybczynski, a professor of urbanism at the University of
Pennsylvania, thought about all the architects in the world. They
live boring lives: ``They work,'' the architect said. ``They sit at
their desks. And they don't write anything down.''
</P>
<P>
   He needed someone who had kept journals captivating enough to
keep your head from hitting the desk in the archives room.
</P>
<P>
   Then he read an essay about Olmsted. The man had been a surveyor
and farmer. A journalist and abolitionist. He'd run the Federal
Sanitary Commission, the precursor to the Red Cross, during the
Civil War. Managed a gold mine in California and faced down a mob
of striking miners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't the conventional life of a landscape architect,''
said Rybczynski, who plunged into Olmsted's papers _ and discovered
the man could write!
</P>
<P>
   Here is the young farmer, on his first trip to England in 1850,
overwhelmed by the countryside _ ``green, dripping, glistening,
gorgeous,'' the hawthorn hedges, ``the mild sun beaming through the
watery atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is his description of Eaton Hall, a large estate in
Cheshire: ``A gentle undulating surface of close-cropped pasture
land, reaching way off illimitably; very old, but not very large
trees scattered singly and in groups _ so far apart as to throw
long, unbroken shadows across broad openings of light, and leave
the view in several directions unobstructed for a long distance.''
</P>
<P>
   All the elements, in other words, that Rybczynski would discover
in his own journey through Olmsted's parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I educated myself,'' he said as we left the cafe and wended
our way along the lake toward Belvedere Terrace. ``At first, I
didn't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   He gestured toward the Lake, which Olmsted had carved out of a
swamp. ``At first, it's just trees and water,'' he said. ``You
don't realize what is going on in terms of composition and light.
You tend to be more impressed by the Mall and the terrace, because
you can see them.''
</P>
<P>
   As we mounted the staircase, Rybczynski pointed out the
intricate carvings of fruit, vines, flowers and birds that Jacob
Mould had carved into the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were allegorical themes,'' he said, ``like the four
seasons, the six continents.''
</P>
<P>
   At the edge of the Mall, as the shade of the great elms gave way
to the sunlit terrace, in-line skaters zigzagged in and out of the
orange markers of their makeshift course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Olmsted would have had lots of suggestions how to deal
with the new things in his parks, like the skaters and car
traffic,'' Rybczynski said. ``But I don't think he thought of tall
buildings. He wanted it so you couldn't see anything but the
trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Central Park was the first baby step of a genius.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not only learning about landscape architecture but how
to make an 800-acre park,'' Rybczynski said. ``Nobody in America
had done anything this big.''
</P>
<P>
   Olmsted's works of art, like Prospect Park and Biltmore, the
6,000-acre Vanderbilt estate near Asheville, N.C., were yet to
come. So were the magnificent parks and leafy parkways Olmsted
created in Boston and Buffalo; the suburbs he designed like
Riverside, Ill.; the scenic drives and lookouts at Yosemite and
Niagara Falls.
</P>
<P>
   As Rybczynski points out in his book, Olmsted saw the grandeur
of Yosemite as a powerful civilizing force. ``In his era, people
believed, literally, in the healing powers of nature,'' he said. By
building parks that brought them closer to the earth, Olmsted left
a lasting gift to America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genius of Olmsted was that he did these large things,''
Rybczynski said. ``He gave structure to the city, so it couldn't be
changed easily. Then he accepted that it would be in-filled by
commercial forces. He laid out the big parks and parkways and then
let people follow their own course. He understood that you couldn't
regulate that. It's too much of a free-for-all.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Without any formal training _ just the skills he learned as a
farmer and surveyor _ but with an innate feeling for powerful
landscapes, Olmsted forged a vision that was near clairvoyant. He
foresaw a time when New Yorkers would need a bit of artificial
wilderness to escape the stress of city life, and when millions of
Americans would flock to Yosemite seeking a fragment of real
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   When Olmsted and the architect Calvert Vaux won the design
competition for Central Park in 1857, it was a long, narrow strip
of rocky bluffs to the north and swamps to the south, with an
unsightly old reservoir in the middle. Not good for real estate
development, in other words. But nothing that a few thousand
workers with horses and mules and a little vision couldn't fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they created this Mall, it was a very formal urban
space,'' Rybczynski said. ``But they tilted it slightly, so it goes
across on a diagonal, not straight up and down, so you look out
across the water toward the trees on the bluff.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned to look across the lake and grumbled, ``The
boathouse ruins the view.'' The original Victorian boathouse was
smaller in scale and enhanced, the illusion of distance, from the
top of the terrace to the rocky bluffs of the Ramble, rather than
dispelling it.
</P>
<P>
   If you try really hard to ignore the skyscrapers (though some
think them almost cozy, rising out of the trees), you could be in
the Adirondacks, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   We walked on to the Ramble, looking for a rustic shelter we knew
was there, and got lost. We found two park employees, who got into
a heated discussion over where it was (``The east side!'' ``No, no!
The west side!'') The Ramble was doing its job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olmsted took the English country park, which is very refined,
and translated it into something much rougher and more American,''
Rybczynski said. ``And he put it in the middle of New York City,
which is very strange.''
</P>
<P>
   And democracy is its soul. ``You can go into it from everywhere
_ there is no grand entrance,'' he said. ``The way you enter is on
the scale of the individual. Certainly his intention was to create
an equalizing meeting place where everybody rubs shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. Dogs swimming (without their leashes!), jogging moms
pushing baby carriages, photographers fussing over brides, in-line
skaters in the Ramble, Stuart Little sailing his boat (``Who?''
Rybczynski asked).
</P>
<P>
   If Olmsted could see us now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
