<HEADER>
A7761 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-REPROGRAMMABLE-CH     06-16 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-REPROGRAMMABLE-CHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROPROCESSOR CHAMELEONS CAN CHANGE FUNCTIONS QUICKLY TO
ACCOMMODATE NEW TASKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Va.)   (af)  
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pentium and Power PC chips that run most personal computers
are the Swiss Army knives of the microprocessor world. They can
take on a huge variety of tasks, but as anyone who has tried to
carve a turkey using a pocket knife will attest, specialized tools
make faster work of some jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The same rule applies to the computer world. Even on PCs, some
difficult jobs need help. The video cards on most personal
computers are, in effect, custom-made chips. But making custom
chips can pose a problem for hardware manufacturers; while
multimedia standards are rapidly shifting, designing and producing
a custom chip can take up to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   But a new generation of programmable chips, faster and used in
place of custom chips, could get around that problem.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional chips are operated by programs containing
step-by-step instructions that are designed to work with the chip's
fixed circuits. But the circuits of programmable chips can be, in
effect, rewired by software to convert them into special-purpose
processors. Their roles aren't fixed.
</P>
<P>
   These chameleons of the chip world can be changed or upgraded an
infinite number of times within a fraction of a second by using new
pieces of software. In theory at least, programmable chips could
have the versatility of general-purpose processors but avoid the
instant obsolescence that plagues most electronics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantages are incredible,'' said Jonathan Rose, a
professor of electrical engineering and computer science at the
University of Toronto who has researched the chips for more than a
decade. ``This offers much more than a little improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those advantages is speed. While a customized chip can
take up to 18 months to produce, a programmable chip, once its
software is designed, can be modified in less than one-thousandth
of a second.
</P>
<P>
   With programmable chips, operators have to come up with, in
effect, a wiring diagram that turns the chip into a machine
designed for handling a particular application. Unlike conventional
chips, programmable chips can be reprogrammed on the fly for, say,
decoding video, then for another task, like voice recognition, when
another batch of software arrives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those very radical changes,'' said Sandeep Vij,
a vice president of Xilinx, a programmable-chip maker based in San
Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Programmable chips can be thought of as a return to the early
days of computing. While pioneering computers like the Eniac used
programs, they also had to be physically rewired for different
tasks using plug-in cables. Programmable chips replicate that at
the level of the microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   Programmable chips have been relatively slow to catch on: Xilinx
sold the world's first commercial programmable chip 15 years ago.
In the early days, the chips were mostly bought by companies that
made specialized products in small numbers, like huge industrial
machinery for automobile assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Such machines needed the performance of custom chips, but
designing and making custom chips, at a cost of $500,000 to $1
million, didn't make sense for a small number of units. The
programmable chips themselves are not expensive _ between $5 and
$100 _ making customization for particular tasks affordable and, as
a bonus, making updating possible.
</P>
<P>
   The chips could soon make their way into consumer gadgets and
PCs because of falling prices for programmable chips and
improvements in their software and performance. The Internet is
making that transition both possible and necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Multimedia files like digital video are exactly the sort of
material that benefit from the increased performance a programmable
chip offers. Gadgets can be modified to meet new standards or offer
new features even after they are manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as a company has an idea, they can put it on a chip
and ship the product,'' Vij said. Over the next year, Vij added,
cellular phones with Internet data capability and computer
accessories like printers are likely to begin making extensive use
of programmable chips.
</P>
<P>
   It is also widely expected that the set-top boxes that cable
companies will use for delivering digital television and data to
homes will also come laden with programmable chips. Such a set-top
box, for example, would allow a customer to download software from
a cable company to customize its circuits for only the services the
customer gets.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, cable companies could easily move to new
technical standards by sending out new hardware configurations to
the programmable chips in their customers' boxes rather than
physically shipping new units.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that some consumer products could eventually find
extended lives through programmable chips. High-end cameras with
such chips, for example, could receive new features or upgrade
their performance by being plugged into a computer that has
downloaded new configuration software from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Peter Athanas, leader of a programmable chip software
group at the Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University,
said there were still some unresolved issues. ``This isn't quite
there yet,'' he said. To start with, the time it currently takes
programmable chips to ``rewire'' themselves can lead to sluggish
performance in some applications. Even though chips can respond to
new software instruction in hundredths of a millisecond, that ``is
years in processor time,'' Athanas said.
</P>
<P>
   But a more important hurdle, Athanas said, is the complexity
involved in creating the software necessary to reprogram a chip
(something beyond the capacity of nearly all consumers). Currently,
it is virtually the same process chip makers follow when designing
new chips. For ambitious and complex projects, that process can
involve a great deal of time and demand highly skilled programmers.
``We need some kind of conceptual leap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Athanas is confident that both problems will be solved, which
could lead to significant changes. Researchers are already working
on fully configurable computers, which would be completely based on
programmable chips.
</P>
<P>
   Computers with such chips, if they proved workable, could be
very fast. But they would not work with current software. And Rose,
at the University of Toronto, said such machines would most likely
be used for only specific future applications like computer vision,
not for common consumer applications.
</P>
<P>
   Athanas agreed that programmable chips were unlikely to become
the engines of ordinary computers. ``You're not going to replace
your Pentium computer with one of these things,'' he said. ``Intel
shouldn't be worried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
