<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV20-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO TRIUMPH WOULD HAVE PLEASED ONE OF ITS FOUNDERS, HARRY TRUMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 20)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The deeds of presidents past often manifest
themselves in the achievements of presidents present.
</P>
<P>
   That's the case with the creation of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization in 1949 during the presidency of Harry Truman and
NATO'S victory over evil in Kosovo in 1999 during the tenure of
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On June 11, the day after Serbian forces began their melancholy
exit from Kosovo and NATO troops prepared to take up their
peace-keeping duties in that battered land, a jubilant Clinton
proclaimed to a military audience in Missouri that Truman would be
very pleased with the outcome of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It is always risky to attribute sentiments to individuals who
are no longer alive. But in this instance it is safe to say that
Truman would be proud of the way NATO forced a murderous dictator
like Slobodan Milosevic to end his cruelty toward innocent
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The plain-spoken Missourian, who served as a field artillery
captain in World War I and headed a Senate committee that monitored
defense procurement during World War II, had no trouble
differentiating good from evil and opposing the latter.
</P>
<P>
   He would recognize in Clinton's castigation by political critics
vestiges of the troubles he faced during a tumultuous presidency
that encompassed seven years and nine months from the end of World
War II through the beginning years of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Truman would be familiar with the political games played by
today's naysayers, who refuse to admit they were wrong about the
air campaign that forced Milosevic to capitulate and who decline to
commend Clinton for his steadfast support of that campaign. Truman
would see them as reincarnations of the myopic politicians who
opposed his historic efforts to provide life-saving aid to the
victims of Nazi Germany after World War II and of the Soviet Union
during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Those critics were the ones who in Truman's day contended that
America had no business providing aid to communist-threatened
Greece and Turkey, creating the Marshall Plan to rebuild
war-shattered Europe, establishing NATO as a bastion against
communist aggression, breaking Moscow's blockade of Berlin in 1948
with U.S. air power and seeking United Nations endorsement of the
U.S. decision to oppose communist encroachment into South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   As some Republicans on Capitol Hill branded the campaign against
Milosevic ``Clinton's war,'' those of the 1950s called the fight
against the communists in Korea ``Truman's war.''
</P>
<P>
   Truman would not be surprised either by Russia's duplicitous
actions in Kosovo. He learned first-hand how Soviet dictator Josef
Stalin brutally broke commitments he made to Truman at Potsdam,
Germany, in the summer of 1945 and, earlier that year, to Franklin
D. Roosevelt at Yalta in the old Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Truman almost certainly would applaud NATO's growth in size and
power.
</P>
<P>
   When the NATO treaty was signed in 1949, it marked the first
time the United States had entered into a military alliance with
other countries. America, Canada and 10 Western European nations
were the original members.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kosovo campaign, 19 NATO nations stood as one. In
addition, the alliance, which was founded to protect Western Europe
from communist aggression, fought its first war against a
non-member nation.
</P>
<P>
   In his prize-winning biography of Truman, David McCullough notes
that although Secretary of State Dean Acheson and British Foreign
Minister Ernest Bevin had ``done most of the work'' in putting the
alliance together, ``it was Truman who provided the commitment,
unreservedly, as he had with the Marshall Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough explained: ``He (Truman) ranked NATO with the
Marshall Plan as one of the proudest achievements of his presidency
and was certain that time would prove him right.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what has happened. Time has proved him right.
</P>
<P>
   But he probably would have been as pleased with the humanitarian
aspect of the mission in Kosovo as with its military side.
</P>
<P>
   Since Truman has become a folk hero, few Americans realize that
he was held in low esteem during much of his presidency and that
his administration was besmirched by scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1951, eight months after he upheld civilian control
of the military by firing Gen. Douglas MacArthur from his command
in Korea, polls showed that only 23 percent of the American people
approved of Truman's handling of his job. Millions of Americans
thought him inadequate to the demands of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But then a magnificent old friend came to call and buoy his
spirits. It was 77-year-old Winston Churchill, who had just been
returned to office as prime minister in England and whom Truman
regarded as the greatest public figure of his age.
</P>
<P>
   Here is McCullough's description of the scene at the end of a
dinner aboard the presidential yacht Williamsburg when the eloquent
Churchill began to speak:
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at Truman, Churchill said slowly, `The last time you
and I sat across the conference table was at Potsdam, Mr.
President.' Truman nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ```I must confess, sir,' Churchill went on, `I held you in very
low regard then. I loathed your taking the place of Franklin
Roosevelt.' He paused. `I misjudged you badly. Since that time, you
more than any other man have saved Western civilization.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In a dark period for Harry Truman, a winter of tawdry scandal,
of interminable war in Korea and greatly diminished public
confidence in his leadership, the gallant old ally had again, as
only he could, served as a voice of affirmation.''
</P>
<P>
   The liberation of Kosovo is not an action commensurate with
those taken by Truman in more perilous times. But it is one in
which the magnificent achievement of an earlier generation and
president served well this generation and this president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
