<HEADER>
A7771 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIGUA-STANFORD-$ADV     06-16 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIGUA-STANFORD-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSTON BUSINESSMAN CAUGHT IN THE CROSSFIRE OF U.S.-ANTIGUA
BATTLE OVER MONEY LAUNDERING
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. JOHN'S, Antigua _ It's another boiling hot day on Antigua,
where tourists chug Carib beer and frolic on sand as soft and fine
as baby powder.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sleepy Caribbean island that boasts 365 beaches -- or
one for every day of the year -- the perfect lure for sun-starved
American tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Antigua's not as prosaic as it might seem.
</P>
<P>
   Antigua, only 9 miles wide and 12 miles long, has become the
latest beachhead in America's war to reshape offshore banking in an
economically troubled region increasingly reliant on this booming
industry.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials charge that recent laws passed here have weakened
controls on money laundering, making Antigua a haven for crooks
with money to hide.
</P>
<P>
   Antiguan officials have agreed to revise some measures, but
argue that most of their laws are first-rate, even when compared to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the crossfire of this war of words is a savvy
businessman from Houston named R. Allen Stanford, owner of the
island's largest offshore bank, Stanford International Bank Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States just doesn't want to see this island
succeed,'' maintained Stanford, who also heads the Houston-based
Stanford Financial Group, in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years, the offshore industry has become the
lifeblood of many Caribbean islands with scant resources beyond
tourism.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. officials say that lax regulation of the offshore
industry -- so named because its banks and other institutions
conduct no business in the country where they're registered -- has
aided money launderers from criminal organizations across the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   Antigua, in particular, has long battled an image as one of the
Caribbean's most corrupt, unpoliced islands.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last year, the twin-island nation of Antigua and
Barbuda, with a population of just under 64,000, was home to as
many as 57 offshore banks, mostly U.S.-owned.
</P>
<P>
   These banks started cropping up a few years ago, when Antigua's
offshore industry was virtually unregulated.
</P>
<P>
   The island made headlines in 1997 when it closed five
Russian-owned banks local officials said were suspected of
laundering hundreds of millions of dollars for the Russian mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Only a year earlier, Antigua had enacted an
anti-money-laundering law, one U.S. officials contend was never
fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in April, the U.S. Treasury Department took the drastic
step of publicly warning U.S. banks to keep close tabs on
transactions conducted through banks in Antigua because of their
susceptibility to money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the second time in history that the department has
targeted a specific country with such a warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that the Antiguan government has, in effect,
turned away from its partnership with the United States government
in combating money laundering and other financial crimes,'' wrote
James L. Johnson, undersecretary for enforcement in the U.S.
Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory was a surprise blow to Antiguan officials -- and to
others -- who point to a continuing effort here to clean up the
reputation of the offshore industry, an effort Stanford has played
a leading role in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are islands with far worse records on money laundering
than Antigua, so we can't figure out why the United States is
picking on this one country, unless it has something against
Stanford,'' said Charles Intriago, publisher of the newsletter
Money Laundering Alert.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and friendly, with a Texas drawl to match, the 49-year-old
Stanford made his money in the early 1980s building houses in
Houston. One neighborhood there, Stanford Oaks, still bears his
name.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s Stanford set up his first bank in the Caribbean
-- where he had once taught scuba diving -- so that his homebuyers
might have a place to deposit their escrows.
</P>
<P>
   He opened his bank in Antigua in 1985. And today Stanford, who
flies in and out of this island in a private jet, is like this
island's own Henry Potter, the character from ``It's a Wonderful
Life'' -- only a kinder, gentler version -- in that he seems to
have his hands in almost every pie.
</P>
<P>
   Antiguans peruse his daily newspaper, the Antigua Sun, and
conduct business at his domestic bank, the Bank of Antigua.
</P>
<P>
   His offshore bank -- one of the first sights people see upon
exiting the airport -- is an imposing structure that dwarfs the
island's other commercial buildings in terms of its grandness.
</P>
<P>
   He's also spearheading construction of a hospital, a hotel and
office complex, and an indoor basketball stadium near the home of
Prime Minister Lester Bird, a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a johnny-come-lately,'' says Stanford, whose
businesses employs some 500 people here. ``I call myself Texan
first, and an Antiguan second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antigua's been my primary residence for seven continuous
years,'' he adds. ``I'm becoming an Antiguan citizen this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   While no one seems to question Stanford's love of the island --
Lionel Hurst, Antigua's ambassador to the United States, calls him
``as forthright and respectable as they come'' -- the breadth of
his business activities here does raise eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most important is that Stanford has helped Antigua
draft legislation to oversee its offshore industry by paying a team
of U.S. consultants to advise Antigua as it prepared amendments to
its anti-money-laundering law.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford said he wants to help Antigua build a respectable
offshore industry along the lines of the Bahamas, which has
tightened controls on money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those amendments -- approved in November -- were viewed
as positive even by U.S. officials, such as the one making it
illegal for offshore banks to accept cash deposits.
</P>
<P>
   But others helped get Antigua, a former British colony, into hot
water.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Treasury officials say the more ``egregious'' amendments
weakened controls on money laundering by inhibiting investigations
and strengthening bank secrecy rules.
</P>
<P>
   They were most alarmed, though, that at least three members of a
six-member board created to oversee the offshore industry
represented the very institutions they were supposed to regulate.
</P>
<P>
   One of those three members was Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Errol Cort, once one of Stanford's attorneys,
explained the reasoning behind the board's make-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that in such a small country, with limited experience,
it would be useful to have people on the board who do have a lot of
experience in the industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Antigua, which earns $5 million a year from
offshore banks, has since reconstituted the board and Stanford is
no longer on it. The island's annual budget is $155 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did raise eyebrows here when Mr. Stanford was chosen to sit
on the board,'' said Althea Crick, the board's executive director,
adding no further explanation.
</P>
<P>
   She defended Antigua's actions, in general, insisting the island
today has ``zero tolerance'' for money launderers.
</P>
<P>
   The Antiguan government has shut down 14 offshore banks
suspected of shady dealings since November -- it expects to close
perhaps 20 more -- and has drafted new amendments to the
anti-money-laundering law local officials insist will satisfy U.S.
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, privately, U.S. officials continue to express suspicion
over Antigua's efforts, saying the island has a poor track record
when it comes to keeping promises and cooperating with U.S.
investigators in cases of suspected money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   They also express suspicion when it comes to Stanford and his
influence on the Antiguan government even though no one will
pinpoint any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that suspicion may be related to last year's discovery
that alleged front men for the late Mexican drug baron Amado
Carrillo Fuentes had deposited $3 million in accounts at Stanford
International Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Stanford willingly handed over that money in February to the
Drug Enforcement Administration, a move that marked the first time
a Caribbean offshore bank has voluntarily repatriated drug money to
a U.S. government agency.
</P>
<P>
   Antiguan officials say the United States must have had an
ulterior motive in issuing the April advisory, which they are
pushing to have lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States doesn't want us to do well because then it
would lose its influence over us,'' said Attorney General Cort.
``The U.S. government would like to keep us as beggars, down on our
knees, looking for U.S. aid.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
