<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7782 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRSHOW-JSF-TEX     06-16 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRSHOW-JSF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKHEED MARTIN, BOEING EXCHANGE BARBS IN CAMPAIGN FOR JSF
CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LE BOURGET, France _ Like two politicians, Lockheed Martin and
Boeing are trading jabs in their all-or-nothing campaign for the
military's 3,000-airplane Joint Strike Fighter contract. And the
gibes have added considerable entertainment at the industry's Paris
Air Show this week.
</P>
<P>
   Companies often don't like to discuss competitors _ but not in
this case. Boeing is crowing about being under cost, a sly
reference to Lockheed Martin's admission of a cost overrun this
year. Lockheed Martin, in turn, is whispering about why Boeing
needed to redesign the tail section of its JSF entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least they have a tail on it now,'' said Mickey Blackwell,
president of Lockheed Martin's aeronautics sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have people coming up to me all the time with these good
rumors about the Lockheed Martin program,'' Frank Statkus, Boeing's
JSF manager, said in an interview Tuesday after his company and
Lockheed held dueling news media briefings on their JSF programs.
``I tell them I don't have time for it. We have a competition to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The barbs at the air show _ a major exposition for manufacturers
and potential buyers _ have underscored the enormous stakes
involved. The competing versions of the JSF won't fly until next
year and the Pentagon won't make its choice until 2001. But the
program is expected to be the last major U.S. military fighter
contract until 2040 and will be worth up to $40 billion in domestic
and foreign sales.
</P>
<P>
   If Lockheed Martin wins, it will do the work at its Fort Worth
plant to replace the current F-16 line. If it loses the contract,
the company has implied that the Fort Worth operation could be hit
hard.
</P>
<P>
   Although rumors have abounded from Washington that the federal
government will split the final contract to preserve two major
fighter contractors, both companies say they're proceeding as if
their lives are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is a must-win,'' said Fort Worth plant President Dain
Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the reports from the rival camps have tended to
exaggerate the others' troubles. Lockheed Martin has taken pains to
refute rumors that its cost overrun has been as high as $300
million, although it won't specify the amount.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Lockheed Martin has noted that it has stuck with the
same design it submitted when it won its way into the final
competition in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Statkus said Boeing's JSF has had a tail from the beginning. It
just needed to be changed earlier this year to meet stability
requirements. No big deal, he said in the same tone that Blackwell
used when talking about Lockheed Martin's costs.
</P>
<P>
   And Lockheed Martin's JSF director, Frank Cappucio, said that
the cost overrun ``doesn't mean that we have run out of money. It
means that the testing on some of the risk factors was a little
more expensive than we had anticipated. We'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have begun assembling their two demonstrator
aircraft at plants in Palmdale, Calif. They will be tested at
nearby Edwards Air Force Base. There will be a fly-off beginning
next year and into 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The plane will be a multiservice aircraft, going to the U.S. Air
Force, Navy and Marines and to the British Royal Navy. Because the
U.S. Navy and Air Force already have their favorite fighters _ the
Navy's Boeing F-18 and the Air Force's Lockheed Martin F-22 _
suggestions have been made that one or both of those services will
bug out.
</P>
<P>
   That has happened before. The Navy was supposed to have been a
part of the F-111 and F-16, both Fort Worth products, but opted
out. If that happens again, the Marines will be left high and dry.
They desperately need replacements for their aging FA-8
vertical-lift fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be out of luck,'' said Marine Lt. Gen. Fred McCorkle,
deputy director of the Marine's aviation program. ``I keep telling
the Navy and the Air Force to stay with this. I think they will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marine version will have vertical lift. To help out,
Lockheed Martin has engaged British Aerospace, builder of the
Harrier ``jump jet,'' as a partner in the JSF. Boeing, which merged
with AV-8 vertical-lift builder McDonnell Douglas two years ago, is
relying on a Harrier-like lift configuration that uses two
downward-pointing nozzles from the main engine.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin officials have suggested that Boeing's hot
exhaust vertical lift plan won't work because it would throw
intolerable heat back into the airplane as it hovers. But Statkus
said that isn't so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our version is no hotter than the Harrier, and the British
have been using it for 30 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin has touted its shaft-driven fan, which blows
cooler, nonjet air downward to propel the craft. Cappucio said,
``We believe in this concept. And the vertical lift will be the
determinant in who wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Statkus doesn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winner will be the lowest-cost provider,'' he said, a
reference to Boeing, which claims to now be within budget while
Lockheed Martin has run over.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Boeing says that the Lockheed Martin vertical lift
might not be all that cool, anyway. Lockheed Martin's entry, unlike
Boeing's, has a swiveling rear exhaust that will point down when
hovering. That exhaust will be pure jet heat.
</P>
<P>
   British Aerospace has about 40 engineers working in Fort Worth.
Northrop Grumman, builder of Navy planes going back to World War
II, is another joint venture partner and has 20 engineers in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is obvious that the rivals have respect for one
another. Statkus said ``I tell my people every day that we can't
count on Lockheed Martin to lose this competition. We'll have to
win it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   JSF CUSTOMERS
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the primary prospective buyers for the joint
strike fighter, a big contract that Lockheed Martin and Boeing are
trying to win.
</P>
<P>
   Service.........Number of aircraft....JSF's role
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Navy.......480...................Complement to F-18
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Air Force..1,763.................Replace F-16 and A-10,
complement F-22
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Marines....609...................Replace F/A-18 and AV-8
</P>
<P>
   Royal Navy......60....................Replace the Sea Harrier
</P>
<P>
   Source: Lockheed Martin, Boeing
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
