<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7840 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECLINERS17-COX     06-16 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECLINERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let Dad kick back in chairs that offer music, massage and
message of comfort
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like modern dads, recliners today are more
sophisticated and sleek-looking than the stuffy, unsightly chairs
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   No longer banished to a corner in the basement or family room,
the new recliners glide, tilt, shake and swivel as well as recline.
Still other styles are big enough to seat two in cozy style.
</P>
<P>
   When Dave Rush, 36, and his family relax in their Marietta (Ga.)
home, they head straight for their two recliners. ``My 9-year-old
daughter Laken loves to sit on my lap when the `Sunday sleepies'
take over,'' said Rush, a principal with Kurt Salmon Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The recliner is not a ``lazy man's chair anymore,'' according to
interior decorator Alison Park of Paisley Park Interiors in
Alpharetta (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   ``It has evolved into a versatile family chair done in beautiful
fabrics,'' said Park. ``For my clients, I put recliners in their
bedrooms as well as family rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the trend in recliners is toward smaller-scale chairs
that don't look like recliners and that don't take up as much space
as the room-eating monsters of a decade ago. These streamlined
styles offer such traditional chair features as wing backs, brass
studs and carved legs and feet.
</P>
<P>
   Other recliners are state-of-the-art chairs in which you can do
everything from ordering a pizza to indulging in a body massage.
For example, Lane's Ultimate recliner, the Voyager, starting at
$999, boasts a built-in speakerphone, a computer hookup, holders
for cups and magazines and a heated massage system. And La-Z-Boy's
newest recliner, the Oasis, which debuts in stores in August
starting at about $900, has its own refrigeration system for
stashing a six-pack.
</P>
<P>
   Also, hidden levers and buttons and streamlined mechanisms make
recliners appeal to a wide range of dads _ and kids.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent ``unofficial'' test of recliners at the HomeLife
store in Alpharetta, 8-year-old Haley Jackson of Marietta
pronounced Lane's Boulder chair, which is actually a
chair-and-a-half, ``comfy and looking good.'' Her dad, Bill
Jackson, 49, general manager of the Marietta Conference Center,
said it would ``be very easy to fall asleep in this recliner.''
</P>
<P>
   Testing Catnapper's leather-like recliner, complete with heated
massage, speakerphone and storage units, WSB-TV advertising
salesman Allen Williams, 46, and his 17-year-old daughter, Nicole,
both agreed _ ``it's great for Super Bowl watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of people are willing to kick back and relax. According to
Furniture Today, an industry publication, sales of recliners
reached $3.3 billion in 1998. This figure was up an estimated 13
percent over the previous year's sales. La-Z-Boy is one of the
largest sellers of recliners. Other names in the business include:
Action Lane, Berkline, Barcalounger, Catnapper and Stratolounger.
</P>
<P>
   Recliners are in style for a number of reasons. ``I call it the
casualization of the American lifestyle,'' said marketing executive
John Chase of La-Z-Boy, whose company last year sold more than 1.5
million recliners. ``Nowadays people entertain less formally, often
sitting around watching large-screen TVs. They want to be able to
put their feet up and relax in the best seat in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   He also sees the recliner spanning the generation gap. ``Today's
kids see that Dad still has a recliner,'' said Chase, ``so they
think, `Hey, a recliner must be good, so I'll buy one too.'''
</P>
<P>
   Prices for recliners range from about $400 for a bare-bones
chair to more than $2,000 for a sleek leather job with all types of
electronic bells and whistles. Most recliners fall in the $500-$700
range.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing salesman David Brooks, 44, is more than willing to fork
over $700 for a recliner. ``After all,'' he says, ``you can't put a
price on pure comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
