<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIFFANY-WINDOWS-ART-2     06-16 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIFFANY-WINDOWS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOWING RIVERS, SITTING DUCKS: TIFFANY'S MASTERWORKS IN VULNERABLE
PLACES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Ill., Pa., Fla., Mass., Mich., Iowa)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The colors are warmest in winter, when the sun's rays
are low in the sky and envelop the stained-glass horizon in amber
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``This window is certainly alive,'' the Rev. Gerald Johnson was
saying the other day, sitting in the pews of the Sage Memorial
First Presbyterian Church in Far Rockaway, Queens, and
contemplating the unsung Louis Comfort Tiffany masterpiece with
great gnarled branches that lies at the end of the A train.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives life,'' added Leonardo Thompson, a car-parts salesman
and longtime parishioner. ``Not only to the church, but to the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Comfort Tiffany, who is buried not far away beneath a
smooth gray granite stone in Brooklyn's historic Green-Wood
Cemetery, designed stained glass windows like this ``Tree of
Life,'' his largest landscape, to be sacred. They still are _ not
only in urban reaches like Far Rockaway, where even thunderous jets
from nearby Kennedy International Airport can't disturb silent
prayers, but also in quiet corners of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany's special effects, pre-Spielberg, still illuminate
churches on Mare Island, Calif., and in New Rochelle, N.Y., and
mausoleums in Steelton, Pa.; St. Louis, and Adrian, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   They were built at the height of turn-of-the-century religious
fervor, when church-building was a national pastime and extravagant
tombs were embellished with art. But in a relatively obscure
private Jewish burial ground called Salem Fields, in Brooklyn, the
sacred has tangled with the profane and the profane has won.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Alastair Duncan, a leading Tiffany expert and scholar
whom colleagues say knew more about the location and authenticity
of Tiffany windows than anybody else, was indicted in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan on charges arising from the theft (or planned
theft) of Tiffany windows and the sale of one from Salem Fields, a
landscape in the ``River of Life'' series, to a Japanese client for
$219,980. If convicted on all counts, Duncan could get 35 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Even before news of this recent theft, paranoia had come to rest
among the tombs of the elite in cemeteries nationwide, where an
unknown number of Tiffany windows still reside. At one Brooklyn
cemetery last week, where windows remain deliberately unpublicized,
wind in the beech trees sent dappled light flickering ethereally
behind Tiffany clouds. And at Woodlawn Cemetery in the Bronx, Greek
Revival mausoleums built to express lofty values are now fortified
with bulletproof glass to protect the Tiffanys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' said Woodlawn president and chief executive
Edward Laux, ``when Tiffany originally designed these
installations, he didn't think about them being stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, which investigated the theft with the New York Police
Department, keeps no national statistics on Tiffanys-at-large. The
Art Loss Register database knows of nine missing Tiffany windows,
including five from cemeteries. More than 30 other period windows
from public spaces remain unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1980 book, ``Tiffany Windows,'' now itself a collectors'
item, Duncan wrote that stained glass windows were Louis Comfort
Tiffany's ``first artistic love.'' The lamps, he noted, were mere
afterthoughts, ingenious ways to re-use waste glass from the
windows that were his passion.
</P>
<P>
   The market for trophy Tiffanys, which resulted in a window
fetching $662,500 at Christie's last week, was feverish even when
the book came out, nearly 20 years ago. If a lamp could fetch
$250,000, Duncan mused in the book (which contains Tiffany's own
partial list of windows and locations), ``what will the major
windows themselves finally be worth?''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan has pleaded not guilty to the charges. He is out on bail
and is scheduled to appear in court next week, when a trial date is
expected to be set. He has long been considered ``one of the icons
of the Tiffany industry'' said Paul Crist, a Santa Fe Springs,
Calif., dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Wild West market,'' Crist added about the growing
demand on dealers, ``so dealers are tempted to skirt the gray
areas. There are so many collectors and so little merchandise.
Competition for a high-quality Tiffany window becomes like dogs
fighting over a bone.''
</P>
<P>
   (Last week, Duncan wrote to friends and colleagues to deny what
he called ``this baseless allegation'' saying, ``It will be
determined that I was a victim in this matter and not knowingly
involved in any wrongdoing.'')
</P>
<P>
   The stolen Tiffany landscape may have been a bargain for the
client. ``The price was very reasonable for a beautiful Tiffany
window,'' said Paul Nassau, the owner of the Lillian Nassau
gallery, noting that a ``terrific one'' can fetch $1 million or
more.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always so: the Tiffany style was considered passe by
1940 and went unnoticed until the 1970s. ``During World War II,
they would take the lamps and smash them on the sidewalk to sell
the lead,'' Nassau said. It didn't change until the '70s, when
celebrities like Barbra Streisand and Catherine Deneuve began
collecting.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the moody evocations of cypresses, wisteria and rivers
flowing into distant hills set collectors' hearts atwitter far more
than religious subjects. ``It's very difficult to sell the New
Testament,'' said Barbara Deisroth, a senior vice president of
Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Nassau put it, ``Nobody is risking their career over a
religious Tiffany window.''
</P>
<P>
   The theft has highlighted the rich legacy of Tiffany windows in
obscure places, including signature ``River of Life'' windows,
dreamy landscapes that flowed through gilded age churches, robber
barons' mansions and tombs. In 1976, a dazzling ``River of Life''
window, with pink irises in the foreground and sinuous cypresses in
the distance, was stolen from the Denkmann mausoleum at
Chippiannock Cemetery in Rock Island, Ill., tomb of a founder of
the Weyerhaeuser timber company. But the search by Rock Island
police, and the FBI (which recruited Duncan as a consultant), went
dormant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later, Gregory Vogele, the cemetery superintendent
like his father and grandfather before him, spotted an article in
an Illinois newspaper about the Charles Hosmer Morse Museum of
American Art in Winter Park, Fla., which has one of the world's
finest collections of Tiffany glass. He sent them a photograph of
the missing window. ``Being third generation, there's kind of a
family history there,'' Vogele said of his attachment to the
cemetery. ``I had the good fortune of growing up looking at that
window in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatefully, several months after getting his letter, the museum
was offered the window, which had suffered an 18-inch diagonal
crack, by a private dealer and collector from Queens, the last in a
22-year trail of owners. It was surrendered to the FBI and recently
shipped back, heavily guarded, to the Denkmann family, which has
decided to restore the window and donate it to the nearby Davenport
Museum of Art, in Davenport, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was amazed,'' Fay Hauberg Page, a Denkmann
descendant, said of the window's recovery. ``Given the current
state of affairs, we decided it was safer in a museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Another stolen Tiffany window from the same cemetery remains at
large.
</P>
<P>
   Because ``no two Tiffany windows are exactly alike,'' said David
P. Donaldson, a former curator at the Morse Museum and now a dealer
in Orlando, a Polaroid may be the best defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The glass is all mottling and striations,'' Donaldson said.
``It's like a DNA print.''
</P>
<P>
   That quality of aliveness, in which a window's aspect shifts
constantly, like a trout stream or a flame, is one reason why
Tiffany windows across the country are being reclaimed and
appreciated anew. ``People today are looking for community,'' said
Virginia C. Raguin, an art historian at the College of the Holy
Cross in Worcester, Mass., who specializes in stained glass. ``They
are also rediscovering ritual. Those contemporary desires find an
echo in Tiffany windows, which create a tremendous sense of
place.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ann Arbor, Mich., a 10-by-6-foot Tiffany window in a 1904
former Unitarian church was rediscovered when an architectural
firm, Hobbs &AMP; Black Associates, moved its offices into the church
and peeled away some plaster. ``Voila,'' said Larry Frank, an
architect with the firm. ``There was the Tiffany.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the full grandeur of a rare, intact Tiffany interior
was unveiled two years ago at the Ayer family mansion (built
between 1899 and 1901), a major Tiffany commission. The building,
now the Bayridge Residence and Cultural Center, a residence hall
for college women, is filled with exquisite Tiffany windows,
skylights and Byzantine and Moorish mosaics.
</P>
<P>
   And at the 1895 St. Gabriel's Roman Catholic Church in New
Rochelle, N.Y., a drive to restore four Tiffany windows has been
undertaken by a largely immigrant congregation. It is a warm,
jubilant place, despite missing pieces of glass and buckling lead,
with masses in English, Spanish and French.
</P>
<P>
   So far about $150,000 has been raised by parishioners, many of
whom hold down several jobs as seasonal laborers, gardeners, house
painters, nannies and country club workers.
</P>
<P>
   The church's population swells in the summer months and then
declines in winter, ``when there are no golf courses to take care
of or grass to cut,'' said Yolanda Davis, 60, a parishioner, who
was born in Guadalajara, Mexico. Her favorite spot is the pew next
to `` `The Visitation' _ the Tiffany,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at that window,'' she explained, ``it makes you
feel the presence of God is there.''
</P>
<P>
   The church wants to raise $300,000 to restore both the windows
and the building itself. ``People see themselves in these
windows,'' the Rev. Patrick Vincent McNamara said. The wedding of
Mary and Joseph, he said, ``looks so human, like the ordinary
marriage of two people in love.''
</P>
<P>
   In Far Rockaway not long ago, the parish got a call from an
antiques dealer offering to buy their window and replace it with a
copy. Even Johnson, the interim pastor, once suggested that the
financially strapped congregation consider selling. ``They didn't
even take me seriously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be here forever,'' said the parishioner
Thompson. ``The other generation passed it down to us, and we want
to pass that same feeling on to them. It's our duty. Money's not
everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
