u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTIST-WOMAN-NYTR &LR;      06-16 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-WOMAN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BAPTIST WOMAN SKIRTS THE EDGE OF CONTROVERSY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CARY McMULLEN   
 The Ledger (Lakeland, Fla.)   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last year, when the Southern Baptist Convention voted
to add a chapter to the Baptist Faith and Message that declared ``a
wife is to submit herself graciously to the servant leadership of
her husband,'' Dellanna O'Brien braced herself.
</P>
<P>
   The executive director of the Women's Missionary Union figured
she would be besieged by the media, wanting her reaction as a
female official of the nation's largest Protestant denomination.
But to her surprise, no one came calling.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for her belated reaction, O'Brien declines. ``I'd rather
not. We have women of every kind of opinion, from
ultra-conservative to moderate. We can argue all day long, a lot of
times saying the same things in different words. I'd rather find
the real sticking points, the ones I'd die for,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In refusing to be drawn into controversy, she shows the
graciousness and diplomatic skills for which she is famous. But she
tips her hand a bit in her views about the place of women when she
describes her work and that of her husband, Bill, a Southern
Baptist pastor and missionary and former vice president of the
International Mission Board. It's a view that skirts the edge of
disagreement with recent Southern Baptist Convention philosophy,
which tends to stratify gender roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were both partners in having a ministry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, 65, delivered her final report as executive director
Wednesday, during the last day of the Southern Baptist Convention's
two-day meeting at the Georgia Dome. She will retire later this
month and was honored by the convention Tuesday with a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Birmingham, Ala., the Women's Missionary Union has
about 1 million members. It was founded in 1888 as a means for
women to organize their work in local churches.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of her accomplishments and her education _ she has
earned a doctorate in education from Virginia Tech _ O'Brien
represents the changes that have occurred in the lives of women in
her lifetime. She says her organization had to adapt.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early time, women were home-centered. There were few
ways they could be involved. Increasingly, women were more educated
and in the workplace. Our greatest challenge was that we were
beginning to see such changes with women in every facet of life,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, O'Brien has managed to have it all. A wife and a
mother, she served alongside her husband as a missionary in
Indonesia. Upon her return to the United States, she taught at The
Collegiate School, a prestigious private school in Richmond, Va.,
but became concerned for the children of missionaries who were
having trouble with school. The doctorate qualified her as a
diagnostician and she formed her own company, International Family
and Educational Services, to work with children and parents.
</P>
<P>
   When she was recruited for the position of executive director of
the women's group, she relied on divine guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't looking for this job, but there was a growing
awareness that God was ordaining this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During her tenure, she has overseen new programs designed to
help working women find ways to serve others, the same impulse that
drove their mothers and grandmothers only in new ways. For example,
the group this summer will produce seven ``women-built'' Habitat
for Humanity homes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other programs she has initiated reflect current
concerns that affect women, such as a Christian Women's Job Corps,
designed to ease the transition of women on welfare into the
workplace by pairing them with mentors for up to two years.
</P>
<P>
   She has also established a foundation to ensure that the
organization will have financial resources to carry out its
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be her greatest accomplishment,'' said Wanda Lee,
president of the Women's Missionary Union executive board. ``She is
one of the most brilliant thinkers I've ever been around. Every
time we room together on our travels, she is telling me about what
she has read.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's obvious abilities experienced a setback in September
when she suffered a stroke. She continues to walk stiffly and
offers her left hand when she introduces herself. But Lee, a nurse,
says she showed determination to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people close up after a stroke. She has not stopped
for one minute to think about herself. There was never any
whining,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With her retirement O'Brien and her husband plan to work side by
side again in missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to Germany in the fall and Australia in January.
We have an assignment to Argentina in the spring,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a warm pink dress that looked both professional and
feminine, she said women have the ability to use their heads as
well as their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid to bring different opinions to women because
they're competent before God. The main goal, though, is to get them
involved in Christian service,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
