<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL FORECAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The first soaking rain in nearly a month will bring relief from
the dry spell to the Middle Atlantic region. Low pressure south of
Richmond will draw warm, humid air from the Atlantic inland and
over the top of a shallow, chilly air mass in the Northeast. There
will likely be two bands of moderate to heavy rain, one in the
Appalachians and the other right on the shoreline. In between,
periods of light rain and drizzle are expected. It will be very
cool with readings at least 15 degrees below seasonal levels from
Virginia to central New York. High pressure in Maine will keep much
of New England dry, but it will turn dull as clouds lower and
thicken.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms will be potent along the Southeast Coast as a cold
front pushes toward the Atlantic. A cluster of heavy thundershowers
may drench northwest Florida as tropical moisture merges with an
approaching cold front.
</P>
<P>
   More record chill is expected Thursday morning in the Middle
West as high pressure dominates the center of the nation. Less
humid and somewhat cooler air will circulate into the middle
Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and showers will persist near the eastern Rockies as
humid winds from the south ascend the sloping terrain. Patches of
moisture will circulate westward into the Four Corners region
leading to a few afternoon storms.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West will be dry and warmer. Sunshine will be ample
from the interior Northwest into California and the deserts of the
Southwest. The Coast will still notice low clouds and fog.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Focus: Hot and Cold &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Very often, when the East gets cold, the West will get very
warm. Wednesday morning, Buffalo and Rochester both dropped to
record lows of 41 degrees, while on Tuesday afternoon, Lewiston,
Idaho set a record high of 99 degrees. The typical distance between
warm ridges and cold troughs in the jet stream is about 2,500
miles, or roughly the width of the United States. Thus, when a
bulge of warm air is over the West, a pool of cold air is often
over the East. A similar situation will occur Thursday, as parts of
the East may have highs only in the 50s in a steady rain, while the
West will again be near 90. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Extended Forecast &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sunday _ High pressure just off the East Coast will
keep most of the Northeast dry and warm. A disturbance in the
Mississippi Valley will spread showers and thunder to portions of
the Southeast. A few afternoon thunderstorms may erupt in Texas,
otherwise, much of the Southwest will remain sunny and dry. A cold
front moving through the Rockies will bring showers and cooler
temperatures to the Pacific Northwest.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Tuesday _ A surge of warmer and more humid air ahead of
a cold front in the Great Lakes will trigger a few thunderstorms in
the Ohio Valley. Winds from the south around high pressure off the
Southeast coast will pump sultry air into the South. A few
afternoon rumbles of thunder may be heard along the Gulf Coast and
in the interior West. Dry and hot weather will continue in the
Southwest while cool air plunges into the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
