<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE, SIGNALING HIS INDEPENDENCE FROM CLINTON, ANNOUNCES HIS
PRESIDENTIAL BID
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTHAGE, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore, signaling his
independence from President Clinton, promised moral leadership in
formally unveiling his ``New Horizon'' presidential candidacy
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you entrust me with the presidency, I will marshal its
authority, its resources and its moral leadership to fight for
America's families,'' Gore said from the steps of the Smith County
courthouse, the spot in Tennessee's hill country from which he
began his political career in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the nearly 8,000 people who jammed the main street of
this small town, the vice president promised to ``take my own
values of faith and family to the presidency, to build an America
that is not only better off, but better.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's remarks were designed to distance him from questions
about Clinton's character. They were sandwiched between comments to
reporters Tuesday and an ABC ``20/20'' interview broadcast
Wednesday night in which he said Clinton's extramarital affair and
lies about it were ``inexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
   But if anyone missed the contrast between the two men, Gore's
own family members and longtime friends reiterated the importance
to Gore of old-fashioned values _ the kind that, in political lore,
are to be found in small towns like Carthage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen how much he cares for his own children and for all
of our children, for his own family and for all of our families,''
said his eldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, who took over the
task of introducing her father to the crowd from her mother,
Tipper, who is suffering laryngitis. Schiff, 25, is expecting the
Gores' first grandchild in 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the kind of values you find on the courthouse squares
of Tennessee,'' said former Gov. Ned Ray McWherter, recalling how
Gore had sought his support in his first campaign for Congress 23
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Carthage itself, as a flag- and banner-bedecked backdrop for
Gore's announcement, helped send the subtle message that the vice
president is more connected to main street America and its values
than to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But in Washington, Republicans tried to undercut that message
with a publicity gimmick in which GOP National Chairman Jim
Nicholson rode a mule-driven cart to the luxurious downtown hotel
where Gore lived while his father was in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The stunt was a response to comments Gore made in March about
spending youthful summers plowing fields on his family's farm in
Carthage. The Gores currently own an 80-acre farm next to that
family farm.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson also ridiculed Gore's attempt to distance himself from
the president, recalling how Gore had defended Clinton last
December in a Rose Garden rally of Democrats following the House
vote to impeach the president. ``Al Gore has been the president's
biggest cheerleader,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore distanced himself from the president on ethical
matters Wednesday, he eagerly credited the president _ and, by
extension, himself _ for the current economic boom and the end of
ethnic brutality in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud that we refused to yield to the forces of barbarism
in Kosovo,'' he said. ``President Clinton was right to stand for
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   He contrasted the current economy with the 1992 recession that
helped drag down the re-election campaign of George Bush, thereby
subtly linking the current Republican presidential frontrunner,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, to his father's economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   And in doing so, he formulated a question similar to the one
posed by Ronald Reagan in his successful campaign to unseat Jimmy
Carter in 1980. Where Reagan asked, ``Are you better off now than
you were four years ago?,'' Gore asked, ``Will we turn back now _
or will we move forward?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not mention Bush by name. But he alluded to the GOP
frontrunner's well-publicized but largely undefined philosophy of
``compassionate conservatism'' in suggesting that the current
economic prosperity should continue ``the right way _ not by
letting people fend for themselves, or hoping for crumbs of
compassion, but by giving people the skills and knowledge to
succeed in their own right.''
</P>
<P>
   He also alluded to Bush's attempts to move his party beyond its
staunch opposition to abortion rights. ``Some try to duck the issue
of choice,'' he said. ``Not me. American women must be able to make
that decision for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore repeated many of the policy positions he has already staked
out: using religious organizations to combat social problems,
curtailing urban sprawl, strengthening gun control laws, stopping
the entertainment industry from marketing violence to children,
``revolutionary'' improvements in public education, a minimum wage
increase, a Patient's Bill of Rights, opposition to privatizing
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his remarks, however, focused on what he described as
``the crisis in the American family today,'' the result of new
``deficits'' that have replaced the nearly $200 billion federal
budget deficit that the Clinton-Gore administration inherited in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are our deficits now: the time deficit in family life;
the decency deficit in our common culture; the care deficit for our
little ones and our elderly parents,'' he said. ``Our families are
loving but over-stretched.''
</P>
<P>
   He occasionally sounded like Bush in promoting ``personal
responsibility'' and admonishing his own baby boomer generation to
``master'' their own lives in order to ``have the moral authority
to guide our children.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Gore's second campaign for the presidency. He ran in
1988, but did poorly. He declined to run in 1992, but Clinton,
after winning the nomination, chose him as his running mate. Prior
to becoming vice president, he served in the House of
Representatives before being elected to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose only opposition for the 2000 Democratic nomination
