<HEADER>
A7923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMWAY-INTERNET-NYTR &LR;      06-16 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWAY-INTERNET-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMWAY RIDES ONTO INTERNET VIA QUIXTAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BOB NORBERG   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Retailing giant Amway is taking its network
marketing business model, the foundation of its $5.7 billion a year
in annual sales, to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing to fruition an effort one year in the making, Amway on
Sept. 1 will open Quixtar, a spin-off company with an Internet site
that will sell Amway's well-known products, such as cleansers,
vitamins and beauty aids, and host as many as 200 other online
stores selling name-brand products.
</P>
<P>
   Though behind trailblazers like Amazon.com and online shopping
malls, Amway's entry to the Web will take direct marketing on the
Web to a new level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Amway 2000, it's the wave of the future,'' said Julie
McGee, a spokeswoman in Amway's Ada, Mich., headquarters. ``The
Internet is the way technology is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Amway is promoting the new venture with an Internet site,
www.countdown9199.com, which recruits investors but cloaks
Quixtar's link to Amway. Aggressive promotion is not new to Amway,
which relies on an expanding network of people's friends and
acquaintances to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was door-to-door stuff, or they would invite people over
to dinner and all of a sudden they'd be getting an Amway
presentation,'' said Ken Abernathy-Hansen of Santa Rosa, a longtime
Amway dealer who acknowledges that some Amway dealers didn't leave
the best impression.
</P>
<P>
   But Abernathy-Hansen says the consumer has to separate the
actions of some sales people from Amway the company, which he said
is ethical and offers people an opportunity to have their own small
business.
</P>
<P>
   John Parker, who holds the dual positions of director of
distributor relations for Amway and director of business relations
for Quixtar, said Quixtar will operate as a separate company from
Amway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quixtar is not a subsidiary nor a division of Amway, but a
sister company owned like Amway by the DeVos and Van Andel
families,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said Quixtar will be an online site that provides
information and sells and promotes products depending on a buyer's
individual profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would my wife look like if she used a different color of
foundation and different shade of eye shadow? She could go online
and experiment with that,'' Parker said. ``In a virtual makeover,
she'll be able to enter information about her skin coloring and
then get information on what works together.''
</P>
<P>
   What hasn't changed is how Amway will be selling its products,
using multi-level marketing in which distributors, in this case
called ``independent business owners,'' refer people to the site
and earn commissions on sales.
</P>
<P>
   The business owners, who pay a $99.95 fee, also recruit others
to form a sales chain and earn commissions on the sales by owners
below them, much like Amway distributors now operate.
</P>
<P>
   As with Amway, the product is almost secondary to the sales
process. The Web site and pamphlets tout the potential for huge
sales on the Internet and the amount of money investors can earn.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said 360,000 have already registered to become
independent business owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way for hundreds of thousands of people to have their
own Web-based business without having the headaches and capital
expense,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   People who are referred to the Quixtar site can opt to just make
purchases, with the commission going to the referring business
owner, or pay a fee to become a client, which earns them points on
purchases and makes them eligible for discounts.
</P>
<P>
   They can also decide to pay their own $99.95 fee and become part
of the Quixtar sales chain, getting commissions on their own
referrals and earning commissions for the business owners in the
chain above them.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is being sold to current Amway distributors as having
the potential to make them a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   With Amway, a distributor can earn $1,300 to $1,400 a month in
commissions if he buys $200 in goods a month and has in the
distribution chain beneath him 46 people who do the same, said
Harvey Bell, an Amway distributor in Rohnert Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Those signing on with Quixtar expect that income to double,
triple or even quadruple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a nice income with Amway, but I think it will go up many
fold,'' said Abernathy-Hansen. ``I'm sitting in a position to
triple my income with what I've already built. I expect my income
to be $5,000 to $6,000 a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Quixtar has posted information ``to educate and to motivate
potential Quixtar business participants about e-commerce'' on
Quixtar's site, www.quixtar.com, and the countdown tease site,
www.countdown9199.com.
</P>
<P>
   Quixtar's high-gloss, color brochures tout the potential of the
Internet and the explosive growth of online shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Financial details about Quixtar, which will be headquartered in
Ada and Grand Rapids, Mich., are few _ the names and even the
number of the other stores have not been released.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said the site make suggestions for products based on the
shopper's personal profile developed from information given by the
shopper.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said the advantage Quixtar has over other Internet sites
is that it can use its existing Amway network to attract traffic,
instead of having to purchase newspaper or television ads. And the
network to distribute the products is already in place.
</P>
<P>
   He said Quixtar is not expected to replace Amway.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long term, there is a place in the market for both
Amway and Quixtar,'' Parker said. ``The growth of the Internet is
significant, but we have a very significant business in the United
States and we see both businesses surviving.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bob Norberg writes for the The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa,
Calif., which is part of The New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group. This article is distributed by The New York Times News
Service. &LR;  &QL; 
4
</P>
