<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   MURDOCK _ CHICAGO _ Rupert Murdock speaks at the Chicago cable
show. Haddad says that there's no way of predicting what he'll talk
about but - obviously - Murdock is a colorful guy and likely to
make news. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   BOARDS-MINORITIES _ Ethnic minority directors captured greater
numbers of seats on corporate boards last year and now have a
presence in 60 percent of America's boardrooms, according to a
study of proxy ballots of Fortune-listed companies released today
by Korn/Ferry International, the world's leading executive search
firm. African Americans make up the largest contingent of minority
directors, moving onto 39 percent of all boards, up from 37 percent
in the 1998 report, according to Korn/Ferry International's 26th
Annual Board of Directors Study. Twelve percent of boards now have
a Latino member - the same as the previous year -- while nine
percent report at least one Asian member, up from six percent a
year earlier. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   ENTREPRENEUR-AWARDS _ Ernst &AMP; Young selects winners for its
annual Entrepreneur of the Year awards. Will feature main story
with list of local nominees in various categories. (Joyner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MICROTEL _ U.S. Franchise Systems opens its first Microtel
property outside the United States. The hotel will open in Honduras
within the next few months. This is just the beginning of the
company's expansion into Latin America. Other projects are planned
for Panama, El Salvador, Costa Rico and other Latin American
countries. We talk to CEO Michael Leven about the company's plans.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE _ Total Systems Services, of Columbus, is teaming up
with Sun Microsystems and other companies to create a
business-to-business e-commerce system. We previewed this last
week. Announcement is today. We'll interview the TSS CEO today.
(Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ Jimmy Carter left the White House $1 million in debt,
but today is a multimillionaire _ as are George Bush, Ronald Reagan
and Gerald Ford. Bill Clinton isn't wealthy yet, but for a time his
blind trust was invested i Internet stocks. These are just a few of
the presidential investment revelations in the latest Money (July).
(Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
