<P>
   BBN-CASEY _ CINCINNATI _ Sean Casey's deep blue eyes flash under
his tousled hair and he speaks in his gee-whiz conversational tone
no matter where he is, what he is doing or to whom he is talking.
Not long after his 34-inch, 32-ounce bat tore a path of destruction
through Kansas City for two days _ 10 hits that included two home
runs, a double and seven RBIs _ Casey thought about last weekend's
series against the Cleveland Indians and it was as if somebody
dropped a concrete block on his size 12 feet. ``Do you realize that
if I were still in the Cleveland organization I'd still be playing
at Triple-A Buffalo?'' Casey said. ``That's the truth. Since I can
only play first base and they wouldn't let me be a designated
hitter, I'd still be playing in the minor leagues because they have
Jim Thome and Richie Sexson.'' Fortunately for Casey and the
Cincinnati Reds, the Indians needed a starting pitcher and
reluctantly traded the 24-year-old first baseman for Dave Burba
less than 24 hours before Burba was to pitch Opening Day 1998 for
the Reds. (McCoy, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
