<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7928 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DESKTOP-DESIGN-AR     06-16 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DESKTOP-DESIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINKING OUTSIDE THE BEIGE BOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the millions of desktop computers in the world could be
stacked into a great wall, the resulting construction might
resemble some enormous Louise Nevelson sculpture dominated by one
oppressive shape: the box.
</P>
<P>
   The BUB, the computer industry's self-mocking acronym for Big
Ugly Box, has ruled computer design for years. Now a wave of design
innovation, or imitation, is cresting at personal computer
companies looking for a way to break out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   Packard Bell NEC, owned by NEC Corp. and Groupe Bull, planned to
formally announce Thursday the release of the Z1, a powerful $2,500
desktop that entirely does away with the box, bulky or otherwise.
At first glance, the Z1 _ which comes with 96 megabytes of SDRAM,
or synchronous dynamic random access memory _ looks like little
more than a flat-screen monitor looming over a keyboard (which is
wireless and has buttons that can do the job of a mouse).
</P>
<P>
   Most of the computer's vital components, usually placed in a
large box, have been made to fit into little more than a slight
bulge behind the sliver of monitor.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gateway introduced the Profile, a sleek desktop PC
for which prices start at $2,000, that manages to make its
formidable electronic innards so compact that the computer and its
monitor can easily take up no more space on the top of the desk
than a sheet of typing paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PC has become the dashboard of our lives,'' said Jeff
Hensen, the marketing manager for Gateway. ``As the technology
becomes more pervasive, there's a need to make it less intrusive,
no matter what environment you are in.''
</P>
<P>
   The new emphasis on PC design has come in the wake of last
spring's stylish darling, the colorful iMac from Apple, but it is
being driven by the advent of flat-screen monitors. The trend began
earlier this year with the release of Sony's gray and lavender VAIO
Slimtop PCV-L600 and with the blue and gray 320 Visual Workstation,
the first consumer-oriented Windows NT machine from Silicon
Graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike notebook computers, long the masters of PC
miniaturization, the two new all-in-one PC's _ in which the
computer and monitor are combined _ do not compromise memory
capacity, storage and processing power for the sake of reduced size
and attractive looks. While both possess lines that would make them
look at home on a museum pedestal, the Z1 packs one of the most
powerful microprocessors, a 450-megahertz Pentium III, and the
Profile uses a new 400-MHz Advanced Micro Devices K6-2 XT
processor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What PC makers are realizing is that design sells,'' said
Lowell Goss, the creative director for Frog, a major industrial
design and communications consulting company based in Sunnyvale,
Calif. Frog helped define the black, minimalist look of the Sony
Trinitron television 20 years ago as well as some of the early
Apple computer designs.
</P>
<P>
   For years, computers were sold by their technology, like
speedier microprocessors, bigger hard drives and more clever
circuit boards. But the nature of the PC business, where high
profit margins depend on assembling new machines quickly using
standardized components, has not been fertile ground for design
innovation and ingenuity, Goss said. But as the field of computer
makers grows more crowded and the prices flatten out, the pressure
to create something that looks distinctive has increased.
</P>
<P>
   The computer that recently brought the subject of design to
public attention was, of course, the iMAC, but that wasn't the
first radical makeover for a computer box. In 1996, Acer's Aspire,
for example, featured rippled edges and a colorful shell with
ventilation holes that looked as if they had been made with
buckshot. But it failed to catch the public's imagination like the
iMac has.
</P>
<P>
   ``The iMac has eaten everyone's lunch,'' Goss said. ``What galls
PC makers is that the iMac is a high-margin machine.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Z1 and Profile have very different genealogies than the
iMac. What is giving rise to the flashy new desktop PC's, said Tim
Bajarian, president of Creative Strategies in San Jose, Calif., is
the flat-panel monitor, almost the antithesis of the iMAC's
retro-curvy box; in this area, the Japanese have been pioneers.
Flat-panel monitors, generally costing four times as much as
conventional monitors, are being used as the cornerstone of these
supersleek computers for a simple reason: profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question in our mind that the future of computer
design is really being defined by the Japanese,'' Bajarian said.
``The motivation is not necessarily, `Let's be innovative,' as much
as it is, `Let's get traditional PC users to see how exciting these
computers with flat screens are and sell them at higher prices.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Omae, vice president for marketing at Sony, said that design
was important to the company when it started making PC's several
years ago. ``We introduced a well-designed PC,'' he said. ``Sony
wanted customers proud of owning a PC.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony made its PC's with new colors and materials. The Slimtop's
sleek box, about the size of two closed laptops laid one on top of
another, was achieved by replacing the standard monitor with a
flat-screen liquid crystal display and integrating notebook-like
technologies to this desktop computer. And that was achieved
without reducing performance and function. The Slimtop is anchored
with a 500-MHz Pentium III processor and a 10.8-gigabyte hard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   When Silicon Graphics, a longtime major company in the powerful
professional work station market, wanted to offer its first Windows
NT machine for a new market this year, it was concerned with the
computer's look as well as its performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make a statement,'' said Cliff Apsey, director of
product marketing for the company's work station division. The 320
sports a 17.3-inch flat-screen monitor and a tower that looks like
a two-toned, asymmetrical silo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is esthetically pleasing, then it adds an extra aura
around the whole product,'' Apsey said. ``But it's one thing to
deliver a nice-looking product. You have to back it up with what's
inside.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7929 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DESKTOP-DESIGN-AR     06-16 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DESKTOP-DESIGN-ART-2DTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: what's inside.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the design approach of the new breed of PC's, like the Z1
and Profile, however, should not confused with that of the much
less expensive iMac. While the colorful iMac eliminated the box,
which has traditionally been beige, it has a standard 15-inch
cathode-ray-tube monitor. The iMac is an all-in-one computer that
is, for most purposes, a what-you-see-is-what-you-get machine. The
user can add memory to an iMac but cannot significantly upgrade it
in other ways, such as by adding a bigger monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The new all-in-one PC machines offer great flexibility. The Z1,
which hides its 8.4-gigabyte hard drive in its base, offers a rear
panel for easy access to inner components and fast upgrades. It
also permits users to remove the screen easily and snap in an
18-inch flat-screen monitor. And like a laptop computer, the Z1,
which will be shipped in August, features two PC Card Type II or a
Type III PCMCIA slots along with four Universal Serial Bus slots.
</P>
<P>
   ``In designing the Z1, we set out to challenge the traditional
beige computer box,'' said Gordon Chapple, executive vice president
of Packard Bell NEC's consumer division. In January, he told the
Z1's designers to come up a computer that was ``elegant,
sophisticated and friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Layered into that statement was `break the rules,''' said
Peter Wyatt-Brandenburg, project manager and senior designer at
Hauser Inc., an industrial design and product development company
in Westlake Village, Calif., that did most of the design work on
the Z1. ``If we didn't push it, there was no reason to be doing the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   After preliminary talks last December, Hauser was given the
go-ahead in January. The five-person design team, housed in an open
loftlike building with its own duck pond about 40 miles north of
Los Angeles, went to work on what a Packard Bell NEC executive
called a ``project without borders.''
</P>
<P>
   The designers looked at other consumer electronics devices that
have become familiar in many American homes, like notebook
computers and digital cameras. An in-house anthropologist gave the
team insights about how people relate to their machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time we talked about it like a coffee-table
computer, something that would look good from all angles, not this
thing with a bad end to it where all the cords come out,''
Wyatt-Brandenburg said.
</P>
<P>
   After guiding their ideas through a series of foam models and
prototypes, Wyatt-Brandenburg said, the design for the Z1, code
named Zuma, emerged in about three weeks. Mal Ransom, senior vice
president for marketing at Packard Bell NEC's consumer division,
sat in the Hauser offices recently, looking pleased as he admired a
preproduction model of the Z1. ``We are ecstatic about the outcome
of the project,'' he told the designers.
</P>
<P>
   But Hauser and Packard Bell NEC officials say they tried to not
overshoot the expectations of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the designers intentionally placed the Z1's DVD and
floppy drives in plain view so that consumers, long used to a
separate computer box and monitor, would not mistake this two-toned
metallic blue PC for merely an overpriced flat-panel monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other big desktop players are being far more
conservative. While International Business Machines designers
recently announced the creation of a wearable Walkman-sized PC, the
company's desktop computers continue to look very much as they have
for years _ boxy. A spokeswoman for Compaq, another pioneer in PC
design and manufacturing, said that company is not making a new
slim PC like the V1.
</P>
<P>
   And in a meeting earlier this year with technology writers and
editors from The New York Times, Michael Dell, chairman of the Dell
Computer Corp., said he did not envision big changes in how his
company makes its desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   So Moore's Law, which says the capacity of computer chips
doubles every 18 months, appears to be holding true for the insides
of computers, but there doesn't seem to be an equivalent axiom for
the outsides of computers _ at least, not yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
