<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-16 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN BIG BOOKS FALL A LITTLE FLAT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens in publishing more often than even sophisticated
readers realize and certainly more than anyone in the business
would like. There are great expectations that a particular book
will break out and become a big-time popular success, its future
guaranteed. Abundant press coverage and good reviews fuel that fire
of anticipation. Then there's no ice cream cone at the end.
</P>
<P>
   That can be heartbreak time, because everyone involved with the
specific book did everything right. There was the splashiest
publication party of the year, and a tub-thumping publicity
campaign that produced a load of press clippings almost voluptuous
in their delights. The author's television and radio interviews
were hip, humorous, inviting, and there are more to come as his
book tour continues.
</P>
<P>
   Reviews ranged from good to raves. Moreover, in one way or
another, the book's subject matter touches nearly everyone's life.
Yet in the mysterious nature of the publishing world, with all of
this going for it, the book still does not become a big national
best seller: successful by some measures but falling short of wow.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent case of this strange publishing ontology is Kurt
Andersen's huge novel ``Turn of the Century'' (Random House), a
sprawling, satirical and often funny work set in the year 2000.
Seemingly, as fiction, it has it all, in a way that says Now!: the
media universe, cyberspace, Wall Street, Manhattan, Hollywood,
Silicon Valley, society being confounded by the very communication
devices that are supposed to make people's lives easier. In short,
it sends up everything Americans supposedly hold dear.
</P>
<P>
   So fingers were crossed that if it didn't actually become this
season's ``Bonfire of the Vanities,'' Tom Wolfe's mighty 1987 best
seller, the new book had the potential for a reach in that
direction and would be a powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Andersen's novel is a success in ways that can make an
author proud. Few first novels get as good or as many reviews,
although the number may in part be because of Andersen's celebrity
in the world he wrote about as co-founder of Spy magazine and staff
writer for The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   The book arrived the first week in May with a printing of 65,000
copies, very large for a literary first novel but fair for a
popular novel. Since then it has gone back to print twice, bringing
the total to 72,000 copies available for stores. So far ``Turn of
the Century'' has been on The Los Angeles Times, The San Francisco
Chronicle and Newsday best-seller lists, and has been No. 15 on the
Amazon.com hard-cover fiction list, but not near the top of Barnes
&AMP; Noble's list. Nor has it made The New York Times' or Publisher's
Weekly lists, which are the only two national lists. Still, most
novels never make any lists.
</P>
<P>
   Random House says it has earned back it's six-figure advance. A
paperback house has guaranteed a minimum price it will pay to buy
``Turn of the Century'' for publication. Foreign rights have been
sold in five countries, but so far there is no movie sale, and that
may be a matter of bad timing.
</P>
<P>
   Books into movies is often cyclic. With the high cost of
production, Hollywood is in an interval in which only blockbuster
books will be easily sold to the movies or to television.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Andersen was on Charlie Rose, Conan O'Brien and cable shows,
and he is booked for ``Politically Incorrect,'' all of which give a
book a glamorous pop. All promotion opportunities first novelists
would kill for.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own expectations have been far exceeded,'' Andersen said.
``I was amazed and happy with overwhelming reviews, and with the
best-seller lists I've made. I feel as though I won the lottery,
the $10 million one, if not the $20 million one. I'm a first
novelist. To book buyers in America I'm not Grisham, Smith,
Harris.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a conventional commercial novel that everyone can
read in three hours,'' he said. ``I wrote it to be a good book, one
that I would like. It's a big, fat, dense first novel, and I can't
tell you how pleased I am to be around the top 10 on some lists.''
</P>
<P>
   There are as many theories about why a particular book doesn't
burst out of the stores and into comfortable niches on the
important best-seller lists as there are titles that are expected
to but don't.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen's book, for instance, is huge, 659 pages; heavier than
many people want to lug in their tote bags. It can be amusing and
insightful, but also difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of the novel is too inside-y, too geared to the
knowing of the New York, Washington and Los Angeles and their
satellites. They are interested in media types, but how many care
in North Carolina or Iowa?
</P>
<P>
   One theory is that its title and its rather documentarylike
cover confuse readers into thinking it's yet another serious
nonfiction book about this century or this or that generation or,
worse yet, about the next millennium, which seems to be boring
people before it's even started. There's even this inside joke: The
novel's natural constituents, media types, all got free copies.
</P>
<P>
   Does this book have a future? Ann Godoff, its publisher, quite
naturally answers with a resounding yes.
</P>
<P>
   She said: ``Word of mouth is the way books ultimately catch on,
and I think this is one of the great word-of-mouth books. Our
numbers are strong, just not that strong yet. It's selling very
well, with best-seller numbers in some places.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs another fix, and I think we have enough ammunition
left to make it a summer read that takes off,'' she said. ``It has
a real story, a real plot. It's a real novel that should have legs
beyond it's first month.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Godoff is a tough competitor. She said that if the
best-seller lists didn't have an ``event book'' on them _ Thomas
Harris' ``Hannibal'' (Delacorte) _ and ``weren't clogged up with
stuff that shouldn't be there,'' Andersen would already be on the
major national lists. That's an old refrain in publishing.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that The Times' hard-cover best-seller list has three
children's books and two dead authors on it. But, hey, that's the
stew pot of book publishing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
