<HEADER>
A7934 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WOMEN-INVESTORS-2     06-16 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WOMEN-INVESTORS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITE-SEEING: MONEY MANAGEMENT FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Homer's ancient world, Cassandra was a beautiful Trojan
princess upon whom the god Apollo bestowed the gift of prophecy.
But when Cassandra refused to repay his generosity with sexual
favors, Apollo put a curse on her: her prophecies _ all of disaster
_ would be accurate but nobody would understand or believe her.
</P>
<P>
   The Cassandra myth has been adopted by the modern investment
community as a metaphor for foretelling disaster. For Ellen McGirt,
the stockbroker-turned-Web-site-producer behind Cassandra's
Revenge, the tale (adjusting it liberally) is a metaphor for the
plight of women seeking to become investors.
</P>
<P>
   Given the right information, Ms. McGirt said, women should learn
to trust their own prophecies and heed their own investment advice.
</P>
<P>
   For many women, that's a stretch. According to Merrill Lynch's
Ninth Annual Retirement and Financial Planning Survey, for 1998,
most American women simply do not feel well prepared for making
investment choices. Only 57 percent of women surveyed said they
felt comfortable (compared with 78 percent of men).
</P>
<P>
   The average woman will spend fewer years in the labor force than
the average man.
</P>
<P>
   To Ms. McGirt, this fact makes women far more vulnerable to
money problems than men, given that they have less exposure to
investment opportunities, retirement contributions and other
advantages of employment.
</P>
<P>
   The Web can help. The early years of the Web saw the rise of
numerous innovative small investment sites. Sadly but perhaps not
surprisingly, by now most of them have disappeared, squeezed out in
part by the onslaught of women's megasites.
</P>
<P>
   On those larger sites would-be investors can usually expect to
find a predictable mix of investment advice columns, on topics like
saving for your children's college education and for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   What these sites try to provide is a comfortable place for women
to seek information, form investment clubs and ask questions of
experts and peers, all without leaving their desks. And then there
are sites that, like the mythical superwoman, try to do it all, by
providing scores of financial calculators and dishing out empirical
advice on investment strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there is no embarrassment of riches here; only a
handful of these sites offer the appropriate tools along with the
depth of research necessary for serious investors.
</P>
<P>
   CASSANDRA'S REVENGE
</P>
<P>
   www.cassandrasrevenge.com
</P>
<P>
   As with its name, this site is as heavy on attitude as it is
with information and is the perfect starting point for first-time
female investors trying to boost their confidence and learn the
basics. (Surprisingly, despite the site's female orientation,
nearly a third of its regular visitors are men.) Cassandra's
Revenge is geared toward serious beginners, and the material found
there is deeper than it is broad. You won't find financial
calculators or stock tables. Instead, there is an articles section
with clever and easily understood writing by the site's founder,
Ellen McGirt, on everything from initial public offerings and Roth
IRAs to investing in collectibles and planning for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGirt takes a moderate approach to stock trading, advising
her readers to pick from a number of carefully described strategies
to find one that suits their ``goals, financial situation and
personality.'' And then, she warns, expect to win some and lose
some (and with some patience, come out ahead in the long run).
</P>
<P>
   From the site's home page you can link to a stock-trading
simulator called Wall Street Connection that lets you pretend to
buy and sell stocks without risking any real money.
</P>
<P>
   It is a useful exercise and a good confidence builder, and it
can put you in touch with other women just getting their feet wet
in investing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGirt, who writes and produces Cassandra's Revenge, is a
full-time finance writer and former stockbroker. Single and in her
late 30s, she manages to understand the needs of professional
women, homemakers, retirees and even widows equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, there is plenty of information specifically for
women,'' Ms. McGirt writes on the site. ``It's called information.
It doesn't have to be gender specific. The key will be the attitude
you bring to the process. So trust yourself and get going.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Cassandra's Revenge can provide a much-needed
pep talk for women intimidated by the notion of investing.
</P>
<P>
   KA-CHING
</P>
<P>
   www.ka-ching.com
</P>
<P>
   This well-designed and informative site was developed by Oxygen
Media, a television and Internet start-up headed by Geraldine
Laybourne, the former Nickelodeon executive. (Its list of
well-heeled investors includes Oprah Winfrey and the television
producer Caryn Mandabach.) So it's no wonder that Ka-Ching (think
cash register) tries to entertain while it informs.
</P>
<P>
   Here, female investors should find everything they need for
researching investments short of actually making a trade. The tools
section is particularly strong, featuring a financial calculator
for every occasion, like saving for college and retirement,
calculating and consolidating debt or paying off a mortgage. A
portfolio section lets you track investments, get stock quotes and
even link to one of four electronic brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   The site's editorial content serves up less attitude than
Cassandra's Revenge (even Ellen McGirt, who writes and produces
Cassandra's Revenge and is a regular contributor, tones things down
for Ka-Ching), but its articles offer equally helpful advice, as
well as profiles of financially successful women.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   A recent article, for example, was a profile of a young mother
who started her own capital management firm; another article looked
at the importance of prenuptial agreements. And an entire section
of Ka-Ching is devoted to financing the care of elderly parents,
offering analyses of issues like guardianship and special trusts.
</P>
<P>
   With its attractive combination of tools and advice, Ka-Ching is
clearly the strongest among the overall investment sites for women.
</P>
<P>
   WIFE.ORG
</P>
<P>
   www.wife.org
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the name fool you _ this site, produced by the
nonprofit Women's Institute for Financial Education in San Diego,
offers a selection of resources for women of all ages and
circumstances. But its creator, Ginita Wall, is a financial planner
specializing in the issues surrounding divorce. For women in the
process of divorce and trying to sort out the financial mess, this
is the site to use.
</P>
<P>
   Wife.org offers an eclectic mix of articles. Though not
exhaustive, they cover some of the important bases. And the tone of
the articles is generally warm and assuring. Recently, there was
even a primer titled ``The Dow Industrials: What Are They?''
</P>
<P>
   The articles at Wife.org are well written and well presented,
but the overall editorial offering is thin compared with other
sites reviewed here.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some women will find the site to be a great resource,
particularly if they are running a household single-handedly or in
the midst of a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY MODE
</P>
<P>
   www.womenswire.com/money
</P>
<P>
   One of the big problems any investor faces is information
overload, and with investing being among the most popular
activities on the Web, the load is getting heavier. The
well-organized Money Mode site produced by the Women.com network
tackles that problem by helping both novices and seasoned investors
find just what they need.
</P>
<P>
   What is notable about Money Mode is that it is produced in
conjunction with Bloomberg, a major force in stock market news and
information that supplies much of site's financial data and all of
its calculators. Bloomberg's presence alone makes the site worth
taking note of, and you can be sure the information is accurate and
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   It also means this site does a good job of tracking events that
affect the stock market, with more news articles, constantly posted
and updated, than the other sites.
</P>
<P>
   One of Money Mode's more interesting features is the
Bloomberg/Women.com 30, an index of 30 publicly traded companies
run by women that the site tracks on a daily basis. So if it is
important to you to invest in companies with a good track record
for promoting women, this index will come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Though you may find everything you need to make informed
investments on Money Mode, one thing you won't find is a heavy
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   IVILLAGE MONEYLIFE
</P>
<P>
   www.ivillagemoneylife.com
</P>
<P>
   The women's online network Ivillage is notable for the sheer
volume of information it offers: its Moneylife site is exhaustive.
If you are not accustomed to the cute language of some women's
magazines, Moneylife may take you aback, or even get on your
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in a section called Market Maven, a financial
planner, Adriane Berg, suggests that stocks are like men _ ``Some
are good for a night out and some for long-term relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you are a regular reader of cover headlines at the
checkout counter, you will feel right at home _ and you'll find
there is a lot to learn on this site.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of useful resources hidden behind the glitz, in
six categories: Starting Out, Couples and Kids, Market Maven,
Suddenly Single, Deep in Debt and Retire Rich. In each section, you
will find well-written articles and the opportunity to chat on the
topic.
</P>
<P>
   There are articles on debt management and cutting retirement
costs, for example, and nearly every investment calculator you are
likely to need. You will also find more personal articles, about
how to stop fighting with your spouse about money, for example, and
the overall importance of spending time with your children.
</P>
<P>
   Ivillage places a huge emphasis on bulletin boards and live
chat, giving participants the chance to sound off on most issues
that come up or to connect with other women in similar situations.
There is a debt recovery group, for example, as well as bulletin
boards for dozens of investment clubs.
</P>
<P>
   SHE'S GOT IT TOGETHER: www.shesgotittogether.com A relatively
new and still underdeveloped site from the publishers of Profit
Magazine, but worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   PINKBULL: www.pinkbull.com Includes the well-written Pinkbull
Market Report, news stories and stock quotes, as well as investment
tools.
</P>
<P>
   FABULOUS MARKET BABE: www.fabmktbabe.com Written by a woman with
both men and women in mind, this site has an irreverent and often
snide tone, but the information appears reliable as well as
occasionally entertaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
