A7941 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     06-16 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV18-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER'S DAY GIFTS CONFUSION
</HEADLINE>
  (For release June 18)  
(rk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is clearly a lot of confusion surrounding Father's Day,
the most recent evidence being a story titled, ``20 Ways To Make
Dad's Day.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of story that a woman might read and say to
herself, ``Well, aren't those some clever and imaginative ideas for
Father's Day gifts!''
</P>
<P>
   It was also the kind of story that a man might read and say to
himself, ``If I move to Alaska now and change my name, she'll never
find me.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked several male friends for their reaction to the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first question I asked myself,'' said my golf buddy,
Blowhole, ``was, `What woman wrote this?'''
</P>
<P>
   My attorney, Jaws, said one word kept repeating itself in his
head as he read the story. ``Divorce. Divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Start a worm farm?'' howled my 13-year-old son, quoting one of
the more reasonable suggestions in the list of 20.
</P>
<P>
   I feel certain that the (female) writer of the story did not
intend to cause such fear and loathing among males, which makes the
whole thing doubly scary. She undoubtedly thought that these were
things that would make Dad happy on Father's Day, the kind of
miscommunication that makes the
Men-Are-From-Mars/Women-Are-From-Venus thing seem like a mind meld
by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the number one suggestion: ``Have a lawn and garden day.
Bring lots of power tools. Rent a chipper shredder, power washer or
tiller, and help Dad get the back yard in order. Spread some grass
seed or just go hog wild and install an automatic sprinkler
system!''
</P>
<P>
   Call me old-fashioned, but to me nothing says Father's Day like
a nice case of sun stroke with a few sliced-off fingers and toes
thrown in for good measure. The trail of blood on the carpet, the
frantic call to 911 and the wild ride in the back of the ambulance
to the hospital emergency room guarantee that this will be a day
Dad will not soon forget, assuming he lives through it.
</P>
<P>
   Number two: ``Plan an overnight camping trip. Yes, one where you
sleep in a tent, by the fire, in the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two possibilities here: Either the writer has never
attempted to sleep in a tent in the woods in Florida in late June
or else she wants to punish her husband for the jumper cables he
bought her last Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Number seven (and my personal favorite): ``Send him on a
surprise trip to visit relatives he hasn't seen in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, maybe there's a reason he hasn't seen those relatives in a
while and that reason is: HE CAN'T STAND THEM!
</P>
<P>
   Haven't you noticed that just the mere mention of visiting these
people sends your husband spiraling into a black hole of depression
that no amount of Prozac will help him escape?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is the explanation for the recent rash of ``air
rage'' where guys drink way too much and try to punch a hole
through the emergency exit: They've been sent on a ``surprise''
visit to hated relatives by their spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Number 12: ``Start a worm farm. He'll never have to buy bait
again!''
</P>
<P>
   What with installing automatic sprinkler systems, visiting
undesirable relatives and slapping mosquitoes in a 120-degree tent,
it's unlikely that Dad will have the time or the energy to do much
fishing. But even if he does, does he really need his own worm farm
to supply his personal bait needs? This seems rather like building
your own nuclear reactor to supply your personal plutonium needs.
</P>
<P>
   Which, come to think of it, might be another fun activity for
Dad this Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
