<SLUG> BC-CIR-MP3-COPYRIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL PITFALLS ARE EASY TO FIND ALONG WITH MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The heart of the MP3 controversy is the copyright issue. Because
of the ease of moving digital files from CD to computer and from
computer to computer, executives at major recording labels are
concerned that their artists' music will be illegally copied.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America tried
unsuccessfully to prevent Diamond Multimedia from releasing the
Rio, a portable MP3 player, because of the potential for piracy.
(Diamond recently announced that it would include special
encryption features to address the problem.)
</P>
<P>
   Some artists want to retain copyright themselves, deciding on
their own whether to distribute music over the Net for a fee. The
rapper Chuck D recently made his group Public Enemy's latest album,
``There's a Poison Goin' On,'' available in its entirety before it
was released on CD.
</P>
<P>
   The MP3 format is legal but can be used illegally. On sites like
MP3.com, many unsigned artists have granted permission for surfers
to download their songs, which is legal. But on sites where
permission hasn't been granted, copying those songs is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Prerecorded music _ a CD, for example _ can be copied to a tape
cassette or to an MP3 format for personal use, to listen to on a
computer or portable player. That copy cannot legally be given,
traded or sold to anyone else.
</P>
</TEXT>
