<SLUG> BC-GEEK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; High-Quality Playback From Apple Computer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer last week officially released Quicktime 4, the
latest version of its multimedia software for Windows and Macintosh
systems. Quicktime 4 (which can be downloaded from
www.apple.com/quicktime) offers high-quality playback for both
streaming and stored video and audio files, a component that can
display video and image files in a wide variety of formats, and
support for MP3 and other compression technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the launching wasn't always as smooth as
well-streamed video. Apple unveiled a beta version on April 19, the
work-in-progress release of a program that allows the company to
get plenty of time-saving bug reports and comments from unpaid
testers.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with beta software, however, bugs and bombs were
not uncommon. Ric Ford's Macintouch page (www.macintouch.com) began
posting user feedback on the software a few months ago, and Apple
also maintains a lively message board and tech-tip exchange on its
site. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest bait for the beta testers was the
high-quality version of the ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace'' Web trailer, exclusively in the Quicktime 4 format. Apple
reports that 6.25 million copies of Quicktime 4.0 have been
downloaded since the beta version was made available. Users were
not shy about posting reports of system glitches they were enduring
after installing the beta version, including unexplained crashes
and problems that spread to other programs, causing some to believe
that maybe the Quicktime 4 beta version itself was a phantom
menace.
</P>
<P>
   The final release of Quicktime 4 came out on June 8. ``The good
thing was, we didn't find many bugs that would be considered
show-stoppers by any software company on the planet,'' said Frank
Casanova, the director of Quicktime product marketing. ``Of course,
software is never finished. It's done, but it's never finished.''
</P>
<P>
   _J.D. BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Automated Strategies to Detect and Defuse Viruses &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The widespread invasion last week by the file-devouring Explore
worm underscored the networked society's vulnerability to malicious
computer programs. But even as the computer underworld is devising
increasingly sophisticated attacks, two major antiviral software
companies _ Symantec, with its partners IBM and Intel, and Network
Associates _ will soon deploy new automated systems to aid in the
speedy detection, analysis and defusing of viruses.
</P>
<P>
   At present, antivirus software carries a database containing the
unique fingerprints of known viruses. The hard part, however, is to
recognize what might be a new disease altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The new technology being developed, part of broader automated
security programs, relies on a central computer that acts like a
digital petri dish. The idea, explained Wes Wasson, director of
security product marketing for Network Associates, is a computer
that simulates a virus' environment and responds like the human
immune system. In particular, the program watches for the telltale
sign of a virus, whether it replicates and spreads, and then
creates a digital fingerprint and designs an antidote.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Symantec Antivirus Research Center in Santa
Monica, Calif., successfully tested the automated system on the
Melissa virus. ``It took it 40 minutes to find a cure,'' said the
company's chief antivirus researcher, Carey Nachenberg.
</P>
<P>
   But viruses are more easily detected than worms. The current
version of the Symantec system was not able to detect the Explore
worm, Nachenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The Network Associates version would recognize Explore as a
hostile program, but would not be able to design a cure, Wasson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Network Associates and Symantec servers will be available to
corporate clients later this year, and the Symantec version will be
available to home users as well.
</P>
<P>
   _SARA ROBINSON
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Digital Recorder Offers Capacity in Hours, Not Minutes  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Digital recorders have at least one great advantage over
magnetic tape models: they have the ability to download your spoken
thoughts into a computer for automatic conversion into printed text
through voice recognition software. The drawback is that digital
recorders generally measure their capacity in minutes, not hours.
</P>
<P>
   Olympus has solved at least part of the problem with its new
$199 DS-150 model, which can capture up to 2 hours and 40 minutes
of conversation or dictation, about 20 minutes less than the
maximum recording time of a traditional microcassette recorder. For
text conversion, that time is cut approximately in half.
</P>
<P>
   The downloading feature, which uses either a computer's serial
or U.S.B. port, is vital. Unlike some other digital recorders,
including the previous model offered by Olympus, the digital flash
memory in which the DS-150 captures chatter cannot be exchanged for
a blank unit when full. But Dave Veilleux, director of business
development at Olympus America, said he expected that many ``road
warriors'' would buy the machine because it allowed them to dictate
memorandums while traveling and then use e-mail to send the results
back to their offices for transcription.
</P>
<P>
   _IAN AUSTEN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Speeding Up Communication by Saving Strokes on a Keypad &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The new technology called T9 is not an ultra-high-speed
telecommunications line. It's software that promises to eliminate
the cumbersome and time-consuming chore of punching text messages
into a wireless device.
</P>
<P>
   The T9 system, developed by Tegic Communications, a start-up
company in Seattle, began as a technology for people with severe
physical disabilities. Eye movements were used to trigger the
desired cluster of letters. To minimize the work required, the
program interpreted the correct spelling from a variety of
possibilities. In the midst of the project, the company's founders
saw greater opportunity in the wireless handset market and shifted
their focus.
</P>
<P>
   T9 requires far fewer keystrokes than the traditional method.
Although each key can be interpreted in three ways _ G, H or I, for
instance _ the program scans all the possibilities to determine the
correct word. Tegic executives say T9 gets the correct word on the
first try 29 out of 30 times. There is also a version in Chinese
and Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to do messaging, short phrases, what you'd
theoretically like to do is look at the lettering on the phone and
just start typing away at the letters and have the system figure
out what the likely words are,'' Gerry Purdy, president and chief
executive of Mobile Insights, a market research company in Mountain
View, Calif. ``They've done quite a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Tegic says it has now licensed the T9 Text Input technology to
more than 16 wireless phone manufacturers worldwide. Don Davidge,
Tegic's vice president for marketing, said he believed that T9
would become one of the features cellular phone customers would ask
for when shopping for a phone.
</P>
<P>
   _KATIE HAFNER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Handheld Device That Packs More Features on One Screen &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Following Palm Computing's phenomenal success in popularizing
handheld devices, a small company is trying to attract one of the
few consumer groups that hasn't yet joined the cult.
</P>
<P>
   The FUGA eDiary is intended for those who might feel intimidated
by a Palm Pilot or Windows CE device. The eDiary's key feature is
its sleek user interface, which integrates different applications
for addresses, tasks, appointments and expenses into a single
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone else does different programs for &QL;
</P>
<P>
   different purposes _ they don't mix and match,'' said FUGA's
president, Jay Goyal.
</P>
<P>
   The eDiary labels different types of items with tags. The
standard ones are appointments and to-do and expense lists, but
additional ones can be created. Numerical items, like expenses and
mileage, can be tallied by date or by category. The to-do list
comes with boxes to be checked off, and unfinished items
automatically roll over to the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The FUGA eDiary is available on the FUGA Web site at www.fuga &QL; 
.com or by phone at (877) FUGA-CORP, for $149.95. FUGA will soon
begin shipping the eDiary to stores.
</P>
<P>
   _SARA ROBINSON
</P>
</TEXT>
