<HEADLINE>
ADVENTURE TURNS TO BOREDOM WHEN KID HAS TONSILS TAKEN OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday June 24)  
(rk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting your tonsils out may be a childhood rite of passage, but
it's not much fun.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the chocolate pudding, popsicles and mashed potato diet.
</P>
<P>
   Despite getting to watch all the TV, play all the Nintendo and
read all the comics you want.
</P>
<P>
   Despite mom, dad and an assortment of baby sitters at your beck
and call.
</P>
<P>
   My 8-year-old son, in fact, is going just a wee bit STIR CRAZY
after a week of ``no outside play, no exertion and no scratchy
foods.'' And there's still another week to go.
</P>
<P>
   We waited until school was out for the surgery, which was
performed, reassuringly enough, by Dr. Good, a cheerful ear, nose
and throat specialist who wore colorful cartoon ties.
</P>
<P>
   The day before surgery, we got the pre-op instructions: no food
past midnight, nothing to drink past 6 a.m. I woke Adam just before
dawn to give him a large glass of Gatorade.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving our 2-year-old with her grandparents, we headed
for the hospital, videos, extra clothes and a 3-foot-long stuffed
monitor lizard in tow.
</P>
<P>
   One stuffed animal was allowed to accompany Adam into surgery.
The lizard was a good choice: not a ``baby toy'' like his teddy
bear, but a ferocious looking guard to stand watch.
</P>
<P>
   Adam, clad in just a cotton gown and tube socks, seemed more
excited than scared, especially after they gave him his ``silly
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   But the night before, as I sat beside him on his bed, he had let
the first sign of anxiety slip out. ``You know what they do at a
hospital when a kid dies?'' he said. ``They gather all the moms
together in an auditorium and read the name on the hospital
bracelet out loud.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled up at me, knowing that this isn't what happens at all,
and that he would be just fine, but needing to hear me say it all
the same.
</P>
<P>
   As Jim and I sat in our little post-op cubicle, though, waiting
for our son to be wheeled back in, I half expected the crackling
voice on the speaker to say, ``Would all moms please report to the
auditorium for a tragic announcement?''
</P>
<P>
   In just under an hour, our son's gurney was being wheeled back
down the hall, lizard-tail first.
</P>
<P>
   When he surfaced from the anesthesia a few minutes later,
coughing and sputtering, Adam wasn't happy. The doctors and nurses
had warned us about this first, rough period, where it starts to
dawn on kids that this isn't a big adventure but something that
hurts pretty bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``My throat feels horrible,'' he moaned, tossing on the bed and
tangling his IV line.
</P>
<P>
   The next hour was a blur of pain meds, slushies, Sprite, crying
and a few excruciating minutes of throwing up.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he calmed down enough to watch one of the videos on the
TV above the bed. After dozing on and off, and keeping some fluids
down, he was cleared to go home about six hours after we had
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a week later, the hardest part for Adam is driving by the
neighborhood pool and seeing all his friends jumping in while he
sits with a book in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   He's waiting impatiently, two tonsils lighter, for the green
light.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
