<HEADER>
A7960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLOOMSDAY-NYT &LR;      06-16 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOMSDAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BLOOMSDAY, IRISH REJOICE IN `RE-JOYCING'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Today is Bloomsday, so thousands stalked the spirit of
Leopold Bloom, the newspaper advertising salesman, the hungry
relisher of innards of beasts and fowls, the cuckold, and the
Jewish outsider who is the hero of James Joyce's enormous novel,
``Ulysses.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the people who imitated Bloom by eating Gorgonzola cheese
sandwiches at Davey Byrne's pub and bought bars of lemon soap at
Sweny's chemist shop, and climbed to the parapet of the stone tower
where the novel opens, was David Norris.
</P>
<P>
   Norris, like Bloom, is himself something of an outsider to the
culture of this overwhelmingly Roman Catholic country. Norris, 55,
is a Church of Ireland Protestant, a homosexual, a senator in the
national legislature, where he has championed gay rights for 12
years. He is also Ireland's most prominent Joycean, giving dozens
of lectures and theatrical readings annually here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Joyce chose to make his hero a Jew because that also
made him an outsider in Irish society, Norris said in an interview
that ``Bloom was an outsider, but he was an insider to readers
because his mind flows in the same way as ours do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an outsider,'' he added, ``but I'm also an insider
because now people appreciate that I have so many things in common
with them. I have a sense of humor. I perform. I make people
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that ``Ulysses'' puzzles and intimidates many
readers and that most people in Ireland have not read the novel,
which was published in 1922. They know that it was once banned as
pornographic, and that it is a very difficult read. He said such
daunted would-be readers could overcome the kind of guilt Joyce
described in ``Ulysses'' as ``agenbite of inwit: remorse of
conscience,'' and begin to understand and enjoy the book.
</P>
<P>
   The trick to taming ``Ulysses,'' Norris said, is to skip the
many difficult or impenetrable passages, and keep reading the
narrative sections that are full of psychological drama, hopes,
fears, puns and jokes. It also helps, he said, to read the book
aloud, as poetry. That would be, in Joycean wordplay, to rejoice in
re-joycing.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom's relevance to contemporary Ireland, Norris said, is
simple: love, not hatred. In the novel, baited by a jingoist Irish
Republican in a pub, Bloom says, ``That's not life for men and
women, insult and hatred,'' ``it's the very opposite,'' ``Love says
Bloom. I mean the opposite of hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, Norris said, Bloom's words applied to the sectarian
violence in Northern Ireland today. ``Instead of bloodshed,''
Norris said, ``get on with lives of ordinary decency and
tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Today is Bloomsday because June 16 was the day in 1904 on which
the events in the novel take place. This afternoon at Sweny's
pharmacy on Lincoln Place, cakes of lemon soap, which had cost
Bloom fourpence in that shop in 1904, were selling quickly for
about $1.80. At Davey Byrne's pub on Duke Street, gorgonzola
sandwiches and a glass of Burgundy sold for about $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two fellas in from the country,'' said the bartender,
Thomas B. McDonagh. ``Terrible country accents. One of them read
from `Ulysses,' one from `Finnegans Wake.' Nobody knew what they
were talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   A relevant passage from a Joyce letter about ``Ulysses,'' Norris
said, might be, ``I've put in so many enigmas and puzzles that it
will keep the professors busy for centuries arguing over what I
mean, and that's the only way of insuring one's immortality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
