<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIRLS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-16 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GIRLS' GUIDE TO HUNTING AND FISHING:' SHE LIVES TO TELL ABOUT
GROWING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the title story of Melissa Bank's charming, funny collection
of seven linked fictions, ``The Girls' Guide to Hunting and
Fishing,'' Jane Rosenal, the protagonist, has grown a little
desperate to find a permanent mate. On a shopping trip to
Loehmann's to buy a dress for a wedding Jane is to attend, a friend
mentions ``a terrible book'' she has been reading called ``How to
Meet and Marry Mr. Right,'' a ``guide to manipulation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I've been trying to catch a fish by swimming around
with them,'' the friend explains. ``I keep making myself get in the
water again. I try different rivers. I change my strokes. But
nothing works. Then I find this guide that tells me about fishing
poles and bait, and how to cast and what to do when the line gets
taut. . . . The depressing part is that you  &UR; know &LR;  it'll work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate fish,'' Jane says.
</P>
<P>
   But at the wedding she meets and falls for Robert, who seems to
like her too. While nervously waiting for his call, she buys the
guide, reads it and applies its lessons. For a while they seem to
work, but then Robert begins to lose interest. When she throws the
book away and confronts him, he reveals that he loved her until she
began playing games. The guide has backfired. (I'm not giving too
much away here; the pleasure is in the details.)
</P>
<P>
   The story is a little O. Henryish perhaps, but it makes the
effective point that manipulation is only for the manipulative.
Besides, Jane is finally ready for love. As the title indicates,
Ms. Bank's entire book is a ``Girls' Guide to Hunting and
Fishing,'' and Jane has learned its lessons well.
</P>
<P>
   In the first story, ``Advanced Beginners,'' she is the
14-year-old younger sister of 20-year-old Henry, whose affair with
28-year-old Julia she deeply identifies with. When things don't
work out because Henry has trouble negotiating his way in Julia's
ultra-WASP world, Jane reports: ``It scared me to think that my
brother had failed at loving someone. I had no idea myself how to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Floating House,'' she is older and has a boyfriend,
Jamie. But when they visit St. Croix as the guests of Jamie's
ex-girlfriend, Bella, and her new husband, Yves, she discovers,
among other things, that marriage doesn't necessarily define the
boundaries of sex. When Jamie eventually apologizes for flirting
with Bella, Jane reports that ``it scares me how fast I go from
disliking to loving him, and I wonder if it's this way for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   In two longer stories, ``My Old Man'' and ``The Worst Thing a
Suburban Girl Could Imagine,'' Jane recounts her long and complex
affair with an older man, Archie Knox, who, her great aunt, a
novelist, tells her, is ``more famous than an editor should be.''
Here Ms. Bank's witty tones turn more somber, as Jane loses her
father to leukemia, her job as a book editor to her unwillingness
to judge other people's writing and finally Archie himself because
of their inability to talk to each other.
</P>
<P>
   But she has grown up enough by now that in ``You Could Be
Anyone,'' when the perfect hunk stays with her through breast
cancer and proposes marriage to her by passing her the engagement
ring she knows he has bought and saying, ``I think I can do it
now,'' she sees herself ``through his eyes, as the Generic Woman,
the skirted symbol on the ladies' room door'' and says goodbye to
him. She is ready to meet Robert.
</P>
<P>
   She is also ready for something else.
</P>
<P>
   Jane's problem is that she is funny: ``funny is the best thing I
am,'' she says. ``Don't be funny!'' say the authors of ``How to
Meet and Marry Right.'' ``Funny is the opposite of sexy.'' ``Humor
isn't feminine.'' But even as a child Jane was always cracking wise
and feeling bad about it. Describing her brother and Julia, she
reports: ``They didn't kiss or hold hands in front of me, though
once, at lunch, Henry sort of rubbed my foot under the table,
thinking it was Julia's. I leaned over to him and whispered,
`You're really turning me on.' I was a teen-ager, after all, an
expert in the art of mortification.''
</P>
<P>
   This habit of hers only grows wittier. When she tells Archie
that she has lost her editing job and he snaps his fingers and says
she must come to work for him at his publishing house, she retorts,
``I could bring you up on charges for that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Work harassment in the sexual place.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all the considerable humor of these stories turns on
Jane's wonderfully clear sense of the trickiness of language. (Of
Jamie's ex-girlfriend she reports, ``Her vowels and consonants are
all off _ trying to understand her is like picking fish out of the
clover and goats out of the ocean.'')
</P>
<P>
   And after Jane's father dies and her editing job begins to fail
her, it is language that helps her to survive and grow. She
explains: ``There's a passageway connecting Port Authority to Times
Square _ the Eighth Avenue subways to the Seventh _ and one morning
when I looked up I saw a poem in the eaves, sequential like the
Burma Shave billboards: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Overslept,
</P>
<P>
   so tired.
</P>
<P>
   If late,
</P>
<P>
   get fired.
</P>
<P>
   Why the worry?
</P>
<P>
   Why the pain?
</P>
<P>
   Go back home.
</P>
<P>
   Do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something changed then. I saw my life in scale: it was just my
life. It was not momentous, and only now did I recognize that it
had once seemed so to me; that was while my father was watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw myself the way I'd seen the cleaning women in the
building across the street. I was just one person in one window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was watching, except me.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon she will quit her editing job and go to work in
advertising. Figuratively speaking, she will write her own book,
``The Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing,'' in which she will
teach amusing lessons in how to stalk and find . . . yourself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE GIRLS' GUIDE TO HUNTING AND FISHING'
</P>
<P>
   By Melissa Bank
</P>
<P>
   274 pages. Viking. $23.95.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
