<SLUG> BC-ICE-CREAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL IDEAS WITH ICE CREAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Cool off your summer with ice cream, sherbet, sorbet,
ices, granita, frozen yogurt or gelato. With so many new choices,
you could have a different frozen treat every day this summer
without repeating.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 261 packaged ice cream and related products
and 98 frozen novelties were introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of light, reduced- and low-fat products declined slightly
in recent years. To confirm the trend toward indulgence, premium
and superpremium ice creams are outselling regular and economy
brands. Another trend is co-branding. New ice cream products are
increasingly using ingredients from well-known candy, cookie, fruit
and flavoring manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest growing flavors in 1998 were caramel, liquor
flavors, peach and coffee/mocha. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The top flavors of ice cream (based on supermarket sales) are
vanilla (29.2 percent), nut (10.7 percent), chocolate (9.8
percent), fruit (8.8 percent), Neapolitan (8.1 percent) and candy
mix-in (5 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Puzzled about what the labels on ice cream really mean? Here are
some label terms you'll see in the supermarket. (Note: In the
following list, overrun refers to the amount of aeration the ice
cream undergoes during manufacture, which keeps it from becoming an
inedible frozen mass.)
</P>
<P>
   -- Ice cream: A frozen food made from a mixture of dairy
products; contains at least 10 percent milk fat.
</P>
<P>
   -- Light ice cream: Contains at least 50 percent less total fat
or 33 percent fewer calories than the referenced product (the
average of leading regional or national brands).
</P>
<P>
   -- Reduced-fat ice cream: Contains at least 25 percent less
total fat than the referenced product (either the average of
leading brands or the company's own brand).
</P>
<P>
   -- Low-fat ice cream: Contains a maximum of 3 grams total fat
per {-cup serving.
</P>
<P>
   -- Superpremium ice cream: Tends to have very low overrun,
higher fat content and uses the best quality ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   -- Premium ice cream: Tends to have low overrun, higher fat
content than regular ice cream and uses higher quality ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   -- Regular ice cream: Meets the overrun required for the ice
cream standard.
</P>
<P>
   -- Economy ice cream: Meets the required overrun and generally
sells for a lower price than regular ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sherbet: Generally an ice in which milk replaces some of the
juice, water or cream. Unflavored gelatin frequently is added to
improve texture. Sorbet is the French word for sherbet; sorbetto,
the Italian word.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sorbets: Light, refreshing ices made with fruit juice and/or
pured fruit but no milk, cream or eggs. Best eaten immediately
after they are frozen. Sorbetti are classic Italian ices. They are
generally made with more fruit juice and less water and remain soft
even after freezing.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ices: Made of pured fruits and/or juices and resemble
sorbets. They must be stirred while freezing or processed in a food
processor for proper texture.
</P>
<P>
   When ice cream is exposed to a temperature of about 10 degrees
Fahrenheit, it may experience changes in body, texture and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some storing and handling tips to keep it in prime
condition.
</P>
<P>
   -- Make the ice cream aisle your last stop in the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   -- Watch the temperature of the grocery freezer case. It should
be no warmer than minus 20 degrees. Kept at the proper temperature,
ice cream will be thoroughly frozen and feel hard to the touch. If
the product is soft, you may wish to alert the manager.
</P>
<P>
   -- In an open-top freezer case, always select ice cream and
frozen treats stored below the freezer line.
</P>
<P>
   -- Put ice cream products in the separate basket of your grocery
cart or on top of other groceries.
</P>
<P>
   -- Insulate ice cream for the ride home. When groceries are
packed, ask for a freezer bag or extra brown paper bag to insulate
ice cream. Or take a cooler with you to the store and pack ice
cream in that.
</P>
<P>
   -- Make the grocery store or ice cream parlor your last stop
before going home. Don't let ice cream sit in a warm car while you
make other stops.
</P>
<P>
   -- Never allow ice cream to repeatedly soften and refreeze at
home because ice crystals can turn into large, unpalatable lumps.
</P>
<P>
   -- Store ice cream between minus 5 degrees and 0 degrees. It
will be firm enough to hold its shape, but easy to dip between 6
and 10 degrees, the ideal serving temperature range.
</P>
<P>
   -- Store ice cream in the main part of the freezer, not in the
door.
</P>
<P>
   -- Keep lid tightly closed when storing ice cream in the
freezer.
</P>
<P>
   -- Store ice cream away from uncovered foods in the freezer to
prevent odor absorption.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
