<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICECREAM-RECIPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE CREAM RECIPES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strawberry Cheesecake Ice Cream
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files. The ice cream won first place in the Texas
Ice Cream Crank-Off in Austin in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar &QL; 
\ teaspoon salt &QL; 
2 cups milk, plus more as needed &QL; 
4 eggs &QL; 
3 cups quartered strawberries, divided &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup brown sugar &QL; 
1 (8-ounce) package cream cheese, at room temperature &QL; 
3 to 4 cups half-and-half &QL; 
1 tablespoon each: fresh lemon juice and vanilla extract &QL; 
}cup finely chopped pecans (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, salt and 2 cups milk in food processor or
electric blender container; blend until sugar is dissolved. Add
eggs; blend until well mixed. Pour into a medium-size saucepan and
cook over medium heat, stirring constantly, until mixture begins to
thicken, about 10 minutes. Refrigerate milk-egg mixture at least 4
hours or as long as overnight. Place strawberries in a large bowl
and add brown sugar; stir well to dissolve sugar, then set aside.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to freeze, combine half the base mixture with cream
cheese in a food processor; process until smooth. Pour into chilled
freezer container. Combine remaining base mixture, half the
strawberries, half-and-half, lemon juice and vanilla in a food
processor; process until smooth. Pour into freezer container. Add
remaining strawberries and pecans to freezer container.
</P>
<P>
   Add milk as needed to fill container two-thirds full. Freeze
according to ice cream maker's directions. Let ripen at least 1
hour to develop flavor. Makes 1 gallon.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cinnamon Ice Cream Philadelphia Style
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Ultimate Ice Cream Book'' by Bruce Weinstein (to be
published July 5 by William Morrow; $15).
</P>
<P>
   3 cups light cream &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup sugar &QL; 
\ teaspoon vanilla extract &QL; 
1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Heat cream in large, heavy saucepan over medium heat until small
bubbles appear around edge. Do not let cream boil. Remove from
heat, add sugar and stir until it is completely dissolved. Whisk in
vanilla and cinnamon. Cool to room temperature. Cover and
refrigerate until cold or overnight. The cinnamon will rise to the
top, but don't worry; it will incorporate into the ice cream during
freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Stir the chilled custard, then freeze in 1 or 2 batches in ice
cream machine according to manufacturer's instructions. When
finished, ice cream will be soft but ready to eat. For firmer ice
cream, transfer to a freezer container and freeze at least 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   --Tea Granita
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Ultimate Ice Cream Book.'' You can use any tea,
including herbal blends, for this granita. The amount of sugar can
be increased or decreased as much as cup, depending on your taste.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups water &QL; 
6 teas bags &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup sugar &QL; 
Juice of { lemon (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Bring water to a boil, remove from heat and add tea bags. Let
tea steep 5 minutes. Remove tea bags and add sugar, stirring until
it completely dissolves. Refrigerate until cold. Add lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   Freeze in ice cream machine according to manufacturer's
directions. When finished, granita will be soft and have
consistency of a sorbet. Transfer to freezer container and freeze
to harden. To serve, scrape top of granita with a heavy ice cream
spade or scoop to create shaved ice crystals. Serve in small
chilled dishes or hollowed-out lemon rinds.
</P>
<P>
   --Easy Frozen Yogurt
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   2 (8-ounce) cartons vanilla or lemon yogurt &QL; 
\ cup light corn syrup &QL; 
2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   Combine yogurt, corn syrup and sugar in medium bowl. Pour into
9-by-5-by-3-inch loaf pan. Cover with aluminum foil. Freeze until
firm. Turn into blender container; blend at medium speed 1 minute
or until liquefied. Return to loaf pan. Cover and freeze until
firm. Let stand at room temperature 10 minutes before serving.
Makes about 1 pint.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: For Mocha Frozen Yogurt, follow basic recipe.
Substitute 2 (8-ounce) cartons coffee yogurt for vanilla. Add 1
tablespoon unsweetened cocoa powder. If coffee yogurt is not
available, substitute vanilla yogurt and 2 teaspoons instant coffee
granules.
</P>
<P>
   --Plum Sorbet
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   3 cups each: water and sugar &QL; 
3 pounds ripe, juicy plums, halved and pitted &QL; 
Plum brandy or fresh lemon juice (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Combine water and sugar in saucepan. Stir until sugar dissolves.
Boil until syrup spins a thread when dropped into cold water (230
to 234 degrees on a candy thermometer).
</P>
<P>
   Puree plums in blender and strain, or peel fruit and put through
food mill. Combine fruit pulp with sugar syrup (there should be 4
cups). Pour into ice cube trays and freeze 30 to 40 minutes. At
serving time, pour into stemmed glasses and top with a dash of plum
brandy or lemon juice. Makes 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If mixture becomes too solid (or if you wish to store it)
before serving, return to blender or beat a few minutes until
sorbet is thick and foamy. Should it become too liquid, return to
the freezer a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   --Peach Champagne Ice
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon unflavored gelatin &QL; 
\ cup water &QL; 
3 pounds fresh peaches, quartered (6 large) &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice &QL; 
2 cups champagne
</P>
<P>
   Soften gelatin in water in saucepan. Stir over low heat until
gelatin is dissolved. Combine peaches, sugar and lemon juice in
large bowl; mix well to combine. Place half the mixture into
blender; blend until smooth. Repeat with remaining half of peach
mixture. Combine gelatin mixture, champagne and all of peach
mixture. Turn into metal pan; freeze until mushy, overnight if
necessary. Remove from freezer; beat smooth. Refreeze until firm.
Makes about 2 quarts.
</P>
<P>
   -- Marshmallow Sauce
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Ultimate Ice Cream Book.'' The sauce is good hot or
cold. It reheats well in the microwave or in a small bowl set over
a pan of simmering water.
</P>
<P>
   2 large egg whites &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
{ cup water &QL; 
16 regular marshmallows &QL; 
{ teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Beat egg whites in mixing bowl until soft peaks form. Set aside.
Combine sugar and water in medium saucepan and place over medium
heat. Stir until sugar dissolves, then let mixture boil 3 minutes.
Reduce heat to low, add marshmallows and stir until they are
completely melted and the mixture is smooth. Remove from heat and
slowly beat hot marshmallow mixture into egg whites. Continue
beating 2 minutes. Beat in vanilla. Serve hot or cold. Makes about
3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   --Nectarine-Pineapple Sundae Sauce
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups fresh nectarines &QL; 
1 (12-ounce) jar pineapple sundae topping &QL; 
Remove peel and cut nectarines into thin slices to measure 1{ cups.
If desired, coarsely crush 1 cup, leaving remainder of fruit in
thin slices. Combine with sundae topping. Cover and refrigerate
until ready to use. Makes about 2{ cups.
</P>
