<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-MBEKI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MBEKI SEATED AS SOUTH AFRICAN PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA _ With cannon blasts and the soaring voices of
children, South Africa inaugurated Thabo Mbeki as its second black
president Wednesday, ushering in a new era and bidding farewell to
a generation that battled racial oppression to emancipate the
masses.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the oath of office in five of South Africa's 11
official languages, Mbeki paid tribute to the elders of the
antiapartheid movement, including outgoing President Nelson
Mandela, Oliver Tambo, Walter Sisulu, and his own father, Govan
Mbeki. Then, acknowledging that the burden falls to his generation
to make good on the promises of liberation, he vowed to tackle the
country's pervasive social problems: soaring unemployment, abject
poverty, violent crime, and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our days and our nights will remain forever blemished as long
as our people are torn apart and fractured into contending factions
by reason of the racial and gender inequalities, which continue to
characterize our society,'' he said. ``The full meaning of
liberation will not be realized until our people are freed both
from oppression and from the dehumanizing legacy of deprivation we
inherited from our past.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 4,000 guests and dignitaries nestled in the sandstone
amphitheater of Pretoria's Union Buildings, and at least 50,000
South Africans gathered at the bottom of the capital's terraced
gardens to watch the ceremony on huge video screens.
</P>
<P>
   Great cheers rang out at the arrivals of two unlikely heroes:
Libya's Muammar Khadafy, who was making his first trip abroad since
the lifting of UN sanctions, and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mbeki, who spent most of his adult life in exile, has
been carefully groomed over the past five years as Mandela's
deputy, the proceedings marked a rare moment in Africa when a
sitting president willingly and peacefully yielded power to a
democratically elected successor.
</P>
<P>
   Punctuated by low-altitude military fly-overs, the event
underscored the extent to which South Africa has changed and
emerged since the end of white rule five years ago. The nation's
top generals, on hand to demonstrate their loyalty to civilian
rule, are now black. Some 30 African leaders, whose countries
warred against the apartheid state, swelled the visitors' ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's inauguration took place on the 23rd anniversary of the
youth uprisings in Soweto, when security police opened fire on
protesting students in the sprawling townships south of
Johannesburg. Nine children were killed that day, and hundreds of
lives were lost in ensuing protests.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the crowds gathered at a People's Concert below the
Union Buildings afterwards, Mbeki said, ``It is right and proper
that this ceremony should have taken place on June 16 because
without the struggle and sacrifices of our youth it is possible
that we would not be standing here today.''
</P>
<P>
   In a last and emotional symbolic gesture as president, Mandela
laid a wreath at Hector Peterson Square, the memorial to the slain
students, before arriving in Pretoria. Mandela, whose 27 years in
prison epitomized the sacrifices of his generation, now hopes to
retire into private life surrounded by his many grandchildren. He
made no farewell remarks Wednesday, and is expected to depart
Thursday with his wife, Graca Machel, for a holiday at an
undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
   If Mandela's exit from the nation's public stage drew sighs of
nostalgia, those gathered to witness the transition hinted that
Mbeki's honeymoon will be short. The ruling African National
Congress won a resounding victory in the June 2 elections, securing
virtually uncontestable majorities in parliament and seven of the
nine provinces. Having returned the ANC to power, the masses now
want faster change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about Mandela's presidency was that he never
showed animosity,'' said Helmsley Thakela, one of thousands
gathered for the postinaugural concert. ``Now we must see Thabo
Mbeki achieve. When he says he will eradicate poverty, I trust he
will be able to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking to Mbeki,'' said David Mafifi, 24, who is
unemployed. ``He must create jobs and stimulate investment. Nobody
is working.'' South Africa's jobless rate hovers near 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki is expected to announce his Cabinet Thursday, including
the appointment of Zulu leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi as deputy
president. There was speculation that he would also hold talks with
visiting African leaders to reach an end to the 10-month multistate
war in Congo, but spokesman Ronnie Mamoepa said no meeting had been
scheduled.
</P>
</TEXT>
