<HEADLINE>
ALSATIAN CLIMATE WORKS WONDERS ON GRAPES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) They're not that tall, but they sure are effective.
</P>
<P>
   The Vosges Mountains in northeastern France run north-south, and
the region of Alsace is on the eastern side, between the mountains
and the Rhine River. The prevailing, sometimes rain-laden winds
often blow west to east, but the mountains block much of the rain.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Alsace is one of the driest regions in France.
</P>
<P>
   Alsace, of course, is that thin strip of real estate fought over
and claimed many times by both France and Germany. The architecture
in the quaint villages is noticeably German, as are many of the
village names (such as Kaysersberg and Riquevihr), but the cuisine
is definitely French _ albeit often with a German twist.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, it was in Alsace that the sculptor who designed
the Statue of Liberty, Auguste Bartholdi, was born. And also Albert
Schweitzer. America's most decorated hero of World War II, Texas'
own Audie Murphy, won the Medal of Honor for heroism in a battle
near the Alsatian town of Colmar.
</P>
<P>
   Alsace's dry climate makes for wines that are less sweet than
those of their German cousins, which are more often ``off-dry'' to
downright sweet. Alsatian wines are dry. The common saying in
Alsace is that it's on the ``dry side of the Rhine.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless an Alsatian wine says Vendange Tardive or Selection des
Grains Nobles (these are late-harvest, naturally sweet wines), the
wines will be bracingly dry and acidic, yet with fine-tuned, often
piercing fruit flavors.
</P>
<P>
   And they go wonderfully with food. That may account for the fact
that Alsace has more Michelin three-star restaurants than any other
region in France. Alsace is both an oenophile's and a gastronome's
paradise.
</P>
<P>
   The company of Alsace Willm dates to 1896. In the early 1930s,
Willm (pronounced Vilm) was the first Alsatian producer to export
to the United States. Willm makes a string of wines, from pinot
blanc to gewrztraminer to a lightly sparkling wine called crmant.
The wines are not as showy as some nor as heavy-handed as others,
and they offer good value.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what's available:
</P>
<P>
   Alsace Willm Crmant d'Alsace _ 41/2 stars_ a blend of pinot
blanc and a dollop of chardonnay, this lightly sparkling wine has a
creamy quality and is an excellent aperitif. At $11.99-$12.59, it
is quite a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Another bargain is the 1998 Alsace Willm Pinot Blanc _ 4 stars
be great with baked fish or chicken. A steal at $7.99-$8.99.
</P>
<P>
   There are few producers of an Alsatian white-wine blend called
Gentil, the best-known being Hugel. One reason so few do it may be
that by blending such distinctive flavors as riesling, pinot blanc,
pinot gris, sylvaner and muscat, you end up with a nondistinctive
wine. That's the case with the 1997 Alsace Willm Gentil _ 3 stars _
a thoroughly pleasant wine but one without any (literally)
outstanding characteristics. The price is right, though:
$6.99-$7.99.
</P>
<P>
   There's an attractive touch of butterscotch in the 1998 Alsace
Willm Pinot Gris _ 4 stars _ and the creamy aftertaste is nice,
too. About $8.99-$9.99.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the 1998 Alsace Willm Gewrztraminer _ 4 stars _ has
just the right ``weight,'' neither too wimpy (like many New World
versions), nor ponderous (like several other neighbors' versions,
e.g. Pierre Sparr). It does have a good dose of that spicy, Gewrz
character. About $11.99.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line on Alsace Willm: good wines that may be underpriced.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Because of a fickle climate, widely varying soils and, frankly,
inconsistent winemaking, making sense of Burgundies requires the
concentration of walking through a minefield. Consistency is hard
to find.
</P>
<P>
   There is only a handful of large producers that you can count on
to produce stylistically consistent wines. These are such
well-known firms as Louis Latour and Louis Jadot.
</P>
<P>
   And Joseph Drouhin.
</P>
<P>
   I tasted a skein of 1998 Drouhin white Burgundies and 1997
Drouhin red Burgundies recently, and although the individual wines
did their individual thing, it was the overall picture that was
most important at the moment. Because of Drouhin's consistency, it
was easy to get a picture of the vintages, and vintages are very
important in Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   The firm of Joseph Drouhin dates to 1880, and today is a leading
producer, making wines from around 80 appellations. The line is
best-known for three white wines: Beaune Clos de Mouches and
Chassage-Montrachet and Le Montrachet from the Marquis de Laguiche.
The reds don't get the press the whites do, perhaps unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   After tasting the 1998 Drouhin white Burgundies, here are some
impressions:
</P>
<P>
   The '98 whites were uneven. Some, such as the underrated
Montagny, showed very well. So did the underpriced Rully, always a
good value in white Burgundy. Others, such as the Meursault and
Puligny-Montrachet, seemed shy. Perhaps all they need is a little
bottle age. The Chassagne-Montrachet, with its lime-citrus quality,
was very attractive, while its more celebrated sibling, the
Chassagne-Montrachet Marquis de Laguiche, was not as forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, not available for tasting was the white Beaune Clos de
Mouches.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line on the whites: Choose carefully. The more expensive
wines will need cellaring.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 reds were fairly simple and straightforward, showing
some suppleness and _ most important _ they're already easy to
drink. Especially when compared with the more substantial,
longer-aging '96s.
</P>
<P>
   Among the less expensive '97 Drouhin red Burgundies, the Cote de
Beaune and the Cotes de Beaune Villages were drinking quite well,
with good smoky plum flavors. The Santenay, usually a personal
favorite, was OK but lacked charm.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a fan of Pommard, but the '97 Drouhin was most
attractive, although it may need a year or two to flesh out. The
red Beaune Clos de Mouches doesn't have the reputation of the white
version, and the '97 was no exception. I liked the pieces _ the
bouquet, the Bing cherry-bacon nuances _ but right now it's a bit
disjointed. Maybe in a couple of years ...
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever seen the descriptor ``cinnamon'' used for a red
Burgundy, take a whiff of the '97 Drouhin Chambolle-Musigny. Now
that's cinnamon. Supple and easy to drink, this is one nice wine
for the short term.
</P>
<P>
   The Gevrey-Chambertin, though, lacked sex appeal, always a major
component of red Burgundy. Give it a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   And the Clos de Vougeot had a nice spicy quality, but it's a
fairly big wine that needs to stretch its legs for a couple more
years.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line on the '97 Drouhin red Burgundies: Many are
drinking well already, making them good candidates for restaurant
wine lists while the harder, bigger '96s mature.
</P>
<P>
   All the '97 Drouhin red Burgundies and '98 white Burgundies will
arrive here in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
