A8001 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACID-RAIN-HNS &LR;      06-16 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACID-RAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS PUSH FOR LEGISLATION TO REDUCE ACID RAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New York lawmakers urged Congress Wednesday to pass
legislation aimed at reducing acid rain, saying it remains a threat
to trees and lakes throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very thing that forests and rivers need to survive _ rain
_ is killing them,'' Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said at a news
conference in front of the U.S. Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., introduced a
bill that would cut the airborne pollutants _ sulfur dioxide and
nitrogen dioxide _ that cause acid rain. However, he found little
support in Congress because some members said the problem affected
only the Northeast and others insisted the government had done
enough to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent federal report found that despite cuts in air
pollution, acid rain is a growing threat to forests and watersheds
in California, Colorado's Front Range, parts of the Southwest and
the southern Appalachians as well as remaining a serious problem in
the Adirondacks in northeastern New York.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued in April, has helped build support for
Moynihan's bill by showing the problem is more than a regional
issue.
</P>
<P>
   So far eight senators, including California Democrats Barbara
Boxer and Dianne Feinstein, have co-sponsored the acid rain bill.
In the House, a similar bill introduced by Rep. Sherwood Boehlert,
R-N.Y., has 39 co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the fact that Canada and Mexico as well as European
nations have been damaged by acid rain, Boehlert said at the news
conference that the problem is ``not simply an Adirondacks issue or
a Northeast issue or even a national issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John E. Sweeney, R-N.Y., called acid rain a ``cancer''
eating away at the country's forests and lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The federal report, which was produced by the National Acidic
Precipitation Assessment Program, a consortium of government
agencies, found that:
</P>
<P>
   _ The San Gabriel Mountains and San Bernardino Mountains in
southern California, the high-elevation forests in the Colorado
Front Range, the Allegheny Mountains in West Virginia and the Great
Smoky Mountains in Tennessee are saturated or close to saturated
with nitrogen.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Chesapeake Bay is suffering from excess nitrogen, some of
it air pollution, which is causing algae blooms that suffocate
other life forms.
</P>
<P>
   _ High-elevation lakes and streams in the Sierra Nevada, the
Cascade Range and the Rocky Mountains may be on the verge of
suffering chronically high acidity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many waterways in the Adirondacks are becoming more acidic
even as sulfur deposits decline. The report cites Environmental
Protection Agency projections that by 2040, about half the region's
2,800 lakes and ponds will be too acidic to sustain much life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The range of the problem is shocking,'' Moynihan said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   His bill would require industry, by 2005, to make an additional
50 percent cut in sulfur dioxide emissions and an extra 70 percent
cut in nitrogen dioxide emissions above those required under the
current clean air law.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the legislation, including utility companies, have
argued that existing laws are having an impact and just need more
time to work. The opponents have noted that industry is well ahead
of schedule in reducing its sulfur dioxide and nitrogen dioxide
emissions. In addition, the reductions have cost industry only a
fraction of what many experts had predicted when the current law
went into effect in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Acid rain occurs when sulfur or nitrogen, which drift eastward
on the prevailing winds, mix with moisture in the atmosphere to
form sulfuric or nitric acid and fall as rain, snow or fog. Dry
nitrogen and sulfur pollution also turn to acid when deposited in
waterways or mixed with moisture in the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Coal-burning power plants concentrated in the Ohio River Valley
are a major source of nitrogen and sulfur pollution.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
