<HEADER>
A8008 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALC-RECIPES-HNS &LR;      06-16 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALC-RECIPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECIPES FROM A LA CARTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
--Deep in the Heart of Texas Backyard Molasses Mopped Chicken
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Dean Fearing, executive corporate chef, the Mansion on
Turtle Creek in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   1 (3- to 4-pound) chicken &QL; 
1 tablespoon canola oil &QL; 
Salt, ground black pepper and dried thyme to taste &QL; 
Crushed red bell pepper flakes to taste &QL; 
3 cups unsulfured molasses
</P>
<P>
   Rinse chicken under cold running water. Remove giblets, pat dry
and cut into quarters. Brush with oil. Season on both sides with
salt, pepper, thyme and pepper flakes. Set aside. Clean grill and
make the fire with charcoal and a few hickory wood chips. Soak
remaining hickory chips in water for smoking. When charcoal burns
down to a white ash, arrange chicken quarters, skin side down, on
grill. Render as much grease from the skin as possible without
burning skin or causing grease flare-ups that burn the skin. Take
your time and watch carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Add water-soaked hickory chips, a small handful at a time, to
the edge of the fire to start the smoking process. Close top of
grill to seal in smoke. Watch chicken closely and turn after about
8 to 10 minutes when the skin has rendered its fat. If the smoke
dies down, add another handful of chips.
</P>
<P>
   Grill and smoke chicken about 15 minutes, making sure the meat
is cooking evenly on both sides. Then begin basting each piece of
chicken with molasses. Don't be afraid to put a heavy coating of
molasses on chicken. Keep turning each piece to prevent burning.
Remove barbecued chicken from grill to a platter when done. Serve
immediately. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   --Jeffrey's Oyster Nachos
</P>
<P>
   From chef David Garrido of Jeffrey's Restaurant and Bar in
Austin. This is one of the best oyster dishes the Food editor has
ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Canola oil for frying &QL; 
Buttermilk and flour for dredging &QL; 
16 fresh raw oysters &QL; 
16 Yuca Nacho Chips (recipe follows) &QL; 
{ cup each: Pico de Gallo and Habanero Mayo (recipes follow)
</P>
<P>
   In a small skillet, heat 1 inch of oil to 375 degrees. Place
buttermilk and flour in 2 shallow bowls. Soak oysters in
buttermilk, then dip into flour (oysters should be lightly coated).
Fry each oyster 45 seconds to 1 minute or until lightly browned.
Drain oysters on paper towels. To serve: Put a teaspoonful of Pico
de Gallo on each chip. Top with a fried oyster and { teaspoon
Habanero Mayo. Makes 16 nachos.
</P>
<P>
   --Yuca Nacho Chips
</P>
<P>
   2 yuca roots (cassava or manioc), peeled and thinly sliced &QL; 
{ cup vegetable oil &QL; 
Sea salt &QL; 
Soak yuca slices in hot water 15 minutes, then drain. Heat oil in a
skillet to 375 degrees; fry chips 1 minute or until light brown.
Drain on absorbent paper and dust with sea salt. Makes about 2
dozen.
</P>
<P>
   --Habanero Mayo
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons each: Dijon mustard and honey &QL; 
{ cup chopped cilantro leaves &QL; 
1 tablespoon minced habanero chili &QL; 
2 egg yolks (see note) &QL; 
1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice &QL; 
{ teaspoon sea salt &QL; 
{ cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   In a blender, mix mustard, honey, cilantro, habanero, egg yolks,
lemon juice and salt. Turn blender on. Remove the cap in blender
and with motor running, gradually pour a thin stream of oil onto
the yolk mixture until it thickens. Refrigerate. Makes 1{ cups.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Because this recipe calls for raw eggs, which can increase
the risk of salmonella poisoning, use pasteurized eggs or egg
substitute for yolks. Or use 1 cup bottled mayonnaise mixed with
mustard, honey, cilantro and habanero.
</P>
<P>
   -- Pico de Gallo
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced tomato &QL; 
{ cup diced onion &QL; 
1 serrano chili, minced &QL; 
\ cup chopped fresh cilantro leaves &QL; 
1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice &QL; 
Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Combine tomato, onion, serrano, cilantro, lemon juice and salt in a
bowl. Refrigerate 15 minutes to allow flavors to blend. Makes 1\
cups.
</P>
<P>
   --Jeffrey's Coffee Crme Brle
</P>
<P>
   Also from chef David Garrido of Jeffrey's Restaurant and Bar in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   1 quart whipping cream &QL; 
{ cup white sugar &QL; 
{ vanilla bean, split and scraped &QL; 
1 tablespoon espresso &QL; 
2 tablespoons Grand Marnier liqueur &QL; 
1{ tablespoons amaretto liqueur &QL; 
3 tablespoons Baileys Irish Cream liqueur &QL; 
2 eggs plus 7 egg yolks &QL; 
{ cup brown sugar &QL; 
Berries for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. In large saucepan over medium heat,
mix cream, white sugar and vanilla bean; cook 4 to 6 minutes or
until cream is medium hot and sugar is dissolved. Remove from heat.
Add espresso and liqueurs, whisking to incorporate thoroughly. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, whisk together eggs, yolks and brown sugar. First
``temper'' egg mixture by adding 1 cup cream mixture. Mix well and
whisk remaining cream mixture into egg mixture. Strain custard.
Pour custard into 8 (6-ounce) ramekins or souffl dishes. Place in
larger pan of water that comes up halfway to top of ramekins.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until custard is set but still a little loose in center, 30
to 40 minutes. Refrigerate until cool. Sprinkle 1 tablespoon brown
sugar over tops and flame with a propane torch until sugar is
caramelized. Or place ramekins on baking sheet and heat under
broiler until sugar is caramelized. Watch carefully. Garnish with
berries. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
