<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-A-LA-CARTE(2TAKES)-HN     06-16 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-A-LA-CARTE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL DESTINATIONS INCLUDE STOPS FOR MEMORABLE GRAZING 

</HEADLINE>
 (2 TAKES)-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editor's note: Zoe has umlauf over the e.) 
 
By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Notes from all over: Recent short trips to New York,
Dallas and Austin turned up some fun food experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch at Zoe in SoHo in New York City was one of the highlights
of a weekend there. Did you know SoHo means South of Houston Street
(or ``HOW-ston'' as they say in New York)?
</P>
<P>
   Zoe was recommended by a friend, Nancy Murray, over tea at
Takashimaya, the Japanese department store (a must-see for New York
visitors). Murray was fashion editor at the Chronicle in the
mid-1980s, when her byline was Nancy Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Zoe, at 90 Prince St., is a high-profile restaurant known for
good food and good times. Diners at a late lunch were enjoying
their food, reminiscent of the hot restaurants in Houston such as
Mark's, Backstreet Cafe, Rainbow Lodge or Daily Review.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Reilly, executive chef, turns out adventurous fare:
Charred Lamb Salad With Avocado, Mango, Peanuts and Spicy Harissa
Sauce; Rotisserie Long Island Duck Breast With Warm Blueberry and
Confit Salad, Hash Brown Potato Cake and Honey-Lavender Sauce; and
Jasmine Rice Crusted Soft Shell Crabs on a Warm Beet and Vidalia
Onion Salad With Lemon Brown Butter Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The lunch menu is equally creative, with such choices as Grilled
Tuna Club Sandwich on Semolina Bread With Applewood Smoked Bacon,
Tomato, Wasabi Mayonnaise and Miso-Carrot Salad (the salad cried
out for seconds); Salad of Seasonal Greens With Toasted Pumpkin
Seed-Verjus Dressing and Slow-Roasted Tomatoes; and House Smoked
Scottish Salmon with Crispy Taro Cakes and Rotisserie Pineapple.
</P>
<P>
   The food was so impressive we complimented the chef on the way
out and met the co-owner, Stephen Loffredo. He said the company
almost opened a restaurant in Houston. They were competing for the
space at the new Saks Fifth Avenue in Galleria, now home of Ruggles
Grille 5115. Loffredo said he and his wife, Thalia, are still
interested in the area and something may develop in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Zoe is the Greek word for life. The restaurant, located in a
copper-topped 19th-century landmark building, is named for Thalia's
grandmother. Diners can sit at the food bar looking into an
exhibition kitchen with wood-burning stove and rotisserie. It is
the source of rotisserie items that have guests standing in line to
see what Reilly will create next. If you go, save room for desserts
from pastry chef Jennifer McClintick. There's a weekend brunch. If
you are going to be in the city, call 212-966-6722 for
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers have already discovered the Loffredos' newest
restaurant, Cena, named for their daughter. It's in the Flatiron
neighborhood, 12 East 22nd St. Call 212-505-1222.
</P>
<P>
   Another New York neighborhood eatery that was a happy discovery
was Cafe Europa, 205 West 57th St., cater-cornered from Carnegie
Hall a block or so from Central Park. It's a great place for
late-night pastry (excellent strudel) and coffee, a sandwich after
shopping or Sunday morning breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   --On to Dallas
</P>
<P>
   If you ever doubted that there are umpteen thousand ways to cook
chicken, you should have been a guest at the National Chicken
Cooking Contest in Dallas recently. As a judge, I sampled chicken
for five straight hours, and still was able to enjoy it at every
official event hosted by the National Chicken Council.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity chef Dean Fearing of the Mansion on Turtle Creek (who
has had to forgo cowboy boots for sabots in the kitchen because of
a foot problem) personally grilled every piece of chicken for the
food editors' dinner at the hotel, he said. Fearing, a native of
Kentucky who helped pioneer Southwestern cuisine, had South in the
mouth this time around. You've never had greens like his mustard
greens mixed with a wonderful ham and cream sauce and corn bread
pan stuffing. Peach-jalapeo chutney was a zesty addition.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
