<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-A-LA-CARTE(2NDTAKE)-H     06-16 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-A-LA-CARTE(2ND </SLUG>
 TAKE)-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
(UNDATED): a zesty addition.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chilled Corn Vichyssoise With Grilled Lobster Relish started the
three-course dinner, and guests were scraping their soup bowls.
Dessert was a futuristic interpretation of coconut cream pie with
tropical fruit ambrosia.
</P>
<P>
   -- ... and Austin
</P>
<P>
   The day after the chicken cook-off, food editors moved on to
Austin. Lunch was set under a tent on the lawn at the Governor's
Mansion. Gov. and Mrs. George W. Bush were in Dallas for the
governor to give the commencement address at SMU). The mansion is
being extensively renovated, but we were able to tour it.
</P>
<P>
   The three-course lunch was prepared by one of Austin's finest,
David Garrido, chef at Jeffrey's Restaurant and Bar, who wowed
guests with the first course, Oyster Nachos (light, crisply fried
oysters on Yuca Nacho Chips with Habanero Mayo; recipe follows).
</P>
<P>
   Chicken was the entree, of course, but Garrido's preparation was
intriguing. Boneless chicken breasts were seared, then simmered in
red wine and seasonings, reheated in hot oil, drained and served
over sweet potatoes with mango salsa spiked with habanero. Garrido
does a similar beef dish at Jeffrey's, Top Sirloin on Yuca Root
Chips With Habanero, Chipotle and Papaya Pico.
</P>
<P>
   The dessert was a silky creme brulee richly flavored with
espresso coffee and lightly studded with pecans. Each course was
matched with wines from Fall Creek Vineyards. Ed and Susan Auler,
owners of the Tow, Texas, winery, commented on the wines _ Fall
Creek's 1998 Sauvignon Blanc (a perfect match for the oysters) and
Meritus 1996 with the chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Garrido is the son of a Mexican diplomat; he was born in Canada
but grew up in Mexico, Puerto Rico and Costa Rica and was schooled
in Switzerland. He brings an international approach to his cooking,
which also is expressed in his cookbook, ``Nuevo Tex-Mex''
(Chronicle Books, $19.95). He's working on a second cookbook
commemorating the 25th anniversary of Jeffrey's. The award-winning
restaurant is at 1204 W. Lynn in Austin. Call 512-477-5584.
</P>
<P>
   Two more outstanding meals awaited us, the first at Hudson's on
the Bend, 3509 Ranch Road 620 North, about an hour's drive from
Austin. The second was Sunday brunch at Fonda San Miguel.
</P>
<P>
   Award-winning chef Jeff Blank hosted the group at his showplace
home on Hudson Bend on Lake Travis, where he teaches cooking
classes. Designed by his son as his master's thesis in
architecture, the house is multilevel and fits right into the
setting. There's lots of natural cedar, indigenous plants and
fabulous vistas. The guest house walls are cedar, so the aroma
might remind inhabitants of sleeping in a cedar chest.
</P>
<P>
   Blank's wife, Shanny Lott, is an artist and did many of the
paintings in the house and the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Blank and the executive chef for the restaurant, Jay Moore, his
co-author, demonstrated several recipes from ``Cooking
Fearlessly,'' their cookbook to be published in September, in the
cooking school area. Food editors adjourned to the restaurant for
dinner. The menu was an eye-opener to many food editors from the
outland: Diamond Back Rattlesnake in a Pistachio Nut Crust over
Chipotle Sauce with Jicama and Cactus Salad dressed with Gingered
Lime Vinaigrette; Pecan Smoked Axis Backstrap Stuffed With Lobster
Standing in Ancho Bock Beer Smashed Potatoes painted with Mango
Jalapeo Sauce and criss-crossed with Peppercorn Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The next ``fearless'' course was Wild Boar and Chicken Nogales
with Maytag Blue Cheese Grits and tri-color Mexican Flag Sauces.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone whose appetite was waning was revitalized with dessert,
Chambord Mousse with Legs of Fudge a k a Tina Turner Mousse. Blank
said he honored the performer for her unforgettable voice and great
legs _ ``legs'' being the term for streams of wine that cling, then
slide down the inside of a glass when wine is swirled. ``In this
case, the legs are swirling chocolate, which makes a tempting
presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Signature gourmet sauces developed for the restaurant are sold
in some gourmet supermarkets: Hudson's on the Bend Mexican Marigold
Mint Mustard, Tomatillo White Chocolate Sauce (a startling take on
mole sauce with tomatillos, cilantro, sesame seeds and a bit of
Belgian white chocolate), Bourbon Vanilla Praline Sauce and Mango
Jalapeno Aeoli. The Orange Ginger BBQ Sauce or Chipotle BBQ Sauce
add culinary fireworks to barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   For cooking class schedules or to order sauces or gift crates
and a recipe brochure, call 800-996-7655.
</P>
<P>
   Just when we thought we couldn't stuff another morsel, it was
time for Sunday brunch at Fonda San Miguel. Four buffet tables were
piled high with specialties from this authentic Mexican restaurant
in Austin, which has the stamp of approval of Mexican cooking diva
Diana Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   One table held entrees including mole, shrimp dishes and
carnitas; the second one held salads and appetizers; the third,
side dishes; and the fourth, desserts. Conservative guests, who
started with just a bite of this and that, went back for seconds,
then thirds on Torta Elote (a glorification of corn pudding),
shrimp, Nopalitos Salad and desserts such as coconut gelatin,
almond squares and Mexican rice pudding.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who can't visit Austin without touring H.E.B.'s
Central Market (and when is Houston getting one?). Now there's a
choice of the original on Lamar or the new Central Market on the
corner of South Lamar and Ben White Boulevard in Westgate Mall.
Central Market is the second biggest tourist attraction in Austin
now after the State Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
