<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELGIUM-COKE-0617-COX     06-16 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELGIUM-COKE-0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COKE IMAGE AT RISK IN BELGIAN HEALTH SCARE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ With a familiar red ``Enjoy Coca-Cola'' sign glowing
above her head, Francine Craeghs paused Wednesday afternoon to
consider the refreshments chilling behind the glass of a cooler in
a small market.
</P>
<P>
   Inside were bottles and cans of Orangina, V-8, various fruit
juices and something called Winny Cola -- but not a drop of the
familiar caramel-colored soft drink.
</P>
<P>
   Craeghs settled for orange juice. ``You know I'm pregnant
anyway, so I must be more careful,'' she said with little remorse.
``And I can live without Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   Each day, more and more Europeans are learning to live without
Coke. Prompted by reports of about 100 cases of illnesses related
to drinking Coca-Cola products, the Belgian government on Monday
took the exceptional step of banning all beverages made by the
Atlanta-based soft-drink giant.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Coke story dominated the nation's newspapers,
each devoting multiple pages to the health scare -- including
hotline numbers, health tips and accounts of Coke's mythical
Atlanta origins.
</P>
<P>
   The story even overshadowed the crisis being managed by the
well-known Brussels concern, NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Across the capital, Coke vending machines were dark and
unresponsive. Empty sections on grocery store shelves marked where
Coke, Fanta, Sprite and other Coca-Cola products had been
displayed. At Quick restaurants, the French fast-food chain, signs
were posted informing customers that they must forgo Cokes with
their burgers and pome frits.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 8, more than 100 people -- most of them
schoolchildren -- have reported suffering headaches, nausea and
dizziness after drinking Coca-Cola products. On Monday, 38
schoolgirls were taken to a hospital in the town of Ghent after
drinking Coca-Cola bought from a vending machine.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the company announced that it had determined that
some of its soft drinks had become contaminated with a fungicide
and others had been infused with faulty carbon dioxide, but
stressed that there was no serious health threat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the company's attempts to allay concerns, however,
Belgium's lead was followed by the Netherlands and Luxembourg on
Tuesday and France on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Across Europe, governments from Poland to Spain reassured their
citizens that it was safe to drink Coca-Cola in their countries,
perhaps inadvertently suggesting to consumers questions about a
product heretofore regarded as the essence of wholesomeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a drop of oil, spreading across the top of the
water,'' said Meike Van den Berghe, the spokeswoman for Belgium's
Ministry of Health. ``When will it stop?''
</P>
<P>
   That's a good question given the rising anxiety in Europe about
the safety of food coupled with widespread loss of faith in public
officials assigned to assure the safety of such products.
</P>
<P>
   The Coke crisis follows the discovery in Belgium earlier this
year of cancer-causing dioxin in chickens and eggs. The dioxin
revelations so angered the public that the government was
overthrown Sunday in national elections.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, the media and government have for months been locked
in nasty debate over safety of genetically modified food, a fairly
common and noncontroversial part of American diets. Additionally,
fears over ``mad cow disease'' still ripple through European food
politics. Consumers across the continent and Britain strongly
support a European Union ban on hormone-treated beef imports from
the United States, even through there is no scientific evidence of
heath damage from consuming such beef.
</P>
<P>
   These attitudes are regarded as partly cultural and partly
political. Europeans often express suspicions about food,
particularly when it comes from any source other than small
familiar vegetable markets, which are rapidly disappearing as
American-style supermarkets move in.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Europe is being reassembled under a unified
economy, there is no independent central authority for assuring
food safety. In the absence of such a body, food scares often
become hot political weapons used by the parties out of power to
attack the parties in power.
</P>
<P>
   This difficult atmosphere could slow Coca-Cola's recovery,
particularly when few signs indicate that the company is out of the
woods with the Belgian government.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the company has admitted problems with its products,
Belgian officials remain unsatisfied and believe the soft drink
concern reacted slowly and arrogantly to their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian Health Minister Luc Van de Bossche criticized Coca-Cola
for a lack of cooperation in handling the health scare. He also has
said that the company waited too long before acting on the
complaints, which surfaced a week before the company acknowledged
that there was anything wrong with its products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disturbing that a big firm with worldwide fame did not
take far-reaching measures more spontaneously and more promptly,''
Van de Bossche said on a local television broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, government officials say that they were moved to
impose the ban out of frustration over Coke's response.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the company has held a news conference to reveal its
discovery that there were problems with its products, Coke has not
provided any information directly to the government, which is
conducting its own research into the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ban remains,'' said Van de Berghe Wednesday afternoon.
``And it will remain until the government is satisfied that
Coca-Cola has explained adequately what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The government wants the company to produce a written report,
which will be reviewed by government scientists, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the ban remains, questions about the quality of Coke
products are likely to linger in the minds of skeptical Europeans.
Additionally, threats of lawsuits in Belgium by some of the people
who fell ill also are likely to keep the soft drink company in the
limelight.
</P>
<P>
   While Coke's lost sales in Belgium mean little to its worldwide
empire, the potential damage to its reputation could prove a more
serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest risk is not to earnings,'' said Marc Cohen, an
analyst at Goldman Sachs. ``The risk is to perceptions about the
integrity of the product.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Pepsi -- which was a common sight on cafe
tables Wednesday -- is more than happy to keep cola consumers here
happy.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Van Lanenhove, who handles orders for Pepsi products in
Belgium, said he's already seeing the impact. ``Since this morning,
the telephone hasn't stopped ringing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
