</P>
<P>
   And even though Europe is being reassembled under a unified
economy, there is no independent central authority for assuring
food safety. In the absence of such a body, food scares often
become hot political weapons used by the parties out of power to
attack the parties in power.
</P>
<P>
   This difficult atmosphere could slow Coca-Cola's recovery,
particularly when few signs indicate that the company is out of the
woods with the Belgian government.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the company has admitted problems with its products,
Belgian officials remain unsatisfied and believe the soft drink
concern reacted slowly and arrogantly to their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian Health Minister Luc Van de Bossche criticized Coca-Cola
for a lack of cooperation in handling the health scare. He also has
said that the company waited too long before acting on the
complaints, which surfaced a week before the company acknowledged
that there was anything wrong with its products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disturbing that a big firm with worldwide fame did not
take far-reaching measures more spontaneously and more promptly,''
Van de Bossche said on a local television broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, government officials say that they were moved to
impose the ban out of frustration over Coke's response.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the company has held a news conference to reveal its
discovery that there were problems with its products, Coke has not
provided any information directly to the government, which is
conducting its own research into the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ban remains,'' said Van de Berghe Wednesday afternoon.
``And it will remain until the government is satisfied that
Coca-Cola has explained adequately what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The government wants the company to produce a written report,
which will be reviewed by government scientists, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the ban remains, questions about the quality of Coke
products are likely to linger in the minds of skeptical Europeans.
Additionally, threats of lawsuits in Belgium by some of the people
who fell ill also are likely to keep the soft drink company in the
limelight.
</P>
<P>
   While Coke's lost sales in Belgium mean little to its worldwide
empire, the potential damage to its reputation could prove a more
serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest risk is not to earnings,'' said Marc Cohen, an
analyst at Goldman Sachs. ``The risk is to perceptions about the
integrity of the product.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Pepsi -- which was a common sight on cafe
tables Wednesday -- is more than happy to keep cola consumers here
happy.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Van Lanenhove, who handles orders for Pepsi products in
Belgium, said he's already seeing the impact. ``Since this morning,
the telephone hasn't stopped ringing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
