<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8015 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-2000-HNS &LR;      06-16 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE OPENS PRESIDENTIAL BID WITH STRESS ON FAMILY VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTHAGE, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore officially opened his
bid for the White House Wednesday by outlining his vision of a Gore
presidency but making only a small effort to distance himself from
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``With your help, I will take my own values of faith and family
to the presidency _ to build an America that is not only better
off, but better,'' Gore told a gathering of a thousand or more
supporters gathered in front of the Smith County courthouse in this
small Tennessee town of 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   In a voice sometimes raspy with emotion, Gore mentioned Clinton
only twice. He praised the president _ and himself _ for bringing
down the budget deficit and creating 19 million new jobs. And he
told the cheering crowd that Clinton ``was right to stand for
freedom'' in the just-concluded NATO bombing campaign over
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath a hazy sun in a courthouse square festooned with Gore
2000 banners, the 51-year-old president sought to etch a vision for
his own presidency after six years of waiting in the wings under
President Clinton. It was a vision focused on cultural issues that
frequently defy governmental solutions.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks came a day after a television interview in which he
said the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal that nearly consumed the
Clinton presidency had made 1998 ``an awful year'' in which he
tried to ``provide some stability and continuity'' by showing up
``for work every day to keep things moving in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech Wednesday was laced with phrases in Spanish _ an
apparent appeal to Hispanic voters, a key Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without action, words mean nothing although they might be nice
ones,'' he said in Spanish at one point. ``My friends, we will
continue working together, hand to hand, for the future of our
families and children.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said that success in closing the budget deficit meant
only that America must turn its attention to ``a deficit of even
greater danger ... the time deficit in family life; the decency
deficit in our common culture; the care deficit for our little ones
and our elderly parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by his wife, Tipper, their four children and his mother
Pauline, Gore ticked through campaign themes that set Democrats and
Republicans apart. He said he favors abortion rights, legislation
regulating managed care health plans, and tougher gun restrictions
_ and opposes privatizing Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said he would focus on what he described as
intangible negatives of American culture that legislation alone
cannot fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``No policy proposal can change a culture that does not place
family life at the top of our hierarchy of values where it
belongs,'' he said. ``History makes no promises to keep the good
times going in the absence of our own wise choices. It is all too
easy to slide backward if we are not vigilant.''
</P>
<P>
   Families need protection from ``a culture of violence and
mayhem'' depicted on television, movies, music and other in other
media, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said American parents must ``master'' their own lives
``if we are to have the moral authority to guide our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Some saw Gore's use of such phrases as ``moral authority'' and
``values and faith and family'' as efforts by the vice president to
distance himself from questions about Clinton's character.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy campaign director Marla Romash dismissed such an
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did today was talk to the American people about issues
that are important and how he'll take his faith, family and values
to the presidency,'' she said. ``He's trying to explain to the
American people what a Gore presidency would be like. This is the
start of the Gore campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   J.V. Derring, 68, a retired electric utility worker who watched
the Gore speech, was skeptical about whether Gore could separate
himself from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about Clinton has been crooked,'' he said, adding
that he had not decided whether to vote for Gore. ``I think Al Gore
is a pretty decent, moral kind of fellow. I hope he's his own man,
but it's hard to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters in the crowd had fewer doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the right man at the right time,'' said William Hayes,
55, a lawyer from Beloit, Wis., who detoured to Carthage from a
country music festival in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   In Carthage and later in a speech at the University of Iowa in
Iowa City, Gore took a swipe at Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
description of himself as a ``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he wanted to keep prosperity going ``the right way,
not by letting people fend for themselves, or hoping for crumbs of
compassion, but by giving people the skills and knowledge to
succeed in their own right in the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, he threw in a pitch for extending prosperity to ``the
farmers and farm communities that are hurting right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters whether his admonition to parents to master
their lives extended to Clinton in the wake of the Lewinsky sex
scandal, Gore replied: ``It applies to every single American.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carthage is near Possum Hollow, where Gore's father, the late
Sen. Albert Gore Sr., ran a 250-acre farm. Gore's mother still
lives there and the vice president and Tipper Gore have an 88-acre
farm of their own nearby.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, the down-home qualities of Carthage were in sharp
contrast with the marble monuments of Washington, where Gore was
born and lived for much of his early life. Gore has used Carthage
as a backdrop for the kickoff of all his political campaigns,
dating back to his first run for the House of Representatives in
1976.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on Wednesday tried turning the Carthage-Washington
contrast to their advantage. Republican National Committee Chairman
Jim Nicholson scheduled a tour of what an RNC press release called
``Al Gore's boyhood home'' _ a luxury hotel in downtown Washington
where Gore and his parents lived during his youth.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Coelho, general chairman of the Gore campaign, described
the RNC tour of Gore's Washington ``homestead'' as ``too cute.'' He
added that Gore worked on his Carthage speech until 11:30 p.m.
Tuesday night, going over nuances with his three daughters and
Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the Carthage crowd defended Gore as an authentic local.
</P>
<P>
   ` `He was raised up right here in Carthage,'' said Clairborne
Carter, 52, a school janitor who worked with Gore on the Gore
family's farm. ``Me and Al grew up together. We raised Aberdeen
Angus cows and plowed the fields. He was a hard worker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still his hometown,'' said Retta O'Dell, a 36-year-old
homemaker and Carthage native. ``Where your roots are is where
you're at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
