<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASIC-ICECREAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECIPES FOR BASIC ICE CREAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   --Basic Custard Ice Cream
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   For safety, homemade ice cream should be made with cooked egg
custards, pasteurized eggs or egg substitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Raw eggs can carry the salmonella bacteria, which causes a
serious, potentially fatal, food-borne illness. Cooking eggs to a
temperature of 160 degrees kills the bacteria, but boiling (212
degrees) will curdle eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Egg substitutes may be used instead of raw eggs because they
have been heat-pasteurized. Most substitutes are made from egg
whites with oil and other additives. Use \ cup substitute for each
egg in the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   If you take the time to make a cooked custard ice cream with
real egg yolks, you'll find the extra effort gives superior
quality. Egg yolks are about 10 percent lecithin, an emulsifier
that helps maintain the even dispersal of fat droplets throughout
the ice cream and keeps ice crystals minimal for a smoother,
silkier and richer ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   -- Revising recipes
</P>
<P>
   To convert an ice cream recipe that calls for raw eggs, combine
milk (or cream), beaten eggs and sugar in a saucepan. Cook over low
heat, stirring constantly, until the mixture thickens and reaches
165 degrees on a candy thermometer. (If you don't have a
thermometer, use a metal spoon: The custard is the proper
consistency when it lightly coats a metal spoon, and your finger
leaves a path when drawn across the back of the coated spoon.)
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the mixture boil, or it will curdle.
</P>
<P>
   Remove custard from heat before adding other ingredients. Cool
custard base completely in the refrigerator before freezing in your
ice cream maker.
</P>
<P>
   If the mixture is warmer than 40 degrees (refrigerator
temperature) when freezing begins, the increased churning time
required may produce flecks of butter. Although harmless, the
butter flecks will ruin the texture.
</P>
<P>
   For quicker cooling, pour cooked custard into a chilled shallow
container and place in refrigerator, or cool over an ice water
bath.
</P>
<P>
   -- No ice cream maker?
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a machine, you can make ice cream, frozen
yogurt, sherbets and sorbets in the freezer with a process known as
still-freezing. You'll need either a food processor or electric
mixer.
</P>
<P>
   First, turn your freezer to its coldest setting. Ice cream will
have a smoother texture if it is frozen quickly. Before starting,
chill all equipment and ingredients, such as fruit juices and
pures. Because there is no continuous agitation of ice cream during
the freezing, the quantity and texture won't be the same as from an
ice cream maker.
</P>
<P>
   Food processor technique: Pour prepared ingredients into a loaf
pan, an 8-inch square pan or a 9-by-13-by-2-inch pan. Cover with
foil or plastic wrap, and place in freezer. Freeze until solid (1
to 2 hours). Break frozen mixture into pieces; spoon into food
processor fitted with metal blade. Process until soft but not
melted. Repeat freezing and processing 1 or 2 more times if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Mixer technique: Pour prepared ingredients into a metal mixer
bowl, cover with foil or plastic wrap, and place in freezer. Freeze
2 hours or until firm at edges and semisoft in center. Beat with
electric mixer on medium-high until mixture is soft but not melted.
Repeat freezing and beating 1 or 2 more times if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Final touches: With either method, after final processing or
beating, stir or fold in any whole or chopped nuts, pieces of candy
or cookies, and pieces of fruit or prepared ingredients used to
produce a swirled or marbled effect.
</P>
<P>
   Most homemade ice cream should be allowed to ``ripen,'' or rest,
for about an hour before eating to allow the flavors to blend.
Homemade ice cream should be kept frozen no longer than 2 days. If
stored for long periods, ice cream develops ice crystals on top and
takes on a heavy, undesirable texture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
