<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8019 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-INTEREST-RATES-HN     06-16 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-INTEREST-RATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD INFLATION NEWS MAY EASE PRESSURE TO RAISE INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in the ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Government economic reports released Wednesday show
that the U.S. economy continues to be strong while inflation
remains in check, easing pressure on the Federal Reserve Board to
raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   A new report on consumer prices, which is the nation's main
inflation indicator, showed that prices paid by consumers for a
range of goods _ from airline tickets to tobacco products _
remained unchanged in May following an unexpected jump of 0.7
percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding food and energy prices, consumer prices rose 0.1
percent during May. Energy prices fell 1.3 percent and gasoline
prices dropped by 2.5 percent in May after a 15 percent spike in
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inflation was a no-show,'' said Sung Won Sohn, an economist at
Wells Fargo Bank in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, many Wall Street analysts feared that the
Federal Reserve would almost certainly boost interest rates, or the
federal funds rate, to 5 percent from its current level of 4.75
percent when the board meets June 29 and 30.
</P>
<P>
   An interest rate increase would be passed along by banks to
consumers in the form of higher rates on consumer and home equity
loans, and credit-card interest rates. An interest rate increase
also makes the cost of borrowing more expensive for businesses,
which would likely slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and Wall Street will be looking to a speech on
monetary policy that Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan is
scheduled to give Thursday before the Joint Economic Committee of
Congress. They will search for hints on whether he will follow
through with recent warnings that a rate increase was likely.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Hoffman, chief economist at PNC Bank Corp. in Pittsburgh,
said it ``remains a toss up'' whether the Fed will boost rates.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets have already factored in an interest rate
hike, with stock prices wobbling and government bonds rising in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond has risen by nearly a
half of a percentage point since the Fed indicated in May that it
was leaning toward boosting rates. Last week the 30-year bond hit a
19-month high of 6.16 percent. This has caused mortgage rates to
rise because they are tied to the bond market. A 30-year fixed-rate
mortgage is averaging about 7.75 percent, up from about 7 percent
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists say the market behavior alone could slow the
economy and allow the Fed to delay a rate hike. They also say with
little evidence of inflation, the Fed won't raise rates at its June
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Chairman Greenspan has enough evidence to hike
interest rates,'' Sohn said.
</P>
<P>
   Sohn said, however, that there's ``brewing evidence'' that
inflation may be on the rise, but that the Fed would likely wait
for more economic data to confirm the trend before deciding whether
to boost rates at its August meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Wages have started to creep upward and the prices of imported
goods have stopped falling as the economy in Asia begins a tortuous
rebound. Economists said economic troubles in Asia caused import
prices to fall for most of 1998, keeping a damper on inflation in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In recent speeches Greenspan and other Fed officials have
signaled that they will likely raise rates to slow the economy. The
last time the Fed raised interest rates was in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   William Poole, president of the Federal Reserve Bank St. Louis
branch, said earlier this month that economic growth has ``been
higher than can be sustained over the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, economists like former Federal Reserve Board governor
Lyle Gramley said that while inflation remains in check, the Fed is
likely to raise rates in order to gently slow the rate of growth.
</P>
<P>
   The economy has been growing at about a 4 percent pace, far
faster than the 2.5 percent level that Federal Reserve officials
believe is possible without eventually sparking price increases
that boost inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are speeding you are eventually going to get yourself
into trouble,'' said Gramley, who is a consulting economist at the
Mortgage Bankers Association in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the government reported that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Construction of new housing rose 6.3 percent in May after
falling by 9.7 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   _ Industrial production, which measures the output of U.S.
factories, rose by 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ A survey of the 12 regional Federal Reserve banks said the
``U.S. economy remains strong'' as a result of continued consumer
spending. The survey reported record-low unemployment, but said
some regions are reporting rising wages, which could lead to
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The financial markets reacted favorably to Wednesday's economic
news as their fears about inflation subsided.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 189.96 points to close at
10,784.95. It was the Dow's best performance since it crossed the
11,000 point threshold on May 3. The Nasdaq market experienced its
biggest one-day point gain by rising 103.16 points to close at
2517.83.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bonds fell to 6.06 percent
from 6.11 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
