<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TARZAN WAS BORN TO BE WILD 

</HEADLINE>
 TARZAN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) With an intriguing beginning, penned in 1911, Edgar
Rice Burroughs gave birth to one of the 20th century's best-known
creations, Tarzan:
</P>
<P>
   ``I had this story from one who had no business to tell it to
me, or to any other.''
</P>
<P>
   Of modern literary characters, perhaps only James Bond and
Sherlock Holmes are as instantly recognizable to so many people
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bond and Holmes, Tarzan won new and greater success on
screen and television. He has swung through almost 50 movies and
several TV shows, from high drama to low parody. He even survived
Bo Derek.
</P>
<P>
   The Lord of the Apes' latest manifestation as an animated hero
in Disney's ``Tarzan'' will add yet another generation of fans,
ensuring his success for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   Like all the previous films, Disney's ``Tarzan'' reinvents the
Ape Man to its needs and style. Yet the original character remains.
</P>
<P>
   Tarzan is a classic version of the anti-establishment hero, with
a hint of the environmentalist tossed in. He believes in the
superiority of nature over human civilization. He kills his food
with his bare hands and eats meat raw, but he respects animals,
even his enemies, more than people.
</P>
<P>
   Even when he dons the clothes of his alternate personality, Lord
Greystoke, and works with people, he is the supreme loner, eager to
``tear off the thin veneer of civilization,'' along with his
clothes, and return to his jungle haunts.
</P>
<P>
   Tarzan is also a basic form of wish fulfillment, the character
who can conquer all through strength, skill and cunning, and live
happily without such irritations as jobs, clocks and freeways.
</P>
<P>
   In Burroughs' books, Tarzan is the son of John Clayton, Lord
Greystoke, and his wife, Lady Alice. In 1888, ship mutineers
abandon the English couple on the west coast of Africa, where they
build a cabin and have a son.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Alice dies and Clayton is killed by great apes. The
baby is adopted by a female ape, Kala.
</P>
<P>
   Tarzan grows to manhood and wins leadership of his tribe, while
teaching himself to read from books in his parents' cabin. His life
changes when American Jane Porter arrives in need of rescue, which
Tarzan supplies repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Tarzan learns fluent English, marries Jane and regains his
rightful title as Lord Greystoke. The couple, now rich and owning
estates in England, elect to live mainly in Africa (but on the
ground, not in a treehouse).
</P>
<P>
   In 24 novels _ some good, some repetitive _ Tarzan roams Africa,
finding lost civilizations, battling evil Europeans and generally
having a bang-up time.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe the answer could start with Tarzan's
unlikely creator, a self-taught writer who never even visited
Africa. Burroughs, has been the subject of many biographies, the
most, though not necessarily the best, the recent New York Times
praised ``Tarzan Forever: The life of Edgar Rice Burroughs'' by
John Taliaferro.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Chicago in 1875, Burroughs better-known as ERB to his
fans, led an early life chasing elusive success. To support a
growing family, he tried many careers, including cavalry officer in
Arizona, cowboy, clerk and business advisor.
</P>
<P>
   As he labored, he day-dreamed a more adventurous life. In
desperation _ and primarily for money, not love of writing _ he
tried his hand at creating the kind of adventure stories he enjoyed
reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan of the Apes'' first appeared in a pulp magazine in
1912. It was an instant success. Movies were not far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan of the Apes'' was a 1918 silent film starring Elmo
Lincoln, a hulk of an actor who was far too old for the youthful
Tarzan character and not at all the sleek jungle man Burroughs had
envisioned. (Burroughs saw Tarzan as an Apollo, not a Hercules.)
There were eight more silent movies with four other stars, but it
was not until 1932 that Tarzan went first-class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan, the Ape Man,'' starring young Olympic swimming hero
Johnny Weissmuller, was a prestige MGM talkie and the biggest film
success of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Geared to a star who was an athlete, not an actor, the film made
Tarzan a man of few and short words: the strong, silent type. Jane
Porter, now Jane Parker, was played by the young Maureen
O'Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan, the Ape Man'' was followed by ``Tarzan and his Mate,''
widely regarded as the best of all Tarzan films and certainly _ in
the restored uncut version _ the sexiest. Weissmuller and
O'Sullivan really were jungle swingers.
</P>
<P>
   As MGM and Weissmuller made 10 more Tarzan movies, the scripts
became more juvenile, and Weissmuller grew flabbier. In 1949, Lex
Barker took over the vine for five films, followed by Gordon Scott
(six films), Denny Miller (one), Jock Mahony (two) and Mike Henry
(three). Ron Ely, who starred in one of several Tarzan TV series,
appeared in films made from television episodes. There were others.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few of these films stand out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan's Greatest Adventure'' (1959), with Sean Connery as a
villain, and ``Tarzan the Magnificent'' (1960), both starring
Scott, were exciting, colorful adventures with decent scripts.
``Tarzan and the Valley of Gold'' (1966) played Tarzan (Henry) as a
jungle James Bond, sophisticated, smart and world-traveling.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982 came the infamously boring ``Tarzan, the Ape Man'' in
which Miles O'Keeffe's Tarzan takes a secondary role to Bo Derek's
usually nude Jane.
</P>
<P>
   The most ambitious Tarzan film was Hugh Hudson's classy-looking
``Greystoke: The Legend of Tarzan, Lord of the Apes.'' Too much
title, too much pretension. The opening hour, as Tarzan grows up in
the jungle, is marvelous, but the film becomes a misguided social
commentary that has little to do with Tarzan or adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the major movies are still available on tape, and the
books are still in publication in paperback.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
