<SLUG> BC-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY BRINGS NATURAL LOOK TO ANIMATION WITH NEW FILM 
 

</HEADLINE>
 TARZAN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) If you thought ``The Lion King'' was the lord of
Disney's jungle, wait until you see ``Tarzan.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Disney studio set out to make its own version of
``Tarzan,'' opening Friday, they were dealing with one of the most
filmed characters in cinema history. It had to be true to the
Tarzan most of the world knows, yet distinctly Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, we wanted to do a `Tarzan' for a contemporary
audience,'' said co-director Chris Buck.
</P>
<P>
   One difference was automatic: This was the first time Tarzan had
been made into a feature-length animated movie. For this film,
however, Disney refined its approach to animation, making
``Tarzan'' look unlike anything the studio has ever done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tarzan'' is a hand-painted movie, like classic Disney, but
uses computer help in a way completely unlike the computer-designed
``A Bug's Life'' or ``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole new process of creating the background,'' Buck
said. ``The computer doesn't do it, we just use the computer as a
tool. We built the jungle in the computer, and painted it. So it
still looks like a painting created by hand, but you can move
around it. It allows us to move as never before, 360 degrees around
the jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with three-dimensional models of the characters and even
props such as tree branches, information was digitized &QL; 
to create a 3-D version of each object. Then the objects could be
projected and painted from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer kept track of all the brush strokes, and you
could move through space,'' said Disney animator David Burgess. ``A
branch would actually exist in three dimensions, and you'd see it
twist and turn, the way it does in real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant we were free. Our camera became like a Steadicam;
you could go anywhere with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The technique gives the film new realism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stylistically, it meant they couldn't look as cartoony,''
Burgess said. ``They had to be more naturalistic and work from all
points of view. If you looked at the Genie (in `Aladdin') from
certain angles, he looked bizarre. He was a cartoon. With these
characters, we had to keep them believable.''
</P>
<P>
   Making ``Tarzan'' contemporary also meant a different approach
to the characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we said we're going to do a `Tarzan'
action-adventure,'' Buck said. ``That's the main thing. After that,
we said we can't just do action-adventure, we should have an
emotional core to the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Buck and co-director Kevin Lima went back to the book ``Tarzan
of the Apes'' and found what they were looking for. Below the
surface of Edgar Rice Burroughs' adventure story was a touching
tale of a young human trying to understand why he is so different
from his fellow apes, and eventually wondering about the strange
humans who look like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started looking for the essence of the book,'' Buck said.
``We wanted to focus more on his emotional journey and his
relationship with the animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``That became this adoption theme. `Do I belong with the people
I look like or the (apes) I love?' ''
</P>
<P>
   What surprised Buck and Lima was how well the test screenings
played to teens, usually the hardest group for Disney to reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of stunned,'' Buck said. ``There's an emotional
story there they seem to hook into. There's a lot of action. They
like Tarzan, he's a cool hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the changes from the story, in many ways Disney's
``Tarzan'' comes closest to capturing the Burroughs story.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that shouldn't be a surprise. In 1936, Burroughs, who was
never really happy with Tarzan movies, considered an animated
version.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``The cartoon must be good. It must approximate
Disney excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   After 63 years, it does.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
