<HEADER>
A8064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GULFTRAIT-0617-COX     06-16 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULFTRAIT-0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GULF WAR VICTIMS SEEN NINE TIMES LESS LIKELY TO HAVE PROTECTIVE
GENE
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Victims of the controversial ``Gulf War Syndrome''
are nine times more likely than their healthy comrades to have a
genetic defect that makes them vulnerable to chemical warfare
agents and similar substances, researchers in Texas and Michigan
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The finding adds evidence to support the often-disputed theory
that soldiers who mysteriously came down with a variety of mental,
cognitive and behavioral disorders after serving in the 1991
Persian Gulf War suffered from exposure to substances such as sarin
nerve gas and organophosphate pesticides, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have identified a gene that predisposes soldiers to Gulf
War Syndrome,'' said Robert W. Haley, an epidemiologist at the
University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gene is important because it determines your level of a
blood enzyme that protects you from nerve gas, particularly
sarin,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The nerve agents also include a number of common pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Haley said Gulf War veterans who were exposed to the substances
and were blessed with high levels of the protective enzyme were
significantly less likely to develop the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   He said a follow-up study will attempt to compare the genetic
differences with the incidence of the fatal wasting
</P>
<P>
   disease, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, also called Lou Gehrig's
disease, among become Gulf War veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Haley and two researchers from the University of Michigan
Medical School published the results of their study in the
scientific journal, Toxicology and Applied Pharmacology.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest questions about Gulf War Syndrome has been
why one person got sick when the person next to him didn't,'' Haley
said. ``That is one of the major puzzles that made many people
think the symptoms were just due to stress.''
</P>
<P>
   After comparing blood samples from 26 victims of Gulf War
Syndrome with 20 healthy veterans, Haley and Michigan researchers
Scott Billecke and Bert N. La Du (CQ), said they found a
significant correlation between the disease and the inability to
produce high blood levels of an enzyme called Q paraoxonase, known
by its biochemical nickname, PON-Q.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies of the effect of organophosphate poisons on the
nervous system have concentrated on levels of a different enzyme,
pseudocholinsesterase.
</P>
<P>
   Haley said PON-Q is a more powerful neutralizer of the poisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just floats around in the blood, chewing up organphosphate
poisons,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   However, the gene that directs the production of PON-Q differs
slightly in different people, he said, and some of the differences
have been shown to lead to lower levels of the enzyme.
</P>
<P>
   The enzyme, which coincidentally is transported in the blood
stream by the ``good'' cholesterol, high density lipoprotein, or
HDL, has been studied in connection with other conditions for many
years, Haley said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his study showed that veterans who are among the most
severely impaired victims of the syndrome are nine times more
likely than healthy soldiers to be in the 25 percent of the
population with the lowest levels of PON-Q.
</P>
<P>
   Haley has become one of the leading scientific proponents of the
view that Gulf War Syndrome is a specific organic disease, rather
than a collection of similar but unrelated symptoms, most of which
could be explained only by ``stress.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he and a group of other researchers from the Dallas
center published a set of three papers in the Journal of the
American Medical Association, concluding that some Gulf War
veterans suffer from brain damage most likely caused by exposure to
chemical agents during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
