<HEADER>
A8065 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISABILITIES-AID-HNS &LR;      06-16 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABILITIES-AID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES BILL TO HELP DISABLED RETURN TO WORKPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Wednesday unanimously approved
legislation to make it easier for people with AIDS and other
disabilities to return to work without losing federal health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a glitch: Lawmakers in both the House and Senate
have yet to figure out how to pay for the popular proposal, which
would cost $800 million over five years. The Senate legislation
sidestepped the issue for now, saying the cost would have to be
paid for by cutting other programs.
</P>
<P>
   More than 7.5 million disabled Americans receive cash and health
care benefits through Social Security disability programs, but many
of them are reluctant to get a job because that could mean losing
their health coverage. Only one-half of 1 percent of those people
leave the disability rolls to return to work, the government says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous that we punish disabled persons who dare to
take a job by penalizing them financially by taking away their
health insurance lifeline,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
one of the lead sponsors of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy predicted that the 99 to 0 in the Senate would provide
momentum for the House to approve legislation, which is popular
with both Republicans and Democrats because it encourages disabled
people to get jobs. The House Commerce Committee has approved
similar legislation, but it must go through the tax-writing Ways
and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James M. Jeffords, R-Vt., also a primary author of the
bill, said the current law erects ``an insane barrier'' for
disabled people who want to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about big government,'' said Senate Finance
Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del. ``It's about getting
government out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would allow disabled people who receive Social
Security Disability Insurance to retain health coverage for up to
six years, up from the current 39 months.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow states to expand Medicaid coverage for
working disabled people who would share the cost of the premiums,
paying more as they earn more.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, moreover, gives disabled people greater access to
job training and employment placement. It also would gradually
phase out Social Security cash benefits to disabled people who go
to work, rather than suddenly cutting them off.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton lobbied for the legislation in his State of
the Union message in January. A slimmer version of the bill passed
the House last year but died in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he hopes to have the bill on his desk by July
26, the ninth anniversary of the signing of the Americans with
Disabilities Act, the landmark legislation designed to increase
access for people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Cox, a senior legislative staffer with the advocacy group
AIDS Action, said the legislation would ``ease the minds and fears
of people with disabilities.'' Cox said many people with AIDS who
have benefited from new medicines fear that if they return to work,
they will eventually lose the federal health insurance that pays
for their treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Ford, co-chair of the Consortium for Citizens with
Disabilities, a coalition of national disability organizations,
said the legislation would ``remove some of the substantial
barriers that keep people with disabilities from working.''
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
