<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8081 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLYWOOD-LEGENDS-HNS     06-16 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-LEGENDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM INSTITUTE PICKS HOLLYWOOD LEGENDS &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   (Undated) As a tribute to stardom, the American Film Institute
has done a competent job in naming 50 screen legends.
</P>
<P>
   But as a publicity stunt to stir interest in our movie heritage
as the century nears a final fade-out, it's fumbled the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Named in a lavish CBS special Tuesday night, the AFI's top 25
male and female screen legends shouldn't spark the fire of
controversy lit by last year's AFI list of the top 100 American
films.
</P>
<P>
   Then, classic pictures such as ``East of Eden'' were excluded
while recent hits such as ``Pulp Fiction'' were included, to name
but one quibble. (Don't get us started.)
</P>
<P>
   But the AFI's roster of 50 screen legends is filled with obvious
choices, from No. 1 Humphrey Bogart, No. 2 Cary Grant and No. 9
Spencer Tracy among the males to No. 1 Katharine Hepburn, No. 4
Ingrid Bergman and No. 5 Greta Garbo among the women.
</P>
<P>
   Who can argue with those? Such performers are undeniably
legendary, whether the AFI calls them that or not.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say omitted stars don't merit legendary status,
from Errol Flynn, Douglas Fairbanks and Frank Sinatra to Lana
Turner, Gloria Swanson and Olivia de Havilland.
</P>
<P>
   Probably more debate will arise over such omissions than over
who made the short list.
</P>
<P>
   Other disputes could concern numerical rankings (John Wayne over
Laurence Olivier? Grace Kelly over Vivien Leigh?) and the AFI's
weird, gerrymander-style rules.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, entry was limited to actors who made their
American screen debut before 1951. But the AFI's rules also had
catches, although it turns out these served only the nominees for
whom they seem intended.
</P>
<P>
   By including ``teams of actors,'' the AFI was able to honor the
Marx Brothers en masse (Laurel &AMP; Hardy lost out), whereas Groucho,
Harpo, Chico or Zeppo never would have been named individually.
</P>
<P>
   By including actors who hit the screen after 1950 but who have
since died, the AFI was able to honor James Dean.
</P>
<P>
   Dean certainly belongs on any list with William Holden, Marlon
Brando and Marilyn Monroe, who also are known chiefly for work
after Hollywood's golden era of the 1930s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   AFI historians' first list of 500 nominees also acknowledged
John Belushi, Elvis Presley, Steve McQueen and even Divine _
``late'' in the mortal as well as the chronological sense.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, none of those made the final list, which was voted
upon by 1,800 filmmakers, critics, historians and cultural leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The ``pre-1951 unless you're dead'' rule rightly ruled out
current or recent favorites (Tom Cruise, Julia Roberts) for
legendary status.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it meant no-brainer legends such as Jack Nicholson,
Paul Newman, Jack Lemmon, Barbra Streisand, Jane Fonda and Meryl
Streep could not be included. Perhaps their turn will come at the
end of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, of the AFI's 50 legends, 41 are deceased, and
the living are largely inactive as actors.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``American'' is slapped all over the rules, but the
honor wasn't limited to American actors.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the AFI embraced actors who made ``a significant screen
presence in American feature-length films.'' That opened the doors
to the European-born Olivier, Grant, Bergman, Leigh, Sophia Loren,
Audrey Hepburn and others.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Audrey Hepburn should be gratified that she was ranked
so highly at No. 3, behind only Katharine Hepburn and Bette Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Others may bemoan that Fred Astaire, while a beloved star, was
No. 5 among males, ahead of Clark Gable at No. 6 and Charles
Chaplin at No. 10. Sidney Poitier, at No. 22, was the only
African-American on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Orson Welles is an odd choice to be among the actors, ranking
No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The honor seems to have been given largely on the strength of
one film, ``Citizen Kane.'' Welles wrote, directed and starred in
that movie, the highest-ranked movie in the AFI's Top 100 list of
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Kelly at No. 15 also seems to have been honored more as a
director, dancer and choreographer than as an actor, a role for
which he wasn't widely heralded.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the AFI could be defining ``actor'' as anyone who
performs on the screen, with popularity also taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   All of these 50 are undeniably great stars, and it's stardom
that begets legendary status, not necessarily acting chops.
Otherwise, top 500 nominees such as Paul Muni or Frances Farmer
might have made the final list.
</P>
<P>
   Peter O'Toole's character in ``My Favorite Year'' made the
proper distinction, even if the AFI does not. ``I'm not an actor!''
he yelled when forced to perform on live television. ``I'm a movie
star!''
</P>
<P>
   As for current stars who weren't eligible, 50 were seen on the
CBS special Tuesday night, which was intended as an honor in
itself. Starting today, many video stores across America will be
honoring those 50 stars and AFI's 50 legends by featuring at least
one film from the careers of all 100.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
