<HEADER>
A8083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0617-C     06-16 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REBUILDING KOSOVO FOCUS OF CLINTON MEETING WITH FRANCE'S CHIRAC
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN-0617.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ President Clinton meets with his French counterpart,
Jacques Chirac, on Thursday for talks on how to divvy up the costs
of rebuilding war-ravaged Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In his first official meeting with a European head of state
since NATO ended its bombing campaign against Yugoslavia last week,
Clinton will reiterate that it's up to Europe to foot the lion's
share of the reconstruction tab.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will acknowledge the importance of the European Union
taking the lead,'' said Mike Hammer, a spokesman for Clinton's
National Security Council. ``But the president will also
acknowledge that we need to do our part as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of Balkans reconstruction is expected to dominate
talks Friday when Clinton and Chirac meet with the leaders from
five other largest industrial democracies -- the so-called Group of
Seven -- in Cologne, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to travel to Cologne Thursday, after his
meeting with Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, accompanied by First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
their daughter, Chelsea, arrived here Wednesday after first
traveling to Geneva, Switzerland to present a speech on global
child labor abuses to the International Labour Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, whose efforts to expand global trade have been
criticized by labor groups in the United States, lent his support
to an ILO convention aimed at providing new protections for the
estimated 250 million children under the age of 14 that are working
in developing countries, often under dangerous and exploitative
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has asked Congress for $35 million this year for
programs aimed at boosting minimum labor standards in developing
countries. On Saturday, he signed an executive order aimed at
shutting out from U.S. government purchases any products made using
abusive child labor practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things we cannot and will not tolerate,''
Clinton said Wednesday. ``We will not tolerate children being used
in pornography and prostitution. We will not tolerate children in
slavery or bondage. We will not tolerate children being forcibly
recruited to serve in armed conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ``These are not some archaic practices out of a
Charles Dickens novel. These are things that happen in too many
places today.''
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in Paris Wednesday afternoon, Clinton and Chirac
had a private dinner at a Paris restaurant and were scheduled to
meet Thursday morning at Elysee Palace.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders were slated to hold a brief press conference after
their meeting, which will likely also touch on a U.S.-French trade
dispute involving beef and bananas and the future of oil sanctions
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   France wants the United Nations mandate for the sanctions
lifted. Clinton contends the sanctions -- which limit Iraq's oil
exports -- are essential to constraining Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein's military machine.
</P>
<P>
   The short-term reconstruction needs in Kosovo are expected to
cost some $3 billion. Coming up with that money is an urgent
priority. An enormous amount of basic rebuilding -- bridges, roads,
shelter, utilities systems -- must precede the return of the bulk
of the 850,000 ethnic Albanians who fled their homes inside Kosovo
and took refuge in neighboring Macedonia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
