<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA ARRESTS TWO WHO LED FARMERS' PROTEST THAT POLICE CRUSHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Five months after riot policemen violently dispersed a
huge demonstration by angry farmers in the southern province of
Hunan, two of the farmers' leaders have been arrested and charged
with serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders, Yang Yaojin and Hu Zhiping, had been fugitives
since the demonstration in Daolin township on Jan. 8. On that day,
thousands of villagers gathered to condemn what they said were
illegal taxes and corruption on the part of local Communist Party
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of police officers dispersed the crowd with tear gas
and clubs. One man was killed by an exploding tear gas canister,
and scores were wounded, according to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration appears to have been one of the largest of
many similar protests reported from rural areas in recent years, as
discontent simmers over official corruption, high taxes and low
grain prices.
</P>
<P>
   Since the confrontation, police had sought several leaders of
the two-year-old illegal farmer association that had mobilized
local villagers. But the men were sheltered by neighbors in the
hilly villages surrounding Daolin.
</P>
<P>
   Early on the morning of June 11, according to two local
residents who spoke on condition of anonymity, police arrested Yang
and Hu. A third organizer of the farmers, Cui Luokun, was not at
home when police broke down the door, and remains in hiding.
</P>
<P>
   On June 12, Chen Lixiang, the Communist Party secretary of
Ningxiang County, which includes Daolin, visited the town and
called a meeting of local officials. He told them that Yang and Hu
had been charged with ``assaulting the government'' and ``holding
illegal rallies,'' according to the local residents.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers still cling to the hope that the Beijing authorities
would support their cause if they only knew the facts, the
residents said. But since January they have been afraid to make any
public protests.
</P>
<P>
   Top officials in Beijing have spoken out against excess taxes
levied by the township and county authorities, and against official
``wining and dining'' with farmers' hard-won earnings. But they
have been frightened by worker and farmer protests and seem
determined to crush independent organizations.
</P>
<P>
   A Hong Kong human rights group reported this week that a total
of nine farmers in Ningxiang County had recently been charged in
connection with January's demonstration, in a list that included
Yang but not Hu. Daolin residents said that only those two had been
arrested from their township and that they were unaware of further
arrests in neighboring areas, but they could not rule them out.
</P>
<P>
   In another typical instance of rural discontent, reported by the
same Hong Kong group, on Monday about 150 farmers held a sit-down
protest at the provincial headquarters of Fujian province in
Fuzhou.
</P>
<P>
   They were protesting inadequate compensation and corruption in a
government takeover of their land, according to the Hong Kong-based
Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in
China. The farmers left peacefully after meeting with officials,
according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
