<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 3 pages of Kosovo-related stories:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Vermitca) _ More than 12,000 cheering, stunned
Albanians begin their journey home, in the first big wave of a
reverse exodus of refugees who were driven from Kosovo in a Serbian
campaign of terror. Their departure created the kind of chaos for
refugee agencies that aid workers had feared. By mid-afternoon, the
line of honking, over-loaded cars, trucks and tractors up the
crumbling road out of Albania toward this Kosovo border village was
five miles long. By Elisabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RETURN (Sopi) _ A vignette on the return of one refugee
to his burned-out home. Formerly well off, he finds everything has
been looted or burned. He will bring his family from Albania and
set up a tent where his house once stood. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Patres) _ Developments: The Kosovo Liberation Army's
leaders have pledged to cooperate with NATO's peacekeepers, but so
far they have not shown much inclination to break up their
insurgency _ just as it has become the dominant political and
military force among Kosovo's Albanians.In the most serious of a
series of confrontations between NATO troops and the KLA, American
marines with helicopter gunships overhead confiscate the weapons of
more than 100 of the insurgents and detain six of their leaders. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Koronice) _ For the last four days, Tom Dedaj has
been going house to house in search of the unburied horrors of
Kosovo. They are not hard to find. A severed foot lies on the grass
of the cemetery. Three doors down from his house, the charred
bodies of five friends are strewn in a rubble-filled room. His own
aunt lies, a mass of lumps and ashes, in her front hallway. Today,
he took a lawyer with Human Rights Watch on a tour of what he had
found, as Kosovo's tragedy entered its next phase: documenting
exactly what has happened since March with an eye toward punishing
the guilty. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Helsinki) _ Defense Secretary Cohen is in Finland
for talks. The Russians say the KLA must be disarmed because of its
``enemy'' comment. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Thomas R. Pickering, the undersecretary
of state, holds talks with the Chinese on the Embassy bombing in
Belgrade. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ The arrival of NATO-led forces has
brought Kosovo's Albanians to city streets and rural lanes to
celebrate, shouting ``NATO!'' and tossing flowers. But not in
Pristina, the Kosovo capital. Here, with some Serbian police and
military personnel still present, the mood is tentative, wary and
restrained. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Grass roots politics is barely
alive in Serbia. Despite the widespread public dissatisfaction with
the leadership of President Slobodan Milosevic, the chances for
rapid political change are small, two leaders of grass roots
movements said today. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WARCRIMES (Washington) _ Folo on reports that U.S. forces
have detained two Serbs accused by ethnic Albanian rebels of
committing war crimes. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
