<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICERS-HAWAII-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT CATCHES BIG WAVE OF HAWAIIAN
OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VANESSA HO  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Don't be surprised if you see King County sheriff's
deputies eating an island-style ``plate lunch'' instead of the
proverbial doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheriff's Office is reaping what it sowed in the Hawaiian
sun last year, when it recruited a huge number of island cops
unhappy with low pay and high cost of living there.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Sheriff Dave Reichert swore in five former Honolulu
officers who are part of an unprecedented wave of Hawaiians joining
Western Washington departments.
</P>
<P>
   Like many agencies, the Sheriff's Office has been struggling
with hiring in a tight job market. Last year, county and Washington
State Patrol recruiters traveled west to lure candidates. This
year, Reichert is expanding some units and replacing retirees in
hiring a record 175 people.
</P>
<P>
   The county has hired 17 Hawaiian officers and plans to hire
seven more in July. On Tuesday, the department celebrated the
swearing-in of their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of living has escalated so much there,'' said Jesse
Barbuta, who had been with Honolulu Police for more than 11 years
and was sworn in Tuesday. ``I couldn't let my wife and children
suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Earl Yamane, who spent more than four years on the
Honolulu force, said he came here this spring, after he missed his
rent three times on a cramped, $900-a-month duplex in a bad
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't afford it,'' said Yamane, who now works in the
Kenmore precinct. ``It's a $10,000 pay raise here. What I make now
is what I made with overtime in Hawaii.''
</P>
<P>
   So many Hawaiians have relocated here that they have their own
association, the Northwest Maka'i Ohana, which means ``police
family.'' Every year its 200 members _ both officers and their
families _ hold a luau with kalua pig and lomi-lomi salmon. It
celebrates its 11th anniversary this year, and has its own Web
page, which allows homesick officers to glimpse Waikiki in ``real
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what these guys are going through,'' said Les Wong, a
Kent police officer who left the Honolulu police in 1980 in search
of a cheaper place to live. ``It's a huge change in culture,
weather and food.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the officers hear about King County and Kent through
established officers such as Wong, whom they jokingly refer to as
``the Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting salary for a King County deputy without police
experience is $3,040 a month, compared with $2,548 in Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   Pay in Honolulu isn't getting much better, where a 1 percent
raise this year has created still more dissension.
</P>
<P>
   Things are so bad, officers here said, that many Honolulu
sergeants are giving up rank for entry-level patrol jobs in other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The floodgates have opened,'' said Tom Clark, a Honolulu
officer of five years who joined the Kent police department in
February. ``Everybody is leaving there. There's going to be a huge
amount of people coming over.''
</P>
<P>
   But relocating comes with sacrifices. Clark said he moved here
in January, leaving an island of endless sun for a depressing
Northwest winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would walk outside at 4 in the afternoon, and it would be
dark, and I thought, `Oh geez, what am I doing here?' But long
term, this was the best decision I could make.''
</P>
<P>
   The large network of Hawaiians in the Northwest has comforted
his longing for the islands, he said, and he often gets a ``plate
lunch'' _ a traditional Hawaiin meal of rice, meat and macaroni
salad _ from a Kent eatery run by a couple from Maui.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
