<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK STRETCHES THE NORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Be it his blocker, his glove, his stick, his
Slinky for a spine, Dominik Hasek is expected to lead the Buffalo
Sabres. They count on their star Czech netminder to lead the
charge, as much as anyone can lead a charge when his first priority
is to stand in front of 24 square feet of open net and turn back
whatever comes his way.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the 34-year-old Hasek has been known to wander. As
goaltenders go, he lives to travel the road not taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell him all the time, `Stay in the net, stay in the net,'
'' said Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff, the morning after his Sabres
pulled into a 2-2 tie in the Stanley Cup finals. ``Then I look up
and he's gone on another of his fishing trips. It's just his way of
staying in the game, and it's something you have to live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek was at his traveling and animated best in Game 4 of the
best-of-seven series Tuesday night, his 30 saves backing the Sabres
to an impressive 2-1 win over the Dallas Stars. When he wasn't
doing the basics, turning himself inside out in front of the cage,
he was straying far afield to handle the puck and sometimes angrily
charging out of his crease, looking like some undersized, outraged
Disney character standing up to whatever fire-breathing Dallas
dragon crossed his territory.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made and written of Hasek's playing style, his
technique, or lack of it. What was once thought to be
unconventional now has become increasingly the norm among NHL
netminders. Witness: with 4:25 to go in the second period Tuesday
night, Dallas netminder Eddie Belfour made a blind backward flip in
his cage and dropped his paddle across the goal line just in time
to prevent Miroslav Satan from popping what would have been the 3-1
lead into the net. Had he not had more pressing matters to attend
to, Hasek right there might have filed for copyright infringements.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek's moves in net keep the editors of Gray's Anatomy up at
night, doublechecking their drawings, making sure the leg bone is
connected to the hip bone. At his double-jointed best, the
170-pound Hasek looks like an escapee from a circus sideshow act.
</P>
<P>
   But his moves out of net are a valuable device, too. He is the
game's best at handling the puck, timing perfectly when to leave
the crease and join the play. Then there is the fiery Hasek, on
display intermittently in Game 4, especially when the likes of
Derian Hatcher and Joe Nieuwendyk got his dander up when they came
a little too close to his personal space.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek on Nieuwendyk: ``He twice slashed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek on Hatcher: ``He tripped me after the whistle _ that's
what got me very, very mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they were too close. Maybe they took their liberties. None
of the alleged contact was anything truly menacing. Hasek's
reactions at times looked theatrical, if not histrionic. From afar,
it looked like Hasek was using the scrapes or near scrapes as
catalysts to get his team going. The day before, in a rare dressing
room speech, he implored his teammates to force the puck up ice, be
aggressive with their play, not to worry about possible odd-man
rushes on his net. If the play turned against him, he told them
all, he'd handle it. And so he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made of rubber, everyone knows that,'' said Dixon Ward,
who cashed in the game-winner with 7:37 gone in the second period.
``You could twist him in knots, it doesn't matter. But he has to be
careful, because he wants to get involved in every area of the game
sometimes. And the physical stuff, a lot of great goalies do it _
it gets them involved in the game. Patrick Roy does it. Ron
Hextall, when he was one of the best in the '80s, he did it. Billy
Smith did it a lot, too, but he swung his stick to a greater extent
than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every Hasek move is calculated, be it the way he stops
the puck or how he pumps up his surrounding defensemen, who needed
something major to get them going after the Sabres managed only 12
shots in Game 3. He constantly loses his stick, but that's a ploy,
too. Ruff explained earlier in the series that Hasek discards the
stick when he senses he can be quicker and better at cutting down
and pouncing on loose pucks without it. He discreetly discards the
stick along the goal line, always in the crease, and then pounces
on the puck the way a kitten would a ball of yarn.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo tough guy Rob Ray, a 10-year aficionado of the fight
game, doesn't worry about the Sabres' prized goalie when the going
gets a little rough out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's bored when he's in the middle of that stuff,'' said
an amused Ray. ``He does it because he wants to get into the game.
Harry Neale and Bob Cole (Canadian television) broadcasters, were
saying on TV the other night that Bobby Orr redefined the game for
defensemen, and Dominik has redefined the way goaltenders play the
game. He heard that and said, `Yeah, if I had a player's skates, I
could get out of the net faster and move the puck up the wall.' And
if he gets in some rough stuff out there, so what, he's got so much
padding, it's not going to hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek turned back 30 of 31 Dallas shots in Game 4. On one stop,
he turned away a Guy Carbonneau shovel that would have tied it at
2-2. In one rare flash when he wasn't in position, he watched
veteran Randy Cunneyworth scurry into the crease and turn back a
Craig Ludwig blast that would have tied it early in the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   When the puck is dropped in Dallas for Game 5 Thursday, Hasek
again will be in net for the Sabres. At least that's where he'll
start. He is two wins away from adding a Stanley Cup to a trophy
case that includes an Olympic gold medal, four Vezina Trophies as
the league's best netminder, and a pair of Hart Trophies as league
MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Barely more than five years ago, no one had ever seen anything
like him. Now he's the norm. OK, maybe ``norm'' is a stretch, but
what else would it be when you're talking about Hasek?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
