<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEADY CONSUMER PRICE INDEX ALLAYS INFLATION FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government said Wednesday that consumer prices were
unchanged, putting an end to April's inflation scare and confirming
that the nation's remarkable era of low inflation and strong
economic growth is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the Federal Reserve Board is still likely to
increase interest rates when its members meet June 29-30. But
positive news about inflation means a rate hike would be limited to
one-quarter of a percentage point _ and no more _ as insurance
against igniting future inflation, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Fed chairman Alan Greenspan's scheduled testimony Thursday in
Congress will be closely watched for clues about his and other Fed
members' thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monetary policy is a forward-looking venture,'' said Oscar
Gonzalez, an economist for John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.,
and Fed chairman Greenspan is ``thinking of pre-emptive moves.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate economic report, released Wednesday by the Fed,
confirmed that ``prices remain generally subdued.'' But the report
showed prices are beginning to rise in some parts of the country
due to strong demand for home furnishings and autos.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department in its monthly report on prices said
Wednesday that there was no inflation in May due largely to a
decline in energy prices _ the biggest monthly drop in more than a
year. Energy prices fell by 1.3 percent in May, the biggest drop
since February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In April, an 0.7 percent increase in the Consumer Price Index
was fueled by soaring energy prices.
</P>
<P>
   On another positive note, the so-called ``core'' inflation rate
_ excluding volatile food and energy prices _ rose just 0.1 percent
last month, down from 0.4 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation remained in check despite other reports that the
economy is barreling along.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of new homes perked up in May after three months of
declines, according to the Commerce Department. Despite a rise in
interest rates for mortgages, which typically dampens demand, total
housing starts rose 6.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 1.68 million units. That reversed a steep decline in April,
at a revised rate of 9.7 percent, and a 0.3 percent fall in March.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial production continued its rebound from a slump last
year in export demand at home caused by economic troubles abroad.
Factory production increased 0.2 percent in May in the fourth
monthly rise, according to the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there is no evidence of inflation today, analysts
believe that Greenspan will stick to statements made last month
that the Fed would lean toward higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting relief that inflation remains in check, the Dow Jones
Industrial average surged 150 points in the first half hour of
trading and finished Wednesday at 10,784.95, up 189.96 points, or
1.79 percent. The technology-heavy Nasdaq index posted a 4.27
percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some conern the Fed might be tightening quite
agressively to slow the economy, especially if we got another bad
inflation report,'' said Robert Mellman, senior econoist for J.P.
Morgan in New York. ``The market's relieved that's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a growing fear of a rate hike has been the primary force
that has knocked the stock market from its levels in April and May.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market also rose for a second day as the reports of low
inflation provided reason to believe that any rate hike in 1999
would not be dramatic. The value of the benchmark 30-year US
Treasury bond increased $5.31, per $1,000 bond, causing yields to
drop 5 basis points.
</P>
<P>
   Fed watchers said that members will keep a vigilant watch due to
that tight supply of workers, which could push up wages, and an
economic expansion in its eight year which could spark higher
prices at any turn.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to inflationary pressures, economies in Asia and Europe
are recovering or strengthening, economists said. Low import
prices, to date, have been a strong force keeping US inflation low;
if prices rise, US producers will have less competition and will be
less inclined to keep their prices low.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is when you've got strong domestic demand and
strong foreign demand, and you let the conditions continue you may
get to a point of more inflation,'' said David Jones, a veteran Fed
watcher for Aubrey Lanston &AMP; Co., a New York securities firm. ``The
Fed will lose its credibility unless it follows up with a couple
quarter-point moves.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wayne Ayers, chief economist for BankBoston Corp., said that
though he believes the Fed is poised to raise rates, there is still
a slight chance they will not do so at the June meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were pushed to the wall, I'd say yes. They feel they have
to do it eventually, and it's going to get harder,'' Ayers said. By
acting soon, the Fed ``won't knock the (stock) market on its heels
because the market has already priced it in,'' Ayers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
