<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8122 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-HNS &LR;      06-16 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE OPENS CAMPAIGN WITH ATTACK ON BUSH, DISTANCE FROM CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTHAGE, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore officially unveiled his
candidacy for the Democratic presidential nomination Wednesday with
a speech giving him moral distance from President Clinton and
policy distance from the Republican front-runner, Texas Gov. George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, born 51 years ago in Washington, D.C., told a crowd of
supporters in his other hometown that he is running for president
``so that our children may make a clean start from the right place,
a higher place, in a fresh century.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore paid his customary salutes to the accomplishments of the
Clinton administration, saying that it rescued the country from
economic doldrums and brought the 20th century to a righteous close
by fighting ``medieval tyranny'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But in introducing himself to the political world as a contender
for his boss's job, Gore loaded his speech with the same preachy
references to morals and ethics that are used by critics of
Clinton's personal behavior with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our own lives we must master if we are to have the moral
authority to guide our children,'' Gore said, shouting and growling
with emotion through much of his address in contrast to his
notorious stiffness. He added that as the country looks beyond
economic prosperity, ``There is a hunger and thirst for goodness
among us.''
</P>
<P>
   To win the Democratic nomination next year, Gore must defeat
Bill Bradley, the former U.S. senator and basketball star from New
Jersey. Polls in key primary states give Gore a less-than-crushing
lead over Bradley, despite Gore's standing as the heir apparent for
the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   But in his speech, Gore was clearly looking beyond the primary
to a potential match-up with Bush, who for now at least does have
crushing poll leads over his primary opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In national surveys, voters say they would pick Bush over Gore
and that the vice president is handicapped by his association with
the negative side of Clinton's record as well as a plodding
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Stabbing at Bush's ``compassionate conservatism'' theme, Gore
said, ``I want to keep our prosperity going and I know how to do
it. I want to do it the right way _ not by letting people fend for
themselves or hoping for crumbs of compassion, but by giving people
the skills and knowledge to succeed in their own right.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also took direct aim at Bush's policy stands in Texas on
abortion, guns and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing his support for abortion rights, Gore said people
have to make decisions on the issue ``based on their own
consciences, not government interference.'' Bush recently signed
into law a requirement that girls cannot get abortions without
their parents being notified first.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he wants to ``get guns off the streets'' while others
``want to pass new protections for gun manufacturers to shield them
from lawsuits.'' Bush has pledged to sign a bill that virtually
bans cities and counties from suing gunmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has championed environmentalism, criticized efforts to
``let polluters off the hook.'' Bush is urging older industrial
plants in Texas to end their exemption from certain pollution
regulations on a voluntary basis.
</P>
<P>
   Making comparisons to Bush even more obvious, Gore delivered a
few sentences in practiced Spanish. Bush's easy use of the language
helped him capture about 40 percent of the Hispanic vote in his
re-election campaign last year, a record high for a GOP candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore never mentioned Bush by name, but campaign aides made it
clear to reporters that the vice president is gunning for only one
of the Republican contenders, even with eight months to go before
the first nominating votes are cast in Iowa and New Hampshire and
18 months to go before the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long campaign if Al Gore is going to be
yelling at us,'' said Bush campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker. ``His
speech sounded like a long litany of carefully tested and
well-polled items in an effort to be all things to all people. It
sounded as if he was previewing, coming soon to a neighborhood near
you, Big Government by Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I do think he offended a lot of good work and good
people of faith by calling them crumbs of compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also listed policy proposals that are, for the most part,
extensions of Clinton's legislative agenda. He pledged to seek new
international trade agreements, a strengthening of the Social
Security system, control of urban sprawl, pre-school programs for
every child, a ``patient's bill of rights'' and new ways for
parents ``to protect their children from the marketing of cruelty
and degradation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore gave his speech to about 2,500 people on the town square,
where he launched his first campaign for office _ a U.S. House seat
_ in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's father, a former U.S. senator who died last year, and his
mother, who attended the campaign kick-off Wednesday, said in 1992
they had raised their son to occupy the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But any regal pretensions to the top job stood in contrast to
some down-home touches added to Gore's first official campaign
event. Gore took the stage to the peppy sounds of a recording by
country singer Shania Twain. Warm-up entertainment for the event in
front of the county courthouse was provided by another Nashville
country crooner, John Michael Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters urging assistance for AIDS victims in Africa briefly
interrupted Gore's speech.
</P>
<P>
   After the visit to the Tennessee town, where Gore and his mother
own adjacent farms, Gore flew to Iowa, site of the nation's first
nominating contest in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will bring my OWN values of faith and family to the
presidency,'' an animated Gore said to a gathering at the
University of Iowa in Iowa City.
</P>
<P>
   Then he and his wife, Tipper, who is taking an increasingly
public role in the campaign, phased into a forum on education. Gore
said it was wrong for politicians to blame teachers for problems
with public education or to rule out a federal government role in
making education better. He also promised stipends for teachers who
sign up for additional training.
</P>
<P>
   It was a theater-in-the-round format, with Gore once again
bucking his robotic image by ad-libbing responses to questions
about education from pre-selected audience members.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign was bound for New Hampshire Thursday,
following the traditional campaign path that Bush took just a few
days ago. In interviews before his Wednesday speech, Gore put new
distance between himself and Clinton _ and acknowledged he was
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's sexual misconduct with Lewinsky ``especially as a
parent, was inexcusable,'' Gore said, and dealing with the
controversy for more than a year ``wasted time'' that could have
been devoted to issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people realize any two individuals are different and
certainly the president and I are,'' Gore told a group of Tennessee
reporters Tuesday, adding that he is now politically free to
disagree with Clinton on policy matters.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Clinton watched Gore's announcement, telephoned him
and said the speech was ``terrific,'' according to spokesman Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
