<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: COURT CLEARS JAYALALITHA
</P>
<P>
   A former actress turned political power broker who helped topple
the government in April was acquitted of one of a number of
corruption charges brought against her. A special court in the
southern state of Tamil Nadu ruled that Jayalalitha Jayaram, 52,
the state's chief minister from 1991-96, was innocent of charges
that she received $1.5 million in a coal import scandal. She said
the decision vindicated her, but she still faces other bribery
charges.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: A MOVE TO HALT KURDS
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Abel Matutes warned that the government would
take ``all necessary steps'' to prevent the self-styled Kurdish
parliament in exile from meeting in July in the Basque region. The
state-owned news agency EFE reported that the Basque nationalists
who invited the 65-member group to meet in the Basque parliament
chamber had begun looking for another site. Turkey links the
Kurdish group to separatist rebels.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: EX-OFFICER JAILED
</P>
<P>
   A discharged army captain, Horacio Montenegro Ortiz, was
sentenced to 21 years' imprisonment after his conviction on charges
of illegally accepting gifts from a narcotics trafficker.
Montenegro was arrested in 1997 with Gen. Jesus Gutierrez Rebollo,
Mexico's top anti-narcotics official, after the two were discovered
to be working for one of Mexico's two largest drug mafias in its
efforts to suppress the other group.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: 13 LEFTISTS SEEK PARTY POST
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen leaders of the leftist Party of the Democratic
Revolution registered as candidates to become the party's new
president. The party has been struggling to select new leadership
after the debacle of its nationwide primary elections in March, the
results of which were nullified after extensive reports of fraud.
The party, which is being led by an interim president, has
scheduled a new national primary for July 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
