<SLUG> BC-KOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA SUSPENDS CONTACTS WITH SOUTH FOLLOWING SEA BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ North Korea said Wednesday that it was
suspending contacts with the South, a day after South Korean
vessels sank one of its warships in the Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension appeared to be retaliation for the sinking of the
ship and the deaths of all 17 crew members. More than 20 North
Korean sailors may have died in a high-seas gun battle that lasted
less than 30 minutes early Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The North Korean suspension immediately endangered talks between
North and South Korea set for Monday in Beijing, although North
Korea did not specifically mention the meeting. It also deals a
blow to South Korean President Kim Dae-jung, who has singled out
closer ties with the North as a major pillar of his presidency. An
aide to Kim declined to comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the suspension appeared to be a careful calculation not to
destroy relations between the countries. In particular, North Korea
is receiving lucrative benefits from recent business deals that it
has struck with the South.
</P>
<P>
   So the North seems to be walking a delicate line, trying to
preserve the advantages of economic ties as it tries to retaliate
for military losses and negotiate for political advantage. That may
explain why it seems to be restricting visits to only Pyongyang,
the capital. It appears that other regions of North Korea are not
affected. But the declaration Wednesday was vague on that point.
</P>
<P>
   A statement carried by the official North Korean news agency
criticized the South for ``bringing the situation of the country to
the brink of war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We solemnly declare that we will restrict or suspend Pyongyang
visits of South Koreans and their contacts with us for the time
being in view of the serious situation created by the South Korean
authorities,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrol boats from the two sides circled Wednesday near the
disputed waters in the Yellow Sea. There was no exchange of fire.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean Chief of Staff Hwang Dong-kyu said the United
States and South Korea were cooperating closely on measures to
respond to North Korea and that the United States had agreed to the
``speedy deployment of U.S. defense resources.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Navy and Air Force planes joined South Korean aircraft
Wednesday in patrolling the Yellow Sea, according to The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation began June 7, when North Korean naval vessels
escorted fishing boats south of the ``northern limit line,'' the
customary demarcation line that separates the seas of the two
Koreas. The North does not recognize the line, but it had never
challenged it so openly.
</P>
<P>
   The North had periodically sent ships south of the line, but
they ordinarily retreated when ordered back by the South. This
time, however, the North Korean vessels refused to back off, and on
Friday, South Korean vessels began to ram the North Korean boats.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, tensions exploded in gunfire. South Korean patrol
boats sank a North Korean torpedo ship, killing all 17 aboard, and
damaged at least five other North Korean vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Two South Korean patrol boats were damaged, and seven South
Korean sailors were slightly injured. South Korea put its entire
armed forces on combat level of alert, which is a state of
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Although the U.S. Command in South Korea is closely watching the
developments, it has not put is 37,000 troops on alert.
</P>
<P>
   The disputed waters are rich in crabs. North Korea, suffering
widespread famine, particularly values crabs, because it can export
them for hard currency.
</P>
<P>
   The two Koreas are still technically at war _ the Korean War
ended in 1953 without a peace treaty _ and there are few visits
between the sides. Still, several thousand South Koreans are in
North Korea at any one time, many in various regions. One
increasingly popular site is Mount Kumgang, a scenic spot where
tours for South Koreans are run by Hyundai Corp., the largest
conglomerate in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism deal that the North struck with Hyundai is extremely
attractive to North Korea, particularly because it has been
receiving millions of dollars each month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
