<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-QUAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLONIAL CITY CLEANS UP FROM HUGE QUAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUEBLA, Mexico _ In this colonial city famous for colorful tiles
and Volkswagen Beetles, the sounds of shovels replaced church bells
as people went to work Wednesday to dig out from a strong
earthquake that damaged the heart of its historic center.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuesday afternoon quake that was felt across seven Mexican
states and rippled through downtown Mexico City killed 16 people _
12 in the state of Puebla, two in the Mexican capital, one in
Guerrero and one in Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred others were hospitalized with broken bones or
rattled nerves.
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of Puebla, in the state of the same name, elaborate
church towers toppled, bell spires cracked and tiled colonial
buildings fractured. Modern offices, apartments and several tourist
hotels also were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   City archaeologist Eduardo Merlo said it would cost millions of
dollars to rebuild the 20 or so historic buildings pierced by the
quake, which measured 6.7 on the Richter scale and greatly damaged
this city of 1.2 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are passing out the hat to collect for their
campaigns,'' he said. ``Well now it is more important to pass the
hat to rebuild the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Yellow police tape cordoned off dozens of city blocks as
residents gawked at their familiar, but now-crumbled sites. Hardly
anyone went to work Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A daughter embraced her mother as they stared at the cracked and
lopsided Jesuit Church, built in 1578.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quake was so strong, everything fell down in the house. I
got under a door and started to pray,'' said Maria Teresa
Maldonado, walking arm-in-arm with daughter Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Two blocks away in Puebla's main city square, Teodomiro Medel,
his hands grasping a trombone, sat on a park bench with friend
Trinidad Dominguez, who held a French horn.
</P>
<P>
   The two musicians are members of the city's band. But city hall,
part of it erected in 1714, may be closed for months or even longer
after ceilings toppled into heaps of rubble, temporarily burying
four people as well as centuries worth of records of births, deaths
and other official documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt the earthquake with such intensity. We thought we
would die,'' said Medel, a musician for the city for the past 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   As a soft breeze rustled the tall trees of the plaza, hundreds
of soldiers wearing blue dust masks over their faces awaited orders
to go inside the massive building, finished in 1906, to clean up
and remove archives.
</P>
<P>
   The quake spared the cathedral, built of marble and onyx, but
just the same it was closed Wednesday. So was the historic
Autonomous University of Puebla, which had more than 20 classrooms
and other buildings damaged by the quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take millions of pesos to rebuild our university,''
said university rector Enrique Dojer Guerrero. ``I don't know where
our 45,000 students will go in the meantime.''
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake was centered in Huajuapan de Leon, 80 miles south
of here, but its strength was felt for hundreds of miles around.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, two people died from heart attacks after
buildings swayed like toothpicks for nearly a minute.
</P>
<P>
   An earthquake measuring 8.1 on the Richter scale killed
thousands in 1985 and memories from that devastating quake are
still fresh.
</P>
<P>
   But Puebla, the heart of Mexico's tile industry where beautiful
Talavera clay pots are exported around the world, doesn't recall
such a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The tremor also temporarily shut down the Volkswagen plant on
the city's outskirts, one of the last places in the world that
still roll out the old-model VW Bug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
