<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LABOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BACKS AGREEMENT TO CURB ABUSIVE CHILD LABOR PRACTICES  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ President Clinton said Wednesday he would
ask the U.S. Senate to ratify an international agreement aimed at
curbing abusive child labor practices that include forcing
youngsters into armed conflict, prostitution and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The president condemned the exploitation of young workers in an
address before the International Labor Organization, an arm of the
United Nations that is expected to approve Thursday the pact
dealing with children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must wipe from the earth the most vicious forms of child
labor,'' Clinton told the ILO delegates meeting at the Palais des
Nations. ``These are not some archaic practices out of a Charles
Dickens novel. These are things that happen in too many places
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged to ask the Senate to approve the agreement as
soon as he returns from his European trip. His advisers said they
do not see major obstacles in getting lawmakers to endorse the
child labor ban, which represents a consensus among business, labor
and government officials from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement relies on voluntary compliance and does not
include penalties for countries or companies who choose to ignore
the prohibition on forced child employment. Rather, administration
officials said they hope that the monitoring and reporting
requirements in the pact will embarrass nations into compliance.
</P>
<P>
   The president's speech in this Swiss city was the first stop in
a weeklong European trip that will largely focus on Kosovo. After
Geneva, Clinton flew to Paris to meet with French leaders. First
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and daughter Chelsea are accompanying
the president on the trip. Both sat in the balcony as he delivered
his address at the labor conference.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week Clinton will attend the economic summit of
industrialized nations in Cologne, where the heads of the NATO
nations will likely hash out with the Russians what their
peacekeeping role will be in Kosovo. Although not officially on his
schedule, officials say it is likely the president will end the
trip with a visit to Kosovar refugees in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   However, the conflict in Yugoslavia took a back seat briefly to
other issues as Clinton used the address to the ILO delegates to
press his case for increasing trade between industrialized and
developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A failure to expand trade further could choke off innovation
and diminish the very possibilities of the information economy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted the criticism of free trade pacts by labor groups
and others who often see such agreements as disproportionately
hurting workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In poor countries the gains seem too often to go to the
already wealthy and powerful with little or no rise in the general
standard of living,'' he said. ``So as we press for more open
trade, we must do more to ensure that all our people are lifted by
the global economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The message on trade appeared to be aimed partly at organized
labor in the United States, which has opposed Clinton's efforts to
convince Congress to give him broader authority to negotiate trade
agreements. Labor groups have argued that free trade pacts often
cost American jobs as corporations seek to take advantage of low
wages in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who joined the president at the Geneva conference
was Jack Sweeney, the president of AFL-CIO, which has strenuously
lobbied against the free trade pacts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton clearly is hoping that leading the effort to eliminate
forced child labor will persuade Sweeney and other labor leaders to
soften their opposition to free trade pacts.
</P>
<P>
   The ILO agreement would apply to children under 18 and would bar
their forced employment in manufacturing and hazardous industries
or in the military. Furthermore, the agreement says these young
people could not be forced to get involved in illicit activities
such as prostitution and drug trafficking. The Clinton
administration has pledged $30 million to help poor countries steer
children into education.
</P>
<P>
   The president noted one success story in Pakistan where children
under 14 who had been forced to work for companies stitching soccer
balls full-time are now able to go to school because adult women
have taken their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said he had taken the lead on the issue by
directing federal agencies not to purchase goods made with forced
child labor.
</P>
<P>
   The ILO agreement would not affect U.S. laws, which, with the
exception of farm work, bars those under 16 from holding full-time
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
