<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8143 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0617-COX     06-16 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVAR REFUGEES IGNORE DANGERS FLOW BACK ACROSS THE BORDER
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MASSACRE; KOSOVO-REFUGEES; CLINTON-KOSOVO;
KOSOVO-DEATHS.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VLLASHNJE, Yugoslavia _ The dispossessed Albanians of Kosovo on
Wednesday began the the long-awaited return to their native land,
flowing back by the thousands to looted and burned villages despite
warnings from NATO and the United Nations that their homes could be
booby-trapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``My blood does not allow me to live as a refugee any longer,''
said 28-year-old Fadil Arifi, who returned to this farm village
three miles inside the Albanian border to find his electrical tools
stolen and his walls scrawled with extremist Serb slogans. The
Yugoslav troops who had occupied his house pulled out under the
NATO-imposed peacekeeping agreement on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Arifi's 50-year-old mother, Ferida, wept as she crossed the
theshhold she had not seen since she took refugee with a family in
neighboring Albania 2 1/2 months ago. ``I cannot take it all into
my mind,'' she said. ``We have come home, but my brother's son is
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Kosovar Albanians are flocking back home, tens
of thousands of Serbians are taking to the roads out of fear of
deadly reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday morning an estimated 33,000 Serbs had fled and many
more were on the way, despite efforts of Yugoslav authorities and
aid agencies to convince them to stay in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything to the Albanian people, but I am afraid
they will not choose who to kill,'' said Diana Grcic, who was
preparing to leave Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NATO troops now are beginning to move into the
central and northern sectors of Kosovo, according to spokesman Col.
Robin Clifford, which are the next areas, respectively, that Serb
forces must leave.
</P>
<P>
   They still must be out by the June 20 deadline set in a military
technical agreement signed by NATO and Serb generals, although the
deadline for the first phase of withdrawal was extended for a day
to expire at midnight Wednesday. The Tuesday deadline was shelved
because roads were so clogged with outgoing traffic that the troops
simply could not get out, Clifford said.
</P>
<P>
   Since entering Kosovo on Saturday, NATO peacekeepers have come
upon or heard about 90 suspected mass grave sites, said Navy Capt.
Mike Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   In Helsinki, Finland, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
reported that after eight house of talks with his Russian
counterpart that they made ``some agreements in some areas'' toward
resolving a Russian-NATO standoff over Moscow's role in keeping the
peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen refused to give details, but told reporters that he and
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev would resume their
discussions Thursday. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
join him in Helsinki Thursday to discuss the same matters with
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   At the Albania-Kosovo border Wednesday, it was a helter-skelter
mass return to the war-ravaged Kosovo province as ethnic Albanians
were pouring across the border at the rate of 1,000 people an hour,
according to the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
   A simultaneous but slower flow of refugees came from neighboring
Macedonia, but at Albania's Morini Border Crossing, road traffic
into Kosovo backed up for seven miles.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was a reversal of the same jam-packed hilltop border
checkpoint this spring where glum refugees crossed after being
driven into exile during a Yugoslav campaign of ethnic cleansing.
That campaign ended a week ago, when Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic gave in to 78 days of NATO bombing, and these same
refugees have been waiting -- some patiently, other impatiently --
to return to what's left of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting atop suitcases and sacks of foodstuffs, refugees from
Kosovo's multitude of isolated villages were mostly riding home in
the same sturdy Yugoslav-built red tractors and farm wagons they
had ridden into their refugee camps. Town-dwellers were homebound
in old Mercedes-Benz sedans, brand new BMWs, taxis, buses and even
small vegetable wagons pulled by garden ploughs.
</P>
<P>
   Just before entering Kosovo, refugees were handed one more
leaflet from UNHCR officials warning that ``everywhere in region
there are mines and grenades all around you.''
</P>
<P>
   The one-page sheet, including a color photograph of one common
type of Serb anti-personnel grenade, which looks like a green can
of shaving soap attached to a white cloth handle. ``Don't touch it
or it can kill you,'' the leaflet warns.
</P>
<P>
   The number of those turning back from fear of mines were
negligible, however, NATO experts saying Wednesday that hundreds of
thousands of land mines have been laid throughout Kosovo, with the
heaviest concentration in the southern border areas.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Serb forces put down mines, but so did the Kosovo
Liberation Army. And unexploded NATO cluster bombs pose a similar
danger.
</P>
<P>
   So far four people have been killed by land mines, but others
have been seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   As they watched the refugees pour through the checkpoint, aid
agency officials expressed alarm at seeing the exiled Kosovars
begin rushing home before mines could be removed and necessary
convoys of medicine, ready-to-eat meals, water and mobile bakeries
could be sent in.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are only have skin-deep awareness of the dangers
they are facing,'' said UNHCR spokesman Rupert Colville. ``We
believe many of the villages may be mined and booby-trapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Also watching in amazement at the frontier was a detachment of
Italian NATO troops that have been training to escort organized
columns of refugees to carefully planned refugee centers at a dozen
sites in Kosovo. The Italians expected their first refugee to enter
Kosovo on July 11 -- nearly a month after this week's unplanned
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very moved about their safety,'' said Lt. Col. Franco
A. Pischedda of the Italian Caribinieri detachment. He said that
the refugees staying at the big Italian-run refugee camp in Kukes
have so far not begun moving home, ``but we don't know how long
they will stay.''
</P>
<P>
   A trickle of refugees, almost all men, began crossing into
Kosovo on Monday and Tuesday to reconnoiter their towns and
villages and then to return to Albania to inform their families.
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR officials noticed that whole families began crossing into
Kosovo late Tuesday, and spokesman Colville said ``this morning
(Wednesday) the floodgates opened.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with scores of returning Kosovars showed that most
were bound for towns and villages close to the Albanian border.
Whether the mass flow will continue in coming days to the more
heavily populated towns deeper inside Kosovo was unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those interviewed crossing from Albania said they had
lived with relatives or in rented apartments rather than refugee
camps. One notable exception were more than 1,000 refugees from the
United Arab Emirates' refugee camp in Kukes, who left the camp en
masse on Wednesday and flooded across the frontier waving flags of
the UAE.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs, meanwhile, were leaving Kosovo en masse. Men were loading
couches and washing machines and other possessions into a semi van
parked outside the residential hotel where the Krajina Serbs have
lived since they came here.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were determined to leave Kosovo by June 20, the
deadline for Yugoslav Serbian military and interior police forces
to withdraw from Kosovo. They fear the celebrations of ethnic
Albanians marking the end of Serb domination could turn from
exuberant to violent.
</P>
<P>
   None of those interviewed seemed to know exactly where the road
out of Kosovo would lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we consider ourselves like the wandering Jews, people who
have terrible experiences wherever they go,'' said Milos Mazibrada,
a third year medical student. ``My future is only one day at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   At Pristina University, dormitory manager Very Denatovic(CQ
both) said she was expecting 4,000 Serbs from Prizren to come
sometime in the night. The school was thrown open to transiting
refugees several nights ago, and the International Committee of the
Red Cross is supplying food to help the moving families.
</P>
<P>
   ``If necessary we will open all the dorms because we want the
people to stay in Kosovo,'' she said. ``We'll tell them to stay
here for a while and if things get better in Prizren to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Any hope of Serb fears being alleviated by the presence of
Russian troops was quickly dissipating.
</P>
<P>
   Between 200 and 300 Russian troops took up positions near the
Kosovo provincial capital of Pristina last Friday, hours before the
first NATO forces entered the province.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has pressed for its own sector inside Kosovo that would
be under Russian control, a position NATO has rejected. NATO's
position is that Russian troops are welcomed, but not to operate
their own sector.
</P>
<P>
   NATO fears that allowing Russia its own sector would risk
splitting Kosovo into Serb and non-Serb areas. Russia has long
historical and cultural ties to the Serbs, who dominate Yugoslavia
but make up only about 10 percent of the population in Kosovo, a
province that is part of Serbia, the main republic in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
