<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8144 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-16 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES FLOOD BACK INTO KOSOVO, DESPITE HAZARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN AND CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia _ The flow of refugees back to Kosovo from
the camps of Albania and Macedonia swelled from a trickle to a
flood Wednesday, despite pleas and warnings from international aid
agencies that it was not yet safe for them to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Columns 13 miles long formed on both sides of the principal
frontier crossing between Albania and Kosovo in a dramatic reversal
of the massive exodus in which 850,000 Kosovars fled the province
during a year of war of conflict with the Serbs and 11 weeks of
intense Serb harassment and NATO bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the thousands pouring across the borders Wednesday were
men who intended to check the condition of their homes, look for
relatives who stayed behind, then return to the camps to bring
their families home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone told me my sister and her four children had been
massacred in their home'' in Pec, said Mexhdet Morina, his face
showing the exhaustion of an arduous, 12-hour trip from central
Albania. ``I am going to look for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Morina and a half-dozen companions hired a wagon driver to take
them over the border to Djakovica, the first major city inside
Kosovo from northeast Albania. From here, they said they would walk
15 to 30 miles to see what, if anything, was left of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt so happy as I am now,'' said Sahit Brzhdara,
73. ``We know our homes are burned and destroyed, but we are
free.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovars who stayed in the province despite the Serbs and the
danger of NATO bombs turned out to cheer incoming NATO soldiers and
offer hospitality to their returning countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   As Morina and Brzhdara's group rested by the Djakovica roadside,
they were approached by Xhavit Llolloni, 45, a local homeowner who
offered to feed and shelter them for the night so they could have a
fresh start in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My food is your food,'' said Llolloni _ an especially generous
offer in an area where food has been scarce for months. But the men
decided to continue on, leaving Llolloni brushing away tears as he
waved goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovar Albanians who had been in hiding, some in cellars, some
in forests, crowded the streets and sat in their overgrown gardens,
celebrating their survival, cheering NATO troops and Kosovo
Liberation Army fighters.
</P>
<P>
   In other major developments Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   _ US Marines patrolling southern Kosovo disarmed about 200 KLA
fighters after a standoff with a guerrilla commander who refused to
surrender his men's weapons.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO said deployment of its KFOR peacekeepers and the
withdrawal of Serb troops were on schedule. A spokesman in
Pristina, the Kosovo capital, said more than 26,000 Yugoslav troops
had pulled out, leaving some 14,000 still to go. In Belgrade, a
senior general said Yugoslav air force and anti-aircraft units had
completed their withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   _ US and Russian defense officials meeting in Helsinki said they
made progress during nearly eight hours of intense talks on the
issue of peacekeeping troops in Kosovo, and would meet again
Thursday. However, there was no resolution of the questions of
Russian participation in the peacekeeping force, or the Russian
occupation of the airport in Pristina, the capital of the province.
</P>
<P>
   _ More evidence of atrocities emerged as NATO troops spread
through central and north Kosovo, the last areas where Serbian
forces are present. French troops found human remains in the ruins
of a house in the southeastern Kosovo village of Vlastica and more
bodies were discovered in four wells in a village near Pristina
where villagers said up to 100 ethnic Albanians were slaughtered by
Serbs shortly before NATO peacekeepers entered Kosovo. A US Navy
officver said peacekeepers has seen or heard of 90 suspected sites
of mass graves since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The American contingent in Kosovo rose to more than 3,000
soldiers, along with 5,000 British and Canadian forces, 4,000
German and Dutch troops, 2,000 Italians and 1,500 French. About
50,000 allied troops, including 7,000 Americans, are expected to
keep the peace in five sectors of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Contacts between KLA guerrillas and NATO soldiers were sometimes
cordial, sometimes tense, as the KLA attempted to establish its
presence in a wide variety of locations and the Western troops
tried to keep control.
</P>
<P>
   KLA fighters walked through the devastated village of Zegra
escorted by US armored personnel carriers on condition they kept
ammunition magazines out of their guns.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers cheered and handed flowers to the guerrillas, who were
clad in black or camouflaged army fatigues and looked exhausted.
But witnesses said the guerrillas, who included some women, were
stopped and disarmed a few miles out of the village. Some of their
officers were handcuffed and arrested.
</P>
<P>
   A Marine officer confirmed that the US forces had to threaten to
call in Cobra attack helicopters before the KLA force submitted and
surrendered its arms.
</P>
<P>
   British government sources in London said NATO and the KLA had
agreed on the outlines of a plan for disarming KLA fighters. They
said the framework agreement was reached at talks between military
officials in Tirana, the Albanian capital, and forwarded to the
North Atlantic Council, NATO's ruling political body. But Russia's
ambassador to the United Nations said the 15-member Security
Council needed to deal with the refusal of the KLA to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   Serb refugees in cars or tractors crammed with their belongings
poured into towns elsewhere in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Some arrived in Belgrade, forcing many in the capital to wonder
whether Kosovo, which Serbs regard as their cultural heartland,
might soon be bereft of Serbs, who made up 10 percent of the
pre-crisis population of some two million.
</P>
<P>
   Marko Jaksic, head of the Kosovo branch of the Democratic Party
of Serbia, said 80,000 Serbs had been displaced since the Yugoslav
army pullout began.
</P>
<P>
   He said columns of refugees heading for Belgrade were several
miles long, and that there were virtually no Serbs left in the
southern part of Kosovo. Many were setting their homes on fire
before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav and NATO officials alike appealed to the Serbs to stay.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's Kosovo Force commander, General Sir Michael Jackson, told
Serb villagers near Pristina: ``We believe the world has too many
refugees already. I beg you not to make the number any greater.
Stay at home and we will look after you.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Bishop Artemije of the Serbian Orthodox Church, who had
urged Serbs in Kosovo's second-largest city to remain, joined the
flight. Under armored escort by German peacekeepers, the bishop and
a number of Serb families left Prizren for Pristina, the German
command said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of the city's last ethnic Serb residents followed
within hours, as refugees on their way back into Prizren jeered and
laughed at them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Milligan reported from Kosovo and Radin from Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
