<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8145 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-2     06-16 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOOD OF RETURNING REFUGEES OVERWHELMS RELIEF WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT7, NYT18 _ have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERMITCA, Yugoslavia _ In the first big wave of a reverse exodus
of refugees who were driven from Kosovo in a Serbian campaign of
terror, more than 12,000 cheering, stunned Albanians began the
journey home Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Their exodus created the kind of chaos for refugee agencies that
aid workers had feared. By mid-afternoon, the line of honking,
over-loaded cars, trucks and tractors up the crumbling road out of
Albania toward this Kosovo border village was 5 miles long. The
trip by car from Kukes, the rutted Albanian town 15 miles down the
mountain where 120,000 refugees have made their temporary homes,
was at one point taking four and a half hours.
</P>
<P>
   Field workers from the office of the U.N. high commissioner for
refugees began registering the names of the returning Kosovar
Albanians at the border at 7 a.m., but gave up three hours later
when it became too cumbersome and slowed down the flow.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee agency in essence ceded the registration to the
Kosovo Liberation Army, the rebel guerrillas who fought Serb forces
in Kosovo. Since the Albania-Kosovo border opened Monday at 6 p.m.,
the rebels have quickly and methodically taken down in spiral
notebooks the names of heads of families, their ages and places of
residence in an awkward but effective partnership with German NATO
forces at the crossing.
</P>
<P>
   The slow trip up to the border seemed to have little effect on
the high spirits of the refugees, who waved the Kosovar
two-fingered victory sign and shouted ``NATO, NATO!'' in what
sometimes seemed like a moving party up the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We survived the worst aggressors in the world!'' shouted
Mehmet Laska, 49, a mechanic from the nearby Kosovar town of
Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   This was the place, just two and a half months ago, that the
same refugees had crossed in a driving rain from Kosovo into
Morini, Albania, weeping and shocked, with lips cracked and
bleeding from thirst on what was often a three-day walk to the
border.
</P>
<P>
   This time the mood was jubilant, even though many refugees were
going home to houses that had been destroyed. ``It's better in a
tent in my garden than here,'' said Qamil Berisha, 35, of the Suha
Reka district, who said his house had been burned to the ground by
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Although workers at the border for the U.N. refugee agency were
passing out leaflets in Albanian that warned about landmines, booby
traps, unexploded bombs and shortages of water, food and
electricity, they elicited mostly shrugs from refugees who for the
first time in months could see the rolling green hills of southern
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflets asked the Albanians to ``please be patient'' while
waiting for aid agencies to accompany them home as soon it was
safe, and for the past week refugees in Kukes have been obediently
saying that they would do so. But in what seemed a massive 24-hour
psychological shift, from a state in which they did not dare to go
home to one in which it seemed impossible to stay away, refugees
listened to the news of NATO's advance on their radios, watched
what their neighbors were doing, then packed up and left.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 Wednesday morning at a Kukes refugee camp, Sahara Sopaj,
23, from the Rahovec district, said that she and her family would
not go home for three or four more days, and that they wanted to be
accompanied by aid workers when they did. But by 6:30 Wednesday
evening, after refugees had poured out of the camps all day, Ms.
Sopaj and her family turned up beaming in the back of their truck
at the border crossing, waving goodbye as they headed home.
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly the kind of mood change that aid workers have
been dreading, fearing that refugees will suffer because they
rushed back before aid workers could establish a system to help
them. Officials from the U.N. refugee agency worked feverishly on
both sides of the border, saying all was under control, although
one worker eyeing tractor after chugging tractor sighed wistfully
and said, ``I feel like I'd like to organize. But it's only a
wish.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis McNamara, the agency's special envoy to the Balkans,
turned up at noon for a hastily called news conference in the front
yard of an elementary school in Prizren and announced that the
sudden migration of the refugees was ``not a nightmare scenario,
it's just rather earlier than we would have wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter from NBC began insisting that someone needed to
control the Albanian border, McNamara responded by asking, ``How do
you control half a million people if they want to move?''
</P>
<P>
   About a million Albanians left Kosovo during the crisis, and
some 435,000 of them are in Albania. Aid workers said the main
problem, aside from the safety of the refugees, is that they are
just beginning to set up an operation to handle the estimated
500,000 ``displaced persons'' who stayed in Kosovo, many of whom
have no homes and have been scrounging for food.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the refugees will have the same needs as the Albanians
who stayed home. One of them is Ferit Saramati, a refugee from the
village of Dobrush, who approached an official of the U.N. refugee
agency, Jean-Marie Garreli, at the border Wednesday morning and
asked for a tent because he had gone back home to discover that the
Serbs had burned his house to the ground. Garreli said he would not
be able to help Saramati for a few more days. ``We are neither
encouraging nor endorsing the repatriation,'' Garreli said
afterward. ``We are insistent on the fact that it's not safe.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite the number of refugees, the procedure once they reached
the crossing point went swiftly. As a vehicle drove in the gate,
workers from the U.N. agency quickly counted the people inside _
there were sometimes 25 or more in the trucks _ then handed out a
plastic card with a number on it to each family head, an
abbreviated version of the more elaborate registration system they
abandoned around 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was that a refugee could use the card in the next
months to more formally, and voluntarily, register. But since the
refugee agency did not take down names to go with the numbers, the
usefulness of the system is unclear. The registration system is
important because most refugees were stripped of their identity
papers by Serbian forces. No one asked the refugees for any proof
of who they were.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the refugees were directed by German troops up to
members of the rebel group, who did take their names, and were
counting up their number, by hand, at the end of the day. The
process was excruciatingly slow until the rebels borrowed a
calculator from a reporter, which helped.
</P>
<P>
   By 7 p.m., the U.N. refugee agency announced that there had been
more than 12,000 Albanians crossing over in the previous 12 hours,
which appeared to be consistent with the number that the rebels
were working out.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the rebels at the border created a delicate
situation for the Germans, who are here as part of a neutral
peacekeeping force that is to protect Serbs as well as Albanians.
But the rebels can take down the Albanian names far faster than the
Germans, and were made part of the border procedure in a meeting
Tuesday between German and rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The German soldiers and rebels at the crossing worked closely
together to solve problems, like moving two stone barricades that
were slowing down traffic, and at one point a German soldier spoke
in German to two members of the rebel group and asked if there were
any girls in town. The rebels said no.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
