<HEADER>
A8157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-SURROI-BOS &LR;      06-16 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-SURROI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN LEADER IN KOSOVO IS ALIVE, BRITISH SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Veton Surroi, the ethnic Albanian leader
in Kosovo whose reported death was a blow to Western allies, is
alive and has met with senior British government officials, they
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said on March 29 that Surroi was murdered by Serb forces, a
claim repeated by the White House on April 6. His purported death
was widely reported as a blow to the efforts to stabilize Kosovo
and establish a democratic government.
</P>
<P>
   But according to a senior British government official who met
with Surroi last weekend, Surroi spent the 78-day war in a Pristina
cellar with his elderly mother.
</P>
<P>
   The British government's account is the first official
confirmation that Surroi, publisher of the ethnic Albanian
newspaper Koha Ditore, is alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quite shaken, but he's alive and well,'' said a British
government official who met with Surroi over the weekend and who
spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Surroi's survival is crucial to the West's postwar strategy of
building a pro-western democracy in Kosovo. The son of a Yugoslav
diplomat, Surroi is seen by Western leaders as the most likely
president of an autonomous Kosovo. Before the war, he was quoted
widely in American newspapers and appeared reguarly on CNN. He
speaks fluent English and is a favorite of Western diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   As the conflict in Kosovo appeared inevitable, Surroi replaced
the ethnic Albanian academic Ibrahim Rugova as the Kosovar leader
the NATO countries preferred to deal with and see as the probable
president in an autonomous Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The peace plan accepted by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
calls for the return of the autonomy that Milosevic unilaterally
ended in 1989. Surroi's support in Washington and the capitals of
western Europe, meanwhile, makes it likely that he will emerge as
the most influential ethnic Albanian in Kosovo, once he emerges
from hiding.
</P>
<P>
   As one US diplomat put it before the war, ``Rugova doesn't have
the street cred (credibility) that Surroi has.''
</P>
<P>
   That credibility with the ethnic Albanians who before the war
made up 90 percent of Kosovo's population will only be increased by
Surroi's having ridden out the war in a damp, musty basement with
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Surroi was a member of the ethnic Albanian delegation which
agreed to a Western plan to end the violence in Kosovo. In a series
of interviews, Western diplomats, including those from the United
States, described Surroi as the voice of reason in the Albanian
camp, bridging the gap between the moderate views of Rugova and the
extreme views of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has stepped into the vacuum created by withdrawing Serb
forces, killing Serbs at a rate that has alarmed the NATO allies.
Surroi is seen as a moderating influence, but it remains unclear
when he will publicly surface, and whether he can rein in the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is waiting until the Serbs leave Pristina,'' a British
official said Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
