<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-     06-16 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY RUNS, A DARK (AND QUIET) HORSE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo of Bradley is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the tall man talks, people tend to listen.
They have to, because he speaks so softly. So the other day, in a
room overlooking San Francisco Bay, maybe three dozen
environmentalists listened closely as Bill Bradley led them through
a discussion that began with the wind in the sycamore trees in his
home town on the Mississippi River in Crystal City, Mo., then
threaded its way through the thickets of California's water wars
and finally, almost by chance, to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, there's only one reason to run for president of the
United States,'' Bradley told a listener who asked him why he was
doing it. ``That's because you think your leadership could improve
the quality of life for millions of Americans. I look at my
situation and think ability matches the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   That understated answer distills the way Bradley has campaigned
up and down California this week: personally, peacefully, almost
obliquely. From a storefront black church in South Central Los
Angeles to a mentoring program for minority teen-agers and new
immigrants in Sacramento, from an earnest discussion with underpaid
home-care workers to a playful pass through the Farmer's Market in
Hollywood, where he made like Meadowlark Lemon with a couple of a
cantaloupes, his style has been the same: He talks quietly about
the issues that drive him, like race relations or the environment,
and lets everything else _ including his candidacy _ speak for
itself.
</P>
<P>
   On this road trip, there is no set stump speech, no repeated
slogan, few snappy sound-bites. There is just a tall man talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted in this trip, notwithstanding what the pundits have
said, to show that you can campaign in California person-to-person
and succeed,'' Bradley said of his nine-day swing through the
Golden State, a bit of creative counter-programming intended to
keep his underdog presence on the radar screen as Vice President Al
Gore, his rival for the Democratic nomination, officially kicked
off his candidacy in Tennessee on Wednesday. ``I want to show
respect for the voters of California, just like I show respect for
the voters of Iowa or New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost no one thinks that retail campaigning is the way to win
in California, where politics sometimes seems to exist only in paid
television advertising and the disembodied debates of direct mail.
But as he finally embraces the quest for the presidency that he
considered and rejected several times before, Bill Bradley is not _
ostentatiously not _ a candidate who buys what everyone else
thinks. And for better or worse, as he lopes along, trailing Gore
in California by worse than 2-1 in the latest Los Angeles Times
poll, Bradley, more than ever, seems to have a sense of where he
is.
</P>
<P>
   There is still the lanky 6-foot-5-inch grace that marked his
years as a basketball star for Princeton and the New York Knicks,
and the cool, cerebral blend of diffidence and directness that
suffused his 18 years in the Senate from New Jersey. But two and a
half years after Bradley left Washington for writing and teaching,
there is something else as well: a kind of Zenlike calm and
self-acceptance that makes him seem looser, easier, lighter than he
did in his days on Capitol Hill, when he tended to come forth
periodically with carefully wrought pronouncements on topics like
trade, taxes or race but otherwise often stayed above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I developed a real peace of mind about what I'm doing now,''
Bradley said in an interview between campaign stops on Tuesday. ``I
have a clear sense of why I want to do it, what I want to do and
how I want to do it. I'm just being myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is not running the anarchic, outsider campaign of a
Jerry Brown or Ross Perot. There are plenty of traditional
campaign-style events, including a Beverly Hills fund-raiser to be
headed by entertainment mogul Barry Diller on Thursday, and
structured sessions of empathetic discussion with diverse
constituent groups that President Clinton has made de rigueur in
contemporary politics. Bradley acknowledges that television
advertising will be important and on Wednesday, he made a
traditional policy speech on child poverty at Para Los Ninos, a
respected child care center on Skid Row downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seven years of the first two-term Democratic
administration since Franklin Roosevelt, the percentage of American
children living in poverty has barely changed,'' Bradley said,
calling for greater parental involvement and improved day care
standards, but omitting mention of the most specific proposals in
the news release circulated by his staff: raising the minimum wage
and expanding the federal earned income tax credit for working
families.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, he is striving to do things differently. He has
yet to take a poll, for example, and is ``not trying to be some
kind of political mannequin,'' as he told a Los Angeles television
reporter. Or, as he told the environmentalists in San Francisco, he
hopes to construct, ``a narrative and some coherence to all these
things that are occurring in people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way politics are done today, too often you try to
be somebody else,'' Bradley said in the interview. ``And I think
that quite frankly the press is bored with this as much as the
politician is bored with it. And I think the idea of my relating to
the press, meaning standing before some backdrop and saying three
or four poll-tested phrases in an attempt to manipulate you only
makes you angrier and therefore your job is to destroy, or as you
would say, unmask, the candidate, and basically on both sides of
the equation it's boring. So my view is my job is to make something
happen with people out there.''
</P>
<P>
   How well that approach will work, and how well Bradley can
execute it, remains to be seen. He says his top priorities will be
to ``be a good steward of a good economy,'' protect the
environment, assure that ``every child in America has a chance to
realize his or her potential,'' and to overhaul campaign finance
laws, but those are not vastly different from Gore's, and Bradley
defers almost all discussion of specifics until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   And although Bradley has criticized Gore for relying on
small-bore ideas, some of his own proposals are not exactly giant,
like the notion of creating ``15-month houses'' where unwed
teen-age mothers could live under supervision in the final months
of pregnancy and the first months of their child's life to learn
parenting skills.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With small groups, Bradley radiates an easy air, as if he were
telling a bedtime story or family yarn. At a round-table discussion
with officials of the local Planned Parenthood in San Francisco, he
studiously avoided taking a position on whether the French abortion
pill, RU-486, should be distributed here and at one point mistook
that drug for the ``morning after'' emergency contraception pill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of Bradley's listeners have been impressed with his
command of their issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not everybody who understands this,'' said Dana Simon, a
lead organizer and field representative for Local 250 of the
Service Employees International Union in Northern California who
listened to Bradley discuss the plight of home-care workers
struggling to win the right to collective bargaining in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, as he joked with political reporters in Sacramento
on Monday, Bradley took heart from the underdog performance of his
old team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' he said dryly, ``the Knicks are proving that speed
and quickness are more important than bulk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
