<HEADER>
A8162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0617-     06-16 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0617-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    AS KOSOVARS FLOOD BACK HOME, A STORY OF ONE FAMILY'S RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN  
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOBOJE, Yugoslavia When Zaim Rahmani and his eight family
members chugged up the hill on their red tractor to this hillside
village, they got some good news: nobody had stolen the cherries
from their one cherry tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot believe it _ it's like a dream,'' said his wife,
Sadet, who returned to find that her home was looted but not burned
to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Their two horses were gone, and so was their Goldstar color TV
set and the dress pants his son had worn for his wedding. So was a
$500 oriental carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Every room in their two-story farmhouse was in shambles from
looters who had ripped apart pillows and pulled off heating vents
looking for hidden money. Happily, they didn't leave behind any
money to steal.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the Kosovar families who flooded back into Kosovo,
the Rahmanis didn't totally ignore the United Nations' warnings
about the danger of mines and booby traps in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they sent Rahmani, 47, as a scout on Tuesday to pick
his way back into the village and determine whether the family
could safely return. He came back Tuesday evening saying there were
no mines in sight. And less than a day later, the family was packed
up and headed home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was impossible to stay there any more,'' said Rahmani. ``We
were 70 people jammed into one private house in Albania. I had to
pay 600 Deutchemarks (about $400) every month for rent there, plus
60 Deutchemarks (about $40) a month for a place to park my tractor.
Now I have no more money to stay there. So we have to come back
here.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the practical part of Rahmani's explanation for why his
family is choosing to risk hunger and hidden explosives to return
home weeks before the international refugee agencies intended.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also the emotional part, the part that touches on
his patriotism toward a spot on a map and a territory called Kosovo
that may never exist as an independent country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to return,'' he said. ``It is my house, it is my
country.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sadet, said she spent all night Tuesday in the
Albanian border town of Kukes packing and preparing food for the
first 10 days back in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:30 a.m., she caught her first glimpse in two and a half
months of her 20-year-old son, Arben, who is a baker. For all that
time Arben has been a captive of Yugoslavian troops, who forced him
to bake bread for the soldiers at a camp near the border. Arben was
found by his father, Zaim, just in time to ride the family's red
model IMT-539 Yugoslav-made tractor from Kukes back to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Another son, 18-year-old Afrim, is a soldier for the Kosovo
Liberation Army. The family doesn't know where he is but has heard
that he is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Rahmani said it's too late this year to plant crops, and he is
worried about how long his supplies will last.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have enough food for the summer,'' said Rahmani. ``We
brought along some canned fish and wheat from Albania, and I have
almost 10 kilograms of sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we can eat the cherries from our tree for about a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
