<HEADER>
A8163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KLA-BOS &LR;      06-16 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBELS PROVIDE OFFICIAL LEADERSHIP IN KOSOVO TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DJAKOVICA, Kosovo _ They've occupied the mayor's office, the
youth center and the post office. They're sending doctors,
medicines and food up to the refugees struggling down from the
mountains. The Kosovo Liberation Army is running this town, taking
charge of everything from civil defense to refugee assistance and
rebuilding of houses, demolished by the Serb military.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is welcome here, and we think they can help'', KLA vice
commander Mehmetali Perolli said from the rogue army's local
headquarters, situated in a local youth center. But the KLA is the
army of the people.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA is supposed to demilitarize, under the peace agreement,
although they are not required to surrender their small arms.
</P>
<P>
   NATO was negotiating with the KLA Wednesday over giving up their
guns to make the exodus of Serb forces from Kosovo less tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make sure that we defuse potentially explosive
situations, said Brig. Gen. Brantz Johnson Craddock. ``We don't
want KLA, armed KLA, in proximity of withdrawing Serbs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA forces are highly visible here, but while all are
uniformed, few Wednesday appeared to be carrying a weapon _ a
switch from the scene on Tuesday, when many of the guerrilla
soldiers had Kalashnikovs slung over their backs.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian Kosovo Force (KFOR) troops assigned to patrol
Djakovica appear to be in friendly cooperation _ though not
collaboration _ with the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are never seen exchanging conversation, but
neither has interfered with the other's movements.
</P>
<P>
   The power vacuum was enormous after the Serb forces pulled out,
and the KLA stepped in immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Taking over the mayor's office was no problem, since the former
mayor, a Montenegrin named Momcilo Stojanovic, headed out of town _
fearful, locals say, of retribution. Stojanovic's modest home in a
mainly Serb neighborhood is closed up and uninhabited.
</P>
<P>
   No aid organizations have arrived here yet to help hungry and
ill locals except for Medicins San Frontiers, a volunteer doctors'
group.
</P>
<P>
   KFOR tanks chug through the city, but residents say they need
their own army to feel safe. ``We're very happy about it. Someone
has to do these jobs,'' said Afrim Brovina, an architect.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian residents of Gjakovica _ a city which endured some of
the most horrifying and destructive attacks of the war _ are mainly
delighted with their new local administration.
</P>
<P>
   Children wear KLA gear, and locals happily helped KLA member
paste official-looking UCK-NATO-Kosova signs all over town
Wednesday. UCK is the Albanian acronym for the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   The handful of Serb civilians who are staying in Djakovica are
more nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not afraid of KFOR, but I am afraid of the KLA, said
67-year-old Milorad Jovanovic. ``I haven't done anything to
anybody, and I'm going to stay here. If they want to kill me, I'm
here''.
</P>
<P>
   The speedy and efficient take-over could position the KLA well
in later elections. Albanian politics are divided loosely into two
camps _ that of the KLA, and that of president-in-exile Ibrahim
Rugova, whose nonviolent approach to gaining independence for
Kosovo proved ineffectual and was one of the main reasons
frustrated Albanians founded the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   KLA leaders say they are focused on the immediate emergency _
not on politics. But they also made it clear that they will not
disband, even though the Serb military is leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the war is not yet over'', said KLA advisor Arben
Hoxha. ``We don't think we have a free country yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
