<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPE-NYT &LR;      06-16 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOSTALGIC POPE RETURNS TO HIS BIRTHPLACE AND ITS MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WADOWICE, Poland _ His fever subsided, Pope John Paul II sought
out the restorative powers of his birthplace, fighting age by
reminiscing about his youth in the small town of Wadowice.
</P>
<P>
   He read a speech, then launched into a long stream of memories,
rattling off the names of streets, shops, the local movie theater,
a few lines from a school production of Antigone, and in one
sobering note, the fate of his Jewish landlord during the
Holocaust. When young people in the crowd sang a Polish traditional
greeting, ``May You Live 100 years,'' the pope listened and replied
wryly, ``Its easy to sing, but its not easy to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The ailing 79-year-old pope had canceled all his public events
Tuesday after the Vatican said he was running a fever linked to a
viral infection. Until Wednesday morning, his aides could not say
whether he would be able to resume his schedule in Poland, but went
ahead and canceled a trip to Armenia on Friday and a Mass outside
Rome on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When the pope arrived at Stary Sacz on Wednesday morning for a
canonization of the 13th-century Polish Queen Kinga, he looked
drawn and still weak. He allowed Cardinal Franciszek Macharski of
Cracow to read his homily, while he listened, eyes shut and his
head resting on his hand. The crowd of 700,000 people seemed to
help revive him. By the end, he joked and talked nostalgically
about hiking trails and boat trips in the surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P>
   In the main square of Wadowice, once named after the Soviet Red
Army and now named after him, the pope seemed suddenly refreshed.
``I have many memories,'' he said, ``at any rate, in this town,
everything started.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Life started, school started, my studies,'' he told thousands
of local residents, many of whom held a vigil for his health over
night, and even today, knelt on the sidewalk to pray hours before
he arrived. He paused, then continued, ``My priesthood started.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, the pope talked of his town, where he lived until
he moved to Cracow to enroll in the university, as a spiritual
source for him. In his spontaneous remarks, he was more prosaic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bookstore was over there,'' he said. ``Is it still here
now?'' He supplied his own answer, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And there was a pastry shop,'' he continued. ``After final
exams we used to go there for cream cakes.'' Covering his face
coyly with his text, he drew bursts of laughter by adding, ``We
survived those cakes.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeatedly tried to stop, saying, ``Enough reminiscing,
that's it.'' When the crowd chanted ``more, more, more,'' the pope
kept on, reciting at one point a few verses from Sophocles'
``Antigone,'' and mentioning the name of his childhood friend,
Halina Kwiatkowska, who starred in the local amateur production.
</P>
<P>
   A local priest interrupted at one point, and said, ``It's time
for the coronation,'' referring to the pope's plan to put gold
crowns on the painting of Our Lady of Perpetual Help, which hangs
in the town's basilica, where he was baptized, and to which he
prayed as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   The pope turned his head toward him, smiled ironically, raised
his hand and made a swatting gesture, as if suggesting the priest
was a spoilsport. He then proceeded with the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Cracow, the pope, seemingly unspent, did not
go right to bed. Instead, he appeared at the window of the
archbishop's residence, a tradition on all his trips home to
Cracow. ``This pilgrimage,'' he began.
</P>
<P>
   When the crowd kept chanting, he said, ``Stop screaming,'' then
resumed when his audience had settled down. ``This pilgrimage is a
return to the beginning,'' he said. ``That's why I went to
Wadowice, where I was born.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, when the crowd shouted ``Long Live the pope!'' John
Paul II did not demure. With a smile, he said: ``You are right. You
are right. I am still alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
