<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-GRIFFIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN GRIFFIN, PILOT AND PIONEER IN AVIATION, FOUNDED SCHOOL; 92 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A memorial service will be held on Monday for John T. Griffin of
Osterville, Mass. and Jupiter, Fla., ``a true pioneer of civil
aviation in Massachusetts'' who blazed new commercial airline
routes across the North Atlantic and founded the East Coast Aero
Technical School.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Griffin died April 10 in Jupiter Medical Center in Jupiter,
Fla. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Quincy, Mass., his interest in aviation was sparked
when he was 5 and his father took him to an air show in the city's
Squantum section. ``We went on the electric trolley,'' he said in a
story published in the Globe on July 20, 1997, ``and I saw them
flying like a bird. I never got over it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, two years after Charles Lindbergh made the first solo
flight across the Atlantic, Mr. Griffin took his first flying
lesson on an East Boston cinder patch that would eventually become
Logan Airport.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Northeastern University, he got his pilot's wings
in 1930 and bought his first plane, a used DeHavilland Gypsy Moth,
for $1,000 in 1931. The following year he founded East Coast
Airways at Dennison Field in Quincy, where he offered flight
training and an apprenticeship program for aircraft mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   When the Boston &AMP; Maine Railroad was awarded a contract to
provide air-mail service to northern New England and sections of
Canada, Mr. Griffin became its chief pilot. When the federal
government forced the railroad to divest itself of the air-mail
operation, it was sold off and became Northeast Airlines. Mr.
Griffin became Northeast's chief pilot.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1940s, he met and married the former Mary Ormsby,
one of the first stewardesses at Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Griffin was also a pilot of the Massachusetts National
Guard. During World War II, in addition to training pilots and
mechanics for the Army at East Coast Airways, Mr. Griffin became a
pilot for the Army Air Transport Command. As the Army attempted to
establish reliable year-round airplane service across the North
Atlantic, Mr. Griffin pioneered several transoceanic routes still
used today. He landed the first Army plane on Baffin Island and
made several experimental landings on Arctic ice floes.
</P>
<P>
   Following the war, he relocated East Coast Aviation to Hanscom
Field in Bedford, Mass. and renamed it East Coast Aero Technical
School. The school has trained about 15,000 airplane technicians.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, when the Aero Club of New England honored Mr. Griffin
with its Godfey L. Cabot Award, Charles Collins, president of the
group, hailed him as ``a true pioneer of civil aviation in
Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife, he leaves two sons, John T. Jr. of Centerville
and W. Nicholas of Framingham, Mass.; five daughters, Mary Blair
Byrd of Roanoke, Va., Anne Herrick and Lisa Hagerty, both of
Osterville, Marcia Russell of Columbia, Md., and Deborah Cuccia of
Milton, Mass.; two brothers, Gerald W. of San Francisco, and
Charles T. of Sandwich, Mass.; 12 grandchildren; and six
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
