<SLUG> BC-MA-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI SEES BRINKMANSHIP IN BUDGET POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Governor Paul Cellucci Wednesday accused the state
House and Senate of ``irresponsible'' brinkmanship in their
impending failure to produce a budget before the new fiscal year
begins July 1.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Globe, Cellucci said the delay is
reminiscent of state government during the financial crisis of the
late 1980s and creates ominous uncertainties for residents,
businesses, and Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most legislatures in the country have ended their session, and
these people can't get a budget to my desk by July 1,'' he said.
``I thought we had moved away from the years of brinkmanship
between the House and the Senate, but it sounds like they're right
back to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so much interested in who gets the credit. I'm
interested in who gets the results,'' he added. ``I want to keep
Massachusetts on course. I don't think this brinkmanship helps. I
think it's irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate and House budget leaders reacted scornfully to the
criticism. Senator Mark C. Montigny of New Bedford, chairman of the
Ways and Means Committee, called Cellucci's spending plan
``probably worth more as recyclable paper than as a budget
document.'' And Representative Paul R. Haley of Weymouth,
Montigny's counterpart in the House, said the governor was being
``disingenuous.''
</P>
<P>
   The possible gubernatorial aspirations of the leaders of both
bodies, House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran and Senate President
Thomas F. Birmingham, have fueled speculation that each man will
want the final budget to bear his imprint. The House plan focuses
on nuts and bolts priorities, plus a modest income-tax cut to 5.75
percent from 5.95 percent; the Senate pays much more attention to
social needs and does not cut the tax rate.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate have yet to meet in conference committee to
hammer out the differences between their fiscal 2000 spending
plans. Montigny and Haley held their first informal session
Wednesday, but the full conference committee is not expected to
begin meeting for three to four days.
</P>
<P>
   Those talks could last for two or three weeks, followed by a
10-day period in which the governor will review the proposal. If
Cellucci vetoes part of the budget, which he has pledged to do,
final approval might not occur until late July.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's budget executives say that such a delay would have a
broad, negative impact. Affected, the aides say, will be cities and
towns that will not know the size of local aid until weeks into the
new fiscal year and human service agencies that cannot expand
programs such as day care until appropriations are approved.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, the budget has been signed before July 1 only four
times _ in 1996, 1995, 1982, and 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Both Haley and Montigny said taxpayers will not be affected if
the Legislature is forced to pass an interim budget until the final
package is adopted. And taking care of the taxpayers' interests,
Montigny said, takes precedence over speed.
</P>
<P>
   Montigny, a Democrat who is shepherding his first budget,
likened Cellucci's criticism to those of fellow Republican Newt
Gingrich when he was minority leader in the US house, before
becoming speaker. ``You don't have to govern,'' Montigny said.
``You can sit there and throw things.''
</P>
<P>
   If the fiscal 2000 budget is delayed a few weeks, Montigny said,
``all that means is that some of his folks will have to work after
4 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the governor truly believes he has a quarrel over the
budget timetable, Montigny said, he should take it up with the
House. The Senate, whose Ways and Means Committee received the
House budget May 17, approved a $20.8 billion spending plan last
Thursday _ or only 3 1/2 weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the House passed its $20.77 billion budget May 12,
nearly four months after Cellucci unveiled his $20.4 billion
proposal. Haley said the governor's document ``was of no help in
moving this process along.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It suggests that we can expand spending, dramatically cut
taxes, and be all things to all people,'' Haley said. ``It
certainly is not a fiscal blueprint for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems the House had to overcome in Cellucci's
budget, Haley said, was the governor's reliance on $130 million in
tobacco-settlement funds that might not be available until next
summer, a proposed reduction in the income-tax rate that would cost
the state $230 million next year, and the lack of a dedicated
revenue stream to replace dramatic cuts in federal highway funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a number of deliberations that had to take place''
during the House budget process, Haley said. ``We had to ask the
administration to supplement their budget recommendations with
backup to demonstrate how we could afford what they were
proposing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's fiscal aides are unimpressed with those explanations.
``It's reasonable to think that the state can have its budget in on
time,'' said Thomas Graf, the state budget director. Failing to
meet that deadline, he said, will have a ``crumbling'' effect on
the state's image for Wall Street bond agencies.
</P>
<P>
   And unresolved issues such as a freeze on the capital-gains tax,
approved by the House and Senate but opposed by Cellucci, will
discourage new business here, said Kristen Keel, undersecretary for
administration and finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``No business will decide to come here until this issue is
resolved,'' Keel argued. She also said schools will have a
difficult time budgeting for the new academic year until the
education-aid package, which differs by $140 million between the
Senate and the House, is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't effectively plan at all until we get this budget
done,'' Keel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
