<HEADER>
A8180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNMARSHALL-CLOSE17-     06-16 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNMARSHALL-CLOSE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    John Marshall Law School will fight for reprieve of death
sentence
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The verdict is in and John Marshall Law School is
headed to death row, unless it wins on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The school, one of two in the state with part-time evening
programs, was notified Wednesday that the American Bar Association
had voted not to grant the school provisional accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   With the decision, John Marshall students won't be able to take
the Georgia Bar exam after Aug. 31, 2001, and the 66-year-old
Atlanta law school will be forced to close because it cannot admit
any new students.
</P>
<P>
   The Student Bar Association plans to petition the Georgia
Supreme Court for extension of the August 2001 deadline, and law
school dean Robert D'Agostino, who filed a complaint with the U.S.
Department of Education, said he plans to ask the ABA's accrediting
committee to reconsider the decision at its Aug. 4 meeting in
Atlanta. If it doesn't, he will appeal to the ABA's House of
Delegates on Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   D'Agostino said the ABA admitted the on-site committee made
several errors in its report on the 250-student school. But it also
noted that the faculty workloads are too high, making it difficult
for professors to do research and perform service, and that the
library collection is too small.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to buy a whole bunch of library books that no
one needs and wants,'' said D'Agostino. ``Our mission is to serve
the educational needs of nontraditional students, not as the ABA
would like us to do, serve the research and leisure time interest
of the faculty.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABA said the school may submit another accreditation
application without waiting the customary 10 months or paying the
$25,000 fee.
</P>
<P>
   D'Agostino said he will explore how the school could survive
financially if it can't admit new students.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
