<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-DUELINGDAD17-COX     06-16 2197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-DUELINGDAD17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tug-of-war between health and taste for Father's Day
 &HT;    By Dale Rice
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's the classic dad dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Father's Day is less than 96 hours away, and millions of
offspring are facing the big dinner question: Do you give Dad
something he thinks tastes good (like a juicy ol' rib dripping in
barbecue sauce and fat) or something you think is good for him
(perhaps a small salad, with grilled fruits and vegetables)?
</P>
<P>
   It's a tug-of-war between taste and health that extends far
beyond this weekend when children want to pamper Dad. This is a
three-meals-a-day, every-day-of-the-year issue: achieving a balance
among food choices that run the gamut on the scale of healthy
eating.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a foodie to do?
</P>
<P>
   One option is to follow the path of Steven Raichlen, the author
of ``The Barbecue! Bible'' and ``Healthy Latin Cooking,'' which
both won prestigious national cookbook awards this year.
</P>
<P>
   Raichlen will dive into a heavy plate of sausage, ribs, pork and
brisket with the best of them, as he did one recent noon hour at
the Iron Works Barbecue in downtown Austin. Then he'll turn around
and prepare a light grilled shrimp for dinner, as he did that night
at Central Market Cooking School.
</P>
<P>
   The key for Raichlen is moderation (he didn't eat every ounce of
that heaping plate) and intense flavors (whether it's barbecue or
low-fat cooking).
</P>
<P>
   And turning on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, grilling is a healthy cooking method,'' says
Raichlen, his head tilted, mouth poised above a beef rib that spans
his face ear to ear. Grilling is a healthy cooking technique, he
says, because ``there is little added fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Grilling also is something Texans endorse enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas,'' Raichlen says, ``is a major epicenter of the two
biggest food trends happening in North America right now _ the
Latinization of the American diet and America going up in flames
with barbecue and grilling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grilling is wonderful,'' says Alexa Sparkman, a registered
dietitian in private practice in Austin. She contends that the
right grilled fish _ such as swordfish or shark _ can taste like a
beef steak if prepared well.
</P>
<P>
   If Dad still is determined to dine on beef, Sparkman suggests a
small tenderloin steak in the 4-ounce range. But first, she says,
trim all the visible fat and discard the bacon that wraps many of
them before tossing it on the grill. If the steak pushes 6 ounces,
which Sparkman says is a whole day's worth of protein, then Dad
should balance it with smaller, lighter meals the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The point, she says, is moderation. In her practice, she tries
to help people find a middle-of-the-road place to begin a healthier
lifestyle. ``Extremes seldom work more than a few weeks,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   She also emphasizes portion control and flavorful ingredients,
such as salsas and pepper sauces, to give spark to meat and
vegetables. With balance and moderation, she says, people don't
have to give up their favorite foods in order to eat healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure life would be worth living without barbecue or
chocolate,'' Sparkman says. ``It's portion control, portion
control, portion control.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a mantra echoed by Raichlen.
</P>
<P>
   He says the traditional Argentinian grill plate, which is 95
percent meat, is enough to give the typical North American
cardiologist a heart attack. Instead of replicating that, he
suggests using a small amount of meat on the plate and filling up
the rest with vegetables and other low-fat items.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use meat as the accent flavor, rather than the focus of the
plate,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That technique, says Dr. Jim Goolsby, a cardiologist with Austin
Heart, would help solve one of the major dietary problems in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   People eat too much fat, Goolsby says. He recommends a diet
concentrating on fish, poultry, fruit and vegetables, while
minimizing red meat and desserts. Still, that doesn't mean Dad has
to abandon steak altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is having steak on Father's Day criminal? No. But we hope to
achieve a life of balance and moderation,'' says Goolsby, a bird
hunter whose ideal meal includes smoked quail, pheasant or turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The important point for Dad to remember on his special day,
Goolsby says, is that parents need to set examples for healthy
eating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fathers need to provide guidance to their offspring, and
that's best done by example,'' he says. ``If a father doesn't eat
right, and hasn't his whole life, then how could he expect his kids
to do any differently.''
</P>
<P>
   To get dads _ and everyone else _ to follow a more healthy
pattern of eating, Raichlen says cooks need to emphasize flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If healthy food doesn't taste well, we've lost the battle,''
he says. ``The central tenet of low-fat cooking is the use of
intense flavorings, rather than fat, to make food taste delicious.
If we could get people thinking about flavors, we would solve a lot
of nutritional problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Tips for healthy cooking
</P>
<P>
   Use chicken or vegetable stock in place of fat in recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Use intense flavors, not fat, to make food taste distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce the meat, increase the vegetables on the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Commandments for the grill
</P>
<P>
   Be organized _ have everything grillside before you start.
</P>
<P>
   Gauge your fuel _ you need enough to cover the time and area of
the food.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to the right temperature _ 500 degrees for direct
grilling to achieve the best seared crust and charcoal flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the grill clean _ clean it twice, before and after cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Keep it lubricated _ oil the grate to prevent foods from
sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Turn, don't stab _ use tongs, not a carving fork, to turn meat.
</P>
<P>
   Know when to baste _ sugar-based sauces should be added near the
end of cooking. Keep it covered _ each time your raise the lid you
add 5 to 10 minutes to the cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   Give it a rest _ let the meat stand for a few minutes before
serving to allow the juices to return to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Never desert your post _ grilling demands constant attention.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an unusual veggie for the grill. Impale okra on a skewer.
Brush with roasted sesame oil. Sprinkle with coarse salt and
pepper. Grill. ``The results are breathtaking,'' says Steven
Raichlen, author of ``The Barbecue! Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Ripe Plantains
</P>
<P>
   4 very ripe plantains
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the grill to high. Cut the ends off the plantains and
cut each crosswise into 2-inch pieces. Coat the cut sides with
nonstick spray. Grill the plantains, turning occasionally, for 10
minutes, or until the skins are charred and the cut ends are brown
and caramelized. The plantains should be very soft in the center.
Trim off the skins (or let your guests do it) and serve at once.
Serves 4. _ ``Healthy Latin Cooking'' by Steven Raichlen
</P>
<P>
   Yucatan Chicken-Lime Soup
</P>
<P>
   4 corn tortillas (6 inches in diameter), cut into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   1 large tomato, halved crosswise and seeded
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   8 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2-8 serrano chile peppers, thinly sliced (wear plastic gloves
when handling)
</P>
<P>
   4 cups Chicken Stock or fat-free reduced-sodium chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups shredded cooked chicken breast
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   4-6 tablespoons lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Arrange the tortilla strips on
a baking sheet. Bake for 3 minutes, or until lightly roasted.
Transfer to a plate to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Working over a small bowl, grate each tomato half on the coarse
side of a hand grater. Discard the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large saucepan over medium heat. Add the
onions, garlic and chile peppers. Cook for 4 minutes, or until the
onions are soft but not brown. Stir in the tomatoes, stock or
broth, chicken and bay leaf. Simmer for 5 minutes. Stir in 4
tablespoons of the lime juice and the cilantro, Season with salt
and black pepper. Remove and discard the bay leaf. Taste and add
more lime juice, if desired. Ladle into serving bowls and sprinkle
each with some of the tortilla strips. Makes 4 servings. _
``Healthy Latin Cooking'' by Steven Raichlen
</P>
<P>
   Texas-style Barbecued Brisket
</P>
<P>
   1 beef brisket (5 to 6 pounds), with 1/4 inch thick layer of
fat, preferably 1/2 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coarse (kosher or sea) salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chile powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the brisket under cold running water and blot dry with
paper towels. Combine the remaining ingredients in a bowl and toss
with your fingers to mix. Rub this mixture into the brisket on all
sides. If you have time, wrap the brisket in plastic and let
marinate, in the refrigerator, for 4 to 8 hours (or even
overnight), but don't worry if you don't have time for this. It
will be plenty flavorful, even if you cook it right away.
</P>
<P>
   Set the grill up for indirect cooking. No drip pan is necessary
for this recipe. If using a charcoal grill, preheat to low. If
using a gas grill, place as many wood chips as you can in the
smoker box and preheat the grill to high. When smoke appears, lower
the heat to medium-low.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, if using a charcoal grill, toss one-quarter
of the wood chips on the coals. Place the brisket, fat side up, in
an aluminum foil pan (or make a pan with a double sheet of heavy
duty aluminum foil). Place the pan in the center of the hot grate,
away from the heat. Cover the grill.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke-cook the brisket, using the indirect method, until tender
enough to shred with your fingers, 5 to 8 hours. (The cooking time
will depend on the size of the brisket and heat of the grill.)
Baste the brisket from time to time with the fat and juices that
accumulate in the pan. If using charcoal, add 10 to 12 fresh coals
per side every hour and toss more wood chips on the fresh coals.
(Add about 1/2 cup chips per side every time you replenish the
coals.) With gas, all you need to do is be sure that you start with
a full tank of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the brisket pan from the grill and let cool for 15
minutes. Transfer the brisket to a cutting board and thinly slice
across the grain, using a sharp knife, electric knife or cleaver.
Transfer the sliced meat to a platter, pour the pan juices on top,
and serve immediately. Serves 10 to 12. _ ``The Barbecue! Bible''
by Steven Raichlen
</P>
<P>
   Catalan Grilled Bread
</P>
<P>
   4 fresh, very ripe tomatoes, cut in half
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, cut in half (optional)
</P>
<P>
   8 slices country-style bread, cut 1/2 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Cruet of extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Small bowl of coarse (kosher or sea) salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the grill to medium-high. Place a half tomato and a half
garlic clove (if using) on each serving plate. When ready to cook,
arrange the bread slices on the hot grate and grill until nicely
browned, 2 to 4 minutes per side. Place a piece of grilled bread on
each plate. To eat, rub a bread slice with cut garlic (if using),
then with cut tomato. Drizzle each slice with oil and sprinkle with
salt and pepper, if desired. Serve immediately. Serves 8. _ ``The
Barbecue! Bible'' by Steven Raichlen
</P>
<P>
   Honey Sesame Shrimp `On the Barbie'
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds jumbo shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons Asian (dark) sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons rice wine, sake or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Thai sweet chile sauce (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Chinese five-spice powder
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed with the side of a cleaver
</P>
<P>
   2 slices ( 1/4-inch thick) fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, trimmed, white part flattened with the side of a
cleaver, green part finely chopped and set aside for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the shrimp under cold running water, then drain and blot
dry with paper towels. Set aside while you prepare the marinade.
Combine 3 tablespoons of the sesame oil, the rice wine, soy sauce,
honey, sesame seeds, chile sauce (if using) and five-spice powder
in a large bowl and whisk to blend. Stir in the garlic, ginger,
scallions and shrimp to coat, then cover and let marinate, in the
refrigerator, for 30 to 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the grill to high. Using a slotted spoon, remove the
shrimp from the marinade to a bowl and toss with the remaining 2
tablespoons sesame oil, Pour the marinade into a saucepan; remove
and discard the garlic, ginger, and scallion whites, using the
slotted spoon. Bring the marinade to a boil over medium-high heat
and cook, uncovered, to a thick, syrupy glaze, about 3 minutes.
Remove from the heat and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, oil the grill grate. Arrange the shrimp on
the hot grate and grill, turning with tongs, until nicely browned
on the outside and firm and pink inside, about 2 minutes per side.
Brush the shrimp with the glaze as they cook. Transfer the shrimp
to serving plates or a platter and sprinkle with the scallion
greens. Serve immediately. Serves 4. _ ``The Barbecue! Bible'' by
Steven Raichlen
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
