<P>
   SLA-FUGITIVE (Los Angeles) _ A former Symbionese Liberation Army
member who grew up in Palmdale, Calif., and has been on the lam for
more than 20 years and arrested in St. Paul, Minn., today is
expected to be sent back to Los Angeles eventually to face state
and federal charges. Kathleen Ann Soliah, 52, was known in
Minnesota as Sara Jane Olson. By Phillip Browne. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CA-TRANSPORT-SPENDING (Los Angeles) _ Gov. Gray Davis on
Wednesday proposed more than $373 million in new highway and rail
projects using the state's share of $1.7 billion in additional
federal transportation funds. By Doug Haberman. (Will move in the
``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-CHARTER (Los Angeles) _ A key component of the voter-approved
city charter is establishment of neighborhood councils that will
serve as advisory panels to the City Council on policy issues. On
Wednesday, a City Council committee takes up creating a Department
of Neighborhood Empowerment to create neighborhood councils around
the city in the first action to comply with the adoption of the new
city charter. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``n'' California
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LATE-LETTER (Los Angeles) _ When an old, browning envelope with
a 3-cent stamp on it arrived in the mail addressed to him and his
wife, Tujunga resident Robert J. Davis knew something was wrong
when he looked at the postmark. It read: ``Winsted, Conn., June 6,
1950.'' ``That was five years before I was even born,'' said the
44-year-old roofer. ``It's kind of weird that I got a letter sent
50 years ago addressed to our address and sent five years before I
was born.'' When he and his wife read the letter, they realized the
tragic reality of a letter lost in the mail for nearly a half
century. The author had written to her daughter and son-in-law to
say she might die at any time and wanted them to come visit her in
Connecticut. It was a letter her daughter and son-in-law never
received. By Troy Anderson and Michael Coit. (Will move in the
``n'' California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MINIMED-FDA (Los Angeles) _ The government approved a test
Wednesday that could dramatically improve how doctors care for
diabetics, by providing the first continuous measurements of a
patient's glucose levels. But MiniMed Inc.'s ``continuous glucose
monitoring system'' won't replace those painful finger-prick blood
tests that diabetics must perform regularly, the Food and Drug
Administration warned. By Dave McNary.
</P>
