<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-EURO17-COX     06-16 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EURO17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Problems called part of political tapestry
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The harsh reaction in Europe to the Coca-Cola health
scare should be seen in the context of politics and not as part of
a wave of anti-Americanism, experts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't jump to the idea that sees this as an attack on a
multinational,'' said Robert B. Zoellick, counselor and
undersecretary for economic and agriculture affairs at the State
Department during the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Zoellick, now with the Washington-based Center for Strategic and
International Studies, attributed Belgium's quick ban on Coke
products to rising concern in Europe about food poisoning and
environmental issues that began with the 1995 mad cow disease scare
in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the Belgian government of Prime Minister Jean-Luc
Dehaene was voted out of office only Sunday after mishandling
revelations that cancer-causing dioxin had entered the food chain
through animal feed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're (Europeans) very jittery,'' added John McIntyre,
director of the Georgia Tech Center for International Business
Education and Research.
</P>
<P>
   Bromis Verhage, marketing professor at Georgia State University,
agreed that Monday's ban on all Coke products by Belgium's Health
Ministry was a ``very predictable reaction, given that the prime
minister had to step down after a similar problem.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre added that the Coke ban is part of a ``power play''
between national governments and the European Union's consumer
affairs commission over control of food regulations. The Belgian
government apparently moved decisively with the expectation that
the EU would act if it didn't, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, McIntyre said, Coca-Cola's relations with the Europeans
were already strained. The Atlanta-based company has angered the EU
by trying to ``pick off one country at a time'' with proposed
acquisitions of beverage operations, instead of going to the
European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Verhage said Coca-Cola's management had also shown a ``lack of
sensitivity'' by not taking decisive action more quickly after
initial reports that 100 Belgian schoolchildren had take ill, given
the fact that ``the whole country is sensitive to food poisoning.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies should learn from Coke's experience, he said.
``It seems that every company should pull out its crisis plan and
be very sensitive when problems like this occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoellick added, ``The basis lesson is react quickly to restore
public confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
