   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-2000 (Carthage, Tenn.) _ Vice President Al Gore officially
opens his bid for the White House by outlining his vision of a Gore
presidency but making only a small effort to distance himself from
President Clinton. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WAR-CRIMES (Paris) _ The Clinton administration welcomes
the Serbian Orthodox Church's call for the resignation of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic and concedes that the indicted war
criminal might gain safe haven inside his own country if he steps
down. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Blace, Macedonia) _ The stream of ethnic
Albanians returning home to Kosovo turns into a tide, while
thousands of Serbian civilians buy and fight their way onto buses
heading north out of the province. By RICHARD MERTENS.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LABOR (Geneva, Switzerland) _ President Clinton says he
will ask the Senate to ratify an international agreement aimed at
curbing the most abusive child labor practices often found in
developing countries. The president condemns the exploitation of
young workers in an address before the International Labor
Organization, an arm of the United Nations. By BENNETT ROTH.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-QUAKE (Puebla, Mexico) _ In this colonial city famous for
colorful tiles and Volkswagen Beetles, the sounds of shovels
replace church bells as people work to dig out from a strong
earthquake that damaged the heart of the historic center. By SUSANA
HAYWARD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GLORIA-TREVI (Undated) _ Mexican pop star Gloria Trevi, who
recently went on the lam after accusations she helped her manager
corrupt young teen-agers, is believed to be hiding in Mission,
Texas. A young performing arts student from Chihuahua recently
lodged charges against Trevi and manager Sergio Andrade, saying
they lured her and other underage girls into sex. By ANDREW DOWNIE
AND JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JUVENILE-GUNS (Washington) _ The House debates a juvenile
justice bill and moves to make gun control a separate measure. Some
aspects of the juvenile bill go so far as to challenge First
Amendment rights even as the gun control issue is being fought on
behalf of the Second Amendment. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   ACID-RAIN (Washington) _ Northeast lawmakers urge Congress to
pass a bill to reduce acid rain. A recent federal study concluded
that despite cuts in air pollution, acid rain remains a serious
problem in the Adirondacks and is a growing threat to forests and
watersheds in the southern Appalachians, Colorado's Front Range and
parts of the Southwest. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PROSTATE-CANCER (Washington) _ Three high-profile prostate
cancer survivors _ former Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole,
onetime junk bond king Michael Milken and New York Yankees manager
Joe Torre _ urge a Senate panel to increase research funding for
prostate cancer. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   DISABILITIES-AID (Washington) _ The Senate unanimously approves
a bill that would make it easier for people with disabilities,
including AIDS, to return to work without losing federal benefits.
By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FED-INTEREST-RATES (Washington) _ Economic reports show that the
economy continues to be robust while inflation remains in check.
Analysts say this combination of healthy news could ease pressure
on the Federal Reserve Board to raise interest rates. By JENNIFER
CORBETT DOOREN. (Also filed in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
