<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8198 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES     06-16 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PEACEKEEPERS STRUGGLE TO KEEP BOLD KOSOVO REBELS IN CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo _ NYT13 _ has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rm) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATRES, Yugoslavia _ After a tense standoff along a rural road,
with helicopter gunships overhead, American marines confiscated the
weapons of more than 100 ethnic Albanian insurgents and detained
six of their leaders Wednesday in the most serious of a series of
confrontations between NATO troops and the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The confiscation of the weapons _ including AK-47s, mines and
rocket-propelled grenades _ came as NATO commanders scrambled to
control the insurgents' increasingly open and brash exercising of
power in Kosovo as the Yugoslav Army and police withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials met with leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army in
Albania to try to arrange the details of disbanding _ or
``demilitarizing'' _ the group and turning its fighters into a
civilian police force for the province.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan drawn up in Belgium by the staff of NATO's
commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, the rebels would have to withdraw
from fortified positions held during the war against President
Slobodan Milosevic's forces, turn over their heavy weapons and
disband in two phases over 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO official said Wednesday night that the commander of the
peacekeeping operation, Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson of Britain,
expected to announce an agreement soon, but that details needed to
be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA's leaders have pledged to cooperate with NATO's
peacekeepers, but they have not shown much inclination to break up
their insurgency _ just as it has become the dominant political and
military force among Kosovo's Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   In town after town, including the capital, Pristina, the KLA's
presence has grown each day, with their red and black flags
adorning ``official'' buildings and their armed soldiers openly
patrolling villages.
</P>
<P>
   The company of insurgents had just paraded through the village
of Zegra, on their way to Gnjilane, when troops from the 26th
Marine Expeditionary Unit confronted them early Wednesday morning a
few miles to the north. Capt. David Eiland, commander of Company K,
said he first asked them to turn over their weapons voluntarily,
beginning two hours of tense negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   When they continued to refuse, he ordered them surrounded and,
with Apache and Cobra helicopter gunships hovering overhead,
arrested six of the company's officers.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until eight hours after the confrontation began that
the insurgents complied. ``We pretty much insisted they turn them
over,'' Eiland said of the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Bruce Gandy, the commander of the Marine ground force
based at a chicken hatchery and slaughterhouse on a hill outside
this village, said Wednesday evening that NATO would release the
detained officers but would destroy the confiscated weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, NATO's interaction with the KLA has been
largely cordial and tolerant. The rebels view NATO as an ally in
their struggle to win freedom for Kosovo's predominantly Albanian
population, and they have generally cooperated with the
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO's commanders here have pledged to be evenhanded in
securing peace in Kosovo after more than a year of civil war and 78
days of NATO air strikes. That also means protecting Kosovo's
Serbs. With the insurgents manning checkpoints in cities like
Cacanik, Suva Reka and Prizren, and opening offices in the capital,
thousands of Serbs have crammed their belongings in cars and fled,
saying they feared reprisals from the rebels, whom they view as
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety among Serbs has grown sharply as the last of the
Serbian-dominated Army and special police units withdrew from a
large swath of Kosovo, following NATO's demands for a phased
withdrawal by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of that withdrawal was supposed to have been
complete on Tuesday night, but NATO granted a 24-hour extension,
saying that the Yugoslav Army was making a concerted effort to
leave but faced enormous logistical challenges withdrawing some
40,000 soldiers and police officers.
</P>
<P>
   A convoy of military vehicles left Pristina at noon Wednesday,
escorting nearly as many civilian vehicles. When asked where she
was going, a woman in one of the cars said simply, ``We don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Army headquarters in Pristina's center, a Serbian woman,
Verica Trajkovic, scolded one of the few soldiers who remained.
``You are leaving us alone,'' she said. ``What are we going to do
without anyone to protect us?''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's commander in Kosovo, Jackson, has repeatedly tried to
assuage such fears, though with little success. On Wednesday, he
met with a large group of Serbs in Kosovo Polje, west of the
capital, and told them the terms for ending NATO's war against
Yugoslavia required the rebel group to be disbanded as an organized
fighting force.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement now being negotiated would more or less mirror the
agreement signed by leaders of Kosovo's Albanians in Paris in
March. It would require the rebels, now thought to number as many
as 17,000, to disband within a month and start training to become a
police force for the province.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the agreement would require the rebels to
respect a cease-fire with the retreating Serbs and keep a little
more than a mile from them. They would also have to stay the same
distance away from the main roads and from the peacekeepers, a NATO
official in Brussels said.
</P>
<P>
   Within four days, the rebels would withdraw from the fortified
positions they held during the conflict. In a second phase, which
would begin after seven days, the rebels would begin turning over
heavy weapons.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 30 days, they would have to disband, ceasing
organized maneuvers and other operations and shedding their
uniforms. The agreement would also require any mercenaries or
volunteers from other countries to leave Kosovo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A major problem in negotiating with the KLA is its opaque
command structure and internal divisions. The group has autonomous
commanders in different regions who have not always been willing to
let the man whom allied officials consider their leader, Hashim
Thaci, speak for them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to get something like the military technical
agreement we have with the Serb forces,'' the NATO official in
Brussels said, ``but a major question is whom do you talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   The company confronted Wednesday, which had 116 soldiers,
appeared to be highly organized, disciplined and armed. ``It was an
organized unit,'' said Gandy. ``And they were loaded for bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Their weapons, when stacked in a pile at the marines' camp near
the village of Patres, reached waist high. In all, the marines
confiscated 105 rifles, some 10,000 rounds of ammunition and 45
grenades. There were two Dragonoff sniper rifles, one with a
silencer, as well as land mines and TNT, presumably for ambushing
Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   First Sgt. Steve Campbell, the squad leader of Delta Company,
which guarded a checkpoint during the confrontation, said the
confiscation could affect what had been a peaceful coexistence in
the first days of NATO's operation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to be a lot less friendly now,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
