<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-QUAKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAKE SURVIVORS RELIEVED THAT LOSS WASN'T GREATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUEBLA, Mexico _ Hardly anyone uses this city's old colonial
name anymore: Puebla de los Angeles _ Village of the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the 1.2 million Pueblans said it must have been
divine intervention that spared them from a potentially
catastrophic earthquake on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a miracle that there was not more death and
damage,'' Josefina Zacula de Guerrero, 65, said Wednesday while
standing near a church whose steeple had been toppled by the
temblor. ``It was an intense and horrible earthquake. But that's
why they say we're surrounded by angels.''
</P>
<P>
   As emergency officials and residents in six Mexican states
cleaned up from the 6.8 magnitude earthquake, there were sighs of
relief that the rattle didn't cause more destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The official death toll stood at 16 late Wednesday, but rescue
workers reported that nearly two dozen people died and another
200-300 were hurt, according to the Televisa television network.
About 500 buildings were seriously affected by the quake that left
about 600 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   But in an area that includes the world's largest metropolitan
area _ Mexico City, with an estimated population of 20 million _
officials concede the toll could have been disastrous. Although the
temblor shook the capital hard enough to sway buildings and send
scores of panicked residents into the streets, the hardest hit area
was Puebla, which lies about 50 miles southeast of Mexico City and
was much closer to the quake's epicenter in Oaxaca state.
</P>
<P>
   Several buildings, including the city hall, were closed to
public access Wednesday because authorities feared they had become
too unsafe. A clock on top of the municipal building remained
locked at about the same time the earthquake hit at 3:42 p.m. local
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid the building would collapse on me,'' said Lilia
Alvarez Romero, 51, an accountant at a downtown furniture store.
``And when it was all over, I couldn't walk out because there was
so much dust and yelling and screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a block from the store where Romero works, St. Agustin
Catholic Church, a colonial, butter-colored structure, lay in
semi-ruins. The earthquake shook the building's concrete steeple,
hurling large chunks of stone to the ground. On an adjacent corner
a vacant office building showed only jagged, clear teeth where
glass windows had once been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's salvageable, look at that tower,''
Fernando Gonzalez, a 36-year-old architect, said of steeple as he
directed a cleanup crew of troops and firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Many parts of Oaxaca state were still without potable water
Wednesday. Churches and older government buildings were seriously
affected in Morelos state. And quake-related deaths were reported
as far north and east as Hidalgo and Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's quake instantly brought back terrifying memories of the
temblor that hit the nation in September 1985. That quake measured
8.1 on the Richter scale and claimed an estimated 10,000 lives,
mostly in Mexico City, which was hit hardest.
</P>
<P>
   For most residents in Puebla, known for its Volkswagen assembly
plant and the two volcanoes that rise only a few miles away,
Monday's quake was the most frightening one they'd felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt the one in 1985, but it wasn't as strong for us in
Puebla as this one,'' Juan Carlos Carbajal, 33, the furniture store
manager, said while standing before a wall of crucifixes and Last
Supper paintings. ``This was much harder, and scarier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
