<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENZYME-SURGICAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENZYME CREATES SURGICAL UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Genzyme Corp. is creating a separate division called Genzyme
Surgical Products, with its own stock. The shares will begin
trading on Monday, June 28.
</P>
<P>
   The change is expected to strengthen Genzyme General, the
biopharmaceutical division, which accounts for more than two-thirds
of the Cambridge company's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   By spinning out its surgical devices and biomaterials, Genzyme
has put a spotlight on the disappointing sales and lack of profits
from its nonpharmaceutical business.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme Surgical is primarily the products and assets of
Deknatel Snowden Pencer Inc., the Taunton, Mass. developer of
instruments for minimally invasive cardiac surgery and specialty
surgical products that Genzyme acquired in July 1996 for $250
million in cash. The diversification into surgical products was
designed to give Genzyme a 52-person US sales force and jump-start
sales of Seprafilm, a thin bioengineered film surgeons apply to
traumatized organs to reduce adhesions after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But three years later, sales of both the surgical hardware and
Seprafilm are well below Wall Street expectations. Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co., for example, predicted that surgical products revenues in 1998
would reach $320 million, much of it from Seprafilm. Instead,
Genzyme this week reported revenues were $104 million last year _
up from $100.8 million in 1997. The division also lost nearly $50
million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting the surgical products operations into a separate group
will improve the operating leverage of Genzyme General,'' said Meg
Malloy, biotechnology analyst for Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. ``Surgical
products won't be profitable for several years, and it sort of
diminished and detracted from the high margins on Genzyme's
therapeutic drug business.''
</P>
<P>
   Since existing Genzyme shareholders will own the bulk of Genzyme
Surgical, the division's shares are known as a ``tracking'' stock,
with a separate price determined on June 28 and traded on the
Nasdaq stock exchange. Genzyme has created several other tracking
stocks from such divisions as Genzyme Tissue Repair and Genzyme
Molecular Oncology for fledlging research and development projects
uniquely different from the company's bread and butter
biopharmaceutial products.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme said it will provide $150 million to Genzyme Surgical
through 2001 to fund the division's operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
