<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENERGY-DEPT-SECURITY-     06-16 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-DEPT-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY SECRETARY TAKES STEPS TO IMPROVE SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on Wednesday named
a retired four-star general to be the department's first security
czar and announced that all normal operations at three nuclear
weapons laboratories will cease for two days next week as part of
an intensive review of security.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's actions are a continuation of Richardson's recent
decision to restructure and centralize the department's far-flung
security functions. The announcements were prompted in part by two
new studies _ one in May by a congressional committee and the other
this week by a presidential advisory board _ that sharply call into
question the Energy Department's ability to properly manage
security.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the new high-level security office is Gen.
Eugene Habiger, who retired from the Air Force last year after
serving as commander in chief of the U.S. Strategic Command, where
he supervised the military's nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Habiger told reporters that the call of patriotism brought him
out of retirement to fix the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very serious problem our country is facing,'' he
said. ``When my country calls me back to do it, I'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He will face a difficult job when he begins his job July 6. The
presidential report, released Tuesday by the President's Foreign
Intelligence Advisory Board, said: ``Even if the new `security
czar' is given complete authority over the more than $800 million
ostensibly allocated each year to security of nuclear
weapons-related functions in DOE, he will still have to cross
borders into other people's fiefdoms, causing certain turmoil and
infighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's other announcement Wednesday will require the
shutdown of the three principal nuclear weapons labs: Los Alamos
and Sandia in New Mexico and Lawrence Livermore in Northern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, Richardson temporarily shut down the computer
networks at the labs as a security precaution. Next week's more
sweeping measure, a ``security immersion program,'' requires all
employees to participate ``in an intensive review of personal
responsibility for security, counterintelligence and
cybersecurity.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said all employees would spend the two days in
training to become familiar with the new tighter procedures on
security issues like personal computer use and electronic mail that
he has put into place in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the move was prompted by both the advisory
board's report and May's report by the select House committee on
China's acquisition of U.S. military and nuclear technology.
</P>
<P>
   The two reports, Richardson said, showed that ``we still don't
have our act together.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential report has also highlighted some disagreements
over what to do with the nuclear weapons complex. Noting the
department's ``organizational dysfunction'' and ``cultural
vagaries,'' the report recommended the creation of an Agency for
Nuclear Stewardship to oversee the department's nuclear
laboratories and related functions through one of two possible
organizational structures.
</P>
<P>
   One mechanism would make the newly created agency
semi-autonomous, headed by a new under secretary of energy and
answerable directly to the secretary. The other proposed structure
would create an independent agency _ like NASA _ to oversee nuclear
functions.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Richardson continued to reject the idea of a separate
agency, saying it would bifurcate security issues at nuclear and
non-nuclear facilities. ``What I don't find acceptable is a
separate agency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he moved closer to endorsing the other proposal, which has
some support in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to accept an under secretary'' and ``work with
Congress'' to merge ``our slight differences,'' Richardson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
