<HEADER>
A8207 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-16 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH- </SLUG>
 PERSONALS-SFCHRON  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE OF A RICH AND FAMOUS MAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Las Vegas Review-Journal reported this week that county
officials are investigating an incident in which  &UR; Robin Leach &LR;  and
six women did naughty things involving food and nudity at
Delmonico's steak &LR;   &LR; house in the new hotel the Venetian.
</P>
<P>
   Leach and his friends _ described as blondes in their 20s _ were
dining in a glass-enclosed private dining room in the middle of the
hotel's kitchen. The alleged revelers are said to have employed
whipped dream and chocolate sauce in their frolics. Leach is said
to have urged kitchen workers to watch and applaud the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The incident caused employees to complain that being subjected
to such goings-on constituted harassment. The county got involved
because it has jurisdiction over the restaurant's liquor license.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the hotel refused to comment, but Leach told the
New York Daily News that the incident was just ``a harmless, fun
whip-cream fight that lasted less than two minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TIES THAT DIDN'T BIND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at the Jewish Community Center in San Francisco,
which is exhibiting a collection of photographs of ketubot, Jewish
wedding contracts, noticed mixed images in the contract of the (now
defunct) wedding of  &UR; Roseanne Barr &LR;  to  &UR; Tom &LR; 
 &UR; Arnold &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Each ketubah includes traditional Jewish design elements, the
names of the couple, &LR;  and personal symbols of the couple.
</P>
<P>
   In the Arnolds' case, the design included columns representing
the great temple in Israel. It also included a sketch of Roseanne's
(she's since dropped a last name) three children from an earlier
marriage and a farmhouse in Iowa that the couple was planning to
build, and symbols of the Grateful Dead, yin-yang and Alcoholics
Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In other family affairs,  &UR; Ellie Stern &LR;  forwards an ad
placed by a self-identified ``German Count'' in the latest issue of
Town &AMP; Country magazine, in the Genealogy section: ``Best Prussian
ancient nobility is offering the unusual possibility of
transferring his name to a solvent lady.'' (Presumably not a
door-to-door saleswoman of dry-cleaning fluids.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Michael Harris &LR;  sends word of an announcement in On
Wisconsin, the alumni magazine of the University of Wisconsin, that
Praise to Thee, Our Almond Mocha is the ice cream named in homage
to the 150th anniversary of that dairy state institution.
</P>
<P>
   - MoJo Wire editor  &UR; Eric Umansky &LR; , a man with an ear for
dialogue, says that Tuesday night's ``Nightline'' included  &UR; Ted &LR; 
 &UR; Koppel &LR; 's reaction (on-air with no bleeps) to a Serbian he was
interviewing: ``Tell him that I know when I get a direct answer and
I know when I get bull_, and this is bull_.''
</P>
<P>
   - A full-size guillotine decorated with multiple Chanel logos by
artist  &UR; Tom Sachs &LR;  has been bought by San Francisco art collectors
 &UR; John  &LR; and  &UR; Dodie Rosekrans cq &LR;  for their apartment in Venice, says
Vogue magazine.
</P>
<P>
   - San Francisco has the highest percentage in the country (72
percent) of adults who use the Internet, says the Wall Street
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   - At the Web site www.howtopayforit.com, people who want plastic
surgery but can't afford to pay for it may apply for loans. ``We
believe that this system will put the patient more at ease,''  &UR; Anne
Tynion  &LR; of Unicorn Financial Services told the New York Times,
``knowing they're approved before they walk into the doctor's
office.''
</P>
<P>
   - Doggie etiquette tip No. 5 for Take Your Dog to Work Day, June
25, as sponsored by pets.com: Keep your dog quiet during conference
calls.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Trophy homes, diamonds of a carat or more, granite countertops
and sport utility vehicles are the primary consumer symbols of the
late 1990s. ... (Americans) have become overly entitled and
spoiled.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Juliet Schor &LR; ,  &LR; author of ``The Overspent American: Why We
Want What We Don't Need,'' in the Boston Review.
</P>
<P>
   ``How come it's OK to lay a slab of granite four times the size
of a countertop over the body of dead Uncle Louie, carve a few
dates in it, and then leave it alone for years, while it's a sign
of a really urgent problem _ the dreaded `luxury fever' _ when the
slab appears in the kitchen where it can actually be used and _
gasp! _ enjoyed?''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; James Twitchell &LR; , author of ``Lead Us Into Temptation: The
Triumph of American Materialism,'' ibid.
</P>
</TEXT>
