<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-LIBERAL-ART-2TA     06-16 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-LIBERAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GAY, LIBERAL DO-GOODER WHO MAY CHALLENGE SAN FRANCISCO'S
MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Not every Tom Ammiano idea rattles the
seismically retrofitted corridors of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months ago, when a fitness club put up a billboard
advertisement that said when aliens land ``they'll eat the fat ones
first,'' Ammiano sat in his lofty oak perch at the San Francisco
Board of Supervisors' chambers and pronounced that the city should
amend its law banning discrimination against race, religion,
ancestry, sex, age, sexual orientation, gender identity, disability
and place of birth to include persons who are overweight.
</P>
<P>
   Presto. It was as good as done.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, however, the president of the governing body for the
nation's most famously liberal city arrives at weekly supervisors'
meetings armed with far more radical proposals, ideas to change
life in this city that leave his colleagues on the board frozen and
mute, as though they had crossed paths with a bear.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when no self-preserving big-city politician will admit
to being a die-hard liberal, when they will bend their sentences
into pretzels to avoid the phrase, Ammiano has emerged as a proud
New Deal big government do-gooder, a throwback to the days when
``liberal'' was a description, not an epithet.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, a 57-year-old former special education teacher and gay
stand-up comedian who bills himself as ``the Queen of Gay Comedy,''
could be the most powerful big-city liberal in the country. More
and more, people here are urging him to challenge the man who now
pulls the levers in San Francisco, Mayor Willie L. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's recent proposals read like a working man's wish list.
His ``living wage'' proposal would set a minimum salary of $11 an
hour plus benefits for city workers and employees of contractors
that do business with San Francisco, which would make the city's
minimum wage the highest in the country. His proposal to grant city
employees a year of paid parental leave, if adopted, would be
another national first. He is still trying to find a way to propose
a way around the state's ban on commercial rent controls so that,
he said, ``small mom-and-pop stores wouldn't be put out of business
by big rich chain stores.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems more amazing than the ideas themselves is that people
are taking them seriously. Of course, this is San Francisco. It may
be verboten for politicians in most places to acknowledge they are
left of center, but here it is practically a prerequisite for
office. Still, San Francisco's liberalism is generally practiced in
the dutiful way of people who attend church because they grew up
with it. Ammiano is an old-fashioned liberal, a fire and brimstone
preacher bent on changing the sinners' ways.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, after months of issuing denials reminiscent of President
George Bush's pledge of ``no new taxes,'' Ammiano has started
saying that he is ``looking into the possibility'' of challenging
the once omnipotent mayor, whose approval rating has slipped to 30
percent in the latest public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you keep hearing people say, `Do it,' and you keep seeing
`Run Tom Run' buttons everywhere you go, you start thinking about
it,'' Ammiano said recently from his office in the majestic
beaux-arts building that is City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, there's been a lot of what I call raging moderates on
the board,'' he added. ``I've had to go out on a limb on a lot of
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is giving him a free ride. Arguably his biggest success
to date is a 1996 ordinance that requires contractors who do
business with the city to provide the same benefits to employees'
domestic partners as to spouses. More recently, he succeeded in
convincing voters to change the way supervisors are elected _ from
citywide to districtwide elections. But his top priorities, like
his living-wage proposal, have yet to make it past his colleagues.
Last month the board voted to table the proposal until an
open-ended study could assess its costs, which Ammiano estimates at
about $25 million and critics put at more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   He blames a board beholden to the mayor, who has appointed six
members (due to vacancies). ``What it really reflects is a
disconnect,'' Ammiano said, ``between a liberal, good-government
electorate and the board.''
</P>
<P>
   But editorial writers are also having a ball satirizing his
loftier ideas. ``We should all help Tom fight his addiction,'' The
San Francisco Examiner wrote in a May 7 editorial headlined, ``I'm
Tom and I'm a big spender,'' which criticized his proposal for paid
parental leave.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano said that those who question how much his
pro-working-class proposals will cost never ask that question when
the city doles out tax breaks to corporations.
</P>
<P>
   No one questions his popularity _ his fans fill the weekly board
meetings, as though they were watching a show _ but he is still not
popular enough to become mayor, said Ken Garcia, a columnist for
The San Francisco Chronicle. ``The far left is still too left to
select the mayor of San Francisco,'' he wrote in a recent column,
``though he might have enough support (if others jump in the race)
to force our lord mayor into a runoff.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Ammiano is not so different from other members
of the board, although he speaks in a nasal squeak that can become
alarmingly shrill. He is not the only openly gay member of the
board, nor is he its only openly ``progressive'' member.
</P>
<P>
   But he is the one who consistently comes up with one radical
proposal after another. On Monday, he began a new practice of
moving the time and place of board meetings, from afternoons in a
hallowed chamber at City Hall to evenings at neighborhood community
centers. The change, he said, will give residents a chance to see
their representatives in action, and prepare them for the change to
districtwide elections next year.
</P>
<P>
   He is also the veteran politician on the board, though his own
elected experience began only nine years ago, when he was elected
to the San Francisco Board of Education, becoming president four
years later.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, veterans of the city's political slugfests say
Ammiano's ideas are rather naive. He himself says he has not
learned to compromise his dreams. ``Some things seem like they
might be a dream,'' he said. ``If you don't go forward, you'll
never know if they can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, who lost his longtime companion to AIDS, has a teen-age
daughter he helped conceive as a sperm donor. The son of a New York
City taxi driver, he grew up in Newark, attended Seton Hall
University and moved to San Francisco in 1963. He was one of the
first openly gay comedians when he began doing stand-up routines
over 20 years ago, and still performs on occasion. Last week, he
headlined a comedy show at the city's Queer Arts Festival, where he
poked fun at himself (''he could be his own first lady,'' he said)
and the mayor. Regarding plans for the new Bay Bridge, Ammiano said
Brown's attitude is ``everyone should walk across the water _ like
I do.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mayor is supposedly furious at Ammiano for considering a run
at his job after he endorsed Ammiano's bid for the board
presidency. Word has it that Brown's endorsement was part of a quid
pro quo designed to win an endorsement from Ammiano. Publicly,
however, Brown's response to Ammiano's possible challenge is
polite, even respectful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supervisor Ammiano is a popular, well-respected member of the
family of San Francisco's elected officials,'' said P.J. Johnston,
the mayor's campaign spokesman. ``Until he says otherwise, we'll
take him at his word that he is not running. If he does, hey, it's
an open election. It's open to all comers.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other declared candidate for mayor, Clint Reilly, a
long-time political consultant, said an Ammiano run would hurt
Willie Brown more than it would hurt him. Both, said, share the
same constituencies _ labor unions, gays and lesbians and liberals.
``I think Tom is a hard-working, honest man,'' said Reilly, who
describes himself as a moderate Democrat. ``But the fiscal
consequences of many of Tom's politically correct proposals have
alarmed many people who are worried about the city's already
bloated government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tom is a hard-working, honest man,'' said Reilly, who
describes himself as a moderate Democrat. ``But the fiscal
consequences of many of Tom's politically correct proposals have
alarmed many people who are worried about the city's bloated
government, which already has more city workers than any other
major city in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano says he is trying to keep the working and middle classes
from fleeing a city that has become the most expensive in the
country. ``Affordable housing is our No. 1 issue,'' he said. ``The
African-American population in this city is already being
decimated.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked like the weight of the world was on his shoulders, and
at that moment it most certainly was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
