<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-     06-16 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBRACING CLINTON AT ARM'S LENGTH, GORE FORMALLY BEGINS RUN FOR
PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)   (With GORE-BIOBOX) 
(nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTHAGE, Tenn. _ Against a backdrop of small-town America, Vice
President Al Gore took his first formal step out of President
Clinton's shadow Wednesday, announcing his quest for the presidency
and pledging to ``bring a new wave of fundamental change to this
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that wave of change, he made clear both in his speech
and in earlier remarks about Clinton's impeachment, would be a
fresh moral start in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you entrust me with the presidency, I will marshal its
authority, its resources and its moral leadership to fight for
America's family,'' he said, with his own family, including his
87-year-old mother and his pregnant 25-year-old daughter, creating
a tableau behind him. ``I will take my own values of faith and
family to the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   While trying to distance himself, however, Gore at the same time
embraced all the issues that form the bedrock of Clinton's domestic
agenda. He said he wants to move more people off welfare, put more
police on the streets, expand the Family and Medical Leave Act,
make college more affordable, provide universal pre-school, protect
Social Security, help the elderly pay for prescription drugs and
raise the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have schools that instill the values and character
we need in the next generation,'' he said, saying every school in
America should be drug-free and gun-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families deserve refuge from a culture of violence and
mayhem,'' he said. ``I will work to give parents the ability to
protect their children from the marketing of cruelty and
degradation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech was marred for several minutes by a small band of
protesters who shouted that the administration was not doing enough
to get AIDS drugs to Africa. The protesters quieted down after
several Gore supporters shouted back to drown them out.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, 51, who spent his boyhood summers on a family farm near
here, spoke in front of the bunting-draped, red brick Smith County
courthouse, where he has declared his candidacy for various offices
seven times before, first for Congress in 1976, then the Senate,
and in 1987, for president.
</P>
<P>
   In that announcement speech 12 years ago, he said he was
restless, and he said so again Wednesday _ restless to enact
specific legislation that at once expands Clinton's agenda but
departs from his presidency in being guided by moral constancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our own lives we must master if we are to have the moral
authority to guide our children,'' he said. ``No policy proposal
can change a culture that does not place family life at the top of
our hierarchy of values, where it belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   If he was distancing himself from Clinton on the character
issue, Gore also signaled to reporters earlier that he might begin
to distance himself on policy matters as well. In fact he said he
had had many such disagreements with Clinton in the past, but
preferred to debate them in private.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to reveal what he and the president had disagreed
on, but he told reports Tuesday in Tennessee, ``Everything changes
when I become a candidate because I'll be describing my own vision
of the future. If that happens to be different in some respects
from what the administration wants, then I think that is
understandable.''
</P>
<P>
   Picking up on a theme espoused by his wife, Tipper, he said he
wanted health care plans to cover mental illness just as they cover
physical illness. He said he wanted to make it easier for the
elderly to receive health care in their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of Gore's speech was that by virtue of his
experience, he was the candidate most prepared to lead the country
and to maintain the record-breaking economic expansion of the last
several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to keep our prosperity going, and I know how to do
it,'' he asserted, without elaboration but with one of several digs
at Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican front-runner, and
Bush's platform of ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do it the right way,'' Gore said, ``not by letting
people fend for themselves, or hoping for crumbs of compassion, but
by giving people the skills and knowledge to succeed in their own
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore emphasized his experience in foreign policy in a world he
called ``complex and volatile,'' and said, ``You deserve a leader
who has been tested in it.''
</P>
<P>
   He also spoke a few sentences in Spanish, directly competing
with Bush, who is fluent in Spanish, in his appeal to Hispanic
voters, who make up an important swing constituency.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore made a straightforward declaration of support for
abortion rights, with a veiled reference to Bush's more ambiguous
comments. ``Some try to duck the issue of choice,'' he said. ``Not
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He also set up a contrast with Bush over the emotional issue of
access to guns. ``While some want to pass new protections for gun
manufacturers, to shield them from lawsuits,'' Gore said, ``I will
work to get guns off the streets, out of the schools and away from
children and criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25-minute speech was notable for its specificity across a
range of issues, and its scant mention of Clinton. Gore said on
Tuesday that his announcement speech was his chance to step out on
his own, and he made that evident in his repeated emphasis on moral
leadership Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But he was most explicit when speaking to reporters the night
before, when he landed in Tennessee. He talked about ``that awful
year we went through,'' referring to the yearlong impeachment
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was most upsetting about it,'' Gore told reporters, was
``the wasted time. I'm even more anxious to move forward swiftly to
make up for that waste of time. We shouldn't have had to go through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore has said _ and repeated Wednesday night in a taped
interview on the ABC News program ``20/20'' _ that Clinton's
behavior was inexcusable, he had not said publicly before that he
was upset over the time that was squandered. During the impeachment
scandal, Gore stood loyally behind the president and declined to
criticize him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton, who left Wednesday for a weeklong trip to Europe,
called Gore in the morning to wish him luck before the speech and
called him again after he saw it on television. Gore was out
shaking hands and Clinton left a message, saying ``Great job, Al.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's formal declaration, of surprise to no one, is unusually
early in the campaign season for an incumbent vice president. But
he was driven by competitive pressures from Bush, and his speech
Wednesday had the feel of a general election campaign, even though
Gore still faces a primary fight for the Democratic nomination from
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
