<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-WEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL STATEMENTS SHOW HOUSE LEADERS MISSED THE BOAT ON BULL
MARKET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Fla., Ill., Mo., Ga., Calif.)  By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While many of their constituents have enriched
themselves by investing in the booming stock market, several of the
House's most powerful members have missed out entirely on the
decade's bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the majority leader, and Rep. Bill
C.W. Young of Florida, the Appropriations Committee chairman, have
invested virtually none of their annual salaries in stocks, bonds
or mutual funds, according to their 1998 financial disclosure
statements, which were made public Wednesday. Armey earns $151,800
a year and Young's salary is $136,700.
</P>
<P>
   The minority leader, Dick Gephardt of Missouri, listed only one
investment on his financial disclosure statement: a growth and
income mutual fund that he estimated was worth $1,001 to $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert also chose to invest almost nothing in
the stock market. His assets are in real estate. Hastert listed his
half interest in the ``opera house'' building in Plainfield, Ill.
The building once housed a theater and his father's restaurant. He
valued it at $100,001 to $250,000. He also valued his 270-acre farm
in Shipman, Ill., at $100,001 to $250,000, and he said the farm
produced income of $15,001 to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip, the House's
third-ranking Republican, may have surprised the House clerk when
he initially reported that his wife, Christine, owned Exxon stock
valued in excess of $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   It was an error, which DeLay corrected in an amended statement
10 days later. DeLay reported that the Exxon stock, which he owned
jointly with his wife, was worth $50,000 to $100,000. They sold the
stock last year.
</P>
<P>
   A review Wednesday of nearly 300 financial disclosure statements
shows that the House's reputation as the poorer cousin of the
Senate may be deserved.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of members of Congress, like Bob Barr of Georgia and
Alcee L. Hastings of Florida, disclosed that their debts exceeded
their assets. Hastings, a Democrat, owes legal fees of at least
$2.2 million to several lawyers who represented him a decade ago
when he was removed from the federal bench after an impeachment
trial in which the Senate convicted him of making false statements
and seeking a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, a Republican, listed credit card debts of $15,001 to
$50,000 on his statement. A board member of the National Rifle
Association, Barr said he also went on four trips that were paid
for by the organization last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1970s, members of Congress and other federal
officials have been required to file financial disclosure
statements to show that they do not have holdings that pose a
conflict of interest with their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But the statements provide the public with only a general
understanding of an official's financial situation because the
ethics rules allow a broad range of their assets and income, rather
than precise numbers. The Senate's disclosure statements were made
public last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Not all House members opted out of the stock market. Many
members showed they hold a wide array of investments, including
mutual funds, bonds and individual stocks. Some members traded
heavily, and often, in Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Turner, D-Texas, disclosed that he had four investments
worth $250,001 to $500,000. In an attachment to his statement, he
included nearly 800 pages that listed hundreds of stock trades made
by his wife, who made multiple transactions on many days.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Sanchez, D-Calif., showed that she and her husband
traded many securities in Internet companies, sometimes on the same
days. Among the stocks she and her husband held jointly last year
were Egghead.com, Infoseek, PSINet Inc., Geocities and E-Trade
Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York area, one representative who is considering a
run for the Senate, Rick Lazio, a Republican, was an active trader
of securities. He traded both stocks and options in a wide range of
companies, including Nike, Compaq and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
