<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-16 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DEFENDING THE STATUS QUO 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state of Texas is not big on protecting the rights of the
accused. And when it comes to providing lawyers for indigent
criminal defendants, it is one of the most backward states in the
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   _It is not uncommon for indigent defendants, some of whom are
innocent, to languish in jail for months before a lawyer is
appointed to represent them. Many Texas counties have no procedure
for the appointment of counsel before an indictment is returned.
</P>
<P>
   _A court-appointed lawyer in Brownsville who met his client for
the first time while a jury was being selected failed to present
evidence during the trial that the man was incarcerated at the time
he was supposed to have raped a child. The man was convicted,
sentenced to life in prison and served five years before a federal
judge ordered him released.
</P>
<P>
   _A severely mentally ill man accused of punching his grandfather
in the arm spent four years in jail awaiting trial in Hidalgo
County.
</P>
<P>
   _A man convicted of murder spent 10 harrowing years on death row
before a volunteer attorney investigated his alibi and won his
release.
</P>
<P>
   The problems have grown so horrible that both houses of the
state legislature have unanimously passed a bill that would make
modest improvements in the way that counsel is provided for
indigent defendants. The emphasis here is on the word modest.
Michael Sharlot, dean of the University of Texas Law School, said
the bill was designed to ``insure that minimal constitutional
requirements are met.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the bill would require that an indigent defendant
be assigned a lawyer within 20 days after a request for counsel.
Twenty days. Most jurisdictions in the United States provide a
lawyer within 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   But for some folks in Texas the idea of providing even minimal
constitutional protections for poor defendants is going a step too
far. And one of those folks appears to be that beacon of
compassionate conservatism _ you've heard of him _ George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   This bill, modest almost to the point of embarrassment, will
become law if Governor Bush does not veto it before Sunday. He
doesn't have to sign it. All he has to do is refrain from vetoing
it. But even though the bill, sponsored by State Senator Rodney
Ellis of Houston, has unanimously passed the Republican-controlled
Senate and the Democratic-controlled House of Representatives, the
word in Austin is that Bush will veto it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we hear,'' said a spokesman for Ellis, a Democrat.
Republican sources in the state capital agreed. A Republican
legislative leader, who asked not to be quoted by name, said, ``All
signs point to a veto.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason is not much of a secret in Texas. A headline in The
Houston Chronicle on June 2 said: ``Judges let Bush know they want
bill vetoed.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges are at the core of the problem. In Texas, the lawyers
who ultimately represent the indigent are nearly always assigned by
local judges, and the judges determine their fees. Cronyism, not
competence, drives the process. Lackeys, incompetents and drunks
are among the many feeding at this trough.
</P>
<P>
   Judges in Texas are elected, and it is clear that many are
steering appointments in indigent cases to lawyers who have
contributed to their campaigns. The system is riddled with ethical
conflicts. The lawyers are too often on the side of the judges who
are their benefactors rather than the defendants they are supposed
to be representing.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis' bill would allow counties to consider other procedures
for the appointment of counsel to the indigent. The entire
legislature has signed on to that approach. But the judges standing
astride their vast patronage system are angry at this threat of
change. And they've voiced their anger to the man they hope will be
their benefactor, the governor who would be president.
</P>
<P>
   In short, a powerful special interest has spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Wesevich, a lawyer who worked for several years with
indigent defendants in Texas, was dismayed at the thought that
Senator Ellis' bill might not become law. ``This reform is so
desperately needed,'' he said, ``and it is so modest, that it would
be a crying shame if the governor vetoed this legislation. I'm
saddened to hear that it might happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
