<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MASSACRE-0617-     06-16 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MASSACRE-0617-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 4th graf, removes extra 'act of'; adds '...before
opening fire: ...'; in 26th graf, adds word 'fell' to read '...
fell upon him dead and ... '
 &HT;    REMAINS OF SERB REVENGE SHOW METICULOUS BRUTALITY
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KORENICA, Kosovo _ At 68, Mark Berishe, was old enough to be
spared.
</P>
<P>
   Serb troops had told him to leave his village, Korenica, and
drive to safety on a tractor with the women and children. But, he
did not know how. ``Fine,'' they said. ``Since you can't drive a
tractor, go inside with the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Against a wall in a bedroom of his nephew's luxurious country
house, he tried pleading for mercy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't you humans like we are? Why are you killing us like
this? Don't you have children, too?'' Berishe asked, crossing
himself in a final act of Roman Catholic faith. A Serb soldier gave
him his answer before opening fire: ``It's too late for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Berishe's skull, charred and cracked, sits amid rubble in
the corner of the bedroom with four other burned corpses. Nothing
but his silver tooth is recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor, hearing the account of Berishe's death from a nephew
who crawled from under the bodies to survive for a day, showed the
house to human rights workers and a few journalists Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With Serb soldiers now out of the region under the agreement
that ended the 78-day NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia, the
veil is being lifted off one of the worst atrocities from the Serb
effort to drive ethnic Albanians out of Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   The killing took place April 27, apparently sparked by a
guerilla attack that left five Serb police dead a few days earlier.
The Serb revenge was sweeping, meticulous and grotesquely brutal.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights workers estimate that at least 100 and possibly 300
ethnic Albanians died. Along a 5-mile stretch of road where they
killing was the thickest, the mushy, putrid, stench of corpses
rises from loose piles of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Meja, near Berishe's home, Serbs separated men
from a caravan of Kosovar Albanian refugees seeking safety over the
border in Albania. The Serbs apparently had trouble disposing of
all the victims they shot in a small field by the road.
</P>
<P>
   A rotting body, cut open and clad in a blue suit, lies in the
shrubs of a small ravine. A leg lies nearby, covered by pants and a
black shoe. Small personal items lie charred on the ground,
obviously the non-flammable remnants of a small fire. A Sharp Water
Sports watch is partly melted, but still ticks.
</P>
<P>
   The ravine, the small path and the fence match the description
given by the refugees who survived and are now in Albania. With the
Serbs leaving, the atrocities reported from afar are now being
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than we knew about,'' said Human Rights Watch's
Joanne Mariner. ``It's systematic. There were a lot of people
involved and it wasn't just some aberration that people were
killed. They pretty much had free reign to terrorize.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gypsy in a nearby town, 30-year-old Kurtesh Morini, said he
was forced by the Serbs to help dispose of bodies, as Gypsies are
often pressed into cleaning duties here. He said that often Serbs
took photographs and videotapes of their victims and recorded their
identities on lists and toe tags.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very organized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the killings of April 27 seemed to tax even the Serb
efficiency. ``There is no list for Korenica,'' Morini said.
</P>
<P>
   The stately homes of Korenica are about a mile from Meja, and
two miles east of Djakovica. It was a neighborhood of some 700
people and most were Catholic Albanians, unlike the rest of the
province which is largely Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   The homes in fertile hills are now abandoned and burned, but it
is clear that they once looked like a postcard version of pastoral
Europe. They had white walls and Spanish tile roofs. Cherry trees
and yellow wildflowers grow in the lawns and many homes have sheds
for horses, cattle and chickens that now wander astray.
</P>
<P>
   Graffiti in English and Serbo-Croation is left behind by
withdrawing Serb troops. It screams obscenities at NATO and
American President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Dedaj, a 38-year-old ethnic Albanian, came back from his
mountain hideout four days ago and has gone from house to house. He
found the charred bodies of eight of his neighbors, including an
aunt and a godfather.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that a few days before the Serb attack, Serb police
who live in the neighborhood had assured residents that they would
not face revenge for the policemen's deaths. Stay in your houses
and you will be alright, they told them.
</P>
<P>
   But, by this time, a month after NATO had started bombing and
the Serbs had stepped up their terror, there were few other
Albanians in the area. Perhaps that is why Korenica became a
target.
</P>
<P>
   Dedaj said that, the day before the Serb attack, seven buses of
Serb military, police and paramilitary troops arrived at a nearby
school. At 7:30 the next morning, they split into groups and fanned
out. Pairs of troops were stationed along the roads.
</P>
<P>
   Many wore sleeveless military shirts with red bandanas on their
arms. Some wore masks. He took his family to the top of the hill
and watched the Serbs approach the homes.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until later that night, though, that he heard what
happened to Mark Berishe. He heard it from Daniel Berishe, the
owner of the three-story, five-bedroom house and once a well-known
Kosovar soccer player.
</P>
<P>
   Astoundingly, Daniel, 40, was in the bedroom but only shot in
the leg. The other men fell upon him dead and he stayed still while
the Serbs laid blankets over the bodies and set them on fire.
</P>
<P>
   When the Serbs left, he escaped. With burns on his arms, he
hustled into the mountains and told the story to Dedaj. The next
morning, Serbs would find and insist on taking him away for medical
treatment. Dedaj found Daniel Berishe's body by the road a day
after that.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Dedaj walked the human rights workers around the
neighborhood. Lying in the entranceway of a house near Berishe's
are the charred remains of Dedaj's aunt, Mire Paloka.
</P>
<P>
   Her skull is cracked open exposing her burned brain. Below that
is just a twisted spine and one leg. But, Dedaj said he found her
burned rings and watch here and holds them in a dirty plastic bag.
He said his uncle's body was here, but has been taken, he's not
sure how.
</P>
<P>
   In another home, the jumbled vertebrae of an 80-year-old man lie
in a charred pile. And in another home, a few bones remain from two
men who have been buried.
</P>
<P>
   There is little property in the homes, no furniture or
appliances. Most of the interiors are burned. Occasionally, a plate
or tiny cup for sipping Turkish coffee can be seen among the
shattered roof tiles.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the items in the homes and sheds outside seem to have
been carefully dismantled or removed.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving families have fled to Europe or Albania. Dedaj's
wife and five children are in Albania. A short, muscular farmer
with chiseled features, Dedaj said he cried at the sight of his
neighbors and relatives, but he would like to go to Europe, make
some money and rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we can never be satisfied with our lives. But what
can we do?'' he said. ``The living people must go on living.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
