<SLUG> BC-RETIREE-HAVEN:NICARAGUA-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. RETIREES FLOCK TO NEW RETIREMENT HAVEN _ NICARAGUA
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``f''
financial, ``i'' international, ``l'' lifestyle, and ``t'' travel
files.)
 By RICARDO CASTILLO 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MANAGUA, Nicaragua _ For Brad Booth, a former sales manager in
the United States, one factor outweighed all others in his decision
to retire in Nicaragua: price. It was not just the low cost of
living in general, as attractive here as it is in other parts of
the developing world, but the relatively cheap real estate. His eye
settled on one particular piece of property on the Pacific coast
that reminded him of San Clemente, California, where he lived for
the past 20 years.
 &HT;    ``I was really surprised, because I owned land in Roatan
(Honduras and in Belize.) But here you can buy land for much less
than in other Central American countries,'' says Booth, 58, as he
rests in a hammock on the terrace of his home. ``The real estate
market here reminds me of what it was like in Costa Rica 20 years
ago.''
 &HT;    Booth bought land in 1997 in La Boquita, a beach area about 45
minutes southeast of Managua, for US$18,000. Construction of his
2,000 square-feet home with an ocean view cost $50,000. ``In Costa
Rica it would have set me back some $225,000. And in California, no
less than a million,'' he says.
 &HT;    According to International Living, an organization that hunts
good real estate deals worldwide for its members, a beachfront
property on Nicaragua's Pacific coast can go as high as $25,000.
Something comparable can cost three times more in Belize, four
times more in Honduras, and five times in Costa Rica. In the U.S.,
a similar piece of land could go for anywhere between 10 and 50
times more. Fleeing chaos and cold. Investors who have followed the
explosive growth of real estate speculation in Central America _
which began in Costa Rica in the 1970s _ saw it happen in Belize in
1985 and later in Honduras at the beginning of the 1990s. The
opportunities in Nicaragua, they say, are just beginning.
 &HT;    Although many of the foreign retirees are elderly, more and more
people between the ages of 40 and 50 arrive every day. These
newcomers are in good shape and are looking for adventure: They buy
properties near volcanoes and next to rivers, lakes and beaches,
where they can pursue their favorite sport or just enjoy the fresh
air. Many others are fleeing the chaos and cold weather of large
U.S. metropolises. An estimated 6,000 retirees in Nicaragua are
from the U.S. and Canada, compared with about 50,000 in Costa Rica,
some 15,000 in Panama and 5,000 in Belize.
 &HT;    ``These markets take years to mature, which is when the great
flow of money arrives, generally from retirees with means,'' says
Robert Fordi, who believes the best opportunities here are near the
Pacific Ocean and on Lake Nicaragua, one of the 10 largest in the
world. Real estate growth in Nicaragua ``started off slowly in
1997,'' he says. ``But the activity and interest has become more
intense over the past few months.''
 &HT;    Fordi looks for investment opportunities in real estate and
arranges trips through International Living. Groups of 15 people or
so travel with him to make contact with local real estate agents,
politicians, accountants and lawyers. He says real estate markets
see real growth when local governments enact policies to attract
foreign capital. In Nicaragua's case, real estate prices and the
number of transactions began to increase in 1997, after the
government approved laws and programs to entice foreign retirees. A
similar policy was highly successful in Costa Rica in the 1980s.
 &HT;    Nicaraguan law offers tax breaks and investment incentives.
Those who want to take advantage of the program must be older than
45 and have monthly incomes of at least $400, plus another $100
monthly for each additional person in their household. Retirees pay
no taxes on their foreign income and can bring as much as $10,000
worth of household goods, as well as a car, duty free.
 &HT;    ``The first investors and retirees started arriving,'' as soon
as the law went on the books, says Alvaro Saballos, partner in
Snider Realty, a Managua real estate agency founded in Costa Rica
during that country's real estate boom. The Nicaraguan-born
Saballos returned to his native country in 1995 when his
brother-in-law, Steve Snider, proposed starting a similar real
estate enterprise in Nicaragua. Snider had sold plenty of
properties to International Living investors, and began to sound
them out about Nicaragua in 1996.
 &HT;    ``Steve showed up with two clients who had already bought from
him and who had made money in Costa Rica. The government there had
done away with incentives for foreign retirees, while in Nicaragua
the program was just getting under way,'' Seballos says. ``When we
began, we averaged about one customer every two months, but later
it grew to one a week. Since February, the number has really picked
up. Most of our clients come from the U.S., but we have some
Canadians and Europeans as well.''
 &HT;    Nicaragua's efforts to attract foreign retirees were made
somewhat more difficult than other neighboring countries because of
its history of violence. ``My husband and I had a layover here in
1992 on our way to Costa Rica, and through the airplane's window we
saw the remnants of bullet-ridden helicopters. We said to ourselves
that we would never come to this place,'' says Diane Jackson, a
U.S. retiree. At the time, Jackson was searching for a place to
retire and had looked in Venezuela, the Dominican Republic and
Puerto Rico.
 &HT;    Her impression of Nicaragua changed when she returned in 1994 as
part of a business and academic mission between Pittsburgh and
Managua. ``The warmth of the people and the price of land really
attracted us, and we realized that things were not really as they
had seemed,'' she says. ``On the contrary, there was a lot of
opportunity because so much needed to be done.'' In the end,
Jackson and her husband were one of the first couples to take
advantage of the fiscal incentives. They moved here in 1996.
 &HT;    Jackson says that since her arrival she has seen growing numbers
of foreigners looking to buy property, not just as investments, but
as places to live. Purchasing land in Nicaragua can be an arduous
process, though. Diplomats here recommend that investors research
potential purchases carefully. Many have two titles the original
one and another issued during the Sandinista era.
 &HT;    Many times, buyers have to negotiate directly with the property
owner and pay in cash. Also, it is difficult to compare prices,
because the market is so new. Municipal governments have few
transaction records and scant information about the value of
properties.
 &HT;    ``One of the things that concerned me the most when I bought was
whether the title was valid or not,'' says Jackson. ``It's one of
the biggest risks, but fortunately I don't know anyone who has had
a bad experience.''
 &HT;    Most investors use lawyers recommended by their native countries
embassies or by agents like Snider Realty. ``Part of the work we do
is investigating whether the properties have questionable titles,''
says Seballos. ``On several occasions we have canceled a
transaction on the verge of closing because we found problems. For
us, the risk is not worth it. It's more important that things work
out properly than to be involved in a legal nightmare.''
 &HT;    Investors appear willing to run those risks to buy, though not
necessarily to build. Several local land owners say that most of
their property has been sold. ``My sales have shot up since
February,'' says Juan Sequeira, owner of the San Juan neighborhood
just outside Granada, Nicaragua's oldest colonial city, on Lake
Nicaragua. ``I've sold land to Canadians, Americans, Spaniards,
Austrians, though none yet show signs of starting construction. I
think they're waiting for market values to rise.''
 &HT;    Erwin Gonzalez, owner of the Pacific Marlin project, says he has
sold 75 percent of his plots to foreigners. He has sunk almost $1
million into infrastructure improvements and has sold half a
million dollars in land. The properties, on the side of a mountain
near San Juan del Sur bay, go for an average of $30,000 each.
 &HT;    ``These kinds of properties cost at least $125,000 in Costa
Rica. That's why we are seeing more Costa Rican clients, because
they recognize an opportunity when they see it,'' he says. ``They
lived through it.''
 &HT;     
