<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-BAXTER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore looking to South for jump start
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was not for family ties alone that Vice President
Al Gore came back to Carthage, Tenn., for the official start of his
presidential campaign Wednesday. Gore needs the South, and he has a
lot of ground to make up.
</P>
<P>
   The political algebra by which Gore might expect to win the next
election is different from 1992 and 1996, and even more heavily
weighted toward the West Coast and Northeast. But the vice
president can't continue to trail by the gaping margins measured
recently in polls in several Southern states and hope to win a
national race.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Gore pointed to Democratic victories last year
in Georgia, Alabama, South Carolina and Kentucky as evidence he can
compete in his home region _ even against an opponent who drops the
g's at the end of his words as easily as Texas Gov. George Bush.
``The new coalition in the South is interested in continuing our
economic prosperity, not going back to the failed approach that
almost wrecked our economy in the past,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the same kind of approach that I took for 16
years as a candidate in Tennessee is resonant not only in the South
but all over the country. I think there's less regionalism today
than there was in times past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   African-American voters were an important component of the 1998
Democratic victories Gore spoke of, and for them, a major priority
is going to be the battle over who is counted _ and how _ in the
census that will determine how the political map is drawn for the
next decade. The vice president pledged he will be unwavering in
his support for statistical sampling, an issue over which the
Clinton administration and the Republican Congress are locked in
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Experts serving the past three administrations concluded that
the ``old approach of pretending that you can put your index finger
on the nose of every citizen and get an accurate count in a nation
of 250 million'' was outdated, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now all of a sudden, the Republican majority in the
Congress, panicked that they are going to lose six seats and more,
have been trying to go to a system which they know very well will
result in an undercounting of blacks and Hispanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Important as minority votes are to his prospects in the region _
and if Bush is the Republican nominee, Hispanic support will be
much harder to lock down _ Gore's best hope, as he indicated, lies
in connecting with those issues that resonate across region and
race.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to sum up his environmental priorities, Gore framed a
pretty complicated answer in terms of Atlanta's sprawl problem and
praised Gov. Roy Barnes for pointing the way ``to how we can untie
the knots that many communities have felt they're tied into, and
give people more time with their children and cut down on traffic
jams.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gore pointed out, however, there were more than 200
anti-sprawl referendums across the country last year, and most of
them passed.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same could be said about a number of the issues the
vice president touched on in this session: school violence,
education standards, care for the elderly, extending the economic
boom times.
</P>
<P>
   These issues play about the same in Gwinnett County as they do
in San Diego. If he is to begin erasing the double-digit advantage
his potential Republican rivals currently enjoy in the polls, Gore
has to make significant inroads in both locations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
