<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House rejects bill to keep violent, sexual material from youth
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House votes on new gun control laws today after
Democrats and conservative Republicans rejected legislation
Wednesday that would have jailed those who sold explicitly violent
or sexual material to juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation on violent and obscene material, sponsored by
Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) as an amendment to a
juvenile crime bill, was the centerpiece of Republican plans to fix
the ``culture of violence'' in America in the wake of shootings in
Littleton, Colo., and Conyers, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal failed 146 to 282, with 127 Republicans voting no.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were misled and disinclined to oppose the powerful
entertainment industry,'' said Hyde. ``I'm sorry to see that
happen. It was a serious attempt to address the cultural
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the House will begin debate on a dozen gun control
proposals, both for and against. The key votes will be on competing
legislation to regulate criminal background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Minority leader Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.) said up to 45 Democrats
will vote against a strict provision that would allow gun dealers
three days to conduct the checks and require all sellers, even
unlicensed ones, to perform background checks on buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said Democrats would need at least 51 Republicans to
pass the measure to be offered by Rep. Carolyn McCarthy (D-N.Y.),
whose husband was slain by a gunman in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up against the best lobby in town,'' Gephardt said.
``This is a tough issue to win.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton sent a letter to 46 GOP lawmakers who
supported the Brady handgun control act of 1993, urging them to
support closing the so-called gun show loophole. Clinton and Vice
President Gore also called members, Gephardt said, but the outreach
to Republicans was too late for some.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Sensenbrenner (R-Wis.), one of the original GOP
sponsors of the Brady bill, said he was on the phone with Attorney
General Janet Reno and other administration officials every day
during that debate. But not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if they are really interested in passing a bill,''
said Sensenbrenner, who said he remains undecided on which gun show
proposal to support. ``I'm not interested in helping them score
political points.''
</P>
<P>
   In a change in tactics, some strongly pro-gun lawmakers such as
Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) said Wednesday they were prepared to support
a much weaker provision targeting gun shows, sponsored by Rep. John
Dingell (D-Mich.), a former NRA board member, and backed by the
NRA.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he and other conservatives were worried that if
Dingell's measure did not pass, the House would adopt more
restrictive measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much better than the alternatives,'' said Barr, an NRA
board member who has said he would back no new gun control
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Majority whip Tom DeLay (R-Texas), whose ability to secure votes
is widely respected, was also trying to rally Republicans behind
Dingell's proposal so that stricter measures would not pass.
</P>
<P>
   After the intensity surrounding a similar debate in the Senate
four weeks ago, Wednesday's House debate was surprisingly low-key.
</P>
<P>
   Members on both sides of the aisle invoked the deaths at
Columbine High School and the shooting in Conyers, but generally
displayed little enthusiasm or passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to report that Conyers is doing just fine without
our help,'' said Linder, whose district includes Conyers. ``We need
to focus on other things than guns, and we need to enforce the gun
laws that are on the books and not continue to take advantage of
personal tragedy to promote a political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde predicted that his amendment dealing with the so-called
culture of violence would be a close vote, but it became clear that
members of his own party were against the idea; member after member
rose to oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my responsibility as a parent to make sure my children
are not watching inappropriate material,'' said Rep. James Rogan
(R-Calif.). ``It's not the responsibility of Congress or
Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr, another Judiciary Committee member, also spoke against
Hyde's amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the parents who have the ultimate control over what our
children see, hear and do,'' said Barr. ``No amount of legislation
we can pass will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
