A8262 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-NOTES17-COX     06-16 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Her tribal clout's showing
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the exhibit hall of the Southern Baptist
Convention, Linda Muse, a missionary to Ecuador, greeted people
Wednesday and offered to share information about international
missions.
</P>
<P>
   Muse wore a bright blue skirt, embroidered blouse and colorful
woven belt, with eight strands of gold beads around her neck. The
outfit, she said, was traditional garb of the Otovalo Indians in
Ecuador, ``except for the tennis shoes,'' she said, looking down at
her neat white Keds. ``They're for comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Muse said the number of strands of beads worn by Otovalo women
indicates their status. Hers, she said, would show that she is
``not too rich.'' Muse and her husband operate a telephone
counseling ministry on the coast of Ecuador that draws about 14,000
contacts a month.
</P>
<P>
   Double headers: Toys or stress relief?
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Kenneth Tan of the North American Mission Board handed
out foam baseballs. For the kids, he said, they were toys. He
encouraged adults to squeeze them for stress relief. ``We want
people to step up to the plate and be involved,'' Tan said.
Meanwhile, children lined up 20 deep waiting for a turn at an
electronic batting cage. Augustine Hui, 8, of New York had been
through the line seven times. ``I only got a home run once,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstore proves popular diversion
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular parts of the Southern Baptist Convention
was its 12,000-square-foot bookstore set up on the floor of the
Georgia Dome with $750,000 in inventory and 18 cashier lines. Among
the most popular items were books by convention speakers, T-shirts
and boxed cards, said David Pigg, store manager.
</P>
<P>
   `Curse Free TV' sanitizes boob tube
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen people stood around a television as Jonas
Robertson demonstrated ``Curse Free TV.'' A box on the top reads
closed captions and substitutes innocent words for 100 words deemed
inappropriate. Other devises, Robertson said, replace naughty words
with words of similar connotation. ``If someone says, `I'm going to
kick you in the rear,' word association tells you what the word
really was,'' he said. His device substitutes ``toe'' for the word
meaning posterior. ``For one really awful expletive, we use the
word `clown,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Call us Southern, conventioneers say
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Southern Baptists rejected a proposal to take
a straw poll on whether to change the name of their group to the
International Baptist Convention. They also turned down an
amendment to poll on the proposed name Scriptural Baptist
Convention, to maintain the SBC initials. Joked one observer, ``The
Southern Baptists just voted not to be scriptural.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
