<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLORIA-TREVI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR IN MEXICO SOUGHT FOR QUESTIONING IN SEX CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW DOWNIE 
and JAMES PINKERTON 
 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Prancing provocatively around the stage in her
combat boots, ripped tights and colorful tops, Gloria Trevi was
known as Mexico's Madonna _ young, beautiful, spontaneous and
uncompromising.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s she was a huge success. Her records sold
millions, her films were box-office hits here, and her risque
calendars became collectors items.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, she was regarded by some artists and writers here
almost as a poster girl for Mexico's popular culture. Essayist
Carlos Monsivais described her as ``the serpent in the Garden of
Eden dressed in a thong.'' Historian Elena Poniatowska called her
``a living work of art.`` Trevi's lover was her manager, Sergio
Andrade.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 10 years since her daring stage presence took this
staunchly conservative nation by storm, she has vanished and is
wanted by police for questioning on allegations about the kidnap
and sexual abuse of a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Texas' Rio Grande Valley said Wednesday that Trevi _
whose real name is Gloria de los Angeles Trevino _ has been seen in
recent months at The Club at Cimmeron, an exclusive golf resort
near Mission, Texas, where many Mexican families have bought second
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal broke in March when the parents of the teen, Karina
Yapor of Chihuahua state, accused Trevi and Andrade of corrupting
the teen-ager after Andrade took her under his wing.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of Andrade's skill as a star-maker in Mexico, Yapor's
parents had given their consent for their daughter to join his
talent-development program. But they became concerned when she
stopped calling home. Then, they received a telephone call from
Spain telling them that their daughter had abandoned an infant son
in a Madrid orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities suspect that Andrade may have fathered the
baby and want to question him about that and allegations that he
and Trevi had lured other young women into sex with the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about the couple's exploits had run through the industry
for some time, but they were not taken seriously until Andrade's
first wife wrote a book about her five years with him and Trevi.
</P>
<P>
   Aline Hernandez, 23, whom Andrade invited to join his stable of
singers when she was just 13, accused Andrade of trying to
brainwash her, starving her and forcing her to have sex before they
were married when she was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a psycopath who gets hold of girls as young as 12 and
dominates them,'' she said in an interview. ``He does whatever he
wants with girls. He has a harem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez published her book last year and asked the police to
investigate Andrade's conduct. Trevi denied the accusations. There
was no comment from Andrade, and little action was taken here until
the Spanish authorities became involved earlier this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Mexico have been scouring the country, seeking not
only Trevi and Andrade but also other young women whom they fear
may have been abused by the couple.
</P>
<P>
   Mission police said Wednesday they were contacted Monday by a
correspondent for the El Manana newspaper in Reynosa, Mexico, who
told them a young woman had come to their McAllen, Texas, office
and claimed she had been raped by Andrade in California nine years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Raul Gonzalez said he contacted the woman, now 25, who
told him she was sexually assaulted in a hotel in Glendale, Calif.,
when she was 15 or 16 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was supposed to go and record a song, and when she was in
a hotel the suspect (Andrade) came into the room and raped her,''
the detective said, adding she wanted to file charges against
Andrade and Trevi.
</P>
<P>
   ``She claims that she (Trevi) was the one who lured her into the
business ... and that's why she is also responsible for what
happened to her,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his department's brief investigation into the alleged
assault was closed after learning the six-year statute of
limitations on the crime in California has expired.
</P>
<P>
   Searches at homes owned by the couple in at least three Mexican
states provided no clues about the pair's whereabouts, and with no
other leads, Mexican police launched a media campaign aimed at
tracking them down.
</P>
<P>
   They put up ``wanted'' posters across Mexico, opened telephone
hot lines in Chihuahua and Mexico City and alerted Interpol, the
international police agency, and foreign embassies to the
possibility that the couple may have secured false passports and
fled to Europe or South America.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities, however, stress there are still no formal charges
against the couple and that they only want to talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal appears to mark the end of the career of a star who
brought a breath of fresh air to Mexico's predictable world of
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   She chose to don a Madonna-like costume of torn fishnet tights
and do outrageous stunts on stage. She was assertive, and she once
defiantly told an audience, ``They want me to see a psychiatrist,
but I am not mad. I am just exasperated!''
</P>
<P>
   Such scenes did not please Mexico's conservative Roman Catholic
church leaders, who labeled her a threat to the country's
traditional values.
</P>
<P>
   She was, however, a huge hit with ordinary Mexicans. Many school
girls identified with her, teen-age boys idolized her and their
elders lined up to buy her calendars that showed her in various
stages of undress.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Mexico's intellectual community remain
infatuated with Trevi. They met last week for what the cultural
correspondent at the La Jornada newspaper called ``an attempt to
unravel the social, judicial and psychological implications of the
Trevi case.''
</P>
<P>
   They, along with just about everyone else in Mexico, are now
speculating about Trevi's sex life, her disappearance and the
veracity of the allegations against her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things they are saying now are very worrying to us,'' said
Jose Luis Cuevas, the painter who organized and hosted the
discussion. ``I don't know what has become of her. I admired her
and when people started to say she was like Madonna I said she is
better than that. I stick to that view. She is a splendid dancer, a
great actress and extraordinarily beautiful. I defend this woman of
the entertainment world.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, too, is standing by her former best friend. It's
Andrade whom she wants to see behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gloria is the world's best manipulator, but she is also a
victim in all this,'' Hernandez said. ``Deep down I know she is not
a bad person. He is a head case and must be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
