<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freed man `bombarded' by journalists, job offers
 &HT;    By Gabriella Boston and Bill Montgomery
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On his first day out of prison after serving 16 years
for a rape he didn't commit, Calvin Johnson rode down Peachtree
Street in a limousine, appeared repeatedly on television and
collected job offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to know what I've done in the last 24 hours?
Interviews, interviews, interviews. One reporter leaves, another
pulls up,'' Johnson said Wednesday. ``I've been bombarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he received five to 10 job offers Wednesday, but
had had little chance to return the calls. He did not disclose the
names of any companies or positions he'd been offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll start (working) next week. But if I don't, it's
OK,'' said Johnson. ``But I have to start the week after next. I
have to get a job.''
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old was convicted in Clayton County in 1983 of rape,
aggravated sodomy and burglary. Johnson was freed Tuesday after DNA
tests conducted at the request of the New York-based Innocence
Project proved he could not have been the attacker.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Johnson's lawyer during the trial recalled a
courtroom divided racially. ``Everyone at the prosecution table was
white, the victim was white, the witnesses against him were
white,'' lawyer Akil K. Secret said. ``It was the opposite for
Calvin. He was black, I was black and his alibi witnesses were
black.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Wednesday he believed an impartial jury would have
acquitted him. ``Things influence people,'' he said. ``When you
have a white jury, a white prosecutor and a black man accused, it's
hard for them to picture me as anything other than guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clayton County District Attorney Bob Keller denied that race
played a part in Johnson's conviction. ``There is nothing I would
do differently,'' Keller said. ``The case was well-tried. He had a
good attorney, and no one made any accusations that there was
prosecutorial misconduct or racial appeals or witness tampering.''
</P>
<P>
   A stroke of luck protected the evidence that allowed Johnson to
be freed. Prosecutors say the cotton swabs used for the DNA tests
were headed for the trash at one point, but were salvaged at the
last minute and kept in the DA's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did we save that evidence?'' Keller asked. ``Certainly
because it was evidence from a serious case. That played a part,
but I don't doubt for a minute that the Lord had a hand in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's younger sister, Tara Burkett, said her brother is
overwhelmed by all the attention and by life outside the prison
walls. Early Wednesday, Burkett said, Johnson was walking down the
hall, but suddenly stopped in his tracks and said, ``Now, what was
I supposed to do?'' Burkett had had to remind him it was time to
brush his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having to point him in a lot of different directions,''
Burkett said. ``He's had such a structured life for 16 years, he
doesn't know where to turn. He's a little lost.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
