<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Thursday, June
17, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   RAINIER-STRESS (SEATTLE) _ A report on the threat to Mount
Rainier National Park resulting from its popularity, and the stress
created by the hordes of visitors, hikers, climbers, etc. Plus an
exploration of the controversial rules that, in the minds of many,
make the park the most regulated _ some say over-regulated _ in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   OFFICERS-HAWAII (Seattle) _ Don't be surprised if you see King
County sheriff's deputies eating an island-style ``plate lunch''
instead of the proverbial doughnut. The Sheriff's Office is reaping
what it sowed in the Hawaiian sun last year, when it recruited a
huge number of island cops unhappy with low pay and high cost of
living there.
</P>
<P>
   By Vanessa Ho. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   PIPELINE (Seattle) _ Nadeene and Vern Hauserman live 28 steps
from the Olympic gas pipeline as it goes through Redmond, Wash.
Last week's deadly pipeline explosion in Bellingham _ which they
watched on the news without much comment _ doesn't worry them. Most
of the other neighbors don't seem worried, either. They've accepted
that living in once rural areas means incorporating pipelines and
such into the local geography. They also think it won't happen to
them.
</P>
<P>
   By Judd Slivka. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MURDER-SOLVED (LYNNWOOD, Wash.) _ Lynnwood police say they've
solved a 23-year-old murder case, thanks to updated DNA technology,
and have arrested James C. Stephens in the slaying of his
sister-in-law, Kimberly Kuntz. Stephens was arrested in the case in
1976, but police didn't have enough evidence and let him go.
</P>
<P>
   By Rebekah Denn. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WHIDBEY-PLANES (WHIDBEY ISLAND, Wash.) _ Whidbey Island-based
EA-6B Prowlers are being sent to South Korea as part of a U.S.
reinforcement of high-technology weapons following this week's
shooting incident between South and North Korean gunboats.
</P>
<P>
   By Ed Offley. (Story will move in the ``a'' and ``i''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING (Paris) _ The Boeing Co. is quickly laying the groundwork
for a commercial version of its C-17 Air Force cargo plane. The
certification process by the Federal Aviation Administration began
last month, and all that's needed before Boeing's board of
directors is asked to approve the launch of the MD-17 is a launch
customer, said Stu Thompson, vice president of business development
for Boeing's airlift and tanker group.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-NOTEBOOK (Paris) _ Notebook items from the Paris air
show.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-FINALS (San Antonio) _ Game 1 of the NBA Finals in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-THIEL-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ Writing from Game 1 of the NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Detroit) _ Mariners at Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK (Detroit) _ Notebook items from
Mariners-Tigers game.
</P>
<P>
   By Tyler Kepner. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN _ Writing on the World Cup women's soccer
tournament, which starts Saturday in Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CAR-UNSER (Undated) _ It's a bittersweet Father's Day for Al
Unser Jr., heading back to Portland, Ore., for this weekend's CART
race. He's at the low point of his career, plus his young daughter
is seriously ill. The last time he had any real success was at
Portland in 1995, when he beat his dad.
</P>
<P>
   By Holly Cain. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
