<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDOCH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murdoch: Cable to lead TV, Internet content distribution
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Rupert Murdoch has pronounced cable TV the
unquestioned winner of the contest for which industry will dominate
the distribution of television and Internet content.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the future is cable,'' said Murdoch,
chairman of News Corp., which owns the Fox TV and movie
enterprises. ``There's perhaps a small corner for satellite
broadcasters, but the challenge from the telephone companies is
doubtful.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch made his industry assessment as the closing act for the
National Cable Television Association convention, which ran here
Sunday through Wednesday. He was interviewed by Fox News
correspondent Brit Hume in front of several hundred cable
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch has a vested interest in seeing cable do well. He owns
several cable TV channels, including Fox News, Fox Sports and Fox
Family. But he also owns Fox Television, considered the fourth
biggest TV network. That makes Murdoch a competitor, too, and he
said some things cable executives didn't necessarily want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   For one, he said the big broadcasters such as Fox would remain
the 800-pound gorillas of the media business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be room for broadcasters,'' said Murdoch.
``The networks' economics are under challenge, but advertisers will
continue to look at the broadcasters as the best way to reach a
mass audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch also challenged the conventional wisdom about the
Internet, saying that most Web sites don't have much of a
commercial future.
</P>
<P>
   In closing, Murdoch agreed with a questioner who said that there
were too few minority-owned cable channel and TV stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too little progress has been made in minority ownership,''
said Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   He said his company was taking the lead in raising minority
ownership, relating a controversial proposal Fox has made to the
Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch has proposed letting big companies like his own lend
money to minority businessmen to buy channels and stations. In
return, he has asked the FCC to ease the cap on how many TV
stations a company can own.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, a company is not permitted to own stations
controlling more than 35 percent of the U.S. TV market.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
