<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTREPRENEURS-AWARDS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Region's best entrepreneurs to be honored
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You've got a can't-miss breakfast meeting with a
client across town to seal a business deal. But your refrigerator
is on the blink, and the repair guy says he'll be there between 9
a.m. and 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you met anyone who hasn't had to be in two places at one
time?'' quips Andrea Arena, owner of 2 Places at One Time, a
corporate concierge service.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta businesswoman is among two dozen entrepreneurs from
Georgia, Alabama and Tennessee competing as finalists in this
year's Ernst &AMP; Young's Entrepreneur of the Year contest. Winners
will be announced tonight at a ceremony at the Grand Hyatt Atlanta
in Buckhead. Seventeen of the 24 finalists are from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Arena, 32, has made a business out of providing concierge
services to companies that want to help employees balance work and
personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, it's like an errand service,'' said Arena, who
started the business about 18 months after she graduated from
Georgia Tech in 1991. You name it, Arena's company has done it: pet
sitting, grocery shopping, waiting for the plumber, delivering
medical products, even planning a few weddings.
</P>
<P>
   The $5 million-a-year business has 70 offices in the United
States and Canada. Clients include companies such as 3Com Corp. and
Motorola. Arena said she got the idea after working as a concierge
at the Hyatt Regency in downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in the Beaver Cleaver environment anymore,'' Arena
said. ``Many (people) don't have a secretary or wife at home who's
going to meet these needs.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some incredible businesses among the entries, said
Elizabeth Camp, a contest judge. Camp, president of Camp Oil Co.,
based in Rome, was one of 10 judges who helped narrow the list of
more than 100 entries to the finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Finalist Jack Alexander, 48, said innovative use of the Internet
and ``an entrepreneurial corporate culture'' helped build his
Buckhead-based corporate travel management firm, WorldTravel
Partners, into a $3.2 billion enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very different structure from our competitors, which
tend to be more centrally owned and controlled,'' said Alexander, a
former certified public accountant for Arthur Andersen who bought
the company in 1987. It is now one of the nation's largest travel
management firms.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
