<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUV-BUMPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUGGED BUMPERS ARE NOT, STUDY FOR AUTO INSURERS SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Sport utility vehicles may look big and sturdy, but
their bumpers actually tend to be weak, allowing more damage to
occur in low-speed collisions than bumpers on cars, an insurance
industry group said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, which is financed by
the nation's auto insurers, conducted crash tests at 5 mph on six
popular midsize sport utility vehicles. It found that the cost of
fixing them was two to three times as much as for a typical small
or midsize car, with the sport utility vehicles sustaining up to
$2,000 in damage for each test, including crushed fenders, bent
hoods, broken tailgates and shattered lights.
</P>
<P>
   The damage is so costly partly because replacement parts for
sport utility vehicles tend to be fairly expensive, the institute
said. But the leading reason cited for the heavy damage was that
the bumpers themselves were not very strong, consisting of
unusually thin sheet metal with little, if any, energy-absorbing
plastic foam behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very different from the rugged image utility vehicle
manufacturers are selling,'' said Adrian Lund, the research
director at the institute, which is based in Arlington, Va.
``Instead of rugged, a more appropriate description for the bumpers
on these vehicles is flimsy.''
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles tested were the Mitsubishi Montero Sport, Dodge
Durango, Land Rover Discovery, Jeep Grand Cherokee, Lexus RX-300
and Mercedes ML-320.
</P>
<P>
   Still, classified as light trucks along pickup trucks and
minivans, sport utility vehicles are exempt from a wide range of
safety and environmental regulations, including Federal bumper
standards that require cars to withstand impacts at 2.5 mph with
little, if any, damage. Lund said that regulators should raise the
standards to 5 mph and apply them equally to cars, sport utility
vehicles, pickup trucks and minivans.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers strongly oppose extending the car bumper standards to
other vehicles but say they are making improvements anyway.
``Customer expectations will drive changes in vehicles if that's
what customers want,'' so regulations are unnecessary, said Gloria
Bergquist, a spokeswoman for the Alliance of Automobile
Manufacturers in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Hurd, a spokesman for the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration, said the agency was not reviewing its bumper
standards. Bumpers are mainly a consumer issue involving the cost
of repair rather than a safety issue for a vehicle's occupants, he
said, adding that the agency has higher safety priorities.
</P>
<P>
   In a high-speed impact, even a car's relatively sturdy bumper
crumples so quickly that it provides little protection for the
car's occupants, and their survival depends on the overall
construction of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But Lund said that the height of sport utility vehicles' bumpers
could have a big effect on the safety of other motorists and damage
to their vehicles. Federal standards require cars to have bumpers
that are 16 to 20 inches off the ground. Yet because sport
utilities are exempt from the standards, they commonly have higher
bumpers that ride over cars' bumpers and doorsills in collisions,
causing more damage and injuries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp. is trying to address this problem. The new
Chevrolet Suburban, which will go on sale this fall, will have a
front bumper extending 4.4 inches lower than on the current model,
putting the lower half of the bumper at the level of a car bumper.
The rear bumper will be 2.5 inches lower, and the stiff steel rails
in the Suburban's underbody, which do most of the damage in the
event of a high-speed crash, will be 1.5 inches lower.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Hazelbaker, a spokesman for the Highway Loss Data Institute,
another insurance industry group, said that insurance rates
depended mainly on the actual cost of claims submitted for
collisions involving a given model rather than on crash tests. But
the tests usually predict the future cost of claims accurately, he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2043EDT &QL; 
