<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former presidents tend to invest well
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jimmy Carter, who left the White House $1 million in
debt, is a multimillionaire now. So are former Presidents George
Bush, Ronald Reagan and Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton isn't wealthy yet, but Money (July), in a look at
presidential investing, says the incumbent president's blind trust
was at one point heavily invested in Internet stocks. Clinton,
however, dismissed the investment firm that had bet on the
Internet, and as a result missed a chance to earn big returns on
Amazon.com, Yahoo! and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer finance magazine's report is based on interviews
with people familiar with the investing of ex-presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Money says Ford's real estate holdings alone are worth $4.5
million, Reagan profited from investing in California real estate
and the Kennebunkport, Maine, estate George Bush bought for
$800,000 is now worth $7 million to $8 million. Carter got into
blue chips.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred high techs
</P>
<P>
   Two Atlanta companies _ BellSouth, the phone company, and
MindSpring Enterprises, the Internet access provider _ are on the
latest Business Week (June 21) list of 100 information technology
leaders. They rank 50th and 51st, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the list are America Online, Dell Computer and
Solectron. In general, the magazine says the standout companies are
the ones ``that are digging the trenches, laying the pipes and
getting their hands dirty building the new Internet economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks with a halo
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch usually doesn't get on most lists of stocks for
socially conscious investors, but it has a stellar environmental
record, says Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine (July) in a look
at this category of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Socially conscious mutual funds usually shun companies the fund
managers think are guilty of some social misdeed, such as making
liquor or military weapons, running casinos or polluting the
environment. The problem, says the magazine, is that the fund
manager's likes and dislikes may not be the investor's likes and
dislikes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ``safe'' stocks on Kiplinger's list are Cisco Systems
(good employee relations), Fannie Mae (helps low-income home
buyers), Hasbro (big charitable donor) and Maytag (offers rebates
to natural disaster victims).
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ The rise in yields is bringing bonds out of the shadows,
Fortune (July 5) reports. Even big firms such as Merrill Lynch are
beginning to offer online trading services in this usually obscure
market.
</P>
<P>
   _ Today's executive has lots of ways to keep in touch and even
be productive on the road, says Inc. Technology (Aug. 17) in a
special edition on ``cool tools for today's road warrior.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
