<HEADER>
A8296 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CHIMP-CULTURE-ART     06-16 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CHIMP-CULTURE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIMPANZEE COMMUNITIES ARE CULTURALLY DIVERSE, STUDY FINDS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By NATALIE ANGIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In East Africa, they are dainty and meticulous, poking a twig
into an anthill and then nibbling the insects one by one. They daub
their bodies clean with napkins made of leaves, or give themselves
a postprandial tickle with any stray object at hand.
</P>
<P>
   In West Africa, they are like children polishing off the cake
batter, sweeping up dozens of ants on a stick and then consuming
the entire swarm with a single satisfied swipe. They use sharp
objects to extract marrow from monkey bones and fan branches in the
air to swat away flies.
</P>
<P>
   They are all Pan troglodytes, or common chimpanzees, but it
turns out that they are uncommonly diverse in their skills and
habits.
</P>
<P>
   In a comprehensive synthesis that covers 151 years' worth of
chimpanzee observations, an international team of primatologists
reports that humanity's closest cousins display what was long
thought to be the sine qua non of humanness: cultural variation.
</P>
<P>
   Chimpanzees living on Africa's Ivory Coast groom, court and use
tools in a very different manner than those apes of the Gombe
forest of Tanzania; while the chimpanzees of Uganda are likewise
slaves to local fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The findings offer the most detailed evidence yet that nonhuman
animals can pick up behaviors through observation and imitation,
and then convey those learned skills to their neighbors and kin,
elements of a scientific definition of culture. The research also
helps buttress the much-beleaguerd nurture half of the endless
debate over whether nature or nurture, culture or chromosomes,
predominate in shaping behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is cultural behavior,'' Andrew Whiten of the Scottish
Primate Research Group at the University of St. Andrews in Scotland
said this week in a telephone interview. ``It's passed on by some
kind of observational learning process. One chimpanzee learns from
another, in contrast to inheriting behaviors through genetics.''
</P>
<P>
   And though some of the seven chimpanzee communities described in
the current study fall into different subspecies of P. troglodyte,
said Whiten, and thus are not genetically identical to each other,
variations in behaviors are found even between two different troops
of the same subspecies.
</P>
<P>
   Whiten is an author of the new report, which appears in
Thursday's issue of the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Animals have been shown previously to learn from their parents
and peers. Song birds, for example, are known to develop their
repertory based on the songs they hear around them. And in a famous
example of learning through imitation, a young Japanese rhesus
macaque monkey living on the island of Koshima 50 years ago,
developed the habit of washing the dirt off sweet potatoes in water
before eating them. Other macaques in the group quickly adopted the
method, and even today, long after the original potato washers have
died, Koshima macaques retain the cleansing tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have asserted that such examples were too narrow and
isolated to be counted as evidence of true culture.
</P>
<P>
   In the new report, however, the researchers list 39 different
behaviors that vary in prevalence and style among the seven
chimpanzee communities.
</P>
<P>
   In a commentary that accompanies the new report, Frans B.M. de
Waal of the Yerkes Regional Primate Research Center in Atlanta,
points out that some hardcore anthropologists and psychologists
have sought for years to keep the ``culture'' tag unique to human
beings, an exclusionary desire that has demanded increasingly
elaborate definitions of the term.
</P>
<P>
   The latest record of chimpanzee inventiveness and diversity, he
writes, ``is so impressive that it will be hard to keep these apes
out of the cultural domain without once again moving the goal
posts.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current paper, nine primatologists, including renowned
figures like Jane Goodall of the Gombe Stream Research Center,
Richard Wrangham of Harvard University and Toshisada Nishida of
Kyoto University, set aside their often competitive ways to pool
their years of painstaking observations from field studies that
ranged from eight to 38 years.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers first compiled a list of 65 candidate behaviors
that they suspected might be specific to different chimpanzee
communities. Some of the proposed behaviors turned out not to be
unique at all, but rather nearly universal, while others varied for
reasons easily explained by the local ecology. For example, the
decision about where to build a sleeping nest appeared to depend
more on local predators than on prevailing community taste.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the researchers came up with 39 different behavior
patterns that fit their definition of cultural variation, meaning
they were customary in some communities and absent in others, for
reasons that could only be explained by learning or imitation.
</P>
<P>
   In the Tai forest of the Ivory Coast, for example, the custom,
when grooming another ape, is to pick off a parasite and then
squash it on one's own forearm. Among Gombe chimpanzees, the
preferred method is to remove the flea or tick and mash it with a
leaf. The chimpanzees of Budongo forest of Uganda pick off the
insect, put it on a leaf for inspection, and then decide whether it
will eat the insect or toss it away.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``This may seem subtle and odd to us, because we don't groom
each other,'' Whiten said. ``But among chimpanzees, grooming is
very important, and these may be the chimpanzee equivalents of
human differences in greeting, where some cultures shake hands,
others kiss on both sides of the cheek, and still others rub
noses.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cultural behaviors have an almost religious sense to
them. In six of the seven communities, the chimpanzees perform a
rain dance, a slow display at the start of rain. ``You're in awe
when you see this,'' said Pascal Gagneux of the University of
California at San Diego, who spent two years in the Tai forest
studying chimpanzees, but did not contribute to the current report.
``The chimpanzees go into a quasi-trance, dancing even when they're
alone, with no spectators, as if they were ritually celebrating the
rainstorm.''
</P>
<P>
   Courting styles also exhibit considerable variation, just as
they do among humans. In some places, the males knock on tree
trunks to attract a female's attention, in other locales they swish
vegetation around, while in still other communities the males
perform an irresistible operation called leaf-clipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hold a leaf in their mouth and clip bits off in a noisy
way,'' Whiten said. Courtship behaviors, he speculated, could be
one arena where it is particularly crucial that a suitor show he is
up on the latest fashions.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers cannot yet say exactly how cultural behaviors
are transmitted among chimpanzees. They only rarely have observed
examples of true teaching, when one ape, usually a parent, corrects
the fumbling attempts of a young ape to do something like crack
open a nut. Nor are they certain how venerable or stable many of
the local traditions are _ that is, through how many generations
they have been passed. Only in the Gombe, the site of the longest
field study to date, can scientists confirm that some behaviors
like termite fishing with leaves, have persisted through three
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the simian traditions will continue anywhere remains
open to doubt. The primatologists warn that chimpanzees everywhere
have lately been under tremendous pressure and assault. Not only is
their habitat being thwacked away by the millions of acres each
year, but roads built for logging have also stimulated a thriving
market in primate meat, called bush meat.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists estimate that at least 4,000 wild chimpanzees
are shot and shipped out of the African forest annually to satisfy
local and more distant tastes for ape steaks. A century ago, there
were millions of chimpanzees across Africa, the scientists said.
Today, there are fewer than 200,000. If current trends continue,
the scientists say, the only culture chimpanzees may be left with
is that of a zoo.
</P>
</TEXT>
