<HEADER>
A8310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-ADVANCE17-CO     06-16 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-ADVANCE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some right at home with Pinehurst
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ To many American golfers, this place feels
foreign. And not just because of the Europeanlike traffic circles.
</P>
<P>
   This small town's most treasured antique _ a 99-year-old golf
course _ feels like it was shipped across an ocean.
</P>
<P>
   And after taking spins around Pinehurst No. 2, testing out the
greens that look like flipped-over bowls, foreign players were
beaming. Greg Norman said the course reminded him of ones he grew
up with in Australia. He also proclaimed this U.S. Open to be the
best one he's ever played in _ never mind that it doesn't start
until this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of an open Open,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, here's the thing: The world's hottest player, a 27-year-old
who was born and raised in Jacksonville, Fla., feels right at home
here, too.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval learned to play golf on the banks of the St. John's
River at Timquana Country Club _ a course designed by Donald Ross,
the same man responsible for the unique character of Pinehurst No.
2.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Timquana) is not a world-famous one like this, but you can
still see some of the same thinking involved,'' Duval said.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Duval talks like he believes course No. 2
will produce major title No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   He has won 11 PGA Tour events, including four this year. He has
passed Tiger Woods and taken over the No. 1 spot in the rankings.
He is, by all accounts, a big part of the future of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as of today, he is to golf what Andre Agassi once was to
tennis _ a player who has collected a lot of money and attention
without winning one of the four majors.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like Duval would win the Masters last year. He led by
three strokes with three holes to play . . . and finished tied for
second.
</P>
<P>
   He began this year by winning the Mercedes Championships and the
Bob Hope Classic, finishing each tournament at 26-under par. He
added titles at the Players Championship and BellSouth Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a sixth-place finish at the Masters, he began to
struggle. He shot a 78 on the third day of the Houston Open and
finished tied for 64th. He went to New Orleans and didn't make the
cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't as ready to play as I would like to be when I
got to Houston,'' he said. ``Maybe it's just I was more drained
from those three weeks before than I had expected. So I chose not
to play for a little while, to get try to get back and get ready.''
</P>
<P>
   After placing third at the Memorial, he returned home feeling as
if everything was in place for the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Then he decided to make coffee.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't necessarily stunning news that Duval hurt himself.
Just the way he did it.
</P>
<P>
   He is known as a bit of a thrill-seeker. Within three weeks of a
record-setting 59 in the final round of the Chrysler Classic, he
was flying down the ski slopes on a snowboard.
</P>
<P>
   He survived that. The injury came last Friday when he grabbed a
scalding pot and sustained second-degree burns on his right thumb
and forefinger.
</P>
<P>
   His practice time for the Open has been hampered. His fingers
are bandaged. And he wasn't able to get in a full practice round
until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after that round, Duval seemed more annoyed with the fuss
being made over his fingers than the actual injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like all I've been talking about,'' he said. ``It
hasn't hampered anything. It hasn't prevented me from performing as
I would like this week. So it wasn't exactly the greatest of
timing, but it looks like it's going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because Duval burned his hand doesn't mean he is doomed to
join Irving Fryar (kitchen knife) and Bob Ojeda (lawn shears) in
the Home Injury Hall of Shame.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he will be like Gary Player.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, Player sliced his finger opening a tin of fruit, then
went on to win the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   In a media poll done this week, one journalist actually cited
Duval's injury as the reason for picking him to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no pressure,'' said Tetsuya Kano of Nippon Broadcasting
System.
</P>
<P>
   More voters, however, believe this U.S. Open will not be won by
the No.1-ranked player. They picked Spain's Jose Maria Olazabal,
the Masters champion, to win _ and become the first European to
capture the U.S. Open title since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Norman also put Olazabal atop his list of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jose Maria comes to mind, because of some of the shots he
played around Augusta National,'' Norman said. ``The little
bump-and-run shots. He's got the visualization, the imagination and
creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he feels at home here.
</P>
<P>
   But so does the Florida native with the, uh, hot hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the course suits me well,'' Duval said. ``It seems to
set up for me well.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
