<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN TO KOSOVO `LIKE THE OKLAHOMA LAND RUSH' 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD MERTENS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ Thousands of ethnic Albanians joyously left
Macedonia and Albania for home Wednesday, ignoring warnings that it
was not yet safe for them to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Oklahoma land rush,'' said Franci Smajlagic, a
United Nations aid worker who watched the movement of people near
the Macedonia-Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   More than 14,000 refugees poured into the province Wednesday,
some 3,000 from Macedonia and 11,000 from Albania.
</P>
<P>
   They crossed into Kosovo by car, taxi, tractor and by foot. Some
carried blankets and clothing, others food unavailable in Kosovo _
sugar, oil, peppers, tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go home as soon as possible,'' said Bukurije
Topani, 36, who was traveling with her husband, four children and a
dozen members of her extended family, all bound for their mountain
village in southern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   They ignored pleas from the United Nations relief agency to wait
until it could organize a safer and more orderly return. ``They're
going back in too much of a hurry,'' complained Smajlagic, the U.N.
aid worker. ``It's understandable but it's not rational. We can't
provide security.''
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the U.N. relief agency indicated that some
authorities had given up trying to stop the rush home. ``Once this
thing gathers momentum there's a snowball effect and you can't stop
it,'' said Judith Kumin.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, the provincial capital, the Yugoslav army pulled
its last troops out of the city, and Serb civilians, fearful of
retaliatory attacks, thronged the bus station for a ride north,
with some offering wads of cash for a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Artemije of the Serbian Orthodox Church, who had urged
Serbs in Kosovo's second-largest city to remain, joined their
flight. Under escort by German peacekeepers, and jeers from
returning ethnic Albanians, the bishop and a number of Serb
families left Prizren for Pristina, the German command said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's commander for Kosovo, British Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson,
urged all Serbs to stay put, promising that his troops ``would have
the same attitude toward everyone.'' In another apparent attempt to
calm the Serbs, NATO's spokesmen announced that a U.S. Marine
detachment had disarmed 200 Kosovo rebels near Pristina and
detained six of their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians have accused Serb forces and paramilitaries of
committing atrocities during NATO's 11-week air campaign. New
evidence of atrocities was found Wednesday around Kosovo by NATO
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, in Helsinki, Finland, U.S. officials met with Russian
authorities and later said they had made some progress toward
resolving a standoff over Moscow's role in the peacekeeping
operation. The negotiations are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Here on Macedonia's border with Kosovo, the refugees were
restless to go home Wednesday morning. Their impatience was
underscored when a police officer blew his whistle and dozens
sprinted to their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Border officials struggled to deal with long lines of cars and
crowds of people crossing on foot.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. refugee agency has been trying to discourage the
Kosovar Albanians from returning immediately for several reasons.
NATO troops have secured main highways and major towns, but not
villages and the roads that connect them. Plus, the sheer amount of
destruction is vast, including burned houses and tainted water
sources. And food is scarce, since most farmers were not able to
plant their spring crops.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest problem, relief workers say, is the danger of
mines, booby-trapped houses and unexploded shells. On Tuesday, a
woman was killed and her husband was injured when she stepped on a
mine in the first town across the border from Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, U.N. workers were handing out leaflets to the
returning refugees that warned about land mines. ``Your life is
worth your being patient for a few more weeks,'' said one of the
leaflets. But few, if any, people turned back.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the refugees were not going home heedlessly. The danger of
land mines was on many minds. Some said they knew from other people
that their homes were safe. Others said they intended to be
careful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my children not to touch anything even before we came
to Macedonia,'' said Bukurije Topani, who set off for home with 17
members of her extended family.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people who crossed the border here Wednesday were
men going to see their houses for the first time since being
expelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the heads of the family,'' said Bexhed Karaliti, 65,
who was accompanied by his elderly cousin, Rexhep Karaliti, and his
one unmarried son, Sadik. ``We are going to see if our houses are
OK or if they are burned.'' Only later, they explained, would they
fetch the rest of their family.
</P>
<P>
   But many families also were on the move Wednesday. Sami Delija,
a 31-year-old doctor, arrived at the border with his wife and four
children in a van packed with 17 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that Kosovo is safe and that peace has won,'' he said.
``We are afraid that the organized way is going to take a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The stream of refugees pouring into Kosovo bore an uncanny
resemblance to the exodus of more than 860,000 refugees out of the
province during the two-and-a-half months of NATO bombing. But this
time the refugees were hurrying over the border not in terror but
with joy and expectation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe I can go so soon,'' said 9-year-old Adelina
Delija, Sami Delija's daughter. ``I'm so happy.''
</P>
<P>
   A skinny girl with short brown hair and a quick smile, she
hopped from foot to foot and insisted on reciting a poem that she
wrote in honor of her grandfather, who died in a massacre in
central Kosovo last September.
</P>
<P>
   The joy at returning was tempered with sorrow for family members
lost to the violence of Serb ``ethnic cleansing.'' And fears
lingered. Ten-year-old Blearta Topani was looking forward to
hugging her grandfather, who had stayed behind in Kosovo, and to
start school again. But she still could not shake the terror of the
police that has stayed with her since the family fled from their
village two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can't believe there are no Serbs there,'' her mother said.
``Until she sees with her own eyes, she won't be convinced.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
