<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIKE17-COX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's tee time at first Nike Dayton Open
 &HT;    By Bucky Albers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Softened by heavy rain Monday and Tuesday,
Centerville's Golf Club at Yankee Trace is bracing itself today for
an assault on par the likes of which it hasn't seen in its first
five years.
</P>
<P>
   A field of 144 players _ including 51 who have had PGA Tour
cards at one time or another _ will tee it up in the first Nike
Dayton Open. It's a four-day, 72-hole event that replaced the Nike
Miami Valley Open held for the last six years in Springboro.
</P>
<P>
   The players have been impressed with the 7,139-yard Yankee Trace
course, the clubhouse and practice facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've traveled the country and this is as good a public golf
course as I've ever played,'' said Brian Claar, who has played the
PGA Tour for 13 years. ``What really impresses me is the practice
area. They should be pretty darned proud of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Claar estimated that a score of 12 or 15 under par will win the
tournament ``if the weather isn't crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning score last year at the par 70 Heatherwoode course,
where runner-up Doug Dunakey fired a 12-under-par 59 in the second
round, was 266 (14 under par) by Craig Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Trace has some deep and wiry rough, but Claar says it is
spotty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen places where it's U.S. Open-like and places where
you can play out of it,'' Claar said. ``There will be some luck
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner gets $45,000 from the $250,000 purse, but a couple of
Kansans could win much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Gogel and Steve Gotsche each have two victories this
season, and would get an immediate ``battlefield promotion'' to the
PGA Tour if they win No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Gogel is a 28-year-old from Overland Park who has won four of
the last 23 Nike events, including the last 10 tournaments of 1998.
He has earned $234,244 in that period.
</P>
<P>
   When he won last week's Nike Cleveland Open by eagling the
second hole in a playoff against Casey Martin, he became the first
Nike member to win three playoffs. He is the only player to win two
Nike events in successive years.
</P>
<P>
   By finishing 16th on the Nike money list last season, Gogel
missed by one spot a promotion to the PGA Tour this season.
</P>
<P>
   Gotsche, a 37-year-old veteran of 15 professional seasons, has
bounced back impressively after going through 1998 without playing
privileges on either the Nike or PGA tour. While biding his time,
he played mini-tour events in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all kinds of state opens in Texas, Nebraska, South
Dakota, Colorado, Missouri,'' said Gotsche, who lives in Great
Bend, Kansas. ``I played the Prairie Golf Tour and Lone Star
Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Gotsche said he won three $3,500 first prizes on the Prairie
Tour and picked up $7,500 for winning the Nebraska Open.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the PGA Tour qualifying tournament in November,
Gotsche tied for 134th, which made him a nonexempt player. Players
with this conditional status have to sit by the telephone sometimes
and wait until Monday or Tuesday to hear if they are in a
tournament. Then they rush to the airport, which can be a 100-mile
drive for Gotsche.
</P>
<P>
   He took care of that problem in March by winning the Monterrey
Open. Then he won the Upstate Classic in Greenville, S.C., on May
2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
