<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Near misses make Lehman more patient
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Maybe Tom Lehman should do everything he can
to avoid a spot in the final pairing for the fourth round of the
U.S. Open on Sunday. After four consecutive years in the final
group and four disappointments in a row, maybe it's time for a
change of scenery, somewhere in the pack.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll never get a negative approach from Lehman, no matter
how many times he's been thwarted in his attempt to win the coveted
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the glass pretty much half-full,'' Lehman said Wednesday
during final preparations for today's first round at Pinehurst No.
2. ``I think it's been disappointing at times, but it's been a lot
of awfully good golf played as well. I've learned some lessons, and
hopefully this year I can put those in good use.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman finished third at Shinnecock in 1995 after a great
finishing performance by Corey Pavin, the winner. He bogeyed the
final hole in 1996 at Oakland Hills after his drive at the 18th
hole took a bad bounce into a fairway bunker. In 1997 at
Congressional, he hit into the water with his approach to the 71st
hole. Last year at the Olympic Club, Lehman made nothing happen in
a closing 75.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have I learned?'' Lehman said. ``Patience and learning to
hit away from the pins when you really want to go at them. . . . l
tended to get very aggressive, especially as I had the taste of
winning. I put myself in good spots, and then I just got too
aggressive and beat myself. The whole secret for the U.S. Open is
not beating yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman should take full advantage of the reduced rough at
Pinehurst No. 2 and plans to use driver as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get too greedy, but you do need to be aggressive off
the tee,'' he said. ``Even though being in the fairway is
important, you do need to give yourself some shorter irons to put
yourself in the right spots on the greens. You're not going to do
too well laying up with 1-irons all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   Different kind of pitch
</P>
<P>
   David Duval's right hand, which has healed from burns suffered
last week on a teapot, will be tested again next week. He'll throw
out the first ball in New York at the Mets-Marlins game on Tuesday.
. . . Masters champion Jose Maria Olazabal of Spain was asked:
``What is your greater asset, your head or your heart?'' Olazabal
replied: ``My nose. Look at it.'' . . . One of the Pinehurst's
oldest traditions is for guests at the Pinecrest Inn to chip balls
into the fireplace through a small opening. Davis Love III, who is
staying there this week, was asked how much money he has won there
during the years on bets near the bar. ``I don't think I ever won
anything,'' he said, ``because I couldn't chip in college.''
</P>
<P>
   . . . Of his role as a sort of hometown favorite, Love, a former
University of North Carolina student and Georgia native, said, ``If
I listen and read very much more, I'll think that I've lived
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
