<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-VP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL VICE PRESIDENT AT COMPAQ RESIGNS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON_ Hans W. Gutsch, the controversial senior vice president
of human resources at Compaq Computer Corp., resigned from the
company Wednesday, telling board chairman Benjamin Rosen that he no
longer wanted to be a ``lightning rod.''
</P>
<P>
   Both current and former Compaq employees say Gutsch was part of
a group of senior executives dubbed the ``A team'' who controlled
access to former chief executive Eckhard Pfeiffer.
</P>
<P>
   Gutsch also was the subject of two sexual harassment-related
financial settlements paid by Compaq, as well as a 1998
investigation into other harassment allegations, detailed in a May
30 Houston Chronicle story.
</P>
<P>
   The claims that sparked the 1998 investigation were found to
have ``no basis'' after the woman who made them refused to give
names, fearing the alleged victims would lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Gutsch is the last A-team member to resign. Earl Mason, Compaq's
former chief financial officer, left when Pfeiffer was forced out
on April 18. John Rose, who headed Compaq's enterprise computing
group, resigned on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer and some sources inside Compaq deny any senior
executives were granted more access to the chief executive than
others. They say accusations that Gutsch and others sought to
divide top management were sour grapes on the part of executives
who were shut out of planning that involved the Tandem and Digital
Equipment Corp. acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   In his resignation letter addressed to Rosen, Compaq's chairman
and acting chief executive, Gutsch wrote about his accomplishments
during his 11-year tenure, but then said ``there have also been
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the recent changes in management, there have been
unfounded and untrue allegations made about my personal conduct and
these anonymous allegations have been conveyed into the increased
coverage in the press the Company naturally received during this
time,'' Gutsch wrote. ``Apart from personal hurt to me and mine,
these allegations are a distraction for the Company at a time it
does not need distractions. I have chosen to no longer be a
lightning rod for this.''
</P>
<P>
   No replacement for Gutsch was named. His human resources group _
which also oversees Compaq's environmental, facilities and security
operations _ will report directly to the three-person office of the
chief executive, which consists of Rosen and board members Robert
Ted Enloe and Frank Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq officials would not comment on Gutsch's departure, and
Gutsch could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   A written statement issued Wednesday characterized Gutsch's
departure as a retirement. In it, Rosen said that Gutsch ``was
instrumental in developing Compaq's global infrastructure as the
Company grew from 2,000 to 70,000 employees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hans managed and implemented world-class human resource and
organizational strategies, personnel development programs, and
safety, security and environmental policies,'' Rosen said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the former Compaq executives who'd been publicly
critical of Gutsch would not comment on his departure.
</P>
<P>
   But Freda K. Hendricks, a former secretary to another senior
vice president who accused Gutsch of sexually harassing other women
at Compaq in a June 1998 letter to board members, said Wednesday
she was glad he had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been a detriment to the company for a while, and it
sends the right message now that he is gone,'' Hendricks said.
``Human resources will now be for the people instead of for
management.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutsch's resignation was announced after the market closed on
Wednesday. Compaq's stock closed at 22 1/4, up 1 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
