<HEADER>
A8328 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-INTLNOTES17-COX     06-16 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTLNOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pack closing on U.S. women
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The fine-toothed comb that some in the media have been
using to detect weaknesses on the U.S. Women's World Cup team might
not be coming across as the biggest reason why the Americans aren't
the overwhelming favorites for the Cup that they were a few months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the U.S. team was rocked by Norway in the 1995 World
Cup semifinals, some of its closest rivals _ as well as others
looking to move into the elite _ have been trying furiously to keep
up or get established. The Americans won the first Olympic gold
medal a year later in Athens, although it wasn't easy, as evidenced
by a grueling 2-1 semifinal win in overtime to avenge the Norwegian
loss.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is still an even favorite, along with China
and defending champion Norway, as it opens World Cup play Saturday
against Denmark at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about American vulnerability in central defense to
swift counterattacks, and the lack of a consistently creative
midfielder have grown out of some recent friendlies, including a
4-2 win over Canada on June 6 in which the U.S. team surrendered
both goals quickly.
</P>
<P>
   China also has taken advantage of those factors to beat the U.S.
team twice this year, the second to snap a 50-match home winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a good team, but we know we can't shut out every
opponent,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said. ``I was really pleased
with the Canada game, because that's the kind of game that's going
to make us a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   Although only five teams are given a legitimate chance to hoist
the trophy July 10 in the Rose Bowl _ Germany and Brazil being the
other two _ the gap between them and some of the others might be
closing, if ever so slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Take Nigeria as a good example. The Super Falcons have had
little success outside their continent, and have lost all six
previous World Cup matches. But the African nation, which plays the
U.S. team June 24 in Chicago, beat China 4-3 over the weekend in an
exhibition match in Los Angeles and showed some dangerous speed and
flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're necessarily catching up all that much,
but they're getting more support at home,'' U.S. goalkeeper Briana
Scurry said. ``They're getting more games and more experience, and
within that are the fruits of victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Atletico avoids relegation
</P>
<P>
   After going through four coaches and enduring the maddening
whims of president Jesus Gil y Gil, Atletico Madrid clinched a spot
in the Spanish Primera Division next year with a resounding home
3-1 victory over Real Madrid on Saturday. The loss was another
serious blow for Madrid, which was still reeling from a 6-0 Spanish
Cup defeat to Valencia last week.... Here's a player whose services
shouldn't be in high demand anytime soon: Tenerife goalkeeper
Carlos Montoya, who has earned the distinction of playing for
relegated Spanish teams in each of the last three seasons. In that
span, he has given up 101 goals in 80 games, and even though he was
benched for the last six games this season, it didn't prevent
Tenerife from dropping down.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Bremen wins Cup
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rost stopped a shot by Lothar Matthaus as Werder Bremen
won the penalty kick round 5-4 and captured the German Cup on
Saturday in a 2-1 upset of Bundesliga champions Bayern Munich. The
loss came after Bayern's shocking loss to Manchester United in the
European Cup finals, but it was a big boost for Bremen, which
finished in the bottom half of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Explosive hurts keeper
</P>
<P>
   Italian fans are notorious for tossing sparklers onto the field
during play, and on Sunday it was responsible for injuring a
third-division goalkeeper during the final game of the season.
Marco Borghetto of Serie C club Lumezanne fell to the ground when
the explosive landed near him in a 2-1 loss to Pistola. He was
taken to a hospital for treatment, but information about his
condition has not been released. Brazil: Edmundo, Romario left off
</P>
<P>
   Brazil coach Wanderley Luxemburgo, saying he wants a unified
team defend the Copa America crown later this summer, is keeping
volatile strikers Edmundo and Romario at home. Romario, who didn't
play in the World Cup last year, is the top scorer in the Rio de
Janeiro state championship for Palmeiras, while Edmundo has been
playing well since rejoining Vasco de Gama last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The verb must always be conjugated in the first person plural
_ `we do, we play,''' Luxemburgo said, referring to no player in
particular. ``The word `I' in a group gets complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the usual suspects were chosen, including Ronaldo,
Roberto Carlos, Cafu, Cesar Sampaio, Rivaldo, Ze Roberto, Leonardo
and Flavio Conceicao.
</P>
<P>
   Amoroso signs for $42.3 million
</P>
<P>
   After Christian Vieri's record transfer from Lazio to Inter
Milan last week for $50 million, another Italian club opened up a
generous checkbook to land Serie A's top goal-scorer. Parma's $42.3
million sum has attracted Brazilian Marcio Amoroso, coming off a
22-goal season at Udinese. But he won't be aided by one of the best
midfielders in the league, as Argentine Juan Veron has left Parma
to join Lazio.... Liverpool paid an English goalkeeping record of
$6.4 million to lure Dutchman Sander Westerveld away from Vitesse
Arnhem. He is the seventh player, and seventh foreigner, signed by
French manager Gerard Houllier, who welcomed back embattled striker
Robbie Fowler with a contract extension.... Brian Laudruphas
returned to Ajax Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
