<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEARSTEARNS-SEC-TALKS     06-16 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEARSTEARNS-SEC-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAR STEARNS SUIT BY SEC SAID TO BE NEAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Settlement talks have broken down between the
Securities and Exchange Commission and Bear Stearns Co. concerning
the firm's activities as a clearing agent for small brokerage firms
that defrauded investors, according to people close to the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Most SEC cases involving brokerage firms are settled before they
reach a courtroom. But unless Bear Stearns offers to settle the
case quickly, the people close to the investigation said, the SEC
is preparing to sue the firm within days.
</P>
<P>
   Though the details are still being worked out, a person close to
the investigation said that the SEC case would most likely accuse
Bear Stearns of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bear Stearns said that discussions were
continuing. A spokeswoman for the SEC declined to comment on the
status of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns Clearing Corp., the firm's unit that clears trades
and provides capital and administrative services to smaller firms
nationwide, has been the subject of an SEC investigation since 1997
after the failure of A.R. Baron &AMP; Co., a brokerage firm in New York
that cleared its trades through Bear Stearns. Bear Stearns and the
SEC have been in settlement talks for more than two months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the SEC inquiry, Bear Stearns is under
investigation by Robert Morgenthau, the Manhattan district
attorney, who won 13 securities fraud convictions against A.R.
Baron's executives and brokers in 1997 and 1998. Morgenthau is
investigating Bear Stearns' role in the A.R. Baron failure, in
which investors lost $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in the U.S. attorney's Manhattan office are also
investigating Bear Stearns as part of their criminal case against
Sterling Foster, a small brokerage firm that cleared its trades
through Bear Stearns. Federal prosecutors contend that Sterling
Foster executives manipulated several small stocks that their firm
underwrote and that the firm, which failed in 1997, was secretly
controlled by Randolph Pace, a former brokerage executive who had
been barred from the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who lost money with A.R. Baron say that Bear Stearns
should have known that the smaller firm was committing securities
fraud and should have acted to prevent it. Bear Stearns has
maintained that the brokerage firms dealing with the customers
directly, not the clearing firm, must police the operations for
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The A.R. Baron case has caused changes in the way securities
regulators regard clearing firms. In early June, the SEC announced
new, slightly more stringent rules for clearing firms that are
intended to help fight fraud at the kind of small brokerage firms
that have caused problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns may yet agree to a settlement, of course. The firm
could also settle after the SEC has filed suit.
</P>
<P>
   But if no settlement is reached, regulators have a couple of
options. They could bring an administrative law proceeding _ a
trial heard by an SEC administrative law judge who issues a
decision and can censure the firm, levy fines, suspend it or bar it
from the business. Bear Stearns could appeal any ruling to the full
commission. Administrative law proceedings can take months or years
to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Or the SEC could go into federal court and ask a judge for an
injunction against the firm and seek restitution and penalties.
This is viewed as somewhat more severe than an administrative
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Most firms avoid all this by settling with the SEC, but
securities lawyers offered several reasons why Bear Stearns might
not want to settle. If the firm cannot also bring the district
attorney and federal prosecutors into the deal _ what is known as a
global settlement _ it may fear that information contained in an
SEC settlement could be used as evidence against it in criminal
investigations. Fighting the SEC before its own judge or in federal
court would not create such a problem because a lawsuit contains
only allegations until a judge rules, which can be many months or
years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a settlement with the SEC could make Bear Stearns more
vulnerable in pending civil litigation related to its clearing
operations. A deal could hurt the firm's relationships with its
lenders and customers and invite actions from state securities
regulators. Even though the firm presumably would neither admit nor
deny any allegations in a settlement with the SEC, a jury or
arbitration panel in a civil proceeding might give it considerable
weight, tantamount to an admission of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC could also charge the firm with aiding and abetting
fraud, a charge that cannot be leveled against the firm in federal
civil lawsuits. In 1995, the Supreme Court ruled that private
actions could no longer be brought against, say, an accounting firm
or law firm for aiding and abetting a violations of securities
laws. But as part of the Private Securities Reform Act of 1995,
Congress stated that the SEC could bring such cases against
ancillary parties to a violation.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what effect an SEC suit might have on the pending
criminal investigations, both Morgenthau and a spokesman for the
U.S. attorney's Manhattan office declined to comment. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
