<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. takes Argentina win in stride
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Let's hear it for the boys.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men's national team stole some thunder before the start
of the Women's World Cup by stunning Argentina 1-0 Sunday in a
friendly. Perhaps the most encouraging sign was how calmly the
American camp reacted to the feat.
</P>
<P>
   An 88th-minute goal by Joe-Max Moore provided the only scoring
as the U.S. team won its third match against a substantial opponent
since coach Bruce Arena came on board last fall, but he's not
letting anybody take it out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still a year away from becoming a pretty good national
team,'' Arena said. ``It's a good win, but we're not going to make
too much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But it certainly figures to add confidence for the Americans as
they prepare for the Confederations Cup in July, with Brazil and
Germany in their pool.
</P>
<P>
   Under siege most of the afternoon by Inter Milan's fleet left
back Javier Zanetti, the makeshift U.S. defense held up relatively
well. Eddie Pope and Carlos Llamosa are out with injuries, but C.J.
Brown's only mistake was a sliding tackle that yielded a penalty
kick stopped by Kasey Keller.
</P>
<P>
   Claudio Reyna had good game as the creative force in midfield,
and the U.S. attack was without injured forward Brian McBride. The
match also gave Arena a chance to continue evaluating a pool of
players he hopes will be up for a much tougher slate next year.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team will give Argentina a rematch in Buenos Aires and
could figure as a tune-up opponent for several qualifiers of the
European championships.
</P>
<P>
   MLS: Hermosillo pays dividends
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Galaxy has the league's worst offense, and home
attendance at the Rose Bowl has fallen under 10,000 for some games.
But Mexican League star Carlos Hermosillo proved an instant tonic.
In his first MLS game this season, he scored to lead the Galaxy to
a 2-1 win over the defending MLS champions Chicago Fire. His return
attracted more than 18,000.... The Fire has lost three in a row and
five of six.... D.C. United, playing without several injured and
U.S. national team players, beat Columbus 3-1 on the road Sunday
for its seventh straight win.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
