<HEADER>
A8332 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-SCHOOL-2TAKES(     06-16 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-SCHOOL-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH LITTLE DATA ON SUCCESS, MANDATORY SUMMER SCHOOL EXPANDS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ill., Wash., Calif., Wis., Md., D.C.)   (nk) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beginning its second year of expanded summer school, muggy
Washington bought fans and bottled water when it realized it could
not install air-conditioning in all its buildings. Boston has
struggled to find transportation for its summer school students,
because not all will attend their neighborhood schools. Los Angeles
is deflecting criticism from teachers that summer school classes
will be too large and the curriculum too vague.
</P>
<P>
   As New York City gears up for the nation's largest mandatory
summer school program _ starting with 70,000 students next month
and growing to as many as 362,000 next year _ the experience in
these cities shows that the logistical hurdles will be formidable.
</P>
<P>
   What it does not show conclusively is whether mandatory summer
school works.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide rush to summer school, in urban districts from
Los Angeles to Boston to Hartford to Denver, is part of a widening
crackdown on social promotion, the practice of allowing failing
students to move on to the next grade. Summer school is seen as a
major ingredient _ popular among parents and teachers alike _
because studies show that holding children back does little good
unless they get extensive tutoring over the summer and afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a vacuum of comprehensive research showing how well
summer school works, how it should be approached and how it
compares with other programs aimed at raising achievement, like
after-school tutoring or smaller class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, which banned social promotion in several grades three
years ago, is furthest along, with 27,000 to 30,000 students
expected in mandatory summer school in the coming weeks. It has
reported some promising signs, in the form of rising test scores.
But even there, researchers say, summer school has not been in
place long enough to draw conclusive results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, some pupils have made progress,'' said Michael Klonsky,
a professor of education at the University of Illinois at Chicago
who specializes in school reform. ``But this is still a mixed bag.
You're doing things to make them give up their summer, teaching
what is basically a `kill and drill' curriculum. It is geared only
toward scoring better on tests.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City's move to mandatory summer school, which could
involve about a third of its 1.1 million students, will dwarf any
comparable program elsewhere _ not just because New York has the
nation's largest school system, but also because it will involve so
many grades, from three to 12.
</P>
<P>
   Most such programs have expanded gradually; New York plans to go
from a voluntary summer program with about 200,000 students _
including nearly 70,000 in grades three, six and eight ordered
there under the threat of being held back _ to a mandatory one. The
total number of students could nearly double next year, because of
more grades and stricter standards.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said they still hoped to be able to accommodate
voluntary students, who are often strongly encouraged by teachers
to attend but who will not be held back if they decline.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators will focus on the lowest performers on state and
city tests and also look at class work and attendance. The students
will have to pass a test at the end of the summer to move up.
</P>
<P>
   The real test will come next year. Officials expect the same
number of students in summer school this year as last, when a
record 200,000 attended; the only difference is that the 70,000 or
so ordered there will be the first to be admitted.
</P>
<P>
   For next year, New York has begun planning to resolve a host of
logistical problems, like finding enough high-quality teachers and
suitable buildings, preferably close to students' homes _ though
Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew says not all students will be
attending their neighborhood schools. Many buildings close over the
summer for renovation, and only about a fifth of the classrooms
have air-conditioning, which is not seen as a luxury when trying to
keep children focused and teachers interested in giving up vacation
time.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While many details remain to be worked out, the demand for new
teachers will be high. Board officials have said that as many as
362,000 students may end up in summer school, but they are hoping
that tutoring and coaching during the regular school year will
reduce the number, to 300,000 or even less.
</P>
<P>
   With the goal, at this point, of having class sizes of 15 or so
but possibly up to 20, board officials are planning on using 18,000
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers' union officials say they do not know where all of them
will come from, since virtually every teacher who wants to work
this year is doing so, and that still only adds up to 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem is that teachers are paid less to
teach summer school than they are paid during the school year.
Susan Amlung, a spokeswoman for the teachers' union, the United
Federation of Teachers, said the board was locked into the $32 per
hour summer rate by a contract not due to expire until November
2000, but she said the union would seek ways to sweeten the job,
such as allowing teachers to accumulate pension credit for summer
work, something not currently allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Board officials say next year's program will cost $175 million
above the $60 million to $70 million normally budgeted for summer
school, not counting money for air-conditioning, which could add
several million more. Crew says that he is determined to find the
financing for the program and that he will look into using
buildings ``in places we might otherwise may not have considered,''
including community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Board officials have said they plan to enlist retirees to
forestall teacher shortages and may hunt in districts outside the
city.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokeswoman, the chancellor has demurred at Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's suggestion to contract with private and
parochial schools to handle some of the instruction.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a common practice, judging from a spot-check of large
school systems.
</P>
<P>
   In Milwaukee, which is entering its second year of voluntary
summer school, all such instruction is done in public schools,
though the superintendent and the Roman Catholic archdiocese last
week agreed to develop and share after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   Logistical problems are to be expected, educators say, as school
administrators grasp at concepts new to them, with few models to go
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you go into something like this, you are going to
have a rocky first year,'' said John Perez, a vice president with
United Teachers Los Angeles, the teacher's union, which supports
the concept of summer school and ending social promotion.
``Teachers welcome it in theory; let's see how it works out.''
</P>
<P>
   Class sizes in the Los Angeles program, financed with $71
million from the state, which is mandating the end of social
promotion, will be about 20 this year, a tad higher than the
average 15 to 18 in most programs.
</P>
<P>
   Most cities look to Chicago, which has had three years to work
out the kinks, as their example.
</P>
<P>
   It is credited with pioneering the idea of mass remediation by
way of summer school as way to raise student achievement _ as
judged largely on standardized tests _ and to avoid having droves
of students left back under a tough new policy intended to end the
automatic promotion of students to the next grade.
</P>
<P>
   The summer classes are typically half-day and half the size of
those in the regular school year; the curriculum is a no-nonsense
drill in basic reading and math, with little or no recess.
</P>
<P>
   Not all cities are sold on summer school. Last year, Seattle
experimented with an ``academic boot camp'' intended to lift the
performance of 200 fifth-graders. In the end, only a few had done
well enough to move on to the next grade, and Sharon Green, the
district's chief academic officer, said such a hard-line summer
school would not be repeated this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, where an estimated 6,500 students in grades two, five,
six, seven and eight will attend a one-month mandatory summer
school for the first time in July, created a position last week to
oversee summer school and iron out difficulties like
transportation. The $21 million allotted for the program will not
fully cover getting students to the schools that will house summer
programs, and parents are complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were worried about whether or not it was just something
they were throwing together,'' said Hattie McKinnis, executive
director of the Citywide Parents Council. ``At this point, the
parents just did not feel that this mandatory summer school is
worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there has not been widespread resistance to the plan by
parents or teachers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But many have sought to insure that the summer school experience
is vastly different from that of the regular school year.
</P>
<P>
   Judith A. Rizzo, the deputy chancellor for instruction in New
York, said students will pore over reading and math to address
their shortfalls in basic skills. Those who do not pass
end-of-summer tests and are forced to repeat the grade will receive
intensive instruction so that they do not go on repeating the
grade, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, teachers will be provided individual assessments of
the 8,000 students expected in summer school this year to hone in
on their weaknesses, said Susan Sclafani, the district's chief of
staff for educational services, who notes that most of the system's
280 schools received air-conditioning in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world these children are moving into is just not the place
without good literacy and numeracy skills,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Karweit, a researcher with the Center for Research on the
Education of Students Placed at Risk, based at Johns Hopkins
University, said she was not surprised at the lack of broad study
of such programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times when interventions are planned around political
things such as standards and accountability, people don't build in
evaluations into the implementation,'' Ms. Karweit said. ``We need
to be more questioning as a society about the kinds of things we
put in place. Sometimes common sense things aren't the best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
