<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-SCENE-A     06-16 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-SCENE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ATTACK ON MODERN LIFE BY THE `REVEREND DELAY'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Texas)  (With CONGRESS-GUNS) 
 (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By the end of Rep. Tom DeLay's pulpit-thumping,
brimstone-seething exhortation against gun controls and the moral
decay of ``liberal relativism,'' the evangelical clergymen
assembled in the morning sunshine bathing the Capitol were moved to
rounds of ``Hallelujah!'' and ``Amen Jesus!'' ``Reverend DeLay!''
boomed one minister, waving the Bible before a clot of television
cameras on the Capitol lawn.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the Reverend Whip'' was more like it for the sulfurous
tinge DeLay lent to the long, miasmic debating day that essentially
broke the complex issue of school shootings into two disparate
areas for blame-saying: the entertainment industry's purveying of
melodramatized violence and easy access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, a pugnacious Texan ever joyous in battle, was all over
the debate in his role as House majority whip and as one of the few
relentlessly dynamic members lately to be seen among the troubled
Republican hierarchy. He was only warming up before the clergymen,
clearing his political preacher's pipes as he denounced the
American culture ``that worships the self and the moment'' and
skewered the ``liberal relativism that has hollowed out the souls
of so many.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's truly big speech, steeped in old-time religion and moral
alarms to the citizenry about everything from evolution to
contraception, from day care to abortion, was to come an hour later
on the floor of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Even opposition Democrats who privately savor DeLay's trademark
political zeal had to look up and listen in wonder as he raged
point blank against modern life and belittled the argument that the
convenient availability of guns was the prime factor in the school
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Glowering, at times fulminating as he put society at large in
the dock, DeLay thoroughly embraced as his own some views what he
said were first penned by a Texan writing a letter to the editor:
``We have sterilized and contracepted our families down to sizes so
small that the children we do have are so spoiled with material
things that they come to equate the receiving of the material with
love.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, anticipating the gun issue as a profitable but
limited agenda item in the elections next year, suddenly were
hearing DeLay sound Joshua's trumpet to a full-scale cultural war
that mainstream Republican presidential candidates like Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas have been shying from.
</P>
<P>
   ``We place our children in day care centers where they learn
their socialization skills among their peers under the law of the
jungle,'' DeLay grumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating ``It could not have been because ...'' as a sardonic
oratorical device, DeLay's causal list for school shootings
featured the argument that ``our school systems teach the children
that they are nothing but glorified apes who are evolutionized out
of some primordial soup of mud.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach our children that there are no laws of morality that
transcend us,'' he continued, ``that everything is relative and
that actions don't have consequence _ what the heck, the president
gets away with it.'' Dripping sarcasm, he concluded, ``No, it must
have been the guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the aisle, Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., rose in rather
delighted opposition to observe wide-eyed, ``I know we've had a lot
of discussion of what was causing the problems here but I just
heard the majority whip say it was Charles Darwin's fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Four blocks from the debate, James J. Baker, the chief lobbyist
for the National Rifle Association, coolly monitored the
preliminary cultural fray as he marshaled a team of a half-dozen
lobbyists on Capitol Hill for the showdown votes on guns, expected
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopping around here,'' he said in a quiet office bunker
above Bullfeathers restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very fluid,'' Baker said as the Republican leadership
flooded the stage with dozens of culture debate proposals and kept
the gun issue waiting in the wings. ``There are all these curve
balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Morning speakers did not wait for the formal opening of the gun
debate as they went after the issue in pro forma one-minute
speeches offered for television markets back home. ``Guns are a
two-edged sword,'' advised one lawmaker. ``Kids, you've seen the
poster!'' another shouted mockingly of the proposal to display the
Ten Commandments in schools. ``Now see the movie star Charlton
Heston, president of the NRA, in a law with loopholes wider than
his parting of the Red Sea!''
</P>
<P>
   In the cultural debate, Democrats and a few Republicans attacked
as clumsy and unconstitutional proposals to try to outlaw
depictions of violence for minors. Proposed definitions of
``mutilation'' and ``flagellation'' in the bill were criticized as
bizarre utterances that should not be debated until after the
children were in bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's nothing in this about spraying 100 people with an
assault weapon,'' exclaimed Howard L. Berman, a California
Democrat, studying the proposal for a reference to the heart of the
matter, the schoolhouse assaults, as the cultural debate wended
into the night.
</P>
<P>
   At each skirmish, DeLay maintained that guns were hardly the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberals demagogue tragedies like school shootings to push a
left-wing agenda,'' he contended, braced for the House debate by a
fresh round of ``Amen!'' and ``Praise Jesus!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
