<HEADER>
A8336 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-SHORTGAME17-     06-16 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-SHORTGAME17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players ready to pitch, putt
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ The U.S. Open usually requires a player to be
part blacksmith and part diamond-cutter. In a typical U.S. Golf
Association setup, strength is required to move the ball from
ankle-deep rough. An equal amount of touch is required to hold and
then putt on devilishly fast greens.
</P>
<P>
   This year, things are different. The man who wins the 1999 U.S.
Open will be the most creative.
</P>
<P>
   In order to win this year's Open at Pinehurst No. 2, golfers
must get the ball up and down from the shaved, sloped areas around
the greens. The greens in Donald Ross' design resemble upside-down
saucers.
</P>
<P>
   Players will use everything to solve the short-game puzzle. Some
will putt from everywhere, adhering to the age-old axiom that a
rotten putt usually beats a bad chip. Some will brandish 3-woods to
make the ball ride above the grass and over the mounds. Some will
pitch into the banks and trickle the ball onto the green.
</P>
<P>
   The occasional daredevil such as Phil Mickelson will even slide
a lob wedge or two underneath the tight bentgrass.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, Masters champion Jose Maria Olazabal, Tiger Woods,
Davis Love III, Payne Stewart, Justin Leonard and Ernie Els should
figure prominently because of the creativity in their short games.
</P>
<P>
   In practice this week, players have experimented at every
opportunity. Ireland's Darren Clarke spent time Wednesday at the
18th green, scooting balls up the steep slope behind the putting
surface with a fairway wood. Woods put in as much time at the
practice areas as he did on the course.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal has worked with every club from a 7-iron to sand wedge.
With two Masters titles, he does not mind Augustalike demands
around the greens; it's better than the high rough of past U.S.
Opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had 5 inches of rough on this golf course and 20-yard
fairways,'' Olazabal said, ``I think Tuesday and Wednesday next
week, we still will be playing golf here.''
</P>
<P>
   The grass used to be spottier at No. 2 when Love III played the
course while in college. Now, the putting surfaces, which were
changed to G-2 bentgrass a few years ago, roll true.
</P>
<P>
   ``The putter is my safest shot, the one I feel more comfortable
with,'' Love said. ``Or if it rolls way down the hill into the
short cut, I've been putting it up with a 3-wood, something I
haven't done much of in the past. . . . The grass is so good and so
tight I don't think I'm going to have much success pitching it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval doesn't use his 3-wood, but when he isn't putting
he'll use a 2- or 3-iron to get above the grass. He also will
consider chipping the ball into the slopes ``and letting it kill it
and bounce it up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every player is going to miss the green,'' Duval said, ``so
you're going to have to be creative and hit a lot of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods enjoys the creativity needed to get up and down from
around the greens. He likes coming up with new methods and always
has been excited about links golf in Europe, where the ball spends
more time on the ground. When Woods faces a chip up a slope that
runs into the grain, he probably will not chip the ball to avoid a
chance of ``stubbing it.'' He will use his putter or 3-wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This golf course from tee to green is very simple,'' he said.
``It's around the green where it becomes complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
