</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND RUSSIAN DEFENSE CHIEFS CITE PROGRESS ON KOSOVO TROOPS
ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ After seven hours of intense talks, Defense
Secretary William Cohen and his Russian counterpart, Marshal Igor
Sergeyev, said Wednesday night that they had made progress toward a
resolution of the touchy issue of Russia's role in the Kosovo
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   But neither side was ready to predict with certainty that a
final agreement would be ready Thursday, when Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov join the
marathon negotiations being held in the Presidential Palace here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we will conclude by tomorrow, but it may take
longer,'' Cohen said at a news briefing late Wednesday night, where
he noted that a number of details were still to be hammered out.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators are under pressure to come up with an agreement by
the weekend, when President Clinton meets President Boris Yeltsin
in Cologne, Germany. Cohen is also due to report on the talks to
the North Atlantic Council in Brussels on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he had been on the phone Wednesday with with NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana, Gen. Wesley Clark, the alliance's
commander, and U.S. military officials, informing them of the
progress of the talks. Some NATO officials had earlier expressed
concern that NATO was not being represented at the U.S.-Russian
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   With Russian paratroopers already on the ground at the airport
in Pristina, the Kosovo capital, the issue of Russia's role has
taken on urgency. In a sudden move that confounded and angered its
Western partners, Russia last weekend speeded up the arrival of its
troops in Kosovo, beating NATO-led forces to the Pristina airfield.
</P>
<P>
   Having presented their U.S. negotiators with a fait accompli,
the Russians are now eager to come up with an agreement. Without an
agreement, countries bordering Yugoslavia _ Hungary, Bulgaria and
Romania _ have said they will not grant air rights to Russian troop
planes. And without more troops, the Russian paratroopers now in
Kosovo are left in an ambiguous and potentially dangerous position
with no clear-cut relationship to the NATO forces around them.
</P>
<P>
   The issues discussed Wednesday by the U.S. and military
delegations _ each with about a dozen members _ included areas of
operations for the Russian troops, their command structure and the
status of the Russians stationed in Pristina, Cohen said Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   He said some issues were closer to a resolution than others _ a
view echoed by Sergeyev, speaking to reporters as he left the
Presidential Palace. But neither would be specific.
</P>
<P>
   Although Russia agreed early in the Kosovo negotiations to take
part in a peacekeeping force, it has consistently opposed sending
its troops to the region under NATO command. For its part, NATO has
insisted that the international force serve under a ``unified
command,'' and has rebuffed Russian proposals for a separate
command structure.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has also opposed suggestions of a Russian-controlled sector
in Kosovo, fearing that it would lead to a de facto partition of
the province. But in the last week, the U.S. position seems to have
softened somewhat, with new proposals for ``areas of
responsibility'' reserved for the Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere in the talks Wednesday was described by Cohen as
``businesslike but quite cordial,'' an improvement over the
tensions that dominated the negotiations in Moscow last week
between Ivanov, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and
military officials. During those talks, Russian officials, speaking
anonymously, criticized the Americans for what they called a rigid
and unconstructive approach that was disdainful of Russian
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving in Helsinki on Wednesday, Sergeyev said he had
received clear instructions from Yeltsin to come up with a way for
Russia to join the peacekeeping force. ``I received Yeltsin's
specific instructions,'' he said, noting that the peacekeeping
operation in Kosovo is of ``unprecedented complexity, and it can be
implemented only jointly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
