<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz rejoins team, reports his elbow is fine
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ John Smoltz rejoined the Braves on Wednesday
afternoon, saying he stayed behind in Atlanta to take care of
personal business and to visit team orthopedist Dr. Joe Chandler,
who checked his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who examined Smoltz's elbow after his first start
since coming off the disabled list on June 1, had been out of town
until Tuesday night when Smoltz went to his house for an informal
exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Joe all the time,'' Smoltz said. ``He said everything
was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz said he is set to make his next start as scheduled on
Friday night in Arizona against the Diamondbacks. He gave up seven
runs in only 2 1/3 innings in his last start Sunday against the
Orioles but has said his elbow was not a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga's prognosis
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga is scheduled to begin 2-3 weeks of radiation
treatment now that his chemotherapy is over, said his Atlanta
teammate Ozzie Guillen, who talks to Galarraga regularly. Guillen
said Galarraga is planning to rejoin the Braves, but not play, in
August for the duration of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga has not been cleared to work out because he has to
give his bones time to heal, Guillen said.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga recently visited doctors in Chicago and got good news
about his treatment for the lymphoma in a bone in his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 98 percent gone,'' Guillen said. ``That's great news.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's hit
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter's game-winning hit on Tuesday night was important
in several ways. Not only did it drive in Otis Nixon for the
winning run but it was Hunter's first at-bat against a right-hander
since getting hit in the face with a Roberto Hernandez fastball
last Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it before I went to the plate,'' said Hunter,
who walked off with nothing more than a bruised upper lip after
being hit. ``Once I got to the plate I thought about getting a hit.
Now I need to see a pitch that's up and in, so I can get everything
back intact, test my reflexes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter admittedly crowds the plate, something he said he's
prepared to do because ``You don't worry about getting hit in the
body,'' he said. ``You can take body shots, but face shots? That's
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving away doesn't pay
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Odalis Perez was fined $360 by the Braves on Wednesday
for throwing dozens of batting practice balls he caught in the
outfield to fans in the crowd. The Braves decided to crack down
after losing a bag and a half of balls during the batting practice
in an April trip to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star Futures
</P>
<P>
   Braves minor leaguers Bruce Chen and Rafael Furcal have been
chosen to play in the All-Star Futures game July 11, which is part
of the festivities leading up to the major league All-Star Game on
July 13 in Boston. The game pits top American minor-league
prospects against their counterparts from foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal, the Class A Macon Braves shortstop from the Dominican
Republic, and Chen the AAA Richmond starter, will play for the
``World'' team. Chen is 5-3 for Richmond with a 3.52 ERA. Furcal
leads all minor leaguers with 57 stolen bases and is hitting .328
in the South Atlantic League.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
