<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-MARKETPLACE     06-16 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: WILL GREENSPAN TELL ALL ON INFLATION? 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ECON-REPORT) 
(DW) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ian Shepherdson, the chief U.S. economist at High
Frequency Economics, is hoping for the ``Full Monty'' on Thursday
when Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, testifies
before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   For Greenspan to bare all his thoughts on the economic outlook
would be startling. Still, that is what the bond and stock markets
want after Wednesday's report that a primary gauge of inflation,
the Consumer Price Index, was unchanged in May, while the core
rate, excluding food and energy, inched up just one-tenth of 1
percent. The news scrambled investor expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Since mid-April bond investors had been doing interest rate fire
drills in preparation for the Federal Reserve's meeting of policy
makers at the end of the month. After all that practice, they had
braced for a quarter-point jump in the short-term interest rate
target.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the incredibly mild May inflation report. It made
April's jump of seven-tenths of 1 percent _ the surge that started
all the fire drills _ look like a fluke, not a trend toward
troublesome inflation.
</P>
<P>
   With that the mood shifted Wednesday in the bond market, which
can change its mind every hour, much less every day, and which
routinely overreacts. A rate increase by the Fed is still expected
this month, but no longer considered ``guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the attitude about a possible second rate
increase in August to further slow economic growth and ward off
inflation has gone from very likely to wait and see. Greenspan
could force a quick revision of that view Thursday in his testimony
about monetary policy before the Joint Economic Committee of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherdson said the benign report on inflation shifted the odds
of a Fed rate increase on June 30 to 50/50 from 80/20. ``I don't
like the uncertainty,'' he said. ``I just want to know, either
way,'' if the Fed is going to sit tight or raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been easier for the markets,'' he said, ``if the
CPI number had been a big plus or a big minus'' and investors could
have been all but certain that the Fed would raise rates _ in the
case of a plus _ or leave them unchanged _ in the case of a
decline.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the inflation report was released by the Labor
Department at 8:30 a.m., the price of the 30-year bond jumped more
than a full point, while the yield, which moves in the opposite
direction, dropped to 6.02 percent, from 6.11 the previous day and
an 18-month high of 6.16 percent last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the 30-year bond gave up half of its early gains later in
the day, with the price rising just 20/32. The yield finished at
6.06 percent. Stocks had a stronger rally.
</P>
<P>
   There is little chance for relief in the bond market until the
Fed chairman speaks. In his three most recent appearances,
Greenspan has done nothing to indicate that the bond market was
wrong to expect a rate increase this month. His silence was
followed by remarks from other members of the Fed, several
considered hawks on inflation and supportive of a rate increase,
who seemed to suggest a Fed move was a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherdson, who forecast an unchanged CPI for May and saw no
need for a rate increase now, said this silence was an indication
that Greenspan would join with the hawks. ``It's a great number,''
he said of the inflation report, ``but I am not sure it's good
enough'' to keep the Fed on hold.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Glassman, senior U.S. economist at Chase Manhattan
Bank, also expects the Fed to raise interest rates this month. But
his argument is based on the rapid pace of economic growth, rather
than on the pace of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   When Fed policy makers announced they were leaning toward a rate
increase in May, they emphasized the ``ongoing strength in demand''
in the United States and the improved foreign economic prospects,
he said. At the same time, they noted that ``trend increases in
costs and core prices have generally remained quite subdued.''
</P>
<P>
   So even though the core rate of inflation has risen just 1.8
percent this year, the fact that the economy is not showing signs
of slowing significantly still gives the Fed a reason to raise
interest rates, in Glassman's view.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Berner, chief U.S. economist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, also argues that inflation is not what will make the Fed
raise rates. He said that the Fed, as officials have signaled
recently, needs to take back some of the three, quarter-point rate
cuts it made last fall, when it moved to calm global financial
markets and to insure that the world's economy would not head into
a downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Now both Asia and Latin America show signs of a turnaround, and
global financial markets have stabilized. Overall consumer
inflation is rising toward 2.5 percent from the 1.6 percent
increase recorded last year. Given that environment, he said the
Fed's short-term interest rate target, which is now 4.75 percent,
is just too low for the present mix of inflation and economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   All three agree that the inflation report _ if it is backed up
in the months ahead _ means that a second rate increase may not be
necessary. The recent jump in certain market barometers showed that
many investors were beginning to bet on two one-quarter rate
increases at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market may move quickly to a view that the Fed won't have
to move any further,'' Glassman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Shepherdson, as he thought of the Fed chairman's testimony
Thursday, said: ``It's completely in Greenspan's court. It's up to
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
