<HEADER>
A8346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEUTSCHE-BANK-PROBE-N     06-16 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHE-BANK-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK OFFICIALS INVESTIGATED IN TAX EVASION CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   German authorities are investigating the chief executive and
five other current and former senior executives of Deutsche Bank AG
for tax evasion, the bank said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The move raises questions about the executives' future and
complicates a recent merger that made Deutsche the world's largest
bank.
</P>
<P>
   None of the executives, including Dr. Rolf Breuer, Deutsche's
chief executive, are accused of personally evading taxes, a bank
spokesman said. Rather, the query stems from a six-year
investigation by state authorities in Germany into whether German
banks helped clients illegally shelter income to avoid taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a technical investigation that involves every big bank
in Germany,'' said Dierk Hartwig, a Deutsche Bank spokesman, in an
interview. ``We feel quite comfortable and are quite sure nothing
will go wrong with the management of Deutsche Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the investigation could have serious implications
for Deutsche Bank and its senior executives. Similar charges
involving another large German bank, Dresdner Bank AG, led to the
resignation of that bank's chief executive, Juergen Sarrazin, in
1997. Earlier this year, Dresdner paid a fine of about $21 million
to settle the charges. Sarrazin also paid a fine and received a
suspended, one-year prison sentence for his role in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the German investigation comes at a time when federal
regulators in the United States have begun re-examining problems
with unclaimed customer funds managed by the Bankers Trust Corp.,
the large American bank that Deutsche bought on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   Unclaimed funds are bank accounts left dormant for a few years;
the money must be turned over to states, which are then responsible
for trying to find the owners. Bankers Trust pleaded guilty in
March to criminal charges of illegally diverting $19.1 million in
cash and other unclaimed funds.
</P>
<P>
   In a public filing with the Department of Labor on June 2
seeking the right to continue managing pensions and other assets,
Bankers Trust noted that it may have to appoint a special
investigator to re-examine the roles played by current Bankers
Trust executives in their internal investigation of the illegal
diversion.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust said it uncovered the fraud in 1996 and quickly
alerted federal authorities. But the extent of the diversion is
much greater than has been publicly disclosed, according to
individuals investigating the bank. New York state alone has
identified more than $41 million owed to it _ more than twice as
much as the bank acknowledged. Some states have started audits into
whether Bankers Trust diverted funds since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust's former chief financial officer, Richard H.
Daniel, resigned from the merged company Wednesday, as reported in
The Wall Street Journal. Daniel was one of the most senior Bankers
Trust officials involved in the investigation of the illegal funds
diversion. A person close to Deutsche said Wednesday that the
Department of Labor has not mentioned Daniel's name as part of
Bankers Trust's application with the agency and that his departure
has nothing to do with that agency's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   At least 12 other Bankers Trust executives are expected to
resign later in the week, but Deutsche Bank declined to say whether
their departures are linked to the illegal funds diversion. Breuer
said in a recent interview that U.S. regulators have granted
Deutsche immunity from any further legal claims relating to the
funds diversion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The charges involving illegal tax diversion in Germany surfaced
after Germany raised capital gains taxes earlier in the decade. As
bank customers looked for ways to shelter that income, German banks
reportedly assisted them by setting up bank accounts in such
tax-free havens as nearby Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Other Deutsche executives who are being investigated in the
alleged scheme include three current board members, Carl von
Boehm-Bezing, Tessen von Heydebreck, and Juergen Krumnow, as well
as two former board members, Georg Krupp and Ulrich Weiss.
Deutsche's Hartwig said German authorities notified the executives
by letter that they were being investigated sometime ``within the
last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Mergers are always thorny affairs, but the various problems
Deutsche is encountering at the management level here and in
Germany make the combination more difficult. Most of the employees
in Bankers Trust's fixed-income unit are being dismissed and
Deutsche faces a potential problem if Bankers Trust employees it
wishes to retain decide to head for the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Other banks said they have been inundated with resumes from
Bankers Trust employees, and many of those banks said they expect
more resumes once Deutsche pays last year's bonuses to Bankers
Trust employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
