<HEADER>
A8350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MOORECOLUMN-ROBIN     06-16 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MOORECOLUMN-ROBINSON17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With feet of clay, Robinson stays his path
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oprah tried, and then she tried some more. She wanted Falcons
safety Eugene Robinson to become the Jimmy Swaggart of the NFL on
her couch. Others, ranging from ESPN to Sports Illustrated to ABC's
``20/20,'' also approached Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   No response. Except for close friends and relatives, Robinson
preferred not to reveal his deepest thoughts on getting arrested on
charges of soliciting a Miami undercover cop for oral sex the night
before the Falcons met the Broncos in the Super Bowl in January.
</P>
<P>
   This was Eugene Keefe Robinson, among the Falcons' primary
leaders. He was a devout family man with a wife and two kids. Not
only that, on the morning of the same day of his trip to Miami's
seedy part of town, he won an award for living his deep-rooted
Christian beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Then something happened. Everybody wanted to know what happened,
but except for a couple of public requests by Robinson for
forgiveness, he mostly has remained silent on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between innocence and righteousness, and
although I was innocent, this is kind of a touchy, iffy
situation,'' Robinson said, his words flowing easily. He sat and
shared his feelings with a visitor in a nearly empty locker room at
the Falcons' headquarters in Suwanee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was down there,'' Robinson said, referring to an area
of Miami known for prostitutes and drug dealers. ``Nobody put a gun
to my head. I was there, and I hollered at (the undercover cop). I
was leaving after that, making my way out, but nobody cares about
that. All they care about is, boom, you were there, and I accept
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson moved closer to the visitor at his locker, before
saying without blinking, ``This is what I've told my friends. 'Hey,
it's on me. Don't look for anybody else. Don't look for any
excuses. I'm the guy. It wasn't a phantom person down there. I'm
telling you this while looking you straight in your eyes, and I'm
asking for your forgiveness.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The early indication is that Robinson's request has been
accepted overwhelmingly. For verification, there is the bulk of his
teammates, still joking with the popular Robinson, still seeking
his advice on matters inside and outside football.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Robinson is amazing onlookers with his work ethic in
the Falcons' current minicamp. ``He's probably in the best shape of
his career,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves said. The 15-year veteran
looks nearly a decade younger than his 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   However, Robinson's teammates remember that his arrest in Miami
damaged their efforts to beat the Broncos. So Robinson took the
same approach with his teammates this spring that he took with
others last winter once he returned to his Seattle home after the
Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And the approach? One-on-one honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way,'' Robinson said, ``if they have any questions, I can
address them at that time. I tell them that we're all human and
we're men. I tell them that I'm sorry and that we need to put this
behind us. I really want them to understand that I'm not cavalier
about this thing, and that I care about what happens with this
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe it, but I've had some of the hardest
dudes on this team tell me, 'Hey, man, you didn't have to do that.
I appreciate you coming to me, because it wasn't necessary.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he heard similar words after he called buddies
around the country to ``dispel all of the myths.'' He had a
confrontation with one of his best friends, who Robinson said was
``disseminating wrong information based on conjecture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to pull him aside,'' Robinson said. ``I told him that it
would be easy for me to be bitter and sad after this, but Satan has
won too many battles. I refuse to let him win any more. My friend
told me that he was extremely sorry, and I told him that we all
make mistakes. The difference is that the sin I committed was out
in the open.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the public, where Robinson said the requests
he gets for signing autographs, working clinics and making
appearances remain at the lofty level of before.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Robinson realizes that his ongoing popularity these
days is spiced with curiosity. Earlier this month, as Robinson made
one of his many roundtrips from Seattle to Atlanta, he heard a
woman whispering to her husband as they left the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned and said, 'How are you doing? I'm Eugene Robinson.
You may have heard about me during the Super Bowl,' `` Robinson
said, smiling. ``Now I could read an awful lot into these
situations, but I refuse to. So I'll break the ice for a person in
a minute. People realize that I'm just a regular dude, and they
also see that I won't be held hostage by this.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither will Robinson's wife, Gia, and their 11-year-old
daughter Brittany and 9-year-old son, Brandon. According to
Robinson, ``It's going great with them (since the incident), but
I've got a lot of work to do. I recognize that, but it's part of
the whole deal.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Robinson's continued belief in Romans 8:28: ``And we know
that all things work together for good to them that love God, to
them who are the called according to his purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My situation dispels the myth that all Christians are
goody-two-shoes, straight-laced and self-righteous,'' Robinson
said. ``This throws some humility in there, and it makes people
realize that I suffer from human frailties like everybody else.
What is getting my wife and I through this situation is nothing but
the grace of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
