</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARGILL EXECUTIVE NAMED IN PRICE-FIXING DOCUMENTS
</P>
<P>
   A senior executive at Archer Daniels Midland told government
investigators that he held secret talks with an executive at
Cargill to rig bids and prices in the citric acid market, according
to recently released documents. Government prosecutors have said
that Cargill did not take part with Archer Daniels and three other
companies in a much broader conspiracy to illegally fix citric acid
prices. But the statements could play a significant role in an
appeal of a class-action suit against Cargill, filed by purchasers
of citric acid who contend they were cheated by the company.
</P>
<P>
   COKE CHIEF APOLOGIZES TO EUROPEANS
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's top executive, M. Douglas Ivester, apologized to
European customers after a growing public outcry over its slow
response to complaints by hundreds of consumers in Belgium of
fever, headaches and nausea.
</P>
<P>
   SOTHEBY'S IN DEAL WITH AMAZON.COM
</P>
<P>
   Five months after announcing a $25 million plan to begin an
on-line auction business, Sotheby's has formed an alliance with
Amazon.com to start selling art and collectibles later this year.
The arrangement combines Amazon's on-line expertise and broad
customer reach with Sotheby's reputation as an authority in the
business of selling fine and decorative arts. Shares of Sotheby's
rose $4.125 yesterday, to $39.25, while Amazon.com rose $15.1875,
to $111.6875.
</P>
<P>
   85 PEOPLE INDICTED IN STOCK CASE
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials announced the indictments of 85 people who
they said had swindled thousands of unwary investors out of more
than $100 million by manipulating the stocks of small and start-up
companies.
</P>
<P>
   QWEST CLOSE TO ALLIANCE WITH CISCO
</P>
<P>
   Qwest Communications International is close to a partnership
worth up to $1 billion with Cisco Systems, the maker of data
communications gar. Under the agreement, Cisco will supply
equipment while the two companies develop advanced communications
services based on Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS SOAR; NASDAQ GAIN A RECORD
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index chalked up its biggest one-day point
gain, 103.16 points, or 4.27 percent, to 2,517.83. The Dow Jones
industrial average climbed 189.96 points, or 1.79 percent, to
10,784.95, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed
29.25 points, or 2.25 percent, to 1,330.41.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE AND WIRELESS SEEKS LINKS
</P>
<P>
   Having beaten Japan's hometown favorite, Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone, in a hostile takeover battle for International Digital,
the British giant, Cable and Wireless, is now in talks to develop
links to local carriers, the head of its global business
operations, Stephen Pettit, said. He did not identify the carriers.
The company needs the links to avoid high access charges.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT WITNESS CITES CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   At its antitrust trial, Microsoft presented its leading
character witness, Gordon E. Eubanks Jr., who portrayed the
software business as an entrepreneurial hotbed, fast-changing and
fluid. Today's dominant company can quickly become tomorrow's
also-ran, he said.
</P>
<P>
   SPORT UTILITY BUMPERS CALLED WEAK
</P>
<P>
   The bumpers on sport utility vehicles tend to be weak, allowing
more damage to occur in low-speed collisions than bumpers on cars,
an insurance industry group said.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO PAPER UP FOR SALE
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Chronicle Publishing said they were exploring the
sale of all or some of the company, which includes The San
Francisco Chronicle, one of the last family-owned newspapers in the
country.
</P>
</TEXT>
