<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOMETOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG SHADOWS OVER POPE'S BOYHOOD HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (with POPE) 
 (bl)  
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WADOWICE, Poland _ As he stood in the main square of his home
town Wednesday night, surrounded by a few surviving old friends and
thousands of cheering local believers, John Paul II departed from
his prepared text and reminisced. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He recalled joyous times, and also the dark days of World War
II, when many of his Jewish friends and neighbors disappeared. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out one building, and said, ``In this house lived
Jurek Kluger,'' without explaining that Kruger was a boyhood friend
who barely survived the Holocaust and now lives in Rome and has
remained close. Later he mentioned his own house, which is now a
museum of the pope's early life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This house, this house where I lived, belonged to Mr. Chaim
Balamuth,'' the pope said. ``I don't know what became him. I think
he died,'' he said to a suddenly silent audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that the Jews of Wadowice endured hard trials. Many
were killed in ghettos and then in camps, because of extermination
acts of the Hitler regime.''
</P>
<P>
   An answer to the pope's rumination about his landlord, whose
name was actually Yechiel Balamuth, was sent June 2 in a letter to
the Vatican by Ron Balamuth, a grandson. Balamuth explained how his
grandfather had died in the Belzec death camp in Poland, and how he
and other surviving grandchildren had been unable to regain title
to the house. A copy of the letter was also sent to The New York
Times on Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past three decades, we have written letters to the
Vatican, who redirected us to the Polish municipality, who then
directed us to the archbishop of Krakow, who again referred us to
the Polish authorities.'' Belamuth wrote. ``We had many lawyers and
other people of influence try and bring this sad case to your
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that you are appalled by the injustice that was done
to our family and we have faith that you will find the appropriate
way of rectifying those past wrongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone Wednesday night, the pope's spokesman,
Joaquin Navarro-Valls, said he was unaware of the letter, but said
he would check into the matter. He noted that restitution is under
the jurisdiction of local and national authorities in Poland. ``The
Vatican is not involved in this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Balamuth said Wednesday night that he was unaware
that the pope had referred to his grandfather. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pope used the name Chaim Balamuth, who was actually
Yechiel's son, who lived in the same house and was 13 years older
than the pope. The pope's family rented rooms in the house, at 5
Ringplatz, until he and his father moved to Krakow in 1938, a year
before the war began.
</P>
<P>
   Yechiel Balamuth, his wife and three daughters all died in the
Nazi camp at Belzec. The son, Chaim, ended up in a Soviet labor
camp and emigrated to Israel after the war. He died there in 1969. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our family's wish,'' Balamuth wrote, ``that the fact
that both my grandparents, their three daughters and their husbands
and children were exterminated in Nazi death camps will be very
prominently acknowledged and memorialized at the house, which
currently serves exclusively as a pilgrimage site for Catholics who
wish to visit Your Highness' birth place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
