<SLUG> BC-COKE-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE'S CHIEF APOLOGIZES FOR RESPONSE ON CONTAMINATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Luxembourg, Belgium, Germany, the Netherlands)   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Coca-Cola's top executive apologized to
European customers Wednesday night in response to a growing public
outcry over its slow response to a soft-drink contamination that
apparently made hundreds of people sick in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The apology by M. Douglas Ivester, chairman and chief executive
of Coca-Cola, the world's leading soft-drink company, came as
French government officials said that 80 people there had
complained about nausea, fever and headaches. French stores removed
more than 50 million bottles and cans from shelves Wednesday, and
bans on the sale of Coca-Cola products remained in force for a
second day in France, Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Coke executives in Paris Wednesday afternoon,
French officials refused to relax their prohibition and delayed any
public comment until Thursday. Officials in the three other nations
said they were awaiting more information from the company about
what exactly had caused the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the authorities began checking the origin of Coke
products and removing any that had been bottled in France or
Belgium. A growing number of consumer groups in Germany and
elsewhere complained that Coca-Cola had been opaque and
unreassuring in its public explanations.
</P>
<P>
   The company's trouble comes at a time Belgium is reeling from a
scandal over cattle infected with dioxin, a cancer-causing chemical
that contaminated feed grain used on many Belgian farms. The
scandal forced the resignation of Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dahaene,
as well as the nation's health minister.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes amid an increasingly heated argument between
Europeans and the United States over American-produced genetically
modified food products, which many Europeans want to ban, and over
hormone-treated beef, which is before the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the concern in Europe, Coke's chief, Ivester,
released a statement from the company's Atlanta headquarters
Wednesday seeking to reassure customers. ``The Coca-Cola Company's
highest priority is the quality of our products,'' he said. ``One
hundred thirteen years of our success has been based on the trust
consumers have in that quality. That trust is sacred to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Promising to thoroughly investigate, he said company executives
``deeply regret any problems encountered by our European consumers
in the past few days.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone of his remarks were considerably more conciliatory than
the response from company executives in Brussels, who had insisted
that Coca-Cola Company drinks did not pose a health problem despite
the complaints of nausea and headaches. The company has attributed
the reactions to what it called bad carbon dioxide used at a plant
in Antwerp, Belgium, and to fungicide from packing crates found on
cans at the French port in Dunkirk.
</P>
<P>
   But Coke executives in Europe did little public campaigning to
reassure consumers. There were no signs Wednesday of advertising
and or more comprehensive explanations of how the problem was to be
solved. ``I have the strong feeling that nobody is really
informed,'' said Ivo Mechels, a spokesman for Test-Achats, a
nonprofit consumer research organization in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Those views were echoed in Germany. ``We couldn't get any
information from the company until we had made scores of calls,''
said Kristiana Schaefer, a nutritional scientist at the Consumer
Center, a government-financed consumer advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people in Belgium, including 38 schoolchildren,
complained of fever, nausea and headaches after drinking Coke
products on Monday. Belgium ordered all Coke products off store
shelves on Monday, followed up by France, Luxembourg and the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   The bans affect all Coke drinks, as well as most of the
company's other soft drinks and juices: Diet Coke, Fanta, Sprite,
mineral water and Minute Maid fruit juices.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, where Coca-Cola operates 32 bottling plants,
government inspectors found no signs of contamination today and
said drinks bottled in the country were still safe. But they warned
about products bottled in Belgium or France and brought over the
border. In the city of Trier, local officials seized 2,500 cans
with French markings.
</P>
<P>
   Although the problem affects less than 1 percent of Coca-Cola's
global sales, it is the biggest product recall in the company's
history. It remains unclear how seriously it will affect Coca-Cola
over the longer term.
</P>
<P>
   Robin S. Socha, a consultant at Control Risks Germany, which
advises corporations on responding to crises, said companies were
frequently caught between the desire to inform their customers and
their fear of losing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``In crises like this one, a company has to draw a line,'' the
consultant said. ``It has to take care of its business and protect
its clients at the same time. Whatever they say, they will either
anger customers by saying too little or endanger their business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
