<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EURO-1STLEDE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Problems called part of political tapestry
 &HT;    EDs: 1ST UPDATE; changes throughout
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The harsh reaction in Europe to the Coca-Cola health
scare should be seen in the context of politics and not as part of
a wave of anti-Americanism, experts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't jump to the idea that sees this as an attack on a
multinational,'' said Robert B. Zoellick, counselor and
undersecretary for economic and agricultural affairs at the State
Department during the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   Zoellick, now associated with the Washington-based Center for
Strategic and International Studies, attributed Belgium's quick ban
on Coke products to rising concern in Europe about food poisoning
and environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, the media and government have for months been locked
in nasty debate over safety of genetically modified food, a fairly
common and noncontroversial part of American diets. Additionally,
fears over ``mad cow disease'' still ripple through European food
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Europe is being reassembled under a unified economy,
there is no independent central authority for assuring food safety.
In the absence of such a body, food scares often become hot
political weapons.
</P>
<P>
   John McIntyre, director of the Georgia Tech Center for
International Business Education and Research, said the Coke ban is
part of a ``power play'' between national governments and the
European Union's consumer affairs commission over control of food
regulations. The Belgian government apparently moved decisively
with the expectation that the EU would act if it didn't, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're (Europeans) very jittery,'' McIntyre added.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre said Coca-Cola's relations with the Europeans were
already strained. The Atlanta-based company has angered the EU by
trying to ``pick off one country at a time'' with proposed
acquisitions of beverage operations, instead of going to the
European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bromis Verhage, marketing professor at Georgia State
University, said Coca-Cola's management showed a ``lack of
sensitivity'' by not taking decisive action more quickly after
initial reports that 100 Belgian schoolchildren had taken ill,
given the fact that ``the whole country is sensitive to food
poisoning.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Other companies should learn from Coke's experience, Verhage
said. ``It seems that every company should pull out its crisis plan
and be very sensitive when problems like this occur.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Zoellick added, ``The basic lesson is react quickly to restore
public confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
