<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOW TO CONGRESS ENDS A THREAT TO HIS NOMINATIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has promised to make no more
appointments when Congress is in recess without notifying Senate
leaders before the recess. In response, a Republican senator
Wednesday withdrew his threat to block all presidential
nominations, including that of Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers to be Treasury Secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The snarl developed after Clinton, on June 4 with Congress on a
10-day recess for Memorial Day, appointed James Hormel to be
ambassador to Luxembourg. Under the Constitution, the president may
make recess appointments when the Senate is not in session to vote
on confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel is the first openly gay U.S. ambassador. The heir to his
family's meat-packing fortune, he has been a big contributor to gay
organizations and Democrats. Republican leaders have refused for
two years to allow a vote on his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged by what he called ``flagrant abuse of the recess
appointment power,'' Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., announced on June
8 that he would exercise his prerogative to hold up all
presidential nominations, and no confirmation votes have been held
since.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the prospect that Summers might not be confirmed, the
international financial markets fluttered briefly after Inhofe's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Hormel appointment, Clinton had followed a practice
dating from the Reagan administration of notifying Senate leaders
before a recess if he intended to make a recess appointment. In the
case of Hormel, however, the leaders were not notified until June
3, the night before the appointment was made, when the Senate had
already been in recess for almost a week.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated June 15 to Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the
majority leader, Clinton essentially said he would not do this
again. Hormel can remain ambassador until the 106th Congress
adjourns in fall 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``My administration has made it a practice to notify Senate
leaders in advance of our intentions in this regard, and this
precedent will continue to be observed,'' Clinton wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe, who never had the full support of Republican leaders,
said he was satisfied. ``My holds were never designed to undo the
appointment of Mr. Hormel,'' the senator said. ``They were designed
to uphold the Senate's proper role in the `advise and consent'
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not explained why he broke practice in the case of
Hormel. Presumably, it was out of exasperation. Although a majority
of Senators have said they would vote to confirm Hormel, many
conservative Republicans object. Bowing to their wishes, the
party's leaders refused to allow a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe has called Hormel ``a gay activist who puts his agenda
ahead of the agenda of America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
