<SLUG> BC-MICROTEL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. Franchise enters Honduras
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ U.S. Franchise Systems (ticker symbol USFS), whose
stock has jumped from a low of $4 in September to more than $20
now, said Wednesday that a Microtel Inn &AMP; Suites has opened in San
Pedro Sula, Honduras. It is the first hotel property in Latin
America that carries a U.S. Franchise Systems brand name.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-room hotel is owned by Connor/Jacobson Hotels, which also
has a license with U.S. Franchise Systems to develop nearly a dozen
hotels in Costa Rica, El Salvador, Nicaragua and Panama over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The financial markets are such in Latin America that a lot of
development depends on what the economic situation is at the
moment,'' said Michael Leven, chief executive officer of
Atlanta-based U.S. Franchise Systems. The company franchises
Microtel, Hawthorn Suites and Best Inns &AMP; Suites brands.
</P>
<P>
   The company will not own or manage any of the properties in
Latin America, which has the potential for as many as 30 sites
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the brand to be in major cities and near airports so
they can be exposed to travelers who are moving from country to
country,'' Leven said. ``The objective here is to get the brand
name, Microtel, in front of as many travel agents and consumers as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they are in the very, very early stages of what
they could potentially do internationally,'' said John J. Rohs, an
analyst with Schroder Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Honduras Microtel is only the second international hotel
franchised by U.S. Franchise Systems now open. A Hawthorn Suites is
in operation in Tel Aviv, Israel. The company has agreements on
planned hotels in Brazil and Argentina and is in talks with
prospective franchisees in Mexico, southern Africa, Canada and
Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a question, an important part of this is that the
company has emerged firmly into profit territory after a first
couple of years of start-up losses,'' said Rohs. ``They've
eliminated the doubts that some non-believers had of the ability of
this company to be profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Franchise Systems stock closed Wednesday at $20.12 1/2, up
62 1/2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
