s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-VANDYCK-2TAKES-$A     06-16 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-VANDYCK-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PORTRAITIST WHO BLENDED DELICACY AND GRANDEUR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes his royal patron was slow to pay, but in the main
England was good to Anthony Van Dyck. He first crossed the Channel
at age 21, summoned to the court of James I as the outstanding
disciple of the magisterial Rubens and already a star in his own
right. That brief stay, from late 1620 into early 1621, was a
prelude to his reign as ``principalle Paynter in ordinary their
Majesties,'' beginning in 1632.
</P>
<P>
   Charles I, a sovereign whose passion for art was no pose, made
him Sir Anthony that same year. Apart from an interval back home in
Brabant from early 1634 to early 1635, Van Dyck remained in England
for the rest of his too brief life. Death claimed him at home in
Blackfriars in 1641. His bones lie at St. Paul's.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Antwerp ever neglected or forgot him. On the town's
Fifth Avenue, the Meir, the casual stroller will discover a
handsome bronze presenting the native son as a gentleman of
youthful yet self-possessed aspect, feathered hat in hand, sporting
the mustaches and pointed tuft on the chin to which he gave his
name. A more compulsive observer soon spots Antoon van Dijck
Straat, the birthhouse of Antoon van Dijck, the Sir Anthony Van
Dijck Restaurant and the Ijssalon Van Dijck (an ice-cream parlor),
the Residence Van Dyck (an apartment house), Van Dyck Glass and
Mirrors, and who knows what other more casual memorials. (After a
while, the motley spellings cease to jar.)
</P>
<P>
   What one does not find in any notable profusion in Antwerp are
Van Dyck paintings. True, the Royal Museum of Fine Arts has a late
``Lamentation'' (1635), a prize example of the painter's sacred
style, holding an eloquent balance of dignity and tenderness. Nor
is his handiwork entirely absent from the churches. But when the
world thinks of Van Dyck, the world thinks above all of the
portraits, in particular the full-length likenesses of the rich and
mighty of England and the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   The bias in Anglo-Saxon territories favors his second English
period, which set the stage for Gainsborough and Reynolds. The
mind's eye of the Italian, by the same token, conjures up the
legacy of the years Van Dyck flourished in Genoa and Palermo,
emulating the genius of Titian.
</P>
<P>
   At the last major Van Dyck show, in Genoa in 1997, the signori
of the 1620s foregathered from every point of the compass in
gorgeously festive assembly. Not to be outdone, Antwerp celebrates
the 400th anniversary of the artist's birth with the richest
panorama of his work Europe has seen in a century. The main event,
at the Royal Museum of Fine Arts, presents the top of his line:
some 100 of his roughly 800 surviving canvases (through Aug. 15; at
the Royal Academy, London, Sept. 16 to Dec. 15).
</P>
<P>
   Over the same period, the Rubens House displays Van Dyck's
landscape sketches, watercolors of unknown purpose, presumably
executed for his private delight and perhaps distributed among
friends as gifts. This material, mostly from the British Museum, is
the rarest of the rare.
</P>
<P>
   Some two dozen of only 30 known sheets will be on view,
supporting the thesis that Van Dyck was Europe's first plein-air
artist and provoking the great question: why? We associate the
phrase more readily with Constable or the Barbizon School. On
canvas, for Van Dyck, as for Giorgione, Titian and Veronese,
landscape meant background.
</P>
<P>
   A third show, at the Platin-Moretus Museum, focuses on Van
Dyck's etchings, deluxe wares for the collectors market, exemplary
in quality but to modern eyes rather antiquarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best student.'' Thus Rubens described Van Dyck at the age
of 19, and the tag never came unstuck. Maybe now it will. In any
case, the translation is open to question. Writing in Italian,
Rubens used the word discipolo, which covers a range of meanings
from pupil to follower to assistant. Certainly, it was never the
putdown it sounds like.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two years Van Dyck's senior, a linguist, antiquarian and
diplomat as well as an artist, with prestige to burn and a thriving
studio of assistants, Rubens appraised the field from the
perspective of his own lofty eminence. His ``best student'' was one
whose work he could recommend to the notice of an important
collector, though of course the master would expect to apply
finishing touches with his own hand.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Van Dyck had by this time already registered _ a very
young master indeed _ with Antwerp's Guild of St. Luke's. Before
long, he would be setting up a studio of his own. Surely the words
of Rubens are best understood as a combination of salesmanship with
avuncular metaphor. Though the evidence of Van Dyck's sketchbooks
shows him to have enjoyed unparalleled visiting privileges at the
Rubens studio from his youngest years, he actually served his
apprenticeship with Hendrik van Balen I, now scarcely remembered
even by specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best student'' _ it took singular talent to earn that
compliment. Yet for all the lessons in stagecraft, color and
lighting Van Dyck had the skill to absorb, the elder artist's
sensibility left the discipolo untouched. The art of Rubens is an
art of muchness _ muchness to the point of surfeit, and often. In
celebrating Marie de Medici _ widow of Henri IV, mother of Louis
XIII and dreadnought regent through the perilous years of his
minority _ he decked out history in mythological trappings so
extravagant that even the tragic episodes verge on comedy for the
gods. (The gargantuan series now hangs at the Louvre.)
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities to strike such pompous themes never came his way.
While he excelled in all other princely genres, history painting _
the pinnacle of his aspirations _ was not to be his metier. Even if
it had, such theatrics from his hand are scarcely conceivable.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the older artist, Van Dyck tempered grandeur with
delicacy. Against the ruddy Olympian vigor of Rubens, he displays
an aristocratic refinement. The upholstered females and unbuttoned
menfolk of Rubens reflect a ravenous personality, in love with
flesh, quick to seize it with both hands. The imagery bespeaks the
pleasures of touch; the figures seem modeled first and colored
later, the hectic skin tones laid on like too much rouge.
(Tellingly enough, Rubens dabbled in sculpture.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyck's vision, however, is diaphanous. His brush, like those
of his exact contemporary Velasquez and the incomparable Titian
before them, captures an image as impalpably yet as entirely as the
eye itself.
</P>
<P>
   In some artists who share it, though not in these three, this
property of unmediated perception entails a clinician's
abstraction: the glare of the mirror or chill of the scalpel. In
Van Dyck, it takes on a discreet benevolence, easy to reconcile
with the observant yet respectful, vulnerable air of the
self-portraits from different stages of his career.
</P>
<P>
   On a quick reading of his portraits of others, a viewer's
attention may seize on details of costume: light yet luxurious
fabrics of dress and coat, feathery laces of cuff and collar. To
meet the people, we must pause. At first glance, the expressions of
Van Dyck's grandees may seem bland: poised yet relaxed in a manner
calculated to please the subject. And why not? Van Dyck prospered
by catering to the prosperous. The job was not to read their minds
but to show them to advantage: picture-perfect, their social masks
firmly in place. Yet again and again, with exquisite tact, Van Dyck
found ways to reveal the living face.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt this was easier when painting a member of his
professional circle. At the Frick Collection in Manhattan, Van
Dyck's portrait of Frans Snyders, a fellow artist in Antwerp who
specialized in still lifes and animal paintings, conveys, as well
as the sitter's thoughtfulness and probity, the portraitist's
affection.
</P>
<P>
   In the half-length Thomas Howard, Second Earl of Arundel, on
loan to Antwerp from the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles, too
much sympathy would have been presumption. But Van Dyck spied in
that mighty patron an incongruous wariness and let it show, neither
flattering nor criticizing. The full-length Henry Danvers, Earl of
Danby, from the Hermitage in St. Petersburg, touches lightly on the
fragility of the man beneath the weight of his court dress and the
heavy chain of the Order of the Golden Fleece.
</P>
<P>
   The full-length triple portrait, ``The Balbi Children,'' from
the National Gallery in London, finds the young subjects on their
best behavior by a pair of classical columns, yet here, too, the
result is generously humane. Prince Ruprecht of the Palatinate,
from the Museum of Art History in Vienna, presents a pale,
melancholy lad of regal consequence: a Danvers in the making,
perhaps, rather sad though not pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere, though, do Van Dyck's gifts of heart and eye converge
with greater felicity than in his state portraits of parents with
children. The Antwerp show illustrates the point many times over
with masterpieces from the world's richest storehouses, but the
case may also be made from three canvases from the permanent
collection of the Louvre. The hand of a woman in a portrait from
the second Antwerp period clutches the arm of her chair, betraying
her tension under the artist's scrutiny, but her brow is smooth and
her lips stir with barely suppressed amusement as her overdressed
toddler barges in for attention.
</P>
<P>
   In a pendant portrait, a gentleman receives a similar visit, and
his features light up with affection. The son of a third sitter has
the greater patience and polished manners of an older boy; his
presence fills his father with quiet pride. The intimacy between
generations _ so injurious to the propriety insecure grownups cling
to among their peers _ dispels the tedium of the long sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Within the framework of timeless formality, Van Dyck catches a
flash of the candid. In the Antwerp selection, such freshness
appears, too, in the magnificent Queen Henrietta Maria with Sir
Jeffrey Hudson, from the National Gallery in Washington, which is
not quite the picture it seems. His cherubic visage and neat
proportions notwithstanding, Sir Jeffrey is not a child but a
dwarf, whose license to create mischief at court appears in the
visible form of his pet monkey, restrained by the queen's ivory
hand.
</P>
<P>
   From Queen Elizabeth II come no fewer than three canvases of
Charles I: one in the robes of the Order of the Garter, another on
horseback attended by an equerry and the third a tour de force
showing Van Dyck's royal patron in three positions. Her Majesty is
also sending one of several treatments of ``St. Martin Dividing His
Cloak'' (another very youthful and very poignant one may be seen on
the way to the Brussels airport at St. Martin's Church in the
village of Zaventem) and a ``Cupid and Psyche.''
</P>
<P>
   Loans from sources in Brussels; Dresden, Germany; Genoa, Italy;
Kortrijk, Belgium; London; Madrid and Paris round out the picture
with examples in the artist's sacred and profane, biblical and
mythological veins.
</P>
<P>
   As the world can hardly fail to see in the presence of such
evidence, Rubens' best student was at heart his own best teacher,
as true masters must be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
