<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-RESEARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER MEDICINE ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Science, like every other field, is being transformed by the
computer age, and as is true in all human endeavors _ even one
committed to pushing back the frontiers of knowledge _ the old
guard is resisting change.
</P>
<P>
   A stern editorial in last week's New England Journal of Medicine
criticized Dr. Harold Varmus, director of the National Institutes
of Health, for his forward-looking proposal to establish a Web site
to disseminate research papers more quickly than the laborious
print publication process allows.
</P>
<P>
   The lag between acceptance and publication can be a year or more
_ too slow for galloping developments in genetic engineering and
disease research.
</P>
<P>
   But The New England Journal of Medicine, like The Journal of the
American Medical Association and others, has long traded on being
the venerable gatekeeper for research. The notion that a paper
could appear on a Web site almost as soon as the authors finished
writing it is anathema to these editors, who fear losing not only
control but revenue to a free-wheeling Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They should relax. Varmus is not excluding them. He proposes a
two-tiered system for publication on the Web site, dubbed
``E-biomed.'' The first tier would follow tradition, posting papers
vetted by scientific journals _ but posting them immediately upon
acceptance. The second tier would bypass that strict review process
and include partial research, follow-ups on previous papers,
developments in arcane subfields, and even experiments that failed,
on the theory that blind alleys can teach a person as much as a
``Eureka!''
</P>
<P>
   Web site postings could include extensive supporting data, even
films and recordings, and would encourage immediate feedback. True,
some junk may get out there, but it's out there now. Varmus, who
calls for an interdisciplinary governing board to oversee the Web
site, is also asking for suggestions on how to make his fine idea
work.
</P>
<P>
   Journal editors should support him and relish the adventure of
change. Evolution is not only inevitable but usually makes survival
a lot easier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
