<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRASS-ROOTS POLITICS LOOKS FOR AN OPENING IN SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ When a small number of residents of Cacak
gathered for a weekly prayer session during the NATO bombing
campaign, they immediately came under police surveillance. When
they started daily meetings in the Town Hall, the organizers were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Grass-roots politics is barely alive in Serbia. Despite the
widespread dissatisfaction with the leadership of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, the chances for rapid change are
small, two leaders of popular movements said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As it became clearer that Milosevic has arranged a deal with the
Radical Party of Serbia, led by Vojislav Seselj, to prevent it from
leaving the government and preserve the status quo, the democratic
opposition faced one option, to go to the streets. For the moment,
however, that is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Verica Barac, a lawyer employed by the Cacak City Council, is an
organizer of the Civic Parliament, a group set up by residents of
Cacak, 60 miles south of Belgrade, to create a forum for freedom of
speech. She was arrested with five others for holding an illegal
gathering and has seen her forum dwindle in recent weeks under
police repression.
</P>
<P>
   The police have been given added powers under the state of war
declared by the government shortly after NATO began its bombing,
and they can grant or deny permission for any demonstration or
public gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Dragoljub Stosic, a former bus driver and the president of the
Union of Free Trade Unions of Yugoslavia, is fighting 100 court
cases for union members who have been discharged because of their
association with his organization.
</P>
<P>
   Stosic and Ms. Barac say it will take prolonged protests to
remove Milosevic or even push him toward political change. But they
say that right now they cannot begin to rally people.
</P>
<P>
   The Civic Parliament of Cacak drew 500 people at its peak a
month ago, before the police began their arrests, Ms. Barac said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people from all across the social spectrum,'' she
said in an interview in Belgrade on Wednesday. ``And we saw that
beside their great fear most of the people understand that
something is wrong, because over the last 10 years we have been
living worse and worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is not to fight for power. But our forum is trying to
enable citizens to gather on squares and speak freely, as in
classic democracies.''
</P>
<P>
   They chose prayer meetings to counter the government's
organizing of daily pop concerts on the main square in Belgrade
during the war, she said. ``We think that the terrible things that
happened to us over the last 10 years were caused by our silence,''
Ms. Barac added.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all her modest aims, she and five other Civic Parliament
members were arrested by police May 23 and given heavy fines for
participating in an illegal gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Since the arrests, a few people have braved the police
harassment. The democratic opposition runs the Cacak City Council
but has been powerless in the face of the security forces.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the council, Mayor Velimir Ilic, has disappeared. He
is widely thought to have fled to neighboring Montenegro after
police had issued an order for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   An eminent university professor has been put on trial, and the
police have called in and interviewed a number of members of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Extensive demonstrations are required to bring about political
change, Ms. Barac said, and that can occur only when the government
lifts the state of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will have to go out onto the streets, because
without massive majority pressure on the government even the most
basic things cannot be changed,'' she said. ``It might seem that
the government is so strong. But with the lifting of the state of
war, people will surely go out on the streets to show that they are
not stupid and that they will not put up with calling this a
victory, a situation in which we lost part of our territory and
suffered this whole tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stosic said people were primed for a popular explosion after the
debacle in Kosovo. ``Public opinion is already changing,'' he said.
``And what has happened now is the last drop in the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   His union has 5,000 members and was at the forefront of the
democratic demonstrations in 1996. Asked whether he was going to
organize demonstrations again, he said, ``We are going to lead the
river of dissatisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned that several thousand army and police officers were
going to arrive in Serbia in a few days, displaced from their
houses in Kosovo, and that could cause unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot tell you their attitude,'' Stosic said. ``But I can
tell what their mood will be when they realize they were
double-crossed and no one will help them but themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   He also warned that workers would start to feel the double
effects of sanctions and bombing, as industries will not be able to
resurrect themselves without outside investment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Stosic can only wait and hope that the state of war is
lifted, so he can start to organize demonstrations. ``We are going
to need civic protest as in 1996,'' he said, ``and as far as I am
concerned, we are not going to stop until there are really
significant changes. I expect great changes in the next few
months.''
</P>
<P>
   He describes Milosevic's Yugoslavia as the last communist
bastion in Europe. Stosic's hope is for changes, in the footsteps
of the Polish Solidarity movement or the Czech model of a velvet
revolution, where churches, trade unions, universities and ordinary
citizens rallied together.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he conceded that the opposition was virtually powerless.
``It seems this government is strong,'' Stosic said. ``It is as
strong as we are weak.''
</P>
<P>
   But worse, Serbian society is hopelessly confused and divided.
``This evil has continued for so long that the people are
disoriented,'' Stosic said, adding that he was worried that
unhappiness could result in serious unrest or even civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
