<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAULDER-EXECUTION17-C     06-16 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAULDER-EXECUTION17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faulder to be executed amid an international furor
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _In 1977, when Joseph Stanley Faulder was first
convicted of killing an East Texas widow in a botched robbery, the
case seemed fairly open and shut.
</P>
<P>
   Bent on stealing cash he thought she had stashed in a floor
safe, then angered when he found it empty, two Texas juries
determined that Faulder had bound and gagged Inez Phillips with
tape, then beat her on the head with a blackjack and stabbed her. A
maid found Phillips' body the next day, a knife protruding from her
chest.
</P>
<P>
   For that, jurors thought Faulder should pay the ultimate price:
death by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's attempts to avoid execution, scheduled for 6 p.m.,
have been pegged not on innocence but on diplomatic mistakes, a
200-year-old federal law, a discredited Texas psychiatrist and
assertions that, because he suffered a serious brain injury when he
was a child, he may be a victim of the most active capital
punishment machine in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has been through every facet that it could possibly
go through,'' said Odis Hill, the former Gregg County district
attorney who prosecuted Faulder. ``I'll be glad when this thing
comes to a conclusion that the jury has determined.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Faulder, 61, moved several steps closer to the
lethal needle. The U.S. Supreme Court and the 5th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals rejected his latest appeals and the Texas Board of
Pardons and Paroles refused to recommend clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``His arguments were not compelling,'' Parole Board Chairman
Victor Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush hinted that he will not intervene. ``I have
seen no new evidence that questions the jury's verdict that he is
guilty of this crime. In fact, his request for commutation was not
based on any claim of innocence,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   A former auto mechanic who was convicted at two separate trials
and has spent 22 years on Texas' death row, Faulder two weeks ago
refused to discuss his case with parole board members and instead
railed against the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin state and federal courts, Faulder's attorneys tried
unsuccessfully to have Texas' secret clemency system declared
unconstitutional. They also unsuccessfully raised questions about
the testimony by Dr. James Grigson, a psychiatrist who labeled
Faulder a sociopath after interviewing him for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Grigson, once nicknamed Dr. Death because of the testimony he
offered against suspects in 400 capital murder cases, was expelled
from the American Psychiatric Association in 1995 amid controversy
over his ability to make such predictions. In a recent interview
with the Toronto Star, Grigson said he stood by his assessment of
Faulder.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's lawyers also have argued his execution should be
stopped because police did not give Faulder, a Canadian citizen,
the opportunity to contact Canadian diplomats after his arrest _ a
right guaranteed foreign citizens under a 1963 international treaty
called the Vienna Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Had Faulder been able to contact Canadian diplomats in Texas,
his attorneys argue, he could have gotten help preparing his
defense _ including evidence of the head injury he suffered when he
fell out of a car in 1941 at age 4. His lawyers believe that
evidence could have prevented the death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   By age 9, he was having seizures blamed on the head injury, and
doctors said he had erratic brain-wave patterns. As a teen-ager, he
was repeatedly in trouble for fights and stealing. By the time he
was 25, had had been in prison twice for car theft.
</P>
<P>
   While Faulder's attorneys insist his brain injury could have
triggered violent impulses, a key question remains: Did Faulder
murder Phillips during such an impulse?
</P>
<P>
   No way, say investigators and prosecutors in the case. By all
indications his behavior on the day of the killing was more
criminal that mental, and he wasn't high on drugs or alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the diplomatic mistake and head injury have become
focal points in an international controversy over the case _ with
an array of Canadian officials and lawmakers, the human rights arm
of the Organization of American States, even U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright weighing in on Faulder's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Faulder went to court in Houston seeking to block
his execution under the Alien Tort Claims Act, a 200-year-old
federal law that allows foreign citizens to sue U.S. officials if
they have been harmed by breaches of treaties. A federal judge
refused to block Faulder's execution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
