<HEADER>
A8371 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINATRA-IMITATOR-ART-     06-16 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINATRA-IMITATOR-ART-580(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFELONG FAN BRINGS SINATRA'S STYLE TO A MANHATTAN NIGHTCLUB
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a teen-ager in the late 1950s, Cary Hoffman spent
hours locked away in his bedroom listening to Frank Sinatra on his
phonograph. He was an awkward and lonesome kid, but the Sinatra
songs could make him feel as if he had the world on a string and
was sitting on a rainbow with the string around his finger.
</P>
<P>
   Like others who resisted his era's lure of rock and roll, he
longed to swagger like Sinatra, to be in the middle of a big band
with a strutting Nelson Riddle arrangement belting songs like
``Night and Day'' and ``I've Got You Under My Skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those other teen-agers, Hoffman actually tried to fashion
a career as a saloon singer. He never made it beyond the circuit of
Catskills hotels and bungalow colonies, and consoled himself by
patching together a show business career as a commercial jingle
writer, talent manager and comedy club owner.
</P>
<P>
   But after 35 years and approaching the age of 60, Cary Hoffman
has finally realized his young man's fantasy of swinging like
Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   On most Thursday nights for the last year, Hoffman has been
found in a usually packed Manhattan nightclub singing the Sinatra
canon with a 14-piece band that has mastered the classic Riddle and
Billy May arrangements, down to the slurping trombones and sassy
trumpets. Although he got the job just over a year ago by
serendipity _ when he went to the Red Blazer, at 32 West 37th St.,
as a customer and quickly found himself on stage _ his patience
finally paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like a kid in a candy store,'' he said, recalling his
first time singing at the Red Blazer. ``I never thought I would
live to be in the middle of a band playing that stuff with great
musicians, guys who play Broadway shows, playing it right on the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman does not look or live like Sinatra. ``I'm not Frank
Sinatra, in case you folks haven't realized,'' he alerted his
audience last Thursday night. ``I'm a Jewish guy from Queens.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a popeyed, genial face, more homespun than handsome, and
until recently affected a stubbly goatee. He is a vegetarian who
does not smoke and only occasionally drinks a glass of wine. He
jogs and is in therapy. He has been married to the same woman _
Suzanne Hoffman _ for almost 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not exactly a ring-a-ding-ding sort of Sinatra guy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At moments, his pealing baritone approximates Sinatra's, and all
those years of record-listening have made him sensitive to
Sinatra's dead-on phrasing and beguiling improvisations.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's audience, Mary McGeachy, a magazine industry
executive, said, ``You close your eyes and you hear Sinatra.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are purists like Jonathan Schwartz, the disk
jockey who has a radio program monopolized by Sinatra songs, who
find the idea of an act like Hoffman's ``embarrassing,'' however
earnest it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of art, the trick is to find your own voice,'' said
Schwartz, who has never heard Hoffman sing. ``The records exist,
the real McCoy exists. Why should I hear a guy named Hoffman
pretend to be something he's not?''
</P>
<P>
   To such criticism, Hoffman replies that he does not consciously
do an impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   All he wants to do, he said, is to pay tribute to Sinatra's
music and strive, however impossibly, to emulate Sinatra's gift for
evoking need or heartbreak or exhilaration. ``He created a style of
intimate singing, converting the art of conversation into beautiful
music, and I want to keep it alive,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Sinatra, Hoffman did not exactly do it his way. The
genesis for his act goes back to when he was 4 and his father, a
Lower East Side lox slicer drafted into the Army in World War II,
was killed in a car accident on leave. His mother, Molly, a
one-time singer, moved the family into the nearby apartment of her
three brothers, Joe, Charlie and Hymie Small, all studio musicians.
Charlie had played with the Tommy Dorsey orchestra, and Joe was to
back Sinatra up on recordings like ``Saturday Night Is the
Loneliest Night of the Week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he died,'' he said of his father, ``my mother went to
live in a house full of music. If he had lived, I probably would
have become the owner of a chain of appetizing stores.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother remarried and moved first to Queens and then to
Westbury, N.Y. At 14 and 15, Cary listened to the new Sinatra, both
torchier and more up-tempo, on Capitol Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was he and I, and he was talking to me,'' he said. ``He was
singing, `In the Wee Small Hours,' and I didn't know anything about
love. Somehow, that spoke to me. Maybe it was the loneliness of my
life, not having a dad. I was kind of a loner, and Sinatra became a
musical friend.''
</P>
<P>
   And also ``a father image,'' he said. He determined to try to
become a Sinatra, but his mother pushed him to study a profession,
and he graduated from New York University with a degree in
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Not willing to forsake his dream, he and a friend drove to the
Catskills and styled themselves as another Dean Martin-Jerry Lewis
duo, with Hoffman singing and his friend poking fun.
</P>
<P>
   But after five years, he was still doing weddings and bar
mitzvahs. One luminous moment was a fleeting encounter with Sinatra
himself, contrived by his agent, outside Jilly's, Sinatra's
favorite Manhattan hangout.
</P>
<P>
   When the agent invited Sinatra to come to hear Hoffman, Sinatra
stepped into his limousine and politely said, ``Send me a demo.''
Hoffman sent him a tape of a single, non-Sinatra song. He never
received a reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized the handwriting was one the wall,'' he said. ``I
was not going to be this thing. An artist who becomes a big star
has to be an original. Sinatra was a one-of-a-kind original. Cary
Hoffman was not.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1965, he gave up singing. He and a friend, Ira Gasman, wrote
songs, one of which, ``Congratulations,'' made the country-music
charts, and an off- Broadway musical. He wrote jingles for Grand
Union and sang Sinatra's ``Come Fly With Me'' for a chain of
Midwestern fish restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, he bought the Stand-Up N.Y. comedy club on the West
Side and later took up management of eight comics and writers.
</P>
<P>
   All this time, he never lost his Sinatra fantasy. Shortly before
Sinatra died on May 14, 1998, a friend took him to the Red Blazer
to hear the Stan Rubin orchestra, known for its Swing Era
re-creations. ``All of a sudden, in the loins of my body, an old
dream is starting to surface and I say these words to him: `Do you
have any of the Nelson Riddle-Billy May arrangements of the 1950s?'
To me, that stuff is Mozart. He says: `Are you kidding? I've got 75
of them.' When he says that, I almost lose my breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin asked him to sing ``Night and Day,'' and he did, ``as big
and loud as I've ever done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, Hoffman started a series of appearances with the
band every other Thursday night that eventually became every
Thursday. He will linger at least until the end of this month, and
there have been talks about continuing his act through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   At the club, Hoffman has learned to his amusement that there are
still young people who carry his old Sinatra torch. ``The other
night, a kid says to me, `Do you mind if I come up and sing
`Witchcraft,''' he recalled, shaking his head to convey the
rejection he gave. ``So his girlfriend says, `He's pretty good.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
