is to integrate film.'' (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) TOKYO -- June 16, 1999 -- JAPAN-CRIME, 6-16 -- A street
in Kabukicho, Japan's largest ``entertainment zone,'' as it is
politely called, in northwest Tokyo. The area of a dozen square
blocks wakes up at noon and parties until dawn. It is where
gamblers and gangsters run rings around the police and where
prostitutes and strippers undress for success. However these days
the area is a reflection of Japan's troubles competing with China
and other Asian countries. (Nicholas D. Kristof/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- June 16, 1999 -- DISABLED-INSURE, 6-16 --
Sen. Ted Kennedy greets represenatives of various organizations
representing disabled Americans on Capitol Hill, after the Senate
approved legislation expanding federal health insurance coverage on
Wednesday. By a vote of 99 to 0, the Senate passed a bill that
would expand Medicaid and Medicare so hundreds of thousands of
people with disabilities could retain their health benefits when
they return to work. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MEJA, Yugoslavia -- June 16, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP-3, 6-16
-- A Kosovo Liberation Army soldier is seen through the window of a
damaged car on Tuesday which was part of a convoy of Serb security
forces attacked in April by the rebels. Locals claim Serbs
retaliated for the attack by killing local ethnic Albanians in a
nearby village. Ethnic Albanians who fled the slaughter in April
returned to the region to find mass graves strewn with remains
lying near where the victims were struck down. (Tyler Hicks/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) KORONICE, Yugoslavia -- June 16, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP-2,
6-16 -- Tom Dedaj, an ethnic Albanian looks at a pocket watch on
Wednesday which belonged to an elderly man who was killed,
allegedly by Serb security forces along with several others, in
April. Witnesses said the killings were carried out in retaliation
for an attack on Serb forces by members of the Kosovo Liberation
Army. Ethnic Albanians who fled a slaughter in April returned to
the region to find mass graves strewn with remains lying where they
died. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BELFAST, Maine -- June 16, 1999 -- FOOD-DUCKTRAP-BOS,
6-16 -- Workers in the slicing and packaging section of the
Ducktrap Farm fish smokery in Belfast. Though it began as a farm,
Ducktrap is now exclusively a smoking operation. (Tom Herde/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- June 16, 1999 -- BIOTECH-LEVIN-BOS,
6-16 -- Mark Levin, the founder and chief executive of Millennium
Pharmaceuticals Inc. He has built a cult-like following among the
pedigreed scientists streaming into the labs of his Cambridge
company, whose payroll has reached 800 employees in just six years.
(Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- June 16, 1999 -- WAR-RAPE-BOS, 6-16
-- Patience, who asks that only her first name be used, at home in
Cambridge with her daughter. Patience, from Cameroon, was whipped
and repeatedly raped by government soldiers in her country in the
early '80s. ``It was like I didn't own myself anymore,'' she says.
``I was just there for anyone to rape me.'' (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MEJA, Yugoslavia -- June 16, 1999 -- KOSOVO, 6-16 -- The
charred identity papers of an ethnic Albanian man is found near
where six bodies were found on Wednesday. Ethnic Albanians who fled
a slaughter in April returned to the region to find mass graves
strewn with remains lying where they died. Ethnic Albanian refugees
fleeing into Macedonia and Albania over the past three months have
reported numerous massacres by Serb forces. Their reports were
impossible to verify until Serb forces began to withdraw Monday.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) KOSOVO-ALBANIA BORDER -- June 16, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, 6-16 -- A van transporting ethnic Albanians back
their home in Kosovo is pushed to the side after it broke down near
a field where mines have been found on Wednesday. Some 30,000
refugees poured over the border from Albania on Wednesday
overwhelming the U.N. refugee agency which gave up trying to
register them. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SAN PEDRO, Calif. -- June 16, 1999 --
CIR-WEB-MICROSCOPE-2, 6-16 -- Girolann Accetta, above, shows
microscopic images to her students from the Dodson Middle School,
including Joshua Gile, left; Daniel Sandri; Alicia Holliman, front;
Annah Inocente and Sean O'Dell. The images were being manipulated
remotely from an electron microscope to the classroom through the
Internet. For all its potential, each remote access project
requires extraordinary coordination between educators and
scientists, and tremendous financial and intellectual generosity.
Fitting it into the school curriculum is the hardest part. (Chris
Pizzello/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 16, 1999 -- TIFFANY-WINDOWS-2, 6-16 --
The colors are warmest in winter, when the sun's rays are low in
the sky and envelop the stained-glass horizon in amber light.
``This window is certainly alive,'' says Rev. Gerald Johnson
sitting in the pews of the Sage Memorial First Presbyterian Church
in Far Rockaway, Queens. Johnson was refering to the stained-glass
window behind him created by Louis Comfort Tiffany. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. -- June 16, 1999 -- TIFFANY-WINDOWS-1,
6-16 --Teresa Lopez, prays near the Tiffany windows at St.
Gabriel's Roman Catholic Church. Stained-glass artistry by Louis
Comfort Tiffany graciously illuminates thousands of quiet corners
in residences and churches around the country. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SAN PEDRO, Calif. -- June 16, 1999 -- CIR-WEB-MICROSCOPE,
6-16 --Students from the Dodson Middle School look at images
magnified by an electron microscope at a site called Bugscope which
they manipulate via the Internet. For all its potential, each
remote access project requires extraordinary coordination between
educators and scientists, and tremendous financial and intellectual
generosity. Fitting it into the school curriculum is the hardest
part. (Chris Pizzello/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- June 16, 1999 -- CIR-DESKTOP-DESIGN, 6-16 --
NEC's Z1 Computer, top, and the 320 Visual Workstation by Silicon
Graphics. New designs for PCs, inspired by the iMac and fueled by
the development of flat screens, could spell the end of the beige
box. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- June 16, 1999 --
CIR-WHARTON-UNDESIGN, 6-16 -- John Wharton ``reverse-engineers'' a
Furby. Wharton is hired as a high-tech detective by law firms whose
corporate clients are involved in patent disputes. They call on him
to take a finished product and trace it back through thousands of
steps to its original specifications to see where an infringement
may lie. In the last 10 years, he has been hired to
reverse-engineer video game players, home health devices, and
several variations on PC circuitry. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
