<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8377 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-VIOLENCE-BOS &LR;      06-16 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REJECTS GOP ANTIVIOLENCE MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Wednesday rejected a GOP measure to crack
down on ``violently obscene'' video games, music, and movies as
Republicans and Democrats embarked on a wide-ranging debate over
their competing visions of how to reduce youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, aimed at the entertainment industry and sponsored
by Judiciary Committee chairman Henry Hyde of Illinois, was
rejected by a vote of 282-146. Members of both parties criticized
the measure banning the sale to minors of violent or sexually
explicit material as a threat to the Constitution's guarantee of
free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe this tramples on the First Amendment and . . . on
the rights of parents,'' said Mark Foley, a Florida Republican.
``It won't solve the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 249-181, the House approved a series of law
enforcement measures aimed at juvenile offenders, including
imposing stricter penalties for numerous crimes and giving
prosecutors the discretion to charge a juvenile as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate Wednesday was only a prelude to a showdown
Thursday over whether the House will follow the Senate and pass
tough new gun-control measures in consequence of the rampage at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., in which 12 students and
a teacher were killed by two students who later committed suicide.
President Clinton lobbied long distance for passage of a measure
that would make background checks mandatory for all firearms bought
at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge you to stand up to the gun lobby once again,'' he wrote
to dozens of lawmakers in a letter from an international conference
in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the House chamber, lobbying by gun-control advocates and
opponents was intense, with the National Rifle Association pushing
to weaken the Senate version. Inside, the GOP tried, without much
success, to shift the discussion from gun control to cultural
issues that it said are the root cause of youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberals demagogue tragedies like school shootings to push
their left-wing agenda,'' said the Republican whip, Tom DeLay of
Texas. ``But the big problem in America is not gun ownership. The
big problem is the abandonment of God in the public arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans lauded their juvenile justice bill as an attempt to
close loopholes and toughen the law for young criminals, but
Democrats accused Republicans of doing the bidding of the NRA and
avoiding the real culprit, guns, by pushing for curbs on violent
images. Waving a remote control in one hand and a cardboard gun in
the other, Florida Democrat Robert Wexler shouted, ``Instead of gun
control, we're doing remote control.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Joe Moakley, a Boston Democrat, said, ``I for one
believe the welfare of our children should be put before partisan
politics. But that's not going to happen today . . . because
partisan politics won out over common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   By midweek, powerful disagreements over how to address gun
violence, pitting suburban moderates and liberals against gun
advocates from mostly Western and Southern states, already had
fractured both parties. Democratic leaders cried foul when GOP
leaders decided to sever the gun-control measures from the juvenile
justice bill, giving their members the political cover to vote to
for one without the other.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who favored gun control fumed over the move, privately
conceding they were unlikely to prevail, while party unity among
Republicans on the floor appeared to collapse late in the afternoon
as rank-and-file members lined up to criticize Hyde's amendment
banning violent and sexual material.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyde antiviolence amendment would have restricted minors'
access to art, video games, movies, books, and musical recordings
that were deemed to contain ``explicit sexual material or explicit
violent material.'' Hyde said it was ``designed to slow the flood
of toxic waste into kids' minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Zoe Lofgren, Democrat of California, the mother
of teenagers, said she was troubled that under the Republicans'
proposals, a clerk who sold her child ``Shakespeare in Love'' might
be subject to criminal sanctions while someone who sold her child a
firearm would not.
</P>
<P>
   While members of both parties agreed on spending $1.5 billion in
grants to states to improve prevention programs and beef up
correctional facilities for juveniles, they locked horns over a
proposal by Representative Bill McCollum, a Republican of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   McCollum's amendment, which passed, would boost gun crime
prosecutions, give prosecutors authority to try youths as adults
starting at age 13, and impose mandatory minimum sentences for a
range of gun and drug crimes, including illegal possession of a
firearm with intent to take it into a school zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids who receive little or no consequences for their
misbehavior are by far the most likely candidates for teenage
violence as they get older,'' said McCollum, whose bill requires
states to create a system to impose increasingly stiff penalities
on criminal juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats rejected the proposal as punitive, contending
that it would charge more youth offenders as adults and force
children to be jailed and imprisoned with violent adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is outrageous,'' complained Representative Maxine Waters,
a Democrat of California. ``This locks up 13-year-olds in the
federal system, creates new federal crimes, and takes away the
discretion of judges, doing nothing to reduce crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the House passed by voice vote an amendment
sponsored by Representative Martin Meehan, a Lowell Democrat, to
expand a program modeled on the Boston Gun Project, which funds
law-enforcement efforts to trace guns used in youth crimes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Eun Lee Koh contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
