<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8382 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS17-COX     06-16 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptists turn up heat on rhetoric
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From a podium near midfield of the Georgia Dome,
retired football star Reggie White scored big with Southern
Baptists on Wednesday night, preaching outreach to the cities and
condemnation of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours earlier, delegates to the annual convention of the
nation's largest Protestant denomination voted to rebuke fellow
Baptist Bill Clinton, accusing the president of endorsing the sin
of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   As gay pride banners flew on the streets of Atlanta, the
Baptists wrapped up the business of their convention by adopting
the rebuke of Clinton that ``deplored'' his proclamation of June as
gay and lesbian pride month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as we express great gratitude to our Lord Jesus Christ
for his forgiveness, we hereby call upon the President to rescind
his proclamation endorsing homosexuality,'' stated the resolution,
approved in an overwhelming show of hands.
</P>
<P>
   White, a former Green Bay Packers star who was greeted with a
standing ovation, did not confine his sermonizing to homosexuality.
He also implored his audience to examine the recent suburban school
shootings in Littleton, Colo., and nearby Rockdale County.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at this, ladies and gentlemen, all the kids doing
these shootings are white kids,'' he said. Shootings ``have been
happening in inner cities for years. When you allow a cancer to
start, ladies and gentlemen, it spreads.''
</P>
<P>
   White urged Southern Baptists to minister to the cities, even to
the point of taking a homeless person into their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for us to get out of the pews and into the
streets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   White quoted a string of theologians, but stuck to Bible verses
when he tackled homosexuality, using texts from Leviticus and
Romans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never criticized the gay lifestyle,'' White told a
cheering crowd. ``I've only proclaimed what God himself said.''
</P>
<P>
   Messengers to the convention praised White's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was awesome,'' said Art Fulks, a music minister
in Rock Mountain, N.C. ``He based what he said on the word of God,
not just on what he thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching the nation's cities has been a major thrust of this
year's meeting, which drew 11,000 messengers to the Dome. The
Southern Baptist Convention claims 15.7 million members in 40,800
churches throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Convention president Rev. Paige Patterson, who was re-elected
Tuesday, has proposed an extensive ministry that will start new
churches in cities outside the traditional Bible belt, buy property
for missions in Manhattan and establish a television super-station
for outreach.
</P>
<P>
   But drawing national attention was the Southern Baptists'
dealing with the issue of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sick and tired of the political machinery of the White
House advancing the homosexual agenda,'' said the Rev. Wiley Drake,
a California pastor.
</P>
<P>
   At Drake's suggestion, the convention amended its resolution
rebuking Clinton to call on the president to rescind the
appointment of James Hormel, a San Francisco philanthropist and gay
rights activist, as ambassador to Luxembourg. The amendment was
approved by a 2,316 to 1,313 vote.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential proclamation issued June 11 calls ``America's
diversity our greatest strength'' and encourages all Americans to
observe gay and lesbian pride month ``with appropriate programs,
ceremonies, and activities that celebrate our diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Southern Baptists' resolution says the president's
proclamation celebrates ``abominable behavior, which is for
millions of Americans an offense to their sensibilities and an
affront to their religious heritage and convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution condemns violence against gays and lesbians and
proclaims the convention's love for Clinton, a Southern Baptist
himself. But ``love compels us to rebuke him and publicly to
deplore his most public endorsement of that which is contrary to
the Word of God.''
</P>
<P>
   In other resolutions adopted Wednesday, the Baptists spoke out
against school violence, human embryonic research and ethnic
cleansing, and endorsed global missions, the changelessness of God,
prayer for public officials and Christian influence in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
