<SLUG> BC-TRINET-REALESTATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STARWOOD TO PURCHASE TRINET FOR $1.5 BILLION  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In a bid to make it easier to get financing, TriNet Corporate
Realty Trust, a San Francisco real estate company, agreed to be
acquired by commercial mortgage lender Starwood Financial Trust for
$1.5 billion in stock and assumed debt.
<P>
   The companies said their combination will create the nation's
largest publicly traded finance company focused exclusively on
commercial real estate.
</P>
<P>
   TriNet will operate as a separately managed subsidiary of
Starwood, which is based in New York, and its 50 San Francisco
employees will keep their jobs ``for the present time,'' said
TriNet President Bill Stein.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood, whose chairman is hotel magnate Barry Sternlicht,
lends to commercial property developers.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were lukewarm about the deal. TriNet stock fell 13
cents Wednesday, to $29.19. Starwood's shares plunged $20.88, to
$34.13, but analysts said the fall was meaningless because few of
the company's shares trade on the open market. TriNet buys office
buildings and commercial properties from blue-chip corporations
such as IBM and then leases the facilities back to them. The
company does business with the pillars of corporate America, which
can negotiate low lease rates because the chances they will default
are small.
</P>
<P>
   The business requires large amounts of capital, which has become
more expensive since once-high-flying real estate investment trusts
fell out of favor with investors a year and a half ago. TriNet's
stock has fallen by about 25 percent in that period.
</P>
<P>
   Joining forces with Starwood to form a bigger, more diversified
company ``will make capital more easily available,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, investors snapped up the stocks of REITs,
which sell shares to the public to finance real estate purchases.
But as property prices climbed faster than rents, anticipated
returns fell and REIT stocks collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   TriNet had its own problems, such as disappointing profits from
its moves into property development. In addition, the narrow
margins and weak profit growth of its leaseback business made it
tough to attract investors.
</P>
<P>
   The company's net income rose 15 percent in 1998, to $62.6
million. But because income was diverted to cover dividends on
newly issued preferred stock, earnings per common share fell 16
percent, to $1.91.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of TRINET17 (33954 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``The stock market looks for growth, and they were not growing,''
said Jefferies &AMP; Co. analyst James Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, hooking up with Starwood actually could raise
TriNet's cost of capital in some cases. Several credit rating
agencies, including Standard &AMP; Poor's, said they were considering
downgrading TriNet's debt because Starwood's business is riskier.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of TRINET17 (33954 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
