<HEADER>
A8395 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRO     06-16 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CHRONICLE PUBLISHING OFFICIALLY ON THE BLOCK  &HT;     By DAN FOST AND PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The board of Chronicle Publishing Co. voted 9 to 0 Wednesday to
formally put the company up for sale.
<P>
   The vote came almost six weeks after the San Francisco company,
which owns The Chronicle, KRON-TV and other media properties, hired
New York investment bank Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette to ``review
and evaluate the company's financial, business and strategic
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   A source who was at the meeting said the privately held company
could fetch more than $2 billion if it were sold in pieces. John
Morton, a newspaper industry analyst based in Silver Spring, Md.,
said that figure sounded like a good estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding is expected to take most of the summer, executives said,
and it probably will be late this year or early next year before
any sales are completed.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the company has not formally solicited offers, DLJ
reported that several media companies already have expressed
interest in buying various parts of Chronicle Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett Co. of Arlington, Va.; Hollinger Inc. of Toronto;
Journal Register Co. of Trenton, N.J.; Knight Ridder Inc. of San
Jose; and Times Mirror Co. of Los Angeles reportedly have expressed
interest in buying the company's three newspapers. In addition to
San Francisco daily, Chronicle Publishing owns the Worcester
Telegram &AMP; Gazette in Massachusetts and the Bloomington Pantagraph
in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Co., which bought the Boston Globe in 1993
for $1 billion, reportedly is interested in the Worcester paper.
Copley Newspapers expressed interest in the Bloomington paper.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder Chairman and CEO Tony Ridder confirmed Wednesday
that his company, which publishes the San Jose Mercury News and the
Contra Costa Times, would be interested in buying all the
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're strong in the South Bay and East Bay but don't have much
circulation in San Mateo, San Francisco or Marin,'' he said,
``Those areas and Alameda are served by The Chronicle, and they're
great markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton said Knight Ridder might face antitrust hurdles if it
tried to buy The Chronicle. ``I don't think the Justice Department
would ever let that one go by,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ridder said that after consulting lawyers, he disagrees. He
also said Knight Ridder would be interested in The Chronicle
despite its joint operating agreement with the San Francisco
Examiner, which is owned by New York's Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of CHRON17 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Under the JOA, which continues into 2005, The Chronicle and
Examiner maintain separate news operations but jointly operate all
production, advertising, circulation and other noneditorial
activities. The two owners share revenues and expenses 50-50, even
though The Chronicle's circulation is more than four times the
Examiner's.
</P>
<P>
   A source at the McClatchy Co., which publishes the Sacramento
Bee, said the JOA discouraged that company from pursuing a bid for
The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Fox Television, USA Network and Young Broadcasting Inc.
have expressed preliminary interest in buying KRON, the NBC
affiliate in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks Muse has expressed interest in buying all the company's TV
properties, which also include San Francisco cable station BayTV;
ABC affiliate KAKE in Wichita, Kan.; and NBC affiliate WOWT in
Omaha, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Television stations are selling for increasingly higher prices.
Last year, Hearst-Argyle Corp., Hearst's television arm, set a
record with the $520 million purchase of KCRA and two smaller
properties in Sacramento, the nation's 20th-largest market. The San
Francisco Bay Area is No.5 in market size.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers say the company is not likely to be sold in one
piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine a single buyer interested in all
properties,'' said Nion McEvoy, a board member, shareholder and
editor in chief of Chronicle Books, one of the company's two
book-publishing divisions. The other is MBI, a Wisconsin publisher
of transportation books.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Also, federal rules prohibit one company from owning a
newspaper and a television station in the same community.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing was exempted from the rule because it went
into effect after the company already owned KRON and The Chronicle.
Industry observers say the Federal Communication Commission
probably would not let a new owner buy both properties.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing, which also operates the SF Gate.com Web
site, employs a total of 3,200 people.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Cuthbertson, executive officer of the Northern California
Media Guild, the union that represents about 350 Chronicle
employees, said he wasn't surprised by Wednesday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of CHRON17 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``All of our concerns remain about jobs and our contract,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By next month, qualified prospective buyers who sign
confidentiality agreements will be given a look at each operation's
financial data, according to an informed source.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle is the 11th-largest daily newspaper in the
country, with a circulation of 482,268.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has expressed interest in buying The Chronicle but not
the other properties, according to a source. Under the JOA, Hearst
has the right of first refusal to buy The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at both the Examiner and Chronicle said yesterday
that they did not know whether that right would hold up if all of
Chronicle Publishing was sold.
</P>
<P>
   At the Chronicle meeting, DLJ representatives handed board
members dark green folders containing financial analyses and sale
options.
</P>
<P>
   The paper is owned by roughly three dozen descendants of
Chronicle co-founder M.H. de Young.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the 10 board members are shareholders, and the others
are outside directors. One family director was absent yesterday as
the board gathered in the company's wood-paneled conference room
under the gaze of the formal portraits of previous publishers.
</P>
<P>
   One major shareholder and former director, Nan T. McEvoy, had
repeatedly advocated keeping the 134-year-old company in family
hands. But she reportedly has ``accepted the inevitable,''
according to one source.
</P>
<P>
   As she left the meeting, McEvoy said only, ``We'll see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The board decided to sell for several reasons, according to
company spokesman Don Solem. The economy is strong, media companies
are fetching high prices, the Bay Area is growing in importance
thanks to Silicon Valley and its perch on the Pacific Rim, and
Chronicle Publishing has a diverse set of assets that could bring
more money separately than together.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Solem said, many of the shareholders are four or
five generations removed from the founders of the newspaper. None
are involved in active management of any of the operating units,
and only a handful are even employed by the company, a big change
from past generations.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of CHRON17 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``All of those things add up to: The time to sell is now,'' Solem
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After years of speculation on this, the future of newspapers
in San Francisco is moving to a fairly quick resolution,'' said Tom
Goldstein, dean of the Columbia University School of Journalism in
New York. If Hearst buys The Chronicle, it likely would merge it
with the Examiner or close one of the two papers. ``The trend
toward one-newspaper towns is absolutely unmistakable over the
years. There are so few left as to be almost statistically
negligible.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of CHRON17 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
