<HEADLINE>
SERIAL KILLER IS PURSUED IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ky., Mexico)  (nk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In a search described as akin to looking for ``a
needle in five haystacks,'' hundreds of federal, state and local
law-enforcement officers in Texas are hunting a serial killer
believed responsible for the fatal bludgeoning of six people on or
near railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The chief suspect in the killings _ five in the last six months
between Houston and San Antonio, the other nearly two years ago in
Kentucky _ is Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, a drifter from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities in the cases, investigators say, suggest the
same killer: All six victims were savagely beaten with blunt
objects. Most were then covered with a blanket or a sheet. In at
least three cases, the killer fled by stealing a car from the
victim, although he shows no apparent interest in robbery.
</P>
<P>
   But the common thread that has instilled the greatest sense of
fear and vulnerability in South Texas railroad communities is that
the killings all occurred near the tracks, as if the attacker had
hopped off a train and randomly searched for someone to murder.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez, described by officials as a transient who has
spent much of the last decade jumping freight trains from Vermont
to California, has not been charged with any of the killings. But
officials say fingerprints in at least three cases, and additional
evidence that they decline to describe, link him to all six deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his habit of staying on the move, and because the
authorities' most recent photograph of him is four years old, the
challenge of finding Resendez-Ramirez is formidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like trying to find a needle in five haystacks,'' said
Ron Walker, a Houston police lieutenant. Earlier this week dozens
of investigators combed hundreds of railroad cars in Brazoria
County, south of Houston, in a search that netted 21 people
suspected of being illegal immigrants, but not Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent clue came on Saturday, when officers in Del Rio,
a border town, found the abandoned white Honda Civic of a Houston
schoolteacher, Noemi Dominguez, who was discovered beaten to death
in her home on June 5. Wednesday the Houston police announced that
the fingerprints of Resendez-Ramirez had been found in the car.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators concede that little is known of Resendez-Ramirez.
He was born in Puebla, about 115 miles south of Mexico City, and is
39, the investigators say. Because of frequent illegal forays into
the United States, he has spent time in federal prisons on
immigration charges, although his past does not appear to indicate
violence. He has used several aliases during the last decade as he
hopped freight trains across the United States. The Mexican
authorities have interviewed a former wife living in Juarez, but
finding relatives or friends has been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a traveler,'' said Mike Cox, a spokesman for the Texas
Department of Public Safety, noting that law-enforcement agents had
been able to place him at various times over the last 10 years in
Michigan, Vermont, California, Missouri, Kentucky and Louisiana. As
a result, officials in a number of states are sifting through
unsolved murder cases, checking in particular any near railroad
tracks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The six victims seem to have had little in common other than
their proximity to the rails. The first, Christopher Maier, a
student at the University of Kentucky, was killed in August 1997 as
he walked along the tracks in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last December, Dr. Claudia Benton of West University
Place, an affluent incorporated city within the boundaries of
Houston, was found sexually assaulted, stabbed and beaten to death
inside her home near the tracks. Her Jeep Cherokee was later found
abandoned in San Antonio, and officials say a fingerprint of the
suspect was found in the car.
</P>
<P>
   The other slayings have all occurred since April 30, when a
minister and his wife, Norman and Karen Sirnic, were discovered
dead inside their home near the tracks in the small town of Weimar.
Their stolen pickup was later discovered in nearby San Antonio.
Then Josephine Konvicka, 73, was found slain on June 4 inside her
home in Fayette County, west of Houston, and a day later the body
of Ms. Dominguez, the schoolteacher, was found in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   While investigators have yet to determine any motive for the
killings, they suspect that they are racing the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most serious case going on in Texas,'' Cox said.
``There's concern that whoever is doing these killings could kill
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
