<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 N.Y. MEDIA PUNCHING EACH OTHER WITH GLOVED FISTS ONLINE  &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
New York _ In two days in Manhattan, I did it all: Ate chopped
liver drizzled with schmaltz at Sammy's Romanian Steak House, saw a
rat scurry through Gramercy Park, toured Theodore Roosevelt's
birthplace, rode out the heat wave in new and old taxis, and
visited three of the top purveyors of online financial news.
<P>
   I'm sorry to report that none of the editors at the Wall Street
Journal Interactive Edition, TheStreet.com or the New York bureau
of CBS Marketwatch.com could spin a story like the yarn my cabbie
told about his run-ins with in-line skaters, cops, judges and
bosses.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wall Street scribes did offer some entertaining tales _
like how none of them sees the others as direct competition, even
though they seem compelled to take pokes at one another.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers, after all, love a fight, and New York's status as a
financial and media capital is fomenting a first-class brawl as the
relatively new online medium builds up momentum.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet, for instance, is the scrappy underdog that started a
mere three years ago. Its pungent commentary contrasts with the
authoritative air of the Journal's online edition, and its emphasis
on analysis makes it different from the data-intensive day-trading
paradise at Marketwatch.com.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet's feisty editor, Dave Kansas, was a Journal reporter
for four years before jumping into the online world. He relishes
his niche as a pesky thorn in his old employer's side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The franchise of financial journalism is theirs to lose,''
Kansas said. ``It's hard to get better than the best. Each person
working to chip away at them is a terrible nuisance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Journal's top newspaper competition, the New York Times, has
even endorsed TheStreet's endeavors _ not only with a $15 million
investment, but, according to the latest filings, with plans to
create ``a jointly owned newsroom to provide continuous coverage of
business news.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas wouldn't discuss the plans for the joint venture, which
sources said would take shape by the fourth quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, offer his commentary on the ties of
Marketwatch, based in San Francisco, to another big New York media
firm, CBS: ``I'm glad we're not locked into a large television
network like they are. We have a lot of options open to us. We can
do anything with anyone. They have a lot of obligations to such a
bigfoot daddy like that.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MEDIA17 (91283 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Uptown, where Marketwatch maintains several desks in CBS's 57th
Street offices, New York bureau chief Emily Church was mystified by
Kansas' comments. ``I've never felt constrained because we're part
of the Tiffany network,'' Church said. ``I don't see how you can
say it hurt us. We had a huge IPO, and we have a huge, huge
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   With a small staff operating in the dimly lit, brick-walled
offices of CBS's new media operations, Church says Marketwatch can
offer both expert commentary on general financial news to deliver
on the CBS Evening News as well as sophisticated, technical reports
on its Web site on topics like the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal claims it's above the fray. The online Journal,
which occupies the same floor in the Dow Jones office tower as the
august print product's newsroom, doesn't even call itself a
financial Web site. Managing Editor Rich Jaroslovsky prefers the
term ``business publication,'' saying, ``We're not aimed at the
narrow world of finance, but at the broader world of business.''
</P>
<P>
   But with increasing numbers of Web surfers turning to
non-journalistic sites like Schwab and Yahoo Finance for
information, Jaroslovsky acknowledged that competition does exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire Web is our competition,'' Jaroslovsky said. ``We
have to be that much deeper and more authoritative than all the
things you can get for free.''
</P>
<P>
   The Journal site is envied in the online world for its 300,000
paying subscribers. The more expensive service of TheStreet.com, by
comparison, is considered successful with only 51,000 paying
subscribers as of March 31, according to its latest prospectus,
filed last month. (The interactive Journal is available for $29 a
year to subscribers of the print product and $59 to all others.
TheStreet costs $99.95 a year, and MarketWatch is free.)
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, it should be noted that the sites all praised each
other: Church admired TheStreet founder Jim Cramer's columns,
Kansas hailed Marketwatch reporters who post two to three stories a
day (as many as his staffers file in a week), and everyone conceded
that all sites do their own things very well.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MEDIA17 (91283 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Could the mutual admiration be a reflection of Rudy Giuliani's
more civil New York? It reminds me of another Manhattan cab ride I
had: a new Crown Victoria, air-conditioned, jazz music playing and
a silent driver. It may be more pleasant, but it's not as colorful
as the old system.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA MONEY ONLY, PLEASE: Imagine throwing a media conference
and not inviting the media.
</P>
<P>
   That was the conundrum at the Pierre Hotel last week, where the
newly merged Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown hosted a media and
telecommunications conference.
</P>
<P>
   Media firms like Marketwatch.com, Cnet and Knight Ridder sent
their executives to peddle their companies to deep-pocketed
investors, but they couldn't send their reporters to report the
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the few conferences we have that is closed to
the press,'' said Chris Cortezi, who handles publicity for Alex.
Brown analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the analysts had invited journalists,'' said Cortezi,
who had the unenviable job of dis-inviting them. ``Some were
understanding, and some were not,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
