<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-GROWTH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SOFTWARE INDUSTRY SEES RECORD GROWTH  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
U.S software sales increased 17.8 percent to a record $141.9
billion last year and the industry now employs 806,900 people
nationwide, according to a study released Wednesday.
<P>
   The software industry should become the biggest contributor to
the U.S. economy of all manufacturing industries by next year,
accelerating past the century-old automobile industry, according to
the Business Software Alliance report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The software industry has emerged as one of the
fastest-growing and most vibrant segments of the U.S. economy,''
BSA President Robert Holleyman said during a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The trade association used the report to punctuate the third day
of a technology industry blitz on Washington, D.C. The majordomos
of leading tech companies such as Microsoft and Intel have huddled
with Capitol Hill legislators and the Clinton administration,
stressing the economic and political importance of their
industries.
</P>
<P>
   To release the report, the alliance trotted out 13 CEOs from its
top member companies, including Bill Gates of Microsoft, Carol
Bartz of Autodesk Inc., John Chen of Sybase, Bill Harris of Intuit
and William Larson of Network Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executives said legislators are more aware than ever
of the key issues on high-tech industry's agenda, from encryption
to software piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the industry's top issue, the Senate passed a bill
this week that would limit lawsuits caused by Year 2000 computer
problems, though the White House has threatened a veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress is listening to this industry very well,'' Gates said
at the press conference. ``I'm pleased with the dialogue and I'm
pleased with the interest level. It's related to the fact we're
creating a number of good jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, prepared by Nathan Associates Inc., said software
industry employment grew 13.9 percent annually from 1994 to 1998,
which compares to an annual growth rate of only 2.5 percent for all
of private industry combined.
</P>
<P>
   The average salary for software workers is $68,900 per year,
compared with $29,800 for other private sector workers.
</P>
<P>
   If the current trend continues, the industry will have more than
1.3 million workers by 2008, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Bartz, though, said illegally copied software cost the industry
$11 billion in lost potential revenue and prevented the creation of
32,700 jobs last year. If that rate continues, the industry would
lose 52,700 new jobs by 2008, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is pushing for stronger copyright protection laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an area where we require help,'' Bartz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
