<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENEDICT IS THE METS' MAD HATTER FOR A DAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ On a day that Bruce Benedict was, in a sense, asked
to wear an entirely different hat as the temporary manager of the
Mets, it made little difference that Benedict forgot his cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I had a little trouble with my hat,'' Benedict said,
betraying the nerves he surely felt Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was about the only difficulty Benedict had in his star turn
as the stand-in for Manager Bobby Valentine, who was serving the
first game of a two-game suspension. With Valentine watching in
suit jacket and tie from a box above home plate, Benedict guided
the Mets to a 5-2 victory over the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   As Valentine sat with Phillips and Assistant General Manager
Omar Minaya in full view of the Mets' dugout, Brian McRae drove in
three runs, Robin Ventura homered and Masato Yoshii (6-5) pitched
six solid innings before four relievers closed it out. John Franco
tossed a perfect ninth to record his 16th save in 17 tries this
season. And the Mets (35-30) have now won eight of their past 10
games since General Manager Steve Phillips fired three of
Valentine's coaches following the Mets' season-high eighth straight
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict, the Mets' bench coach, was spared Phillips' purge. He
stepped in when Valentine was banished for donning a fake mustache
and sunglasses and remaining in the dugout tunnel after he had been
ejected June 9.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict takes over as manager when Valentine is ejected. But
Wednesday he managed his first major league game from beginning to
end, and he was so nervous that he emerged from the clubhouse
without a hat. When he ran back to his locker, he picked out the
one the Mets use for batting practice. It was not until the fourth
inning, Benedict said, that Charlie Samuels, the Mets' equipment
manager, brought him a regular game cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he was a little nervous,'' Valentine said of Benedict.
``I was nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped that the Mets took an early lead and never fell
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura helped contribute to the Mets' first four runs. After
Mike Piazza opened the second with a double to extend his hitting
streak to 19 games _ matching his career best _ Ventura moved
Piazza to third by grounding out to the right side of the infield.
McRae singled Piazza home, and the Mets led, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura then led off the fourth against Steve Parris (4-1) with
his 11th home run of the season, before the Reds answered with
single runs in the fourth and fifth to tie the score at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Then Piazza reached first on Aaron Boone's error at third to
open the sixth. Ventura moved Piazza to third when he was credited
with an Astroturf double that bounced over center fielder Mike
Cameron's head. And both runners scored on a single to right by
McRae, who stumbled rounding first. The Mets led, 4-2, but McRae
felt a whiplash effect in his neck, and was thrown out at second as
he banged his sore left knee on the slide.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii worked his way out of jams in the fifth and sixth
innings. In the fifth, he picked Cameron off second, in one of the
game's key plays. Had Yoshii not, the Reds might have gone on to
take the lead instead of merely tie. Then, with the Reds trailing,
4-2, the red-hot Sean Casey singled to lead off the critical sixth.
Against Greg Vaughn, who belted 50 homers a year ago, Yoshii fell
behind three balls and no strikes. The pitching coach Dave Wallace
made his way to the mound to buy Greg McMichael some time in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii threw a fastball. Vaughn grounded into a double play.
Barry Larkin grounded out. End of threat.
</P>
<P>
   Then Benedict went to his bullpen, just as he and Valentine had
planned. McMichael and Dennis Cook pitched the seventh, with Cook
stranding a runner on third. Cook and Armando Benitez pitched the
eighth, with Benitez stranding a runner on first.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the ninth, Edgardo Alfonzo singled home Matt
Franco with an insurance run. In the bottom of the ninth, John
Franco came on for the save, and Alfonzo helped out again with a
sensational, leaping stab of an Eddie Taubensee liner for the
second out. Then McRae ran down a Cameron liner to deep center, bad
knee and all, before doing what Benedict said looked like a
Spiderman impersonation on the center-field fence, as he held on to
the game's final out.
</P>
<P>
   What was it like playing for Benedict instead of Valentine?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I noticed was that it was real quiet in the
dugout,'' Yoshii said through his translator. ``That's when I
noticed Bobby wasn't there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
