<SLUG> BC-FEINGOLD-DONATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR VOWS TO NOTE DONATIONS IN DEBATES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to breathe some life into moribund campaign
finance legislation, Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., announced
Wednesday that in debates on legislation favored by interest
groups, he would make a point of identifying how much money those
groups had given to candidates and parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaign contributions are involved in virtually everything
that this body does,'' Feingold declared in a Senate speech. ``We
cannot just pull our head out of the sand to discuss the influence
of money on the legislative process once a year when we take up
campaign finance legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   With Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., Feingold is the chief Senate
sponsor of legislation that, among other steps, would outlaw the
unregulated contributions, or soft money, that businesses and labor
unions give to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the measure, backed by almost all Democrats and a few
Republicans, won support of a majority of the members of the House
and Senate, but it died in a Republican-led filibuster in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois has said the House will not
take up the legislation until September, and the Senate will
probably not deal with it until the House has acted. Even then,
there is no indication that the bill can get the 60 votes necessary
to overcome a filibuster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
