<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-US-OPEN-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE U.S. OPEN, GOLFERS ARE GIDDY OVER PINEHURST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ In the opinion of many players, the U. S. Open
Championship is being played at a perfect site this year.
</P>
<P>
   The fairways are wide enough to enable players to use their
drivers. The three-inch rough is high enough to create difficult
shots, but low enough to give players options. The sloping
turtle-back greens will put a premium on the short game and force
players to be creative.
</P>
<P>
   The overall challenge of the Pinehurst Resort and Country Club's
No. 2 course, one of the world's most revered, creates a special
atmosphere: a national treasure will be playing host to the
national championship for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The 99th U.S. Open, which begins Thursday, should present a fair
yet difficult test. The winner will need imagination, short-game
skill, patience and a few good breaks. Expect an unpredictable
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   If the weather is wet and the greens are soft, the winning score
could be 6-under par or lower. But if the greens remain firm, and
if there is even the slightest breeze, the winning score could
easily soar over par. So get ready to see a different Open, with
players putting with 3-woods from off the green, players using
every club in their bag and a large group of players starting the
tournament with a legitimate chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   After three days of practice _ and hearing so much about the
nuances of Pinehurst and the genius of the course architect Donald
Ross _ the players have given their stamp of approval. But loving
Pinehurst is easy. To win at Pinehurst will be far more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is in agreement that it's going to be a fantastic
Open,'' Greg Norman, who will be playing in his 17th U.S. Open,
said. ``They've done a phenomenal job in the setup of the golf
course. This is the best I've seen and that's pretty much the word
on the driving range and the putting green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be more of an international Open. A lot more
players could win this golf tournament than we've seen in the past.
Before, the U.S. Open was conservative; the driver wasn't in your
bag. This week, you're hitting a lot of drivers, plus medium iron
shots into the greens. And if you miss the greens, you've got a
variety of different shots, anywhere from putting with your 3-wood
to putting with your putter to using an iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who grew up in Europe, the guys who grew up in
Australia and the U.S. guys have all played these type of courses
before. So it's more of an open Open.''
</P>
<P>
   No European has won the U.S. Open since Tony Jacklin in 1970,
but many believe that could change this weekend. Colin Montgomerie
of Scotland, who endured heart-breaking second-place finishes in
the 1994 and 1997 Open, agreed that Europeans like himself _ Lee
Westwood and the Masters champion Jose Maria Olazabal _ could fare
well. Chipping and putting is also important at the Masters, where
Europeans have won 11 of the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's motivation for every European golfer,''
Montgomerie said of the dry spell at the Open. ``I think it's been
too long. Nick Faldo has lost in playoffs. So have I. It's a matter
of trying to walk through when that door is half ajar, and not
finishing second.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, one of the beauties of Pinehurst is that not everyone
agrees on what will happen. Westwood did not buy the theory that
Europeans have a better chance this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing like this course in Europe,'' Westwood, the
world's eighth-ranked player, said. ``I don't know why somebody has
the impression it's going to suit the European player. That's just
a proviso in case one of us wins.''
</P>
<P>
   But the list of favorites is a long one. Tiger Woods is playing
his best golf in two years, having won his last two starts. David
Duval, who burned his right thumb and forefinger on a pot last
week, has been able to practice since Tuesday, and he expects to
play well.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Janzen, the defending champion, has won the Open twice, and
he has the toughness and temperament to do it again. The same could
be said for Ernie Els, another two-time U.S. Open champion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But there are several keys to winning. Driving the ball
accurately will still be important, because it will be difficult to
land approach shots from the rough onto the green with consistency.
Avoiding three-putts at any tournament is crucial, particularly at
the majors. Avoiding big-number holes will also be important.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to make a big number at Pinehurst is to miss any
green in the wrong spot, particularly past the pin, thus leaving an
impossible chip shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the rough cut to three inches, the players may be tempted
to hit a long shot toward the putting green, with little or no
control over the golf ball,'' Trey Holland, chairman of the U.S.
Golf Association championship committee, said. ``Where it ends up
is going to be anybody's guess. We think it's going to result in a
very exciting championship, something the fans and players have not
experienced with a U.S. Open setup for years.''
</P>
<P>
   And the players can hardly wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun,'' Curtis Strange, a two-time Open
champion, said. ``We're playing a little bit in the unknown. But
it's going to be a ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
