u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUVENILES-GUNS-HNS &LR;      06-16 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUVENILES-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REJECTS STRICT LIMIT ON SEXUAL OR VIOLENT MATERIAL FOR MINORS
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House rejected a proposal Wednesday that would
have placed strict prohibitions on the sale and dissemination of
explicitly sexual or violent material to minors as members began
consideration of juvenile crime and gun control bills in the wake
of the Colorado school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The 282-146 vote against restricting the sales of video games,
movies, music, books, art and other forms of entertainment followed
several hours of spirited debate over whether the measure sponsored
by Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., would violate
the Constitution's First Amendment guarantee of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, the House approved an amendment in
direct response to the Littleton, Colo., school shootings and
bombings that would crack down harder on major juvenile crime by
imposing tougher penalties and making it easier for minors to be
tried and incarcerated as adults. The measure, sponsored by Rep.
Bill McCollum, R-Fla., was approved 249-181, despite attempts by
some Democrats to kill it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, said she was concerned that
the McCollum amendment ``ignores studies'' indicating that tougher
penalties don't necessarily result in reduced crime. She called on
her fellow lawmakers to do more in the area of prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The McCollum measure, she said, ``locks up our juveniles. It
throws away the key and it doesn't focus us on rehabilitation and
prevention programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The votes cleared the way for a debate today on several gun
control measures that were hammered out in response to the
Columbine High School tragedy in which 14 students and one teacher
were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, over Democratic objections, succeeded in
separating most of the gun control issues opposed by the National
Rifle Association from the juvenile crime bill, hoping to avoid a
contentious debate that might end up killing legislation to
strengthen enforcement efforts targeted at the nation's youth.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate over the Hyde amendment and other crime measures
sparked a number of angry exchanges, including a few over GOP
efforts to focus the debate more on ``cultural problems''
associated with youth violence rather than the guns used to commit
much of that violence.
</P>
<P>
   Waving a gun and a television remote control at his colleagues,
Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., accused Republicans of trying to avoid
the hard decisions required to help limit youth access to guns by
muddying the waters with a debate over violence as depicted in the
entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of gun control, we're doing remote control,'' Wexler
bellowed. ``Instead of going after NRA, we're going after NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Benjamin Cardin, D-Md., said he was concerned that
Republicans were intent on spending ``more time debating why a
child shouldn't see a handgun on TV instead of how to keep a child
from getting his hands on a handgun in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the attacks on Republican motives, Hyde insisted that
while common sense gun controls are important in the fight against
juvenile crime, Congress has an obligation to ``stand with''
parents and help them ``slow the flood of toxic waste into our
kids' minds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's critical that Congress address some of the
cultural issues ... that cause children to get a gun and commit a
violent act,'' he said, adding that passing more gun laws ``won't
get at the heart of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem is that many youngsters have been
overexposed to violence,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Hyde amendment, which included a number of his
Republican colleagues on the judiciary panel, said it amounted to
an unconstitutional attack on First Amendment rights. If passed and
upheld by the courts, they said it could lead to censorship of
family movies and even nursery rhymes containing references to
violent acts.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, D-Dallas, called it ``an unparalleled attack
on the first amendment,'' while Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., said it
would outlaw the rental and sale of Academy Award-winning movies
like ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A dealer who sells a `Shakespeare in Love' video would be
subject to criminal sanctions,'' she asserted, while a dealer who
peddles automatic weapons designed solely to kill people would not.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyde amendment would have placed severe restrictions on
youth access to art. For example, Democrat and Republican opponents
noted that it would prohibit minors in some instances from viewing
sculpture depicting female and male nude forms.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., said his colleague's proposal would
``create a police force'' to decide what is decent, violent or
pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   He wondered whether popular movies with depictions of violence
like ``Home Alone'' or ``Saving Private Ryan'' would be subject to
censor.
</P>
<P>
   Included in some of the other measures passed by the House on
Wednesday were penalties designed specifically to address firearms
taken to school by students.
</P>
<P>
   One amendment approved 296-133 would prohibit federal courts
from imposing early release programs because of prison crowding or
other conditions. The measure was sponsored by House Majority Whip
Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who told his colleagues that ``all the talk
about fighting crime and keeping children safe boils down to
nothing if we are not willing to keep prisoners behind bars where
they belong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already passed its own version of the juvenile
crime bill, including extending background checks to pawn shops and
gun shows. The House bill, which will be completed today, is
expected to be weaker on gun control but tougher on penalties for
juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills will have to be merged into one in conference before
a final version can be sent on to the White House for the
president's signature.
</P>
<P>
   A number of amendments could prove too objectionable to
President Clinton and might prompt a veto, including DeLay's
amendment that would severely curtail the authority of federal
judges.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
