<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-CABLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AT&AMP;T APPEALS RULING FORCING IT TO SHARE CABLE LINES  &HT;     By DEBORAH SOLOMON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
AT&AMP;T Corp. filed an appeal Wednesday of a ruling that would force
the telecommunications giant to share its cable lines with
competitors in Portland, Ore.
<P>
   As expected, AT&AMP;T is challenging a June 3 U.S. District Court
decision that allows other Internet service providers, such as
America Online, the right to offer high-speed Internet access over
AT&AMP;T's cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling could set a national precedent, as San Francisco and
other cities have been closely watching the Portland case and may
model their own policies on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's appeal, filed in San Francisco, said the ruling violates
the Cable Act because municipalities don't have the right to
require ``open access.''
</P>
<P>
   When AT&AMP;T bought Tele-Communications Inc. last year, it had to
apply for a transfer of control of TCI's cable TV franchises in
each city where TCI operates. Officials in Portland said they would
approve the transfer but said AT&AMP;T had to lease its cable lines to
competitors who wanted to offer phone, video and high-speed
Internet access. AT&AMP;T and TCI sued Portland, saying cities had no
right to require this open access as a condition of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, a U.S. District judge sided with Portland, saying
cities could indeed impose open access.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, AT&AMP;T called the judge's decision wrong and said the
Cable Act specifically prevents municipalities from requiring
access to AT&AMP;T's high-speed pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal law could not be clearer,'' said Jim Cicconi, AT&AMP;T's
general counsel. ``By requiring that AT&AMP;T unbundle its cable
network, the Portland ordinance does exactly what federal law
forbids.''
</P>
<P>
   John Raposa, general counsel for GTE, which argued against AT&AMP;T
in the Portland case, said the ruling should be upheld because it
will give consumers more choices for high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, if Bay Area customers want to connect to the Internet
via cable TV lines, they have to go through Redwood City's Excite
AtHome. The service is available in about 40 Bay Area communities
for $40 a month, on top of the fee for cable TV service.
</P>
<P>
   If AT&AMP;T is forced to lease its lines to AOL, Compuserve and
other Internet service providers, consumers could soon get
high-speed Internet access from a number of players, potentially
reducing costs, Raposa said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0500 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8423 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BELFOUR-HNS &LR;      06-16 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BELFOUR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ The situation is familiar, but the timing is just a little
off.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Dallas Stars last encountered a playoff Game 5, the sun
was high in the afternoon sky, and Ed Belfour regarded the
scheduling with all the enthusiasm of a vampire caught out after
hours. In the Western Conference finals against Colorado, the Stars
goalie watched the red light go on a whopping six times, by far his
worst effort of this postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Bad luck? Tough bounces? Poor defense?
</P>
<P>
   All of those played into that 7-5 loss, certainly, but Belfour
offers a more colorful explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an afternoon game,'' he recalled Wednesday. ``I don't
think either goalie was awake.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Belfour faces another Game 5, the next big step in these
Stanley Cup Finals against a Buffalo Sabres team that has been
reluctant to concede the issue. If the Stars could find any
consolation in all those missed chances in Tuesday night's 2-1 Game
4 loss in Buffalo, which tied the series at two games apiece, at
least they knew this much:
</P>
<P>
   Game 5 is a 7 p.m. start, getting Belfour back on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   This quirk was worth mentioning Wednesday as the teams returned
to Texas, since the Belfour-Dominik Hasek battle that gradually is
taking center stage in these Finals features players so different
in personality and image, yet so similar in results.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek is The Dominator, the Czech Olympic hero, the fellow
generally deemed the best in the world at what he does. His 30
saves in 31 shots Tuesday night makes a good argument on his
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the leader for us,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said. ``He
just said, `Bring it on.'''
</P>
<P>
   Through four games, Hasek has faced 127 shots, compiling a 1.89
goals-against average against a Dallas team generally considered
deeper and more talented. Should the Sabres go on to win the
series, the perceived edge in goal will get plenty of mention in
explaining how the No. 7 seed in the East could find itself
hoisting the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In getting his team this far, though, The Dominator has been no
stranger to showmanship, some of it seemingly gratuitous.
</P>
<P>
   Before Game 4, Hasek urged his team to take more chances
offensively and allow him to cover any defensive lapses. He backed
that up with a solid game that may not have been quite as
spectacular as the numbers would suggest, but some still wondered
what it all meant in terms of who was running the show.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Hasek's would-be heroics in Game 4, Belfour
shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time the goalie starts telling the forwards how to play
the game, it seems a little ridiculous,'' he said. ``It would be
like them telling me how to stop the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek wasn't quite done, though. For good measure, he also
turned in several Academy Award-caliber flops in the interest of
drawing penalties and fueling the fires of both teammates and fans.
</P>
<P>
   The message: You want a hero, Dom's your man.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, by contrast, is a sad-eyed fellow who carries the
baggage of playoff failures past. As recently as the Colorado
series, when he got the better of three-time Stanley Cup winner
Patrick Roy, even teammates feared the 34-year-old ``Eagle'' was a
meltdown looking for a place to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, who served as Belfour's backup when the two were in
Chicago earlier in the decade, doesn't mind encouraging talk that
the Stars keep Belfour in more of a comfort zone and that his old
teammate doesn't really measure up with the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our teams are different,'' Hasek says. ``The way they (the
Stars) play, their goalie does not see as many shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Belfour saw only 18, but that didn't make it an
easy night.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's first goal came on a breakaway fueled by a Dallas
turnover. The second was the result of a giveaway when defenseman
Craig Ludwig virtually put the puck on Dixon Ward's stick in the
slot for what proved to be the winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, given such shoddy support, Belfour might have
gone ballistic. When Game 4 was in the books, he was the portrait
of calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens once in a while,'' he said. ``You'd like to have
them both back, but they (the Sabres) made some nice shots, some
nice plays.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   With a little less than seven minutes remaining in the second
period, he stoned the Sabres' Joe Juneau at point-blank range,
keeping the Stars within a goal. A few minutes later, Belfour made
the most spectacular save of the evening, diving through the crease
to blunt Miroslav Satan's shot with a stick he extended over the
line at the last second.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a guy make plays like that, you'd like to be
able to score a couple of goals for him,'' Stars defenseman Richard
Matvichuk said. ``We haven't been able to do that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Stars are two games away from winning hockey's
greatest prize, in large part because Belfour's 1.89 GAA has
matched that of the more celebrated Hasek. True, Belfour has been
asked to face just 75 shots in those same four games, but that _ as
Hasek noted _ is largely a product of Dallas' stifling defense and
emphasis on shot-blocking.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: ``These games are 2-1 because of the guys in
goal,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Eddie Belfour has held up his end of the bargain. If he
can keep doing so over the next few games, the Stars will be happy
to wake him up in time for the parade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
