<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-JACKSON-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT MATES: JACKSON ACCEPTS LAKERS' OFFER, CITING A MATCH OF
TALENTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Phil Jackson, scheduled to appear in Los
Angeles on Thursday to help his former teammate Bill Bradley in his
quest for a $200,000-a-year job, showed up a day early and landed a
$6 million-a-year job for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who was wooed by the New York Knicks and the New Jersey
Nets, ended his one-year sabbatical Wednesday by formally accepting
a five-year, $30 million contract to become head coach of the Los
Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to Bradley's presidential campaign was a coup for a
Lakers team in need of a leader to harness the talents of Shaquille
O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew he was the right coach for this team; we all in
management knew he was the right coach for this team, and now the
players know it,'' said Magic Johnson, a Lakers vice president and
part owner who walked away from the coaching job after 16 games in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's enthusiasm reflected an urgency in the front office of
a franchise that won five National Basketball Association
championships in the 80s, but has not been to the finals since
1991. This season the Lakers were swept by San Antonio in the
second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the start of another fantastic time for us,'' Jerry
West, the Lakers' executive vice president, said at a news
conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's salary is less than the $7 million a year the Nets are
believed to have offered him, and the $8 million a year Pat Riley
earns as coach and general manager of the Miami Heat. But it still
makes him one of the NBA's highest-paid coaches. The Lakers'
majority owner, Jerry Buss, had been reluctant to pay huge salaries
to coaches. But after the Lakers were swept in the second round of
the playoffs by the San Antonio Spurs, West quickly hammered out a
deal with Todd Musburger, Jackson's agent. Negotiations culminated
last week, while Jackson was fishing in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in an Eskimo village and a kid came out and said he
wanted my autograph because I coach his favorite team,'' Jackson
said. ``I told him I don't coach the Bulls anymore. He said his
favorite team is the Lakers and I was just hired. That's how I
heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who is 53, left the Chicago Bulls after coaching them
to their sixth championship in eight seasons and has the highest
regular-season and post-season winning percentages in NBA history.
He spent the last year ``re-energizing'' and campaigning for
Bradley, once his teammate with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said his family helped persuade him to return to
coaching because ``it's what I do best,'' and that while he
considered other offers, it was the Lakers who piqued his interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my talent and the talent of the team matched up,''
he said. ``It kind of meshed. Shaq, I feel for him. He's
underplayed his ability. He could be mvp I'm intrigued with Kobe.
He has Jordanesque-type ability, but he's uneducated in basketball
and in life. And it ends up with Jerry West, one of, if not the
best general managers to get talent. All these things fit
together.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Jackson criticized the East Coast news media for making an issue
of his secret meeting in April with Dave Checketts, the Madison
Square Garden president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Knicks were in ninth place at the time,'' he said. ``We
talked about searching for players and positions. It was blown
completely out of proportion. Obviously, Dave had people working
behind his back against him. There were no negotiations at that
time. I respect Dave and felt he had been maligned in that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that in talks with the Nets in late May or early
June, he told Raymond Chambers, one of the team's owners, that the
organization was moving in the right direction but that he did not
feel up to coaching this year. Chambers asked if there was any team
that could make Jackson change his mind. ``I said the Lakers,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he needed to talk to the current coaching staff
before naming his assistants. That includes his predecessor, Kurt
Rambis, who has been promised a job in the organization after
taking over from Del Harris 12 games into the season.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
