<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8425 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IDEAL-HUSBAND-FILM-2T     06-16 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDEAL-HUSBAND-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT LITERATURE. PERIOD COSTUMES. THAT IS SO COOL.  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Oliver Parker's slick new screen adaptation of ``An Ideal
Husband,'' one of Oscar Wilde's lesser-known stage comedies, all of
the well-heeled characters, played by such of-the-moment film
actors as Rupert Everett, Cate Blanchett and Minnie Driver, gather
for an evening in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   The camera shifts fleetly from box seat to box seat, recording
the stars' suggestive smiles and meaningful glances and helping to
frame one of the movie's motifs, that in the social whirl of London
100 years ago, the privileged classes were as prone to the vanities
and weaknesses of the heart, soul and purse as the beautiful people
of today.
</P>
<P>
   As we watch them watch, the sights and sounds of an actual play
can be discerned, and any theatergoer with even a passing
acquaintance with Wilde will get the director's joke. It is Wilde's
masterpiece ``The Importance of Being Earnest'' that unfolds in the
background. Yet more than an homage is intended, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the rest of Parker's chiseled, glamourpuss production,
the sequence from ``Earnest'' is starchy and antique-looking, a
pill prescribed by a Victorian physician. In the contrast one can
infer the director's subliminal message. That may have been your
great-grandfather's ``Earnest.'' But this is (italics)your(end
italics) ``Ideal Husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker's movie, which opened Friday, is the latest entry in a
burgeoning genre, the hip theatrical period piece. ``Shakespeare in
Love'' is the apogee in this prestige category, having polished the
concept to a high gloss and hit the jackpot with a film that was
not only robustly witty and romantic but also helpfully filled with
young stars like Gwyneth Paltrow and Ben Affleck.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Ideal Husband'' aspires to the same kind of crossover
appeal to literary and popular tastes. (Less successful was the
recent ``Midsummer Night's Dream,'' with Michelle Pfeiffer and
Calista Flockhart.)
</P>
<P>
   ``An Ideal Husband'' is polished, too, and filled with
first-rate British acting talent in small roles down to
infinitesimal ones. (Great actors of the London stage are often
wasted in movie walk-ons; here the travesties include peekaboo
appearances by Simon Russell Beale, recently seen as Iago in Sam
Mendes's ``Othello,'' and Nickolas Grace, so wonderful years ago in
``Brideshead Revisited.'')
</P>
<P>
   And in the participation of Everett, Ms. Blanchett, Ms. Driver
and the cast's single American lead in Julianne Moore, the film
more than meets the demand for players who can garner the attention
of editors at People and Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with its formidable quotients of finery and
celebrity, ``An Ideal Husband'' is less than an ideal transfer from
the stage to the screen. It's a sleek film, yes, but it also seems
supermodel-scrawny, thin and alabaster pale to the point of
translucence. Of course it comes with the trademark Wildean
epigrams: ``To love oneself is the beginning of a lifelong
romance''; ``what is unfashionable is what other people wear'' _
all those juicy bon mots uttered on divans, bridle paths and
greenswards over Darjeeling, port and Havanas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all of its glibness, the movie is neither particularly
redolent of Wildean hilarity nor infused with the playwright's
celebrated iconoclasm. It's a rather numbing little melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, ``An Ideal Husband'' is not Wilde in tiptop form. The
play has had its admirers _ George Bernard Shaw famously declared
it superior to ``Earnest'' _ and rare, acclaimed revivals like
Peter Hall's 1996 Broadway production. Nevertheless, Wilde's
achievement here is a lesser one, on a par with his conventionally
well-made ``Lady Windermere's Fan'' rather than the eternally
piquant and winning ``Earnest.''
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway, Hall enriched the proceedings by accentuating the
play's obsession with money and the sexual ambiguity of a central
character, Lord Goring, played intriguingly onstage by Martin Shaw
and less so in the film by Everett.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hall made it clear that while the confirmed bachelor Goring
might have been ``the idlest man in London,'' he was the most
entertaining personage in the story. It concerns the blackmailing
of Goring's best friend, Sir Robert Chiltern (played in the movie
by Jeremy Northam), by the mysterious Mrs. Cheveley (Ms. Moore).
Chiltern is a revered Member of Parliament and outstanding husband,
one of the ideal ones of the title, who hides a secret about
ill-gotten gains. Mrs. Cheveley threatens to expose him, blackening
his name and likely ruining his marriage to the worshipful Gertrude
(Ms. Blanchett).
</P>
<P>
   Around this pivotal crisis orbit the tale's other ethical and
farcical elements, including the question of whether Goring will
ever wed the adoring Mabel (Ms. Driver, in a role pumped up for the
movie version).
</P>
<P>
   Wilde once declared to a friend that ``An Ideal Husband''
``contained a great deal of the real Oscar.'' In the Broadway
revival, Hall clearly took Wilde at his word, turning Goring into a
stand-in for Wilde himself, an invention that enveloped Goring's
flirtations with Mabel in an ironic and gently touching air.
Parker, who also wrote the screenplay, takes a more widely
commercial (and less interesting) tack, conceiving Goring as a
fin-de-siecle matinee idol.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Ideal Husband'' pins its hopes, in fact, on the bankable
charms Everett exhibited in ``My Best Friend's Wedding.'' If the
success of ``Shakespeare in Love'' was embodied most completely in
the star-making performance by Ms. Paltrow, who was rewarded with
an Oscar, the filmmakers here appear to be counting on similar
feats of cinematic strength by Everett, whom the camera stalks
throughout this picture like an obsessed fan.
</P>
<P>
   Near the beginning of the film, there's a shameless
acknowledgment of the actor's physical appeal. Parallel scenes of
the upper-class men and women in leisurely pursuits have Ms.
Blanchett and Ms. Driver trapped in the contortions of a living
tableau, while Northam and Everett lounge in some sort of sauna.
Northam is bundled up. Everett, however, reclines in the pose of a
Greek hero, bare-chested and beaded with perspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Wilde's risible characters tend to be in on the elaborate joke
or completely out of it. Everett occupies some territory in
between; he's terribly self-conscious in this movie, his every roll
of the eye and peeved grimace and pouting glance slavishly
documented by the cinematographer. The effect on an audience is
predictable: at a recent preview, appreciative laughter rose from
his fans at the slightest on-screen wince or flinch.
</P>
<P>
   But his is not the only overdone portrayal: Ms. Moore, a
delightful chameleon of an actress on most occasions, is weirdly
woozy here as Mrs. Cheveley, speaking oddly through clenched teeth
and appearing at times to be a victim of overmedication.
</P>
<P>
   Parker takes some liberties with the text, creating, for
example, a character for the actor Jeroen Krabbe in a flashback
sequence that provides more heft and emphasis for Chiltern's
misdeed. But it is not the mechanics of adaptation that constrain
this ``Husband.'' It's the attempt to dress Wilde to the teeth, to
package his words, rather than live in them again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
