<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8427 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALM-ORGANIZERS-SFCHR     06-16 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALM-ORGANIZERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LATEST PALMTOPS ARE PUMPED UP  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Combine the proven popularity of 3Com's Palm handheld organizers
with the allure of the Internet, make it work without wires, and
you have something that ought to be unbeatable.
<P>
   It's called the Palm VII, and it truly is nifty _ a tantalizing
taste of a future in which wireless communicators are as
commonplace as calculators, or maybe even wristwatches. But put it
to work in the here and now, as I have been doing for the past
couple of weeks, and you quickly bump up against some frustrating
limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I have also been trying out the Cassiopeia E100, a
pocket-size competitor from Casio. It does not have wireless or
even a conventional modem built in, and its software, Microsoft's
Windows CE, is not as elegant as Palm's. But the E100 has some
unique virtues of its own _ notably, a gorgeous color screen and a
headphone jack that lets you listen to digital music in stereo.
</P>
<P>
   Neither device is easy to get hold of, and in both cases prices
are steep. The Palm VII costs $599, plus monthly service fees, and
it is currently on sale only in the New York area, although the
wireless features work anywhere in urban America. (It is slated to
go on sale nationwide this fall.). The Cassiopeia E100 lists for
$499, and although in theory it is available anywhere, in reality
dealers report long waiting lists for it.
</P>
<P>
   PALM BASICS: The Palm VII looks like older Palm organizers,
rather than the sleek and silvery new Palm V. In most ways, it also
works &LR;   &LR; like previous models. It has the same easy-to-use software
for recording names and addresses, appointments, to-do items,
expenses and notes. You enter your information the same way, by
writing on it with a stylus in a simplified alphabet called
Graffiti. And, as before, you can connect the device to a PC or a
Mac and synchronize handheld and desktop data at the press of one
button.
</P>
<P>
   The new model also shares the shortcomings of its older
siblings. The monochrome screen is sharp but small _ about 21/4
inches square _ and dim. Switching on backlighting turns it a
garish green. A pair of AAA batteries can still run it for weeks,
depending on usage; unfortunately, unlike the new Palm V, it does
not have a rechargeable power pack built in.
</P>
<P>
   NET ACCESS, PALM-STYLE: Aside from a slightly elongated shape,
the only visual clue to the Palm VII's uniqueness is a small
plastic antenna along the right side. Swing it up, and within
seconds you are automatically connected to 3Com's Palm.net service.
Work your way through a few simple screens to set up your account
and you are ready to start exchanging e-mail or gathering
information from the Web wirelessly.
</P>
<P>
   Within limits. You have to use a new e-mail address at Palm.net,
rather than your existing address. Long messages are cut off or
simply not delivered, and attached files, except plain-text memos,
are removed.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, it is somewhere in between a full-blown e-mail
system and a text pager. Unlike a pager, though, the Palm VII does
not automatically receive new messages sent your way _ you do not
get them until you fire up Palm's iMessenger program to check for
them.
</P>
<P>
   As for the World Wide Web, you can't browse it in the
traditional sense from the Palm VII _ the screen is too small and
the wireless network Palm uses too slow (a paltry 8 kilobytes per
second) for that. What you can do is choose among a set of small
Palm programs that let you retrieve specific bits of information,
which Palm calls ``Web clippings,'' from selected sites.
</P>
<P>
   You can, for instance, get news briefs from ABC News and USA
Today, headlines and summaries from the Wall Street Journal (and
full stories if you open an extra-cost subscription) and sports
scores from ESPN. You can get stock quotes (but not trade) via
E-Trade, check your Bank of America balance and get the address of
the nearest ATM. Or look up phone numbers, e-mail addresses,
airline schedules, movie show times, hotel and restaurant listings,
traffic and weather reports, even miniature maps. Answers generally
come back within 5 to 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Such tidbits are a far cry from the breadth and depth of the Web
itself, but they will be of great value to many users, especially
busy business travelers. And being able to get them within seconds,
wherever you are, without even having to plug into a phone line, is
a huge convenience.
</P>
<P>
   You will pay for the convenience, though. Besides a one-time $20
set-up fee, basic service is $9.99 a month. But that covers only 50
Kbytes of transferred data _ something like 30 messages (one a
day), 20 stock quotes, 10 sports scores, 10 traffic reports, and 10
weather updates. For $24.99 a month you can receive three times as
much data. But serious Internet junkies will eat through that in
days, and with either monthly plan, Palm charges 30 cents for each
extra kilobyte.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the Palm VII is both elegant and innovative. But as
an Internet access device, it is also pricey and limited. If you
want full untethered access to the Net, you will be better off, at
least in the Bay Area, with one of Metricom's Ricochet wireless
modems.
</P>
<P>
   BOLD AND BRIGHT: The Palm VII's other big weakness is its
screen, which my over-50 eyes found difficult to read under many
lighting conditions. The opposite is true of the Cassiopeia E100:
Its screen is its most outstanding feature. It is noticeably bigger
than the Palm VII's, but the real difference is that Casio's
display has bright, crisp 16-bit color. Color is not just more
pleasant to look at than the drab Palm screen _ it also makes text
much easier to read and screen controls easier to manage.
</P>
<P>
   The silver Casio unit itself is a little thicker and heavier
than the Palm VII, but it still fits easily in a shirt pocket. Its
lithium-ion battery pack lasts around six hours. That could be a
problem if, for example, you plan to use it while hiking,
especially because you can't just swap in a new set of disposable
batteries. But if you keep it in its cradle when at your desk, and
plug its AC adapter into the cradle, it will recharge as you work
and be ready to roll when you are.
</P>
<P>
   The device's software, the palm-size edition of Windows CE,
provides personal-information management features like Palm's,
except that, oddly, there is no expense-recording program. As with
Palm devices, you enter data with a stylus, but with the Casio you
get more choices about how: You can tap out your words on an
on-screen keyboard or use a program called Jot, which does an
excellent job recognizing either conventional block printing or
Graffiti-style script.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Windows CE often complain that its desktop-derived
user interface is too complex and clunky for palm-size devices.
There is truth to that, but Casio has gone a long way toward
addressing the issue by adding a new iconic program-launching
screen, plus several user-configurable buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Windows CE's desktop-connectivity software could be simpler to
set up, but it works well with Windows PCs. (There is no Mac
version at all.) I configured the software to synchronize
automatically with Outlook 98 on my PCs at home and at work, so
every time I enter an appointment or contact name on the handheld
or either desktop machine, it is automatically copied to the others
the next time I plug the E100 into the PC. I don't even have to
remember to push a button!
</P>
<P>
   MULTIMEDIA IN YOUR HAND: Where the E100 really leads the pack is
in its audio and even video capabilities, though you will have to
install some extra software to take full advantage of them. At
www.audible.com, for example, you can find a free player for audio
books and articles. And at &LR;   &LR; www.xaudio.com, you can download the
killer app for this device: a free player for MP3 music, the
digital-audio format that has taken the Internet by storm.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Cassiopeia comes with 16 megabytes of RAM (compared to
only 2 MB in the Palm VII), you will probably have room for only
two or three cuts. But since the E100 has a special slot for a kind
of add-on memory called CompactFlash, you can easily pop in extra
RAM. I added a 48MB CompactFlash card, which should easily hold
between 10 to 20 songs.
</P>
<P>
   What you end up with is a full-blown pocket-size MP3 player,
comparable to Diamond Multimedia's popular Rio, except that the
E100 is also a versatile organizer. A small built-in speaker puts
out surprisingly good-quality sound, though not much volume. But
most people will use the headphone jack, which generates output
that to my ear is nearly indistinguishable from CD-quality.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM LINE: Which, if either, of these devices makes sense for
you obviously depends on your needs, tastes and budget. Personally,
I was more excited to discover the Cassiopeia E100, which has not
yet received much publicity, and more frustrated by the limitations
of the Palm VII, about which there has been so much hype. But both
devices, in my opinion, are indisputably cool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
