<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0505 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8428 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-OPHULS-$ADV20-     06-16 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-OPHULS-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPHULS' MOVIES DISPLAY DEPTH THAT MADE HIM A FILMMAKER'S ROLE MODEL
  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By PHILLIP LOPATE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whatever the summer movies may bring, it is a safe
bet that the most ravishing, romantic images on-screen this season
will be at the Max Ophuls retrospective, starting on June 26 and
running through July 15 at the Film Society of Lincoln Center's
Walter Reade Theater.
</P>
<P>
   This virtually complete selection of 21 Ophuls films, with many
rarities and new prints, will be catnip for film buffs, who regard
the divine Max as their patron saint _ perhaps because no other
director in the history of movies wrung so much emotional resonance
from cinematic technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``His camera could pass through walls,'' said Stanley Kubrick,
referring to Ophuls' penchant for movement. The French New Wave,
especially Francois Truffaut, regarded him as their auteur role
model, because he had managed to impose a personal style in the
face of producer pressures. A bon vivant who was subject to fits of
depression, Ophuls dramatized the will to pleasure and its
attendant humiliations.
</P>
<P>
   But Ophuls also had his detractors, who saw him as a decorative
stylist without substance. The fact that he made what might be
called ``women's films'' held him back from being taken seriously
during his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after his death, in 1957, that he was canonized,
though there is still debate whether to regard him as a ``beloved
minor master'' (Richard Roud) or ``one of the greatest of film
directors'' (David Thomson). The paradox of Max Ophuls is that he
may have been both _ minor and great.
</P>
<P>
   One is tempted to call Ophuls a Viennese master, since so many
of his signature works are set in 1900 Vienna. Yet the facts are
that he was a German who gravitated to France.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn imaginatively to the end of the century Vienna of
Schnitzler, Freud and Hapsburg pomp, Ophuls re-created it on the
sound stage as a closed society with recognizable types (army
officer, artist, investor, beautiful young woman desired by all),
locales (Opera, Prater park, train station) and moral quandaries
(family pressure to marry, adultery, aristocratic code of honor,
the duel.)
</P>
<P>
   Ophuls himself came from a more bourgeois, nondueling
background. He was born Max Oppenheimer in 1902; his German-Jewish
family owned a department store, and in deference to their
proprieties he changed his name when he decided to pursue acting.
</P>
<P>
   Short, not particularly handsome, with no acting talent, he
quickly switched to directing. By age 23 he had directed hundreds
of plays, operettas and radio shows, and worked at the Burg theater
in Vienna (the one year he lived in that city). There he also met
and married actress Hilde Wall. By 1930, recognized as a premiere
theater director, he was lured into filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   The tragic love story ``Liebelei'' (1933), adapted from
Schnitzler, gave Ophuls his first international success. In
``Liebelei'' a young opera singer and an officer of the dragoons
fall in love, but past mistakes catch up with the officer: he is
forced to fight a fatal duel with an ex-mistress' husband. This
simple, delicate film is embellished with tender scenes of lovers
riding through the snow, waltzing all night in a Viennese cafe.
Courtship passages were an Ophuls specialty.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s Ophuls left Nazi Germany to make movies in Italy,
Holland and France. ``La Signora di Tutti'' (Everybody's Woman),
shot in Italy in 1934, was a particularly sparkling, if mordant,
tale of a reluctant femme fatale: a young woman whose beauty brings
death and misery to everyone around her. She ends up a movie star.
</P>
<P>
   The shot of her rowing in a boat while her elderly married
suitor drives along the riverbank in pursuit has a gliding
liquidity, both pastoral and ominous. ``La Signora di Tutti'' also
initiated the Ophuls tendency to tell a character's life story,
``Citizen Kane''-like, through a complex flashback structure.
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight features he shot in France during this period, all
have their charms, but the freshest is ``Divine'' (1935), from a
Colette script about music-hall life. Ophuls loved to film the
backstage milieu, the agitations of show people. The result was
what Truffaut called ``a little masterpiece of verve, health and
life with that Ophulsian fury that drives the camera up staircases,
into the flies, in and out of the wings.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1941, just managing to escape the Gestapo, he landed in
Hollywood, along with many other European refugees, and cooled his
heels for four years, waiting for someone to offer him work. He
finally directed four pictures for small studios, including an
under-rated 1949 gem, ``The Reckless Moment,'' with Joan Bennett
and James Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Koch, who wrote the screenplay for Ophuls' best American
movie, ``Letter From an Unknown Woman,'' recalled: ``I remember my
first impression of him as a baldish Peter Lorre, with the same
heavy-lidded, wide-set eyes and the same impish sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Ophuls had transported to California his wife, Hilde, his son,
Marcel (later to become an important documentary filmmaker) _ and
his attractive young mistress. ``Since Americans are not adept at
this sort of thing,'' wrote Koch, ``Max undertook to instruct me on
some of the finer points. One of his rules that I recall is that
cut flowers are properly sent to one's mistress as they are
perishable, whereas a plant, being more durable and therefore more
economical, is the correct choice for one's wife.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this wry, unshocked recognition of the desires and
complications of adult life that Ophuls brought to the American
screen. In ``Letter From an Unknown Woman,'' for instance, a young
Viennese woman, Lisa (warmly played by Joan Fontaine), has a
gigantic crush on a dashing composer-pianist, Stefan (Louis
Jourdan). She tracks him down, sleeps with him and, when he
disappears, bears his child without telling him.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, married, she bumps into him, goes to his rooms
again, ready to throw over all her security for love _ only to
discover he has no memory of her. Yet, for all her disillusionment,
she is throughout, as critic Molly Haskell has observed, the active
party, one of those Ophuls heroines who become ``militarists of
love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Letter From an Unknown Woman'' offers a feast of
black-and-white chiaroscuro: pools of shadows and gaslight
distributed impeccably in the frame, thanks to Franz Planer's
brilliant photography, but also to Ophuls' theater background,
which encouraged Expressionist lighting and a stylized suggestion
of background detail. Meanwhile, his gliding camera roved up
staircases and paced through rooms, bringing a joyous pulse to this
otherwise plangent material.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Why did Ophuls move his camera so? Much learned nonsense has
been written about the symbol of the Ophulsian circle, about time,
transcendence, the lustful gaze of the moviegoer trapped and
imprisoned within the frame. Perhaps James Mason (who starred in
two Ophuls movies and revered him) came closest with the rhymed
suggestion that he did it for fun:
</P>
<P>
   A shot that does not call for tracks
</P>
<P>
   Is agony for poor dear Max
</P>
<P>
   Who separated from his dolly
</P>
<P>
   Is wrapped in deepest
</P>
<P>
   melancholy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ophuls seemed to take boyish pleasure in solving the technical
questions of the long take. His curiosity kept him glued to his
protagonists, while showing the whirl of indifferent life around
them. Others have suggested that he moved his camera to help his
actors, who were forced into naturalness by motion. His mobile
camera imposed a sense of fatalism on the story, oddly enough, as
though all this lilting motion were only there to hasten a final
stasis.
</P>
<P>
   When Ophuls returned to France in 1950, he embarked on a quartet
of historical films considered by critics to be his most
significant works: ``La Ronde,'' ``Le Plaisir,'' ``The Earrings of
Madame De ... ,'' and ``Lola Montes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``La Ronde'' took Ophuls back to Schnitzler's 1900 Vienna: he
solved the challenge of the play's maddening kaleidoscopic shifts
by inventing a new character, the master of ceremonies, played by
Anton Walbrook, who keeps reappearing under different disguises,
commenting on the ``art of love'' and binding the film together
while pointing out its artifice. (At one point he is glimpsed
mischievously snipping out a sex scene.)
</P>
<P>
   Ophuls had a brilliant cast to work with, including Simone
Signoret, Gerard Philipe, Danielle Darrieux, Serge Reggiani and
Jean-Louis Barrault. The film was an enormous popular success. He
followed this up with ``Le Plaisir'' (``Pleasure''), a ripe,
virtuoso compilation film drawn from three de Maupassant stories.
Again there was an invented narrator-character, adding another
worldly layer of commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Ophuls had reached a new stage in handling romantic genre
material. From the straight renditions of ``Liebelei,'' he had
moved to complicate, take apart, use flashbacks within flashbacks,
multiply narratives into vignettes and intrude an ironic narrator.
He also took to fragmenting images by shooting characters through
windows, behind glass partitions and in front of mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Ophuls became, in short, more of a self-consciously modernist
artist.
</P>
<P>
   This self-reflective process reached its apotheosis in his
disturbing last film, ``Lola Montes'' (1956), the only one he made
in color and Cinemascope. Here the backgrounds are sumptuously
animated, while the central performance, Lola (Martine Carol),
remains wooden. True, the barely adequate, sex-kittenish Carol was
not his choice, but having accepted her, Ophuls did little to bring
her performance alive, gambling that its very blankness would drive
home the point of the film, that desire was a matter of projection.
</P>
<P>
   He confessed he was not much interested in this courtesan. ``But
the people around her, they are passionately interesting,'' he
said. ``If the public understands that these characters are not
secondary or `episodic,' as people like to say, then all is well.''
The public didn't; they heckled so much that police had to be
called in. Truffaut, Rossellini, Cocteau, Tati and other respected
filmmakers signed a petition endorsing the film.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics consider ``Lola Montes'' Ophuls' supreme
masterpiece. I regard this as wishful thinking by auteurists, who
want to see his last work as the summit of his art, not as a
fascinating, flawed, transitional film he had the bad luck not to
outlive.
</P>
<P>
   True, ``Lola Montes'' makes the best case for Ophuls as a
pioneering post-modernist. But before we enshrine him as a clever
deconstructionist of spectacle or a Brechtian practicing alienation
effects, we ought to remember what draws us to his art in the first
place: his capacity to convey feelings rapturously onscreen.
</P>
<P>
   In each Ophuls film, there is a moment when a man and a woman
first become aware of their magnetic attraction and lean into each
other. It is always a believable scene; Ophuls had the knack of
capturing sexual emanations on film. He was not necessarily a big
believer in love: sometimes the infatuations signify no more than
physical attraction, or painful misunderstandings with eternal love
on one side and momentary appetite on the other (``Letter From an
Unknown Woman'').
</P>
<P>
   Ophuls was always a realist when it came to the transience of
erotic feelings. ``La Ronde'' and ``Le Plaisir'' are sardonic
paeans to the mechanical underpinnings of amorous transport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Earrings of Madame De ...'' represents an exquisite
balance in Ophuls' late manner between engagement and detachment,
cynicism and idealism. It is graced by three immortal performances.
A witty, hardened general and his vain, frivolous wife (played by
Charles Boyer and Danielle Darrieux) are used to deceiving each
other. He has mistresses, and will accept any number of his wife's
suitors, so long as her heart is untouched by love.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, she meets an elegant Italian diplomat (Vittorio
de Sica), who sweeps her off her feet. The great ballroom montage,
which conflates weeks of courtship into a single protracted waltz,
leads to her confession of love: ``I don't love you,'' she says,
meaning she does. Used to lying as a matter of course, she finds
herself confounded by the rules of genuine feeling. Ophuls gave
Darrieux the instruction to use her charms to ``incarnate a void.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Chekov's lady with a lap dog, Madame De, initially shallow,
becomes deepened and purified, if destroyed, by the experience of
love. What makes the film so extraordinary is the coexistence of
the libertinish pleasure given to the eye, and the cruelly moral,
inexorable narrative tightening like a noose.
</P>
<P>
   One may go back and forth in one's feelings about other Ophuls
movies, falling under their spell one time, coming back years later
and finding them contrived or melodramatic. But ``The Earrings of
Madame De ... '' is always sublime. It is a perfect film. Anyone
who made one of the greatest films of all time cannot, in the end,
be considered minor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
