</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEVELAND-MUSIC-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDUCTING A CHEMICAL EXPERIMENT 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Calif.)   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Franz Welser-Most's scheduled ascendance in 2002 to music
director of the Cleveland Orchestra is hopeful news. Conductors and
orchestras are sometimes about individual and collective
personalities, but in some places, Cleveland among them, the
subject is chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Christoph von Dohnanyi was the missing ingredient when he took
over a brilliant band of Cleveland players in 1984. Extraordinary
ensemble virtuosity met deep and implacable seriousness, setting
off some of the most significant orchestra playing of the
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Dohnanyi may not be the best conductor in the world, nor
Cleveland the best orchestra, but together they are hard to beat.
</P>
<P>
   With its ensemble skills still palpably in place from the George
Szell era, Cleveland could just as easily have slipped into the
narcissism that beset our own New York Philharmonic under Zubin
Mehta. This was bad chemistry, in which the worst instincts of both
parties served as mutual catalysts. If Kurt Masur's tenure, itself
about to end, has been a little dour, it has scrubbed away
accumulated slickness.
</P>
<P>
   Welser-Most's recent guest appearance in New York produced a
Bruckner Fifth Symphony filled with structural disconnections and a
brass section turned loose to bully everything around it. Tough and
talented professionals don't like conductors who talk a lot, and
this was one of the complaints coming out of his rehearsals here.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Sanderling has not had a happy time in New York either,
although the Los Angeles Philharmonic likes him a lot. Colin Davis,
however, has players here in the palm of his hand and has got
wonderfully musical performances from them. Strange indeed are the
chemical reactions of the orchestra business.
</P>
<P>
   Welser-Most, a serious and talented musician, took a public
beating at the London Philharmonic a few years back, as London's
many (perhaps too many) orchestras competed viciously not just for
a finite audience but also for shrinking government financing.
</P>
<P>
   He is older, at 38, and Cleveland will be a quieter place.
Indeed, his new ensemble may profit from being in a less glamorous
city. The Cleveland Orchestra tours and records to great acclaim,
but it can always return to the relative peace of Severence Hall
and a loyal, sophisticated audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Welser-Most appointment removes one name from many other
short lists. Esa-Pekka Salonen was said to be coveted in Cleveland,
but he will remain in Los Angeles, if, that is, composing
aspirations do not siphon his energies. Salonen has been brave,
forward-looking and a salesman as well.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Boulez's visits to Cleveland have heavily supplemented
Dohnanyi's efforts to make the orchestra a force in 20th-century
performance, but basically this is an ensemble grounded in an older
tradition. Maybe that fact gave Salonen pause. He is getting his
way in Los Angeles. He also might not trade the seductions of
Southern California for those of industrial Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Like New York and Cleveland, the Philadelphia Orchestra has
asked its departing music director to stay around until a
replacement is in place. But as Wolfgang Sawallisch gradually makes
his way to the door, no one new has appeared. Philadelphia
management salivates over the prospect of Simon Rattle, who has
conducted there with great success and is now cut loose from his
orchestra in Birmingham, England.
</P>
<P>
   Rattle could certainly muster the earthmoving equipment
necessary to a bring a relatively staid city and a conservative
orchestra board up to his standards of adventure, but it would
require a tremendous effort.
</P>
<P>
   Riccardo Chailly, now in Amsterdam, might try. He knows the
orchestra; he has good contacts with the recording business, and he
could well rouse Philadelphia to old standards. Chailly's
glamour-minded conducting and the Concertgebouw Orchestra's
strait-laced tradition have created odd bedfellows, but there has
been a rise from financial decline.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that could happen in Philadelphia, a city that has clung
to an old concert space of atrocious acoustics and been dragged
toward a replacement hall kicking and screaming.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on Rattle in New York either, even though he could
handle the city's pressure and its show-me toughness as well as
anybody. He has never conducted the Philharmonic, though if my
sources are right, it is not for lack of being asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rattle reportedly wants Europe as his base and has his eye on
yet another opening, at the Berlin Philharmonic. As Claudio Abbado
gradually withdraws from that job, aspirants have been narrowed to
two: Rattle and Daniel Barenboim. Barenboim, music director in
Chicago and a big player in European music, appears to be the
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Rattle, linked for years to the Boston Symphony's future, is
probably tired of waiting. For better or worse, Seiji Ozawa seems
an immovable incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   The name now circling the New York job is Riccardo Muti. I don't
think the yearslong chemistry of Muti's tenure in Philadelphia was
a good one, but his straightforward musicianship and great skills
might work here. Muti, it is also said, is not indifferent to
history and might find attractive a job once held by another
Italian, Arturo Toscanini.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest conducting talent floating around America
is an American, James Levine of the Metropolitan Opera. Levine has
his European orchestra now, a Munich Philharmonic badly in need of
rehabilitation. He has also shown in a brilliant and expanding
series of concerts how well he and his opera orchestra can play the
symphonic repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Levine would compromise that relationship for the New
York Philharmonic job is an interesting question. It could
certainly save on cab fare. His two offices at Lincoln Center would
be about 100 yards apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
