<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NY-GALLERY-$adv20     06-16 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NY-GALLERY-$adv20-2takes-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORING YESTERDAY'S STARS TO THE LIMELIGHT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY SCHWABSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The rich and various history of art in New York in
the 1960s and 70s is being rewritten _ not at any of the
universities where graduate students avidly pore over the origins
of Pop, Minimal and Conceptual Art, nor at the uptown museums that
seem content to keep reinvestigating acknowledged masters like
Jasper Johns and Ellsworth Kelly, but at a hole-in-the-wall
storefront gallery on Thompson Street. The gallery can't even open
before 3 p.m. because its owner, a high school science teacher
named Mitchell Algus, arrives after his first workday ends.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what a growing number of artists and critics
have been saying over the last few years. All of them seem to have
heard of the gallery by word of mouth, or just by having happened
to walk by when something interesting in the window caught their
eye. It's not unusual, of course, for galleries that show work by
young and relatively untested artists to be run on this kind of
shoestring basis. But the Mitchell Algus Gallery has a different
kind of program. Though Algus sometimes shows emerging artists too,
many of those he exhibits have had long and significant careers.
Some have had retrospectives at major museums; their work has been
featured on the covers of prominent art magazines or reproduced in
standard references like Irving Sandler's ``New York School'' or
Lucy Lippard's ``Six Years: The Dematerialization of the Art
Object.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all that, their names now trigger little more than a
vague recognition on the part of even the most passionate art
lovers. The museums keep their works in the basement, not on the
wall. They are artists who, for one reason or another, have dropped
out of the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   A good example would be Larry Zox, an abstract painter who was
honored by a full-scale retrospective at the Whitney Museum in 1973
but whose show at the Algus Gallery last winter was his first in
New York since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Another is Nicholas Krushenick, whose last works (he died of
cancer in February) are currently on view at the gallery, along
with a pair of his first mature paintings, dated 1962. The artist
Peter Halley, writing in the May issue of Artforum, called him
``one of the most exciting painters to emerge in the early 60s,''
thanks to his ``uncanny ability to transform dynamic forces into a
disembodied language of cartoonlike forms.''
</P>
<P>
   Algus is making ``an incredibly important contribution,'' says
Raphael Rubinstein, an art critic who is a senior editor at Art in
America. ``Other people talk about revisionist art history, but he
shows how narrow most others' ideas of revisionism really are.''
Algus himself seems to see it a little less earnestly. ``It's like
being a kid in a candy store,'' he says, referring not to the size
of his storefront but to his pleasure in immersing himself in art
that no one else seems to want anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the end of the war to the mid-70's, New York was it,'' he
explains. ``Now it's as though we're sitting around in Florence
after the Renaissance thinking that there were just a couple of
interesting artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The kind of art Algus shows _ the Color Field painting of Edward
Avedisian, the homoerotic hyper-realism of Harold Stevenson, the
``destruction art'' of the conceptualist Raphael Montanez Ortiz
(which indirectly inspired primal scream therapy) or the futuristic
polyester sculptures of Nancy Arlen _ actually recalls the period
between his first experiences of art and his own decision not to
make it himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was a dentist who had painters among his patients, and
there was always art around the house,'' says Algus, who grew up in
Brooklyn and on Long Island. ``I remember him taking me to the
Howard Wise Gallery to look at kinetic art.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his university major was in geology and he earned a
doctorate in the subject at McGill University, he ``spent a lot of
time in college and graduate school in the art library reading art
magazines,'' he recalls. He then began making art on his own as
well, exhibiting it in group shows at galleries around New York
including that of Pat Hearn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, a friend, Leecha Jimenez, told him that she needed a
partner to help run her gallery in the Williamsburg section of
Brooklyn, where his sculpture had also been exhibited. ``Once I
started running the gallery I stopped making art,'' he recalls.
``I'd always been interested in Robert Mallary's sculpture, so I
just called him up.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mallary was a pioneer of ``junk art'' assemblage who later
became one of the first to try his hand at computer art. ``I found
him up at the University of Massachusetts. He opened up his barn
and there were all those pieces I'd seen in crummy black-and-white
illustrations. And a light went off. Everything I wanted to see in
my art was already out there, and I just had to find it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the year after his partnership with Ms. Jimenez
dissolved, he opened his Thompson Street gallery.
</P>
<P>
   It is Algus' way of seeing the art of 30 years ago with the eye
of a contemporary artist that gives his program more than
antiquarian interest, though he has the kind of microscopically
detailed familiarity with the period that allows him to casually
cite, for example, the time and place where Jules Olitski and
Stanley Twardowicz bought their first spray-guns together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about resurrecting anybody,'' says Mary K.
Weatherford, a painter who frequents the gallery. ``It's just about
showing interesting work that younger artists have absorbed through
osmosis without ever having actually seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another painter, David Reed, explains that in the case of an
artist like Krushenick, who made abstract painting with a Pop
sensibility, the very factor that led to the artist's fall into
obscurity is the one that makes him interesting today. ``Nick was
excluded from the history of Pop because his work has no figurative
content, yet it didn't fit in with what was going on with
abstraction, so it wasn't canonized there either,'' says Reed.
``But Pop in abstraction is very important to current painting, so
he turned out to be one of the most influential painters of his
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Algus is clearly delighted by the interest of the artists and
critics who can often be found chatting with him in the gallery.
``It's great when young artists come in,'' he says, ``and I'm
showing the work of someone like Wojciech Fangor, who they've never
heard of, and they say, `But that's what I've been trying to paint
in the studio!'''
</P>
<P>
   He laments, however, the indifference of collectors to his
efforts. When asked about sales, the answer comes quickly:
``Nothing. Nothing. Artists have bought, a couple of critics have
bought, but collectors? There aren't many who have the courage of
their own perceptions. It's just buzz. So if no one's bought the
work for 20 years _ they don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're missing the real satisfaction of being able to deal
with major pieces,'' he continues. ``It's not like getting a
Lichtenstein print. You can get the best painting this artist ever
made.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   The gallery's supporters extend a similar critique to the museum
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a painter in New York since 1971, and before that a
student here, and there's a wonderful history that I'm aware of
because I've seen it,'' says Reed, ``but the museums aren't paying
attention to it. Instead this high school teacher steps in and does
it at one-one-thousandth of the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rubinstein agrees, saying that ``his program should be
putting pressure on MOMA and the Guggenheim to take another look at
what they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Storr, a curator at the Museum of Modern Art, disagrees.
``It's done all the time,'' he says. ``Laura Hoptman recently did a
show on Op Art here because it was something younger artists have
become interested in. What contemporary artists do always suggests
new ways of looking at the past. But you can't turn into the Museum
of Restored Reputations.''
</P>
<P>
   Another curator at a New York museum, who asked not to be
identified, concedes, however, that museums shy away from
re-examining underrated artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they should be looked at, but they're interesting mostly
for an art world insider audience, not a general audience, which is
what museums are looking for, with an eye on the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the same curator also points out that overlooked
artists still turn up at museums in group shows. The Algus
exhibition of Ortiz coincided with one at the Whitney, he notes,
and the painter-turned-conceptualist Lee Lozano's exhibition with a
show at the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rubinstein, Algus is playing with the effects of
nearness and distance in history. ``He makes you realize how far
away we are from a time as recent as 35 years ago, yet he also
makes you realize its relevance, that it's not so distant after
all.'' His project may be less like that of other galleries, let
alone museums, than it is comparable to that of certain artists who
have systematically blurred the line between art making on the one
hand and curating or collecting on the other. He could be compared
to Jim Shaw, with his hoard of thrift-shop paintings, for instance,
or Douglas Blau, with his salon-style concatenations of
reproductions.
</P>
<P>
   For Algus, what counts may really be less what he shows, despite
his interest in the recent past as a historical context for today's
art, than how it is seen. When art is overlooked by the
institutions that interpret history, its meaning becomes equivocal.
``People don't know how to see this work,'' he says. ``It could be
conventional or it could be ironic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more fun to show work that's elusive in that way. It
becomes an internal dialogue about what you bring to it. You can
make up your own story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
