<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DANES HOPE TO SILENCE THE AMERICAN PARTY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The official video promoting the Women's World Cup begins with
the Stars and Stripes. Then there is footage of Mia Hamm scoring a
goal. Next come more Stars and Stripes. Then a tape of the Olympic
gold-medal ceremony in Georgia in 1996. It is, shall we say, a
trifle jingoistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys are very good at that,'' said Lene Terp, the Denmark
captain, who noticed.
</P>
<P>
   The Danes are getting the feeling they are accessories to the
mission, the march of the Americans to the finals in the Rose Bowl,
theoretically after Norway and China finish beating each other up
in the other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   This soccer tournament was made in America, by Americans, for
Americans, but the Danes are just worldly enough to see the bright
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's been very good for soccer,'' Terp said. ``We would
not have done the same stuff if we were the host.''
</P>
<P>
   The Danes and the 14 other countries find themselves as honored
guests at a party, and they all like the sound of the party, if not
the anticipated result. Over 460,000 tickets have been sold, an
average of 27,000 per event.
</P>
<P>
   When the Danes march onto the lovely lush green anti-Parcells
grass field of Giants Stadium with their American sisters on
Saturday, at least 74,000 seats will be occupied, and maybe all
77,000 by that time.
</P>
<P>
   The extremely impressive sales are a testimony to the American
women being 1991 World Cup champions and 1996 Olympic champions
(even if NBC could not interrupt its canned features in Atlanta to
show live women actually competing.)
</P>
<P>
   The sales are also a tribute to the business acumen of Marla
Messing, the president of the organizing committee, who admitted
she would like to see ``a little more parity'' in the promotion of
the World Cup, the way Germany and Brazil are always esteemed
visitors at every men's World Cup around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   There is the danger that the enthusiasm for the Americans could
obscure the progress in other countries in overcoming traditional
taboos against female competition. As Messing noted, this is only
the third women's cup, ``and we are swimming upstream.'' Besides,
she said, ``It is hard to get footage of other teams. There just
aren't that many tapes in the vault.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks have earned the triumphalism. With it goes the
American-style excess, some of it downright smarmy. ESPN has been
carrying a craven plea for President Clinton to attend the final in
the Rose Bowl, as if only the presidential presence would justify
what these female athletes do. With any luck, he won't show, and
mess up traffic, besides.
</P>
<P>
   However, Giants Stadium will be jammed on Saturday, and the
crowd will probably be even more one-sided than the audiences at
the 1984 Summer Games when those great Americans, Mickey and
Minnie, won most of the medals in the absence of most of the Soviet
bloc and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have 300 Danish people,'' proudly announced Jorgen
Hvidemose, the Danish coach. ``They will all be sitting together
waving Danish flags.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his players would be aware of their 300 fans among the
screaming Americans, he replied, ``When we go up, 2-0, you will be
able to hear them,'' a wry smile indicating he was joking.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's news conference in New York, Hvidemose showed
himself to be a Victor Borge without the piano. He insisted
somebody in Michigan (not a journalist, he assured us) once
informed him that Denmark was the capital of the Netherlands. He
also said that while waiting for the team bus in Montclair, N.J.,
the other day, he met an American who did not know where Denmark
was.
</P>
<P>
   The Danes, meanwhile, tend to speak perfect English _ and not
just Mikka Hansen, who grew up in California and played for Santa
Clara University and for the American under-21 team for a while,
before opting for Danish dual citizenship to play in this World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen said her teammates were not totally put off by the
newspaper coverage and the publicity for Hamm and the rest of the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `That's America,''' Hansen said. ``They're all
talking about what a great job the U.S. is doing. They're looking
forward to playing in front of 75,000 people. They don't mind if
Mia has the commercials. It's good for soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, an American title would be good for soccer in
the home of the gigantic corporations that could sponsor leagues
and tournaments. But an upset of Ms. Goliath would be popular all
over the world. The makers of the official 1999 film would have to
include a foreign championship somewhere between shots of the Stars
and Stripes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
