<HEADLINE>
BOEING WORKING ON COMMERCIAL VERSION OF C-17; A CUSTOMER WOULD
HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Boeing Co. is quickly laying the groundwork for a
commercial version of its C-17 Air Force cargo plane.
</P>
<P>
   The certification process by the Federal Aviation Administration
began last month, and all that's needed before Boeing's board of
directors is asked to approve the launch of the MD-17 is a launch
customer, said Stu Thompson, vice president of business development
for Boeing's airlift and tanker group.
</P>
<P>
   At about $175 million a plane, the customer would have to have
very deep pockets. So to help reduce customer risk, Boeing is
taking a page from the fractional ownership concept _ multiple
owners or users of a single plane _ that has made the market for
business jets so successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullish index on the MD-17 has increased,'' Thompson said
in an interview this week at the Paris Air Show.
</P>
<P>
   The C-17 was built by McDonnell Douglas, and the MD designation
for the commercial version did not change after the company's 1997
merger with Boeing. If a launch customer is signed up, a new
designation for the MD-17 will surely follow.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he is much more optimistic today than he was a few
years ago that the MD-17 will become part of the Boeing commercial
airplane family.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell Douglas was talking about the MD-17 as far back as
1994. Expectations were raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, we probably started too early,'' Thompson said.
``The program may not have been mature enough for us to be
promoting the MD-17 as early as we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The C-17 program came close to being canceled by the Air Force
in the early 1990s because of cost overruns and questions about
performance. But reforms demanded by the Pentagon were put into
place and the program was dramatically turned around.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force awarded McDonnell Douglas a multiyear contract for
120 planes, which are built in Long Beach, Calif. The 52nd plane
off the assembly line will be delivered to McChord Air Force Base
near Tacoma next month.
</P>
<P>
   Congress just approved funding for an additional 15 planes to be
used for special military operations.
</P>
<P>
   And Boeing recently made an unsolicited proposal to the Air
Force to sell the service 60 planes at an average cost of $149
million in 1999 dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Under its current contract with Boeing, the Air Force is paying
an average of $198 million in 1999 dollars for its final 80 planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see here is our business base expanding,'' Thompson
said. ``This provides a stable production base so we can consider
the commercial plane as more viable.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is now engaged in trade studies to evaluate the
commercial pricing structure for an MD-17, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been out there in the commercial market place since
1996 with a catalogue price of $175 million flyaway cost for an
MD-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last summer, we began to read about what was happening in the
business jet market, with fractional ownership. The concept of a
shared risk to lower the entry barrier ... if we could find a way
to soften that huge initial acquisition cost, we might actually be
able to break down that barrier.''
</P>
<P>
   So Boeing began looking at a consortium approach to MD-17
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Potential customers could come from the oil, construction or
aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at the order book for big satellites,'' Thompson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is astounding. People don't put satellites on trucks or in
the holds of ships.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-engine giant, 174 feet long with a wingspan of 170
feet, can carry a maximum payload of nearly 170,000 pounds and can
land on short runways of 3,000 feet or less.
</P>
<P>
   It was designed to carry some of the Army's biggest weapons,
including the Apache helicopter and the M-1 tank.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's huge An-124 has proved there is a civilian market for
such a plane. Even Boeing occasionally uses the Antonov plane to
transport big items.
</P>
<P>
   To develop the MD-17, Boeing would have to remove military-type
items from the plane. But that could be accomplished for much less
than it now costs Boeing to build a derivative of one of its
commercial jets, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   A team from Boeing, the Air Force and the FAA are working on the
certification process that would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   When McDonnell Douglas first built the C-17, it was certified by
the Pentagon. The FAA may be able to get much of that flight test
data from the military, which could considerably shorten the
civilian flight test program.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing believes it can design, build and flight test the MD-17
within 36 months after it gets the green light from the board to
proceed with development.
</P>
<P>
   But that launch customer has still not come forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a lot of interest, but so far no one has come
forward with a checkbook,'' Thompson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
