<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-BOMB-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INDICTS 2 MORE MEN IN EMBASSY BOMBINGS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two men who the authorities say are leaders of an
Islamic terrorist organization were indicted Wednesday by a federal
grand jury in Manhattan on charges that they had a hand in the
bombing last summer of two American embassies in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the two, Ayman al-Zawahiri and Khalid al-Fawwaz,
are close associates of Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile who has
been charged with ordering the bombings in Kenya and Tanzania,
killing hundreds of people and injuring 4,000. The indictment also
charged both men with conspiring to kill Americans around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Like bin Laden, neither man is in U.S. custody, although Fawwaz
is being held by British authorities and is awaiting an extradition
hearing that could order him to New York for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Zawahiri is thought to be in Afghanistan along with bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's indictments raise the number of those charged in the
bombings to 15; five of the defendants are being held in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In a detailed indictment issued by the U.S. attorney for the
Southern District of New York, Mary Jo White, both men are
described as vital members of bin Laden's organization, Al Qaeda,
who were intimately involved in planning the Aug. 7 bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's indictment underscores our resolve to bring to the bar
of justice each and every person who participated in these heinous
crimes that resulted in the death of hundreds of innocent people,
both American and foreign nationals of all religions,'' said Ms.
White. ``The charges also show the reach of the worldwide terrorist
network threatening civilized society.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that Fawwaz has been running media operations
for Al Qaeda; his duties include publicizing statements made by bin
Laden, recruiting military trainees, transmitting confidential
messages to members and purchasing communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also believe that Fawwaz was instrumental in
disseminating bin Laden's fatwahs, or death sentences, including
those that ordered Muslims to kill Americans anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Officials charge that after the bombings, Fawwaz helped forward
messages to various media outlets claiming responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Zawahiri was a leader in al Jihad, a terrorist organization that
authorities believe was responsible for the assassination of
Egyptian President Anwar Sadat. In 1995, the organization's leader,
Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman, was convicted in a plot to bomb New York
City landmarks, including the World Trade Center. Three years
later, his group merged with bin Laden's Al Qaeda.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Katzman, a senior analyst for the Congressional Research
Service, described Zawahiri as a military expert and a top
lieutenant in Al Qaeda. ``Once he lost his patron, he came under
the wing of bin Laden, who has the organization and the money,''
Katzman said. He added that Zawahiri is wanted by Egypt for his
role in the assassination of Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   When the United States attacked bin Laden's headquarters in
response to the embassy bombings, Zawahiri called a Pakistani
newspaper and issued a threatening response. ``The war has just
started,'' he told a reporter. ``The Americans should wait for the
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Zawahiri could receive the death penalty,
according to the indictment. Fawwaz faces a maximum sentence of
life imprisonment without the possibility of parole, the indictment
says.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the government indicted Ali A. Mohamed, a former
U.S. Army sergeant, on charges of collaborating with bin Laden in a
conspiracy to kill Americans abroad, asserting for the first time
that Al Qaeda was behind the embassy attacks in Africa. U.S.
officials claim that Al Qaeda plotted against the United States for
arresting and prosecuting its members and those affiliated with its
terrorist groups, including Abdel-Rahman.
</P>
<P>
   There are $5 million rewards for the fugitives, including bin
Laden, who was recently placed on the FBI's 10 most wanted list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
