<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8440 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GRAVES-1STLD-W     06-16 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GRAVES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL AUTHORITIES COLLECT DATA ON KOSOVO ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs to fix spelling of dateline and references to it within
the story) (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT8, NYT12 _ have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) Locator map is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By IAN FISHER with DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KORENICA, Yugoslavia _ For the last four days, Tom Dedaj has
been going house to house in search of the unburied horrors of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   They are not hard to find here. A severed foot lies on the grass
of the cemetery. Three doors down from his house, the charred
bodies of five friends are strewn in a rubble-filled room. His own
aunt lies, a mass of lumps and ashes, in her front hallway.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he took a lawyer with Human Rights Watch on a tour
of what he had found, as Kosovo's tragedy entered its next phase:
documenting exactly what has happened since March, with an eye
toward punishing the guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of killings of civilians in Kosovo have so far been
secondhand _ or even more distant _ based on interviews in refugee
camps in Macedonia and Albania, with no way to confirm the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Now that NATO peacekeepers and other outsiders have entered the
province, they are collecting evidence in village after village in
an attempt to assemble a complete picture of the civilian toll of
the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on investigation is evident around the province as
NATO troops, who have been in Kosovo only since Saturday, have
moved to secure sites where mass killings are said to have been
carried out. In fact, Wednesday morning, Brigadier Gen. Fritz von
Korff, the commander of the German sector, which has several mass
grave cites, told reporters that NATO would start using the phrase
``crime scene'' instead of ``mass grave.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, there is no evidence of massacres of the astonishing
scale of the one in Srebrenica, the village in Bosnia where Serbian
forces killed as many as 7,000 people in 1995. But after only a few
days of open access to Kosovo, it is becoming clear there may be
hundreds and hundreds of smaller sites with numbers of victims
ranging from one or two to perhaps several hundred.
</P>
<P>
   And while most victims are buried under newly churned earth, it
is also clear, from a tour of this village and several others
within a few miles, that there is much evidence in plain view.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing several sites Wednesday, including Korenica and
Meja _ and finding more than a dozen unburied bodies _ the Human
Rights Watch lawyer, Joanne Mariner, said she could draw a few
preliminary conclusions about the deaths of civilians: ``We knew a
lot of people were killed but we're finding a lot more than we
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You add it up and it adds up to a lot of deaths,'' she said.
``It's systematic. There were a lot of people involved. It wasn't
some aberration that people were killed.''
</P>
<P>
   But proving exactly what happened _ and exactly who did what _
may be a difficult task. Ms. Mariner said that even after extensive
interviews with refugees, and the beginnings of interviews inside
Kosovo, she has heard relatively few names of people accused of the
killings. Some of the killers were masked, she said witnesses told
her; some were strangers. Often there were no witnesses at all.
</P>
<P>
   And finding witnesses who can agree on details of killings is
equally hard. There is no doubt that many people were killed here,
and in the neighboring village of Meja, just outside Djakovica. But
the accounts can be strikingly different.
</P>
<P>
   In Meja, the remains of six men, all in civilian clothes, still
lie scattered around a ditch. One man in a leather jacket had no
head. A pair of pants was filled by a single leg, with a black shoe
and blue sock still at the end of it. A stretch of ground near a
cemetery, apparently the killing ground, is littered with human
teeth, bits of skull and the pink plastic of shattered dentures.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, refugees and villagers say there appeared to be
two sets of killings on the same day: In Meja, Serbian forces and
paramilitaries, they say, separated the men from women and children
in a huge convoy of ethnic Albanians fleeing from Kosovo on April
27, killing between 100 and 300 of the men.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Korenica, villagers say that these same forces killed as
many as 100 more people, burning many of them in their own homes:
Dedaj, a 38-year-old farmer, recognized his aunt by the jewelry on
the floor and a necklace she had tucked away in her bra. He
recognized an 80-year-old man by a metal box he found next to the
body with the man's pocket watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a person who is mentally ill or sick can do this,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both mass killings appeared to be in retaliation for an attack
by the Kosovo Liberation Army in Meja in which five Serbian police
officers were killed.
</P>
<P>
   But Kurtshtest Morina, a 30-year-old sanitation worker, said
Wednesday that it was his job to drive people from where they were
killed to the cemetery in Korenica and he saw at most 40 bodies in
the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   He is a Gypsy and was not targeted by Serbian forces as the
ethnic Albanians were. He conceded that Serbian forces might have
buried more bodies on their own, but he had not heard of hundreds
of people being killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might have been more that I haven't seen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Morina said that the Serbian forces were meticulous about how
they buried the dead.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``They would take pictures of the bodies,'' he said. ``They
would write down the names of the dead. They would attach a number
to the corpse. And according to that number they would bury the
body.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the grave would have a number,'' he said. ``They were
very organized.''
</P>
<P>
   The same questions and contradictions are surfacing in other
areas of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Drenica, the heartland of the Kosovo Liberation Army, a day
after Serbian forces largely withdrew, signs of death were
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Makermal, near Drenica, Habib Gjinovci, a
farmer and KLA fighter, was trying to figure out whose blackened
skull was lying in the charred wreckage of his corn hutch. He said
the remains he found might be those of a teen-age boy Serbs
captured a month ago with roughly 20 others.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the size of the skull, it could be a woman or a child,''
he said. ``There were some kids who were 14 or 15 arrested that
day.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Serbs withdrew from the village on Monday, returning
Albanians found eight fresh graves in the cemetery. They dug up two
of them and found several sets of charred bones in each grave, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Rezalle, KLA, soldiers dug up what they
thought would be a mass grave only to find a dead cow.
</P>
<P>
   Two local Albanian rebels said the grave formerly held the
bodies of 50 to 80 Albanians killed by Serbian soldiers on April 5.
Observing from across the front line, the two soldiers, Aziz Aruqa
and Musa Derguti, said that they saw Serbs bury the bodies in the
mass grave. But two weeks ago the Serbs returned with heavy
equipment, removed the bodies and then shot cows and buried them in
the pit, the soldiers said.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees who fled Poklek, a KLA-controlled village at the
southern end of the Drenica region in May, carried with them the
tale of a mass killing of women and children there April 17.
</P>
<P>
   The home of Qamil Mucolli, the scene of the deaths, has become a
shrine to the 50 people killed that day. Mucolli, a 27-year-old KLA
fighter, said his wife, his two small daughters, his parents and
four sisters were among those killed when a Serbian soldier threw a
hand grenade into the crowded first-floor room. Mucolli, who was
fighting with the rebels at the time, said he understood that the
Serbian assailant then opened fire with his assault rifle, killing
all but four of the people inside. The Serbs burnt the bodies that
day in the room where they died, leaving it charred. Later the
rebels collected the bones for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in his basement, Mucolli pointed out how blood from the
first floor had trickled down through the ceiling and along the
basement walls to form dark red pools on the floor. Two months
after the attack, the pools of blood are black and untouched except
by the mold growing on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not cleaned it,'' he said, ``because we want everyone
to see the evidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
