<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 SPORTS COLUMN: THE `HOME' PROFESSIONAL'S LOVE OF PINEHURST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ If there's a ``home pro'' for the 99th U.S.
Open that begins Thursday at Pinehurst No. 2, it's Davis Love III.
As a youngster, he often accompanied his father, a storied teaching
pro, to Golf Digest schools here. As a three-time all-American at
the University of North Carolina, he played here in the prestigious
North and South Amateur, winning it in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot of little things that have been important to
my game,'' he said. ``This was my favorite place to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 35-year-old Davis Love III is among the favorites to win the
first Open here at the Pinehurst Resort and Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember spending a lot of time pounding balls here
with my Dad and Jack Lumpkin,'' he said, referring to another Golf
Digest pro. ``I remember Jack teaching me how to pitch in one of
the deep holes on the side of the 15th green, how to get the ball
up in the air. I remember winning the long-drive contest off the
14th tee here at No. 2.''
</P>
<P>
   How far had he hit it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said with a slow smile. ``Longer than
everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for John Daly, Tiger Woods and maybe David Duval, he
still does.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Open is special for me,'' Love said. ``I get to go to the
Pine Crest Inn and the Carolina Hotel and my friends are in town
and that's where the sentiment comes in. And we've never seen a
town and fans so excited. They are nuts about it and it's great to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pine Crest Inn, for $1 or more a shot, you can chip a
golf ball off a mat on the lobby floor at a hole in a target in
front of the fireplace. If you chip it through the hole, you
collect whatever money has accumulated from all those who have
missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to do that,'' Love said, ``but the line is too long
this week.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he played in the North and South Amateur in this
pine-shaded village with 38 golf courses, he must have collected a
Pine Crest pot or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I ever won that game,'' he said. ``I couldn't
chip in college.''
</P>
<P>
   He can chip now. On the PGA Tour he's won more than $11.4
million ($1.4 million this year) and 13 tournaments, including one
major, the 1997 Professional Golfers Association Championship at
Winged Foot. If he hadn't three-putted the final hole at the 1996
Open at Oakland Hills, he would have been in an 18-hole playoff
with Steve Jones.
</P>
<P>
   More than most of the Open golfers, Love understands the nuances
of Pinehurst No. 2's turtleback greens, softened by Wednesday
evening's rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it won't be a chipping contest,'' he said. ``I think Tiger
summed it up, saying you have to hit the ball in the fairway enough
times to get the ball on the green and have some chances for
birdies. You're not going to win unless you make some birdies.
Nobody is going to make 72 straight pars and win. It's going to be
who can be the most patient and put their misses in the right
spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss the second green too long every day and you can make
three pars and a bogey. Miss it short and right every day and you
make three bogeys and a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where you're going to have to be patient enough to say,
`Look, I can't shoot at any pins on the right front of that green,
I have to keep it over to the left.' And when you get to the fifth
green, you can't miss it short and left. Every miss has to be long.
And playing that kind of patience game is going to be hard. I think
that's where it's going to be won and lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the rough will be kept at 3 inches, instead of the
Open's usual 4 to 5 inches, Love expected more double bogeys than
usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``With normal U.S. Open rough, you hit it in there, hack it out,
hit it on the green and one putt or two putt,'' he said. ``But
here, a guy that hits it over the third green, he might be talking
to guys down on the fifth green, deciding who's away.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't smiling now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit a little flier over the 14th green, which I've done in the
North and South, and it's down on the 10th fairway,'' he said.
``You could see some big, big numbers because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Davis Love III dismisses the value of his personal sentiment
for Pinehurst.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start playing,'' he said, ``you better start hitting
the fairways and the greens, or sentiment is not going to help you
very much.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
