<SLUG> BC-BOEING-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRPLANE MAKERS KNOW HOW TO PLAY NUMBERS GAME ON JET ORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The aircraft order game was in full evidence Wednesday
at the halfway mark of the Paris Air Show.
</P>
<P>
   And like Alice in Wonderland, things keep getting curiouser and
curiouser.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus Industrie, whose just-launched A318 is in a dogfight with
Boeing's new 717 that has been making daily demonstration flights
for air show crowds, held a news conference with its top guy,
managing director Noel Forgeard, to announce that it had won 60
firm orders from International Lease Finance Corp., 30 of which
were for the A318.
</P>
<P>
   Only 24 hours earlier, Steven Udvar-Hazy, president and chief
executive officer of International Lease, had stood with Boeing
commercial boss Alan Mulally and announced an order for 50
next-generation 737s with options for 50 more _ a nearly $5 billion
deal that, with options, would be Boeing's largest ever for the
next-generation 737.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Udvar-Hazy and Forgeard were announcing an even
bigger firm order for the Airbus A320 family, which now includes
the A318.
</P>
<P>
   But wait a minute. Hadn't International Lease announced at the
Farnborough Air Show outside London last September that it would
order 30 of the A318s?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Udvar-Hazy acknowledged in response to questions, but at
the time International Lease was only making a commitment to buy
the Airbus plane. Since the A318 program had yet to be officially
launched, the orders had not been firm. Now they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first firm order for the A318,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release, Airbus said the same thing: ``The
announcement marks the first firm order for the A318.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait another minute.
</P>
<P>
   In April, when Airbus called a news conference to announce the
formal launch of the A318, Forgeard said the European airplane
maker had 109 firm orders, including the 30-plane International
Lease order as well as orders by Air France, TWA and AirEgypt.
</P>
<P>
   TWA had announced earlier in the year that it would buy 50
Boeing 717s and 50 Airbus A318s.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, newspaper and trade magazine stories that have been
written about the Boeing and Airbus 100-seat airplanes have
referred to the 109 firm orders for the A318 and the 115 firm
orders for Boeing's plane.
</P>
<P>
   It was only recently revealed in a published report by Flight
International that the April announcement by Forgeard was a bit
premature, and that the Airbus supervisory board had not yet given
its OK to launch the A318.
</P>
<P>
   The hangup was a dispute between the German Airbus partner
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace and Aerospatiale Matra, the French Airbus
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospatiale wanted the A318 to be assembled in Toulouse, where
it builds the A320 and the widebody Airbus planes. DaimlerChrysler
wanted to assemble the new plane in Hamburg. The A318 is a
shortened version of the A319, which is assembled in Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an agreement reached days before the Paris show
opened Saturday, Hamburg will get to assemble the A318, but some
A319 assembly work will be shifted to Toulouse. That settlement
cleared the way for the official launch of the A318.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard was asked Wednesday if the previously announced 109
firm orders for the A318 are actually firm or merely ``letters of
intent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are more than that,'' Forgeard said. They are a
memorandum of understanding. That's to say, firm commitments with
down payments. He said Airbus ``expects'' firm orders from ``most''
of the previously announced A318 customers.
</P>
<P>
   An Airbus executive said later the consortium was ``close'' to
signing firm deals with the previously announced A318 customers.
</P>
<P>
   But people familiar with the matter say Air France is not happy
with the choice of Pratt &AMP; Whitney as the A318 engine maker, and
TWA has so far balked at officially signing a firm deal.
</P>
<P>
   Udvar-Hazy said after the announcement that International Lease
has so far commitments for nine of the A318s from airlines, but he
would not identify them.
</P>
<P>
   One of those customers is thought to be Northwest. If that's so,
it would be a blow to Boeing's 717.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is pushing the 717 as a replacement for the aging fleet
of DC-9s, and Northwest has the largest DC-9 fleet still flying _
nearly 200 planes. Both Airbus and Boeing executives have been
heavily courting Northwest to buy their 100-seaters.
</P>
<P>
   The A318s will be delivered beginning in 2002, the earliest
Airbus will have them ready.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 30 A318s, Udvar-Hazy also announced that
International Lease has ordered a mix of 30 Airbus A320s, A319s and
A321. He described them as firm orders. At least three of the
orders have been previously announced by Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aircraft have been ordered,'' he said. ``As usual, because
of the volume there is flexibility of model type .... that's
important since many will not be delivered for three, four or five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Boeing nor Airbus ever disclose the value of the orders
they receive. Reporters come up with a value based on the list
price of the various planes, but the list price depends on the
configuration of the particular plane ordered. So at best it's an
educated guess.
</P>
<P>
   And even if that educated guess is close to the actual list
price, Airbus and Boeing customers get discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much of a discount International Leasing received for
the 60 Airbus planes, Udvar-Hazy said, ``we paid a reasonable
price.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Boeing knows how to play the numbers game, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Boeing executives were concerned in the last weeks
before the Paris Air Show that the company would be shut out of a
major order announcement, leaving the important world stage to
Airbus. So Boeing convinced International Lease to go ahead and
announce the 100-plane deal even though final details still had to
be worked out, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The first question Udvar-Hazy was asked after Tuesday's
100-plane announcement was whether International Lease and Boeing
had actually signed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   No, Udvar-Hazy said, the papers have not been signed. But they
will be, he said, probably next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
