<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8594 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIPELINE-SPI &LR;      06-16 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW IN REDMOND, WASH., GET STIRRED UP LIVING RIGHT NEXT TO
PIPELINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ The Hausermans were watching television in
their family room when the news about the Bellingham pipeline
explosion came on.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't get too excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vern,'' Nadenne asked, turning in her chair to face her
husband. ``Isn't that what we have outside the house?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, we have a natural gas pipeline out there,'' Vern said,
believing it. But the pipeline 28 steps from the front door of the
Hausermans' ranch-style house carries petroleum products _ just
like the one that ruptured and caught fire last week in Bellingham,
Wash., killing three people. In fact, it's the same pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline, owned by the Olympic Pipe Line Co., is just part
of the geography in the section of Redmond between Northeast 60th
and Northeast 80th streets, a fact of life. The way it is along
Hanna and Whatcom creeks in Bellingham, and throughout Western
Washington from Cherry Point near the Canadian border to the
Columbia River.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline started flowing in 1965 and predates nearly all of
the homes, the junior high school across the road, the once-swanky
apartment complex around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors either don't think about it or don't know it exists.
It's a lot like the family uncle who's gone to prison: No one
thinks about him until he calls collect to tell you he's been
released and needs a ride from the bus station.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pipeline back there,'' says Rich, a Microsoft
employee who lives on 135th Place Northeast, gesturing out his back
window. ``Power lines, yes. Pipeline, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim, a mother of two who lives on 137th Avenue Northeast, knows
about the pipeline but doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no concerns about it,'' she said. ``It's just there.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Olympic pipeline was permitted in 1962, Redmond's
population was 1,426, and much of eastern King County was
undeveloped farmland. So why not put a petroleum pipeline there, or
a natural gas pipeline such as the Williams pipeline, less than a
mile west?
</P>
<P>
   Eastside development was sparse. Who could have predicted then
that Redmond would have more than 40,000 people? Or who would have
foreseen the extent of the Eastside boom, when grazing land got
plowed under for subdivisions?
</P>
<P>
   ``The pipeline has been operating for 34 years,'' Olympic
spokesman Joann Hamick said. ``We didn't encroach upon them. We've
been encroached upon.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the pipeline became incorporated into the area's
geography, something to be considered by builders as they put up
ranch houses along streets that dipped and swayed like the country
lanes they were supposed to emulate.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulations mandate how deep the pipeline needs to be,
how far back structures are supposed to. But it's up to the local
governments to decide nearby land use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulation says that if the pipe is buried only 3 feet
deep, structures are not supposed to be any closer than 50 feet to
the pipe,'' Hamick said. ``That's not the easement. That's how
close they can be to the pipe. If the pipe is buried 4 feet or
more, then there is no setback.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond has no rules about building right up to the easement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't regulate private companies in that regard,'' said
Scott Thomasson, the city's utility engineering manager. The city
follows the same policy with public-utility easements, believing
that the right of way provides a sufficient buffer.
</P>
<P>
   So people do build up to the easement, and residents rarely
think about the pipeline, though it runs under the track of Rose
Hill Junior High School, not more than 200 feet away from the
girls' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Principal Steve Mezzich has been at Rose Hill for a year, and
didn't know of the pipeline's existence until Wednesday, though the
school's track team does endurance training by running up and down
the hill between pipeline markers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me, really,'' Mezzich said. ``We have the
power lines, and apparently a pipeline, too. I guess I'll just have
to think that the tragic accident in Bellingham was the exception
and not the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easier to focus on the power lines, and so the pipeline
becomes something secondary, in the back yard, or over the fence or
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   At Sixty-01 Village, an apartment and condominium complex along
the right-of-way, the pipeline has a putting green built over it,
and P-patches _ now fragrant with late spring blooms _ planted
around it. There's a tennis court there, too, and a volleyball
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I've got more concern with the high-power lines
overhead than I do with the gas lines,'' said Randy Kundert, who
directs maintenance at Sixty-01.
</P>
<P>
   Across Old Redmond Road, at her home on Northeast 137th Street,
Gloria Hull reads voraciously, watches the Seattle Mariners every
night and looks out her back window at the birds and squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   For 31 years, when she lived two and a half miles down Northeast
137th, she had a pipeline and power lines running through her
property.
</P>
<P>
   When they put the pipeline in there, she said, she moved her
horses out of the barn _ just in case. But that was the extent of
her worries.
</P>
<P>
   For the past six years she's lived with the pipeline just beyond
her brown wood fence, and when the trees get full, she can barely
see the triple-phase power lines that mark the pipeline's path
through east King County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those type people who won't worry about something
they have no control over. And I don't have any control over
that,'' she says nodding toward the pipeline's vicinity. ``So why
worry about it?''
</P>
<P>
   There is some concern, of course. Lou Kelly, a maintenance
worker at Sixty-01, has been regarding the grounds differently
since the Bellingham blast. Especially since his job takes him into
the soil near the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the pipe (in Bellingham) was buried 15 feet deep, and
last week we were out at the gate digging around 20 feet to fix the
fence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another resident of the complex, Carol, is aware of the pipeline
and doesn't like it much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think about it,'' she said. ``I know it's
there, and I think about it when my daughter and I take walks and
cross over it. My hope is that if something goes wrong, the
fireball isn't too big.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Tom Paulson contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
