<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BIG-BUDGETED CAMPAIGNS FOR AUTO RACING AND GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As summer approaches, two sports organizations are running
multimillion-dollar advertising campaigns to woo spectators,
participants and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The Indy Racing League, an 11-race, open-wheel series owned by
Indianapolis Motor Speedway Corp., whose prime event is the
Indianapolis 500, has hired Wieden &AMP; Kennedy to create its first
national ad campaign ever. In addition, the U.S. Golf Association,
the 104-year-old golf governing body, is running two new TV ads by
BBDO New York, a unit of the Omnicom Group, during the U.S. Open,
which starts Thursday in Pinehurst, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jeff Chapman, director of marketing and branding
for the racing league, public awareness of the league, which
started in 1996, has been very low. ``The equipment, cars and teams
do great,'' he said, ``but we knew we needed to formally launch the
product from a marketing standpoint.'' Increasing attendance and TV
viewership ``could lead to increased sponsorships,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, attendance at Indy Racing events has grown 13
percent. It has 10 major sponsors, led by The Pep Boys _ Manny, Moe
and Jack, the Philadelphia-based automotive parts and services
company. According to IEG Sponsorship Report, a newsletter that
follows sports marketing, the league's sponsorships, including
sponsors for teams and tracks, totaled an estimated $101 million in
1998, and are expected to reach $105 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wieden &AMP; Kennedy is the Portland, Ore., agency whose work for
Nike and ESPN has won many plaudits.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has created a $10 million campaign that will run
through October; almost 70 percent of the budget is devoted to
national television and print media, while the remainder is
allocated to local print and TV.
</P>
<P>
   There are a dozen 30- and 60-second national TV spots, five of
which appeared last month before the Indianapolis 500. Four will
break next week. These commercials, with the tag line ``You had to
be there,'' are running on cable channels like Fox Sports and on
cable programs like ESPN Sportscenter and Inside NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second commercials are irreverent and entertaining, a
tone that is typical of Wieden &AMP; Kennedy. In one, Davey Hamilton, a
driver, brags about his new helmet to another driver, Sam Schmidt,
only to discover, to his chagrin, that its design is identical to
that of Schmidt's helmet; rather like two women arriving at a
dinner party in the same dress. Another spot, accompanied by Tommy
Roe's 1969 song ``Dizzy,'' shows spectators spinning their heads
around to watch an Indy race on an oval track.
</P>
<P>
   A 60-second commercial, whose tone is entirely different from
the others, is a tribute to Jerry Unser, one of the three legendary
Unser brothers, who was killed in 1959 at the age of 26 at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway. The ad shows his son Johnny, now 40
and a driver in the league, at the speedway, as well as footage
from family movies and photographs of Jerry Unser competing.
</P>
<P>
   Print advertising for the league, which is running in magazines
like Car &AMP; Driver and Motor Trend, in USA Today and local
newspapers, contains striking photographs shot by Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy's creative team at two Indy Racing events earlier this
year; one ad, for example, shows Scott Goodyear, a driver,
autographing a model car in the pit. This advertising has the same
tag line as the TV spots.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Chipps, an editor of IEG Sponsorship Report, said he
thought the league had opted to run a big-budget campaign because
``attendance has been struggling,'' and NASCAR doesn't ``have to
spend that kind of money to draw people to their events.'' CART is
the Championship Auto Racing Team and NASCAR is the National
Association for Stock-Car Auto Racing.
</P>
<P>
   He also questioned whether the advertising could lift attendance
for Indy Racing, saying, For ``true-blue motor sports fans, their
allegiances are already set.''
</P>
<P>
   The golf association is running two new spots by BBDO, seeking
to promote the association's services and increase membership,
during ESPN and NBC broadcasts of the United States Open and five
other championships through October. Air time is worth an estimated
$8 million.
</P>
<P>
   A 60-second, sentimental spot, partly shot in soft focus,
suggests the association ``handles'' golf ``with care'' and
includes an ``800'' number golfers can call for membership
information. The second, a 30-second spot that shows dawn breaking
over a course as a group of male golfers arrives to play, is
amusing: It says studies have shown man can survive for four weeks
without food, for three days without water, but for only one day
without golf. At the end, one of the golfers _ who is apparently
still half-asleep _ is told to leave because he is wearing pajamas,
an outfit the course has forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we're accused of being humorless,'' said Marty
Parkes, senior director of communications for the golf association.
``But a lot of the reason people play golf is fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the ``for the good of the game'' theme created for
the golf association by BBDO when it won the association's business
two years ago, Parkes added, ``Part of the good of the game is to
make sure people continue to have fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
