<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL AUCTIONS OIL LICENSES, ENDING SOME STATE CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SIMON ROMERO    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ The government ended Brazil's oil monopoly
in a two-day auction that concluded Wednesday, overcoming
nationalist resistance and recently weak petroleum prices to
auction the first exploration licenses to big foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
   The AGIP unit of ENI of Italy, BP Amoco PLC, Exxon, Texaco and
Unocal were among the victors in the auction for 12 of 27 fields,
which took place in Rio de Janeiro. Companies agreed to pay $181
million to Brazil for licenses to explore for oil mainly off the
Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the Italians, the Spanish, the Argentines, the
Americans and others that won fields,'' said Jean-Paul Prates, the
president of Expetro, a Rio de Janeiro-based consulting firm
specializing in oil and gas. ``It is a new competitive era.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction of the licenses is part of a wider easing of the
government's grip on energy. Over the last several years, foreign
companies have purchased such state assets as electric utilities
and gas companies as well as licenses to expand Brazil's natural
gas grid.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it has been in the oil industry, a redoubt of nationalists
and labor interests, where the government has found the strongest
opposition to its privatization program. To proceed with this
week's auction, officials had to overcome last-minute legal
challenges from left-wing opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone on its home turf, Petroleo Brasileiro SA, or
 &UR; Petrobras &LR; , the state-controlled company created in the 1950s amid
cries of ``the oil is ours,'' bid aggressively and won some of the
choicest licenses. It thus put on a show of the government's
continued strength in a new competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The valuation of the Brazilian oil business has risen to a new
level, and we're well positioned to compete,'' Petrobras president
Henri Philippe Reichstul told reporters in Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso has
discarded the idea of ceding state control of Petrobras in the
foreseeable future, the results of the auction are expected to bode
well for the next big development in Brazil's oil industry, the
sale of a large minority stake in the company. The transaction has
been delayed since turbulence hit Brazilian financial markets late
in 1998 and early this year.
</P>
<P>
   While Petrobras and other companies, most notably AGIP,
submitted pricey bids for some areas, other oilfields were ignored,
suggesting Brazil's the perceived low potential as a producer
compared with Latin American countries like Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil has about 9 billion barrels of proven reserves, compared
with roughly 64 billion barrels in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Petrobras has made strides to lessen Brazil's
dependence on foreign oil through the development of advanced
offshore drilling methods. Brazil produces about 1.2 million
barrels of oil a day, equivalent to two-thirds of its daily
domestic consumption. In the next three years, domestic production
is seen growing to 1.5 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   Production from the fields auctioned this week should start
within six or seven years. The government is hoping for investments
of $15 billion and the creation of up to 300,000 jobs, according to
David Zylbersztajn, the head of Brazil's energy regulatory agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the breakup of the monopoly accomplished, we can move
forward,'' Zylbersztajn said.
</P>
<P>
   Before investments proceed much further, however, tax and
regulatory details must be worked out, oil industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is still seen as messy for many oil companies,'' said
Declan Ryan, head of Latin American energy research at Wood
Mackenzie Consultants in Edinburgh, Scotland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
