<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR DE FRANCE ORGANIZERS PULL WHEELS OUT FROM UNDER DRUG
OFFENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Responding to the drug scandals that have tarnished
bicycle racing for nearly a year, the organizers of the Tour de
France announced Wednesday that they had banned four French riders,
an entire Dutch team and the director and doctor of a Spanish team.
</P>
<P>
   The action was unprecedented in the recent history of the Tour,
which began in 1903 and runs for three weeks in July. The race was
crippled last year, and almost ended prematurely, when riders
reacted to police drug raids by staging two strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the right, indeed the duty, to protect the race,''
said the race director Jean-Marie Leblanc as he formally announced
the names of the 20 teams of nine riders each that were invited to
the race _ and those who were banned. None of those barred has been
found guilty or confessed to any crime, but Leblanc dismissed a
question about the legality of the action. ``Organizers can invite
whom they please.''
</P>
<P>
   The major name on the banned list was Richard Virenque, a French
idol who has finished as high as second in the Tour and four times
has been its mountain-climbing champion. Virenque, 29, was the
leader of the Festina team that was expelled from the race last
July 18 after team officials admitted that the riders had
participated in systematic doping.
</P>
<P>
   Virenque has denied knowingly using any of the illegal
performance-enhancing drugs that six of his teammates have admitted
they took. He is under formal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Festina affair has become doping affairs _ in the
plural,'' Leblanc said, citing ``the major shock waves and traumas
of doping'' that continue to echo in the sport. On June 5, Marco
Pantani, the Italian winner of the last Tour, was forbidden to ride
the final two stages of the Tour of Italy, which he was leading,
after he failed a blood test.
</P>
<P>
   Leblanc said Wednesday that Virenque's ``presence would be
incompatible with the image of the Tour, and the one we want to
preserve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Virenque epitomizes, in his name, in his image, the
doping phenomenon,'' Leblanc said, ``whether or not he is
responsible for the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tour organizers also barred Laurent Roux of the Casino team and
Philippe Gaumont of Cofidis, both under suspension from their teams
in drug cases. Also, they announced, Pascal Herve, a Festina rider
who was not on the initial team list of Tour riders, would not be
welcome. Herve, like Virenque, has never admitted using drugs.
</P>
<P>
   All other riders on those teams are acceptable, organizers said.
They skirted a decision on Pantani, noting that he has said he does
not want to ride in the Tour because the course displeases him. His
Mercatone Uno team was invited, and Leblanc said, ``If Pantani
changes his mind, we will have to review the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Leblanc said that the Festina team was invited. None of the six
riders who admitted to doping and served suspensions before joining
new teams was banned.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the ban on Virenque, Polti announced last month
that it would fight legally and possibly withdraw its team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot say yes to a team and no to one of its riders,''
the team sponsor, Franco Polti, said. ``Excluding Richard Virenque
does not solve the problem of doping.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish team ONCE may also withdraw because its director,
Manolo Saiz, and its doctor, Nicolas Terrados, were banned.
Terrados is under investigation in a Tour drug case, and Saiz was
critical of the race's organizers when he pulled his team out last
year to protest continuing police investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The TVM team from the Netherlands was banned, Leblanc said,
because of what he called improper behavior last summer. Under
investigation in another drug case in France, TVM riders were
questioned by the police after a stage and then kept late at a
hospital to give urine, blood and hair samples for drug inspection.
The team's doctor and director were also arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their attitude was an insult,'' Leblanc said, citing the ``V''
for victory sign the riders made as the race crossed the border
from France into Switzerland and the team's withdrawal once on
Swiss soil.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude Killy, president of company that owns the Tour de
France, opened Wednesday's news conference by saying that there was
no question the Tour would be held this year. He pointed out that
only World Wars I and II had stopped the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why penalize millions of spectators and 160 million TV viewers
around the world and, indeed, the Tour itself?'' he said. ``The
Tour de France is part of ourselves, part of our identity.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
