<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8608 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USOPEN-HNS &LR;      06-16 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PINEHURST, N.C. _ Jack Nicklaus always used to enjoy coming to the
U.S. Open, not so much for the golf as much as for the whining.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I used to love listening to them gripe,'' Nicklaus said of the
players who routinely bashed the Open courses. ``Somebody would
say, `The rough is too high.' You could check him off. `The greens
are too fast.' Check him off. `The course is too long.' Check him
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could just check guys off as they complain because they
complained themselves right out of the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   This year at Pinehurst No. 2, there's not much checking off
being done.
</P>
<P>
   The 99th U.S. Open, which starts this morning, is going to be
the first one in a long time in which the course equalizes the
field rather than separating it into haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got that many fellows who are happy with the golf
course, there must be something wrong,'' Nicklaus said.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong is that this truly should be a wide Open.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is complaining about conditions or the setup of
Pinehurst's fabled Donald Ross layout. The rough isn't as long as
it was last year at The Olympic Club. The greens have been softened
by on-and-off showers during the past few days, and even the nasty
greens shaped like upside-down saucers that feed shots into closely
mowed collection areas aren't drawing any rants.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody, it seems, feels like there are parts of Pinehurst
that fit their game well. And that makes the list of contenders
long.
</P>
<P>
   However, even if there are 50 or more players who genuinely have
a shot at winning this week, they first will have to beat two
people _ Tiger Woods and David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you beat Tiger, you're going to have a good chance
to win,'' said Colin Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie meant that Woods may not be accepting the trophy
Sunday afternoon, but there's a good chance he's going to be in the
hunt to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Even Duval believes it's going to be a lot more than a
one-on-one Open. If this ends up as the coming-out party of a
Duval-Woods rivalry, it will be surprising to one of the
participants in that anticipated duel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the way the setup is will bring a lot more people into
the mix,'' Duval said. ``When you play a typical Open, you know the
fairway is going to be narrow and the rough is going to be high.
But here, you have options of advancing the ball from the rough.
And that brings more people into play. I think it's a lot more
wide-open.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one thing about the Open: This is my seventh or eighth
Open, and I've yet to play in one that hitting it in the fairway
and knocking it on the green doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   And Duval expects to have a good chance of doing just that this
week despite some leftover blisters on his right thumb and index
finger where he received burns last week when picking up an
overheated teapot.
</P>
<P>
   Duval said he has overcome that and a midseason lull that he
said hit him after the Masters and caused him to play poorly at the
Shell Houston Open and miss the cut the following week in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a lot of hard work in on and off the golf course getting
ready for the run from The Players Championship to Augusta,'' Duval
said. ``As a result, I just wasn't as ready to play as I would like
to be when I got to Houston. Maybe it's just that I was more
drained from those three weeks than I had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I chose not to play for a while, to try to get back and get
ready. And yes, I'm very eager to play now.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval still owns the No. 1 world ranking over Woods, but just
barely. And a Woods win this week would send him back into the top
spot he surrendered to Duval in March.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of the teapot injury wasn't lost on Duval. ``I've gone
snowboarding a lot,'' he said, ``and people think that I'm crazy to
do that. But then I almost take myself out trying to fix a cup of
coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Woods, he is the pre-tournament favorite by virtue of
having won the last two times he has played, once in Europe and two
weeks ago at the Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   And Woods should benefit from the fact that the rough is two
inches shorter than it was last year at The Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this course a lot,'' Woods said. ``The course is
playing a little more friendly than I thought it would. I think the
USGA recognized the fact that they made a mistake last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``From tee to green, this is a very simple course. It's around
the green where it gets very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But even around the green this week, players can make shots.
They may be difficult shots. But they can be made, unlike some of
the thatch-roof lies that confronted them last year when Lee
Janzen's winning score was even-par.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot more players could win this golf tournament than we've
seen in past U.S. Opens,'' said Greg Norman. ``I think that's a
credit to the USGA for setting up the course the way they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that players should get comfortable with the surroundings
this week. Even if the rain keeps the track soft all week and
scores dip, the USGA has no intentions of letting the Open become a
shootout every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf-course architecture lends itself to this setup,
whereas others do not,'' said Trey Holland, chairman of the USGA's
Championship Committee. ``We'll find ourselves going back to
(other) styles when we go to golf courses that lend themselves to
that style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus will continue to be trying to put the supreme test,
if you will, for the United States Open championship, and that
objective will not change.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's very safe to say that the rough here is a little bit
more along the lines of what the players are used to. We feel the
rough is much more fair and it's going to allow players to do
things with the golf ball that they haven't been able to do at
prior U.S. Opens.''
</P>
<P>
   As Davis Love III said: ``When you have a great golf course that
can't be set up with deep rough around the greens, you know you're
going to get a fair test of golf. This is a special Open and a
special place.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the week, the scores might suggest that this
week did not give, as the USGA likes to say, the supreme test of
golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in, I feel the players are going to score fairly high
or fairly low,'' Nicklaus said. ``I don't think it will be in the
middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the Open record will be broken or you'll have a
hard time breaking par, depending on the conditions. If the rain
continues and the greens are soft and these guys can throw the ball
at the pin, then they are long enough and strong enough to (shoot
low).
</P>
<P>
   ``If the golf course stayed fairly dry, and we have any wind at
all, I think they'll have an awfully hard time staying around
par.''
</P>
<P>
   But the tournament will start with the soft conditions, meaning
this will begin as the warm-and-fuzzy U.S. Open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
