<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SESSION ENDS, LITTLE TO SHOW, AND STILL NO STATE BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Legislature's 1999 session reached its
scheduled end Wednesday with all the usual frenzy but none of the
results, as lawmakers failed to make deals on most unresolved
issues, and girded for a showdown over whether the state would keep
paying hospital bills after Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican senators and Senate aides said that on
Thursday, Republican Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, will, for the
first time, allow his chamber to vote on a bill making it illegal
for protesters to block access to an abortion clinic. The bill,
which is almost assured of passage, would not go as far as the one
passed by the Democrat-controlled Assembly, and it would include
tougher criminal penalties for stalkers, which some Democrats
dislike. But aides to Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said it would
be seriously considered.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the proposal stalls in the Senate, it represents an
important turn by Bruno, who has refused to permit a clinic access
bill to reach the Senate floor. ``I do sense a change in climate,''
said Sen. Roy Goodman, R-Manhattan, who favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The state has no budget, 2{ months into the fiscal year, and its
hospital financing system expires later this year, so everyone
knows the Legislature will return to Albany several more times this
year. On Wednesday, the leaders of the Senate and Assembly said
they would be in session again Thursday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the scene in the Capitol reflected end-of-session
tradition, as lawmakers tried to make a flurry of deals and to rid
themselves of their ordinary business, while lobbyists and interest
groups crowded Capitol hallways, trying to buttonhole legislators
and raise their voices above the din. Orthodox Jews pressed for a
law requiring health insurance plans to cover infertility
treatment, as environmentalists tried to block a bill permitting
cellular phone towers with no environmental review.
</P>
<P>
   But at day's end, the Legislature had little more to show for
its efforts than a handful of routine bills passed by both houses,
and controversial ones that passed in one house but were dead on
arrival in the other.
</P>
<P>
   In another end-of-session tradition, top lawmakers made a raft
of new proposals. Pataki called for campaign finance reform and a
renewal of the state's Superfund program for toxic waste cleanup,
while Silver proposed a $294 million effort to build or buy housing
for 3,500 mentally ill people.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time, legislators' paychecks are being
withheld as long as the budget is late, and the day brought them
unwelcome news. In May, in a suit filed by 14 Democratic
legislators, a Brooklyn judge struck down the law, but Gov. George
Pataki and Attorney General Eliot Spitzer appealed to the Court of
Appeals, New York's highest court. Wednesday, the court turned down
the plaintiffs' request that they be paid pending the outcome of
the appeal and set oral arguments for Aug. 24, meaning that it
probably would not rule until October.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, held another in a series of budget talks
Wednesday with Silver, but they said they were no closer to an
accord. ``At this point, I think we're still in the exploratory
stages of setting up parameters for going to conference
committees,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this year, lawmakers face a significant
deadline in the budget battle. Cuts to Medicaid that were made in
1995 and 1996 are set to expire June 30, and if they do, state and
local governments will find themselves paying more to hospitals and
nursing homes, at a rate of almost $1 billion a year. The governor
is determined to continue the cuts, but the Democrats want to
restore some of them.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have kept the government running through a series of
emergency spending bills, and Thursday, Pataki will send another
one or two such bills to the Legislature, to cover operations
through July 11. That means that for the first time, the governor
will be trying to extend 1995 and 1996 cuts past their expiration
date, which he says is essential. Silver has said that he will not
allow that, but he refused to comment on the subject Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the governor said it is still unclear whether he will
send one emergency bill for the entire state government, or two,
one for Medicaid and one for everything else. If he sends a single
bill, brinkmanship over the cuts would threaten to shut down state
government Monday.
</P>
<P>
   And if, as most officials here believe, he sends two bills, the
stalemate would threaten to cut off all state Medicaid payments to
hospitals, nursing homes and home health care providers Monday.
Some of those hospitals say that without Medicaid reimbursement,
they would be unable to meet their bills within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters, the state is required to send the Federal
government, by June 30, its plan for Medicaid spending for the next
year. State and federal officials say they do not know what will
happen if the state simply ignores the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   June 30 represents still more deadlines, including expiration of
the law controlling rents for thousands of people who live in
converted lofts, mostly in Manhattan, one of the issues still in
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few deals of note to be struck in the closing frenzy
would give parole officers the presumption that any heart disease
they suffer is job-related, allowing them to retire early with
greatly enhanced pensions. The Assembly was expected to pass it
Thursday, but it was not clear whether Pataki would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Such laws are controversial, because the workers involved are
not required to show any connection between their ailments and
their jobs, and because they increase government costs.
</P>
<P>
   Similar laws have been enacted for New York City police and
firefighters and city and state correction officers.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, Silver and Bruno are close to an agreement on a law
making it easier to compel mentally ill people to undergo
treatment, and in some instances to commit them against their will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
