<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS TO PONDER ON VACATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know about your workplace, but at mine the
most-often-uttered sentence of the month has been, ``I need a
vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the time of year when long lunch hours or early Friday
escapes aren't big enough battery rechargers to count. It's time
for longer getaways from the grind. It's also time to ponder:
</P>
<P>
   Can a nation awash in annual productivity gains continue to
expect improvement from workers who have comparatively little
vacation reward and relaxation time?
</P>
<P>
   Or does America derive its productivity strength precisely from
the fact that U.S. workers don't get as much vacation time as
workers in other developed nations?
</P>
<P>
   Among world commerce leaders, the United States stands markedly
apart in that it has no statutory vacation requirements. Without a
government mandate, most American workers work longer than their
global counterparts to earn their paid vacation time, according to
a survey by Hewitt Associates.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest differences is that most U.S. employers base
vacation time on job tenure. A typical American worker needs to
work five years in the same place before getting three paid weeks
off _ a vacation duration that is the norm for European workers
after only one year of service.
</P>
<P>
   (A separate survey by Management Recruiters International found
that 82 percent of 5,000 managers surveyed said they took work
along on their vacations, so ``vacation time'' may be a misnomer
anyway. But that's another topic.)
</P>
<P>
   The Hewitt survey looked at vacation policies around the world
and found that the Danish government mandated 33 vacation days a
year, making it the world leader in required paid time off. (But
Denmark's standard workweek is six days, not five, so its vacation
mandate isn't all that huge in terms of hours worked.)
</P>
<P>
   Government-mandated vacation among America's international
business competitors ranges from Mexico's six days to Denmark's 33
days (for workers with one year of service), according to the
Hewitt survey.
</P>
<P>
   Other nations with six-day workweeks include Austria, with 30
mandated vacation days, and France and Norway, with 25 required
days. Sweden has a five-day workweek, but also decrees 25 days.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium, Finland, Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands, Spain and
Switzerland order between 20 and 24 vacation days for their
five-day workweeks. Australia requires 20. Fifteen days are
mandated in New Zealand and the United Kingdom, but the U.K.
requirement rises to 20 in November.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and Canada provide 10 vacation days after one year on the
job, which coincides with typical U.S. business practices. Hewitt's
survey found that 81 percent of U.S. employers provided two weeks
of vacation after one year of service.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that 80 percent of U.S. employers offered
three weeks of paid time off after five years of service and that
87 percent allowed four weeks off after 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   But remember the big difference from world competitors: U.S.
vacation time usually is earned based on tenure beyond one year. So
when someone says, ``Enjoy your time off; you've earned it,'' you
really have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
