<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, June 17. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) _ He's a small slender man with a long
narrow face, a long thin nose and a bald spot on the back of his
head that'll get bigger and bigger as he ages. But for now he looks
young and, when wearing his large oval spectacles, innocent. If you
saw him outside the courtroom, Scott Falater would remind you of
Don Knotts, not a guy who stabbed his wife 44 times and dumping her
body. Then claimed he was sleepwalking. By E.J. MONTINI Story will
move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories.
</P>
<P>
   OKCORRAL (Phoenix) _ To begin with, ``OK Corral'' has a nice,
snappy, Western sound, perfect for the site of a shoot-'em-up. If
the event had taken place at, say, Fred's Corral or the OK
Bathhouse, the Old West's most famous gunfight might not have
become so famous. And thanks to the fuzziness of contemporary
accounts _ plus all the subsequent yarn spinning and moviemaking
and book writing _ the history of that bloody day is still not
particularly certain and the story is all the more enduring. By
CLAY THOMPSON. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   QUAYLE (Concord, N.H.) _ GOP presidential hopeful Dan Quayle
ripped what he views as the ``mushy'' message of GOP front-runner
George W. Bush Wednesday, saying that it could lead, at best, to a
hollow victory for Republicans. An intense Quayle compared the
Texas governor's unwillingness to take a stand on many issues to
President Bill Clinton's ``triangulation'' strategy designed to
seek the middle ground between the extreme factions of his party.
It was developed by Clinton's former advisor, Dick Morris, who was
fired for dallying with a prostitute. ``Republicans don't win
elections trying to be like Bill Clinton and being Dick Morris
Republicans,'' Quayle said in an interview. ``If you are going to
run an ambiguous, mushy, equivocating, triangulation, Dick Morris
type of campaign, what good is it to be elected? You're not really
going to change the country. And I want to change the country.'' By
KRIS MAYES and CHARLES KELLY. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SLEEPWALK (Phoenix) _ Scott Falater, taking the stand in his
defense Wednesday, testified amid tears that he did not
deliberately stab his wife 44 times and that she was the love of
his life. ``Some people talk about their spouse as their right
arm,'' said the man who claims he was sleepwalking when he stabbed
his wife 44 times. ``She was like both my arms, and my legs, half
my head and all of my heart. By JERRY KAMMER. Story will movein the
``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
