</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE WAR RAGES IN HOUSE AS PRESIDENT SCRAMBLES FOR VOTES ON GUN
CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS to UPDATE with House passing minimum prison sentences
for juvenile crime, trims and clarifies throughout.) 
 (With CONGRESS-GUNS-SCENE) 
(rm) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bitterly divided House plunged Wednesday into the
nation's culture wars, passionately debating long into the night
whether school prayer, a clampdown on violence in entertainment,
stiff prison sentences or gun control was the answer to the spate
of school shootings that have left teen-agers dead.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was the beginning of a two- to three-day free-for-all
as the House considered 44 amendments on cultural issues and crime
and 11 gun-control proposals. The House approved tough mandatory
minimum sentences to combat juvenile crime. But in a blow to social
conservatives, the House on Wednesday night voted 282-146 to reject
a measure sponsored by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill, that would have made
it a crime to expose children to movies, books or video games
containing explicit sex or violence.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans _ including three members of Judiciary
Committee, which Hyde chairs _ strode to the Democratic side of the
chamber to agree with Democrats that Hyde's legislation was an
unconstituional abridgement of the First Amendment right of free
speech. Ninety-two Republicans joined 189 Democrats and one
independent to defeat the measure, while 127 Republicans and 19
Democrats voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   But if they suffered a loss, the conservatives had their day on
the stage as the House Republican leaders made sure the cultural
debate came ahead of the gun control debate preferred by Democrats.
The scheduling gave Republican after Republican a prime-time
platform for arguing that it was not guns, but a depraved culture
and a glorification of violence that had led to the nation's school
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House minority whip, delivered
several thundering jeremiads on the House floor, brushing aside the
gun debate to blame American culture as the source of youth
violence. He pointedly read aloud a letter, sent to a local Texas
newspaper, that condemned everything from birth control to day care
to the absence of prayer in school.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating the words of the letter-writer, DeLay bitingly asked
why school shootings happened and suggested that everything from
daycare to television to birth control was to blame. ``It couldn't
have been,'' he said, reading from the letter, ``because our
children, who historically have been seen as a blessing from God,
are now being viewed as either a mistake created when
contraceptions fails or inconveniences that parents try to raise in
their spare time.''
</P>
<P>
   As the debate raged on the House floor, a fierce struggle for
votes was waged behind the scenes over gun control.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, flying to Geneva in advance of a meeting in
Germany with leaders of industrialized nations, telephoned two
wavering Democrats _ Nick Lampson of Texas and Bob Etheridge of
North Carolina _ to urge them to support a measure sponsored by
Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., that would regulate sales at gun
shows nearly as stringently as the Senate voted to do last month.
The Senate narrowly approved a measure that broadly defined gun
shows and gave vendors up to three business days to conduct
mandatory background checks on buyers. Mrs. McCarthy's amendment
had identical provisions but eliminates some of the paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   The president also sent a letter to moderate Republicans who had
voted for background checks for handguns six years ago, imploring
them to put ``the interests of the American people over the clout
of the gun lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the issue, a dozen National Rifle
Association lobbyists worked Capitol Hill. And DeLay similarly
sought to rally some of the most conservative members of his party
around a weaker gun show measure that has been proposed by a
Democrat, Rep. John Dingell of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay told them that if they tried to vote against all gun
control, they might inadvertently help the Democrats. ``You hate to
vote for any gun control if you're a defender of the Second
Amendment,'' he said. ``At the same time, what do you do to stop
the gun control people?''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the emotions of the day, Mrs. McCarthy choked back
tears at one news conference where she and another lawmaker were
displaying weapons that could be purchased at gun shows. She said
one of them reminded her of the gun that had killed her husband on
the Long Island railroad shooting of 1993. ``This is personal to
me,'' she had said earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House minority leader, told reporters
Wednesday night that he expected to lose about 45 Democrats when
the McCarthy measure comes to the floor. He said that would mean
gun control advocates would need to pick up 51 Republican votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a chance to do that,'' he said. But he
complained that moderate Republicans did not seem to be lobbying
their colleagues aggressively. In a backhanded compliment to the
National Rifle Association and DeLay, Gephardt said, ``We're up
against the best lobby in town and we're up against Tom DeLay's
whip organization.'' His comments minimized the role of Dingell, a
fellow Democrat fighting at DeLay's side.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J., who is co-sponsoring Mrs. McCarthy's
measure, said she could not say how many Republicans would vote
with her. ``I have not been going around counting noses,'' she
said. In another effort to draw Republicans, Democrats recruited
Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., to join them in sponsoring one
comprehensive gun control measure.
</P>
<P>
   Wavering Republicans were under all kinds of pressure. Michael
Long, the chairman of the New York State Conservative Party, sent a
letter to New York Republicans calling Dingell's amendment
essential. That posed a political bind for Rep. Rick Lazio who may
challenge Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for the Republican Senate
nomination next year.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has not returned calls from reporters in recent days and
an aide said she did not know how he would vote on gun measures.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert has cast the gun control vote as a matter
of conscience. But Delay, his third in command, has been working to
pass the Dingell measure. DeLay said today he is not cajoling
Republicans to vote Dingell's way but only telling them that he
planned to vote with Dingell in order to keep gun control advocates
from prevailing.
</P>
<P>
   He delivered that message to some 24 to 30 of the most
conservative members of the House over Chinese food in his office
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell's gun show amendment is the least stringent version that
will come before the House. Republicans fear it could yet be
defeated if more than a dozen conservatives decide that they cannot
abide any kind of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, DeLay, the hard-driving majority whip, was
everywhere. He made a star turn at a rally, for ``God not guns,''
on the Capitol grounds with black and Hispanic ministers from New
York, whose followers waved their Bibles in the air to punctuate
the speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``What message is sent when it is illegal to pray in schools?''
the Texan asked. ``This rejection of God must change.'' He said
that in the battle against a decadent culture ``we all need to
understand that you cannot stand up for America _ you need to kneel
down for America and stand up for God.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite the day's heated arguments over amendments, the basic
bill the House was debating is a bipartisan juvenile crime
initiative that allocates $1.5 billion in block grants to state and
local governments for aggressive prosecution, punishment and
prevention of juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the measures yielded passed by simple voice votes. They
included block grants to help local governments computerize their
juvenile records and mandatory life imprisonment for people
convicted of a second sexual offense against a child.
</P>
<P>
   A proposal by Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., that included stiff
mandatory minimum sentences for crimes involving guns and children,
was opposed by many liberal Democrats but passed by a vote of
249-181. It also gives federal prosecutors authority to try youths
as adults starting at age 13.
</P>
<P>
   Other amendments provoked fierce disagreement, such as Hyde's
proposal to bar youths from being sold or shown violent
entertainment, books or video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entertainment industry gets away, literally, with
murder,'' Hyde said. ``Anybody that doesn't think rotten movies,
rotten rap lyrics, rotten video games aren't poisoning _ toxically
poisoning _ our kids' minds and making some kids think that's
acceptable, just isn't paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally impassioned, Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., countered that
Hyde's legislation ``grows the government ever larger'' and would
require a police force to determine ``what is decent.'' Asking what
movies would be banned from teenagers under the bill, he asked,
``Is that a movie like `Home Alone,' is that a movie like `Ben Hur'
is that a movie like `Private Ryan?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
