<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-ENVIRONMENT-215&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI PROPOSES EXTENDING AND EASING SUPERUND PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki on Wednesday proposed spending
nearly $4 billion over the next 20 years to extend the state's main
program for cleaning up toxic waste.
</P>
<P>
   But he also sought to ease many of the program's stringent
cleanup standards, as a way to spur businesses into developing
thousands of abandoned industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican who has worked to mold a prominent
pro-environment image, has been under intense pressure to renew the
program, known as Superfund, because it is running out of money.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been slow to do so, largely because the issue placed
him in a political bind. He was caught between environmentalists
who wanted the program refinanced and even strengthened, and his
corporate allies who wanted him to relax the burdensome and costly
cleanup requirements imposed on businesses and owners of polluted
properties.
</P>
<P>
   The plan released Wednesday, essentially an opening bid in
negotiations between the two competing camps, calls for some of the
most sweeping changes to the program since its inception nearly two
decades ago in the wake of Love Canal. Both sides said that
Pataki's bill fell short of meeting all their goals, but that they
welcomed his overture as an opportunity to advance an issue of
major importance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think it is an effort to address widely different viewpoints
on key issues like cleanup standards and funding,'' said Kenneth
Pokalsky, an official with the Business Council of New York State,
a statewide chamber of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Izeman, a senior attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council, also gave the plan mixed reviews. ``The governor deserves
credit for advancing a proposal for refinancing the Superfund
program and attempting to stimulate the reuse of abandoned
industrial sites,'' he said. ``But the details on insuring public
health protection are critically important, and it's not clear
whether the proposal achieves that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's plan would extend the life of a program that was
created in 1982 to clean up toxic dumps and spills that are not
covered by the federal Superfund program. Since its creation, it
has spent more than $1 billion. The last time it was refinanced was
in 1986, when voters approved a $1.2 billion bond act to pay for
it, but all that money is now either spent or spoken for.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the state's program, formally known as the Inactive
Hazardous Waste Disposal Site Program, has cleaned up more than 300
waste sites, from landfills to abandoned dry-cleaning plants and
gasoline stations, and it is still cleaning 511 others. But it
lacks the money to finish all of those sites or to clean up about
300 other properties identified by state officials as posing a
``significant threat to public health.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's proposal calls for $3.89 billion over the next 20
years, with the costs being evenly split by industry fees and the
state's taxpayer-financed general fund. The proposal particularly
troubled business leaders, who complained that it significantly
raised existing industry fees that are used to help pay for some of
the costs of the Superfund program.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's bill also calls for easing some of the state's strict
cleanup standards in an effort to encourage businesses to develop
long-dormant industrial sites that contain hazardous waste. The
bill would determine the level of cleanliness for a polluted site
depending on how the site would be used. Put another way, a
property to be used for a dry-cleaning plant would not have to be
as thoroughly cleaned as a site intended for a school or day-care
center.
</P>
<P>
   That approach was supported by business leaders and even some
environmentalists. They contend that current standards _ which
require polluted sites to be thoroughly cleaned, no matter what
their ultimate use _ are too costly and have discouraged investors
from developing hundreds of tracts of abandoned industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
   But some environmentalists Wednesday criticized that approach,
saying that no one can be sure how a property will be used in
future years as ownership changes _ though the bill would require a
more extensive cleanup if a property's designated use changed. The
critics also contend that failure to entirely eliminate pollutants
poses a risk to natural resources like groundwater, and that the
bill itself allows the new relaxed cleanup standard to be used even
on properties near such resources.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also seeks to relax some of the rules in the area of
so-called cleanup liability. The current program holds not only the
major polluter of a site responsible for its cleanup, but also a
long list of others _ from banks that foreclosed on contaminated
property to subsequent owners.
</P>
</TEXT>
