<HEADER>
A8623 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-NKOREA-LADN-(SLAN     06-16 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NKOREA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREANS SUPER SERIOUS IN PRACTICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ It's been a sight to see the North Korean
women train at Pomona-Pitzer College this week. Their workouts seem
more like military boot camp than soccer practice.
</P>
<P>
   All the players sport short haircuts. And instead of laughing
and talking during informal scrimmages, the North Koreans conduct
drill after drill in silence. Their coach is the only one who
speaks.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the shoes. As they switch from turf shoes to
soccer boots, they leave their turf shoes perfectly lined-up,
side-by-side _ another sign of the discipline that embodies North
Korean soccer.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea, which meets the looser, singing Nigerians Sunday at
the Rose Bowl in their opening game of the 1999 FIFA Women's World
Cup, is the most secretive team in the tournament. And the team
that has the least contact with the rest of the world rarely grants
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the coaches and players like the media because
we're trying not to divert their attention from the training,''
said Korean secretary Mun Si Song. ``We don't find any positives
from doing interviews. We didn't come here to talk politics, we
came here to play the match and to train.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary general Ryu Song II endorsed those feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not distract the players,'' Song II said. ``Doing any
activities that might affect players while they are conditioning
and training is not good.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans are expected to grant required interviews as
the tournament moves on, but for the most part, it is a team that
keeps to itself.
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans are intent on reaching the second round and
qualifying for the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, so players follow
strict team guidelines. While Germany and Italy are visiting
Universal Studios and Santa Monica Beach during their short stay in
Los Angeles this week, North Korea has planned no sightseeing
adventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' said Si Song. ``We're here for training and
match, that's all. We have a schedule from the coach and we plan to
follow it.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea also prefers not to deal with the media because the
questions often turn political.
</P>
<P>
   Since U.S. forces joined South Korea in patrolling disputed
waters in the Yellow Sea after a South Korean gunboat sank a North
Korean gunboat Monday, questions about unrest in the communist
country seem natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to say much,'' said Si Song. ``Sometimes we say
something one way and your reporters say it another way.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Women's World All-Star match in February, North
Korean coach Myong Ton Chan dismissed any political questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are problems I do not want talk about,'' Ton Chan said
through an interpreter. ``That kind of thing is not for this forum.
I know there are things, but if I say there are problems or
something, it is not a good thing to say.''
</P>
<P>
   One example of life in North Korea surfaced following a comment
from a North Korean official while the team was training by a golf
course in New Jersey last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have a golf course in my country,'' he said.
``But I am not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that the North Koreans earned their first
Women's World Cup berth thanks to a 1-0 upset of Japan in the
semifinals of the Asian Cup. In group A with the United States, the
North Koreans will meet the Americans on June 27 in Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   What the Americans and other teams do know about North Korea is
that the players are technical, physical and played China tough in
a 2-0 loss in the Asian Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say my country is young and green,'' said Tong Chan back
in February. ``We don't have a lot of experience like the USA, but
we welcome our chance to play them. If you are going to catch a
tiger, you have to get in the cave with them.''
</P>
<P>
   And North Korea might be the most rapidly improving team in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think women's football is one of the sports close to Korean
women in a physical sense,'' said Kim Hak-Yong, the team's
technical official. ``In elementary schools and higher schools, we
have a football class, and each school district has extracurricular
activity for football. We have a program to bring up the women at
all levels and in every age group.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of girls who look forward to becoming a football player
believe this World Cup is an inspiration to the development of our
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
