<HEADLINE>
TRUSTEE GIVES $35 MILLION FOR INSTITUTE AT PRINCETON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   (nk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As universities race to establish research centers in the
growing field of genomics, Princeton University on Wednesday
announced a $35 million gift for its new Institute for Integrative
Genomics. The gift will cover nearly half of the $75 million
Princeton is trying to raise for the institute.
</P>
<P>
   The gift is part of a $55 million donation by an insurance
company executive, Peter B. Lewis, a 1955 Princeton graduate and
university trustee who has also made major gifts to arts
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second-largest gift Princeton has received, after the
$100 million pledged by a Hong Kong businessman, Gordon Y.S. Wu, in
1995. Although Wu has encountered business difficulties in recent
years, a Princeton spokesman said Wednesday that his gift was still
on track.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who is chairman and chief executive of the Progressive
Corp., an insurance company based in Cleveland, said in a statement
Wednesday that what drew his interest to Princeton's genomics
center was the way young scientists from many fields would converge
to try to develop an important new scientific discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a risk-taker myself, and this new institute
seems very much in that spirit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the mapping of the human genome nearly complete, Princeton
researchers hope to use analytic tools from physics, chemistry,
computer science, mathematics and engineering to study how various
genes work together in living organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations that have announced major research
initiatives intended to build on the genome sequencing work that is
nearly complete include Harvard University, Stanford University,
Cornell University and the Scripps Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley M. Tilghman, the Howard A. Prior Professor of the Life
Sciences at Princeton and director of its genome institute, said
money raised for the institute would pay for a new building and
equipment and also for the research itself. The field is so new and
so interdisciplinary, she said, that researchers will have to take
many risks and therefore could find it difficult to raise grant
money to pay for their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The really exciting thing about the Lewis gift,'' she said,
``is that it will allow us to give these young people five years of
secure funding _ core funding with which they can try new things.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lewis pledged $50 million to the Solomon R.
Guggenheim Museum, of which he is chairman. It was one of the
largest cash gifts made to any visual arts institution and the
largest the Guggenheim had ever received. He also helped create the
Cleveland Center for Contemporary Art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
