<SLUG> BC-CERNER-EXPANSION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CERNER SEEKS TAX BREAKS FOR $237 MILLION EXPANION IN NORTH KANSAS
CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH and MIKE RICE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that could more than double its area employment,
Cerner Corp. is proposing a $237 million expansion of its North
Kansas City headquarters campus.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the project would be built in five phases over 15
years, from 2000 to 2015, and would have space for an additional
3,600 employees. The development would be about one-third the size
of the new Sprint Corp. campus being built in Overland Park, Kan.,
a Kansas City suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner, one of the world's biggest developers of health-care
information technology, is asking for about $42.09 million in
property tax abatements under Missouri's Chapter 353 redevelopment
law. Officials said Cerner needs the tax breaks to compensate for
the added costs of building on the site's silty, erosion-prone
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner is pursuing the project at a time when its bottom line is
being squeezed by competition, belt-tightening in the health-care
industry and fallout from potential customers delaying purchases
because of the year 2000 computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   The company's earnings and stock also have been pressured in
recent years by expenditures to develop its HNA Millennium
software. Cerner has spent about $150 million on the software,
which is designed to loop together the information systems of
hospitals, pharmacies, laboratories, doctors' offices and other
health-related entities.
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn Tobin, Cerner's executive vice president and chief
operating officer, said Wednesday that the campus expansion was an
``absolutely natural step. We are reaching the end of available
space on this campus. To grow, we need a place to put those
people'' the company plans to hire.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said Cerner expects its headquarters employment to double
in the next three to five years, from 1,600 to 3,200.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said the added office space ultimately could hold 3,600
more workers than the company now employs at its headquarters,
though he did not estimate an employment figure by the project's
completion in 2015.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner officials, who noted that the company's employment rolls
have doubled in the past few years, expect continued rapid growth
from sales of its new family of software products and consulting
services.
</P>
<P>
   Mike T. White, a lawyer representing Cerner, said the company
had received feelers from other cities seeking Cerner's
headquarters. White and Cerner officials declined to identify those
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said Cerner is ``not actively seeking out those offers nor
are we entertaining them. We believe there is a lot of opportunity
in North Kansas City to bring together highly valued workers from
throughout the Midwest and the United States. We believe it is very
good business to be located in (metropolitan) Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerner, founded in 1979, moved to North Kansas City in 1981. It
bought the property northeast of Missouri 210 and Walker Road in
1994. Of the 98 acres, 43 are developed.
</P>
<P>
   The Cerner campus currently consists of six office buildings and
an associate center with meeting rooms, a fitness center and a
child-care facility, for a total of 500,000 square feet of
developed space. Most of the buildings were built in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion would add nine office buildings of one to five
stories, for about 1 million square feet of new office space.
</P>
<P>
   It also would add three parking garages and surface lots that
would increase parking capacity from 1,850 to 4,700 spaces. It
would include about 45,000 square feet of renovations at two
existing buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion is meant only for Cerner's use and not for leases
to other companies, Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Sprint's 3.9 million-square-foot campus in
Overland Park will cost nearly $1 billion. That includes the cost
of installing Sprint's new ION advanced communications technology,
as well as a recently approved addition to the project.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed 353 plan, the new Cerner buildings would
receive 100 percent real estate property tax abatements for 10
years and then pay 50 percent of its real estate taxes for 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   Some North Kansas City leaders were skeptical about the Chapter
353 plan when it was presented at a City Council meeting Tuesday.
Councilman Merle Walker asked why the financing tool was needed
when the seven existing buildings were constructed without such tax
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   White said Wednesday that the existing buildings were on land
that is flatter than the proposed expansion site. He said the
company probably will not proceed with the expansion if the tax
breaks are not approved.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner would make payments in lieu of taxes to the taxing
authorities in the project area.
</P>
<P>
   White said developing the project with the requested tax
abatements would generate $27.3 million in real estate taxes over
25 years. If the project is not developed, the real estate taxes on
the existing headquarters complex would be $15.5 million during the
same period, White said.
</P>
<P>
   White said the 353 plan would not cut personal business property
taxes on items such as new computer systems. The expansion would
triple the company's personal property taxes from an annual
$370,000 to $924,000, according to a report prepared by Cerner.
Annual utility taxes would grow from $45,000 to $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   George DeFrench, city administrator for North Kansas City, said
the Cerner project would be one of only a handful of 353
redevelopment projects approved by the city. It would be the city's
first such project to include a finding of blight based on the soil
conditions of vacant land, he said.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrench said the City Council would discuss the Cerner proposal
further in a week or two. If the council agrees to proceed, a
public hearing will be held. A final vote by the council could come
at or after the public hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0548 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CUP-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-16 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CUP-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IT'S A GREAT SERIES: IS ANYBODY WATCHING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Derian Hatcher, the captain of the Dallas Stars, is a
big, tough, talented defenseman with an intimidating style and a
rap sheet to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher began the two-month Stanley Cup tournament under a
five-game suspension because his vicious check put Jeremy Roenick
of Phoenix into the boards and out of action with a broken jaw. In
a previous game, Roenick's hard hit had hurt Mike Modano, the
scoring star of the Stars. Hatcher's retaliation is the way hockey
players sometimes settle such scores.
</P>
<P>
   Before the final round against the Buffalo Sabres, when asked if
he accepted terms such as ``scary'' and ``dangerous'' and
``intimidating'' as complimentary, Hatcher chuckled and said,
``Well, I would have to.'' He added: ``I don't know if guys should
be scared, but if they are, I guess I am doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night in Buffalo's new Marine Midland Arena, a 2-1
Sabres victory that sent the series back to Dallas tied at two
victories apiece, even an unsophisticated fan or television
director could see several Sabres charging full speed toward
Hatcher, hurling their smaller bodies into his 6-foot-5-inch,
225-pound frame. Even Dominik Hasek, the Sabres' goalie, greeted
Hatcher with a gratuitous bump that prompted a four-penalty melee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dom's got a black belt,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said. ``So
he'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest that Hatcher and the Stars are
intimidated by the Sabres, a younger, lesser-paid team that
finished far below league-leading Dallas in the 82-game regular
season. It is merely to illustrate the intensity of competition in
what may be the NHL's best championship round of the decade after
four consecutive years of four-game sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   Challenging Hatcher in this manner is like clicking a stick
along the bars of a lion's cage or lighting cherry bombs while
pumping gasoline. But this sort of thing is happening all over the
ice in most minutes of every game. When asked if he felt like a
target, Hatcher said Wednesday: ``Yeah, sometimes I feel like they
are coming at me. I am a big guy. I can handle it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher's Stars still should win this series, which resumes
Thursday night in Dallas. Even though the Sabres have the reigning
most valuable player in Hasek, the Stars have more talented players
and they have more playoff experience. Two of the remaining three
games are in Reunion Arena, an older building with newer fans who
match the passion of the Sabres supporters but lack both their
Canadian-border hockey hipness and Buffalo's sincere, almost
painful yearning for a championship after decades of civic
deprivation, inside and outside sports.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sabres have an advantage, it is in their youth and
relative freshness at the end of a nine-month grind of more than
100 games, the hardest ones last. Dallas played three longer,
tougher rounds in this tournament and the Stars are hurting the
most.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull missed most of Game 3 and all of Game 4 with a groin
pull and his return is questionable for Game 5. Modano is playing
with an injured left wrist that hampers his stick-handling, passing
and shooting. The rest of the Stars, gnarled old pros, throw
themselves in front of speeding pucks the way soldier-heroes jumped
on hand grenades in the old war movies. Surely these slap shots
have left their welts and contusions.
</P>
<P>
   By now, even the savvy hockey mavens who complained in advance
about the defensive orientation of these teams have to acknowledge
that low scoring isn't necessarily boring when both sides use
high-pressure checking systems instead of the passive neutral-zone
trap so popular at mid-decade with finalists like the Devils and
the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   But, outside the hockey cult, in places such as basketball-mad
New York, does anyone else notice the drama? No matter the
marketing rationale, it is preposterous to extend a hockey season
until the hot days of mid-June, when baseball approaches midseason
and hockey players complain about mushy ice.
</P>
<P>
   As for attracting a broader television audience, it is
self-defeating to show the games from Dallas on the Fox network,
which frequently interrupts its horrid camera work with lengthy
commercial breaks and smutty promos for silly sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey buffs who grudgingly concede that their sport does not
translate perfectly to television have learned one hard lesson from
the soon-to-end Fox experiment: that low camera angles and
ill-timed close-ups away from the puck make hockey almost
incomprehensible to even veteran viewers.
</P>
<P>
   So, we close this season and this rant with a version of the old
catcall usually aimed from the cheap seats to the referees: Hey,
Fox! Hey, America! Open your eyes! You're missing some great games!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
