A8635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-BALKE-NYT &LR;      06-16 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BALKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. BRUNO BALKE, 91, INNOVATOR IN STUDY OF PHYSICAL CONDITIONING
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Colo., Wis., Ore.)  (nk) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruno Balke, a sports medicine innovator who preached a regimen
of sensible exercise as an antidote to heart ailments, died on June
7 at St. Mary's Hospital in Grand Junction, Colo. He was 91 and had
lived in Grand Junction in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Balke was credited with being the first exercise physiologist to
chart the precise relationship among oxygen consumption, exercise
and cardiovascular health. At a time when bed rest was the general
prescription for heart patients, he was an early advocate of
heart-strengthening exercises of the kind that became popular in
the 1970s with the growth of aerobics and fitness salons.
</P>
<P>
   Balke was a professor emeritus of physiology and kinesiology at
the University of Wisconsin in Madison. Earlier in his career he
accompanied a German expedition in the Himalayas, tested the
stamina of German Alpine troops in World War II and helped the U.S.
Air Force determine how the human body could adapt to space flight.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Braunschweig, Germany, he graduated from the German
Academy of Physical Education in 1931. He earned his medical degree
at the University of Berlin in 1936 and added a doctorate in
medical rehabilitation at the University of Leipzig in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   From 1936 to 1942, Balke was affiliated with the department of
sports medicine at the University of Berlin. As the team physician
for German climbers in the Himalayas in 1938, he found an interest
that would last the rest of his life: high-altitude conditioning
and human endurance under extreme stress.
</P>
<P>
   He served in the German medical corps in World War II but
contracted infectious hepatitis on the Russian front. After that,
he was posted to the medical school of the German Army Mountain
Corps to lead its department of performance physiology.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Air Force recruited him for its School of Aviation
Medicine in 1950. That allowed him to continue his research in San
Antonio, where in 1958 he subjected himself to 10 grueling days in
a simulated space capsule.
</P>
<P>
   Later he became chief of the biodynamics branch at the Civil
Aeromedical Research Institute of the Federal Aviation
Administration, joined the faculty of the University of Wisconsin,
worked with the Green Bay Packers football team, helped American
athletes prepare for the high altitude of the Mexico City Olympics
in 1968 and led a committee that created Medicine and Science in
Sports, which became the journal of the American College of Sports
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Balke's wife, Annemarie, died in 1996. He is survived by three
sons, Horst, of Basalt, Colo.; Frank, of Salem, Ore., and Per-Olof,
of Grand Junction; a daughter, Hedda Marg of Alzey, Germany; 11
grandchildren, and four great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
