<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-FINANCE-NYT     06-16 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI URGES MONEY CURBS IN CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki proposed Wednesday that New
York for the first time place significant restrictions on the way
politicians raise and spend money. But the governor waited to
present his long-promised campaign finance plan until the last
scheduled day of the Legislature's session, giving the measure _
unpopular among lawmakers anyway _ almost no chance of passage in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki plan would sweep away a system that has, in practice,
allowed parties and candidates to collect virtually any amount of
money from anyone, with little fear of punishment for violating the
few existing rules. The proposal would ban unregulated
contributions, lower many contribution limits and step up
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's timing spurred some Democrats and advocacy groups
to question whether he was announcing the measure mostly so that he
could portray himself as a reformer, while having little interest
in actually bringing about change. Pataki, who has been the most
successful fund-raiser in the state's history, shrugged off the
attacks. He said he stood behind the plan and hoped the Legislature
would eventually approve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fair and good proposal and I will work to try and
get it passed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor made his comments at a news conference during
which he was notably alone at the podium, unaccompanied by any of
the legislators who typically join him at such events.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day, it became clear that he had done little in
either major party to garner the support of lawmakers, who are
generally resistant to toughening the state's lax campaign finance
system. The existing rules bestow major advantages on incumbents _
the same men and women who would have to vote to modify them.
</P>
<P>
   Even Pataki's staunchest Republican allies, state Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno and Republican State Committee
chairman William Powers, declined to endorse the package of
measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
