<HEADER>
A8639 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OKCORRAL-AZR &LR;      06-16 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKCORRAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACTS HAZY ABOUT EPIC GUNFIGHT AT OK CORRAL  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CLAY THOMPSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ To begin with, ``OK Corral'' has a nice, snappy,
Western sound, perfect for the site of a shoot-'em-up.
</P>
<P>
   If the event had taken place at, say, Fred's Corral or the OK
Bathhouse, the Old West's most famous gunfight might not have
become so famous.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to the fuzziness of contemporary accounts _ plus all
the subsequent yarn spinning and moviemaking and book writing _ the
history of that bloody day is still not particularly certain and
the story is all the more enduring.
</P>
<P>
   This much, we think, we know for sure:
</P>
<P>
   About 2:30 p.m. Oct. 26, 1881, in a vacant lot behind the OK
Corral in Tombstone, Ariz., Virgil Earp, the marshal of Tombstone;
his brothers Wyatt and Morgan, and their pal John ``Doc'' Holliday
shot it out with brothers Ike and Billy Clanton, Tom and Frank
McLaury, and Billy Claiborne.
</P>
<P>
   When the shooting stopped 27 seconds later, more than 30 shots
had been fired. Wyatt Earp was unscathed, his brothers were
seriously wounded and Holliday had a scratch.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the McLaurys and Billy Clanton were killed,
Billy begging right up to the end for someone to hand him one
bullet so he could get another shot off at the Earps.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, 2,000 people turned out for the funerals of
Clanton and the McLaurys.
</P>
<P>
   The story Hollywood has given us casts the Earps and Holliday as
white-hatted lawmen, outnumbered but bravely facing the blazing
guns of a passel of no-good rustlers.
</P>
<P>
   The truth of course, if there is any, is less clear-cut. The
Earps and their hangers-on drifted into Arizona about 1880 from
Dodge City, Kan., where they had been known as the Fighting Pimps.
</P>
<P>
   The Clanton faction, on the other hand, were ranchers, though
not exactly noble sons of the prairies. They had been accused over
the years of rustling, thievery, harboring fugitives and general
orneriness.
</P>
<P>
   There was bad blood between the two sides for several months
before things came to a head at the OK Corral.
</P>
<P>
   The story of that bad blood fills several pages of colorful
Arizona history and involves stagecoach robberies, smuggling, women
of doubtful character and various people on both sides taking
potshots at each other and whacking each other over the head.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the feud boils down to this: Wyatt Earp, a
Republican, was banking on being appointed sheriff of the newly
formed Cochise County. Instead, the job went to a Democrat, John
Behan, a Clanton ally.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt's motives were not all based on his thirst for law and
justice. In ``Arizona,'' historian Marshall Trimble notes: ``Being
a law enforcement officer could be quite lucrative in those days
when the citizenry was more tolerant of certain extracurricular
activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the shakedowns and tax-skimmings that could have been
his, Wyatt Earp was out about $30,000 or $40,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   So the bad blood simmered and boiled until Oct. 26, 1881, a day
that left Tombstone on the western mythology map forever.
</P>
<P>
   In the months following the Gunfight at the OK Corral, Wyatt
Earp and Doc Holliday faced a monthlong hearing on murder charges
and were cleared. Virgil Earp was wounded in an assassination
attempt and Morgan Earp was murdered while shooting pool. Wyatt
Earp eventually killed three men he believed murdered his brother
and left Cochise County for Colorado, never to return. &QL; 
John Behan went on to serve as superintendent of the territorial
prison in Yuma.
</P>
<P>
   Ike Clanton eventually was shot and killed by a private
detective. Virgil Earp died in Nevada in 1905. Holliday died of
tuberculosis in Colorado in 1887.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt Earp died in 1929 in Los Angeles, hoping to the end that
William S. Hart would play him in a movie based on his life. He
didn't. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
