<HEADER>
A8640 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-TEX-LADN-(SLANG)     06-16 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TEX-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY SIGNS OF WINTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ First Phil Jackson, then Tex Winter?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if Jackson, who officially became the Los
Angeles Lakers head coach Wednesday, is reunited with his longtime
assistant and master of the triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given me free opportunity to pick my own staff,''
Jackson said during his press conference at the Beverly Hilton. He
wouldn't, however, go as far as to name names until the team's
incumbent staff is consulted.
</P>
<P>
   But the first name might be Winter's.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson is the high priest of sideline karma, Winter _ who
just finished his 14th season as a Chicago Bulls assistant _
qualifies as the Jedi prophet of offensive flow. His celebrated
system served as Michael Jordan's tactical censor during six NBA
championship runs by Jackson and the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   So after a season of separation, is Winter planning to ride
shotgun for Jackson again?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little premature for that,'' Winter said Wednesday from
the Bulls' Berto Center complex, which remains home at least
through the length of a contract that expires June 30. ``Phil's a
little busy with things out there, but I'm sure we'll talk.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a Bulls source, Bulls coach Tim Floyd has been
advised to start interviewing for Winter's position.
</P>
<P>
   While carefully articulating his interest in working for the
Lakers, Winter did inquire about the location of the team's new
practice home, as well as the construction progress at Staples
Center. The 76-year-old Winter knows his way around town, having
played at USC, then returning as head coach at Long Beach State for
five seasons (1978-83).
</P>
<P>
   ``The triangle is something that just evolved,'' said Winter,
who credits Sam Barry, his coach at USC, with providing basic
principles he's tweaked during each stage of a 53-year coaching
career. ``I think it's pretty simple, and it has to be, because I'm
a rather simple-minded guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the inevitable caterwauling of critics already has suggested
the young, me-oriented Lakers will be unable to assimilate what is
perceived as a sophisticated scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better you are as a basketball player,'' Winter said,
``the better the triangle will be. If you don't have the talent, it
can be difficult. This year with the Bulls, we had marginal
players, really, so we struggled.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Lakers don't seem to have that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the Lakers seem to have the talent requirement licked, but
will a system that traded on the versatility of Jordan and Scottie
Pippen invalidate the low-post lease of Shaquille O'Neal?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm biased,'' Winter said, ``but with a dominant
center, it (triangle) should work even better. And it should help
Kobe (Bryant) the way it did Michael. It's a five-man concept, but
it adjusts to your personnel. That's the great thing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   During Jackson's last three (championship) seasons in Chicago,
the low-post hub of the triangle was Luc Longley, whose offensive
flair was overshadowed by his ability to achieve a
body-surfing-related injury. Longley averaged 11.4 points per game
in his last Bulls run but dipped to 8.7 this season while playing
for Phoenix in a more NBA-conventional offense.
</P>
<P>
   As Winter points out, the triangle will promote plenty of
opportunities for O'Neal to get his hands on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just have to see how good he is at passing it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where Jackson comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he joined the Bulls, Phil had a selling job to do with
Michael,'' Winter said of the crucial Jordan endorsement. ``He
could have sabotaged everything. So could Shaq and Kobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think that's Phil's strength. He's a great motivator and
a good psychologist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0553 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8641 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      06-16 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU RUSE, YOU SNOOZE, YOU LOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ He's a small slender man with a long narrow face, a
long thin nose and a bald spot on the back of his head that'll get
bigger as he ages. But for now he looks young and, in his large
oval spectacles, innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, where he's on trail for stabbing his wife
44 times and dumping her body in the family pool, he reminds you of
Don Knotts in ``The Incredible Mr. Limpet,'' a character whose bad
eyesight and wimpy physique keeps him from passing the army
physical.
</P>
<P>
   `` '' It's exactly the image Scott Falater's lawyers want the
jury to see.
</P>
<P>
   A weakling.
</P>
<P>
   A nebbish.
</P>
<P>
   All Wednesday morning, as he has throughout his trial, Falater
sat studiously at the defense table _ the bookish kid in science
class who purposefully sits in the front row.
</P>
<P>
   He wore a dark suit and a dark tie, occasionally making notes on
a legal pad with a perfectly sharpened pencil, occasionally
crossing his arms over his chest, always with his eyes fixed
attentively at the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ronald Reinstein's fourth floor courtroom was jammed with
family members, reporters and courthouse gawkers as word spread
that Falater was about to testify in his own defense, to say with
his boyishly straight face that he was sleepwalking when he carved
up his wife, Yarmila, and tried to hide the bloody evidence. &QL; 
Looks are everything &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Falater must know that nothing he says could excuse such horror.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers know.
</P>
<P>
   They know that neither sleepwalking experts nor their client's
testimony will convince jurors to set him free.
</P>
<P>
   His appearance, however, just might.
</P>
<P>
   No one, not even the defense's experts, can say they're 100
percent sure Falater was sleepwalking on the night of his wife's
death. But everyone, from the judge to the guy who sweeps out the
courtroom, is 100 percent sure he killed her.
</P>
<P>
   And yet there he sat, calm, unflinching, even as the temperature
rose in the courtroom. He didn't remove his jacket. He didn't
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear this is the best and boldest method for trying get
away with murder. Admit to the killing and ask jurors to set you
free anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Without ever speaking, everything about Falater says, ``Look at
me, I'm a twirp, a mama's boy. I could never do such a thing if I
was awake. I ``must'' have been sleepwalking.''
</P>
<P>
   His story is that he was asleep and went outside to fix the pool
pump in a trance-like state. The ``tool`` he brought with him was a
knife.
</P>
<P>
   (Perhaps he couldn't find the hunting rifle he normally uses for
home repair.)
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer says his wife interrupted him in his sleep and he
hacked her up, rolled her into the water, then packed the knife and
his bloody clothes into a plastic container, which he wrapped in a
plastic bag and hid in the wheel well of his Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, when he ``awoke'' and was told about what happened,
he didn't fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   He was calm, like Wednesday. &QL; 
No explanation, no excuse &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom, he smiled at relatives and made notes on a
legal pad while lawyers argued over the scientific viability of
sleep experts and no one discussed poor Yarmila.
</P>
<P>
   In this day and age, ordinary victims aren't nearly as
interesting as extraordinary defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they manage to convince a juror or two that Falater was
asleep during the murder, those people will still have to ask, `'So
what?''
</P>
<P>
   It's an explanation, not an excuse. There is no excuse.
</P>
<P>
   And if Scott Falater, who took the stand Wednesday afternoon,
was the pious, law-abiding man his lawyers claim he is, he wouldn't
be looking to weasel out of responsibility for his wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   It's a B-movie performance going at the courthouse, a show.
</P>
<P>
   I got the actor right but I picked the wrong Don Knotts picture.
This one's more like ``The Ghost and Mr. Chicken.'' &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-99 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990616.0554 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-16 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8642 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      06-16 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU RUSE, YOU SNOOZE, YOU LOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
