<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KOHN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAROLD KOHN, 85, LAWYER IN CLASS-ACTION CASES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (rk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harold E. Kohn, a lawyer who filed some of the earliest class
action lawsuits accusing corporations of anti-competitive
practices, died Monday at his home in Philadelphia, a law partner
said. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Kohn became nationally known when he won a key
case against General Electric, Westinghouse and two dozen other
companies that the federal government had charged with illegally
fixing the prices of the electrical equipment they sold.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who had purchased the equipment filed hundreds of
civil lawsuits against the companies. Kohn's case, brought on
behalf of public utilities, was the first to go to trial and
resulted in a $29 million verdict.
</P>
<P>
   During the litigation, the courts began consolidating the
hundreds of cases and handling them as if they constituted several
large class-action lawsuits. After the lawsuits were settled, Kohn
helped draft some of the rules that courts began to use in
class-action cases. Soon, he and other lawyers around the company
were filing class-action lawsuits against numerous companies,
charging them with fixing the prices of products as diverse as
plumbing fixtures, antibiotics, paper and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Kohn brought a class action lawsuit against the timber industry,
and the jury awarded his clients $2 billion in 1981, then the
largest verdict in an antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   But Kohn also brought public interest cases on the behalf of the
American Civil Liberties Union and other groups. During the Vietnam
War, he helped file a case that contended that the military draft
was unconstitutional because it excluded women. The case went all
the way to the Supreme Court, which ruled in 1981 that the
exclusion of women did not violate the Fifth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Kohn also represented Ralph Ginzburg, the publisher, who was
trying to appeal his 1963 conviction for mailing obscene
literature. Ultimately, Ginzburg, who had been sentenced to five
years in prison, was paroled after eight months.
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, Kohn graduated first in his class from the University
of Pennsylvania Law School. In 1939, he began practicing law at the
Philadelphia firm of Murdoch, Paxon, Kalish &AMP; Green, which later
changed its name to Dilworth, Paxon, Kalish, Kohn &AMP; Dilks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Kohn formed his own law firm, which is now known as
Kohn, Swift &AMP; Graf.
</P>
<P>
   Kohn is survived by his wife, Edith; three daughters, Amy Kohn
Goldberg, Ellen Kohn Goddard and Lee Ann Glanton; his son, Joseph,
and eight grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   While Kohn became wealthy from the fees he earned on
class-action cases, he often differed with some lawyers who had
helped bring the antitrust cases on the issue of legal fees. At
times, Kohn argued that the fees that his colleagues were
requesting were too high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
