A8645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-PATAKI-CAMPAIGN-     06-16 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PATAKI-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PATAKI'S CAMPAIGN REFORM CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid the gloom that has settled over New York state's do-nothing
Legislature this session, Gov. George Pataki on Wednesday offered a
flicker of enlightenment. It came with his long-awaited campaign
finance reform package, which the governor wants in time for next
year's elections. The package, announced as this session moves to a
close, instantly sent grumbles through the Statehouse where
legislators do little more than talk about reforming one of the
least savory campaign financing systems in the country. But what
the governor has presented could be a starting point for real
reform _ especially if the details match the promises and if the
Pataki political clout is securely attached to it.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's package leaves some questions and issues unresolved,
especially since many of the details are yet to emerge. Most
disappointingly, the proposal falls short of authorizing public
campaign funding for candidates and setting spending limits, the
best hope of generating competition for members of the state
Assembly or Senate whose election is now tantamount to legislative
tenure. Last year the re-election rate for incumbents was 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's interest in the issue, however, stirs an
unfamiliar hope that New York's lax campaign financing system,
which has few limits on raising or spending money, could become a
thing of the past. Pataki announced that his plan would reduce
campaign contribution limits from $30,700 to $5,000, ban
housekeeping slush funds for political parties, crack down on sham
``issue ads,'' require more disclosure by candidates and toughen
enforcement of campaign laws.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, his proposal aims to curb the fund-raising hustle that
has overtaken recent legislative sessions. With New York's feeble
lobbying law set to expire this year, a few legislators are trying
to limit influence-buying by lobbyists rather than extending the
old law that only loosely regulates such activities in the state
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with proposed changes to their job protection plan,
legislators quickly took on self-protective tones. Minutes after
the governor announced his plan, it was being called a last-minute
distraction designed more to create better press coverage than to
produce decent legislation. Although Democrats have for years been
pushing for even stronger versions of campaign reform, such
criticism misses the point. This is a good starting place for
negotiations to end the easy influence of money in Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
