<HEADER>
A8648 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-TEX     06-16 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HULL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL'S RETURN MAY HELP STARS' OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Brett Hull danced on the ice yesterday afternoon
at the Dr Pepper StarCenter. He had bounce, he had energy, he had
jump.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Brett skated despite a sore groin and flicked pucks
at the net from every angle. He went top shelf, he aimed for the
corners, he threw backhands and his patented snap shots and rarely
failed to find twine.
</P>
<P>
   And all the Stars need is for one of those pucks to nestle into
the back of the net tonight at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   What difference can Brett Hull make? With or without Hull, the
Stars have one goal in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably one goal,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said, only
half-joking.
</P>
<P>
   It has come down to that, this nail-biting best-of-seven Stanley
Cup series between the Stars and Buffalo Sabres that resumes tied
2-2 with Game 5 at 7 tonight at Reunion Arena. Brett Hull's return
from a groin injury could mean one additional goal for the Stars.
Benoit Hogue's return from a severely sprained knee could mean one
goal. The improvement of Mike Modano's wrist after another day goal
could result in one extra goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's been the difference,'' center Guy Carbonneau said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nearly 13 periods of hockey played in the Stanley Cup
Finals, the games have been within one goal for all but 26 seconds.
One goal in mind? It's not just the Stanley Cup, it's the theme of
this series _ finding any way to score one goal.
</P>
<P>
   After missing Game 4, Hull has been upgraded from doubtful to
questionable and could be moved to probable if he has a good skate
this morning. Can he add one goal?
</P>
<P>
   Hogue is listed as ``available for selection'' after missing
three weeks with torn ligaments in his left knee. Can he add one
goal?
</P>
<P>
   One goal in mind; it rings true.
</P>
<P>
   Were you frustrated you couldn't help in Game 4, Brett?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an understatement,'' Hull said. ``Especially in that
one-goal game when I think the majority of people agree the one
thing I can do is score goals. And to be just that one short, it's
as frustrating as you can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars know the drill on Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek, who
lowered his goals against average to 1.83 and raised his save
percentage to .938 after a 2-1 victory in Game 4. The book says
shoot high and get plenty of traffic in front of him. But that's
easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much room on either side, so it's really hard,''
Carbonneau said. ``But you get used to it and you know you just
have to work hard for your chances.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, you never know when one player will make a mistake.
You never know when that mistake will lead to a goal, as it did for
Buffalo in Game 4 when Craig Ludwig's turnover turned into Dixon
Ward's game-winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't play 55 or 56 minutes, because that's not good
enough now,'' Carbonneau said. ``You have to play 60 minutes... and
more if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   One goal in mind. Maybe it's the goal of Hull, the thoroughbred
shooter with goal-scorer's lineage. Maybe those hands that have
produced 586 regular-season goals and 76 more in the postseason
don't need the rest of Hull to be completely healthy. Maybe he can
come back on a bad leg and still find the back of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hands are fine,'' Hull said. ``Hopefully I'll be 80 and the
hands will still be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock called him a ``shark,'' lurking in the open spots on
the ice. Benoit Hogue referred to Hull as a ``caged tiger'' trying
to watch the game from the locker room. Hull could be the wild card
the Stars need.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, they simply need to play their game and not worry
about forcing a goal against Hasek. Maybe looking for goals would
be playing right into the hands of the Sabres' backstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start putting pressure on yourself to score and score
and score, you start giving up odd-man rushes,'' Hitchcock said.
``I don't think we need to start exchanging chances.''
</P>
<P>
   One goal? Maybe the goal is patience. Maybe it's becoming
predatory. Maybe the Stars need a shark or a tiger.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup Finals have become a best-of-three series and
the Stars have two of those games at home. Their one goal is a
victory and they need at least one goal to do that. However, it
would help if they had more.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides know that's pretty difficult, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, two looks like a pretty good number and three looks
phenomenal,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   One goal indeed. It will probably come to that again.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
